<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DENIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTHS OF DENIAL HAVE TAKEN TOLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (Washington) _ The American public
Monday finally got President Clinton's long-delayed answer to a
very personal question.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now another question might be: Could this mess all have been
over seven months ago, almost before it even began?
</P>
<P>
   To Republicans the answer is easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people aren't stupid,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah,
the Republican chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, said
Monday before the president's admission that he tried to mislead
the public about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. ``They know
he could have done this seven months ago, and it would have been
much more acceptable then.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody Cozad, chairman of the Missouri Republican Party, agreed.
``It should have taken 24 hours to sit down with family, friends
and advisers to say, `We have a problem.' They should have said,
`Let's deal with this, tell the truth and move on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not, say the president's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal's duration depends upon whom you're going to blame,
said Harriett Woods, a longtime Democratic activist from Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fallible president, admittedly,'' she asked, ``or the nasty
politics that seems to obsess us in finding something wrong with
our leaders?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spent four years and $40 million trying to pin down
some criminal fault in the president. We're boiling it down to him
testifying about the possibility of sexual relations with a
consenting adult....
</P>
<P>
   ``I can feel real annoyance with him, and I do. But I can also
feel a fury for those who have been pursuing this goal of bringing
him down, even when it no longer seemed to be attached to the very
legitimate issue of performance in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Duncan, a historian who worked in the presidential
campaigns of Democrats Walter Mondale and Michael Dukakis, said he
was not so confident in the ability of the media and the political
culture to tread softly on such an explosive issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had he said that seven months ago, ...we would still be
talking about it today,'' he said. ``The length of time which this
has preoccupied the media is a manifestation of a modern
fascination with incredibly personal things. Then it would be:
`Which night did he do what? What did they do?' It wouldn't have
ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fallout from scandal-related developments has
created an atmosphere where previous thresholds of taste and
political etiquette have been breached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the impact on children,'' said Arthur Miller, who teaches
political science at the University of Iowa and directs the
Heartland Poll. ``What it means to have a president whom their
parents couldn't talk about because it was embarrassing. Those are
more enduring and go beyond the remaining period of Bill Clinton's
term.''
</P>
<P>
   But the seven months of denials have taken a more immediate and
serious political and personal toll. Because of the president's
defense strategy, the courts have placed him and future presidents
further from Secret Service guardians and personal advisers.
</P>
<P>
   First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton has been his chief defender,
discounting claims of infidelity as a product of a right-wing
conspiracy. The president reportedly told his wife and daughter,
Chelsea, for the first time over the weekend what he was going to
tell the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The president also denied the stories to his Cabinet. Although
some in the White House were saying that they just wanted to move
on and accomplish the tasks of the administration, others
reportedly were disillusioned and feeling betrayed by his admission
about Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put people through hell, including the staff and people who
are my friends,'' Dee Dee Myers, Clinton's former press secretary,
told /{The New York Times./}
</P>
<P>
   Former Republican Congressman Robert Walker said: ``My great
fear is that the trust that the president has to have in order to
govern effectively has been lost. If we find ourselves in a crisis
situation, either domestically or internationally, he won't have
the basis of trust on which to draw.''
</P>
<P>
   The paradox of the political drama that has enthralled
Washington for seven months has been the consistent disinterest by
the public. There may lie the benefit of Clinton's decision to
withhold the truth for so long, and his political salvation.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the public has always believed that the
president and Lewinsky had sexual relations. But a somewhat smaller
majority also thinks that even if he lied, it does not warrant his
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will still be some who will say, `What's really
upsetting me here is the process. We should have never gone through
this,' '' Miller said. ``But most of the people just want to get
this behind them and be told there was nothing criminal here.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Dixon, a pollster who teaches political science at Sonoma
State University in California, said the drip-drip-drip about
Clinton's alleged transgressions actually might have ``cushioned''
the public to acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want our public figures to be larger than life,'' Dixon
said. ``It's very disconcerting when they look like us. So when it
comes slowly, well, it's less of a shock.''
</P>
<P>
   And that may be a crucial factor in the way Washington deals
with the effect of the president's admission. There has been little
enthusiasm for this scandal on Capitol Hill, where independent
counsel Kenneth Starr is expected to send his report this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are fearful that the microscope could be turned on
them,'' said James Slattery, a former Democratic congressman from
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   But Slattery, who has defended the president, said that
regardless of whether Clinton survives politically, the larger
message may be one that was made obvious a quarter of a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole ordeal once again painfully reminds us that truth
is the best policy,'' he said. ``The tragedy of it, if we didn't
learn anything from Watergate, is that truth in Washington will
ultimately be revealed.''
</P>
<P>
   /{Staff writers Kevin Murphy and Scott Canon contributed to this
article./}
</P>
</TEXT>
