<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Colts have found a leader in Manning
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ On one side of Cinergy Field on Monday night, you
watched a desperate _ and possibly divisive _ tug of war for the
very heart of a ballclub. On the other, you witnessed a
franchisewide coronation that will help ensure a team's strength
and stability.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the divergent worlds of the Cincinnati Bengals and
Indianapolis Colts less than three weeks before the start of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   While quarterbacks Neil O'Donnell and Jeff Blake wrestle for the
steering wheel of a Bengals team that hasn't been able to stay on
track the past seven seasons, quarterback Peyton Manning is
cementing his place as a cornerstone for what should be a resurgent
Colt team this season.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the two teams that met in Monday night's preseason
exercise have been a lot alike in the 1990s. The Bengals have lost
83 of their 128 regular-season games, the Colts 78. Both have gone
through quarterbacks, coaches and several rebuilding plans.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin Coryatt, who has been a Colts linebacker the past seven
years, put it best: ``I've had three head coaches. I've had four
position coaches. I'm on my third or fourth defensive coordinator.
And God knows how many starting quarterbacks there have been (16 in
the past 14 years). It's made for a lot of new faces. And you can't
win if you keep bringing in new faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts took a big step toward staunching the bleeding by
making Manning the top pick of last April's draft and then getting
him under contract _ thanks to an $11.6 million signing bonus _ for
six years at $48 million.
</P>
<P>
   Already the Colts players are rallying around him. They sang his
praises in the preseason opener when his first NFL pass went for a
48-yard touchdown to Marvin Harrison. They did the same Monday
night when he opened his only half of action by completing his
first three passes for 84 yards, then closing out his night with a
12-yard touchdown pass, again to Harrison.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts like the way the 22-year-old Manning can read defenses
and spot alternate receivers. They like his work ethic _ he spent
so much time in the University of Tennessee film room they
nicknamed him Caveman _ and they're impressed with the confidence
and poise he's shown.
</P>
<P>
   The Colts, several veteran players have said, appear to have
found their leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals should be seeking the same. Then again you remember
Boomer Esiason's parting words last winter. He said Cincinnati was
a team mired by factions and malingers. And in a recent national
magazine story you learn of a scenario that caused Blake's
unraveling last season.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Pickens, as mercurial and me-first of an athlete as you'll
find, began bellyaching in the huddles that Blake wasn't getting
him the ball. Soon that carried over to the dressing room and the
practice field.
</P>
<P>
   Blake tried to salve the situation and began forcing the ball in
Picken's direction every chance he could. Often it was into
coverage and the Bengals offense sputtered and all but stopped
until Esiason took over the last five games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals got rid of some of their clubhouse problems when
they sent Dan ``Big Daddy'' Wilkinson packing to Washington, but
there still is Pickens, Darney Scott and, according to Esiason,
linebacker James Francis.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals need a leader and right now they have none. Blake
tries but the role fits him like a pair of shoes two sizes too
small. As for O'Donnell _ who took the Pittsburgh Steelers to Super
Bowl XXX _ he's too busy just trying to win the quarterback job.
Right now _ no matter what coach Bruce Coslet says and especially
after Blake's 0-for-7, one-interception, often-booed start Monday
night _ it's his to lose. If not, Bengals president Mike Brown
wouldn't have signed the veteran to a four-year, $17 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Although the NFL nearly always provides a black-and-blue baptism
for a rookie quarterback, it seems as if Manning was groomed for
this job his entire life. That's due to his dad, Archie Manning _
the 14-year NFL veteran and last true college football hero.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Peyton's story is happily infused with his father's
legend. Archie _ the juke-mad, pocket-busting All American
quarterback from Ole Miss _ was a Southern icon. At the University
of Tennessee, Peyton got similar treatment. Even though he had
grown up on his daddy's NFL wealth in a 140-year-old house in New
Orleans' toney Garden District, privilege did not leave him soft or
searching for pop's coattails.
</P>
<P>
   Colts' president Bill Polian claims he watched the tapes of
every pass thrown last season by Manning and Washington State's
Ryan Leaf _ three times _ before having his coaches do the same.
Then he paid NFL brain-trust Bill Walsh to study the two. Every
assessment came up with Manning.
</P>
<P>
   So the Colts go into the season with one man to lead them.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals, meanwhile, are groping their way through yet
another quarterbacking controversy. Sides are being drawn and the
picture this far into the preseason looks no better than last
year's troubled trek.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Archdeacon's column appears in the Dayton Daily News,
Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
