<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMILIATION COULD BE PART OF CLINTON'S LEGACY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton has confessed. Now for the fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton tried to close the curtain on his sordid,
extramarital affair, he and the nation will now be jarred by the
inevitable cascade of legal, political and personal consequences
that flow from the president's decision to own up to his
long-denied sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary events of Monday will affect Clinton's
leadership at home and abroad, almost certainly hobbling and
possibly crippling him. The coming days will gravely test Clinton's
repeatedly demonstrated ability to rebound from personal and
political crisis _ and, in this instance, humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his continuing high job-approval ratings, ``lame duck''
does not begin to describe Clinton's problem as he faces the 28
months remaining in his term.
</P>
<P>
   In his public statement, the president could not bring himself
to state clearly that he had sex with Lewinsky and lied to the
American people about it. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; No matter how Clinton sought to explain his agitated,
finger-waving denials in January, it is clear that he did not tell
the truth about 18 months of repeated intimate encounters with the
former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   The veneer of moral authority on his presidency was already
thin, and today probably has been worn away entirely.
</P>
<P>
   This leaves Clinton politically naked to friends and enemies
alike, and, depending on the public reaction to the president's
address, they will not be shy about taking advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   At minimum, Clinton faces an increased question of credibility.
For years, he has been known as a hair-splitting lawyer-politician
whose every word should be weighed as much for what is being
withheld as for what is being disclosed. His testimony and
statement Monday put new emphasis on this point, and will make his
attempts to press on with work at home and abroad more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, Clinton was questing after a grandiose
legacy. Now he faces entering the history books as an asterisk
likely to bring a smirk and snicker from future generations. That
is an utterly galling prospect for a man who has dreamed about the
presidency throughout his adult life.
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now _ admittedly with more than two years left
on his White House lease _ Clinton can point to no initiative or
achievement that is likely to overcome the shadow of the Lewinsky
affair.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's public apology came with the earnest, polished, human
delivery that is his trademark. It also came with an attempt to
wall off his private life, which may be too much to ask of even a
generally supportive American public.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans are softies for a contrite confession and a
suggested promise to sin no more _ although some may feel they've
heard this from Clinton one time too many in regards to
extramarital sex. The president may be helped through the coming
days by the realization that the public's heavy discounting of
Clinton's character helped get him to the White House and may keep
him there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's greatest advantage at the moment is that the nation,
which did not believe his denials of a sexual affair, is tired of
the tawdry tale.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Clinton delivered his personal apology to the nation
and plea to move on, his lawyer, David Kendall, sought to feed the
widely held view that it is time for independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's four-year, $40 million inquiry to end.
</P>
<P>
   Only if Starr can come up with solid proof of a sustained
attempt by Clinton to obstruct justice in the Lewinsky matter is
the public likely to rally behind any attempt to impeach the
president and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is sticking to that part of his story, and the burden is
on Starr. The sexual questions may have been the most personally
difficult part of the president's closed-circuit appearance before
the grand jury, but inquiries about whether he participated in
cooking up a cover-up would have been the trickiest.
</P>
<P>
   This is key, at least far as public feeling stands now. A Zogby
America Poll conducted over the weekend found that the only
circumstance under which a majority of Americans would favor
impeachment is if Clinton engaged in ``a pattern of obstruction of
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Congress, many of whom would like Clinton's head
on a platter, will be guided by the public reaction as they ponder
what, if any action to take against Clinton. With the Republican
hold on Congress, especially in the more politically volatile
House, so tenuous and elections less than three months hence, GOP
leaders may be inclined to let Clinton limp through his remaining
months in office.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who, for their own benefit, proved so legislatively
accommodating with Clinton in the days before the 1996 presidential
election, will be less ready to deal with the White House now.
Clinton's ability to advance his agenda _ or even to focus on it _
since the Lewinsky matter came to light has been negligible.
Monday's dramatic developments will not improve his chances.
</P>
<P>
   For many Democrats, Monday was a sad day of reckoning. Among the
most doleful sights on a gray day in Washington was White House
aides and fellow Democrats who had believed _ or wanted to believe
_ the president's denials and had staunchly defended him.
</P>
<P>
   They felt betrayed as they wrestled with the realization that
Clinton had risked his presidency for gratuitous sex. This was what
had so troubled George Stephanopoulos, the former close adviser to
Clinton, who refused to defend the president as the Lewinsky affair
began to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanopoulos said Monday that Clinton's actions were ``a
breach of trust.'' He had a lot of company in holding that view.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
