<SLUG> BC-GUS-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME CITIES IMAGINE THE WORLD CARES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Perhaps you have
noticed the way ``national news'' is defined as anything that
happens within commuting distance of the island of Manhattan.
<TEXT>
<P>
   California also comes in for occasional notice, but only in
times of earthquake, riot and mud slide, or when freak waves carry
off the beachfront homes of entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   If the middle regions of the country get mentioned at all, it is
in connection with outbreaks of tick fever and head lice, or public
manifestations by Ku Kluxers _ items which reinforce the notion
that the candle of civilization does not throw its light far
inland.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, however, no event is too trifling to rate
prime-time network coverage. The bias is understandable, since the
principal news organizations are based there.
</P>
<P>
   However the result, as seen from afar, borders on the grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   Political races in New York are reported in such detail as to
confound the 33 out of 34 Americans who neither live there nor give
a hoot who carries away the booty.
</P>
<P>
   The financial woes of the city are covered as though a slip in
its municipal bond rating might cost the rest of us our sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The lecheries, failed unions and rancorous divorces of various
celebrities and stars are chronicled as solemnly as the fall of
monarchies.
</P>
<P>
   Junkies, panderers and transvestites thronging Times Square are
offered as proof of decaying American morality, the woe of the
underclass, the triumph of deviancy or some other national
affliction.
</P>
<P>
   It is the city of Wall Street, the city of puts and calls. It
calls for our undivided attention, and puts forth the myth of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   One day recently, the lead story on a national newscast was what
the commentator _ or, to be precise, the news reader _ described as
an attack on the motorcade of the New York mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Then it turned out that the so-called attacker was unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was revealed that his ``attack'' consisted of running up
to the line of cars and pounding with his fists on the window of a
municipal truck until he was seized by police.
</P>
<P>
   From his screams of outrage, it was deduced that this solitary,
unarmed urban terrorist was protesting the lamentable state of some
of the city's public services. Authorities afterward described him
as deranged, although, given the state of things there, it sounded
like perfectly reasonable behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the incident was so trivial that the mayor, riding
in another vehicle, may not even have noticed it. But evidently it
was information the rest of America could not do without.
</P>
<P>
   The telling of the day's events by the Eastern cabal of
communicators is a most peculiar exercise.
</P>
<P>
   They remind me of an editor I once knew who defined news as
anything he could see from his office window or heard about over
lunch. A tree limb down across the street he habitually drove along
to work rated page one coverage.
</P>
<P>
   His was the very essence of self-absorption _ no great sin if
you're a local or regional journalist, but ludicrous if you imagine
you're speaking to the world.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, isn't it, that the most powerful voices in the land
should be, after all, so relentlessly /{provincial/}.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 0004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
