<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOL-PROBEACH-SIDEBAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S TOUR HAS TOPPLED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA HADDAD  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Linda Chisholm emerged last year as one of the more noteworthy
stories on Women's Professional Beach Volleyball Association Tour _
a founding member of her sport, who had fallen out of favor,
returning to make amends.
</P>
<P>
   At 39, the Birmingham High graduate and Van Nuys resident teamed
with Deb Richardson (36) to form the tour's oldest team. They both
finished in the top 10, placing as high as third in one event.
</P>
<P>
   Based on her performance, Chisholm had her sights set on another
season. Then the curtain suddenly came down.
</P>
<P>
   The WPVA, after firing president Nancy Lengel and promoting
assistant David Williams at the beginning of the season, ceased
operation in March. Chisholm and other players had been optimistic
to that point. But Williams failed to sign any of the handful of
companies interested in replacing Evian as title sponsor and chief
financier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another year goes by and another year you get older,''
Chisholm said. ``I don't think I'm ready to retire yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Two wealthy entrepreneurs, Charlie Jackson and Eric Spector,
stepped forward last spring with plans to save the tour, but both
pulled out because of infighting among the players. Many of them,
like Chisholm, had steered this sport from their seats on the board
of directors.
</P>
<P>
   Now women's pro beach volleyball is no longer a sport _ at least
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The death of the WPVA, said Chisholm and other veterans, can be
traced to decisions made by an unqualified, player-run board of
directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but start serving your own interest once you
step over to the business side,'' said Liz Masakayan, a UCLA alumna
who played with Chisholm in the Olympics before starting her beach
career. ``It's human nature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to keep your mind on the business when you're
playing,'' Chisholm said. ``We followed the (Association of
Volleyball Professionals) footsteps that way. We fell first.''
</P>
<P>
   The AVP survives _ barely _ because it managed to retain its
title sponsor, Miller Brewing Company. The WVPA wasn't so
fortunate. So top U.S. women like Holly McPeak, Lisa Arce, Nancy
Reno and Barbra Fontana have shifted to the Federation
Internationale de Volleyball, a world tour that limits U.S.
participants. Chisholm and many other players, who were the
backbone of the WPVA, are left with scraps.
</P>
<P>
   And there haven't been many morsels. Chisholm has played in two
events this summer while hoping that promoters who promised
smaller-scale, one-time tournaments in Southern California keep
their word. The American Volleyball League this week canceled one
of those events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm playing two or three times a week just to stay in shape,''
Chisholm said. ``It's been kind of like, `OK. Let's keep in touch
with the ball.' Whatever comes up, you're ready for it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, who is playing on the FIVB tour, doesn't understand how it
came to this. ``The talent has never been better. The product is at
its peak. It seemed like the sport had so much momentum,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Chisholm is supporting herself by working as a personal trainer
in a Brentwood fitness club and tutoring young beach players. She
believes the women's doubles tour will re-emerge. And when that
happens, Chisholm hopes it remembers the beach-party atmosphere
that made the sport so popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go back to retro volleyball in the '70s and go
crazy,'' she said. ``As bad as it sounds, sex sells. A lot of women
go see the men play because they're gorgeous. And it's the same
with women.''
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, they aren't playing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
