<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-NIXON-NYT     08-18 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NIXON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL CLINTON'S SPEECH DO FOR HIM WHAT CHECKERS DID FOR NIXON?
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE,
CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT.) 
(nk) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Clinton looked exhausted and sounded as defiant as a
regretful man could in his four-minute speech last night. It was
not the familiar, soulful Bill Clinton who turned up, not the one
who knows how to look a camera in the eye, but a far more
reluctant-sounding person. But every poll in the last week had told
the president that he had to make this speech, and he appeared as
reluctant as if the American people had subpoenaed him.
</P>
<P>
   No one expected much in the nature of revelation. Every poll in
the last months had also told him that most Americans assumed he
had had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky and had lied about
it. So amid the vague admission of ``misleading people,'' the
acceptance of responsibility and the bitterness at Kenneth Starr's
investigation, came a line that is central to the whole crisis: ``I
ask you to turn away from the spectacle of the last seven months,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   And when he insisted, ``I intend to reclaim my family life for
my family,'' this media-made president was virtually attacking the
culture of celebrity that helped create him.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Lewinsky scandal has been shaped by videotape,
television and the trappings of entertainment. Some tapes have been
replayed so often they are as familiar as family photographs: Bill
Clinton hugging Monica Lewinsky at a public reception; his
finger-wagging denial that ``I did not have sexual relations with
that woman.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the grand jury heard and saw his testimony on
closed-circuit video monitors. It was totally fitting that at the
end of the day, he finally spoke directly to the public on
television.
</P>
<P>
   It is necessary to go back to 1952 and Richard Nixon's
desperate, career-saving Checkers speech to find the original
ancestor of Clinton's speech on Monday. Nixon's appearance was a
defining moment not just in that presidential campaign, but also in
the use of a televised speech as a political life preserver.
</P>
<P>
   And despite similarities, the distance between the Checkers and
the Clinton speeches may be even more revealing, suggesting how
drastically the political and television landscape has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't easy to come before a nationwide audience and air
your life as I have done,'' Nixon, then a senator, said in the
almost eerie foreboding of the Clinton speech. Accused of having a
slush fund and about to be dumped from the Republican ticket as
Eisenhower's vice-presidential candidate, Nixon bypassed the
politicos and reporters and spoke to the people. He justified the
legality of the fund, just as Clinton insisted he had not lied
under oath or told anyone else to.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon started out sounding apologetic and then turned defiant,
charging his opponents with ``smearing'' him, just as Clinton
quickly turned his attention bitterly to the long investigation by
Starr and to what he considers an invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the true importance of the Checkers speech existed in the
way it shifted Nixon's image: from on-the-ropes politician to
family man and political survivor. Nixon said he would not return
the one personal gift, the dog named Checkers, that his daughters
loved. He ended by asking the public to ``wire and write'' the
Republican National Committee (which had bought the air time for
his speech) to say whether he should stay on the ticket. It worked.
</P>
<P>
   Television, which would treat Nixon so brutally eight years
later when he debated John F. Kennedy, was kinder to him in those
early days. Eventually, Nixon thoroughly lost his instinct for
televised political theater, as his pantheon of sound bites came to
include ``You won't have Nixon to kick around anymore'' and ``I am
not a crook.''
</P>
<P>
   The Checkers speech seems primitive by today's standards. Nixon
sits behind a desk most of the time, stiffly; there is little eye
contact with the camera. Not far below the surface, in hindsight,
is the snappish Nixon of the Watergate years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, of course, we live in a culture of sound bites and
confessions. It says much about our celebrity culture that the
actor Hugh Grant's apology for a sexual indiscretion on ``The
Tonight Show'' provides a closer parallel to Clinton's effort to
reclaim his privacy and his presidency through this speech.
</P>
<P>
   But videotape has dogged Clinton even as he has used it to
escape. Among the endless replays in the saturation television
coverage have been Hillary Rodham Clinton on the ``Today'' show
defending her husband, and a raft of Clinton supporters insisting
he did not have an affair with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   A succinct report by Sam Donaldson on an ABC special on Sunday
night quickly trotted out several examples of public finessing in
Clinton's past. ``I'm really sorry for that,'' a young,
brown-haired Bill Clinton tells the people of Arkansas about a tax
increase during his first term as governor. He tells reporters it
never occurred to him to mention that he had gotten a draft notice.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there was his most famous example of
television-as-life-preserver. ``That allegation is false,'' he told
``60 Minutes'' in 1992 about Gennifer Flowers' claim that she had a
12-year affair with him.
</P>
<P>
   But no one really expects the spectacle to end. Hours before
Monday night's speech, it was already being leaked and spun. As
Claire Shipman of NBC put it, ``the expected message: regret, but
perhaps not a formal apology.''
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Jackson spoke of Mrs. Clinton's ``unconditional love'' for
her husband and, anticipating the president's own line of attack,
wondered how different things would have been ``if we'd had a
special prosecutor outside the bedrooms of Jefferson, Roosevelt and
Eisenhower.'' Instant polls showed positive results for Clinton.
The story is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that one has to know how to use television.
What was Linda Tripp's ``I am you'' statement after her testimony
before the Starr grand jury but a clumsy attempt at a Nixonian,
Checkers-like image readjustment? The glare of all those television
cameras, the mercilessness of videotape, has made image-shifting
harder to achieve than ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
