<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE ON FAMILY VACATION IN HAWAII AS CLINTON FACES LONGEST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for updated top and extensive rewrite to reflect Gore's
response to Clinton's TV address)  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-SCENE, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-HISTORY,
CLINTON-NIXON.) 
 ( mk )  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the early days of the Monica Lewinsky
investigation, Vice President Al Gore strongly defended President
Clinton against all allegations of wrongdoing, saying he was a
strong and honest leader whom he was proud to work with.
</P>
<P>
   But as the investigation dragged on, Gore adopted a somewhat
modified approach to defending the president, saying instead that
Clinton had denied any wrongdoing and that there appeared to be no
reason to question that denial.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, after the president appeared on nationwide
television and admitted that he had been less than forthcoming
about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky, Gore, whose political
hopes in the year 2000 could well depend on the outcome of the
Lewinsky investigation, once again spoke out strongly in defense of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of him,'' he said in a statement issued by his
office, ``not only because he is a friend, but because he is a
person who has had the courage to acknowledge mistakes. I am
honored to work with this great president on his agenda for the
nation and I believe it is time to put this matter behind us once
and for all and move forward with the business of the United States
of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is on vacation in Hawaii, about as far away from
Washington, the president and the grand jury as he could get and
still be in one of the 50 states. According to Monday night's
statement, he called the president after his television appearance
and said that he and his wife, Tipper, have Clinton ``in our hearts
and in our prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Devlin, a press aide to Mrs. Gore, said the Gores had
gone to Hawaii for a work break that had been ``in planning'' for
at least three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vice president and his family always take a two-week
vacation at this time of year,'' Ms. Devlin said. ``He's staying at
a private home on one of the islands _ we're not saying which one _
and his schedule is private except that on August 25 he'll do a
Democratic fund-raiser in Honolulu and also will speak to a meeting
of the American Federation of State, County and Municipal
Employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he spend the day on the beach or next to the TV?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing on that,'' Ms. Devlin replied.
</P>
<P>
   The Gores arrived in the islands on Aug. 11 and will depart on
Aug. 26 for San Francisco, where they will participate in several
Democratic Party events before returning to Washington on August
28. Ms. Devlin said the couple have a sentimental attachment to
Hawaii, having spent their honeymoon there in 1970 and having
returned a number of times.
</P>
<P>
   At one point on Wednesday, the Gores were spotted swimming with
pet dolphins in a pool at the Hilton Waikoloa Village on the island
of Hawaii _ but not until after security personnel had plunged in
first to check things out.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore meets with Hawaii Democrats on August 25, he likely
will face a warm and eager audience.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaii has traditionally been heavily dominated by Democrats.
But because of cutbacks in military spending, a decline in the farm
sector and a sharp falloff in tourism from Asia, the state is one
of the few that face economic hard times, and polls indicate that,
as a result, Democratic candidates throughout the islands will need
all the help they can get in this year's elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8592 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATINO-VOTING-LADN     08-18 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATINO-VOTING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURALIZED LATINOS SURPRISE IN ISSUE-FILLED '96 POLLS, REPORT
SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a reversal of normal voting trends, Latino
naturalized U.S. citizens voted at a higher rate than Latino
native-born U.S. citizens did in the November 1996 election,
according to a Census Bureau report.
</P>
<P>
   Since native-born citizens usually vote at a higher rate than
naturalized citizens of the same racial or ethnic group, some
analysts said controversial ballot issues such as welfare reform
and California's Proposition 187 might have accounted for the
difference in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The census report, and the unusual voting pattern it describes,
stand in contrast to previous studies that show older, wealthier
and better educated voters are more likely to turn out on election
days than younger, poorer and less educated voters _ which
naturalized immigrants tend to be, said Census Bureau analyst
Loretta Bass, co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``Voting and Registration in the Election of
November 1996,'' represents the first time census officials divided
voters into categories of native-born and naturalized, said Bass,
who has a doctorate degree in sociology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should be careful about concluding anything'' based on the
data, she said. ``We're not sure if this is a new trend.''
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau didn't delve into explanations.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of Latino naturalized U.S. citizens _ 53 percent
_ voted in the fall 1996 election compared to 42 percent of the
native-born, the bureau reported.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Gold, senior director of naturalization programs in the
Los Angeles office of the National Organization of Latino Elected
and Appointed Officials, said it's important to remember the
context of the time leading up to the November 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 187 and welfare reform proposals to strip legal
immigrants of benefits had sparked a backlash among Latino
immigrants and prodded many of them into increased political
activity, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still had people who were getting energized and
mobilized'' in an atmosphere they perceived as threatening their
rights, Gold said. ``Naturalized Latino citizens felt they had to
make their voices heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturalized U.S. citizens comprise only 12percent of the Latino
population in the United States but account for one-fifth of all
Latino U.S. citizens, she said. Forty percent of the Latino
population of the United States aren't American citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Pachon, president of the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute in
Claremont, said the census findings might be tied to what he called
``the California phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, 250,000 Latinos became citizens _ 150,000 of them in
the Golden State, he said. Many of them evidently went to the polls
that year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's conventional wisdom that ``people who are newer to the
system are more enthusiastic about it,'' said Anthony Chavez, an
attorney with the Mexican American Legal Defense and Education
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Pachon said the factors that drove naturalized Latino citizens
to the polls in November 1996 may not be as compelling now. ``The
anti-immigrant drumbeat has really slackened in the last year,''
Pachon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau statistics show Latinos were a larger
percentage of overall voters in the 1996 vote _ 4.7 percent of all
those voting nationwide compared to only 3.7 percent in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   That corresponds to a growing Latino population nationally,
although studies have shown that such factors as youth, lower
socioeconomic status and lower education levels _ all of which
define the Latino population taken as a whole _ typically lead to
less political involvement, said Gold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth in population doesn't always translate into growth in
participation,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Latino political involvement is still lagging, she added.
``There is a gap between Latino participation and non-Latino
participation'' both in terms of registering to vote and among
registered voters, Gold said.
</P>
<P>
   Only 44 percent of Latino citizens voted in 1996 compared to 59
percent of non-Latino citizens.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the U.S. voting-age population (54 percent)
reported voting in the 1996 election, down from 61 percent in 1992.
The seven-point drop was the largest decline between consecutive
presidential elections since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The findings in the new Census Bureau report are based on the
November 1996 Current Population Survey, which routinely
overestimates voter turnout compared to figures from other sources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
