<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S STRATEGY: PLACE BURDEN ON STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Updates throughout following Clinton's Monday night address.)  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE,
CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT, CLINTON-NIXON.) 
 (JT /js )  
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his admission of an inappropriate relationship
with Monica Lewinsky, President Clinton on Monday night unveiled a
new legal and political strategy that effectively shifted the
burden to the special counsel to carry on what Clinton described as
a needless and intrusive enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our country has been distracted for this matter for too
long,'' Clinton said in his public address Monday night. ``Now it
is time, in fact it is past time, to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   These remarks appear to have been aimed at what the president's
supporters have long believed is the particular vulnerability of
the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr: the widespread public
perception that his investigation is largely a prurient pursuit of
the details of the president's private life.
</P>
<P>
   In his sometimes combative appearance before the grand jury
Monday, Clinton refused to answer in detail some questions about
the relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's investigation has dealt with a wide variety of issues,
including whether Clinton colluded with Ms. Lewinsky to tailor her
story, whether he counseled her to conceal gifts he had given her
and whether he participated in an effort to help her find a
desirable job as a reward for her silence.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday night's speech, Clinton dealt with those issues by
tersely denying that he had obstructed justice or persuaded others
to lie under oath or conceal evidence about his relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky. ``I told the grand jury today and I say to you now
that at no time did I ask anyone to lie, hide or destroy evidence
or to take any unlawful action,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that assertion is unlikely to end Starr's inquiry. He has
taken extensive testimony from witnesses about those subjects and
they are certain to figure prominently in any report sent to
Congress, which may then consider whether impeachment is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Starr may not be satisfied with Clinton's
incomplete answers about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky and may
decide to seek a subpoena to force the president to answer the
questions more fully. Clinton's associates said Monday night that
such a move would be vigorously challenged.
</P>
<P>
   While the issue of a sexual relationship between Clinton and Ms.
Lewinsky has occupied most of the public commentary, Starr's view
of the investigation, people close to him say, has always been that
any untruthfulness about the sexual relationship was part of a
wider pattern of deception on the part of the Clinton White House.
</P>
<P>
   Some questions concern conversations Clinton may have had with
Ms. Lewinsky, a former White House intern, once it became known
that she might become a witness in the sexual misconduct lawsuit
brought against the president by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones, a former clerical worker for the state of Arkansas,
had sued Clinton, charging that in 1991, when he was governor of
Arkansas, he made a crude sexual advance that she rebuffed. On Jan.
17 in a deposition taken by lawyers for Mrs. Jones, Clinton denied
having had ``sexual relations'' with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's acknowledgment to the grand jury that he had had, as
his lawyer put it, ``inappropriate contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky
carries risks. He has now acknowledged having been, at the least,
misleading in his testimony at the January deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's advisers said the president had agreed on a strategy
of asserting that he did not commit perjury when he denied in the
January deposition that he had had ``sexual relations'' or an
``affair'' with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Monday night, Clinton said that while his answers
in the deposition were ``legally accurate,'' he did not ``volunteer
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky has told friends and presumably testified before
the grand jury that in the middle of December she had a
conversation with Clinton in which he told her: ``If two people are
in a room, and they both say nothing happened, how will anyone
know?''
</P>
<P>
   This conversation would have taken place before Ms. Lewinsky had
been subpoenaed in the Jones lawsuit, although Ms. Lewinsky's name
had by then appeared on a list of potential witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   In the January 17 deposition, Clinton replied ``I'm not sure''
when asked whether he had discussed with Ms. Lewinsky her possible
testimony. A judge dismissed Ms. Jones' lawsuit in April, but legal
experts have said that Clinton could still be liable for any crime
he committed while the suit was still alive.
</P>
<P>
   The precise wording of any conversation the president and Ms.
Lewinsky had about her testimony could be important because lawyers
say there is a thin line between suborning perjury and discussing
hypothetical situations. Ms. Lewinsky provided an affidavit in the
Jones case in which she denied having had a sexual relationship
with Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
