<HEADER>
A8595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-18 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Turns out 
Johnson 
is human
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros' new ace outpitched &QL; 
as Phils' Byrd spins 4-hitter
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
PHILADELPHIA _ He pitched a shutout. He did not allow a runner to
advance to second base. He had six strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was little-known righthander Paul Byrd who stole the
show Monday night, tossing a four-hitter as the Philadelphia
Phillies handed the Astros a 4-0 loss before a crowd of 18,975 at
rain-soaked Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``A David-and-Goliath story came true out there tonight,'' said
Byrd, who threw the first complete game of his career. ``I was
facing a giant.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros hardly resembled the National League's top-scoring
team in being shut out for the fifth time this season. Ditto for
Johnson, who relied on spectacular control in three straight
flawless starts for the Astros but watched it abandon him in losing
for the first time with his new club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out there a little flat,'' Johnson said. ``I think the
way I go out there will dictate the way the team reacts, too. If I
go out there a little flat, the team will go out flat. It's my
responsibility to pitch with a little more intensity and get the
team up more. I didn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said it would have been tough to expect the same results
he achieved in his last start against the Phillies _ a five-hit,
9-0 shutout Aug. 7 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was going to be a test,'' he said. ``It's always a
test facing the same team back-to-back. I didn't have the same
stuff I had in Houston against these guys. I struggled with my
mechanics and didn't have a whole lot behind my pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson (3-1), who had thrown shutouts in his previous two
starts, allowed a run-scoring single to Byrd in the second inning
and a two-run homer to Scott Rolen in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   That was all the support Byrd needed. The 27-year-old
righthander, who had been pitching for Atlanta's Class AAA
affiliate in Richmond, Va., before being claimed off waivers this
past weekend, kept the Astros off-balance with an assortment of
pitches. He retired 15 of the final 18 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rains forced the cancellation of pre-game batting
practice. The Astros could have used it as the top three hitters in
their order _ Craig Biggio, Bill Spiers and Derek Bell _ failed to
reach base and went a collective 0-for-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the best game Byrd has ever pitched in the
big leagues and probably not one of the best Randy's pitched,''
said Astros manager Larry Dierker, whose team has a 7{-game lead
over the Chicago Cubs in the NL Central. ``When we hit well, they
go over the fence. We hit the ball well but not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was like that old saying: There are going to be 50
games you lose, and 50 games you're going to win. This was one of
the 50 we were going to lose. We didn't play anything close to
inspired baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, making only his fifth start in 88 big-league appearances,
did get a few breaks. The Astros had four deep flyouts late in the
game that died at the warning track.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd gave the Phillies a 1-0 lead in the second inning with an
RBI single that snapped Johnson's scoreless-innings streak at 21.
Johnson had not allowed a run since the fifth inning against
Pittsburgh in his Astros debut Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Glanville led off the Philadelphia fifth with a single to
left field, and Kevin Sefcik walked. Glanville was thrown out
trying to steal third base, but Rolen sent a 2-and-2 fastball into
the right-field stands for a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was replaced by Scott Elarton at the start of the
sixth, allowed three runs, six hits and four walks in five innings
and finished with only three strikeouts in his shortest outing
since he lasted three innings for Seattle in a 10-4 loss to the
Texas Rangers on May 19. He threw 101 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just couldn't find any rhythm at all,'' Dierker said.
``What has impressed me the most about him in his first three
starts was his control, and he just didn't have it. Not only that,
but he started losing velocity. I think he got frustrated. You
could tell with his body language.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd, meanwhile, didn't allow a hit until Jeff Bagwell singled
with two out in the fourth. As Byrd recorded the game's final out
on a pop-up to third base, he clenched his fist and began to
realize his accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the crowd gave me a standing ovation (in the eighth
inning), I wanted to cry,'' Byrd said. ``I'll remember this
forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
