<HEADER>
A8597 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-TV-RESEND-COX     08-18 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TV-RESEND-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANALYSIS: After a long wait, Americans treated to `crummy TV'
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oh, that woman.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton reversed his version of the truth about ``that
woman, Miss Lewinsky'' on Monday, first before a grand jury, then
in front of a national TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first appeared from the White House map room at 10 p.m.
looking as if he'd been sent to time out. He apologized (``it was
wrong''), hinted he might agonize (``I misled people, including,
even, my wife''), then rallied into a political statement. For four
minutes and ten seconds, he never reached for a Clinton prop,
though they never seemed far away: the bitten lip, the tear-welling
eye.
</P>
<P>
   It was two speeches in one, and it baffled many usually
unbaffable pundits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you saying you're not impressed?'' CNN's Larry King asked
Jeff Greenfield after the newsman's first post-speech comments.
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield gave it another shot. ``It was the most unusual and
difficult speech any public figure has had to give. To judge it on
a scale of `rhetoric: 8, cosmotology: 6' is almost offensive in
this context.''
</P>
<P>
   Offered CBS's Bob Schieffer, ``You don't hear this kind of thing
very often.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never heard it from an American president,'' said anchor
Dan Rather.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a rare telegenic moment in this long-running drama.
For all the day's historic weightiness, what led up to Clinton's
tell-little was mostly crummy TV _ a stunning letdown for those who
thought this might be a kind of final, rewarding episode to this
seven-month series. The broadcast networks interrupted regular
programming for a few minutes when Clinton began his grand jury
testimony shortly before 1 p.m. _ then scrammed (NBC cut off Tom
Brokaw in mid-sentence and leapt to its soap opera ``Sunset
Beach'').
</P>
<P>
   CNN wasn't so lucky. It was stuck with endless hours of expanded
coverage and little new to fill it with. There were rare bright
exceptions, such as Candy Crowley's feature on Clinton's
truth-telling options (``Isn't it mind blowing how truth is talked
about as multiple choice?'' she asked with the lively frankness
usually reserved for Greenfield).
</P>
<P>
   The most mind-blowing comment on truth, however, came from Sen.
Charles Grassley (R-Iowa) on CNN, when he advised Clinton to be
honest, adding, ``George Washington didn't lie. Now, I don't know
if that's true or not ...''
</P>
<P>
   But CNN did for much of the day what it's done for weeks: let
commentators speculate about what prosecutors would ask, what
Clinton would answer, and admit it had no idea. CNN producer Ted
Barrett got a morning peek inside the grand jury room and reported:
``It's a large court room with very tall ceilings, a pale white
wood, very light marble walls ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``All day we had the most lethal of situations: an intense
interest and no news,'' said Terrance Smith on PBS's ``The NewsHour
with Jim Lehrer.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN tried to spike drama into this static situation _ so static
reporters were reduced to fashioning metaphors out of rain falling
over the White House _ with a tiny box in a corner of the screen,
ticking off the minutes of Clinton's testimony, as if it were a
World Cup soccer match. The network ditched the box less than two
hours later: it couldn't account for breaks during testimony, which
apparently rendered its clock ``unofficial.''
</P>
<P>
   When testimony ended at 6:25 p.m., the networks' nightly news
was left largely with news it had reported all weekend: Clinton
'fessed to a ``relationship.'' But Rather was still revved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is live TV,'' he reminded us. ``Trying to cover this
story is like trying to put a fan belt on a moving Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather later threw to Schieffer: ``Let's go for a quick
analysis, as far as there can be any.''
</P>
<P>
   Schieffer confirmed Rather's worst fears: ``I don't think
there's much more to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But by prime time, the pundits were in full throttle _ just as
we like 'em. CNBC's Chris Mathews may have broken his own run-on
record. At one point he unloosed 196 words in a 40 second riff _
4.9 words a second!
</P>
<P>
   Too bad CNN didn't have its clock on him to make it official.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
