<HEADER>
A8599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BETTS-BUSH-535&AMP;ADD     08-18 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BETTS-BUSH-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DEMOCRAT, BUT AN F.O.G. _ AS IN GEORGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (js) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was, by his own
admission, the party-animal-like president of his Yale fraternity,
Roland Betts was his rush chairman. When Bush needed a political
launching pad, Betts helped buy the Texas Rangers and set Bush up
as managing partner. And now that Bush, a Republican, is expected
to run for president, Betts is warming up as his unofficial finance
chairman and head cheerleader in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a Democrat my whole life,'' Betts said the other
day, ``but I'm George's biggest fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts is the chairman of Chelsea Piers, the once-ailing Hudson
River sports complex rescued two years ago by Gov. George Pataki.
Now Betts is leading _ with his business partner, Tom Bernstein _ a
club of two: New York liberal Democrats for Bush. ``It's fun to
talk about,'' Betts said, ``because people don't expect us to be
fans of George.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts, 52, is an imperious, amusing and bearlike former Yale
hockey player whose company, Silver Screen Management, financed
nearly every Disney movie made between 1985 and 1991, including
``Beauty and the Beast,'' ``The Little Mermaid'' and ``Pretty
Woman.'' He was also president of a company that financed the films
``Gandhi'' and ``The Killing Fields.'' He broke with Disney after
1991 because, Betts said, ``they wanted to pay us less.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Betts is a very rich showman-entrepreneur who sits
on the right boards (Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center,
American Museum of Natural History, etc.). But his friendship with
Bush could turn him into a political player, a New York F.O.G.
</P>
<P>
   It will shock no one to learn that Betts thinks President
Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky is paving the way for
his fraternity brother in 2000. ``There's just no possibility that
George would be in the kind of stuff that Clinton is,'' Betts
asserted. ``He doesn't have it in him.''
</P>
<P>
   (On Monday, a skirmish broke out over this very issue. At a news
conference in Texas, Bush said he was ``embarrassed for the
country'' over the president's testimony. This prompted Lanny
Davis, a Clinton defender, to say on MSNBC that he was at college
with Bush and that the governor ``shouldn't throw stones.'')
</P>
<P>
   Many of Betts' Democratic friends in New York are skeptical of
his enthusiasm for Bush. ``Initially, he may be a hard sell,''
Betts admitted. It may not help that Bush has a position on
abortion that appears calculated to please both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that's the single toughest thing for George,''
Betts said. ``What he says is, `I uphold the law of the land.' ''
Bush describes himself as personally ``pro-life,'' but says the
Supreme Court has already settled the right of a woman to chose.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Bush, the son of former President George Bush, took a
few moments from campaigning for re-election in Texas to talk about
his friendship with Betts, which he called ``close'' and ``able to
stand the test of time.'' He also expressed pleasure that Betts had
owned up to being his rush chairman at Delta Kappa Epsilon, or DKE,
known at Yale and elsewhere as the jock house. ``Did he admit to
that?'' Bush said. ``Good. And he did a very fine job.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Betts talked in his office at Chelsea Piers, which is very large
and overlooks two roller rinks. He is 6 feet, 1 inch tall, weighs
220 pounds and looks like an entertainment mogul dressed in golf
clothes. ``What is this _ a dating service?'' Betts said when asked
about his height and weight. He is married, has two daughters and
lives on the Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   His good friend, writer Roy Blount Jr., devoted a chapter to
Betts in ``Be Sweet,'' his recent memoir, and wrote that Betts
became a mogul _ and that Blount did not _ because Betts is good at
getting up in the morning. ``He generally goes to bed early, gets
up early, runs and then works,'' Blount wrote. ``He loves to work.
That's another reason he's a mogul and I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Betts did not have a completely predictable ascent to
moguldom. True, his father, Allan Betts, was a longtime associate
of Vincent Astor and a director of the Astor Foundation. And true,
Roland Betts grew up in Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y., went to boarding
school at St. Paul's and then moved on as expected to Yale, like
three generations in his family before him.
</P>
<P>
   But then he worked for eight years as a teacher and
administrator in the New York and New Jersey public schools,
including five years spent teaching math and history at
Intermediate School 201 in Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote a book about it, ``Acting Out,'' published by Little,
Brown in 1978. ``Substitute teaching in the New York City schools
is masochism in its purest form,'' is how he started the chapter
called ``Subbing.''
</P>
<P>
   Betts left, exhausted, for Columbia Law School, became an
entertainment lawyer at Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison,
and then began financing movies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, he was the single largest investor in a group that
bought the Texas Rangers baseball team, which Betts describes as a
vehicle for Bush to demonstrate leadership skills out of the shadow
of his father. It also made Bush rich. Bush invested $600,000 in
the Rangers and made $14.9 million when the Rangers were sold this
summer. Before that, he had been moderately successful in the oil
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he never hit the mother lode,'' Betts said. ``He became a
rich guy last month.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
