<HEADER>
A8607 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-CROUSE-COLUMN-LA     08-18 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY WAS OUR MICHELANGELO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jim Murray once wrote about making a pilgrimage to Yankee
Stadium as a teen-ager to see Babe Ruth play in what would prove to
be his final season with the Yankees. Ruth hit a home run. As the
slugger trotted around the bases, Murray, to his dismay, felt none
of the drama that permeated the prose of his favorite sportswriter
of that era, Grantland Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth's power was prodigious, but what struck Murray that day was
the power of the written word. The pen, he realized, could be
mightier, even, than The Babe's bat.
</P>
<P>
   What Murray learned from reading the likes of Rice he would, in
turn, imbue in generations of Angelenos. Just how privileged we
were to sit at Murray's knee as he spun his stories will become
painfully apparent now that he's gone.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, the lead sports columnist at the Los Angeles Times since
1961, died Sunday of cardiac arrest at his Brentwood home at the
age of 78. Fifty years to the day after Ruth died of throat cancer,
the sportswriting world lost its home-run king.
</P>
<P>
   There will never be another voice like Murray's. It rang as true
as the man himself. He did not scream at the reader, demanding to
be heard. He did not sermonize or patronize.
</P>
<P>
   His subjects might have been skewered on occasion but they never
felt burned. He was a wordsmith, not a character assassin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could write a story about you that might sound a little
derogatory,'' said jockey Willie Shoemaker. ``But the way he wrote
it, you had to laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray had no discernible ego, a quick wit and an encyclopedic
knowledge of world events, the latter owing to his voracious
reading habits as well as years spent as a Time magazine reporter
covering everything from presidential hopefuls to Hollywood stars.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Murray's subject, he mixed and matched words like the
very best fashion designers do cloth swatches, then accessorized
his sentences with humor and history. The results were images like
the one Murray once painted of the infield-fly rule. It ``is about
as simple as calligraphy,'' he wrote. ``It might as well be a
Japanese naval code.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an ability to write a paragraph that made you want to
get to the next paragraph,'' said friend and longtime Lakers
broadcaster Chick Hearn.
</P>
<P>
   As far as paragraphs go, it's pretty hard to top the one Murray
filed from Indianapolis 500 one year: ``Gentlemen, start your
coffins.''
</P>
<P>
   Sportswriters had largely refrained from reporting on the
dangers of racing until Murray happened upon Gasoline Alley. He was
less interested in what made the hunks of gleaming metal run than
what made the drivers tick.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when he accepted the columnist job at the Times, he told
his longtime friend, Will Fowler, ``I don't want to write this for
statistics. I want to write about people.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was he filled his news hole with stories that stirred
the soul, aroused the senses, tickled the funny bone and
occasionally opened the tear ducts. Among his two-hanky pieces was
the tribute he penned in 1984 to Geraldine, his wife of 39 years,
after her death of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the subject was familiar or not, Murray always got to
the heart of the matter. He dug deep for information, going so far
as to look up Marilyn Monroe's birth certificate at City Hall
before interviewing her for a Time story.
</P>
<P>
   Once he turned his reporting and writing skills to sports, the
awards and honors started piling up faster than a stack of
newspapers. In 1990 he became only the fourth sportswriter to win
the Pulitzer Prize for commentary.
</P>
<P>
   The award meant so much to the modest Murray, he hung his
Pulitzer proclamation in the foyer of his home. But it wasn't the
dominant piece of art on the wall. Above it hung a framed letter
that golfer Ben Hogan had written to Murray praising him on his
ability to write about people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim said many times he prized that letter from Ben Hogan over
the Pulitzer,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   In July of 1982 Murray wrote of the late Pulitzer-winning
sportswriter Red Smith, ``People knew the name. And what it stood
for. Uncompromising integrity. A surgical deftness with words that
made some of us wonder if Red wrote with rubber gloves.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray might as well have been writing about himself. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
