<HEADER>
A8627 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      08-18 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READINGS OUT ON TOWNS, TEA LEAVES AND TACKLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You've got questions on Husky fall football camp, at
least 14 of them. We've got answers, guesses, observations and
prevarications:
</P>
<P>
   1. What's the chance of Lester Towns, the inside linebacker,
getting over his foot problem and being ready for Arizona State
Sept. 5?
</P>
<P>
   A: UW coach Jim Lambright put a positive face on it Monday, but
Towns' odds of playing appear to be about the same as those of
Larry Parrish, the guy who monitors the gate at Husky practices.
Towns hasn't run since April and he's only walking (with a limp)
around practice.
</P>
<P>
   2. How much of an impact will Toalei Mulitauaopele have at
defensive tackle?
</P>
<P>
   A: If vowels determined the starter, Mulitauaopele would have
Mac Tuiaea swamped, 8-5. Mulitauaopele, 6-foot-5 and 320 pounds, is
as big as his surname, but he's still somewhat shy on conditioning.
He passed nine of his 16 timed 110-yard dashes in testing, and that
factor, combined with his inexperience at this level, likely will
keep him at a backup position behind Tuiaea and Jabari Issa.
</P>
<P>
   3. What's it going to cost the Huskies to lose Mel Miller, the
corner, to a three-game academic suspension?
</P>
<P>
   A: After a solid redshirt-freshman season in 1996, Miller
leveled off and had only an average sophomore year. But the Huskies
are losing experience there, since sophomore Toure Butler moves
into Miller's spot and redshirt freshman Wondame Davis must
progress quickly in camp to assure his role as third corner.
</P>
<P>
   With Towns also less than iffy, it means Arizona State _
designated by The Sporting News as having the nation's No. 1
offense this year _ won't know where to prod first, the middle or
the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   4. Does Ja'Warren Hooker really like football less than he likes
track?
</P>
<P>
   A: Put it this way: He likes football somewhat less than the
offensive coaches like what he can do with a football.
</P>
<P>
   5. Is Gerald Harris recovered from his ugly knee injury of fall
camp, '97?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harris, the wideout from Kent, says he's fully rehabilitated,
and Lambright can only cheer that. A year ago, the Husky offense
took a major hit when Harris tumbled awkwardly out of bounds in
practice, removing the third man in their three-receiver sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a tape of it,'' Harris said furtively. ``The coaches
don't know it. They didn't want me to see it because it was so bad,
but I've seen it a bunch of times.''
</P>
<P>
   6. How do the Huskies like the switch of Tony Coats from weak
tackle to guard?
</P>
<P>
   A: Very well. ``He's got a lot of ability to pull and run,''
says Steve Morton, his position coach. ``Sitting in that weak
tackle spot, he hasn't been able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   7. Is there a reasonable facsimile of Lawyer Milloy or Tony
Parrish ready to step in at free safety?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, and his name is Hakim Akbar, but he's an 18-year-old
freshman. Brendan Jones, a senior, likely will hold onto the spot
he won in the spring, but he'll have to do it with savvy and
experience; Akbar vertical-leaps 38 inches, Jones 30.
</P>
<P>
   8. Can Washington return to the glory days when it could stop a
run up the gut?
</P>
<P>
   A: No guarantees. But the quickness up front will be improved
this year. Both Tuiaea and Issa have slimmed down to the 280-pound
range, and Jeremiah Pharms is a bullet train at the defensive end
spot vacated by Jason Chorak.
</P>
<P>
   9. Will Jerramy Stevens, the freshman from River Ridge, stay at
quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   A: ``They told me I'd get my shot,'' Stevens says. ``If it
doesn't work out, it doesn't work out. As long as I get my shot,
I'll be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   10. What might we expect from Brock Huard?
</P>
<P>
   A: Probably more than he gets from ESPN Magazine, which doesn't
include him in a list of six Heisman Trophy candidates: In order,
UCLA's Cade McNown, Kentucky's Tim Couch, Texas' Ricky Williams,
Wisconsin's Ron Dayne, LSU's Kevin Faulk and Ohio State's Andy
Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   Recognition has been a tough sell lately for the Huard family.
The other night, Mark Malone of ESPN asked Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson about Damon ``Hue-rad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And he's a freakin' Sun Devil,'' Brock said, referring to
Malone.
</P>
<P>
   11. Uh, who's going to play running back?
</P>
<P>
   A: The hunch here was that it'll be holdover Maurice Shaw. But
Shaw is limping around practice with a pulled hamstring, leaving
the door wide open for freshman Willie Hurst, who has a nice burst.
The back who has surprised UW coaches most is 6-1, 200-pound
freshman Braxton Cleman of Oroville (pop. 1,505).
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's absence means the No. 1 guy there now is junior Jason
Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``All he has to do is stay healthy,'' Lambright says. ``He's got
all the shake and move of any of the tailbacks we've had. But he's
had an awful time trying to stay healthy. We're trying to get him
through what was and get him seeing himself successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   12. Will this team be able to catch the ball better than the
Mariners?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are a lot of candidates, and a lot of questionmarks.
Right now, the ones who likely would line up in most three-receiver
sets are Hooker, Harris and Western Washington transfer Dane
Looker, a Puyallup High teammate of Huard. But you're likely to see
a good many four- and five-wide receiver sets.
</P>
<P>
   13. Scrubbing Miami for Utah State? Ugh. Any chance we'll see
the 'Canes anytime soon?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're in luck, stone crab-breath. An old Pac-10 association
between UW athletic director Barbara Hedges and former Miami (and
Cal) A.D. Dave Maggard resulted in a second home-and-home
arrangement that brings Miami here to open the 2000 season, with
the Huskies returning the game in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Another scheduling twist: Army, which was due to follow up a
1995 visit with another stop here in 2000, has been replaced by
Idaho. The Cadets bailed because of a new membership in Conference
USA.
</P>
<P>
   14. Forget the Rose Bowl. What's Washington's chance of beating
Oregon?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not very good, until the Huskies take the game as seriously
as the Ducks do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
