<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DUBLIN-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TAKES ON SWANK AMONG DUBLIN HOTELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 23.)  
(js) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The signs of Dublin's astonishing renaissance are everywhere: in
the cafeteria at the National Gallery, where the food is
Mediterranean, the waiters are from Spain and the customers are
from all over the world; in the long taxi line at the airport,
filled with Eurobusiness executives on day trips; in the crush of
shoppers crowding the city's stores. With its continuing revival,
fueled in part by money from the European Union and in part by its
own extraordinary business resurgence, Dublin has become one of the
region's liveliest spots.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, I stayed at two of the city's most exciting hotels,
one new, one opened in 1996. Although each is expensive and boasts
a five-star rating, the two can scarcely be more different in
outlook and ambiance: one is a classic luxury hotel, the other a
quiet bastion of minimalist chic full of quirky touches. Each one
suits a type of guest with a type of mood, and the question I faced
as I planned my trip was, what type of hotel would appeal to my own
willful sensibility?
</P>
<P>
   For the first night of this self-generated experiment, I stayed
at the Merrion, one of Dublin's newest and grandest hotels. Opened
in October 1997 after a $46 million construction project that
included restoring and converting four Georgian town houses, the
Merrion is perfectly situated for those who want a quick infusion
of activity without having to go far.
</P>
<P>
   A five-minute walk in one direction gets you to Merrion Square,
a tiny but lovely park; Ireland's handsome government buildings,
and the National Art Gallery. Five minutes' walk in the other
direction takes you past St. Stephen's Green, another smallish
park, to Grafton Street, which is closed to traffic and brimming
with shops.
</P>
<P>
   But it's worth staying inside. The Merrion murmurs elegance and
comfort from the moment you are greeted in the marble-filled front
lobby by an array of staff members whose helpfulness stops just
short of obsequiousness. If checking in tires you out, there are
several restful drawing rooms on the ground floor, decorated with
French chandeliers, plush period furniture, and Irish art from the
private collections of the chairman of the hotel and one of its
directors.
</P>
<P>
   The day's newspapers are laid out; drinks and snacks (including
proper Irish tea, with cakes and sandwiches) are available; there
is a cocktail bar, called No. 23, at the far end.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is large, with 125 rooms and 20 suites, but doesn't
seem impersonal. The more expensive rooms are in the old part _
each is based on a real room from one of the original houses _
while the rooms in the newly built Garden Wing, connected to the
main house by a glass walkway, are slightly cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   My room (one of the latter) was spacious and traditional but
full of modern conveniences like a fax machine, a well-stocked
minibar and a large umbrella. The room opened into a gratifyingly
oversized bathroom, which offered a delightful choice: a deep
bathtub with a very large hand-held shower attachment, or a big
separate shower with clean architectural lines and vigorous water
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But it was only early afternoon, and, sadly, not yet bathing
time. I made my way down to the hotel's gym and spa in the
basement, to be greeted by a stunning sight: It was deserted.
Either no one else felt like exercising on a Thursday afternoon, or
exercise is not high on Dublin's list of priorities. There was one
man in the pool, so slow and unthreatening that I figured the
chance of his kicking me in the head and yelling at me to move was
minimal.
</P>
<P>
   The pool was a pleasure, dark blue with a water level so high it
spilled from the edges and onto the floor, and the small gym had
individual televisions and headphones connected to the treadmills,
so that you could actually hear something other than your own
tortured breathing. I collapsed in a chair by the pool, wearing my
fluffy white Merrion-provided towel, and plucked grapes from the
fruit bowl while reading fashion magazines.
</P>
<P>
   I rolled upstairs. Because it was my night on my own _ my
husband wasn't scheduled to join me until the next morning _ I
thought I would do something cultural instead of sitting around.
Maybe I could take myself to the movies. But the concierge's cheery
alacrity in response to my request for a movie schedule was no
match for my inertia.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly the prospect of the outside world seemed awfully bright
and noisy. I took a nap. I watched television. I received several
faxes. I ordered dinner, a baked potato and some steamed vegetables
(not on the menu, but not a problem) as part of the health program
I had apparently started that day. I watched some more television.
I sat in the bath for a long, long time. Then it was time for bed.
</P>
<P>
   My husband, Robert, arrived as I was finishing breakfast on
Friday. It was 10:30. The newspapers were spread out across the
bed, covered in crumbs. No more sitting around! I had planned a
morning of activity in the spa. I got a soothing facial; my husband
had a deep-cleansing back massage. During my facial I fell into
another doze, punctuated only by the chatter of the attendant.
</P>
<P>
   Scrubbed, buffed and polished, we managed to stagger back to our
room and change in time for our next activity _ a lavish lunch. The
Merrion actually has two restaurants: the Mornington in the
basement, which features contemporary Irish cuisine, and the
elegant Patrick Guilbaud, where we ate, the only restaurant in
Ireland to have two Michelin stars.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant is in a light, airy room with high ceilings, lots
of windows, and more paintings from the proprietors' contemporary
art collections. The food was amazing: Robert had a big slab of
beef, as he always does when he's away from home, and I had a
beautifully cooked chicken breast surrounded by tiny vegetables. We
both had several drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Our heads were spinning as we checked out and traveled by taxi
across town to our next hotel, the Clarence. How could it be as
nice as the Merrion?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the Clarence's most appealing characteristics is its
provenance: originally built in 1852, it was bought in 1994 by Bono
and the Edge, the two coolest members of the supercool Dublin-based
rock group U2. The pair spent almost $8 million on a thorough
overhaul, reopening the hotel as a much more luxurious version of
its past self in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bono and the Edge do not stay at the Clarence when they
are in Dublin _ they have their own houses _ they have succeeded in
lending an aura of glamour to the hotel, situated in the city's
bustling Temple Bar district.
</P>
<P>
   Right on the Liffey River _ a none-too-attractive waterfront
that is poised for a major overhaul _ the hotel is within walking
distance of the scores of restaurants, bars and stores that have
given the Temple Bar the reputation of being Dublin's SoHo.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel is smaller than the Merrion, with only 50 rooms (five
of them suites), and no wasted space. Even the employees reflect
the hotel's minimalist ethos, wearing gray suits with subtle
pinstripes that make them look like extras in the movie
``Gattaca.'' ``Everyone keeps asking if I'm a clerk,'' complained
one staff member, as he rode up in the elevator with us.
</P>
<P>
   The Clarence's lobby is small and intimate, decorated in the
white American oak that forms most of the hotel's interior, and
opens out into an inviting common room known as the study. Here you
can read the papers, have a drink or take light meals in an
atmosphere of pleasant camaraderie (if you find camaraderie
pleasant) at the large table in the middle of the room or one of
the smaller tables nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel's halls are cozy rather than spacious, decorated with
tall, funnel-shaped silver lighting fixtures that during my stay
were each graced by a Granny Smith apple, meant to be a decoration
rather than a snack.
</P>
<P>
   Each guest room is decorated in one of the five colors that form
the hotel's color scheme _ crimson, royal blue, purple, gold and
chocolate _ and ours was red-themed, with an an enormously inviting
white comforter on the bed and interestingly constructed red
curtains that were built to swing back and forth on wooden poles.
</P>
<P>
   Another red curtain separated the bedroom from the tiny entrance
hallway, and the bathroom was a model of the efficient use of
space, with wooden shelves and a bathtub that earned a 5.5 (out of
6) in my own personal tub-rating system.
</P>
<P>
   The room was slightly too small for a long afternoon indoors, so
I strolled through the neighborhood, stopping for a snack at the
Temple Bar Food Market, an open-air market in nearby Meeting House
Square that, each Saturday, sells soup, cheese, baked goods and a
variety of meats, fish and fresh produce. There were a number of
inviting-looking restaurants and cafes in the neighborhood, one of
which had apparently been visited by Quentin Tarantino. (A receipt
signed with his name was in the window.)
</P>
<P>
   There was no gym at the hotel, so my husband stayed in and took
a nap. Dinner was at 7 p.m., the only time they could take us, and
we felt a little put out _ what a ludicrously early time! But the
food was so good that we felt ashamed for quibbling.
</P>
<P>
   After a drink in the popular and unusual Octagon Bar, which
really does have eight perfectly proportioned sides, we moved on to
the Tea Room restaurant, in a long room with a bar at one end,
reachable by a few stairs.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many of the tables were filled with early-shift
diners struggling to get their small children to put the food in
their mouths and not in their hair, we were separated from the
crowds by a discreet partition that gave us the feeling of being
intimate and alone. Not with each other so much as with our food.
</P>
<P>
   Bread is bread and I can take it or leave it, but here, where we
were presented with a selection of exotic breads in different
shapes, sizes and flavors on its own little bread board, it was as
good as a course in itself. I went on to have salmon tartare as an
appetizer and grilled salmon as a main course (salmon, of course,
being an Irish specialty), but was particularly enamored of my
dessert, a selection of apple-themed sweets that included apple
sorbet, apple cream from what looked to be the creme brulee family,
and a kind of apple tart.
</P>
<P>
   We made our way upstairs in high good spirits, which only
improved when Robert put his shoes out to be shined and found that
they had come back an hour later.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, breakfast ordered in our room _ complicated,
because Robert likes scrambled eggs and sausages and local
delicacies made of things like innards, and I like lots of fruit
and yogurt _ arrived on time, and so did the four fat Sunday
newspapers we'd asked for.
</P>
<P>
   We left feeling very rested and very pleased, and eager to get
back to the baby at home, which was part of the point of going away
in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Which hotel to choose? It depends. If you want cutting-edge
ambiance, a happening neighborhood, and a feeling that you might be
among the famous and the fabulous, stay at the Clarence. If you
want to unwind from your incredibly busy life in circumstances of
such luxury that you don't even care what is going on outside your
room, stay at the Merrion.
</P>
<P>
   Or do what I did, and stay at both.
</P>
<P>
   Napping or not
</P>
<P>
   The Merrion Hotel, with 145 rooms and suites, is at 21-24 Upper
Merrion St.; telephone (353-1) 603-0600, fax (353-1) 603-0700.
Double rooms start at $309 a night for two, including tax but not
breakfast. (Prices were calculated at $1.47 to the Irish punt.)
Continental breakfast is $16, Irish breakfast $19 a person. A
three-course dinner for two with a bottle of wine at Patrick
Guilbaud costs around $175. The restaurant also serves a two-course
set lunch for $30 a person without drinks. In the spa, the
deep-cleansing back treatment, 45 minutes, is $59; an hour-long
facial, $74.
</P>
<P>
   The Clarence, with 50 rooms and suites, is at 6-8 Wellington
Quay; (353-1) 670-9000, fax (353-1) 670-7800. Double rooms start at
$257 a night for two, including tax but not breakfast, which is $16
a person for Continental, $19 for Irish. A three-course dinner at
the Tea Room restaurant with a bottle of wine costs around $100 for
two. A two-course set lunch is $20 a person with coffee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
