<SLUG> BC-BBN-BICKLEY_DBACKS-DAAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEP DAAL STRONG WITH NEW CONTRACT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Omar Daal has a decision to make.
</P>
<P>
   He can play the hero, bow to national pressure, succumb to all
the pats on the back. Or, when his bust-out season is in the books,
he can rest his wing for the winter, even if it means alienating
the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Please his country. Or please his employer.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks should make this simple.
</P>
<P>
   If they can rip up Jorge Fabregas' arbitration award, surely
they can avoid potential disaster with Daal. Because the last thing
you want is your potential ace leaving his arm in Venezuela, piling
up innings in winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what we're going to do,'' Daal said. ``We're
going to talk to manager, the pitching coach and make a decision.
I'm the ace in Caracas (Venezuela). Everybody loves me there.
Everybody wants to see me pitch, you know? But if they give me a
new contract where I can take care of myself, they'll have to
understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Since their 8-31 start, the Diamondbacks have posted a better
record than eight of their major league counterparts. Part of this
is because of the incredible emergence of Daal, a left-hander with
a stocked arsenal, a guy who has drawn rave reviews from pitcher
Curt Schilling to Cubs' manager Jim Riggleman to nearly every
opponent who has waved a bat in vain.
</P>
<P>
   If this guy is legitimate _ and all signs are in his corner _
the Diamondbacks should avoid arbitration with Daal, who currently
is earning $575,000. They should give him a nice raise under the
condition he refrain from winter ball. Or, at the very least,
severely limit his appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, the Latin players have done this their
whole lives,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said. ``And many
of them do it as a way to supplement their income.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Wilson Alvarez, who hails from Daal's hometown of
Maracaibo. Every winter, he would feel the pressure from his
countrymen. Every winter, the White Sox would cringe while Alvarez
continued to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Alvarez is 28, recovering from tendinitis in his shoulder.
After missing six weeks, he has lost six of his last seven
decisions. Coupled with a five-year, $35 million deal, Alvarez is
tagged as a huge bust in Tampa Bay. And the pressure is so great
he's begun sniping at teammates.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lesson to be learned here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar is a sharp young man,'' Showalter said. ``He realizes
where he is contractually in his career. There are a lot of things
he and the people who look out for him have to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Diamondbacks, who may have unearthed a jewel
in the expansion draft, a guy seizing his first real opportunity as
a starter. In three stints with the Dodgers, Daal was relegated to
the bullpen. He accumulated nine career starts in separate tours
with the Expos and Blue Jays, teams that also mistakenly slotted
him as a Paul Assenmacher clone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised because I know what I can do,'' Daal said.
``As a reliever, I couldn't use all of my pitches. I'd throw
fastballs and sliders. Now, I'm going to throw any pitch anywhere
in the count. I'm going to show everyone that I can be a starter.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, he's supremely confident. He has a dizzying array of
pitches, including four different speeds of change-up. He throws
them all for strikes.
</P>
<P>
   If he had enough innings, his ERA of 2.58 would rank sixth in
the National League, while his opponent batting average of .233
would rate fifth. If Daal averages 6.2 innings over his final seven
starts, he will qualify for ERA recognition.
</P>
<P>
   He also will have thrown over 162 innings _ nearly double his
previous high.
</P>
<P>
   Do you really want this guy moonlighting in Venezuela, where he
threw 80 innings last winter?
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough,'' Daal said. ``I grew up there. It's not fair to
the people there who want to see me pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you tell a man not to be hero to his people? To the
ones that loved him long before he put on the purple?
</P>
<P>
   Pay him, that's how. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
