<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8632 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-1STLD-     08-18 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: CLINTON'S CALCULATED GAMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to refine writing and tighten throughout.)   (Eds: The following story is an added starter on The New York Times
front page.) 
(Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE,
CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT,
CLINTON-HISTORY.) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his grand jury testimony and his brief and
defiant public admission of an inappropriate relationship with
Monica Lewinsky Monday night, President Clinton is hoping, as he
has so many times in the past, that the public will respond with
forgiveness and not disgust.
</P>
<P>
   The president, relying on polls and his own sense of the
public's weariness with a sordid story of presidential sex, took a
calculated gamble that he can escape indictment by prosecutors or
impeachment by lawmakers over what he declared was a private
matter. In his testimony and his testy four-minute speech to the
nation, he offered partial admissions but refused to answer many of
the questions that have swamped his presidency since January.
</P>
<P>
   And almost before he finished his grudging televised confession,
he turned on his inquisitors and demanded that the investigation of
his private life come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   He confessed, he expressed regret and he asked for instant
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it is time _ in fact it is past time _ to move on,'' the
president said with anger, not anguish, in his eyes, laying the
blame for seven months of national trauma on his political enemies
and Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   His words of apology and contrition were belied by a tone that
was laced with anger and in an important way, unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   He left no doubt that his strategy is the same as it has been
for the past seven months: to give as little ground as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The president sacrificed some of the dignity of his exalted
office by admitting a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was
``wrong.'' But he implied that the investigation that has cornered
him was just as wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has gone on too long, cost too much and hurt too many
innocent people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He sought to justify his misleading testimony and his months of
resistance to federal prosecutors as a fitting response to a
politically inspired invasion of privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is also counting on a continued strong economy and the
forbearance of a public aware that he was a less than faithful
husband even as they were twice electing him to the nation's
highest office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even presidents have private lives,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   But he was largely silent on the more serious accusations _
conspiracy, obstruction of justice, witness tampering and suborning
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   His four and a half hours of questioning by Starr and three of
Starr's deputies was hostile and only added to the anger the
president and his top aides feel about Starr's intrusive inquiry,
according to lawyers present at the session.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lead private counsel, David Kendall, signaled
the continuing hostility in a brief statement after the testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that the president's testimony will finally
bring closure to the independent counsel's more than four-year and
over $40 million investigation, which has culminated in an
investigation of the president's private life,'' the ordinarily
mild-mannered Kendall said with evident contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said later that Clinton had refused to answer many of
Starr's questions and, while candid, the president was less than
complete in many of his responses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's limited expression of contrition was only part of an
emerging White House strategy to continue fighting Starr on broad
legal and political fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has privately raged at Starr, believing he is a
Republican artisan and a blue-nosed moralist prying into the
president's private behavior. He has dispatched a dozen aides and
defenders to demonize Starr and question the legitimacy of his
investigation. That explains his long refusal to answer Starr's
questions about the Lewinsky matter and the scorched-earth legal
strategy he has pursued to delay his date with the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Erskine Bowles, the White House chief of staff, began calling
leading Democrats within minutes of the end of Clinton's grand jury
session, coordinating a political counteroffensive. The Rev. Jesse
Jackson appeared on television Monday night to hammer Starr for
intruding on the private lives of the president, his wife and
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone thought Bill Clinton would come away deeply humbled
and considering resignation, they were wrong. He will fight.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's most difficult day in office is now behind
him. What now lies ahead?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike President Reagan after the Iran-Contra debacle, Clinton
cannot simply confess error, shoulder responsibility and dismiss a
handful of top aides. In the Lewinsky matter, the fault was not in
the president's policy, but in himself. It is vastly harder to
repair a reputation than to repudiate a failed policy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the investigation by Starr is far from over. Whatever
errors or evasions Clinton admitted today must be weighed in light
of voluminous evidence collected over seven months that the
prosecutor may believe add up to the ``high crimes and
misdemeanors'' standard for impeachment set by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   It is now up to Starr how to portray the president's actions and
his words in a report expected to be delivered to Congress this
fall. But however the president is ultimately judged by Congress,
he must also confront the judgment of the citizenry, which has thus
far been indulgent of its wayward president while also finding his
personal standards of morality and honesty distasteful.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   His job approval ratings have remained in the mid-60's. But a
growing proportion of the public came to believe he was stingy with
the truth, a fatal affliction for a politician with ambitions for a
legacy among the top ranks of American presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewinsky saga would be little more than a sordid national
soap opera if the stakes were not so great. Many observers believe
that the Serbs in Kosovo, Saddam Hussein in Iraq and perhaps even
the terrorists who attacked United States embassies in Kenya and
Tanzania were emboldened by a perceived power vacuum at the White
House. ``It is no coincidence,'' said a top-ranking official of the
State Department, ``that the really bad guys of the world, like
Slobodan Milosevic and Saddam Hussein, have picked this summer to
cause the United States trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   And the American people, enjoying economic bounty and 20-year,
record-low gasoline prices, have sacrificed a measure of national
pride because of the sex-stained spectacle playing out in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scandal has prevented people from feeling better about
the country because the principal complaint about the country is
its moral climate,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew
Research Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   And despite recent polling that indicates Americans are willing
to again forgive the president his trespasses, Kohut said the
public verdict is not so certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has the last and often a counter-intuitive word on
issues like this,'' Kohut said. ``The public is not so predictable
and the impact on the president and the presidency I think is yet
to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he falls from grace, we will look for someone with grace to
replace him in 2000,'' Kohut concluded. ``It will be the equivalent
of Jimmy Carter in 1976, a search for character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
