<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 01:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8637 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOLF-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI     08-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLF-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURRAY'S DEATH A LOSS FOR SPORTS AND LANGUAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ As with everything else, the business of
writing about sports isn't what it was. Heroes are harder to find,
stories are more complicated, motives are muddled ... well, I don't
have to tell you. You read sports.
</P>
<P>
   What you might not know is sports just got harder, more
complicated and more muddled. The guy who did the best job of
sorting it out, elevating it, humbling it, describing it and
laughing at it, died late Sunday, and I can't tell if I'm more sad
or irked.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray, of the Los Angeles Times and the English language,
hero of the chroniclers of heroes, had the audacity to depart
without a successor, despite thousands of applicants, including me.
</P>
<P>
   He would never dream that such a thing would be needed, because
he always thought what he did for a living was mostly silly and
shouldn't be done by respectable people. He was right, as he almost
always was, but that didn't change the fact that his fellow
sportswriters worshipped him like they never heralded any jock.
</P>
<P>
   The feeling wasn't limited to his professional brethren. Readers
of the Times, and millions who read his nationally syndicated
columns over four decades, were enchanted, enthralled and sometimes
enraged by the wit and insight he used like a sword.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't had the pleasure ... well, whereinhell have you
been? Since 1961, the man rarely missed a big sports event in the
nation or world, and saw it better than any of us, even though he
has been legally blind for about the past 20 years. His columns
became the definitive, often hilarious, summary of every event,
carried by every newspaper that wanted a sports section that didn't
fall asleep in a reader's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at 77, he attended one of the most surreal events in
sports history, the heavyweight fight in Las Vegas that ended when
Mike Tyson bit the ear of Evander Holyfield. As many of us
scrambled to explain the significance and the weirdness, here was
Murray's grasp of the absurd on a tight deadline:
</P>
<P>
   ``As this is written, newsmen are asking whether Holyfield will
give Tyson a return match. Give Tyson a return fight?! What would
Evander have to do _ put ketchup on his ears?! Mustard on his
nose?!
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Tyson should be allowed to fight only a thing that can
bite back ... I don't know what he could do to restore his dignity
and professionalism. Become a vegetarian, for starters.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for the theory that Murray was down to fumes. From
beginning to end, he was the wordsmith, the thinker and the
storyteller that most of us wanted to be, never were, never will
be.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from my limp hi-howaya handshake as an awestruck kid
reporter at the Rose Bowl, my first real encounter with the legend
illuminated the part apart from the writer. On my first World
Series assignment as a freshly appointed P-I columnist in 1987, I
was in the auxiliary press box down the left-field line at Busch
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The event's novelty for me was exhilarating, until I saw the
name on the press-table seat next to me _ Jim Murray. I started
spasming like Daffy Duck encountering Martian monsters.
</P>
<P>
   He sat down, we shook hands, I mumbled something vapid about how
much I liked his work, then sat there, hanging on to my chair for
dear life.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to him, what in the world can I write that won't
come out like the blather of a 2-year-old? I spent years reading
his stuff out loud and laughing, amazed at how he did it; now I
could do little but sneak glimpses at his screen to see for myself.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he smelled the fear. Maybe he'd seen it before. He started
making small talk about the game. Soon enough he said, ``I have no
idea what to say about this game. Got any ideas?''
</P>
<P>
   Me? You're asking me? Well, uh, I think maybe the pitching, or
maybe the hitting, or ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you're right,'' he said. I can't exactly remember my
inanities, or what else he said, or what I wrote, but getting
validation from Murray, however gratuitous, broke my mental
lock-up.
</P>
<P>
   I learned later that that sort of humble social graciousness was
a Murray hallmark. No one was beneath him, everyone he encountered
was made to seem special. Everything he wrote about was felt, not
just understood, by the reader.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the first big-time national sports commentators to
rely upon the truth as his shield. His honesty and humor opened the
door for Howard Cosell, Sports Illustrated, the ESPN wiseacres,
talk radio and nickel-dimers around the country like me who enjoyed
sports, liked language better and savored edgy newspapering above
all.
</P>
<P>
   I guess it's foolish to be irked. There is no successor to a
pioneer, just followers. We are left to dream about treating
subjects so deftly and words so majestically.
</P>
<P>
   The hole in American daily journalism, large with the deaths
this year of Chicago's Mike Royko and San Francisco's Herb Caen,
grows immense. And sports are out one more hero.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
