<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-MCCOMBS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCOMBS' OFF-SEASON WORK YIELDS PROMOTION AT LINEBACKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A special teams player for the final third of last season, Tony
McCombs hardly seemed a candidate to advance to a starting outside
linebacker spot this year.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs' emergence as an impact player has been the surprise of
training camp so far. It's perhaps less of a surprise to his
position coach, Glenn Pires, who worked with him in the off-season
to learn the intricacies of his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony plays with a high motor,'' Pires said. ``He plays hard
and he plays physical.''
</P>
<P>
   But tackling the nuances of the defense proved more elusive to
McCombs than tackling, say, Terry Allen. His whirlwind rookie
season hadn't been an adequate learning forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got hurt,'' said McCombs, who suffered a stress fracture in
his foot at midseason. ``When a young player first comes in here,
it's tough enough learning this system, but that injury set me
back. I'd never been hurt before. I thought I'd never get
injured.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though McCombs healed in time to play the final five games,
almost exclusively on special teams, he didn't appear to be a
contender for a starting spot this season. But when middle
linebacker Eric Hill left via free agency and the coaches moved Ron
McKinnon to the middle from the right side, they had few
alternatives outside.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs was promoted to the first team over Terry Irving and
Patrick Sapp after the first intrasquad scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn spent a lot of extra time with me,'' McCombs said. ``I
knew the spot was wide open for the best man to win. Right now, I
think I've got a good opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one that few sixth-round picks from small schools _ McCombs
was drafted in 1997 out of Eastern Kentucky _ get.
</P>
<P>
   McCombs caught the coaches' eyes early. He is big (6 feet 2, 246
pounds) and athletic _ ``A thick guy,'' Pires said _ and has
strength at the point of attack. He blocked a punt in Week 3 at
Washington that set up a touchdown. He made 13 tackles on the
special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was coming along,'' Pires said. But he wasn't quite there.
</P>
<P>
   Those private tutorials with Pires _ observing, absorbing and
retaining _ along with the personal friendship McCombs struck up
with Jamir Miller, who had played the right side before moving to
the left last year, are proving valuable.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said McCombs became a student of the game, ``the first
thing necessary for anyone who wants to take his game to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it wasn't so much by me sitting him down and telling him
everything,'' said Miller, the senior member of the linebacking
corps. ``It was more Tony watching me, seeing how I did it. He had
all the tools. He just didn't know how best to use them in this
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That took me back a couple of years because that's exactly how
I learned from Seth Joyner. I learned everything from Seth, but it
was more by me watching than asking. I see Tony now doing some of
the same things. Glenn encouraged me to talk to him and work with
him, and we built a personal friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd better be ready. Teams have established in preseason that
they're going to run away from our left side. They're attacking the
opposite side. Tony is going to get his opportunities to make
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   While the early returns on McCombs were encouraging enough for
the coaches to promote him, the appointment is not permanent.
Irving remains in contention _ the coaches like his experience,
professionalism and playmaking.
</P>
<P>
   But McCombs is the leader in the clubhouse with his ability to
battle a tight end, or take on a fullback on an isolation play, or
rush a passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no such thing as a comfort zone,'' said Dave McGinnis,
defensive coordinator. ``That's not where we are as a team, and
that's not where we are as a defense.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
