A8640 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTEBOO     08-18 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDINALS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE LANDS BROWN NO. 2 JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hitting his first nine passes Friday night didn't clinch the
backup quarterback job for veteran Dave Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did directing a drive in the final four minutes to run out
the clock in the 27-24 victory over the Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   The clincher was Brown's 53 career starts to Stoney Case's one.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin announced Monday that Brown will begin the
season as the No. 2 quarterback behind starter Jake Plummer and
will play the fourth quarter of Saturday's preseason game against
Seattle at Sun Devil Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stoney has had a tremendous camp, and I think he's very, very
close,'' Tobin said. ``But sometimes as a head coach, you have to
go on gut feelings. The experience Dave has . . . if he has to come
off the bench and play, you want that experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Case and Brown have been effective running the team's new West
Coast offense in the preseason. Case, a fourth-year pro, completed
12 of 21 passes for 126 yards and one touchdown in the preseason
opener at Detroit. Brown was 16 for 24 for 121 yards and was
intercepted once against the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I had to come in and play well against the Bears,''
said Brown, a three-year starter for the New York Giants who signed
a two-year, $2.5 million free-agent deal with the Cardinals in the
off-season. ``I couldn't afford to come in and waste my
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Case was disappointed with the decision but chose his words
carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows how I feel,'' he said. ``It's no secret.'' &QL;  &QL; 
Talks to resume &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After not speaking for more than a week and a half, the
Cardinals and the agent for unsigned first-round draft pick Andre
Wadsworth are expected to resume negotiations soon.
</P>
<P>
   Wadsworth, the Florida State defensive end who was the third
pick overall, is one of only two first-round picks not signed. The
other is Nebraska defensive tackle Jason Peter, the 14th pick by
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State running back Curtis Enis, the fifth selection
overall, signed a three-year, $3.6 million with the Chicago Bears
on Monday. The deal included a $3 million signing bonus but no
voidable years or buybacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't seem to be close contractually,'' said Wadsworth's
agent, Eugene Parker. ``But we're still maintaining a positive
attitude to get things done.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin said Wadsworth's 25-day absence from training camp hasn't
been a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a high priority in the players' minds,'' he
said. ``They have their own jobs and their own families to feed. I
said from the beginning I'd like to have him. When he gets here,
he'll have holes in his game that you never catch up. We've moved
on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Short shots &QL;  &QL; 
The Cardinals released four rookies on Monday _ seventh-round draft
pick Ron Janes, a fullback from Missouri; punter Marcus Williams of
Tempe McClintock and Arizona State; defensive end Terry Wilkerson
and defensive lineman Desmond Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Rob Moore missed practice because of the birth of
his son, Satchel.
</P>
<P>
   Fullback Larry Centers (hamstring) and cornerback Ty Howard
(knee) returned to drills.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals said their attendance for the Bears game was
33,082, not the 30,983 announced. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
