<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8641 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-SMI     08-18 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-SMITH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLIND-SIDE BLOCKING KEY TO ASU'S SMITH  
 LEFT TACKLE PROTECTS QB IN OBSCURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BECKY GRUHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAYSON _ Marvel Smith carries one of the heaviest yet least
heralded responsibilities on the Arizona State football team.
</P>
<P>
   As left offensive tackle, he's the man charged with protecting
quarterback Ryan Kealy's blind side.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most high-profile position on the line with a
right-handed quarterback,'' offensive coordinator Dan Cozzetto
said. `You're playing out in space a lot, in no-man's land.
Marvel's kind of on an island out there, always going against the
best pass rusher on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``His game's gotta be right every snap.''
</P>
<P>
   The importance of the job doesn't guarantee acclaim, however. In
fact, if his name wasn't printed on the back of his No. 71 Sun
Devils jersey, chances are most fans wouldn't even know Smith was
on the roster.
</P>
<P>
   It's a life of anonymity masked by a helmet and pads. A life
with which the 6-foot-6, 300-pound sophomore is perfectly content.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is probably the last one mentioned after any win,'' he
joked. ``You know you're not going to get any spotlight at this
position. I'm used to it and really don't even think much about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Smith doesn't attract the attention of teammates such
as J.R. Redmond and Kealy, the sophomore has hardly gone unnoticed.
He's already being touted as an honors candidate in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year as a redshirt freshman, Smith played in 10 games,
starting seven. He and right guard Victor Leyva enter their
sophomore seasons with the opportunity to join the small, elite
fraternity of offensive linemen starting for four consecutive
years.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has proven himself capable of rising to a challenge. He
was the first in a family of five siblings growing up in Oakland,
Calif., to graduate high school and attend college. He was also the
first lineman from Oakland's Skyline High School to receive a
Division I scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Now entering his third year enrolled at ASU with a major in
interdisciplinary studies and a minor in English, Smith has not
been forgotten by his hometown fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People call me about every week to see how I'm doing,'' he
said. ``They're giving me support every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago as a junior at Skyline High School, Smith was
envisioning a future just down the road at California. He gave the
Golden Bears an oral commitment.
</P>
<P>
   But after a solid senior season, Smith began getting noticed
outside his home state. He broke his premature promise to the
Golden Bears, telling the coaching staff he wanted to step back and
weigh his options.
</P>
<P>
   Their reaction was anything but understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it seem like I owed it to them to go there and that
I wouldn't have been noticed as much my senior year without them,''
Smith said. ``There was a lot of pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Cozzetto, Smith was convinced ASU would be the
best fit for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically why I came here was to get out and do my own
thing,'' Smith said. ``There's a lot of pressures back home, and I
just wanted to get away and become myself.''
</P>
<P>
   For Smith, that's best accomplished after taking off his uniform
and leaving the game on the field. It's during that time, time away
from football, when he's able to focus all his energy on his other
passion _ writing.
</P>
<P>
   From poetry to short stories to music lyrics, Smith uses his
papers as a canvas and his words and thoughts as paint.
</P>
<P>
   He has dreams of using those skills to work with children or
perhaps even own his own record company someday. Then of course,
there's always those visions of working on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I think about playing in the NFL every day, but
I think about it a lot,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Cozzetto isn't ruling out any future possibilities for his
soft-spoken lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very gifted person,'' Cozzetto said. ``His work ethic
is unbelievable. He's got a goal in mind, he sets dreams and he
works hard to achieve them. You can't say enough about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Smith should prepare for that spotlight after all. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
