<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8652 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LAVENDER-PROVENCE-IND     08-18 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAVENDER-PROVENCE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAVENDER REVIVAL RESCUES PROVENCAL VILLAGES  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business Editors)   (This interesting 1,000-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news, ``i'' international news and ``f'' financial news
files.)  
  
 By MARCUS TANNER  
 c.1998 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMIANE-LA-ROTONDE, FRANCE _ ``In 1949, when I moved here, there
were children and shops,'' said Martin Gilbert, the retired mason
of Simiane-la-Rotonde, an ancient hilltop village in Provence
surrounded by fields of lavender.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a baker, two grocers, cafes... (but) the young have
all gone off to Marseilles, like my daughter. Now I rattle around
this big house with my wife,'' he said, jabbing a finger at a fine
17th-century stone four-story house shadowed by the bell tower.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert is one of the few local people to be seen in the
village's charming but empty streets, carving miniature versions of
Provencal borries (stone huts) in a garage to sell to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph by Henri Cartier-Bresson, exhibited recently in a
London gallery, shows a gaggle of children in Simiane's old covered
market a few decades ago, prancing before the camera. Today the
market is pristine and silent, but for the sound of Gilbert
tap-tapping his borries in the street below.
</P>
<P>
   A similar silence envelops the village pump, where not that long
ago women gathered to wash their clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The church of Ste. Victoire is locked. At the turn of the
century it was a thriving parish, and the patron saint's feast day
was the high point of the year.
</P>
<P>
   A summoner clattered around the winding streets, shouting out a
long program of events which included the blessing of the entire
population of 1,300 in the square and a great procession headed by
four women carrying the reliquary of Ste. Victoire around the
village, followed by dancing and feasting.
</P>
<P>
   These days an old priest comes from the famous cheese town of
Banon once a month to say Mass to a congregation of about 20.
</P>
<P>
   At the neighboring hilltop village of Oppedette, the church is
shut all the time. ``Except for funerals,'' one villager said. ``We
lock it to keep out vandals _ unemployed people from the city.''
</P>
<P>
   With tourism unable to provide an income for many in villages
off the beaten track, the blue and purple fields of lavender that
unfold like a pleated peasant's skirt beneath the walls of Simiane
and Oppedette perhaps offer the only lifeline by which the local
communities will survive.
</P>
<P>
   A few decades ago, even this industry seemed on the edge of
extinction. Farmers were giving up the struggle to scratch a living
out of stony fields on steep hillsides, and then searching for an
often unscrupulous middleman to buy up the lavender and sell it on.
</P>
<P>
   The market was shrinking, as foreign firms turned to synthetic
substitutes for their oil, or to ultra-cheap ``cloned'' lavender
from Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   But French lavender today is big business once again, as public
interest booms in herbs and alternative medicine. Synthetic
substitutes are out.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby town of Apt, a few miles from the much-publicized
Museum of Lavender in Cordes, most shops heavily promote lavender
products. One is devoted to nothing else, selling lavender soap,
lavender shampoo, artful postcards showing lavender fields in
various shades of purple, oils of course, sprays for the kitchens
and potpourris.
</P>
<P>
   The piped music is of cicadas, presumably to give visitors the
feeling of being in a lavender field.
</P>
<P>
   The cognoscenti can muse over whether to buy bags of seeds of
``Lavandin'' (the hybrid, cheaper stuff) or pure ``lavande,'' the
infinitely more expensive wild variety, which only grows above 800
meters (2,500 feet).
</P>
<P>
   The church has tapped into a burgeoning ``New Age'' perception
that herbs, monks and alternative medicine are all intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cistercian abbey of Senanque and at Ganagobie, the monks
have opened sophisticated shops, selling a huge range of lavender
items far removed in quality from English cathedral shop tat.
</P>
<P>
   As well as their own generous range of lavender soaps, oils and
creams, the abbeys promote books in several languages on monastery
herb gardens and the ancient ``secrets'' of lavender, secrets
presumably preserved over the centuries only by the clergy (which
wouldn't be surprising, as the abbeys sit in fields of the stuff).
</P>
<P>
   Five drops drunk in a glass of wine, I read in one book, can
cure ``hysterical vapors.''
</P>
<P>
   The revival of the once moribund lavender industry of Provence
is not, however, a mere side-effect of the growing attraction to
New Age mysticism and alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Simiane's farmers have helped themselves too, setting up a
co-operative that dispatched the middlemen to oblivion. Out, too,
went ``romantic'' looking scythes (except for folk festivals) and
fat copper stills.
</P>
<P>
   While the tourists trundle around Simiane's pottery shop, the
village farmers sweat in the burning August heat, taking their crop
to the large and distinctly unpicturesque modern distillery that
the co-op has set up on the edge of the village.
</P>
<P>
   Mothers and sons join in with their men, stacking the
fast-browning bales into the giant vat. Clouds of steam rise
through the stalks, carrying the precious oil in pipes through a
cold water tank to rows of barrels underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The undulating lavender fields of Simiane and Oppedette may look
as if they are kept on for the benefit of the heritage industry or
for tourists, but the product is, in fact, sold direct to Proctor &AMP;
Gamble and Colgate.
</P>
<P>
   The Cooperative Agricole des Plantes a Parfum de Provence and
its 290 members have seized almost a third of the total French
lavender oil production, three times more than before the co-op was
set up 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Its still a hard living,'' says Claude Coutant, a 30-year-old
farmer, laughing mirthlessly at the notion that the industry's
revival has ensured farmers a comfortable life.
</P>
<P>
   Perspiration streamed from his brow as the lavender was
pitchforked into the vat amid wafts of scalding steam. ``Whatever
money we make goes back into investing in equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Coutant's father and grandfather farmed lavender before him, and
so will he. Lavender will guarantee the survival of a way of life,
if not prosperity. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this interesting 1,000-word article, it must be
purchased _ the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times
Syndicate sales representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
