<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S EXPLANATION FAILS TO QUIET REPUBLICANS OR FIRE UP
DEMOCRATS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A number of Republican lawmakers said on Monday
night that they were far from mollified by President Clinton's
declaration to the nation that his ``not appropriate'' relationship
with Monica Lewinsky was now between himself, his family and their
God.
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators said the televised speech did nothing to
change their feelings that impeachment should be considered if it
is merited by a report they expected to be sent to Congress by
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Democrats, meanwhile, offered muted responses,
with some saying that Clinton had achieved what he needed to in his
speech but others finding it difficult to muster enthusiasm for
their deeply wounded president.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Republican leaders, including House Speaker Newt
Gingrich of Georgia; Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority
leader, and Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the chairman of the House
Judiciary Committee, declined to comment on Monday night, their
spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Others were on vacation and unreachable, their aides said.
Republican strategists have said that before issuing public
pronouncements the party's leaders were likely to analyze Clinton's
performance carefully and the public's reaction to it.
</P>
<P>
   But among senators, there were some sharp attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who is chairman of the Judiciary
Committee, used some of the harsher language to criticize the
president. His remarks came after several days of making
conciliatory comments that had seemed to suggest that impeachment
proceedings could be avoided if Clinton would offer a full and
contrite explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't that pathetic?'' Hatch asked. ``I tell you, what a
jerk. That's the biggest mistake he's ever made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was superb on rhetoric and he was totally inadequate on
facts,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter, a Pennsylvania Republican who is
on the Judiciary Committee. ``He said his testimony was totally
accurate, he didn't ask anybody to lie. But the artful words he's
used in the past leave us a great deal of leeway for serious
charges. I think it presents no plausible defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some of Clinton's most ardent congressional supporters said
they found the president to be a tad too defiant in a speech that
they said could have used more repentance and less forcefulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more hard than I thought he would be,'' said Rep.
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y. ``I thought there would be more humility.
But he was forceful enough. I don't know really whether that works
or not. I think it works for the people who wanted to get it behind
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Dispersed to all corners of the country in the August recess,
many members of Congress viewed the president's statement just like
their constituents, with slippered feet propped up on living room
loungers. And despite seven months of Beltway immersion in the
details of the Lewinsky matter, many lawmakers reacted just like
their constituents, by shaking their heads in disbelief at the
televised spectacle they found themselves watching.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Clinton was testifying before the federal grand jury on
Monday afternoon, White House aides were calling Democratic members
of Congress to implore them to deliver statements expressing hope
that the country could now move beyond the investigation. And
shortly after Clinton's testimony ended, Erskine Bowles, the White
House chief of staff, called leading Democrats and their aides to
inform them that Clinton planned to use his statement to accept
full responsibility for his actions and to express real regret.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of Democratic congressional aides said that it
might take time for Clinton's partisans to rally to his side. ``Our
sense is that members aren't going to be quite ready to go out and
push the White House line,'' said an aide to one top Democrat.
``There's a feeling of betrayal, particularly for the members who
have been out front defending the president with some blind
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, however, gamely took up the call. ``We are all
human,'' said Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa. ``We all make mistakes _
even the president. Most Americans share my belief that it's in our
best interest to put this behind us and move on.'' Harkin also took
a swipe at Starr, calling his investigation ``a sanctioned
witchhunt into the president's personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., said that Clinton ``did what was
appropriate.'' More than that, Frank said, Clinton did what was
necessary. ``He really had to apologize,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Steve Grossman, the national chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, predicted that Clinton's four-minute speech
would have ``a galvanizing effect on grassroots Democrats'' that
would lay the foundation for victory in this November's elections.
He insisted that there was ``a huge reservoir of goodwill'' toward
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The most generous Republican comment came from Rep. Jim Leach of
Iowa, the chairman of the House Banking Committee, who said: ``I
think he did precisely what he had to do, and that doesn't mean the
presidency hasn't been damaged. But it does mean we are all
obligated to proceed with the business of governance in as
constructive a way as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a distinction between character flaws, political
embarrassments and constitutional challenges,'' Leach said. ``We
have the first two, but as yet we certainly don't have the third.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans were almost uniformly critical. Rep. Bob
Barr of Georgia, who has trumpeted the loudest calls for
impeachment, reacted to Clinton's speech by saying, ``So what?'' He
added: ``What really matters is not the president's spin but Mr.
Starr's evidence. That's what I'm waiting to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ed Bryant of Tennessee, was equally caustic. ``An apology
does not exonerate anyone from criminal wrongdoing,'' he said.
``Were that the case, our prisons would be empty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
