<SLUG> BC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS WORLD LOSES A LEGEND IN JIM MURRAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He wore glasses so thick the lenses looked like they could have
been lifted from the bottom of a couple of Coke bottles, the result
of a terrible eye disease that left him almost blind, but there was
never any question about Jim Murray's ability to ``see.''
</P>
<P>
   He could cut to the quick _ to the heart of a story _ like a
butcher's meat cleaver through a tenderloin steak.
</P>
<P>
   When the great columnist from the ``Los Angeles Times'' passed
away Monday, the world of sports journalism took a deep and ragged
breath. For the second time this year, we have lost one of the flag
bearers of our profession.
</P>
<P>
   As we did when Shirley Povich of the ``Washington Post''
preceded Murray a few months ago, we can only stop and pay our
respects, for today we are so much poorer than we were yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   I can't remember the first time I read a Jim Murray column, only
that it left me with tears in my eyes, I was laughing so hard.
</P>
<P>
   We would often run Murray's syndicated pieces in the
``Star-Telegram'' back in the late '60s and early '70s. He was, I
quickly learned as a young rim-man, editing copy between covering
the high school beat, the unchallenged master of the overstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's columns read like the monologues of today's late-night
talk show hosts, only better. Letterman and Leno should only hope
to be so funny.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his subject might be, Murray would make his point again
and again, with usually hilarious and rapier-sharp one-liners that
could leave a reader gasping for air.
</P>
<P>
   After I began covering the Rangers in the mid '70s, I had the
opportunity to meet Murray, but I was way too much in awe of him to
do much more than squeak out a meek hello, then or later.
</P>
<P>
   Talk to Mr. Murray? You gotta be kidding. He lived somewhere up
on sports journalism's Mount Olympus. Me, I was just a kid wannabe.
Still am. If he had merely hinted that he'd like it, I'd have
carried his typewriter all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   I can still remember the story of Murray's first interview with
Mark ``The Bird'' Fidrych.
</P>
<P>
   This must have been sometime late in Fidrych's rookie season in
1976, when he was on his way to a 19-9 season. The mop-haired,
gangly right-hander had captured the imagination of the country
with his penchant for playing in the dirt around the mound and for
giving specific verbal instructions to every pitch he threw.
</P>
<P>
   Fidrych and his idiosyncrasies eventually drew the attention of
every major columnist in the country. ``The Bird'' was a great and
colorful story on his way to being a one-season wonder. Somewhere
along the way, Murray, already a legend in his business, caught up
with the kid who wanted to be one.
</P>
<P>
   Murray waited for the media crowd around Fidrych to drift away
from his locker, then, notebook and pen in hand, sidled over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say,'' Murray is said to have begun, peering myopically
up at Fidrych's boyish face, ``you talk to baseballs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was as good an opening line as any reporter could ever hope
to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was also a man who could walk 18 holes with Jack
Nicklaus, talk to him alone for half an hour after the round, and
never use a quote in his column.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't need 'em. Murray's lines were generally far better than
anything an athlete might have to say.
</P>
<P>
   At the World Series it is common practice for baseball beat
writers to get the choice press box seats and for columnists to be
shunted off to the ``aux box,'' which often is simply a seat in a
section of the stands with a table set up in front of it.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the weather, in other words, and late October in New
York, Cleveland, Boston, Pittsburgh, Baltimore, etc., can be more
than chilly.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for the columnists to shun their outdoor seats
for a spot in the warmer working press room, where the game can be
watched on television screens and the coffee pot is always close
by.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great pleasures in life, when they were still
traveling, was to land at the same table occupied by Murray and
other titans of the business who tended to flock together. Povich,
our own Blackie Sherrod, Edwin Pope, Dave Anderson. Each legends in
their own time.
</P>
<P>
   At those fortunate times, one personal rule superseded all
others: Keep your mouth shut and your ears open. You might learn
something in the presence of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   A baseball anthology on the bookshelf in my office carries one
of Murray's stories. This was one he wrote in 1972, concerning
baseball player Babe Herman and the myth that Herman once tripled
into a triple play (actually Babe doubled into a double play, but
that doesn't make the story any less intriguing).
</P>
<P>
   Murray started it this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``History, Henry Ford said, is bunk. Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   Did George Washington really throw a dollar across the
Rappahannock?
</P>
<P>
   Was that midnight rider really Paul Revere? Or two guys from
</P>
<P>
   Springfield? Did Shakespeare really write those plays? Think
Patrick
</P>
<P>
   Henry really said ``Give me liberty or give me death''? Or did
he say,
</P>
<P>
   ``Lemme outta here, you guys are nuts!''
</P>
<P>
   It's the same in sports. Did Babe Ruth really call his shot in
the
</P>
<P>
   World Series? Did Willie Keeler really say, ``Hit 'em where they
</P>
<P>
   ain't''?
</P>
<P>
   Men usually become legends posthumously. Nothing promotes the
</P>
<P>
   growth of a legend like the demise of anyone who might
contradict
</P>
<P>
   it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that last paragraph that caught my attention because Jim
Murray has been a legend in my business for as long as I can
remember.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't have to die to get there. He literally wrote his own
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And I can't think of anyone who would contradict that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
