<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE LIFTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Chris Pritchett's three-run double and RBI
single propelled the Angels to a 7-2 victory over the Chicago White
Sox Monday night before 22,174 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Chris who?
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett, the first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett's big night helped the Angels increase their American
League West lead over Texas to one game. The Rangers were rained
out in Boston Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Nevin chipped in for the Angels with a two-run homer
(No.8), and starter Steve Sparks (7-2) won his fourth decision in a
row, going seven innings and allowing two runs and nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's runs came on back-to-back homers by Frank Thomas and
Albert Belle in the fourth, Belle's homer a cause for controversy
when a fan reached above left fielder Orlando Palmeiro's glove to
steal what would have been a fly out at the short fence down the
left-field line.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels had no reason to fret, not with Pritchett setting
a career high with four RBI. In fact, before Monday he had a total
of three RBI in his major-league career.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett was called up from Triple-A Vancouver on Aug. 10, when
the Angels placed Darin Erstad on the disabled list. But he is not
the only strange face in the home clubhouse these days.
</P>
<P>
   Six players on the Angels' 25-man roster (24 percent) weren't
with the team the last time the Angels played at home on Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Pritchett, Jack McDowell, Todd Greene, Mike Fetters, Jeff Juden
and Reggie Williams joined the club by either trade (Fetters and
Juden), promotion from the minors (Pritchett and Williams) or
activation from the disabled list (Greene and McDowell).
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to make an equipment manager's head spin, to say
nothing of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You kind of become callous to it,'' said shortstop Gary
DiSarcina, who leads the team by playing in 120 of the Angels' 124
games. ``You say, `All right, the new guys are here.' But you do
your best not to change anything drastically.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like an engine. You fix the broken parts in it.
You try to make yourself mentally used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Disrupting ``clubhouse chemistry is not an issue,'' DiSarcina
says. Not as long as the team is winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're winning, you could have 25 of the most diverse
people on the planet and everything's going to be good,'' DiSarcina
said. ``As long as you have guys with the same goals, I don't care
if you're black, white, yellow, green or an alien. When you leave
the clubhouse, everybody knows you're doing what you have to do to
help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Pritchett's turn Monday, starting with his bases-clearing
double off White Sox starter Jim Parque (3-5) with two out in the
third inning, increasing the Angels' lead from 3-0 to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   That was plenty of support for Sparks, who pitched seven or more
innings for the fifth time in his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Surgery for Hollins: Dave Hollins will have season-ending
arthroscopic surgery on his right shoulder Wednesday at the
Kerlan-Jobe Health Center in Los Angeles. Dr. Lewis Yocum will
perform the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins has been on the disabled list since Aug. 10 with an
inflamed shoulder. He had been bothered all season with a sore
shoulder before he aggravated it when sliding head-first on July
18.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins lost his starting job at third base after the Angels
promoted Troy Glaus from Triple-A Vancouver on July 30. Hollins had
been getting time at first base when he went to the DL.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins hit .242 with 11 homers and 39 RBI this season. He also
made a team-high 17 errors. He is under contract for next season at
$1.9 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
