<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS' OFFENSE CONTINUES TO GO SOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Let's hope the Dallas Cowboys did some
sightseeing.
</P>
<P>
   They offered few visible signs of accomplishing anything
concrete in their trip across the border for Monday night's 21-3
American Bowl loss to the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you count comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Cowboys receiver Jimmy Oliver slip and fall on the
Azteca Stadium turf while returning a kickoff brought a roar from
the 106,424 fans, the second-largest crowd to watch an NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the largely pro-Cowboys crowd didn't have a reason
to laugh, they resorted to jeering the Cowboys' numerous dropped
passes, several interference penalties, two muffed punts and some
botched snaps. Such a performance probably made Cowboys fans glad
to watch something else when ABC pre-empted coverage to show
President Clinton's address to the nation, switching coverage to
ESPN2 at 9 p.m. ABC Sports spokesman Mark Mandel said it was the
first time a ``Monday Night Football'' telecast has been moved to
another network.
</P>
<P>
   With injured running backs Emmitt Smith and Chris Warren on the
sideline for precautionary reasons, the Cowboys' offense offered a
second consecutive poor performance and showed no signs of adapting
to first-year coach Chan Gailey's offense.
</P>
<P>
   And the defense continued its pass-rush woes, minus defensive
end Kavika Pittman, cornerback Deion Sanders and defensive tackle
Leon Lett, who were in Dallas nursing injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts,'' Gailey said after the Cowboys fell to 0-3 in
preseason games. ``It's no fun to lose. I don't care if it doesn't
count.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, who didn't use the absence of the injured stars as an
excuse, was left frustrated, especially with the offense. Rookie
seventh-round pick Tarik Smith started at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the first team's inability to sustain a
drive,'' Gailey said. ``Basically, it's inconsistency. We'll do a
couple of things good then shoot ourselves in the foot. We're also
not making big plays; we have to make big plays on offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman and the first-team offense
played the first three series of the game, totaling 46 yards and
two first downs. They managed no first downs and minus-6 total
yards in their previous outing against the Raiders, a 16-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made too many mistakes offensively to be able to generate
any kind of consistency,'' Aikman said of Monday night's game.
``It's disappointing because we wanted to move the ball better, and
we just made too many mistakes to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys next play the Rams in St. Louis on Saturday night.
And Gailey said he will take a longer look at the starters, which
have played only a quarter in each of the first three games.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots (1-2) came into Monday night's game hoping for a
solid performance after being shut out, 28-0, in their most recent
outing against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The importance the Patriots put on the game was evident from the
outset. New England coach Pete Carroll played his starters,
including quarterback Drew Bledsoe, the entire first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys fell behind 21-0 in the second quarter before
salvaging a field goal to close the first half that included three
Patriots touchdowns that were nullified by penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Drew was sharp, and I thought the running game did
pretty good,'' Carroll said. ``Sedrick Shaw did a good job around
the goal line.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, rarely pressured by the Cowboys' defense, completed 9
of 14 passes for 69 yards and directed two touchdown drives.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' first score came after a Gailey gamble on
fourth-and-one failed on the Cowboys' 39-yard line. Fullback Daryl
Johnston was stopped for no gain and Patriots took quick advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw capped the drive with a 9-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe engineered a 63-yard touchdown drive in the second
quarter, featuring two pass interference penalties against the
Cowboys. Shaw scored from 1 yard out.
</P>
<P>
   New England cornerback Ty Law took put the final points on the
scoreboard for the Patriots when he returned a pass from Cowboys
quarterback Jason Garrett 26 yards for a touchdown late in the
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' Richie Cunningham kicked a 40-yard field goal to
close out the first half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
