<SLUG> BC-BBN-EXPOS-DIAMONDBACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENES, DULLUCCI LEAD DIAMONDBACKS OVER EXPOS  
  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The look on David Dellucci's face said it all. Relief. It had
been a long time since he had made a significant contribution for
the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the arrival of Bernard Gilkey in a July 31 trade with
the New York Mets, Dellucci lost his spot in left field. When he
did play, he struggled at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday night against Montreal, Dellucci stepped in to
play center field while veteran Devon White nursed a tight
hamstring and came up with the big hit of the game for Arizona, a
bases-loaded triple in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks went on to record a 6-1 victory as right-hander
Andy Benes won his fourth straight to even his record at 11-11.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Arizona's second in a row and put its record at
47-77. The Expos, making their first visit to Bank One Ballpark
after winning five of six against the Diamondbacks at Olympic
Stadium, lost their seventh in a row and fell to 49-76, just 1{
games ahead of the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   With one out and Travis Lee and Matt Williams on base after
being walked by right-hander Jeremy Powell (1-3) and Jay Bell
aboard as the result of a swinging bunt single, Dellucci hit a ball
over the head of center fielder F.P. Santangelo to the base of the
wall, 407 feet away. All three runners scored easily as Dellucci
cruised into third. After a 1-for-15 slide, it was just what the
doctor ordered.
</P>
<P>
   ``David hasn't played a lot lately, but he's been working
hard,'' Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said ``It was good to
see him come through tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players don't always have to agree with these types of
decisions, but I think David understands the need to evaluate other
players than just him. He'll get his chances along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes was in control most of the night. He had a difficult act
to follow, after left-hander Omar Daal stifled the New York Mets on
two hits through eight innings in a 6-1 victory on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Omar throwing as well as he is, I needed to come up with
a good performance to keep things going,'' Benes said. ``I made
good pitches when I needed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go out and put up some zeroes on the board, that
makes your own hitters relax when they go up to the plate and it's
easier for them to hit the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Tony Batista gave Benes and the Diamondbacks a
1-0 lead with one out in the first inning when he hit a homer to
left field, his 11th of the season. He now has six homers and 10
RBIs in his last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos tied it at 1 against Benes in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Vladimir Guerrero, one of baseball's rising young
stars, hit a one-out double and scored on Chris Widger's two-out
single to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   After their big fourth inning, the Diamondbacks picked up an
insurance run in the fifth against right-handed reliever Anthony
Telford and could have had more.
</P>
<P>
   Batista doubled to right-center with one out and scored on Matt
Williams' two-out line-drive single to left-center that barely
eluded the grasp of leaping shortstop Orlando Cabrera.
</P>
<P>
   Telford walked Karim Garcia and Bell to load the bases before
Dellucci grounded to second for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   Benes, meanwhile, retired nine in a row before leaving after the
eighth. Left-hander Alan Embree set down the side in order in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually thought Andy's last three innings were his
strongest of the game,'' Showalter said. ``He's a strong
second-half pitcher. Hopefully, we'll be able to keep him
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes threw 113 pitches, and his fastball was clocked at 91 mph
when the pitch count reached 111. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
