<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
MEN AGAINST 'BOYS FOR PATRIOTS
</HEADLINE>
 FBN-PATRIOTS-COWBOYS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Nick Cafardo 
c.1998 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's team, the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Though they were booed before the game by the second-largest
crowd in NFL history _ 106,424 _ the Patriots eventually won over
the fans in Azteca Stadium and defeated the Dallas Cowboys, 21-3,
in an exhibition contest Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The first-team offense, which staggered for the first two games
of the exhibition season, showed progress, putting up two
touchdowns and moving the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, who did all their scoring in the first half,
accomplished the following:
</P>
<P>
   1. Drew Bledsoe, though he twice missed a wide-open Terry Glenn
for what could have been touchdowns, had a better rhythm in the new
passing game, completing 9 of 14 for 69 yards in just under a half.
</P>
<P>
   2. Sedrick Shaw gained 50 yards on 14 carries (a 3.6-yard
average) in his best performance of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   3. The offensive line showed signs of being able to run-block,
as Todd Rucci and Zefross Moss moved bodies on the right side and
created opportunities for Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   4. The defense continued to be outstanding, as the first unit
allowed only 118 yards in the first half and Ty Law returned an
interception 26 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was, by far, our best game of the preseason,''
said Patriots coach Pete Carroll. ``I thought Sedrick did a nice
job around the goal line and getting into the end zone. Drew was
also sharp, though he just missed a long one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said, ``That was more along the lines of what we would
like to be. We threw the ball, we ran the ball, and we were able to
connect on third downs. There was a play that we missed to Terry _
it felt great when it left my hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see Terry playing so well. He's really into it
now. I guess I'll blame that one on the altitude because it really
got away from me.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bledsoe was upset about penalties, three of which nullified
apparent scores. ``Whether they were bad calls or great calls, I
don't know,'' he said. ``But we can't have touchdowns called back
because of penalties.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' domination of the Cowboys, who played their No. 1
units on offense (minus Emmitt Smith and Chris Warren) and defense
(minus Deion Sanders) for a little more than a quarter, was even
greater than the score indicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wild first half,'' said Carroll. ``We have to feel
good about getting in the end zone, but we have to clean up our
game to take advantage of some of the big plays. Without the
penalties, I thought we played a heck of a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Not often in recent times has a good defensive stand provided
momentum for the offense, but that changed Monday night. On fourth
and inches from the Dallas 39 with 3:31 left in the first quarter,
defensive linemen Chad Eaton, Mark Wheeler, and Willie McGinest
stopped fullback Moose Johnston dead in his tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The offense didn't fumble the chance. It took only six plays to
score. Shaw gained 15 of the 39 yards, including the last 9 on a
touchdown run around left end after being sprung loose by a nice
block from rookie tight end Rod Rutledge.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the series, Bledsoe completed a 9-yard pass to Lovett
Purnell and Shawn Jefferson made a nifty sideline grab, taking
advantage of defender Kevin Mathis falling down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see that because it provides us with a comfort
zone that we can make plays and the offense will put points on the
board,'' said Law.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second quarter, Bledsoe executed a a superb screen
pass, drawing in the defense and dumping off to Derrick Cullors,
who ran 52 yards down the left sideline. But Ben Coates was caught
holding safety George Teague, nullifying the touchdown, and the
Patriots had to punt.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the quarter, Troy Brown fielded a Toby Gowin punt on
the 30 and ran it back all the way for the score, sprung loose by a
classic takeout block from Tony Carter on Bobby Rodriguez. But the
return will live only on the highlight film _ not the scoreboard _
because Larry Whigham was flagged for holding Izell Reese.
</P>
<P>
   There was a happy ending on this sequence, however. After
Bledsoe threw a knuckleball over the middle that Brown couldn't
handle, he lofted a soft pass into the corner of the end zone to
Jefferson. The pass was incomplete but Jefferson was held by Lee
Vaughn, so the ball was placed on the 1. Shaw went over for the
second score, making it 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   That touchdown came after a 4-yard run by Shaw into the end zone
was called back on a Coates holding penalty.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:08 left in the half, Law intercepted a Jason Garrett pass
intended for tight end Eric Bjornson and scampered 26 yards to
paydirt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sitting on the route and Jason was looking right at
me but he still threw it,'' said Law. ``I was ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaton was immense in the middle of the line, while McGinest put
constant pressure on the quarterback and Ferric Collons was tough
against the run.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas didn't get into New England territory until there were
only 13 seconds left in the half. With the clock ticking down,
Carroll decided to take advantage of the experimental instant
replay rule. He questioned whether wide receiver Billy Davis had
both feet inbounds on a sideline pass that got the ball to the
Patriots' 23. The replay showed that he did, and Richie Cunningham
came on to kick a 40-yard field goal as time expired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
