 LINE-TEX 
COWBOYS OFFENSIVE LINE STUMBLES, AGAIN (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The offensive line was supposed to be the one
thing the Dallas Cowboys could count on this year. But for the
second consecutive preseason game, the line nearly had Troy Aikman
counted out.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman was hit on five of his seven pass attempts Monday night
in the Cowboys' 21-3 loss to the New England Patriots. That none of
the wallops resulted in a sack is more a testament to Aikman's
quick release, which let him dump the ball off to his running backs
before he hit the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding sacks was the only thing that went right on offense.
For the second consecutive game, the Cowboys' offensive attack was
just short of pedestrian. The first team gained 46 yards on 13
plays.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey has raved all summer about how his
offensive line has improved; Nate Newton's waist, Clay Shiver's new
strength, and the additions of Everett McIver and Flozell Adams
gave Gailey confidence that he could move the ball this year
against clubs like the Washington Redskins, who feature Dana
Stubblefield and Dan Wilkinson, and the Arizona Cardinals, who
feature Eric Swann.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night, the middle of the Cowboys' line had trouble
keeping up with a journeyman backup. Patriots tackle Chad Eaton
harassed Aikman all night, slamming Aikman to the Azteca Stadium
surface particularly hard on one play. McIver and Shiver appeared
to be responsible for turning Eaton loose on his romps through the
Cowboys' backfield. But Cowboys coaches will not know for sure what
went wrong until they review film of Monday night's loss, which was
the second consecutive game that the first-team offensive line
could not lead the Cowboys to a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coaches said the blitzes and stunts used by the Raiders
last week were too much for a Cowboys line that was employing
vanilla blocking schemes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Patriots did not use much gadgetry Monday night. It was
man vs. man. And no where did that come into play more than when
the Cowboys tried to go for it on fourth-and-one. Fullback Daryl
Johnston was stuffed at the line by linebacker Willie McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston's failure to gain a foot highlighted the sluggish
running game. Yes, Emmitt Smith (thigh) and Chris Warren (groin)
sat out while nursing injuries. But it's not as if there were a
whole lot of holes for third-string tailback Tarik Smith, who
gained 12 yards on five carries with the first-team offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   So after three preseason games and two scrimmages, the Cowboys
on offense do not look much different from the unit that ranked
20th in total yards last season. And with two games to go before
the season opener against the Cardinals, one wonders how much
improvement they can make.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
