r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX     08-18 1204
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BLAMED FOR ATHLETES' ANTICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last fall, when ESPN invited a panel of athletes, coaches and
sports officials to discuss the reasons for a decline in
sportsmanship, the network opened itself up to more than a little
finger pointing.
</P>
<P>
   The taunting, the spitting, the brawling?
</P>
<P>
   Panelists and viewers of the program seemed to agree: The media
made them do it.
</P>
<P>
   Or, at the very least, the media were responsible for
perpetuating bad sportsmanship by showing taped highlights or
photos of misbehavior ranging from biting boxers to chest-thumping
football players.
</P>
<P>
   Such coverage, the panelists and viewers suggested, prompted
further transgressions and was bound to be imitated by the youth of
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highlights every night are the outrageous and the
unsportsmanlike,'' said Joe Dumars, a veteran guard for the NBA
Detroit Pistons renowned for his decent behavior on a team that
once bore the nickname ``Bad Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   As for its influence on children, Dumars added, ``All these
young guys know what it takes to lead off the sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Burke, former head of hockey operations for the NHL, now
general manager of the Vancouver Canucks, was visibly angry when
asked if he felt the media, especially television, put too much
emphasis on the unsportsmanlike behaviors of a few. In hockey, that
meant showing too many fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll see a great game, 5-4,'' Burke said, by way of example.
``Lots of goals, lots of banging. Lots of great goaltending.
\RLater\S I turn on ``SportsCenter'', and the first thing they show
is the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It drives me crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear media critics tell it, everybody would be a lot better
off if only TV, magazines and newspapers would stop showing, over
and over, those images of Roberto Alomar spitting at the umpire,
Dennis Rodman kicking that photographer, or Deion Sanders strutting
into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, media executives, particularly those for the
major TV sports networks, which get most of the blame, disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly something we think about and discuss, but we
think our first responsibility is to report what happened. We get
very uncomfortable when we make social judgments,'' said Bob Eaton,
vice president and managing editor for ESPN, a company that perhaps
has had the greatest media influence on sports fans in the past
decade thanks to its popular ``SportsCenter'' shows and its three
networks, including the 24-hour-a-day ESPNews.
</P>
<P>
   Eaton's beliefs are echoed by others in sports journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should edit out something that's news,'' said
Steve Robinson, managing editor for CNN/SI and a former senior
editor for the most influential sports magazine of the modern era,
``Sports Illustrated''.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he believed the media could help cut down on
unsportsmanlike behavior by being more selective in what it airs,
Robinson added, ``We're not activists. We're not advocates.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a view not welcomed by one critic, baseball pitcher Orel
Hershiser, who, speaking on the ESPN panel, said, ``The leaders at
the network can change. They can make different choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics suggest that sports media could offer more of a
balance in their coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interpreters of the images on TV and in the print media
have failed to reinforce the good conduct like they do the bad
conduct,'' said Big Ten Conference commissioner Jim Delany. ``They
pay more attention to an unusual event and repeat it. You'll see
someone kick dirt on an umpire 100 times. You might see someone
help someone up once.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' Dallas Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman adds,
``Sensationalism sells.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports media executives say their mission is other than what
critics suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of the networks and all the media is to find the most
compelling story and to tell that story, as well as to adhere to
certain levels of journalistic integrity,'' said Terry Ewert,
sports executive for CBS. ``The ultimate in journalism is truth. As
broadcasters, we would be criticized if we ignored elements that
fit into the story of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, journalists say they're acutely aware of the
sportsmanship issue, and some say they take behavior issues into
consideration when deciding what to air, and what not to air.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the ability through this medium to reach millions and
millions of people,'' said Vince Wladika, spokesman for Fox Sports.
``We have to take it seriously. We have meetings on subjects like
this all the time. We don't have a blanket policy. We take each
situation individually and analyze it.''
</P>
<P>
   At Fox, Wladika said, that can mean leaving out a hot-dogging,
showboating act by a player, assuming it's deemed to be not
newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Sports journalists say an act is newsworthy when it has an
impact on the game, the team or the player in some important way. A
basketball brawl or a baseball beanball scuffle gets airtime,
network executives say, as do off-the-field problems.
</P>
<P>
   It is not, they maintain, simply a case of, ``If it bleeds, it
leads,'' the credo of the sensationalist media.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the taunting of opponents is generally ignored on
sports shows, they add, as are outbreaks of rowdy behavior by fans
in the stands. In most cases, they say, these incidents don't
affect the story of the game. Further, media executives say, they
don't want to promote copy-cat actions by viewers watching such
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sports news sources aren't the only media outlets under scrutiny
in the sportsmanship debate. Corporate America, through its
aggressive marketing and advertising of sports-related products,
has also drawn attention.
</P>
<P>
   Two advertisements on display in a recent ``ESPN Magazine''
reflect the change in corporate attitudes toward the importance of
sportsmanlike behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A computer game called ``NFL Xtreme,'' endorsed by the NFL, is
touted as ``gridiron war. There's no rules, no penalties and no
boundaries,'' according to the advertising copy. ``It's a
helmet-popping, trash-talking, late-hitting free-for-all.''
</P>
<P>
   Another advertisement, for adidas athletic shoes, suggests, ``Be
at war with your opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``ESPN Magazine'' is geared toward a young readership, a fact
clearly known by the two advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Sports media executives agree that whether or not there actually
is more unsportsmanlike behavior today, there certainly appears to
be. That's because a viewer can now watch the same highlight clip
repeatedly throughout the day, whether on the same station, or on
different networks across the dial.
</P>
<P>
   Says Robinson, ``Perhaps it does give the impression that
there's more today.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of media coverage suggest that the more unsportsmanlike
behavior shown, the worse it is for society. But Robinson, for one,
says there might be some redeeming quality in exposing such acts to
viewers and readers, no matter how unpalatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's a good thing for people to see this stuff,'' he
said. ``If a brawl is portrayed in a way that shows that it's
really ugly, maybe people will think something should be done about
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
