<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-BULLPEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAILOUT ON WAY FOR RANGERS' BELEAGUERED BULLPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Left-hander Scott Bailes, who Monday rejoined the Texas
Rangers in Boston, pronounced his left shoulder ready for duty.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates will decide when Bailes resumes his role in
the Rangers' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Bailes, who went on the 15-day disabled list Aug. 1 with
bursitis in his left shoulder, could be reinstated as early as
before the second game of Tuesday's scheduled doubleheader against
the Red Sox at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Rain forced Monday night's game to be rescheduled as part of
Tuesday's day/night doubleheader. The Red Sox scheduled the first
game for 12:05 p.m. and the second for 5:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that with the bullpen the way it was that we would
be better off by not making a move and standing pat for a day or
two,'' Oates said. ``We could make a move between games (Tuesday)
depending on what happens in the first game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' four-game series with the Yankees in New York taxed
their bullpen. Right-hander Danny Patterson and left-hander Eric
Gunderson pitched Friday, Saturday and Sunday. Right-handers Xavier
Hernandez and Tim Crabtree pitched Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers require right-hander Al Levine in the bullpen
should the need arise for a long reliever. Oates does not want
Bailes being forced to pitch three or four innings in his first
appearance after a medical rehabilitation assignment with Double-A
Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   Bailes pitched Friday and Saturday for the Drillers and said his
arm ``feels better than it has in a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailes passed one test by pitching consecutive days without
discomfort, but his velocity dropped during his second appearance.
Bailes' fastball registered 88-91 mph during his appearance Friday,
but it fell to 86 mph during Saturday's appearance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That showed that it might not be best for me to pitch
consecutive days until I get a couple of innings under my belt,''
Bailes said.
</P>
<P>
   Bailes could provide the Rangers' bullpen a shot in the arm upon
his return should he pitch effectively. The Rangers missed Bailes
even more during Gunderson's recent struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was not a good situation,'' Gunderson said of his
performance combined with Bailes' absence.
</P>
<P>
   However, Gunderson enters Tuesday's games with 2 1/3 scoreless
innings in his past four appearances. That includes the critical,
inning-ending, double-play ground ball he induced from Yankees
first baseman Tino Martinez, a left-handed batter, during the
seventh inning of Sunday's 6-5 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I've worked some things out and will pitch better
now,'' Gunderson said. ``The most important part of our season is
coming up. What's in front of us is far more important that what I
did the past two weeks. Plus, we're going to get another lefty back
in the bullpen, and that will help.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
