</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTIFY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY PROVIDED BY BILL AND HILLARY CLINTON AND PREVIOUS
PRESIDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also see: CLINTON-RDP, CLINTON-PSYCHE, CLINTON-PROCESS,
CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-FRIENDS, CLINTON-GORE, CLINTON-SCENE,
CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-MEDIA, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-REACT,
CLINTON-NIXON.) 
(js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Following is a list of the times when President
Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton, as well as other presidents
over the last two decades, have provided testimony. Clinton is the
first president to testify in a criminal investigation of his own
conduct, but other presidents have testified in criminal matters.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony by the Clintons
</P>
<P>
   June 12, 1994 Clinton and his wife, Hillary, provide sworn
testimony to Robert Fiske Jr., the independent counsel
investigating the Whitewater matter. The president and Mrs. Clinton
are questioned separately in the White House. Clinton spends 90
minutes answering questions from Fiske and his deputy. Mrs. Clinton
is questioned for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   April 22, 1995 The president and Mrs. Clinton are questioned in
the White House by the new Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth
Starr, and his aides. Clinton's interview lasts about two hours.
Mrs. Clinton's interview also lasts about two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 16, 1996 Mrs. Clinton testifies for more than four hours
before a federal grand jury in Washington investigating the
disappearance and sudden recovery of billing records from her
former Arkansas law firm that detail some of Mrs. Clinton's legal
work on Whitewater-related matters while at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   April 28, 1996 Clinton gives videotaped testimony in a criminal
trial involving his former Whitewater business partners, James and
Susan McDougal. He testifies for more than three hours in the White
House as a defense witness for the McDougals. All copies of the
taped testimony are ordered sealed until played at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   July 7, 1996 Clinton gives a sworn deposition in the trial of
two Arkansas bankers charged with making illegal donations to his
1990 campaign for governor. The testimony is videotaped in the
White House and lasts two hours 20 minutes. The deposition is given
at the request of the defense. The tape is ordered sealed until
played at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 14, 1998 Mrs. Clinton is questioned at the White House for
about 15 minutes by Starr and his deputies concerning the White
House's gathering of FBI background files on political appointees
from past Republican administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 17, 1998 Clinton is questioned for six hours in his
lawyer's office by lawyers for Paula Corbin Jones in her sexual
misconduct suit against him. The deposition is videotaped. He is
asked, among other things, about Monica Lewinsky, a former intern
at the White House, and he denies he had a sexual relationship with
her. In March, Ms. Jones' lawyers release excerpts from the
president's deposition.
</P>
<P>
   April 25, 1998 Starr and his deputies question Mrs. Clinton for
nearly five hours at the White House about her work as a private
lawyer for the failed savings and loan at the center of the
Whitewater investigation. The session is videotaped so it can be
presented to an Arkansas grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 17, 1998 Clinton is questioned for four hours in the White
House Map Room by prosecutors for Starr about his relationship with
Ms. Lewinsky. The questioning is videotaped and broadcast via
closed-circuit television to the Washington grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony by Previous Presidents
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan agreed in November 1987 to respond to written
questions from Lawrence Walsh, the special counsel in the
Iran-contra inquiry. After leaving office, he gave videotaped
testimony in 1990 in the Iran-contra trial of John Poindexter, his
national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter testified on videotape for two prosecutions: one in
1978 in a federal gambling conspiracy case against a Georgia state
legislator, and another in 1980 in a grand jury investigation of
Robert Vesco, the fugitive financier. In 1979 he gave a four-hour
deposition at the White House to a special counsel investigating
accusations of financial improprieties at the Carter family's
peanut warehouse. And in 1980 Carter gave a deposition to the
Justice Department about his conversations with Attorney General
Benjamin Civiletti about an investigation into whether Carter's
brother, Billy, had violated the Foreign Agents Registration Act.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Ford while in office gave a videotaped deposition in the
trial of Lynette Fromme, who was accused of trying to assassinate
him, after the court rejected a White House proposal that he submit
a written statement. Ms. Fromme was convicted in 1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
