<HEADLINE>
POSITION CHANGE NOTHING NEW FOR TCU DEFENSIVE BACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ When TCU dropped in on Kansas for the 1997
season opener, Reggie Hunt _ former all-state tailback _ was back
in his accustomed niche.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a handoff early in the game, the former Denison High
School star whizzed through a gap, ripped off an impressive gain
... and fumbled the ball.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the season generally progressed in a southerly
direction for Hunt and the Horned Frogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad start,'' he says, smiling. ``I get about 12 or 13 yards
and then fumble. From there, it was a bad year _ bad for us, bad
for the coaches, bad for the fans, the student body, the people in
the community ...''
</P>
<P>
   But this is a new season, and Hunt _ moved back to the secondary
after the fourth game last fall _ is figuring to fill a key spot in
coach Dennis Franchione's innovative 4-2-5 defensive scheme.
</P>
<P>
   And Hunt is feeling good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like this,'' he says. ``We have a new system, a new
coach, and definitely a new attitude. This year is going to be a
whole lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, Reggie, you'll never really miss not carrying the ball
anymore, eh?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just every day,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunt, who became a starter in the TCU secondary as a
freshman in 1996, is realistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a running back was always my thing,'' he says, ``but
there are an awful lot of good running backs. This way, I think I
can contribute more right now _ and I have two full years to learn
this system and settle in.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly the way Franchione has it figured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew about Reggie's athletic ability when we came here,''
he says. ``I just felt that what he needed most was a position. He
needed to find a particular position on the team and stay there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he just keeps bouncing around from spot to spot, he'll
never learn any position, and that doesn't help any of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The position Hunt is learning is weak safety _ the spot occupied
on Franchione's New Mexico team last year by former Lamar High
School standout Scott McGarrahan, who won All-Western Athletic
Conference recognition.
</P>
<P>
   It is basically the ``extra'' safety position in Franchione's
three-safety secondary scheme specifically devised for the
pass-oriented WAC.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll line up on the weak side of the formation and give us
extra run protection,'' Franchione says, ``but he's also always in
the pass coverage scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key man back there is probably the free safety, because
he's the `quarterback' of the defense. But the weak safety is a
very important cog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, if that player plays well, the defense plays well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt says he likes the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying it,'' he says. ``It's a defense that can be
confusing to the opposing offense, but it's not really difficult to
learn. I'm not having a problem with it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for that daily yearning ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw a good running back who didn't want to carry the
football,'' Franchione says. ``It's natural, but he'll have a
chance to touch the ball on kickoff returns, so he won't be
completely away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the experiment in the offensive backfield last year
produced only 89 yards on 27 carries, Hunt did average 27.1 yards
on 10 kickoff returns after leading the team in that department in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs hope he will become the defensive back he was two
years ago, when he had 55 tackles, two forced fumbles and two sacks
after becoming a starter at midseason.
</P>
<P>
   As a high school senior in '95, Hunt was all-district both ways
and all-state on offense when he ran for more than 2,000 yards and
scored 40 touchdowns while leading Denison to a 15-1 record and a
berth in the state finals. His ankle injury in a semifinal victory
against Mount Pleasant probably doomed the Yellow Jackets to a
lackluster finish _ a 31-8 loss to La Marque in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get a little twinge in that ankle occasionally,'' Hunt
says, ``but mostly I get a lot of grief about that La Marque game
from all the guys on this team that are from that area down there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days, I considered myself mainly a running back, but
I always thought I might be able to live on my defensive ability if
I had to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
