<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYER TAMES TIGERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Radar guns don't register efficiency and location.
They measure speed, not guile. They don't tell you a thing about
Jamie Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariner left-hander has the look of a batting-practice
pitcher who lobs fat ones across the plate. But his smooth delivery
and fluctuating velocity confuse overeager hitters. They flail and
lunge and head back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   In his own way, Moyer overpowered the Detroit Tigers Monday
night. Backed by Ken Griffey's two-run double in the first inning
and Russ Davis' RBI single in the sixth, Moyer pitched the Mariners
to a 3-1 victory in front of 38,639 fans at the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer improved to 10-8, a record suggesting an average season,
even disappointing compared to last year's 17-5. But he might be
having a better year now. The Tigers won't argue.
</P>
<P>
   In four outings covering 301/3 innings, he has given up just two
earned runs against Detroit, an ERA of .059
</P>
<P>
   ``There are usually one or two teams a year you have success
with, one or two you don't,'' Moyer said. ``Why? I don't have an
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers were also clueless. They sat in the dugout, eager to
attack. You see Moyer on the mound, all 6-feet and 170 pounds of
him, an unimposing presence who throws junk. The deduction is that
he can be had.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like you could take some good hacks against him,''
said Detroit third baseman Gabe Alvarez. ``But then you get up
there and the ball is right off the corners and every pitch is
knee-high.''
</P>
<P>
   More than staring them down, Moyer studies hitters. He plays
games, outguessing them. They think fastball, he throws a change or
vice-versa. Every five days, Moyer conducts clinics. Monday night,
the Tigers were unwilling participants just as they have been all
season.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer needs perfect location and varying speeds to succeed. His
typical fastball travels at 85 mph. His change is consistent at 73
mph. The cutter, a combination of a fastball and slider, might come
in at 80 mph. He's a cab driver on the mound, hitting the brake and
then the gas, a herky-jerky master of motion and deception.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer studies hitters, knowing strengths, exploiting weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does it better than any pitcher I've ever seen,'' said
catcher John Marzano.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Piniella points to Moyer's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might have the best walks-per-inning-pitched ratio in
baseball,'' the Mariner manager said. Moyer walked one, lowering
his average to 1.7 for every nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   So you know you're going to get something to hit. But there is
too much hesitancy and not enough patience. All the while, Moyer
mixes his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about getting up on the plate,'' Alvarez said.
``Then he started busting everybody inside. He made it extremely
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth inning, Alvarez stood in the box with the bases
loaded. Thankfully, Moyer was gone, replaced by Mariner closer Mike
Timlin. That calls for another adjustment, trying to get around on
fastballs and sinkers in the low 90s. Alvarez bounced into a
forceout.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer reduced his ERA for the season to 3.55, an improvement
over 3.86 last year. The difference is that the Mariners have not
supported him with enough help from the bats and the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   He found assistance Monday night. Griffey's bolt off the
left-center-field wall, the first of his two fence-rattling
doubles, brought home Joey Cora and Alex Rodriguez. Tiger starter
Brian Moehler was rocked before he registered the first out.
Griffey did not homer Monday night, remaining at 42 and on a pace
for 56, which would match his total from '97.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin got the last out in the eighth and struck out Paul Bako
to end the game for his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer escaped two earlier jams with two runners on. The Tigers
failed to capitalize because of identical developments. In the fith
and seventh innings, Bako lined out to Shane Monahan in left field.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners improved to 56-66 and remained 10 games behind the
Angels. Even if the M's go 29-11 in their final 40 games, the
Angels could go 19-19 and still win the AL West title at 86-76.
That doesn't even factor in what the Rangers might be doing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners need to face the 48-74 Tigers more often in the
stretch. They have taken five straight from Detroit but only have
one game remaining Tuesday night at the Kingdome. Paul Spoljaric
will face Seth Greisinger at 7:05.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had success against Detroit,'' Piniella said. ``I hope
it continues for one more day.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an important eight-game homestand against weak
opponents. The Mariners need to win every game against Detroit,
Toronto and the Chicago White Sox or at least go 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no room for losses,'' said third baseman Russ Davis,
who played his ninth consecutive game without making an error.
``We're 10 games back. It's reachable. It's been done in the past.
As long as we take care of our part, hopefully other teams will do
their part and lose.''
</P>
<P>
   After the homestand, the Mariners face a daunting nine-game road
trip that takes them to Cleveland, New York and Boston, confronting
the three best teams in the American League.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
