<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AGGIES-TEX </SLUG>
 
LINEMAN'S DECISION PAYS OFF FOR TEXAS A&AMP;M (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Junior guard Semisi Heimuli is
scheduled to start his 26th consecutive game in the offensive line
for Texas A&AMP;M when the Aggies line up against Florida State in the
Kickoff Classic on Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Where he might have been on that day if his former coach at
Trinity High School in Euless, Texas, had not talked him out of
returning to California five years ago is open to conjecture. Not
all of the possibilities are pleasant to contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back home now and see my old friends and not one of them
is playing at a big college or anything like that,'' Heimuli said.
``Some of them have been locked up. A couple of them are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Heimuli, born in San Francisco of Tongan heritage, moved to
Euless with his father in time to enter Trinity High School. But
late in his sophomore year, he was so overcome with homesickness
that he decided to go to the West Coast to visit his mother. The
visit only exacerbated his California dreaming, and he decided to
return there to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt out of place in Texas,'' Heimuli recalled. ``The
pace was just so much slower.''
</P>
<P>
   Heimuli had to clear one obstacle, however _ getting Trinity
football coach Ed Hickman to sign forms for dropping classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got signatures from every one of my teachers,'' Heimuli
said. ``But I couldn't go to coach Hickman. I saved him for last. I
even tried to get one of the assistant coaches to sign my sheet,
but he wouldn't do it. When I finally walked into (Hickman's)
office, I couldn't talk or look at him straight in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Hickman left no doubt where he stood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tore up his drop sheet and told him to go back to class,''
Hickman remembered. ``I said, `Son, if you stay here, you're going
to go on to be a big-time player in a big-time program.' And he
has. I'm very proud of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Heimuli hasn't looked back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he talked me out of it,'' Heimuli said. ``He told me
that if I went back home, some not-so-good things could happen to
me. What he said made a lot of sense. I lived in a rough part of
the Bay Area. There were a lot of gangs. Everyone was going at
everyone _ Tongans against Samoans, Samoans against Mexicans,
Mexicans against blacks. It was pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Add A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum to the list of those happy that
Heimuli chose the route he did. Not only has Heimuli (6-foot-1, 310
pounds) become an anchor for the offensive line, he has helped the
Aggies recruit two more highly regarded line prospects from Trinity
_ redshirt freshman and fellow Tongan Moses Vakalahi (6-5, 295) and
freshman Chris Montgomery (6-8, 335).
</P>
<P>
   Plans are to hold out Montgomery for a redshirt season, where he
won't play but will practice and have four years of eligibility
remaining. Vakalahi will be a swing backup at tackle this fall,
primarily playing behind senior Rex Tucker. Right tackle Cameron
Spikes and Heimuli are the two returning starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some holes to fill, but we have some candidates,''
Slocum said. ``It's time for Semisi to take it up a notch. To this
point, he's been the tag-along to the experienced guys like (center
Koby) Hackradt and (guard) Steve McKinney, a guy you plug in to
fill a hole. But now he's one of those veterans who has played a
lot and we need him to step it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said Heimuli has compensated for a relative lack of
height with tenacity, an unusual football IQ and maturity gleaned
from a strong high school program that enabled him to start as a
redshirt freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably going to be the biggest and best offensive
line I've played on since I've been here,'' Heimuli said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Aggies hope to have a more efficient and versatile
passing game this season to complement a respected running attack,
the offensive line is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen how well they play and how soon they
play well,'' Slocum said. ``But considering the guys we open up
with, it better be the first ball game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
