r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-USC-LADN     08-18 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 PUNISHES USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC has been stripped of a men's basketball
scholarship for the 1999-2000 school year because last season the
university's director of compliance misinterpreted NCAA rules and
awarded one scholarship above the limit.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific-10 Conference penalized USC after discovering that
walk-on guard Claude Green was illegally awarded a scholarship last
season. USC director of compliance Leslie Daland approved the
scholarship for Green without realizing the Trojans were already
considered at the legal limit of 13.
</P>
<P>
   According to sources, confusion arose because center Philip Von
Backstrom transferred during the school year and his scholarship
was not properly counted when Green received his grant.
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought once Philip left, his scholarship was available,''
a university official said. ``It wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's faculty athletic representative, Noel Ragsdale, said
Monday that USC simply overlooked a provision of the NCAA manual
when it made the mistake. She did not specify the nature of the
error.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good faith error was made,'' Ragsdale said. ``It was a
complicated process of putting together four provisions of the NCAA
manual. One was labeled in a way we didn't look at and that turned
out to be the controlling provision. There were four provisions and
one was overlooked.''
</P>
<P>
   NCAA rules actually call for two scholarships to be eliminated,
but Ragsdale convinced the Pac-10 to reduce the penalty because
USCwas not trying to gain an athletic advantage by giving Green a
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it was awarded to Claude Green was not for athletic
purposes but to help him get his degree,'' Ragsdale said.
</P>
<P>
   USC paid a heavy price for giving Green his scholarship. Green
appeared in just one game last season and played one minute. He
ended up quitting the team before the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Because USC is currently at its scholarship limit, the penalty
goes into effect next season. That means USC coach Henry Bibby will
be able to sign just two players this year instead of three. It is
particularly harmful because this is considered a deep recruiting
class in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans already have an oral commitment from 6-foot-5
shooting guard Nate Hair of Capistrano Valley, and will be limited
to signing one other player.
</P>
<P>
   Bibby is on vacation and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
