<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Clinton should resign
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the admission he lied about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky, President Bill Clinton goes from lame duck to dead duck.
The Clinton presidency is over and the president would do best not
to wait to see if he can hold enough public and congressional
support to linger in office but to resign and let Vice President Al
Gore start a new slate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has lost all moral authority in the office. That he lied
under oath _ or was only ``legally accurate,'' as he put it _ is of
course a legitimate issue of law but in the politically contrived
circumstances of the lie, pretty thin law. The testimony was
inadmissible in a civil suit filed as a political ploy and thrown
out by the judge as groundless.
</P>
<P>
   Crucially, the president lied to the people, on whose sole
authority his tenure rests, and that is a matter of trust. What is
more, with his dodgy language at first, and now apparently
attempting a silly and hopeless distinction about what is and isn't
sex, he lied by coyness. He compounded brazen dishonesty with the
petty con of a barroom grifter.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, as emotionally slovenly and insanely reckless as his
relations with a White House intern were, we still never should
have known of them. The affair was consensual; no matters of state
were involved. We will be a long time sorting through the
hyperkinetic workings of the special-prosecutor law and the
relentless machinations of Clinton enemies that, combined, finally
accomplished their long-sought end of maneuvering the president
into what amounted to a trap.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Clinton's own manifest misbehavior that was the
proximate cause of this presidency's collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The president's perfidy has put the nation through seven months
of psychodrama. It has financially ruined and emotionally
devastated untold numbers of his associates and has drawn from his
defenders prodigies of dissimulation and rationalization that ought
never been asked, or allowed. We can only guess at the damage to
his family.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Clinton's long retreat through a season pinstriped
with backup lines and Kenneth Starr's hounding excesses have
damaged the institution of the presidency, if not beyond repair
then in ways that it will take a long time to fix. Future
presidents will come less to a magisterial office than to hardened
political bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is well-prepared for the presidency. A senator for eight
years, he hasn't been the mere time-server many vice presidents
have been but an active partner in the policies of the
administration and in their execution.
</P>
<P>
   He would come to office against a backdrop of Republican efforts
to make his campaign fund-raising molehills into the mountains of
malfeasance, but that game is mainly a partisan move to block a
Gore nomination in 2000. Most Americans recognize Gore as honest
and would accept him as constitutionally authentic in the office.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton has fumbled away his presidency. He nonetheless has
a case to make to history for his accomplishments, but that case
will be better made now from a private den than from a hollowed
public office _ and better made to a nation composed by his
retirement than uneasy over his tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 0855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8991 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-MIRABILIS-0819     08-18 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-MIRABILIS-0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SMALL ISRAELI SOFTWARE COMPANIES CATCHING EYE OF AMERICAN GIANTS
 &HT;    With photo to be placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ With recent software deals pouring hundreds of
millions of dollars into Israeli companies, the new celebrities
here are no longer army generals or politicians, but high school
dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   In June, America Online announced that it bought Tel Aviv-based
Mirabilis Ltd. for $287 million in cash and up to another $120
million based on future growth. The two-year-old company invented
ICQ, an Internet chat service with more than 14 million users.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the money goes to its four twenty-something
founders -- two of whom never made it through 12th grade -- and one
of their parents.
</P>
<P>
   But, Mirabilis was topped -- in dollars if not in cult fame --
last week when the more conventional software company, Memco, was
bought for $412 million in stock by Illinois-based Platinum
Technology. Memco makes software for securing information stored on
Internet servers.
</P>
<P>
   The two deals highlight the growing Israeli software industry,
where companies are making their marks as acquisition targets or
niche providers.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 Israeli software firms had about $1.2 billion in
sales for 1997, with growth running at about 25 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The growth has been fueled not only by government incentives,
but also by Israeli attributes that mesh well with software
development.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's small population, about 6 million, requires any
software maker seeking sales to aim for a global product. Israelis
are generally highly-skilled and English, the first language of the
Internet, is common here.
</P>
<P>
   Also, hostile neighbors have prompted a defense industry that
emphasizes high technology and spawns entrepreneurs. The founders
of Memco, with about 200 employees and $30 million in revenue last
year, were once in the army's computer unit.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, unlike other industries, software can be developed even
in a country with little land and few natural resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``The starting point for everyone is more or less equal,'' said
Yoav Shaham, vice president of marketing for Israel's Formula
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Formula, a conglomerate of about 30 software companies, makes
products sold around the world for controlling airport lighting
systems, converting European businesses to the new Euro currency
and fixing the so-called Year 2000 bug.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of the few Israeli software companies that has reached
a substantial size, and is making a global impact. It is traded on
NASDAQ and has about 2,200 employees.
</P>
<P>
   But, tiny Mirabilis (Latin for ``Marvelous'') has captured the
most attention lately. Though they have refused most interviews,
the T-shirted, borderline-scruffy, founders made a splash in the
Israeli media.
</P>
<P>
   When one went, unintroduced, to check out the selection at an
upscale car dealership, the salesman took at look at the youngster
and cracked, ``Who do you think you are, one of those Mirabilis
kids?''
</P>
<P>
   The co-founders hatched their idea over games of ping-pong. Most
had been using computers since childhood but were bouncing between
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   They convinced Yossi Vardi, venture capitalist and father of
co-founder Arik Vardi, to invest in the plan. The company grew to
about 65 employees and did not seek to generate revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was to build a community of Internet users so large
that a larger company would want to buy it -- and it worked.
</P>
<P>
   Vardi said the founders are working nights now trying to improve
their product in defense against plans by Microsoft to hatch
another instant chat service.
</P>
<P>
   The key to Mirabilis' ICQ is that it automatically tells users
if any of their friends are also on the Internet, allowing for
instant contact.
</P>
<P>
   Vardi calls the stand against Microsoft a ``David and Goliath''
battle and says it's a familiar role for Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   (Relevant websites: www.icq.com and www.formula.co.il)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
