<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Aug. 18, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Wednesday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INTERNET (San Francisco) _ President Clinton's historic
on-air mea culpa was followed by a historic on-line tidal wave of
instant reaction. News and ``portal'' Web sites like Yahoo logged a
crushing record number of visits from Web users, who unleashed an
outpouring of sound and fury that most agreed signified, well, not
much. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   RAINFOREST-BIRD (San Francisco) _ It has a raucous call, massive
bill and huge wingspan and until recently was thought to be a
sedentary creature. But scientists at two California universities
now say the hornbill may be the key to saving the vanishing
tropical rain forests in western and central Africa. By LARRY D.
HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   LAWSCHOOL-ADMISSIONS (Berkeley, Calif.) _ As UC-Berkeley's Boalt
Hall Law School approaches a second year of post-affirmative action
admissions, officials announced that minority admissions will be up
32 over what they were at the beginning of the 1997-98 school year.
The increase brings the number of minority students enrolled at the
law school to 85 of the total 275 student enrollment. By ROBERTS
SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MASSAGE (San Francisco) _ The city of San Francisco's Board
of Supervisors voted unanimously to place a moratorium on any
future massage parlors in the Tenderloin district, and to restrict
existing ones when there is a change in ownership. The board will
review the bill next week for final passage. By MARIANNE
COSTANTINOU and GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ASIAN-ECONOMY (San Francisco) _ The East Asian economies _ and
now Russia's, as well _ may be bleeding, but timely intervention
can staunch the hemorrhage and eventually restore the patients to
health. That was the assessment of James A. Harmon, chairman of the
Export-Import Bank of the United States. By DAVID ARMSTRONG.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING (Albany, N.Y.) _ For those with doubts about President
Clinton's honesty, a Seattle company is offering a watch that
features a caricature of Clinton against an American-flag backdrop.
Under-the-dial animation produces the effect of Clinton's nose
tripling in length every 10 seconds. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-FORTUNE (Albany, N.Y.) _ ``Wheel of Fortune'' is now entering
its 16th year, started when Merv Griffin preciently determined an
expanded version of the kids' game hangman would translate well to
television. The genius of the syndicated monster is the game's
simplicity. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-REVIEW-MYSTERIES (Undated) _ Tom Clancy's ``Rainbow Six''
(G.P. Putnam's Sons, $27.95, 740 pages) starts with a hijacking on
Page 4 and the pace rarely slackens in this well-crafted, very
readable thriller. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEE-STADIUM (New York) _ The old cathedral has outlived
its usefulness. Hallowed grounds or not, the place should be
condemned. Yankee Stadium is a prisoner of its proud past, out of
date and unequipped to offer even the most modest amenities of the
modern ballpark. By STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Giants coach Jim Fassel surveys the
rubble of his 24-10 exhibition loss to the Jacksonville Jaguars and
declares, ``I'm not very happy right now.'' Maybe he'd feel a
better if he looked at the New York Jets, who suffered their worst
exhibition defeat in 22 years against the Baltimore Ravens. By
STEVE CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS-GRAHAM (Albany, N.Y.) _ In a seven-year NFL career,
Kent Graham has become Fassel-ized. Graham is on his second tour
with the New York Giants, again as a backup quarterback, but the
familiarity is more with Jim Fassel, his offensive coordinator in
1992 and 1996 and his head coach this season. By PETE DOUGHERTY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Here's one of Bill Clinton's
legacies. Eight-year-old Frances Moreau will remember that the
first time she was interviewed by reporters was after President
Clinton's speech admitting he lied about his affair with Monica
Lewinsky. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Gary Evans saved prosecutor Ken
Bruno from having to decide whether to seek the death penalty for
the career criminal who'd admitted to five murders. Evans killed
himself, rendering the question moot. Still the issue of capital
punishment deserves exploration. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
