<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9028 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANYON-NORTHRIM19-COX     08-18 2072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANYON-NORTHRIM19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grand Canyon offers unparalleled views, appreciation for time
and space
 &HT;    By Kendal Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND CANYON, Ariz. _ There really is no way to prepare for the
initial impact the Grand Canyon has on you. Especially from the
North Rim.
</P>
<P>
   At first you're seduced by the climate. As you make your way
from Jacob Lake through the Kaibab Plateau, the only reasonable
entrance to the North Rim area, the air becomes clean and dry and
the temperature steadily drops. The harsh desert floor that makes
up most of Arizona slowly transforms into an Alpine forest, with
lush, wild flower-laced meadows framing hills covered with towering
pines and wide birch trees.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as you approach the North Rim lodge, an old but sturdy
log-and-stone structure specifically built to blend into the rustic
setting, you are impressed by the rugged elegance of the area.
Visitors wander along parklike paths, from the gift shop to the
saloon, either waiting to eat in a dining room that's been booked
for three days or heading back to the small but comfortable cabins
nestled in the trees.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very hypnotizing, this beautiful combination of natural
and man-made scenery, a vacation spot seemingly made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   And then you see the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   From the veranda of the lodge the horizon gives way to one of
the most incredible geological wonders on the planet. Peaks and
cliffs stand on top of slopes and ledges, shielding the great
chasms at the bottom from view, all of it dotted with trees and
shadows, thousands of feet down, miles across.
</P>
<P>
   The variations of landscape within the canyon are a result of
different layers of rock reacting differently to millions of years
of slow and silent erosion. It covers a vast amount of land, over a
million acres. Measured by the Colorado River, the canyon is 277
miles long, and at its deepest it is 6,000 vertical feet from rim
to water, all of it a collection of diverse geological and
biological features. It can not be taken in with a quick glance or
described by measurements. The stunning beauty of the Grand Canyon
is a testament to the awe-inspiring power of time and space.
</P>
<P>
   Over five million people a year visit the Grand Canyon. The
license plates in the parking lot of the lodge literally represent
every state in the union, but on the veranda it becomes apparent
that a large contingency of visitors are from abroad. Italian,
German and Swedish are as likely to be overheard as a Southern
drawl.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of these visitors congregate at the South Rim of
the canyon, which is more accessible and more tourist-oriented. The
Grand Canyon was home to entrepreneurial enterprises before it
became a national park, and the South Rim reflects that historic
commercialism. Open all year long, the South Rim has more places to
stay, more things to do. If you can't afford a helicopter ride or
don't feel up to riding a mule to the bottom, there's even an IMAX
theater to recreate the experience. And if you want to spot a
celebrity, chances are they will be frequenting the South Rim.
</P>
<P>
   But the North Rim, open from May 15 to Oct. 15, offers forests
in place of scrub brush, wilderness to development. And, since the
North Rim is higher in elevation than the South Rim, the view is
more spectacular, especially in the early morning or late evening,
when the shadows move quickly, giving every crevice and crack depth
and life, and the colors become bright and vital.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors must pay to enter the Grand Canyon National Park, but
the fee is nominal considering the wealth of serene and majestic
scenery the area offers. Once in the park, no fees or permits are
required for day hiking, which is the simplest way to acquaint
yourself with the canyon's immense size and natural beauty.
</P>
<P>
   From Bright Angel Point, a short walk along a paved path, there
are views of Roaring Springs, the only water source for the entire
park, and the San Francisco Peaks. Along the Widforss Trail, mule
deer and Kaibab squirrels can be spotted through a dense forest of
white fir, aspen and ponderosa pines. For more serious hikers, the
North Kaibab Trail leads 3,400 feet below the rim, past Coconino
Overlook and Supai Tunnel to Roaring Springs, but the trip is
strenuous and takes most people a full day.
</P>
<P>
   Several other equally beautiful points are easily accessible
from the North Rim lodge. A breathtaking, curving 20-mile drive
leads to Cape Royal, the only spot on the North Rim that offers a
view of the sinuous, muddy-green Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   The short trail from the parking area to Cape Royal is shaded by
tall pinyon pines and juniper trees. Beneath those the land is
dotted with sagebrush and cliff rose bushes. Before you reach Cape
Royal, openings in the greenery afford a glance through Angel's
Window. Fractures of weakness in a large, jutting rock, coupled
with eons of weathering and the constant pull of gravity have
formed the window in this point, through which a bend in the
Colorado River is clearly visible. On top of this particular point,
visitors enjoy a 360-degree view of an area of the canyon that
inspired some of the earliest explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Dutton, who led the 1880-81 survey party to the North
Rim, named many of the landmarks in this part of the canyon. His
interest in Eastern religion and philosophy is responsible for the
heroic nomenclature of the area. Wotan's Throne, a narrow crag of
rock below Angel's Window, rests between Zoroaster Temple and
Vishnu Temple. To the right sits Brahma Temple, to the left,
Krishna Shrine.
</P>
<P>
   A shorter drive brings one to Point Imperial, the highest point
on the North Rim. From here visitors can see the Painted Desert in
the distance, just past Marble Canyon, which is a smaller precursor
to the Grand Canyon. This area, sandwiched between the Vermillion
and Echo cliffs, is where the Colorado River begins to carve its
way through the area, and is where the earliest pioneers began
their courageous explorations of the canyon.
</P>
<P>
   For those who wish to camp in the area, there are many options.
The lodge itself has a campground, complete with showers and
laundromat, but spaces are usually reserved well before the season
begins in May. Camping is allowed at designated spots within the
canyon, but these spots require back-country passes, which must be
reserved in advance. Campers in these back-country spots are asked
to adhere to the ``leave no trace'' principles, which include
staying on main trails, burying human waste and packing out all
garbage, including toilet paper. Fires are prohibited below the
rim.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to camp away from the crowds but don't desire to
hike into the interior of the canyon, there are sites all around
the canyon that are accessible by vehicle. However, most of these
are within national parks and can only be reached by driving long
distances down primitive roads that are not regularly maintained.
Ample supplies, such as water, food, gasoline and tools are
encouraged, since the only habitations on these routes are ranger
stations, which are closer to the canyon than they are to the main
roads.
</P>
<P>
   Point Sublime, widely heralded as the most beautiful spot on the
canyon rim, is at the end of a forest trail that is virtually
impassable by anything less than a four-wheel-drive vehicle.
Toroweep, although certainly not easy to get to, can be reached if
the driver casts fate to the wind, and the vehicle is still under
warranty.
</P>
<P>
   Toroweap has 11 established camp sites, two of which are
directly on the overlook, a narrow, 3,000-foot sliver of canyon
directly above the Colorado River. The area is populated with yucca
plants and cactuses, coyotes and jack rabbits. There are outhouses
available, but campers must bring their own water to drink and
their own wood to burn.
</P>
<P>
   The view is worth the drive. The rim along this slim portion of
the canyon is made up of huge sandstone boulders with large
crevices in between, allowing campers to climb down to lower
shelves on the wall. You can get as close to the edge as your
nerves allow, or you can sit comfortably at the top, watching the
sun dip below the plateaus in the distance, painting the skyline
pink and the landscape gold.
</P>
<P>
   The original Grand Canyon Lodge at the North Rim was built on
the canyon's edge in 1928 and was designed expressly to blend in
with the limestone cliff on which it stood. Destroyed by fire in
1932, it was rebuilt in 1936. Log cabins can be reserved ahead of
time, or day visitors can relax in the saloon or peruse the books
and maps in the visitors center. Although the lodge is impressive
in its remote luxury, it was obviously constructed with the main
attraction in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every part of the lodge affords a view of the canyon. The
many windows in the dining room assure that every seat is a good
one. From the sun room, with its huge floor-to-ceiling windows,
visitors can meander out onto the wide veranda to sit in rocking
chairs and ponder the landscape and the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The custodians of the canyon are eager to share the history of
the area. Flashlight hikes are held every night, with park rangers
pointing out stars and constellations that can't be seen in less
remote places. Also, in the afternoons, talks are held on the
veranda. Visitors that may be expecting dry, academic lessons in
geology are usually surprised when rangers like Rick Danley make
presentations on topics such as the writers, artists and
photographers that were inspired by the canyon and helped document
it when it was first discovered. Danley's speech begins with the
story of John Wesley Powell, the explorer whose reports to the
government read more like poetry than a geological survey. Powell,
in turn, brought to the canyon photographer Jack Hillers, whose
work spurred painters such as Thomas Moran and Gunner Widforss,
among others, to dedicate much of their work to capturing the
visual beauty of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all that the North Rim offers hinges on one activity
_ looking. The longer you stare at the canyon, the greatest abyss
save the human soul, the more the canyon seems to touch you.
Perhaps it's the vastness, the unfathomable magnitude, quiet and
unchanged despite the multitudes that flock here every year. This
giant was here long before any of us, and will continue on long
after we are gone. Watch for any length of time and the whole
thing, as silent and still as the canyon is, seems to change as the
day changes, offering a new insight into the incredible power of
time, how the hardest of rocks can be sculpted with water and wind,
a concert of the most basic and lasting elements of this world.
Come with an attitude of innocent awe. Prepare to be moved.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon Lodge: motel units, frontier cabins, pioneer cabins
and western cabins available. For reservations, call (303)
297-2757.
</P>
<P>
   North Rim campground: 82 sites, no hookups, showers available.
Fee: $15 per night. Stays limited to seven days per season.
Reservations for individuals and organized groups of six to 50
people with a sponsorship, charter or recognition may be made
through Biospherics, 1-800-365-2267. Campgrounds may be open past
Oct. 15, weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   Open camping: Kaibab National Forest, surrounding the park, is
open to ``at large'' camping one-quarter mile away from paved
roads, meadows, and water sources. Campers must observe all fire,
off-road, and sanitation restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   North Rim Visitors Center: Park rangers and Grand Canyon
Association employees are available to answer questions from 8 a.m.
to 8 p.m. daily. The visitors center features exhibits and a
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   (Many North Rim viewpoints, facilities and some trails are
wheelchair accessible or accessible with assistance. Inquire at
visitors center for more details.)
</P>
<P>
   Backcountry permits for overnight hiking: Fees: $20 permit fee,
$4 user impact fee (per person, per night in addition to back
country fee.) Overnight permit requests should be sent well in
advance to: Back country office, P.O Box 129, Grand Canyon, Ariz.,
86023.
</P>
<P>
   Other accommodation reservation information: Grand Circle
Association, 1-(800)-557-8824; Grand Canyon and surrounding
communities information and reservation service, ``Tele-Park''
(900) 976-7888.
</P>
<P>
   For information on the Internet: www.thecanyon.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
