<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9030 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-NOCOPS19-COX     08-18 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-NOCOPS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officers turn into laptops
 &HT;    By Ian Trontz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ According to Washington, 15 of President
Clinton's army of 100,000 new community police officers are
stationed in Riviera Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't see them anywhere except on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Three aren't officers at all. They're laptop computers. The way
the government figures it, the time the computers will save each
officer from returning to the police station to write multiple
reports has the effect of putting three new officers on the street.
</P>
<P>
   The other 12 were actual officers to be hired with a $1.3
million federal grant that was to pay their salaries from 1996 to
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``This grant award approval was one of the best moments in my
20-year career,'' police Chief Jerry Poreba wrote in an effusive
letter to Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, only six officers have been hired, and two of
those have left, leaving four. And the police department can't hire
the other eight because it can't afford to follow federal grant
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Poreba, 1998: ``Everybody thinks, `It's a grant. Happy days are
here again.' They're not.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Justice Department figures, that it admits may not
be accurate, 24 police and sheriff's departments in Palm Beach,
Martin and St. Lucie counties will have received $14.8 million for
237 new positions by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the cities that most need the extra officers, like
Riviera Beach, are the ones having the most trouble hiring them.
Both nationwide and locally, about a third of the positions are
actually computers or civilians who count as officers under a
federal formula.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's voodoo math,'' said one local police chief who didn't
want to jeopardize future grant requests by allowing his name to be
used for this story. He said the computers allow his officers to
spend more time away from desks, but that's not the same as having
actual officers.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1992 campaign, Clinton pledged 100,000 new officers
nationwide. In 1994, Congress came through with a landmark
anti-crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Justice Department has given grants for 77,212.6
positions. Of those, 53,965 are certified officers. Even more money
is likely to come as the government attempts to reach Clinton's
golden number by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, police and sheriff's departments could receive
federal grants that would pay new officers' salaries for three
years; buy equipment, like computers; or pay civilian assistants
for three years. In most cases, localities also had to contribute
at least 25 percent of the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Temporary solution
</P>
<P>
   But local departments have to take full responsibility for
paying the salaries of new officers and civilians after the three
years. They also cannot supplant their existing employees with new
ones, or delay filling vacancies, to lighten the financial burden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fear a lot of police departments are jumping on the
bandwagon of community policing because the budget is there, and
that once the money dries up, they will go back to traditional
policing,'' said Robert Friedmann, chairman of the criminal justice
department at Georgia State University.
</P>
<P>
   The program's philosophy: If police get to know residents rather
than spend their time answering 911 calls, crime will drop in the
long run.
</P>
<P>
   Most local police and sheriff's departments say they have had no
problems spending the money.
</P>
<P>
   Boynton Beach, for example, hired three community police
officers in 1995 with a $225,000 grant matched by $120,000 of its
own money. Beginning next year, it will pay the entire salaries for
the three, said the department's Mike Munro.
</P>
<P>
   The city has spent another $164,000 in grant money and $55,000
of its own money for laptops and records management software. Under
federal calculations, those are worth 16.4 new officers.
</P>
<P>
   Port St. Lucie has received three grants, worth $1.9 million,
for 25 new officers. It also received $219,000 in 1995 to hire
three civilians _ a duty officer, crime scene technician and crime
prevention coordinator _ which allowed the three officers in those
jobs to join the community police patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The department has put more than $745,000 of its own money
toward the 28 salaries.
</P>
<P>
   But Belle Glade, whose 1997 crime rate was twice the national
average, had to reject a $450,000 grant for six officers in 1996
because it couldn't contribute $150,000 of its own. Nevertheless,
the Justice Department still counts those six officers toward the
100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've sent them at least two certified letters telling them we
rejected the grant,'' Belle Glade Police Chief Michael Miller said.
``They still send us letters asking for quarterly reports and those
kinds of things. It's a bureaucratic situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department spokesman Kevin Avery said such errors
happen, but are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be as accurate as possible,'' he said. ``We've had
changes in grant advisers for Florida and a few might have fallen
through the cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby Pahokee, which also exceeds the national crime rate,
hasn't spent its $143,000 grant for two officers because it can't
fill the positions it already has, Sgt. Donna Salvatore said.
</P>
<P>
   `The concept works'
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Riviera Beach had 104 officers, but by 1996, when it
received its grant, the city council had cut back to 91 positions.
</P>
<P>
   Riviera Beach was supposed to spend $383,000 of its own money
for the 12 new officers, but the Justice Department threw in an
extra $295,000 because the city met the criteria for ``extreme
financial hardship.''
</P>
<P>
   The grant now pays for four officers, including Scott O'Hare,
who spends his shifts visiting residents of crime-plagued apartment
complexes and trailer parks.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hare, a fresh-faced 28, could be the poster boy for community
policing. When he drove into an Avenue J complex on Wednesday,
about two dozen kids ran from the mustard-colored buildings.
</P>
<P>
   They surrounded O'Hare for their weekly dose of ``Junior Police
Officer'' stickers.
</P>
<P>
   He said he visits the complex three times a week, which was
confirmed by Patricia Green, 40, who lives there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done a pretty good job controlling the drugs,'' she
said. Dealers, she said, no longer congregate in the parking lot,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept works,'' O'Hare said. ``We just have to have the
manpower to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Last August, because of little growth in the city's tax base,
the council cut another four regular police positions.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the city can't hire the other eight community
police officers Clinton's program would underwrite. That would be
illegal ``supplanting.''
</P>
<P>
   The city asked the Justice Department to waive that rule, but
one year later, no response has arrived. Avery said the request is
``under review'' and could not comment further.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about $1 million for Riviera Beach remains unspent.
The grant will expire next April, although extensions are common.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Belle Glade accepted a $596,000 three-year grant for
six officers after the Justice Department waived the local
contribution requirement. It did not do the same for the later
$450,000 grant, which the city consequently rejected.
</P>
<P>
   A reduced forceNo money returned?
</P>
<P>
   When the first grant expired this year, the city couldn't afford
to keep the six positions. No one was laid off because the
department had six vacancies on its regular roster from retirements
and resignations. It reduced its force from 49 to the original 43.
</P>
<P>
   Still, those six positions, like the six Belle Glade rejected,
are being counted toward the 100,000, according to Justice
Department statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would like for us to keep the positions, and believe me,
so would I,'' Miller said. ``They weren't happy about it, but it's
a fact of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery said only that the Belle Glade case was ``under review.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not aware of any cases where the Justice
Department asked cities to return money for violating grant rules.
</P>
<P>
   A September 1997 General Accounting Office report criticized the
Justice Department for inconsistent monitoring of the community
police grants. Since then, the department has hired more monitors,
Avery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make the grants work for them, but we want to make
them work correctly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Jennifer Peltz, Rachel Masory, Alexandra Navarro
Clifton, Monika Gonzalez, Africa Ragland, Lillian Weis, Jill
Taylor, Scott Cech and Teresa Lane contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Ian Trontz writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
