<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9032 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KABAT-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commentary: Spreading the work around
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There's great excitement at our house. Let me put
that another way: I am greatly excited. After several years of
part-time and free-lance work, I am back in the workforce full
time.
</P>
<P>
   One might understandably ask, why would someone be excited about
such a change? Longer hours, more responsibilities, more time away
from home and family, and less time to take care of same.
</P>
<P>
   I am not naive about these matters. Nevertheless, I am eager to
begin this next phase of my life. I have been fortunate all these
years to be able to balance my time between children and work. Now,
however, with our eldest son heading off the college, the time has
come for me to increase my take-home ... and I don't mean his dirty
laundry each week.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, I have been readying the home front for this
momentous change in our lifestyle. I took a week between jobs to
put our lives in order. (NOTE TO FILE: Next time, take a month.
Better yet, make sure there is no next time.)
</P>
<P>
   I have sorted through the various piles that have cluttered our
tabletops for the last several months. I have updated the boys'
school memory books, adding all their papers, awards and ribbons
from the last school year _ just days before the new school year. I
have dated and filed enough photographs to fill three bookshelves.
Too bad I don't have three extra bookshelves. I have cleaned our
closets and dressers and under-the-bed boxes.
</P>
<P>
   I even prepared meals and put them in the freezer. Nothing like
whipping up a batch of beef stew and lasagna in 101 degree heat. I
have no doubt we will quickly forget we have this largesse in the
freezer and will discover it years from now in some
undistinguishable cryogenized state.
</P>
<P>
   I have weeded the flower beds, trimmed the hedges and supervised
the painting and cleaning of our garage. I would have done the
latter myself, but I wanted to brush up on my supervisory skills.
Anyway, that's what I told my sons, who seemed to think my
supervisory skills were unparalleled.
</P>
<P>
   I have organized the clothes and shoes in my closet by color,
fabric weight and style. I have purchased a supply of new hosiery.
</P>
<P>
   We had a family meeting and discussed the redistribution of
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot work all day, come home, fix your dinner, do the
laundry, clean the house and help with homework,'' I began.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' all three sons asked. My husband wisely remained
quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``For starters,'' I continued, ``I want each of you to be
responsible for preparing a meal one night of the week. I have
outlined some simple meal plans,'' I said, spreading out my
color-coded menus before them. ``It shouldn't be too hard. Any
questions?''
</P>
<P>
   The three boys and my husband looked at each other silently, as
if to ask, ``Has she gone mad?'' No one spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, our youngest son said, ``I get the night we go to
McDonald's!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice try. That's not on the list,'' I answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you going to give us any training?'' one son asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking opening cans and boxes,'' I explained. ``It
doesn't take a lot of expertise, but yes, I'll share with you my
best rip-and-pour techniques.''
</P>
<P>
   More silence. Then our oldest son visibly perked up. ``This
doesn't apply to me, right? I mean, I'm going to college this fall.
I'll be on the meal plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your meal plan until Welcome Week is right here,'' I said,
pointing to the menu cards on the table before us. He sagged.
</P>
<P>
   Another son asked, ``Does cereal count as a meal?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Only for breakfast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear,'' I said to my husband, who had been noticeably silent,
``comments?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just wondering if you can buy Hamburger Helper by the
pallet-load,'' he moaned.
</P>
<P>
   As I said, I am greatly excited these days. I want to see if I
can get through a whole week without cooking a single meal.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco (Texas) Tribune-Herald.
She can be reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
