A9033 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANE-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Commentary: It's moving day at the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   By Mark Lane
</P>
<P>
   c. Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ I've been trucking files over to the new place,
looking around and seeing where they would look right. It's a good
feeling having a big empty place to put your things.
</P>
<P>
   The old place was a mess. Stuff everywhere. No room to move.
Nowhere to unpack if you found something cool to bring home.
</P>
<P>
   The new place is roomy and decorated better. It's in color. The
old place was black and white. I put up new wallpaper. Really
brightened things up.
</P>
<P>
   I like virtual moving day much better than real moving day. No
boxes to schlep around. Fewer orthopedic dangers. You don't have to
bribe friends into carrying things by passing out pizza and beer.
You just swap floppies back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   My computer habits are the technological equivalent of a guy
with a truck on cinder blocks in the lawn out back. The old
computer was powered by an Intel-386 chip, this is the computing
equivalent of a 1973 Dodge Dart. It's now in the closet on cinder
blocks.
</P>
<P>
   The new computer is powered by a 486 chip, the computing
equivalent of a 1989 Honda Accord. It still has lots of miles left
in it. The power-users laugh and want to race, but I pay them no
mind. It gets me where I'm going.
</P>
<P>
   Like any move, this change has sent ripples through my life.
There are no simple moves. Even virtual ones.
</P>
<P>
   It is an iron law in computing, as in automobile ownership, that
one change sends other, less expected ones into motion. And they
all cost.
</P>
<P>
   This move should have stayed strictly on the digital level:
moving files, updating to Windows 95 and seeing if my Magic 8-Ball
program would still run on the new operating system. (``All signs
point to yes.'') But within a week or two the virtual became actual
-- as it will, more often than you think. I was moving furniture
around. I was hefting real boxes. Damn.
</P>
<P>
   In no time, my experiment in deskless living ended.
</P>
<P>
   I have lived without a desk for a couple years now. This has not
been a sacrifice. My desk at work is mostly a compost bin for
paper. I do all my work at the computer next to it. At home, I'm a
mobile typist. I type on the laptop wherever I want. Usually the
kitchen table. Sometimes on the porch. Even outside.
</P>
<P>
   Desks breed paper. You can't be too careful with them.
</P>
<P>
   But with the new computer, the system started breaking down. The
balance was upset.
</P>
<P>
   The new laptop can connect to the Internet. It has to be near
the phone. Soon, it was always at the table. Soon, my daughter was
always at the table, checking e-mail and finding new ways to tie up
the phone. Soon, the food function of the table was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I happened upon a second-hand docking station. You can
plug the whole laptop into it and do all kinds new things. Hook up
a keyboard that wouldn't squish your fingers together. Hook up a
monitor that wouldn't make you squint. More storage. Make sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was no longer a mobile computer. It needed a place of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   Next thing I knew, I was bolting a desk together from
instructions probably written in a language other than English and
translated word-for-word. (``Starting with screw Shelf Rod onto
Desk Top using the end containing pre-assembled table screw.'')
</P>
<P>
   Bringing in a desk is an extreme step. But a necessary step to
save our eating space. To reclaim dinner from the computer. To keep
crumbs out of the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   The purchase that was merely supposed to replace a broken
computer with a working one, continues to kick into motion a
disquieting number of life changes.
</P>
<P>
   At this pace, before the month is over, I'll shave off my
mustache, get a tattoo, a new passport and a Zip drive. Maybe a
breadmaker and fishbowl with computer interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder people are scared of technology. It's not the fear of
pushing the wrong button, it's the fear of where the buttons will
push you.
</P>
<P>
   I look at the computer on its new desk at night. It seems
content for now but I wonder what it's planning for me next.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
