<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRATT-PROPULSION19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pratt raising profile of Space Propulsion, Russia ties
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pratt &AMP; Whitney signaled its plan recently to expand its Space
Propulsion unit and its business alliances in Russia with the
appointment of Richard Whiston to president of space and Russian
operations, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Whiston is vice president and general counsel of Pratt. Doug
North, space propulsion president, and Bob Rosati, Pratt senior
vice president of international business, will report to Whiston,
who will be based at Pratt's headquarters in East Hartford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are bringing him on board because of his expertise in
mergers and acquisitions,'' spokesman Patrick Louden said. ``They
want to make space a core business.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt's main sources of revenue come from its Large Commercial
Engines and Large Military Engines division. Its rocket business
accounts for about $600 million a year, a pittance of Pratt's total
$7.4 billion, and until two years ago was part of its military
engine unit. Now, it is separate, with Its chemical-systems
operation is based in San Jose, Calif., and its liquid-propulsion
business in northwestern Palm Beach County.
</P>
<P>
   The operation here makes upper-stage rockets and turbopumps for
the space shuttle's main engine. It does research and is developing
a lower-stage rocket with a Russian company. About 800 people are
involved Pratt's space operations in Palm Beach County, accounting
for about $200 million a year in revenue. The company wouldn't say
what impact the new strategy would have locally.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Paul Nisbet of JSA Research said an acquisition strategy
is sound. ``That part of the industry really hasn't participated in
consolidations,'' Nisbet said.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt &AMP; Whitney is one of five companies that make rocket
engines.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt's parent, United Technologies (NYSE: UTX, $87.44), had
$718 million in cash at the end of the second quarter, so it is
well-positioned to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Because its debt-to-equity ratio _ a barometer of its ability to
add debt to its balance sheet _ is 36 percent, it can afford to
triple it its long-term debt from $1.2 billion to more than $4
billion, Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very well heeled. But it's there their borrowing power
that's enormous,'' Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   United Technologies (NYSE: UTX) closed at $87.44, up $2.31 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
