</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawsuit will put the judge's ability not to laugh on trial
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Have you heard about the guy in Clearwater,
Fla. who is suing a topless nightclub because, according to his
story, he suffered whiplash when a dancer unleashed her 60-HH bust
and jumped up and slammed her breasts into the victim's head? He
says it felt like he'd been hit with two cement blocks. Says the
impact just about knocked him out.
</P>
<P>
   The alleged injured party is suing for $15,000 _ that's $7,500
per, right? Can't help wondering, is his attorney going for assault
with deadly weapons?
</P>
<P>
   Although it may sound like it, don't think I'm taking all of
this lightly. Let me make (ITAL)this(END ITAL) politically correct
statement about (ITAL)that(END ITAL): I feel his pain. Well, maybe
not really, but I have put a lot of thought into the unfolding
courtroom drama; like how all involved are going to manage not to
crack (up) under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   First, how is the prosecution going to present its case? ``Your
Honor, we intend to prove beyond any reasonable doubt that the
accused did, with malice and aforethought do bodily harm to my
client.'' Later on, he'll probably introduce a psychologist who
will testify the victim is now unable to lead a normal life based
on an excessive fear of women's chests, hereinafter to be referred
to as 'bustaphobia'.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the problem of introducing the weapon(s) into
evidence. My take on it would be something like: ``Uh, your honor,
the prosecution would like to introduce these, uh...'' (this is
where he rolls his eyes and jerks his head around to indicate the
accused's double-H chest) ``as evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The disconcerted judge says it will be so noted and routinely
instructs a court official to place the alleged weapons on the
evidence table. Nobody moves. Snickers all around.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if this will make Court TV? If not, it's a shoo-in for
the Springer show _ particularly if the accused agrees to bare not
only her soul but her weapons as well.
</P>
<P>
   This was too good a story not to share so I called a friend of
mine, a retired judge, to discuss the case. She says it will
probably be a civil suit to be decided by a preponderance of
evidence, ``...which ought not to be much of a problem,'' she
snickers, ``unless the accused wears a pup-tent to court.''
</P>
<P>
   I can't resist asking her what she would have done if the case
had been brought to her courtroom. ``I'm afraid I'd have indulged
in some highly undignified giggles and snorts,'' she laughs, ``and
then I would have suggested the plaintiff wear a batting helmet the
next time he goes bar hopping.'' She hesitates before she adds,
``Really, what is it with
</P>
<P>
   guys anyway?'' I tell her maybe it's because they don't have
library cards. Then I remind her women go to places like that too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, true,'' she agrees, ``and anyway, who are we to judge?''
By way of proving her point she asks what I did last night. I tell
her that Sharon, my sister-in-law-twice-removed (we used to be
married to brothers but now we're not) and I went to a nearby town
to buy toilet seats. This cracks her up and she mutters something
about getting a
</P>
<P>
   life.
</P>
<P>
   I tell her it was coincidence that we both needed new ones at
the same time and assure her we hadn't planned it as a big Friday
night on the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``What'd you do last night?'' I ask in the hope of proving a
point. She hesitates before confessing that she'd been up until 2
A.M. lemon oiling her furniture. I tell her I'm glad her social
life is looking up.
</P>
<P>
   We call it a draw and get back to the lawsuit. I ask her if she
thinks he'll collect and she says she doubts it. Says the case is
liable to boil down to a definition of terms. I ask how. She
responds with a ladylike chuckle and tells me the whole proceeding
could bog down in a turgid sea of semantics with one lawyer calling
them 'deadly weapons' and the other referring to them as
'attractive nuisances'.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's polite titter has erupted into an abandoned guffaw
as she tries to add, ``And how in the hell is anybody going to keep
a straight face?''
</P>
<P>
   So much for jurisprudence.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett is a teacher and writer in Gibsonburg, Ohio.
Her e-mail address is eschuett(at)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
