<SLUG> BC-FEATURES-BJT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE WEDNESDAY FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Wednesday, August 19, 1998,
are moving today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e category)
</P>
<P>
   TGRAHAMBROWN _ Throughout the 1980s, T. Graham Brown was a
rising star in Nashville, churning out Top-10 country hits and
recording duets with the likes of Tanya Tucker. It was a long way
from his frat party days at the University of Georgia, where he got
his start as half of the popular house band Dirk and Tony. But by
the mid-'90s, Brown's world crumbled as he fought declining record
sales and escalating alcoholism. Now Brown's back with a new album
and a new, sober lifestyle. His new single was released Tuesday.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TVSURFER-COLUMN _ What else could follow Comedy Central's
``South Park'' (it begins a new season tonight), but something like
the bizarro ``Upright Citizens Brigade,'' a thoroughly quirky,
outlandish longform sketch comedy show that for all appearances is
just the kind of programming you'd expect to see on Public Access
Television but never do. ``UCB'' is from a Chicago-bred troupe and
its first 30-minute sketch is the astoundingly weird tale of a
small band of space-flying geeks who do everything in their power
(including using their trusty Bucket of Truth) to wreak havoc on
Earth. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   AARON-ECKHART _ Interview with actor in new movie coming out
this weekend, Your Friends and Neighbors, from Neil LaBute, who did
last year's controversial, In The Company of Men. (Palm Beach Post)
ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE _ Advance story on the 2nd annual African American
Festival of Dance. (Kerr, Austin American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TV-ANYDAY _ TV's a strange business. Just when you think you'll
never see a promising new show again, Lifetime _ yes, Lifetime of
all places! _ serves up a potential winner. ``Any Day Now'' is a
poignant, heartwarming show about race relations that could easily
become the season's best _ and most intelligent _ drama. (Thompson,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (l category)
</P>
<P>
   PLAYMATE-AGES _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ There are a couple ways you
could analyze DeDe Lind. That this beach-going, water-skiing,
roller-skating, divorced mother can relaunch her nude modeling
career from her Boca Raton condo at an age when most women are
concerned with just keeping body parts from sagging south, is
enough to give aging Baby Boomers a glimmer of hope. Or a pang of
jealousy. (Houck, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CANYON-NORTHRIM _ Although the climate is better and the scenery
more diverse, the North Rim of the Grand Canyon isn't as widely
visited as the more popular South Rim. Which makes it a perfect
vacation destination. (Rogers, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD
</P>
<P>
   AUSTINSPICE _ Austin's hot. So are its women. An increasing
number of them have made careers out of working with spicy foods
from salsas to satays. Meet five of them: Thai Spice, Relish Spice,
Salsa Spice, Tamale Spice and Saucy Spice. (Timing this story while
the real Spice Girls are on their Texas tour and just before
theTexas Fiery Foods Show at which several are exhibiting.) (Austin
American-Statesman) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-LUNCHBOX _ Lunchbox letters to clip and put in the kids'
lunchboxes for back to school. w/ story on a lunchbox letters book.
(Anna, Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COOL-LUNCH _ Blurb on cool lunchboxes that are available. (Anna,
Palm Beach Post) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-TEXASFAIR _ Dallas, 1998 State Fair of Texas, Sept.
25-Oct. 18, stars LeAnn Rimes, Clint Black and the Royal Lipizzaner
Stallion Show under the theme, ``Puttin' on the Glitz.'' (Paterau,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-SMOKYMTNS _ Smoky Mountain Folk Festival Sept. 4-5 at
Lake Junaluska (near Waynesville, N.C.) features traditional
mountain music with ``jammin' in the yard'' performances and a
children's tent at Stuart Auditorium. Coincides with the Autumn
Showcase, works by Haywood and Jackson county artists at Balsam
Mountain Inn Sept. 1-Oct. 31. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE (a and/or l category)
</P>
<P>
   PRATT-PROPULSION _ Pratt &AMP; Whitney signaled its plan recently to
expand its Space Propulsion unit and its business alliances in
Russia with the appointment of Richard Whiston to president of
space and Russian operations, a company spokesman said. The
operation makes upper-stage rockets and turbopumps for the space
shuttle's main engine. It does research and is developing a
lower-stage rocket with a Russian company. (Pounds, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-INDIANGAMBLING _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ More than 200 years
ago, the framers of the Constitution cut a deal with the nation's
Indians that today may clear the way for 24-hour casinos featuring
booze, blackjack, lotteries, parimutuels and other games of chance
year-round. Now, seven years after the Seminole Tribe of Florida
first asked to open full-blown casinos, maneuvering over the issue
is intensifying: A tribal proposal is being reviewed by the state.
(Staletovich, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-NOCOPS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ According to Washington, 15
of President Clinton's army of 100,000 new community police
officers are stationed in Riviera Beach, Fla. But you won't see
them anywhere except on paper. Three aren't officers at all.
They're laptop computers. (Trontz, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
