A9118 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES1     08-18 0278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ShortTakes: It's the heavy breathing stuff, stupid
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The response to Bill Clinton's mea culpa was predictable and
along party lines. The Democrats thought it was good enough. He
said he misled, he was wrong, he was sorry, what more do they want?
Details, the Republicans responded in a nano-second. It isn't
really a confession until Bill gives us the good stuff, like how
the star-crossed lovers Did It.
</P>
<P>
   According to instant CBS polling, the American public was
lenient. OK, can we talk about something else now, huh, please? The
few people I've talked to think Bill could have done without
bringing up his Ken Starr gripes. Knocking Starr while in full mea
culpa degrades the culpa.
</P>
<P>
   As for heavy breathing, if I were Bill and if the Republicans
want details, I'd give them lots. Sort of like this, ``Well, Monica
was at the bookstore and along with an embossed leather and
parchment copy of the poems of Elizabeth Barrett Browning, she got
a Best Parts Version of the Kama Sutra. We started with `Crane
Walks on Misty Lake,' which begins with the woman putting her left
foot on your forehead and ends with the walking part, which is
pretty tough if you're 52. I really started thinking I was doing
the wrong thing morally at Chapter 72, `Muskrat in Bamboo Grove.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I make a solemn pledge to the country that I'll never do that
again. Threw my back out for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
