<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9202 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-STADIUM-H     08-18 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STADIUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SKY IS FALLING ON THE SOARING YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The old cathedral on 161st and River has outlived its
usefulness. Hallowed grounds or not, the place should be condemned.
We know this because the proprietor, George Steinbrenner, is
helpful enough to point out to potential paying customers the
perils of taking in a baseball game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Bronx neighborhood once deemed worthy of constructing a
showcase house for Babe Ruth has succumbed to urban decay. On a
good day, as Steinbrenner can and does attest, traffic to and from
the games speeds to a crawl. Yankee Stadium is a prisoner of its
proud past, out of date and unequipped to offer even the most
modest amenities of the modern ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, not crumbling to quarter-ton pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week before Yankee Stadium celebrated its 75th
birthday, a 500-pound steel joint fell through the underside of the
upper deck and crash-landed onto some mercifully empty seats. To
paraphrase old Yankees philosopher Yogi Berra: If people don't want
to come to such a place, then nobody is going to stop them from not
coming. Berra stopped coming to Yankee Stadium after he got fired
as manager in 1985. He is one of the few, the stubborn, who can
resist the pull of venturing in for a firsthand look at the Yankees
team to beat all Yankees teams.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, 47,841 paying customers flocked to see the
Yankees pound the Minnesota Twins into submission. The next day,
53,835 paid to see the Yankees feast on fresh meat _ the Texas
Rangers. Then, 46,547 watched the Yankees have the Rangers for
seconds. On Saturday, 53,117 showed up expecting yet another course
of Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would have to be living in a flour sack,'' Yankees manager
Joe Torre mused, ``not to know something special is going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Stadium is where the Babe became larger than life. Yankee
Stadium is where Lou Gehrig confronted death and declared himself a
lucky man. Yankee Stadium is where Joe DiMaggio and Mickey Mantle
roamed center field, where Don Larsen set down 27 Brooklyn Dodgers
in a row, where Reggie Jackson went deep on back-to-back-to-back
World Series swings, where Wade Boggs did victory laps on a police
horse. Yankee Stadium is getting up in years, and it may not be as
spry and sturdy as it used to be, but has it ever seen better days
than the ones that keep unfolding this season?
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 Yankees have it in their power _ not to mention their
pitching, their defense, their situational hitting, their
baserunning _ to establish themselves as a team for forever. They
passed the 2-million mark in attendance Saturday. By season's end,
more than 3 million fans will have ventured to the old cathedral by
the Harlem River. Not once, not with Murderer's Row, not with Roger
Maris hitting 61 homers in a season, not during any of their 23
world championship seasons, have the Yankees drawn 3 million fans.
Such is the pull of a team so dogged, so persistent, so
professional in its pursuit of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates meant it as a compliment when he
said recently that the Yankees are not an overwhelming team to look
at, that their whole far exceeds the sum of their parts. The
Yankees have set the time-honored tradition of approaching a
baseball season like a marathon on its ears, running an entire
pennant race at full sprint. They are running at such a brisk pace,
they could stumble, fall and still have time to get to the finish
line faster than any team in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've got a whole lot of superstars,'' Yankees
pitcher David Wells said. ``I don't think anybody wants that title.
We're one big family. We enjoy coming to the ballpark. There's no
tension, no self-centered guys. We're just going out and having a
good time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere we go, we're going to be the favorites,'' Torre
said. ``But that's fine. I think when you play in New York,
everybody expects you win. They don't care what anybody else says
anywhere. There's always pressure. I think saying, `Oh, there's no
pressure,' is nuts. It's just what you do in the face of pressure.
Pressure is what you make of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect nothing less than the Yankees to make the pressure work
for them. A team that can turn a tattered old cathedral on 161st
and River into the trendiest spot in New York is capable of
anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9205 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-18 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH PENALTY: TOO HIGH A PRICE TO PAY? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gary Evans saved Ken Bruno from a tough decision.
Bruno was pondering whether to try to kill the guy.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Evans broke away from federal marshals, took a
spectacular header off a high bridge over the Hudson River and
rendered the question moot immediately upon impact with the rocky
shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question deserves exploration. Evans was a career
criminal who'd admitted to five murders. Last week, Bruno, the
Rensselaer County district attorney, had moved to prosecute Evans
for the murder of one Timothy Rysedorph, another lowlife who'd
known about some of Evans' crimes. Bruno was still weighing whether
to ask for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   According to the polls, four in five New Yorkers favor capital
punishment, which is why the Legislature reinstated it shortly
after the election of Republican Gov. George Pataki four years ago.
Certainly, nobody could disagree that Gary Evans was sort of a
poster boy for the death penalty. A life of crime capped by at
least five murders. You don't come across a guy like that every
day.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Evans would never see daylight for as long as
he lived. Sticking a needle full of poison in his arm would cost a
ton of money _ vastly more than simply keeping him locked up until
he shuffled off this mortal coil to explain himself to a higher
power than Ken Bruno.
</P>
<P>
   Which was, in fact, why Evans kicked out the window of a
transport van and took his swan dive off that bridge. Years in
prison appealed to him less than a quick death. There may be a
lesson in that.
</P>
<P>
   How many other bad guys would have been permitted to plea
bargain to minor offenses because the Rensselaer County District
Attorney's office and the State of New York were spending big bucks
to execute a guy who would never again be in a position to hurt
anybody? How many of those bad guys would end up back on the street
sooner than they should have, doing violence to innocent people,
because of money?
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, none. But society has a budget for this sort of thing.
That's the real world. And death penalty cases are spectacular
budget-busters compared to simply keeping a dirtbag like Evans
locked up until he offs himself or dies on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works:
</P>
<P>
   It costs roughly $28,000 a year to keep an inmate in a cage in
the New York state prison system. Evans was in his early 40s. New
Yorkers would have spent $1.26 million if he'd been kept behind
bars for 45 more years.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the state would have had to pay for some appeals for him,
but that wouldn't have amounted to more than a few hundred thousand
dollars, tops. The legal system permits appeals in non-capital
cases, but it's vastly more generous in permitting and financing
appeals in death penalty cases. That's because the consequences of
mistakes in cases like that are enormous. New York has executed
more than 200 people in this century, and decent evidence turned up
after the fact that as many as eight of them were innocent.
</P>
<P>
   But if Evans had gone on death row, with extremely tight
security, New York would have spent not $28,000 a year to keep him
caged up but many times that figure. He would have been there a
minimum of 10 years. And paying for lawyers to defend him at trial
and to handle his appeals would have run into the millions.
</P>
<P>
   Texas spends almost $2.5 million to execute just one guy.
Florida spends more than $3 million. New York has one guy on death
row now, but the state has executed nobody yet. The best estimates
of the cost of doing that in New York approach $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   For some killers _ a Timothy McVeigh, for example, who killed
168 people, some of them babies, in a strike at the very heart of
our democracy _ money shouldn't be a factor. But for a Gary Evans?
</P>
<P>
   Letting him rot would have made more sense.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
