<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9210 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-18 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEGACY: SEX, LIES AND BROKEN PROMISES 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Bill Clinton wants to know what his legacy will
be. Here's one of Bill Clinton's legacies.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Moreau, 8, will remember that the first time she was
interviewed by reporters was after President Clinton's speech
admitting he lied about his affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Washington Square Bar &AMP; Grill, where her dad Rob
Moreau and dozens of diners and passersby gathered to watch the
unprecedented presidential address. Their hoots, jokes and distress
were observed by a television news crew, a still-news photographer
and a columnist in what you might fittingly call a media regress.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked young Frances what she told the TV news crew, she
tightened her jaw and said, ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Good idea, I said. Don't get caught in this mess.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in 20 years young adults of Frances' generation will
marvel at the idiocy of these times, the way we marveled at the
idiocy of the McCarthy era we called childhood. Unfortunately, it
looks like Ken Starr will still be special prosecutor, and Clinton
will be in some court or other.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone I talked to expressed a desire for our long national
Penthouse Forum to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tawdry,'' said retired public-relations woman Pat Umberger,
condemning everybody involved. ``What would your mother have said
about this?''
</P>
<P>
   Flight attendant Dana Davis said, ``The only thought I have is
how someone so intelligent is dumb enough to get caught doing this.
I guess when you have that much power you think you can do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of Clinton's very short speech, Umberger was saying,
``He's good. He's really good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he's good all right,'' Davis said with a strong note of
sarcasm.
</P>
<P>
   We all want to ``get on with our national life,'' as Clinton
said in his forced fess-up, but our national life still seems to
revolve around Clinton's so-called private life.
</P>
<P>
   Whether we love him or hate him, we're his co-dependents.
</P>
<P>
   You want a Clinton legacy? Whatever happens in the rest of his
presidency, Monday night's speech, no matter what you thought of
it, will be replayed throughout Frances Moreau's life.
</P>
<P>
   Her dad, Rob Moreau, said, ``I thought it was one of the best
speeches I've ever heard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was aimed at a fifth-grade intelligence,'' said
pianist Chris Huson. ``He said it was wrong, but he didn't say what
`it' referred to.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, reporters are scouring the nation, trying to find
someone who doesn't know what ``it'' referred to, and the only
people we can find are 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republicans are moving the goal line. Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, who just two days ago offered forgiveness to Clinton
if he fessed up, advanced the national dialogue after the speech by
saying, ``Wasn't that pathetic? I tell you, what a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are from Venus. Republicans are from Mars. Clinton
admitted adultery and lying (well, not in so many words, but in
weasel-speak) and the Mars-like Republicans loosed the hounds of
Hades on him.
</P>
<P>
   The glorious baby boom wasn't supposed to come to such an
adults-only thud.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton and I are the same age, and neither of us expected
our lifelong ambitions to come out like this. He wanted to be
another John F. Kennedy, and he achieved that ambition in quite the
wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to write, but never expected to be writing about this.
That speech was clench-jawed braggadocio. He seemed to be saying,
``Yeah, I did it, now let's get on to the important business of
beating up on the special prosecutor and the vast right-wing
conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   What he literally said at the end was pap about getting on to
``the promise of the next American century.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, wasn't there some kind of promise broken right here in this
century?
</P>
<P>
   When I was in elementary school, all I knew of the president was
that he was to be honored, no matter who the president was. He was
a guy in my Weekly Reader. The host of the kids show I watched
toasted him with milk.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in between then and now, John Kennedy, Lyndon Johnson
and Richard Nixon happened, and made baby boomers what we are
today. We elected Bill Clinton, and he is us.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he is some of us. His inner child seems to keep saying,
``I get to.''
</P>
<P>
   And what he gets to do isn't even the kind of free love where no
one is supposed to get hurt. Everyone's hurt _ Hillary, Chelsea,
Monica and all the rest of America. There's no such thing as free
love, or a cheap, inappropriate relationship. It's $40 million love
in special-prosecutor costs alone. But Ken Starr started it, as
Clinton kept saying throughout his speech.
</P>
<P>
   Look, I want this to be over so the nation can move on to lying
and adultery as usual, but I've been looking at the text of
Clinton's short speech, and I do not see the phrase ``I'm sorry''
or ``I lied.''
</P>
<P>
   All I see are things such as ``false impression,'' ``not
appropriate'' and ``critical lapse in judgment.'' All I see is the
language to which nothing sticks, Tefloglossia.
</P>
<P>
   What was that mealy-mouthed boy talking about?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
