<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9216 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-FORTUNE-HNS &LR;      08-18 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FORTUNE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TV GAME PLAYERS, FORTUNE COMES A LETTER AT A TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ RSTLNE.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a typo, or a word, but a mantra, the code for
success.
</P>
<P>
   RSTLNE.
</P>
<P>
   It is the secret that unlocks the mysteries of the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over Marita Brown and Marquerite Alexander had the
lesson ingrained. ``We had a coach who drilled us,'' Brown said.
Mom, Marvella Brown, was the coach, tougher than any other in her
single-mindedness.
</P>
<P>
   RSTLNE.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Alexander, sisters, twin sisters at that, studied
hard. They learned the letters, earned a trip to Pittsburgh and the
right to hear those three intoxicating words shouted:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wheel ... of ... Fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   Those five consonants and a vowel are what the 39-year-old
Albany women say are key to solving the program's puzzles: call out
those six letters to start, then there is a good chance you are on
your way to winning the game.
</P>
<P>
   Both avid fans of the show, they competed as teammates in a
regional audition in May in Boston. They were selected as part of
``Wheel's'' AFL-CIO ``Salute to America's Working Families Week,''
featuring contestants from various AFL-CIO unions. Alexander is a
member of the Civil Service Employees Association, while Brown,
because of a job promotion, is a former member.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wheel of Fortune'' is now entering its 16th year, started when
Merv Griffin presciently determined an expanded version of the
kids' game hangman would translate well to television. From those
roots grew a syndicated monster now seen around the world (prizes
and riddles are tailored to individual countries).
</P>
<P>
   While host Pat Sajak briefly left the show for his ill-fated
late-night talk fare (``The Pat Sajak Show,'' CBS, 1989-90), he
will be taping the 3,000th ``Wheel'' episode sometime this season.
</P>
<P>
   The genius is the game's simplicity; it requires some knowledge,
but not a reservoir of minutiae like ``Jeopardy!''
</P>
<P>
   The two sisters, who took part in a taping earlier this month,
have a couple of insider insights:
</P>
<P>
   1. The wheel is actually very heavy and hard to spin.
</P>
<P>
   2. Contestants look the same height because they stand on risers
that can be raised or lowered.
</P>
<P>
   3. The players are under constant surveillance from the moment
they enter the venue for the competition. Game shows are still
leery of the scandals that plagued the industry in decades past.
</P>
<P>
   4. A week's worth of five episodes are taped in one day.
Contestants are grouped into three teams, and then each group draws
numbered balls to determine in what order they will appear. For
example, drawing one means you go first with your show airing on a
Monday. The shows are taped in order.
</P>
<P>
   The twin sisters said Sajak and letter-turner Vanna White (who
now merely has to touch a monitor for a letter to show up) were
surprisingly genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very approachable, very approachable,'' Brown said.
``They responded to every little detail.''
</P>
<P>
   The obvious question _ with side-bet potential is: How did they
do?
</P>
<P>
   Watch the Thursday, Sept. 10, episode (check local listings),
the sisters say. The rules specifically state contestants can't
talk about results until after the show airs. But you can be
guaranteed one thing: Neither lacks in the enthusiasm department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was funn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
