<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: 10 years later, Moscow is meaner
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ On the way into Moscow from the airport, my old friend
and interpreter Pavlik was telling me how much things had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of crime in Moscow now, he said. But not to worry.
</P>
<P>
   Pavlik spoke to our driver in Russian. The driver moved his hand
to the edge of his suit coat.
</P>
<P>
   One moment his hand was empty. The next moment, a black
automatic pistol filled his hand.
</P>
<P>
   The driver smiled from behind his aviator-style sunglasses. I
shivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old Russians carry pistols to protect themselves from this new
democracy,'' he said, as Pavlik translated. He moved his gun hand
up to his neck. ``We are up to here with democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver, I'm told, had served as a military officer with the
Red Army in Afghanistan. He is no longer a Red _ more of a redneck.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not for show that he carries a pistol. Such a weapon is
required to hold your own in Moscow traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as Russian-roulette road rage.
</P>
<P>
   You pull out in front of the wrong guy _ what they call a steep
guy _ and you can pay a steep price.
</P>
<P>
   Steep means something like macho, only more so. It's a
brotherhood. Wise guy, in the Mafia sense, probably comes close.
</P>
<P>
   These are the junior-grade gangsters driving fancy Western cars,
wearing expensive suits and dripping with heavy gold jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   They'll curb you at the slightest provocation. At the very least
they'll curse you and humiliate you. They're likely to demand money
as payment for getting in their way. You say the wrong thing _ or
just anything _ and they'll beat you senseless.
</P>
<P>
   It's not for nothing that kick-boxing is one of Russia's most
popular sports among young people. It serves as training for steep
wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the little kids dream of,'' Pavlik said. ``It's
their ticket to a life of luxury cars, long-legged girls and
casinos.''
</P>
<P>
   And guns.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when I first visited Moscow, crimes involving
firearms were rare. Now it's everyday news _ contract murders, bar
shootouts, innocent bystanders killed by stray bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the law requires that you obtain a license from
police before you can buy a pistol. Even then you are allowed to
keep it only in your home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a few hours on the street market you can have a
pistol,'' Pavlik said. ``Probably 70 percent of the guns in Moscow
are illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like most everything else in Moscow nowadays. Money works.
Laws do not.
</P>
<P>
   Every business from flower shops to supermarkets pays for
protection. In a word, it's krysha. In Russian that means roof. You
pay for a roof over your head _ protection.
</P>
<P>
   Not that all of Russia is like Moscow. It never has been, it
never will be. The old rule still applies:
</P>
<P>
   You go 100 kilometers from Moscow, and you go 10 years back in
time; 1,000 kms, 20 years; 5,000 kms, 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Later that same day, when we no longer had the services of our
gunman driver, I came face to face with modern Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   We had hitched a ride. Amazing that you can still do that here.
You stand at the corner, raise your hand as you would in hailing a
cab, and in a minute or two a driver will stop to see where you're
going. For a couple of bucks, he'll take you.
</P>
<P>
   This was an old fellow in a beat-up old car. Probably he wasn't
that good of a driver. All of a sudden we found ourselves pulled
over to the curb by a steep guy in a new Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   We spent the next couple of minutes being screamed at. Nobody in
our car said a word. Our driver went pale. Probably I did, too.
Finally the Mercedes drove off.
</P>
<P>
   I asked Pavlik what was said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'Are you looking for trouble, goat?'''
</P>
<P>
   Goat?
</P>
<P>
   ``Goat is gangster slang,'' Pavlik said. ``It means a passive
homosexual. It is an insult to kill over.''
</P>
<P>
   Good grief. Where's the KGB when you need them?
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
</P>
<P>
   AWEW18A(at)prodigy.com; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
