<HEADLINE>
TRUTH OR CONSEQUENCES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (k and w coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- In David Kendall's perfectly crafted words, ``The
truth is the truth. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's lead lawyer came up with those words to
refute what he considered silly newspaper stories over the weekend
that his client was considering different versions of a story to
tell the grand jury Monday about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   His agreement to testify under oath, Kendall said, included by
definition an agreement to tell the truth. Period. But in that
spirit of simple clarity, it follows that a lie is a lie. Period.
</P>
<P>
   There is no amount of sugar that can ever adequately coat a lie
to make it something else.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is a lie is a virus that attacks everything around it.
The only vaccines that ever work _ in private or public matters _
are confession, followed by truth and expiation.
</P>
<P>
   When lies are told, relationships fray. Whether they permanently
rupture depends, but without the vaccines there is no hope, nor
should there be.
</P>
<P>
   As a national sorting out process begins this morning, there is
a remarkable but still inadequately appreciated political reality
in the country worthy of benchmark status.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans agree that the president's job was literally on
the line Monday, that anything other than what Kendall called ``the
truth'' is unacceptable as a basis for his continuing in office.
</P>
<P>
   But most Americans also appear to have been ahead of the players
in this mess (Clinton included) in making some tentative
conclusions about this mess, processing those conclusions, and
making some critical, discriminating judgments about what matters
to them.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, most Americans appear to have concluded that the
president and Lewinsky had some kind of sexual contact and that
they could care less what kind it was. They also appear to have
concluded that if the relationship did not extend to a clear
subornation of her false affadavit to Paula Jones's lawyers or a
clear effort to obstruct that civil lawsuit, they can live with it
as long as the president told the truth Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That does not preclude, nor should it, a full range of visceral
reactions to the belated disclosure of what had better be the truth
_ from a shoulder shrug to disappointment to disillusionment to
disgust and betrayal. The president should be prepared for them.
</P>
<P>
   As the sorting out begins, the real question is whether the
truth can reaffirm the preconfession willingness of most people to
support his presidency if the truth includes some kind of physical
relationship and falsehoods about it, but nothing else. For
starters, it will help to know a few things this morning:
</P>
<P>
   _Did he focus on his statements to the public last January _
first on the evening of Day 1 and then with his finger wagging on
Day 5 _ that he did not have sexual relations with Lewinsky? And do
we now know what he says the truth is, in English? In particular,
has he taken at least a step beyond the word ``inappropriate''?
</P>
<P>
   _Did he avoid a quibble or word game about how he answered the
specific questions of Paula Jones's lawyers in last January's
deposition? Eventually, lawyers, pols, and even the rest of us can
fight about what the correct term is, but this morning it's what he
said and now says to the country that matters.
</P>
<P>
   _Has he released a transcript of his testimony? The truth
Kendall defined as the truth is the president's only valid weapon,
and the transcript is the proper starting point for any effort to
reestablish trust.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more. Someone who has not told the truth is
invariably and appropriately faced with some version of the
following: If you didn't tell the truth about X, how can your
statements about everything else be worthy of belief?
</P>
<P>
   Within reason, the president would be well advised this morning
to give that sentiment the legitimacy it deserves. Some people may
want to ask again about Kathleen Willey; others may have a
Whitewater question; and others may even veer toward the financing
of his reelection campaign. Sounds like an argument for a very long
press conference. Given the horrid results of seven months of
lawyer-led silence with a flat-out denial hanging out there about
sex, the value of truthful, timely public statements seems
self-evident.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was an obvious perjury trap, largely of the president's
making. But if Clinton's testimony puts a real wall between an
acknowledged personal relationship and the abuse of his office the
scandal culture has been braying about irresponsibly, most
Americans would prefer to move on. But only if the bricks in that
wall are made of truth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
