<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR BILL? THINK ABOUT HIS DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - What I remember from 24 years ago is Tricia Nixon's
face. It was the day after her father resigned and he was saying
goodbye to the White House staff. Tricia was off to his left, next
to her mother, staring at the president, never taking her eyes off
him.
</P>
<P>
   I remember she tried to force a smile even as her eyes welled up
and her skin turned a translucent gray, as if a light bulb inside
her suddenly burned out.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, news broke of a recording made in the Oval Office
in which the president tried to get the CIA to interfere with the
FBI's Watergate investigation. After that, Nixon had no choice but
to quit.
</P>
<P>
   It was August, like now. I was home from college, working the
night shift at a steel mill when I heard the words on a portable
radio someone had carried into the plant: ``Therefore, I shall
resign the presidency effective at noon tomorrow . . .''
</P>
<P>
   I cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The old-timers gathered around the radio shook their heads and
walked away.
</P>
<P>
   The next day I gleefully switched on TV as Nixon was about to
say a final farewell to his staff. I believed _ stupid kid that I
was _ it would be good for a few laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Then I saw Tricia's face.
</P>
<P>
   The family was all behind Nixon. Tricia, her mother, her sister
Julie, their husbands. The day before, they'd urged the president
not to resign. Investigators had the man cold, but his daughters
never wavered. They never doubted him. They loved him.
</P>
<P>
   You could see it in Tricia's eyes. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Breaking hearts &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Her heart broke for him, and yours broke for her, as it should
break now for Chelsea Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was easier for Nixon's girls than it is for Chelsea. Tricia
and Julie's father hadn't done anything to them, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Or to their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Their father was accused of being a bad president, not a bad
husband.
</P>
<P>
   Their father was accused of carrying on a criminal conspiracy,
not carrying on with a woman only a few years older than his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us can argue over whether the investigation of Bill
Clinton was worth the money.
</P>
<P>
   We can ask if spending $40 million to investigate a man's
personal life is wise in an era when 257 people die in a terrorist
bombing in Kenya because there's not enough money for a new
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   We can argue about policy and philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's family doesn't have that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   What happened between Clinton and Monica Lewinsky couldn't be a
surprise to Hillary. She's stuck with her husband through similar
problems. Chelsea had no choice. She may be 18 years old, a college
student, an adult, but she can't divorce her father.
</P>
<P>
   And apparently, she doesn't want to. &QL; 
`Open arms and devotion' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
The Rev. Jesse Jackson, who was at the White House on Sunday night,
said Clinton's family was behind him. ``Fortunately for him,''
Jackson said, ``they are greeting him with open arms and devotion.
. . . He won't have to testify with one eye on the grand jury and
one eye on his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's exactly what he should have done.
</P>
<P>
   All day Monday, commentators on TV were saying it was the most
difficult day in Bill Clinton's life _ first testifying before
Kenneth Starr's grand jury, then speaking on television to the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   I hope they were wrong.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't difficult for Clinton to say on national TV, ``Now
this matter is between me, the two people I love most, my wife and
my daughter, and our God. I must put it right, and I'm prepared to
do whatever it takes to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   That was theater. It was spectacle. It wasn't tough. The tough
part, I hope, came earlier, away from the cameras, when Clinton had
to tell his daughter what he'd done. That was drama. That was
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   I hope no one was there to photograph her face. &QL; 
{E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
