<HEADLINE>
SEVEN GABLES AND FOUR FACTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you visit a famous building like Salem's House of the Seven
Gables, which has been around since 1668, you get a hefty serving
of history with your tour. But what is likely to remain with you
are the ``little'' things that show just how different life was in
the 17th and 18th centuries. Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   _The beds are short not only because people were slightly
smaller then but because residents slept sitting up to ease
breathing difficulties caused by sooty fireplaces and other
respiratory threats.
</P>
<P>
   _At different times, the famed Secret Staircase hid goods
(purportedly to elude the British taxmen) as well as escaped slaves
en route to Canada via the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   _The youngest child was given the unenviable job of emptying the
chamber pots. So that child would, of course, pray for Mama to have
another baby!
</P>
<P>
   _Behind the house, you could stroll just a few feet into the
ocean and pick up huge lobsters. These would be given to the pigs
and the indentured servants. Proper people wouldn't dream of dining
on those shell-covered scavengers.
</P>
<P>
   The House of the Seven Gables Historic Site is open year round
except for the first two weeks in January. It constitutes its own
national historic district with a collection of six houses on the
National Register of Historic Places. There are also two seaside
Colonial Revival Gardens and an 18th-century granite sea wall. For
more information, call 978-744-0991 or visit www.7gables.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Travel Trivia: &LR;  Which country separates the North Sea from the
Baltic Sea? (Answer at end of column.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; In a name: &LR;  Come spring, the refurbished 134-room Wilson World
Hotel in Memphis will be renamed Heartbreak Hotel. Would it
surprise you to learn the hotel is near Graceland?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Quotable:  &LR; ``Nothing has been left undone, either by man or nature,
to make India the most extraordinary country that the sun visits on
his rounds.'' _ Mark Twain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Freebie: &LR;  Grand Circle Travel offers an excellent free booklet
called ``Going Abroad: 101 Tips for Mature Travelers.'' For a copy,
call 800-248-3737. You can also expect to receive literature about
Grand Circle trips, but that's no bad thing, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; A lotta languages: &LR;  A total of 6,701 languages are currently spoken
in the 228 countries of the world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Just wondering: &LR;  Why is it that the Thames River in England is
pronounced TEMS but Thames Street in Newport, R.I., is pronounced
THAYMES? Or that Houston Street in New York City is pronounces
HOW-ston but Houston, Texas, is pronounced HEW-ston? Or (as Valerie
A. Russo of Weymouth informs us) Wareham, Mass., is pronounced
WARE-ham whereas the Canadian and English towns are pronounced
WARE-em?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Today's fractured English lesson: &LR;  A sign in a Swiss mountain inn
told customers: ``Special today _ no ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Never on Tuesday: &LR;  Hanauma Bay, the beautiful and popular
snorkeling spot on the Hawaiian island of Oahu, is now closed each
Tuesday for cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Did you guess it? &LR;  Denmark separates the North Sea from the Baltic
Sea.
</P>
