<HEADER>
A9244 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-HARRIS-2ND &LR;  &UR; T     08-18 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-HARRIS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... was the president.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1968, Harris took a job at Sun Oil as a community relations
consultant. Once again, she was promoted, eventually chosen to head
the company's public relations department in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was briefly married and divorced. She has no children.
None of her friends was willing to talk about the former husband,
except to say that he remained close enough to the family to attend
Miss Bea's funeral. Harris declined to answer questions about her
personal romantic life.
</P>
<P>
   Key elements in Harris's life have been her friendships, her
civil rights activism, and her work in the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church was not something to be played with for Barbara,'' said
Washington. He met Harris in the mid-1950s, when both worked as
church youth counselors. ``She was never someone you could describe
as a pew warmer. She was going to get in the midst of things.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Civil rights crusader
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harris switched parishes as an adult to be closer to Washington,
a priest and author well known in Philadelphia for his political
activism. Fighting for the rights of blacks and women became a
central part of her life during the 1960s. She marched with Martin
Luther King Jr. and worked for the Urban League and other
organizations. She is still active in Episcopal groups for
African-Americans and is very outspoken against the church's
lingering disapproval of homosexuals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Harris, still a laywoman, was asked to be the cross
bearer at a historic ceremony in Philadelphia when the first 11
women were ordained as Episcopal priests.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``a beautiful foreshadowing of what was to come,''
according to Reverend Ann Robb Smith, now the priest at Harris's
hometown church, and one of many in attendance that day who
remember her leading the procession.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after the ceremony, Harris said, she felt God tugging
at her to become more involved in the church. When asked to
describe that time in her life, Harris got a look in her eyes that
was so peaceful and intense it bordered on sadness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to explain,'' she said. ``I had a very
active lay ministry, which was very satisfying. But I discovered
that there was a different shape to my ministry, and that I was
being led to the ordained ministry for a different dimension of
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled against it for a long time. I didn't feel that I
was a worthy candidate. A friend of mine who was a priest and is
now a bishop said, `God does not call those who are worthy; he
makes worthy those who are called.' That helped.''
</P>
<P>
   After deciding to become a priest, Harris continued working at
Sun Oil. She took seminary classes nights and weekends and spent
her vacations studying, a nontraditional route. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Entering the order
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harris was ordained a deacon in 1979, and a priest in 1980, at
the age of 50. She left her position at Sun, but remained a
consultant for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Her first religious job was as part-time priest in charge of a
church in Norristown, Pa., called Saint Augustine of Hippo. Then,
in 1984, Harris was named executive director of the Episcopal
Church Publishing Co. and publisher of The Witness magazine, long
an open forum for dissent within the church. Harris had been on the
board of the company for years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, she took Washington's place as interim director of the
Church of the Advocate when he had stepped down. That same year,
she attended the Lambeth Convention, a gathering of Anglican
bishops from all over the world, in Canterbury, England, as a
reporter for The Witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was open talk at the time that a woman might be elected
in the United States,'' said Reverend Canon Edward W. Rodman, the
canon missioner for Massachusetts and Harris's friend for 30 years.
``Her name was lifted up at that time as one of the possible
candidates. She came back sort of on notice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really torn about whether it was something I really
wanted to do,'' said Harris. ``I thought about all of the potential
problems. I thought I wouldn't be nominated, as a woman. Then I
thought that I would not be elected, even if I was nominated ... I
was greatly surprised at each step in the process.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Caring and alert'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When she came in for the formal interview with the committee,
it was so very clear in that time that she would be one of the
nominees,'' said John J. Bishop, a retired priest living in
Yarmouthport, who chaired the committee that elected Harris as a
bishop. ``She was just caring, alert, bright, committed to the
issues that were confronting the church at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington remembers the day Harris was elected. ``She received
a call from David Johnson, the bishop of Massachusetts at the time,
saying she had been elected. I did the sermon at her ordination to
the priesthood, and she called and said `You better get another
speech prepared.' That was deep.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris's consecration as bishop was widely supported in this
liberal state. But some in the church, such as the Episcopal bishop
of South Carolina, who resigned one week after Harris was selected,
said her unorthodox religious education was unacceptable. Others
showed up at the consecration to protest, because of Harris's
gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the protests were very personal,'' Harris said. ``I
got death threats.'' She stopped to grin, and added, ``All in the
name of the Lord, of course.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 years since Harris became a bishop, her performance
has opened doors for other women in the church. There are now eight
female bishops in the United States, seven in Canada, and one in
New Zealand. ``That's why the people who protested did so,'' Harris
said. ``They knew that if one woman was consecrated, that there
would be no stopping us after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris has also elevated the visibility of nonwhites in the
local Episcopal church, which has become increasingly diverse. She
works in tandem with the diocesan bishop, Thomas Shaw, in a
relationship that those who know them describe as harmonious and
productive. The arrangement, by which they share most duties, is a
new system, and one that Rodman says was created to increase
Harris's visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her energy, and her clear love of the work, church rules
require that all bishops retire at 72, four years from now for
Harris. Though she is vague about her plans after retirement, those
who know her say to stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always say that we haven't seen the best from Barbara Harris
yet,'' said Rodman. ``There's no telling what she'll do next, but
you can be sure it will be amazing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
