<HEADER>
A9250 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-ART-2TAKE     08-18 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI _ LOW-KEY CONSENSUS BUILDER 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A few months ago, the Big Dig faced big disaster, a
shutdown caused by lack of funding. Acting Governor Paul Cellucci,
working with legislative leadership, was able to cobble together a
$1.5 billion rescue of the downtown Boston project by pushing
through a complicated bond deal that allowed the state to borrow
for 15 years without consequences to its bond rating.
</P>
<P>
   The story didn't lead the noon news, the late-night news, or the
front page of the news. In fact, no one reported it at all. It was
too bureaucratic, too inside. Too colorless, too boring. Good
government isn't news.
</P>
<P>
   But in its small way, it illustrated Cellucci's strengths and
the problems confronting his campaign to remove ``acting'' from his
job title.
</P>
<P>
   A man who has served in the State House for nearly his entire
adult life, Cellucci, 50, is renowned for his ability to dive into
issues, forge consensus, and reach resolution. Unlike his
predecessor, William F. Weld, Cellucci is fascinated by the act of
governing, and by the minutiae of issues many others find tedious.
</P>
<P>
   But critics complain that in the body of the acting governor
beats the heart of a former small-town selectman, a man of modest
thoughts and minor causes. They say he is an inadequate substitute
for a man who cut taxes, uttered such memorable one-liners as ``you
can lead the House to order, but you can't make it think,'' and
jumped into the Charles River during a press conference just for
laughs.
</P>
<P>
   There are not many colorful Paul Cellucci stories, even fewer
memorable quips. He works, plays boccie with his best friend and
his 74-year-old father, and goes to movies to unwind.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents savage him as colorless and unimaginative, a
politician who hopes to ride Weld's increasingly distant coattails
into a full term. They say a misguided ``Rose Garden'' strategy
seeks to cover up an administration that has left almost no
footprints after more than a year in office. Even Weld, now
comfortably ensconced in a State Street law firm, acknowledges the
public does not have much sense of who Paul Cellucci is or what he
is for, against, or about.
</P>
<P>
   Despite often being touted as Weld's ``co-governor'' _
accurately, by all accounts _ Cellucci still faces the classic
challenge of the number two executive who seeks to become number
one: proving that he has the stature to run the show.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci betrays little concern about any of this. He is, he
says, a man committed to doing his job, the job the people of
Massachusetts elected him to do. He will continue to push for
deeper tax cuts, more money for education reform, and the
restoration of the death penalty. Much like his political role
model, former governor John A. Volpe, he believes he represents the
silent majority of Massachusetts voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just intent on doing my job,'' he said recently during an
interview in his office. ``I'm just continuing to fight for the
things that I think are important to the working families of
Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   His stance reflects values forged early in life in Cellucci's
native Hudson, a central Massachusetts town of abandoned shoe
factories and steel mills, recently revived by high-technology
businesses. His grandfather settled in Hudson in 1910 after
emigrating from Italy. Cellucci's father, Argeo L. Cellucci, owned
an Oldsmobile dealership.
</P>
<P>
   Both his grandfather and his father held public office in Hudson
_ his grandfather as a public works commissioner, his father, to
this day, as head of the industrial commission, a panel designed to
lure business to a sleepy town dotted with decaying red brick and
often overshadowed by neighboring Marlborough.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's interest in politics was evident at an early age. As
a 10-year-old, in 1958, he handed out leaflets for his
grandfather's public works campaign. Two of the three commissioners
had resigned in a dispute with the town power department, and Argeo
L. Cellucci had decided to replace one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going door-to-door, passing out pamphlets for my
grandfather,'' Cellucci recently mused over coffee at Nick's Diner,
where he has breakfast most mornings. ``I loved the challenge and
excitement of politics then, as I continue to today.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick's is a place where nearly everyone greets him as Paul,
where a man who once served with him on the Hudson board of
selectmen shoos him to a more distant table during an interview
because he is disrupting everyone else's good time.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson of the 1950s and the 1960s was a town in transition.
After the construction of the Massachusetts Turnpike and I-495 made
it accessible, the town nearly doubled in size, from a little over
8,000 in 1960 to 16,084 in 1970, according to the US Census. The
Celluccis, who sold Oldsmobiles for 69 years and Chevrolets for
nearly 30, took an active role in helping to manage the town's
growth, forming what remains a notably grass-roots view of the role
of government.
</P>
<P>
   One of three children, young Paul Cellucci's days and nights
were dominated by many of the classic pursuits of small-town
boyhood _ baseball and football, playing alto saxophone in the band
at Hudson Catholic High School. He was popular, but not what you'd
call a star. He was class treasurer, not president, and the kind of
athlete who won sportsmanship awards rather than set records.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pulled the usual boyhood pranks, but nothing serious,''
recalls Robert Yesue, then and now one of Cellucci's closest
friends. ``Paul always had access to a car, because of the
dealership, and he spent a lot of time driving the rest of us
around to practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci graduated from high school in 1966, at the height of
the Vietnam War. He was opposed to the war, but speaks of that
epochal event with little of the passion he brings to discussions
of tax cuts or education reform. He never participated in a Vietnam
protest, and he joined the ROTC as an undergraduate at Boston
College.
</P>
<P>
   A training exercise at Fort Devens in Ayer provided one of the
lighter moments of his college career. During an escape-and-evasion
exercise, Cellucci, was ``captured'' by a group of upperclassmen
pretending to be North Vietnamese soldiers. He talked his way out
of captivity, escaping into a swamp. When he made it out, he was on
Lunenburg Road in Lancaster, in battle fatigues, carrying an
unloaded M-1 rifle. He hitchhiked back to Devens at 2:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci graduated from BC with a degree in accounting in 1970,
and was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the Army. But he
never made it any closer to Vietnam than the Aberdeen Proving
Grounds in Maryland, where he spent three months in the reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, he continued to work in the family business,
commuting to classes at Boston College. He washed cars, waxed cars,
and sold cars. He remembers horrifying his father in 1973 by
ordering 100 burnt-orange Cutlasses at the end of the model year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just liked the color,'' Cellucci said with a laugh. ``We
were selling maybe 500 cars a year, so 100 was a huge number. But I
sold them all, and once in a while I still see one around town.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
