<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 13:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     08-18 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... around town.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After zipping through Boston College Law School, Cellucci, by
then married to his high school sweetheart, the former Janet
Garnett, began a career as a Hudson lawyer, handling everything
from real estate closings to criminal law. They have two daughters,
Anne, a government student at Harvard, and Kate, a student at
Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci was elected to a commission revising the Hudson town
charter in 1971, just after finishing his undergraduate degree.
That was followed by winning a seat on the town's board of
selectmen. Then, in 1976, he was elected to the Massachusetts House
(and later the Senate), the only Republican to win a formerly
Democratic seat in the first post-Watergate election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became rather frustrated as a selectman because I found that
a lot of things were out of our control,'' Cellucci says now.
``They even passed a law that said what we had to pay our police
chief and our fire chief. I became an advocate of home rule.''
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature of the 1970s was a considerably different
institution than it is now. For one, it was larger (the House had
240 members, compared to 160 now), was more rigidly
liberal-Democratic and colorful, and was plagued by corruption
cases. Cellucci quickly forged a reputation as a reformer. He
played an important role in pressing for action on the University
of Massachusetts building scandal that ended the careers of a
passel of old-boy legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was exceedingly hard-working,'' recalls former state
senator David Locke. ``I considered him to be an expert in certain
areas. He was one of our key people on health care issues and on
legal matters, and he was particularly strong on local affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Locke also recalls Cellucci often walking into the Senate
carrying a stack of telephone messages and correspondence,
scrambling to maintain his ties to constituents in Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   He was active on a lot of health care issues _ one of his
signature triumphs was a bill to allow midwives to deliver babies.
He also pushed through a bill expanding the duties of optometrists.
</P>
<P>
   He was an advocate for seatbelt laws and laws requiring crash
helmets. Colleagues still remember him making an impassioned speech
on the Senate floor sympathizing with people who had to ``clean up
the mess'' after fatal auto crashes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``He was known as a very good lawyer in the Legislature,''
recalled Andrew Card, a former legislator and a close friend of
Cellucci. ``People would go to him to get the legal view of
legislation. He was quiet and hardworking, I was more of a
firebrand.''
</P>
<P>
   But by 1988, after six years in the House and five more in the
Senate, he was itching to play on a bigger stage. He became an
early supporter of George Bush's campaign for president, and as
state coordinator, helped him secure the endorsement of several
Massachusetts police unions, endorsements that helped cement the
image of Democratic nominee Michael S. Dukakis as a liberal out of
touch with such issues as public safety.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also became the catalyst for Cellucci's change in
position on the death penalty. He says police officers he met
during the campaign convinced him that the death penalty would make
their jobs safer. Cellucci has evolved over the years from a death
penalty opponent to its chief standard-bearer in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's drubbing in Dukakis's home state was a foregone
conclusion, but Cellucci had been instrumental in striking a nerve,
and convincing people that the much-beloved idea of the
``Massachusetts Miracle'' just might be on borrowed time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, almost everyone was surprised in 1989 when he
began making noises about running for governor.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican field was bursting with better-known,
better-financed candidates, including Locke; Andrew Card, then an
aide to Bush; former US representative Paul Cronin; state
Representative Steven Pierce of Westfield; and former US attorney
William F. Weld.
</P>
<P>
   But one by one, the Republican field melted. And that October,
while Cellucci was still undecided about leaping into the fray,
Weld approached him with a novel idea. They would be running mates,
and if elected would govern together as full partners.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a governor and lieutenant governor running in tandem
was unusual. And so was the team, Weld, the patrician from Oyster
Bay, N.Y., and Cellucci, the ethnic pol from tiny and unglamourous
Hudson. Besides that, they barely knew one another. They'd travel
on the political circuit, but had no personal relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But Weld had never held office, and was intrigued by having a
partner with Cellucci's deep knowledge of the State House and
contacts in the Legislature. He also, he says, had a gut feeling
about Cellucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great instinct and a great knowledge and background
in the Legislature,'' Weld said recently. ``Paul was absolutely a
full partner. He was in every meeting, he was in on every
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   They toppled Pierce, the darling of the party faithful, and to
slip past Boston University president John R. Silber in the most
dramatic governor's race in years.
</P>
<P>
   If Weld is thought of in more cerebral terms, Cellucci is
considered more passionate, and far more of a hands-on manager.
</P>
<P>
   But to his adversaries, Cellucci's reputation for deft dealing
in the State House is a camouflage for constant compromise with the
enemy. They accuse him of allowing two Democrats, House Speaker
Thomas M. Finneran and Senate President Thomas F. Birmingham, to
wrest much of the power away from the governor's office. Between
them, they have killed Cellucci's tax cut ideas without a trace of
remorse, sabotaged his dreams of funding a new stadium for the New
England Patriots, and ignored huge chunks of Cellucci's legislative
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Trimarco, deputy treasurer under Cellucci's primary
opponent for governor, Joseph D. Malone, and a longtime activist in
the state GOP, says Cellucci has simply given away the store.
``It's tragic what's happened in this state,'' Trimarco says. ``We
were all elected in 1990 as reformers, and instead Paul simply goes
along to get along. We may lose, we may not win, but I would rather
lose as a Republican than just give the Democrats whatever they
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not surprisingly, Cellucci does not take such criticism
seriously. He points to close to $1 billion in tax cuts as evidence
of his success in influencing Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think voters elected me to do a job and I've been doing that
job,'' Cellucci said. ``And if I'm elected I'm going to keep on
fighting to get the tax rate back to 5 percent, fighting for
teacher testing, and to bring back the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue that has continued to haunt Cellucci _ one initially
believed fatal to his hopes of becoming governor _ is his mountain
of personal debt, estimated at $700,000. It has forced his family
to liquidate real estate holdings in Hudson and other properties to
meet payments. Cellucci emphasizes that he has never missed a
payment, that the debt is the result of raising his two daughters.
But critics have argued that it casts doubt on his management
ability _ at the least _ and insist that Cellucci's explanations
cover little more than half of the debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The substance of this story is and always has been that I
built up the debt providing for my family and I have never missed a
payment,'' Cellucci said last week. ``It has nothing to do with
being governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it may help me to understand families working to
make ends meet,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Though some recent polls indicate his race with Malone is closer
than had been expected, there has been little change in Cellucci's
low-key manner. He is, friends say, what he is: A policy wonk
dedicated to government, low on flash but bullish on the idea that
less government is better government.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been given an opportunity not many people get,'' he said
last week. ``And whether I'm governor for one year, one term or two
terms, I want to know I've been able to get things done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
