<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S LARGEST GLOBE IN MAINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The earth is yours to behold in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme, a mapmaking company renowned for its atlases and
mapping software titles, is out to take title to the world's
largest moving globe. ``Eartha is the largest image of Earth ever
created,'' said David Delorme, chief executive officer of the
Yarmouth company.
</P>
<P>
   Eartha is 42 feet in diameter and rotates and revolves just like
the real earth. Every continent is vividly detailed. Eartha can
easily be seen from Interstate 95, but it's best to get off and
head over to Route 1 for a close up look from inside the DeLorme
headquarters. Visitors are welcome in the building daily from 8:30
a.m. to 6 p.m. and Sundays from 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   To get a good look, just head for Freeport's famed outlet shops
and, of course, L.L.Bean, the store that never closes. DeLorme is
just a mile south of downtown Freeport.
</P>
<P>
   DeLorme is submitting Eartha for inclusion in the Guinness Book
of World Records, noting that it exceeds the size of the globe
currently listed as the largest, the Globe of Peace in Apecchi,
Italy. DeLorme hopes Eartha will give visitors a better
appreciation of the world around them, and help the company create
even better maps. DeLorme just released two Eartha-related
products, the ``Eartha World Travelog,'' a paper atlas of the
world, and ``Eartha Global Explorer,'' a CD-Rom with 3-D views of
the earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
New World Festival
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Randolph, Vt., is the place to be Sept. 6. That's the day for
the annual New World Festival, an event born from a disaster. After
three disastrous fires, the town conceived the festival that
celebrates the musical heritage of the region _ Celtic and
French-American music and dance. The festival takes place in the
downtown area (on the National Register of Historic Sites) and at
the Chandler Music Hall, considered one of the finest small concert
halls in America. It should be a great day filled with food, music,
drink, and fun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Upcoming
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Adams Farm in Wilmington, Vt., will hold its annual Sheep &AMP;
Fiber Festival Aug. 22-23. There will be sheep shearing, herding,
spinners and weavers, and sheep, alpacas, llamas, and goats on
view. Call 802-464-3762.
</P>
<P>
   The seventh annual White Mountains Jazz and Blues Festival will
be held Aug. 22 in Conway Village. For information on the New
Hampshire festival, call 603-447-2639 or visit www.jazzblues.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Seashore Trolley Museum in Kennebunkport, Maine, will roll
out trolleys with 25, 50, 7,5 and 100-year birthdays on Aug. 22. If
you show a Maine driver's license, you can get in for just 5 cents.
Call 207-967-2800 for details.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Caribbean combo
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two deluxe resorts in the Caribbean have teamed up to offer a
``Double Island Vacation Combo'' for as little as $300 a person.
The resorts are the Westin Rio Mar Beach Resort &AMP; Casino on Puerto
Rico's northeast coast, and the Westin Resort, St. John, on St.
John's Great Cruz Bay, and the offer is valid through Dec. 15.
Prices begin at $300 a person, double occupancy, for two nights at
each resort, or $450 for three nights at each property. Also
included are free meals for children 12 and under, $500 in discount
coupons,and a $100 food and beverage credit. For reservations or
more information, call 800-WESTIN-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
