<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WE MEAN WHEN WE SAY BULL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: note dictionary style)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What confusing times! The stock market soars, the stock market
plunges. Earnings look great, earnings look bad. One day your
Chrysler's a Chrysler. The next day your Chrysler's a Daimler. Old,
comfy products vanish. New ones burst onto the scene out of
nowhere. The values of yesterday are not the values of today.
Sometimes it seems modern business speaks in a language all its
own.
</P>
<P>
   To help you sort through today's vocabulary, we present excerpts
from the Dollars &AMP; Nonsense Dictionary. In its entirety, the hefty
tome is an indispensable tool for economists, stock market
analysts, corporate leaders, and con men. As Ivan Boesky, that
exemplar of business for our generation, has said: the dictionary
defines modern economic life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   airport n. shopping mall where planes land and depart
</P>
<P>
   American Dream n. state of prosperity and happiness open to any
American born into a family bearing the name Rockefeller, du Pont,
or the like _ SYN. see LUCK
</P>
<P>
   appreciation n. 1. the increase in value of your possessions,
i.e., stocks, real estate, jewelry, works of art, beanie babies 2.
the feeling you experience when your possessions appreciate _ ANT.
see DEPRECIATION
</P>
<P>
   Barnes &AMP; Noble n. coffee and pastry shop that sells books
</P>
<P>
   bear market n. 1. a quaint antiquity long forgotten by most
investors 2. stock market condition that confirms the adage: those
who forget history are destined to repeat it
</P>
<P>
   bull market n. condition in which the stock market grows ever
more full of bull
</P>
<P>
   business cycle n. period of business activity in which corporate
fortunes go up and up and up and up and up
</P>
<P>
   business journalism n. the craft of glorifying executive
mongrels
</P>
<P>
   buying and selling n. primary occupation of humans today,
replacing the archaic occupation of learning
</P>
<P>
   chief investment strategist n. the investment sage at a mutual
fund company, brokerage, bank, etc., whose value to the
organization is measured not by his market insight but by the
number of his appearances in the media
</P>
<P>
   credit n. opportunity to buy now and pay many times more later
</P>
<P>
   depreciation n. 1. decline in value of an asset over time, such
as your 1976 Chevy Vega 2. feeling you experience when you realize
the 76 Vega isn't worth the price of a sandwich _ ANT. see
APPRECIATION
</P>
<P>
   employment n. opportunity to do for eight hours a day what a
person would rather not do at all
</P>
<P>
   full employment n. desired economic condition in which an entire
nation has the opportunity to do for eight hours a day what it
would rather not do at all
</P>
<P>
   greed n. self-interest disguised as public good
</P>
<P>
   Internet n. superhighway with no speed limit, no guard rails,
and no road signs packed with blind drivers racing who knows where
</P>
<P>
   loyalty n. devotion to a person or organization, characterized
by a commitment that ignores all outside entreaties until something
better comes along
</P>
<P>
   luck n. 1. cosmic force that determines whether or not one is
born into a family bearing the name Rockefeller, du Pont, or the
like. 2. cosmic force that determines whether or not one is
attractive to a member of a family bearing the name Rockefeller, du
Pont, or the like
</P>
<P>
   money n. scraps of paper whose allure dwarfs the demands of
love, family, morality, sex
</P>
<P>
   productivity n. the efficiency of a corporation after it throws
most workers into the street and cracks the whip on the suckers
left behind
</P>
<P>
   profit n. greed disguised as excellence
</P>
<P>
   stock n. a share in a company the ownership of which causes
sentient beings to completely lose touch with reality regarding the
accumulation of personal wealth
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steven Levingston can be reached at leving(at)bu.edu.)
</P>
</TEXT>
