<HEADLINE>
FAMILY LEAVE ACT STILL GOING THROUGH GROWING PAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Family and Medical Leave Act is five years old this month, a
significant feat for a profamily law whose birth caused so much
hoopla back in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Carved out of a long line of drafts and redrafts, the FMLA has
gone through radical changes since Georgetown University law
professor Donna Lenhoff helped write the initial bill in 1984.
Under the current law, workers at firms with at least 50 employees
are permitted to take up to 12 weeks of unpaid leave to care for a
newborn or newly adopted child; tend to a sick parent, child, or
spouse; or recover from their own serious illness. The measure
protects the worker's job and health benefits while he or she is on
leave.
</P>
<P>
   The original law, by contrast, guaranteed 18 weeks of leave
every two years, with 26 weeks for employees with serious health
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s, Lenhoff and US Representatives Maxine Waters
and Howard Berman, both California Democrats, set out to develop a
broad law that would cover fathers and mothers, adoptive parents
and legal guardians, employees with needy older parents, and
employees who simply needed time to iron out personal problems or
issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, the law guaranteed an employee an equivalent job if
he was out for the birth, adoption, or serious illness of a child,
or because of his own serious medical conditions,'' says Lenhoff,
who is also an attorney at the National Partnership for Women and
Families in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   But the bill's debut in 1984 elicited bitter reactions.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush vetoed it twice; he thought it unAmerican. The US
Chamber of Commerce slammed it. It said employers would wind up
spending $16.2 billion a year to fill vacant jobs and continue the
health benefits of workers on leave. Congressional foes chided
Waters and Berman for promoting a measure that would force the
private sector to pay for social welfare. They also said it would
be too hard to maintain and track.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 18 hearings over nine years in the House and
Senate,'' recalls Lenhoff. ``By the time my own daughter was born
in 1992, the bill had been passed twice and was about to be vetoed
the second time.'' Lenhoff watched debates on the bill on C-Span
during her own parental leave.
</P>
<P>
   Even some supporters were leery: How effective could such a law
be, they said, if the only people who can afford an extended unpaid
leave are dual-income couples and professionals?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still naysayers out there,'' says Margaret Sotham, a
spokeswoman for the national partnership. ``There are people who
still think the law leads to abuse, but the truth is most people
cannot afford to take unpaid leave just for the heck of it. This is
for employees who need time for serious emergencies, for family
issues that cannot be handled in a few hours or a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, plenty of people can attest to the bill's importance
in their lives. But even with such a law in place, problems arise,
particularly for males at companies at which leave-taking is viewed
as something only women do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fathers, in particular, often feel pressured not to take a
leave or not to take as much time off,'' says Jennifer Swanberg,
senior research associate at The Families and Work Institute in New
York. ``Some of it is covert, some overt. And most of it is social
pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent study, The Families and Work Institute found that
maternity leave is still more acceptable than paternity leave, even
though companies are legally bound by the law to offer both to
workers who need time off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty-three percent of the 1,000 businesses with 100 or more
employees surveyed offered time off for maternity leave with some
type of replacement pay,'' says Swanberg. ``But for paternity
leave, it was 13 percent. Culturally, businesses are more likely to
support leave for working moms then men.''
</P>
<P>
   Machinist Mark Duckworth of North Berwick, Me., is a living
example of why a law like the FMLA is needed. So is David Watkins,
also of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after suffering an accident, Duckworth took 52 days of
medical leave from his job at Pratt &AMP; Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   When Duckworth tried to return to work following a layoff,
however, he was barred because of poor attendance. Duckworth argued
that his poor attendance was due to the medical leave.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a federal appeals court in Portland, Maine, agreed. It
ruled that a personal or family leave cannot be held against job
applicants by potential or prospective employers.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, while recuperating from a second heart attack,
David Watkins of Waterville was replaced as an oil company manager
even though he still had time left on his 12-week leave. When
Watkins returned to work, the only job he was offered was pumping
gas on the third shift.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins quit. Then he sued and won: A jury later found that
Watkins' employer had violated the FMLA and awarded Watkins $43,000
in back pay and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Diane E. Lewis is a Boston Globe staff member. She can be
reached at The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107, or by e-mail at
work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
