<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY PROPOSAL TO MOVE SPARKS FEUD OVER SITE IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jobs and tax breaks. Tax breaks and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is a game that Fidelity Investments has become expert at
playing as its payroll has exploded to more than 27,000 with this
longest of all bull markets. Fidelity played the jobs card hard
here two years ago when it wrestled a $40 million tax break for the
state's mutual fund industry.
</P>
<P>
   Now the game has shifted to Texas, where Fidelity has been
scouting to expand its regional operation. Code name: Project
Roadrunner.
</P>
<P>
   The prize is one of the hottest development areas in all of
north Texas and the players include the likes of Ross Perot Jr.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of maneuvering, Fidelity is close to a deal that
would allow it to move its 2,700 Texas employees from Irving, just
outside Dallas, to a new campus-like setting on 300 acres in rural
Westlake, just outside Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity says it has no plans to expand its Texas work force,
but local officials there note the company has approval to build as
much as 5 million square feet of office space, which could
accommodate as many as 10,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity emphatically says it is not planning to shift
Massachusetts workers to Texas and notes it has just announced
plans for a new building in South Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The money that comes with all those white-collar Fidelity jobs
set off the usual feverish courtship by the surrounding
communities. It also plopped Fidelity smack in the middle of a
blood feud that literally nearly wiped Westlake (pop. 250) off the
map.
</P>
<P>
   For two years now, Westlake has been torn by a proposal by
Perot's company to develop the 2,500-acre Circle T Ranch in
Westlake into offices, a shopping center, apartments, a golf
course, and something dubbed ``Texas Town,'' a town square with a
historical theme.
</P>
<P>
   Blocked by Westlake's mayor, who opposed Perot's plan, the board
of alderman staged a coup that forced Mayor Scott Bradley briefly
from office last year. In the best Texas tradition, the aldermen
then allowed Perot and other unhappy landowners to secede from the
town. Development-friendly Fort Worth and a small adjacent town
almost immediately accepted jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a donnybrook ever since, with lawsuit after lawsuit,
two of which are now scheduled to be decided by the Texas Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity has changed the equation.
</P>
<P>
   When the big Boston mutual fund company expressed interest in
the Westlake site, Perot and Bradley (back in office after a town
vote) and his allies immediately made peace. Fidelity made it clear
it did not want to be caught up in some never ending battle of
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   David Weinstein, chief of administration and government affairs,
said Monday Fidelity was attracted to Westlake because many of its
employees from its Irving operations lived in the Westlake area.
</P>
<P>
   But it also had another reason for favoring Westlake: The town
has no property taxes. Fort Worth, which now claims the Circle T
property, does. ``No taxes is very appealing,'' a Fidelity
spokesman told Fort Worth Star-Telegram reporter Miles Moffeit.
</P>
<P>
   Not only does Westlake have no property tax, but the alderman
also approved guidelines that will ensure that Fidelity's bills
could be discounted by as much as 90 percent if a property tax were
ever imposed. The board also established a ``reinvestment zone''
that will allow Fidelity to strike tax-break deals with adjoining
counties. The Westlake initiatives came, in part, to counter
aggressive tax-cut deals by at least three nearby communities.
</P>
<P>
   All that stands in the way of Fidelity and Westlake is an
agreement by Fort Worth to give up its claim to the Circle T land.
Fort Worth isn't about to back down yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has changed, tell us?' asks Pat Svacina, a Fort Worth
spokesman. ``Why would they go into Fort Worth one day and out on
another day?''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bradley, 59, has no small interest in the outcome.
Fidelity reportedly paid him $10 million _ ``I won't argue with the
number,'' he says _ for his 100-acre family ranch, which will
become ground zero for the new Fidelity campus. But he says he
excused himself from all the council's deliberations and says it is
not about the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart of hearts I would have preferred not to sell,''
Bradley said Monday on his cellular phone as he bounced along a
country road in his pickup with a load of Longhorns in tow. He said
he sold only because he became convinced that the Fidelity deal
offered the town the best way out of its war with Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he does not believe any company, Fidelity included,
decides to move based on tax cuts. But he added: ``They are smart
enough to play the game to get as many tax benefits as they can.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Speaking of Fidelity, the fund company won't have to rely on
former Magellan manager Peter Lynch to provide the humor in its
upcoming broadcast ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Comedian Lily Tomlin has been signed to join Lynch in the
campaign that will air later this year, a company spokesman
confirmed. Fidelity is also believed to be in discussions to add
comedian Don Rickles later in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity is expected to debut the ads at a New York press event
within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
