<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-GRAHAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CARDINAL IS BACK AT HOME WITH THE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PETE DOUGHERTY  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In a seven-year NFL career, Kent Graham has
become Fassel-ized.
</P>
<P>
   Graham is on his second tour with the New York Giants, again as
a backup quarterback, but the familiarity is more with Jim Fassel,
his offensive coordinator in 1992 and 1996 and his head coach this
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants signed Graham as a free agent from the Arizona
Cardinals, where he spent two years as a sometimes-starter in an
offensive system Fassel employed there in 1996 prior to getting his
first NFL head-coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of success underneath him,'' Graham said.
``I've been with him a lot. In Arizona, I had a lot of success when
he was there. This offense was the same thing we were running
there.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no quarterback competition at this Giants camp. Danny
Kanell won the job from Dave Brown during last season and will take
the first snap Sept. 6 when the regular season opens.
</P>
<P>
   Barring injury, of course.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Giants and a lot of other NFL teams have gone
after experienced backups. The injury rate on quarterbacks seems to
increase each year, putting more value on having a competent
backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's going to happen during the year,''
Graham said. ``It's a long season. Obviously I'm not content being
a backup. I want to be a starter. Everybody does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the reality is Danny is starting. So I've got to
deal with that. If I am given the opportunity to get in there to
play, I feel, in this system, I have a really good chance of being
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   So far in the exhibition season, the results have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, slowed by a groin injury, struggled in the opener
against Cincinnati, completing 2 of 4 passes for 20 yards. He was
the Giants' most statistically productive offensive player in
Friday night's 24-10 loss at Jacksonville (8 of 11, 104 yards), but
the numbers are somewhat deceiving. He got 73 yards on a 10-yard
pass to Amani Toomer, who was not whistled as being down by contact
and rambled the remaining 63 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting there,'' Fassel said of Graham. ``He's getting
the rhythm back. He's a strong guy, he's got a powerful guy, and
the tendency with a lot of those guys is they wait until the guy's
open and wait until they see him and they power the ball in there.
He needs to be fluid, throw early, anticipate it, and he's starting
to get that feeling back.''
</P>
<P>
   An eighth-round draft pick of the Giants in 1992, Graham spent
his first three pro seasons in New York, backing up Phil Simms the
first two years and Brown the third. He was released by the Giants
after preseason in 1995 and hooked on with Detroit, but he never
threw a pass for the Lions. He signed with the Cardinals as a free
agent prior to the '96 season.
</P>
<P>
   When Graham played with them previously, the Giants were
rebuilding, going 6-10 under Ray Handley, then 11-5 and 9-7 under
Dan Reeves. Graham was on the other coast last year when the Giants
won their first NFC East title since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot different,'' Graham said of the new Giants.
``The attitude's different, the coaching staff is extremely
different. Players-wise, a lot of the defensive guys are still
here. Offensively we have a lot of changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen people who played in 1994, Graham's last season in New
York, are still with the Giants, although only tight end Howard
Cross, guard Greg Bishop and wide receiver Chris Calloway are
offensive players. ``I felt like I was back home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham also believes he's a better player than he was when he
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a lot more experience now,'' he said. ``I've been a
starter in the league. I feel comfortable in this offense, should
they need a different quarterback. Obviously I've got to go out and
prove that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
