<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAY-CENTENNIAL23-COX     08-18 2094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-CENTENNIAL23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    100 YEARS OF THE DAYTON DAILY NEWS, THE FIRST COX NEWSPAPER
 &HT;    (From the Daily News's special Centennial Section; embargoed
until Aug. 23. FOR MORE INFO, CALL PAT THOMAS (937) 225-2441.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Dale Dempsey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It's late. The presses are running. In the
newsroom, you can't hear them but you can feel them, a steady,
throbbing drone through the floor, off the walls. The whole
six-floor building pulses as thousands of newspapers fly from the
end of the massive, two-story press, each an identical copy _ until
changes are made. There are always changes.
</P>
<P>
   A press is the heart of a newspaper, the beating center fed by
cells of words and pictures, metal and paper, connected to the
extremities of the world by clanking arteries of folders, stackers,
bundlers, chutes and loading docks.
</P>
<P>
   Ink doesn't really get in your blood, but it fills the senses.
Gov. James Cox, founder of the Dayton Daily News , knew it.
Three-time governor of Ohio, would-be president, confidant of the
wealthy and the accomplished, he wrote in his autobiography that if
reincarnated and given the choice he would ask for the aroma of
printers' ink.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his life amid that aroma as well. After losing the
1920 presidential election, he returned to Dayton to guide a
growing business empire from an office not 200 feet from an inky,
black-stained, rumbling press.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News , the Miami Valley's recorder of news and
history, repository of found jobs and lost cats, resting place of
obituaries, reflector of opinions, sometimes wrapper of fish, turns
100 years old this year.
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back to the beginning, switching on an imaginary
reverse button on the big press. Slowly, 36,500 editions (not
counting remakes and extras) begin to fly off coffee tables, out of
newsstands and street boxes, unfolded and flattened into a backward
spinning press that has become a time machine. Billions of words
spill back into computers and typewriters and notebooks; 1.3
million tons of newsprint are returned to neat, unmarked rolls; 2.4
million pounds of black ink siphon back into barrels.
</P>
<P>
   There go the '90s. A Pulitzer Prize for stories on military
medicine. It's gone in a second as the press picks up speed. The
Dayton Peace Accords. The war in Bosnia. Deaths. Murders. The Gulf
War. A World Series victory for the Cincinnati Reds all disappear
in a blur of paper.
</P>
<P>
   The '80s flash by. The Berlin Wall is crumbling and the map of
the Soviet Union is redrawn. AT&AMP;T hangs its shingle on the NCR
world headquarters. The Challenger shuttle hangs in space for a
single, dreadful second. Hostages return from Iran. It all flashes
by as the press rolls on.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s come and go (disco mercifully so). A tornado, wide as
an interstate highway, hovers outside of Xenia. Fireworks light a
Bicentennial. The Reds and the Red Sox play a World Series for the
ages, masterfully recounted by columnists Si Burick for the News
and Ritter Collett for The Journal Herald. The Journal Herald,
created by Cox in 1949 but an editorial competitor of the News,
comes and goes, too.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s, the war-filled '40s, Depression '30s, Roaring '20s.
The Flood. A flight. The second war to end all wars and the first.
Inventors. Builders. The newspapers rush by, color fading into
black and white, headlines growing larger then smaller, fashions
changing, sports scores blaring briefly then fading into memory,
comics, columns, cooking, crime, catastrophes, congressional
elections, county controversies, city meetings, Christmas lights,
cars, concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, as the press comes to a stop, you're back in 1898 and
a young James M. Cox, with modest experience as a schoolteacher, a
journalist for the Cincinnati Enquirer , and an aide to Middletown
Congressman Paul Sorg, is putting down $26,000 to buy two
newspapers in Dayton, Ohio: the Dayton Evening News and the Dayton
Morning Times .
</P>
<P>
   To tell the truth, neither was much of a buy. The papers
routinely published ``boilerplate,'' a newspaper term for canned,
prewritten features already set in metal, with headlines like
``Aluminum Foil; Industry's Solution To Having Leftovers Lying
Around Loose in Your Freezer.'' They were timeless and cheap, but
provided little more than filling space around the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Before Cox, no one had stepped forward to meet the asking price
of the owner, Charles H. Simms. The papers had meager staffs,
rickety equipment and shaky finances.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook was not good, but Cox set out to remedy the problems
of both news and circulation.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped the Morning Times to concentrate on the News ,
changing Evening in the masthead to Daily .
</P>
<P>
   The name change was significant. Even though the new century had
yet to begin, the Wright brothers had yet to fly, Cox must have
sensed the dynamic, changing place the Miami Valley would become
and with it a demand for up-to-the-minute news. Tossing the
boilerplate, he sent reporters out into the streets to report on
crime, government, business and society. And he ordered the latest
wire services to bring news of the growing nation and the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Daily News debuted Aug. 22, 1898. The front page
carried no mention of the paper's new owner, who nonetheless was
energetically starting to make changes.
</P>
<P>
   By 1900, The Dayton Daily News had become the leading paper in
Dayton and, with bundles tossed onto the interurban railway cars of
the day, was reaching out to Springfield, Piqua, Xenia and
Greenville. Cox was able to buy out his original co-investors in
1900.
</P>
<P>
   By 1903, the paper was a business success, with the rival Dayton
Press going out of business. Cox bought the Press' equipment _
better reproduction, faster delivery _ and bought the Springfield
Press-Republic, which he renamed the Springfield Daily News.
</P>
<P>
   It was the start of a media empire that would grow to include
newspapers, radio and television stations, cable companies and
automobile auctions.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the 20th century, being a newspaper
publisher brought with it considerable political power and Cox used
it to run for office. He was elected to Congress in 1908 and was
voted Ohio's governor in 1912 and 1914. After losing the 1916
gubernatorial election, he won the seat again in 1918, becoming
Ohio's first three-time governor. He oversaw progressive
legislation in law, school, tax and prison reforms.
</P>
<P>
   In 1920, Cox won the Democratic nomination for president of the
United States. Franklin Delano Roosevelt was his vice presidential
running mate. After losing his presidential bid (to fellow Ohio
publisher Warren G. Harding of Marion) Cox turned his attention to
building his businesses, but politics were never far away. Former
news editor Carl Beyer recalled a story told by switchboard
operator Eleanor Hopkins:
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor would pick up the telephone and say, 'Get me
Frank!' and Eleanor would dial the White House so Gov. Cox could
call President Roosevelt. Once she heard FDR come on and say,
'Well, hello, Jim, what can I do for you today?' ``
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office and library still stand _ largely
unchanged from the day of his death on July 15, 1957 _ on the third
floor of the neoclassical building at Fourth and Ludlow streets in
downtown Dayton, where the newspaper's business, editorial and
advertising offices are located. Cox commissioned it in 1908 with
the instructions to architect Albert Pretzinger to construct a
stately structure that looked like a post office, or better yet, a
bank. That year Cox had been flatly rejected for a loan by
Valentine Winters, one of Dayton's most prominent bankers.
</P>
<P>
   Snubbed, Cox replied that he had such faith in the future of the
business that he wouldn't trade it for Winters' bank. The
four-story building, with its tall Greek columns, was completed in
1910, and survived the 1913 flood. (The newspaper also continued to
publish through the ``Time of Terror'' that was the Great Flood,
first printing free handbills from the NCR plant on higher ground,
then setting up a temporary press.)
</P>
<P>
   The hum of the press will soon be gone from the back of the
building, relocated to the new $90 million printing facility being
built on Interstate 75 at Ohio 73 in Franklin. The main offices and
majority of employees will remain downtown, with computer terminals
connected by fiber optic cable to the new plant. The newsroom may
no longer rumble with the start of the presses, but a new era is
beginning, filled with new products and new ways to deliver
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to produce a different kind of product for a
different kind of society,'' said Brad Tillson, Gov. Cox's current
successor as publisher of the Dayton Daily News and chief executive
of Cox Ohio Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Those newly reinvented newspapers, and Internet services like
www.activedayton.com and NewsLine reports, are sure to reach back
into the region's history on occasion. Newspapers, sometimes called
a ``first draft of history,'' are deeply entwined in the
communities they serve, and the newspaper offices, from the
archives to the more recent electronic library are filled with
nearly every story published in the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relationship between a community and its newspaper is a
complex, symbiotic one. Newspapers cannot survive without
supportive communities of readers and advertisers. Likewise, good
newspapers contribute to the quality of their communities,''
Tillson wrote in an introduction to a book, ``Dayton Ink ,'' on the
paper's centennial.
</P>
<P>
   Headlines have described every war from the Spanish-American War
to Desert Storm. Politics, of course, got intensive scrutiny, then
as now. Photographs increasingly emerged from the early years to
the present as a way to bring the story to the people. In April
1913, the News ran a panoramic photo across the entire front page
showing the ruins from the flood and ensuing fire that devastated
downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Stories on internationally known Dayton poet Paul Laurence
Dunbar, the Wright brothers and industrialists John Patterson, Col.
Edward Deeds and Charles F. Kettering appeared frequently, although
to Gov. Cox's dismay, as noted in his autobiography, the first
flights of the Wrights at Huffman Prairie did not initially receive
the attention they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   Cox's dictum to bring the nation and the world to his readers
was carried to sports. Sports Editor Si Burick used to joke that
he'd worked at the News for more than 50 years without receiving a
promotion. That was because Cox made him the sports editor in 1925,
when Burick was just 19 years old. From then until his death in
1986 at the age of 77, Burick's byline became known all over the
world, in a class with such famous sports columnists as Red Smith,
Joe Falls and Shirley Povich. Burick traveled the nation and the
world covering major events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Si put Dayton on the map,'' wrote Tom Callahan, a former
sports columnist for the Cincinnati Enquirer.
</P>
<P>
   Part of a newspaper's service to a community is its watchdog
role, and the Dayton Daily News has always taken it very seriously,
from Cox's early battles with NCR founder John H. Patterson to the
Pulitzer Prize-winning series on military doctors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, David Easterly became the paper's first environmental
reporter. One of his stories documented oils that were running out
of Miami Valley machine shops through storm sewers into the Great
Miami River. Then Easterly found out that Dayton Newspapers was
doing its own polluting. The paper ran the story and corrected the
problem. Easterly, of course, is no longer the environmental
reporter. He is now president of Cox Enterprises and the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution and is based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Easterly is just one of many editors and executives to pass
through Dayton on their way to the top of the Cox organization.
Chuck Glover, Robert Musselman, Roger Kintzel, Booker Izell, Randy
Preddy, David Scott, Charles Reinhart, Tom Teepen, Bob Sherman,
Gregory Favre, Ed O'Neill, Dan Mahoney, Joe Englert, Brian Cooper,
Jay Smith, Arnold Rosenfeld, Jim Fain all went on to bigger things
with the company.
</P>
<P>
   Their stops at the News were not brief layovers; all spent a
considerable number of years here. While Burick's 60-year career
may stand out, there are many Dayton Daily News employees in all
departments who have shown considerable loyalty to the paper,
racking up careers of 30, 40 and 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   And many are looking forward to the next century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
