<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-TUPA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUPA GETS A KICK OUT OF A DUAL ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Whether he's playing pool with Drew Bledsoe or
Ping-Pong with Scott Zolak, or taking part in a putting contest
with other teammates, Tom Tupa always wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great athlete,'' marveled Patriots coach Pete Carroll.
``His movements are so smooth. He's such a cool customer out there.
We're so fortunate to have a guy like that who can punt and protect
us at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   There were days during training camp when Tupa looked like the
best quarterback on the field. His spirals were tight, his motion
mechanically sound. He threw the long ball with grace and the
sideline pattern with zip. He holds on field goals for Adam
Vinatieri, and has it down to an art. And to watch him punt?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' said Carroll. ``He's such a weapon for us
because he can kick them so long and so high. He's very good at
pinning the other team inside the 20. He's one of the best in the
game. To have someone of his athletic ability, that other teams
have to keep their eye on, I mean, he can complete a pass and that
threat is there, and it has to be on their mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Punting is the reason Tupa is a Patriot, but the other part of
the equation is his quarterbacking. Bill Parcells recognized long
ago that to have a punter who can protect you at quarterback meant
saving a roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa hasn't had much opportunity to show his signal-calling
skills, though. Two years ago, the team ran a fake punt against
Denver, but Tupa's pass to Tedy Bruschi, which would have resulted
in a first down, was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   If Bledsoe and Zolak went down, how would the Patriots fare with
Tupa at the helm?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about a long-term thing, but I think in the short
term I could get in there and run the offense and do the best I
could,'' Tupa said. ``I prepare as a quarterback. I learn the
playbook, I go through the reps in practice. I think I can still
throw the ball and I've had a lot of rest. It's been a while since
I've been in a regular-season game.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-4-inch, 225-pounder has thrown three passes in the
NFL since 1994. His last significant time at quarterback was in
1992 with the Colts, when he completed 17 of 33 passes for 156
yards. With the Arizona Cardinals in 1991, he started 11 games
after starter Timm Rosenbach was hurt. Tupa led the Cardinals to a
4-7 record, completing 52.4 percent of his passes on a bad team. He
had his best day against the Patriots, throwing for three
touchdowns and 312 yards in a 24-10 win.
</P>
<P>
   His professional punting career began in 1989 with the
Cardinals, when he filled in for the injured Rich Camarillo the
last two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   By 1993, the Cleveland native had signed with Bill Belichick's
Browns. Following the 1995 season, after Belichick was fired by
Cleveland and came to the Patriots, Belichick recommended him to
Parcells, who signed Tupa to a three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   This past offseason, there was talk by Patriots management of
relieving Tupa of his quarterback duties so he could devote more
time to punting. But that hasn't come to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never said anything about that, so that was never my
request,'' said Tupa. ``I've never thought the quarterbacking hurt
my punting. For the last three years I've been as good as anyone in
the league. I've always felt it was a valuable thing. I don't think
there have been too many punter/quarterbacks in the league over the
years, so it's unique and that helps the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The last quarterback/punter of great note was Dallas's Danny
White, who did both jobs for many years. The 32-year-old Tupa, in
his 10th year, believes he can do both for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never think you can do something forever, but you look at
Steve DeBerg out there at 44 years old and you hope you're that
lucky,'' he said. ``Zo and I have a good time in practice because
we make a game out of it to see who can complete the most passes.
It makes practices go a little faster for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa is quite comfortable with new coordinator Ernie Zampese's
offense, because he operated in similar ones during the year he
started for Phoenix and also in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``People shouldn't panic that Drew isn't going to get the
offense,'' said Tupa. ``It's just new and different and the timing
with the receivers really does take a few games to get going. I
think by the end of the preseason he'll be fine, and this offense
will click pretty well. You can already see the improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his punting, Tupa said, ``It's going pretty good. I'm
ahead of where I was last year at this time. I'm still trying to
refine myself. Once we get close to the start of the season, I'll
work more on my punting and less on the QB stuff. Right now, I do a
lot of quarterback reps, but before practice Dante Scarnecchia
watches me. He knows my punting stuff real well now, and if I hit a
bad ball he knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Tupa is working on the hang time and direction of his punts.
He's had excellent hang time so far and in two exhibition games
he's already hit three punts more than 60 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he averaged 45.8 yards per punt, a Patriots record. He
led the AFC in average and finished one-10th of a yard behind New
Orleans's Mark Royals for tops in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I just do what I'm capable of doing, I can just keep going
on,'' he said. ``I don't think I need to hit the ball any harder,
but I have to keep refining what I have. I think there's a lot more
bigger-type punters in the league now. Guys year in and year out
who have been in the upper echelon are usually 6-3, 6-4, and some
weigh as much as 240 pounds. The averages are going up. When I
first started there were a couple of guys averaging 45 and 46; now
it seems there are a lot of them around.''
</P>
<P>
   Does quarterbacking help punting?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really know because this is all I've ever known,''
said Tupa. ``I've always had to prepare to be a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly helps him in team competitions. A great athlete at
Ohio State, Tupa not only holds the school's career punting record
(44.7 yards per kick), but he also played on the championship
intramural basketball team, along with Keith Byars, Cris Carter,
Pepper Johnson, William White, and Jamie Holland.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day after practice, several players took part in
a putting contest on a green located just beyond the practice
field.
</P>
<P>
   Tupa sank a 3-footer to win the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't surprise anyone,'' said Carroll. ``He wins
everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
