<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-SINGH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SINGH, PRACTICE MADE PERFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ There was no rainbow in the sky Sunday, as
there was when Davis Love won the PGA Championship a year ago at
Winged Foot. There was a storm brewing that soon would drench
Salahee CC, just an hour after Vijay Singh walked up the 18th
fairway with his first major victory all but assured. Storm clouds
have hovered over Singh before.
</P>
<P>
   He was suspended for altering a scorecard in the 1985 Indonesian
Open when he was a young player on the Asian Tour, and accused of
leaving unpaid bills behind when he was on the Australian Tour. But
he has compiled a global record of considerable accomplishment, one
that reached its zenith Sunday across the lake from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   If there were questions about his putting, he answered them by
switching to a cross-handed style in the Western Open two months
ago. It was his putting in Sunday's final round that lifted him to
a 9-under total of 68_271 and a two-shot victory over Steve
Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning a major is something special,'' said Singh, ``because
you only have four chances in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh spoke Sunday night of the influence of Scottish caddie
David Renwick, who carried for Jose Maria Olazabal when he won the
Masters in 1994 and for Steve Elkington when he won the PGA
Championship in 1995 at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept talking to me,'' said Singh. ``We were talking about a
lot of things other than just golf. I told him, `Let's just talk
today, have a conversation, and keep our mind occupied and not just
think about what we're doing on the golf course.' We talked about
horse racing. We talked about a lot of things when we were walking,
and that kept me very calm all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh has won five times on the US PGA Tour, including twice a
year ago, at the rain-shortened Memorial and the Buick Open. He has
won 18 times internationally, including the Malaysian PGA
Championship on the Asian Tour in 1984, before the scorecard
incident. He has won the Nigerian Open, the Swedish PGA
Championship, the Ivory Coast Open, the King Hassan Trophy in
Morocco, the South African Open, and the Zimbabwe Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to Africa, all parts of Asia, India,'' he said. ``I
can't really pick one out. There's been a lot of crazy places I've
been. I think in Africa playing on sand greens in Nigeria, where I
won twice, was a great experience. That's all past and it's all a
learning process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be here. I just hope they had a live feed on this
in Fiji. It's not too many times a golfer in Fiji can win a major
event.''
</P>
<P>
   Fiji, his homeland, is made up of more than 100 islands, and it
is not a rich country. The majority of the population is of Indian
descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest sport in Fiji is not golf,'' Singh said. ``It's
rugby. Everybody plays rugby there. Golf is just a part-time thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that everybody in Fiji has seen this and I hope
I'm a hero in Fiji. I haven't been back for a long time, but when I
go back I'll find out the answer to that question.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker, whose wife and former caddie, Nicki, is expecting
their first child this month, more or less bowed out of contention
in the PGA when he failed to get up and down out of a trap on the
17th. Thoughts of his wife were an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's part of the reason why I played so well this
week,'' he said. ``Just because of this great thing that's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the last of the major championships in 1998, and they
will be remembered for Mark O'Meara's dominance. He won the Masters
and British Open to become the oldest player, at 41, to win two
majors in a year. O'Meara made a run at Hogan's standard of three
in one year, but bogeys at the sixth, seventh, and eighth Sunday
ended the dream. ``They took the wind out of my sails,'' said
O'Meara, who nevertheless finished a respectable joint fourth, five
back of Singh.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time a major was held in the Pacific
Northwest since Hogan won the 1946 PGA Championship at Portland
(Ore.) GC. The crowds were enthusiastic, knowledgeable, and in
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great course,'' said Love, who stayed in contention and
finished tied for seventh at 70_277.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf course was set up perfectly,'' said Tiger Woods, who
ended up 71_279. ``The fairways were lush, the greens were perfect,
and the course could have been had if you hit the ball in the right
spots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
