<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE HOUSE BATTLES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No 3-year-old worked harder last year than Free House. The big
gray ran 10 times and finished in the money in all three Triple
Crown events. In the course of compiling a 10-3-2-3 record, the
California-bred son of the modest sire Smokester, who once stood
for a stud fee of $1,500, earned more than $1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Free House's battles with Silver Charm, who won the Kentucky
Derby and Preakness and was named 3-year-old champion, were
legendary. Leading up to the Triple Crown, Free House beat the more
agile Silver Charm in both the San Felipe and the Santa Anita
Derby, after losing to him in the San Vicente. But Silver Charm was
too good in the chase for the Famed Triad, as Free House finished
third in the Derby and second in the Preakness. When Touch Gold
ended Silver Charm's bid for the Triple Crown by catching him near
the wire in the Belmont Stakes, Free House was a close third.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm went on the shelf after the Belmont, but Free House
did not. He won the Swaps in July, ran third in the Haskell in
August, and then his season finally ended when he bled badly while
finishing sixth and last in the Super Derby Sept. 28.
</P>
<P>
   This year, owners Trudy McCaffery and John Toffan, who bred Free
House, and trainer Paco Gonzales kept him idle until the Bel Air
Handicap at Hollywood Park July 11. Free House won his 4-year-old
debut by 7 lengths, but his urine test came back positive for
clembuterol, which is prohibited for racing use.
</P>
<P>
   Clembuterol is a bronchodilator used to treat respiratory
infections. The Federal Drug Administration legalized the drug May
11. In Canada, where the drug has long been legal, the accepted
withdrawal time from a horse's system is 72 hours. However, more
sensitive testing done in the United Sates _ tests designed to
assure that Lasix, an anti-bleeding medication legal for race use,
does not mask clembuterol _ can detect the drug in a horse's system
for up to 13 days.
</P>
<P>
   Some trainers in the United States were confused on the
withdrawal time of the drug, which can be used for training, and
positives began to show up, most notably in Kentucky and
California. On July 30, the California Horse Racing Board announced
that 20 horses had tested positive for clembuterol between May 16
and July 11. Free House was one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Free House camp has vehemently denied that the horse has
ever been on clembuterol, even if innocently applied. ``I do not
use clembuterol,'' Gonzalez said, flatly. A second test of the
sample has since been ordered. McCaffery was especially upset by
the finding and, while unable to explain the results, said she felt
``helpless,'' believing the results to be inaccurate but having no
way to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of those bad feelings were alleviated on Sunday, however,
as Free House dominated a top field to capture the $1 million
Pacific Classic at Del Mar. Off at 7-2 ($9.20 to win), Free House
ran right past defending champion Gentlemen, the 6-5 choice as
coupled in an entry with Puerto Madero (who finished sixth), to
score by 4 lengths under Chris McCarron in the time of 2:00 1/5 for
the 1 1/4 miles. Also left in Free House's wake was 3-2 second
choice Touch Gold, who finished fifth. Always a big boy, Free House
is reported to be even bigger this year, and he may have grown into
an absolute monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time off helped him a lot,'' said Gonzalez. ``He's a
bigger, stronger horse. He's more mature and relaxed. He trained
better for this than he did for the Bel Air. He came out of that
race in great shape. I knew he was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I cam up alongside Gentlemen turning for home, I knew I
had more horse,'' said McCarron. ``My concern was with Touch Gold,
that's why I looked back. I wanted to see if he was coming at me or
backing up. He was going the right way for us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A quick `Skip'
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away zipped 6 furlongs in 1:10 during a public workout
between the fourth and fifth races at Saratoga Monday. To put the
move in perspective, the fastest 6 furlongs during a race at The
Spa this meeting has been 1:09 3/5, run by Kelly Kip in the A
Phenomenon Stakes. Kelly Kip is the 6-furlong track record-holder
at both Belmont Park and Aqueduct.
</P>
<P>
   Handled by regular rider Jerry Bailey, Skip Away went fractions
of :23 1/5, :46 3/5, and :58 1/5 on the way to his 6-furlong
clocking. He then galloped out 7 furlongs in 1:23 3/5 and was
pulled up after going a mile in 1:43 1/5. Skip Away's efforts were
greeted with applause from the crowd of 52,245, drawn, in part, by
a Skip Away poster giveaway.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they say he doesn't like Saratoga,'' said trainer Sonny
Hine. ``The workout was good. I would have liked to see him go in
1:11, but he always goes quicker than I want him to. It seemed like
he was confused when he heard the crowd and there were no other
horses around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away, the handicap champion who is 5 for 5 this season, is
training for the $500,000 Iselin Handicap at Monmouth Aug. 30. His
schedule then calls for him to run in the $500,000 Woodward Stakes
Sept. 19 and the $750,000 Jockey Club Gold Cup Oct. 19, both at
Belmont, before finishing his career in the $4 million Breeders'
Cup Classic at Churchill Downs Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meet the new boss
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Former New York Times racing columnist and New York Racing
Association executive Steven Crist took over the Daily Racing Form
as of last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Crist, who will be both editor and publisher, heads the Alpine
Capital Group, a New York banking investment firm, which purchased
The Daily Racing Form from Primedia for a reported $40 million.
Crist was also editor-in-chief of the short-lived Racing Times, a
paper that originated greatly improved past performance
information. The Daily Racing Form incorporated much of what Crist
developed when it eventually took over the Racing Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daily Racing Form is a very profitable company and has
never lost money,'' said Crist at a press conference at Saratoga.
``It is not an issue of survival. We think this paper has the
potential for a big turnaround. The current management was
hamstrung by the previous owners. We think we can make the product
better and, if so, more people will buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was
used to prepare this report.)
</P>
