<HEADER>
A9296 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MINORS-ADVISORY     08-18 1361
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-ADVISORY </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   MINOR-LEAGUE BASEBALL SERIES
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: SPORTS EDITORS, ESPECIALLY FLA., VA., ORE., GA., S.C.
</P>
<P>
   The journey to the major leagues is a long and difficult one
that few ballplayers survive. The rugged climb up the minor-league
ladder claims most prospects long before they reach the big leagues
_ less than 10 percent of players who sign pro contracts make it to
the majors, even for one day.
</P>
<P>
   To chronicle one team's organization, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution staff writers Guy Curtright and Jack
Wilkinson, with AJC photographer Ben Gray, took a road trip through
the eight-team Atlanta farm system. The Journal-Constitution has
produced an eight-part series, a comprehensive look at one baseball
club's minor-league organization from top to bottom, from the dusty
barrios of the Dominican Republic to AAA ball in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The series looks at teams in these cities and leagues:
</P>
<P>
   _ San Pedro de Macoris, Dominican Republic, Dominican Summer
League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Orlando, Gulf Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danville, Va., Appalachian League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eugene, Ore., Northwest League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Macon, Ga., South Atlantic League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Danville, Va. (moving to Myrtle Beach, S.C., next season),
Carolina League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Greenville, S.C., Southern League.
</P>
<P>
   _ Richmond, Va., International League.
</P>
<P>
   Following is a budget. The first three days' installments are
moving now; the rest will move daily through the end of this week.
For more information, please call Cox News Service at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Day 1:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DOMINICAN _ SAN PEDRO DE MACORIS, Dominican Republic _ In
the Dominican there is only one way to avoid a life of hard work
and poverty: baseball. Young boys grow up playing with milk cartons
for gloves and dreaming about being the next Sammy Sosa or Pedro
Martinez. The most promising youngsters are signed at 16 or 17 and
start working their way up beginning in the Dominican Summer
League. All 30 major league clubs have teams in the league. While
in camp, they are fed and housed in barracks. Bonuses and salaries
are very small, but much more than their fathers will ever earn.
Competition is fierce. Only two or three Braves players a year win
a spot for the next season in the U.S. Those that fail in the
minors are sent home in disgrace, a life of poverty almost assured.
(Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DOMINICAN-FACTS _ Facts about the league.
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-TALENT _ The search for baseball talent has gone
international. The Braves have one of the most lavish scouting web
in all of baseball and have players from more than 15 countries in
their minor-league system. But less than 10 per cent of all players
signed make the majors. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-SYSTEM _ A look at the Braves minor-league ladder.
(Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 2:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-GULFCOAST _ ORLANDO, Fla. _ Team is based at the Braves'
spring camp at Disney World, but don't be fooled. There is nothing
magical about this first stop in the minor leagues for most Braves
prospects. Games begin at noon under the blazing Florida sun. No
admission is charged, but a game is lucky to draw 10 fans. There is
that many countries represented on the Braves' 30-man roster.
English classes are held two nights a week. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 35''
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-GULFCOAST-FACTS _ Fact box on team. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 3:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DANVILLE _ DANVILLE, Va. _ Away from home for the first
time and making $900 a month, young players scrabble to find a
place to live in the Appalachian League. Most stay four to five in
apartments in an attempt to hold down costs. Life can be lonely and
the road trips through the mountains often harrowing. The highlight
of the summer is usually a visit from parents or your girlfriend.
(Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DANVILLE-FACTS _ Danville Braves fact box. (Curtright,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 4:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-EUGENE _ EUGENE, Ore. _ This is as close as most Braves
minor-league signees will get to a big-time atmosphere. Eugene
regularly fills its 6,000-seat stadium from late June through
August. All games are on radio, and TV highlights dominate the
evening news. For the 14th consecutive season, Eugene's season
attendance has been greater than its population. Most players are
in their second season or just out of college. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) NO PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-EUGENE-FACTS _ Eugene fact box. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 5:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-MACON _ MACON, Ga. _ Marcus Giles was taken by Atlanta in
the 53rd round of the 1996 draft and his chances of making a career
in baseball like older brother Brian (Cleveland Indians) appeared
almost nonexistent. But Giles is determinted to prove everyone
wrong. Although less than 5-foot-8, he is threatening the South
Atlantic League in homers and is beginning to improve his play at
second base by constant work with Macon coach Glenn Hubbard.
(Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-MACON-TOPPICK _ Not all No. 1 picks pan out. While
low-round pick Marcus Giles stars at Macon, No. 1's Troy Cameron
and Jacob Shumate struggle. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-MACON-FACTS _ Macon fact box. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 6:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DANVILLE-MANAGER _ DANVILLE, Va. _ Paul Runge played
briefly in the majors with the Braves, but never made a name for
himself. Now he is trying to get back to the majors as a manager.
But managing in the minors isn't easy. You are paid to develop
players, not win games. But if you lose too much, you never
advance. In the Carolina League this season, Darrell Evans was
fired by the Royals with his team in first place because he was
eschewing player development to win games. (Wilkinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DANVILLE-MYRTLE _ The Braves' Carolina League team will
move to Myrtle Beach, S.C. next season. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-STANDINGS _ Braves farm system records. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-DANVILLE-FACTS _ Danville fact box. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 7:
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-GREENVILLE _ GREENVILLE, S.C. _ George Lombard was happy
when Aug. 1 arrived. After weeks of hearing he might be traded by
the Braves for needed bullpen help, Lombard knows he still has a
chance to reach the majors in his hometown. After turning down a
football scholarship at Georgia to sign with Atlanta, the private
school graduate struggled for his first four seasons. But now he is
showing the talent that the Braves always thought he would.
(Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-GREENVILLE-CHAPEL _ Baseball Chapel offers spiritual
support to players struggling in the minors. In Greenville, the
weekly services are led by former major leaguers Marty Clary and
Jose Alvarez. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-GREENVILLE-FACTS _ Greenville fact box. (Curtright,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Day 8
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-RICHMOND _ RICHMOND, Va. _ Richmond is one step from the
majors, but yet unreachable for most of the veterans like Gene
Schall who hang on at AAA for one more chance. Many players are in
their 30s and have families. Yet they make as little as $10,000 a
season and work at whatever job they can find in the winter. Schall
is married and his baby had health problems at birth, forcing him
to stay away from the team. (Wilkinson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-RICHMOND-CHEN _ When the Braves talk trade, Bruce Chen is
always a name that comes up. But the Braves don't want to lose
their top prospect. Chen was recently promoted to Richmond from
Greenville, where he led the league in strikeouts. His story is an
interesting one. He is an Asian who was born and raised in Panama,
and has studied math in the off-season at Georgia Tech. He is
scheduled to begin classes Sept. 23. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINORS-RICHMOND-FACTS _ Richmond fact box. (Curtright, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
