<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DATA-GENERAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DATA GENERAL GROOMS CLARIION UNIT TO RIVAL EMC, OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just as it appeared Data General Corp. was drifting back toward
oblivion, the onetime technology giant is again trumpeting its
turnaround, with a renewed emphasis on its Clariion computer
storage division.
</P>
<P>
   The Westborough, Mass. computer company is pumping resources
into the Clariion unit in a bid to compete more effectively with
storage industry giants such as EMC Corp. of Hopkinton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Data General has some catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   The company suffered a setback earlier this year because of
a &UR;  &LR; production delay in launching its next generation of computer
storage equipment. As a result, sales of the new systems, featuring
advanced so-called fiber channel technology, didn't grow fast
enough to offset the decline in storage systems that used an older
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost a year's worth of growth in the market,'' conceded
Joel Schwartz, appointed four months ago as senior vice president
and general manager of Clariion.
</P>
<P>
   Data General has lost money during the past two quarters, and is
expected to fall short of break-even again in the current quarter,
which ends in September, according to analysts polled by First Call
Inc. of Boston. On June 1, the company announced a restructuring
charge of $135 million for the quarter ended in June &UR;  &LR; and said it
would lay off 400 workers.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz contends that production problems have been resolved
and Data General is now shipping a complete line of fiber channel
products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Once a giant in the minicomputer industry, Data General missed
the shift to desktop computers. But the company revived itself in
1995 by moving to servers based on Intel Corp.'s Pentium
microprocessors. After two years of improved results, the company
fell behind competitors earlier this year because of the slowdown
in its storage business.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Schwartz says Data General has a technology edge over
companies like EMC that will enable Data General to make up ground
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   All computer storage manufacturers are moving toward fiber
channel technology because it allows users to transmit more data
over greater distances, an advantage for companies that must share
information over far-flung computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   But the storage systems sold by most manufacturers feature fiber
channel connections only on the ``front end'' _ between the server
and the storage equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Clariion systems are more advanced, Schwartz said, because they
also use fiber channel technology on the ``back end'' _ to connect
the network of disks inside the storage equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Data General also got a big boost earlier this year when
fast-growing Dell Computer Corp. selected Clariion as its provider
of fiber channel storage products, to be sold under Dell's
PowerVault brand name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We evaluated quite a few potential partners and decided that
Clariion's fiber channel technology was superior to anything else
on the market,'' said Dell spokesman Jim Mazzola.
</P>
<P>
   But while Data General expects the deal with Dell to help it win
significantly more business, it is also hiring its own sales force
that will call directly on corporate customers and sell
Clariion-brand equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, virtually all of Data General's $500 million in
storage system revenue came from computer makers that sold Clariion
machines under their own brand names.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to build up the Clariion brand name, said Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Data General also is investing more in software. In the
restructuring announced in June, the company transferred 100
employees to the Clariion division, most of whom work in research
and development.  &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clariion name is well-known in the industry, but not by
the end user,'' Schwartz said. With a direct sales force, more
advertising and more investment in software, he hopes to boost its
brand awareness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1336EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9298 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MINORS-DOMINICAN-     08-18 2559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-DOMINICAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINOR LEAGUE SERIES: The Dominican Republic is a logical
starting point
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN PEDRO DE MACORIS, Dominican Republic _ First pitch: 10:25
a.m. Game-time temperature: Sizzling. Today's attendance at Estadio
Tetelo Vargas: 56, including two unarmed soldiers in fatigues and
two National Police officers packing pistols.
</P>
<P>
   While the San Pedro de Macoris Braves play the Houston Astros'
Summer League affiliate on the field, the essence of Dominican
baseball skips along a concourse in the stands. Alejandro Michel,
11, is bouncing a baseball off a concrete wall and deftly fielding
it. The ball, its horsehide cover worn off, is just a core wrapped
with white string that's slowly unraveling. On his left hand,
Alejandro wears his glove, which symbolizes both this country's
widespread poverty and its absolute obsession with baseball.
</P>
<P>
   It's a milk carton. An old carton, crushed and folded just so.
The ridges for Alejandro's fingers are visible. Forget Rawlings or
Wilson. As for many Dominican youngsters, his glove is a one-liter
Parmalat model.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same mitt Rafael Belliard and Danny Bautista used as
kids in the Dominican, long before they became Atlanta Braves. ``We
all had them,'' Bautista says.
</P>
<P>
   So did Dario Paulino. ``When I was growing up, that was the kind
of glove I was using,'' said Paulino, 27, once an infielder who
reached Class AA Greenville in the Braves' farm system, for four
years now a coach back home with San Pedro. ``A milk carton. Every
little kid uses it. Only if your father is middle class can you
afford a glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro's father is not middle class. There's virtually no
Dominican middle class, not even here, 45 miles east of the capital
of Santo Domingo, in this mill town with a population of 120,000
and seven sugar mills. Both of Alejandro's parents work in a hotel.
So he flashes milk carton, not leather. He backhands a short hop
and hopes to one day join the line of major-league San Pedro
shortstops, who are nearly as plentiful as hand-rolled Dominican
cigars.
</P>
<P>
   ``A baseball player,'' Alejandro, a fifth-grader, says when
asked his life's ambition. ``Because I'd be given the opportunity
to get some money for my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like Sammy Sosa, who grew up dirt-poor a few blocks from
the downtown stadium and is now chasing home-run history, secure in
his $42.5 million free-agent contract. Sosa has built a spacious
house here for his mother, which backs up to Plaza 30/30, his
three-story office building. The 30/30 includes ``Sammy Club,'' a
subterranean disco; ``Hit Bar,'' a tavern; and a courtyard fountain
in which stands a life-sized statue of Sammy at the bat that looks
nothing like Sammy in the flesh.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is Alejandro's favorite player. ``Because he's from here,''
Alejandro said, ``and I like the way he plays.'' So Alejandro plays
as children here always have: nonstop, passionately, hoping to get
off the island and reach the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   For today's Dominican League game, two of the most interested
observers are in the grandstand behind home plate. Deric Ladnier
and Jose Martinez are wearing Atlanta Braves polo shirts and
clicking their stopwatches incessantly. In front of them sits a
Braves pitcher aiming a JUGS gun so Ladnier and Martinez can gauge
the velocity of the starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play,'' said Ladnier, the Braves' director of
minor-league operations. ``I mean they play. That's the difference
between the kids in the States and here. In the U.S., they have all
these other things: basketball, football, movies, all these
luxuries. They don't have that here. They have baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you come down here and you're looking for baseball
players and you see people playing on street corners and in fields,
you think, `What a great place to come. They play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable to come over to this country,'' said
Martinez, 57, a former major-league player from Cuba in his 39th
year of professional baseball. As the special assistant to the
general manager for player development, Martinez is John
Schuerholz's most valued Latin American liaison. ``Everywhere you
go, you see a guy playing baseball. I've never seen it like this
anywhere (else) in Latin America. Everywhere you go, baseball.
Being Spanish myself, that's the hope they've got for getting ahead
in life. I don't know if it's the right thing to say, but I don't
think they're interested in going to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the economy, the kids here have to go to work to help the
family. But this is their hope. Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why hope swings eternal at the fastball, on the parched
fields and barrio street corners, in the vacant lots, anywhere kids
stuff a pair of socks and hit it with a bat that's sometimes a
broom handle, sometimes a tree branch. That's why Alejandro Michel
catches a frayed-string baseball with a milk carton, in range of a
JUGS gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit the whole spectrum of baseball here,'' Ladnier said.
``Technology to ingenuity.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, 107 years after two Cubans brought the game to the
island, baseball talent here is as abundant as sugar cane. Despite
a population of just eight million and an area about the size of
West Virginia, the Dominican Republic had 89 major-leaguers in
1997, second only to California. Of the 1,200 players on 40-man
major-league rosters when spring training opened in February, 111
were Dominicans _ compared with 12 in 1968, when big-league scouts
were first scouring the island for talent.
</P>
<P>
   The galaxy of Dominican stars, past and present, is luminous.
The three Alou brothers. Juan Marichal. Ex-Braves Rico Carty,
Rafael Ramirez and Alejandro Pena. Pedro Guerrero. George Bell,
Joaquin Andujar and Julio Franco. Raul Mondesi and Montreal's
Guerrero brothers, Vladimir and Wilton. There were four Dominicans
in this year's All-Star Game: Sosa, Cleveland's Bartolo Colon and
Manny Ramirez, and Pedro Martinez, last year's NL Cy Young winner,
who signed a $75 million contract last winter with Boston, the
richest in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez and Sosa are idolized here, for their humility, their
play and their paychecks. ``Here in San Pedro, people see baseball
as (a means) to be rich soon,'' Paulino said. ``It's the only way
to work hard and be rich.'' And when players fail? ``It's very,
very hard. They look at this as the way to get out of the poor
life.''
</P>
<P>
   That path begins with the baseball academies, and teams, that
all 30 major-league teams operate in the Dominican. Atlanta has had
a team here since the summer league was formed in 1985, practicing
and playing in the old downtown stadium. Players can sign when
they're 16 and play three years _ both summer and winter ball _
from ages 17-19. Many are often referred by buscones, or
``finders,'' bird-dog scouts who usually receive from $250 to $500
if a team signs a player.
</P>
<P>
   Like labor here, baseball talent is cheap and plentiful.
Dominican players traditionally have signed for bonuses in the
$2,000-$3,000 range, but that is changing. In separate bidding wars
after both players were found to have signed early with other
teams, Toronto signed a Dominican shortstop named Josephang
Bernhardt for $1.1 million in January 1997. Earlier this year, the
Yankees signed pitcher Ricardo Aramboles to a $1.52 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it's all gone up,'' said Pedro Gonzalez, 58, the
ex-major-league infielder now in his 27th year in the Atlanta
organization, the last five in his hometown as GM and manager of
the San Pedro de Macoris Braves. ``But believe me, for $100,000 you
could sign 10 quality players for $10,000 each.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominicans are exempt from baseball's amateur draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other great thing about here is, you can sign 'em,''
Ladnier said. ``You don't have to wait for the draft.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 35 players, 30 of them active, on the Braves' summer
league roster, usually 30 to 32 for the winter league. It is
low-level rookie league ball, the lowest rung on Atlanta's
eight-team farm ladder.
</P>
<P>
   The summer league has a 72-game schedule, running June through
August. Teams play six mornings a week and take Sundays off.
There's a 70-game winter schedule from late October to early
February. Most players earn $850 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 23 players _ 21 from other parts of the country and
two Venezuelans _ live in the San Pedro Braves ``dorm,'' a spare,
three-story building in the heart of the city at 104 Avenida
General Cabral. Right next door at No. 102: Pedro Gonzalez's house.
Local players live at home.
</P>
<P>
   At the dorm, players arise at 7 each morning for breakfast. By
8:30, they're on the field at the stadium, taking batting practice,
then infield and outfield, working on fundamentals. Games begin at
10:30, followed by running and conditioning. The locker room is
bare-bones, with a few free weights and exercise machines and no
showers. Players shower back at the dorm, where two cooks prepare
three meals a day; local players may eat there, too. A typical
lunch: rice, ladled with beef and beans from a huge pot, a salad
and water.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoons, players take English classes twice a week and
an occasional social-skills class, lift weights or nap. ``They put
in a full day,'' Ladnier said.
</P>
<P>
   The goal is to improve sufficiently to warrant a promotion to
the U.S. and justify using one of Atlanta's 28 visas for the
organization. ``They're a precious commodity,'' Ladnier said of the
visas. ``You've got to pick the right one.''
</P>
<P>
   Major-league teams must re-apply annually for visas; this year's
range is 23-30 per club. Ladnier said only one or two of the
Braves' Dominican players each year are promising enough to get a
visa. No player has ever started with the Dominican Braves and
worked his way through the farm system to reach Atlanta. Odaliz
Perez, 20, a left-hander from Las Matas de Farfan who was signed at
16 and recently was promoted to Class AAA Richmond, is one of
Atlanta's top three prospects and the most successful Dominican
signee by the Braves to date. He did not play in the summer league.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even without a home-grown, north-to-Atlanta success story,
signing and nurturing players here is a necessity. ``You have to,''
Ladnier said. ``It still comes down to the same thing. If you sign
the best players, you've got the best chance.''
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of players. Such as Hector Francisco, a catcher from
Esperanza who plays because, he said, ``I love baseball and to help
my mother financially.'' But Francisco is now 19, in his third
season and far more likely to get released than to get a visa after
this year. If so, ``I'll keep practicing (baseball) and be a
mechanic,'' said Francisco, the only wage-earner in his family.
</P>
<P>
   Players such as Miguel Bernard, 17, a converted third baseman
and promising catcher who lives on Calle O in the Restauracion
barrio, about a 10-minute walk from the ballpark where he first
watched games at the age of 7. ``It's my job, and I like this,''
said Bernard, who says he earns $400 a month. ``Baseball's the game
of the country, a culture game.''
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Bernard sometimes broke wooden legs off tables to use
as a bat and hit bottle-cap balls. Calle O is an unpaved, dirt
road, but Bernard's house _ where he lives with his mother, Lydia,
and sister _ is neat, one of the nicest in the barrio and the only
two-story home. And if he doesn't succeed at baseball?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll return to the university and study architecture,''
Bernard said before walking around the corner to Calle K, where a
crowd has gathered to watch six barefoot boys play beisbol in the
street with a broken bat now sawed down the middle and a
stuffed-sock ball.
</P>
<P>
   And such players as Juan Santana, 18, a right-handed pitcher and
San Pedro's starter on the morning the Braves got to Boca Chica to
play Toronto's affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves drive 45 minutes along the coast highway in their
bus, an old Blue Bird Co. bus painted blue, without
air-conditioning or any working gauges. Turning off the highway,
the bus bumps slowly along a pot-holed dirt lane, passing goats,
chickens and dogs, past dilapidated shacks built from cinder blocks
or wood scraps. The dirt path then eases past cow pastures and
undergrowth before turning left to a gated entrance with a sign:
``Las Americas Baseball Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Opened in 1997, the $1.6 million complex was built by the
Arizona Diamondbacks and Toronto Blue Jays and houses both clubs'
Dominican-league players in a huge dormitory with two roof-top
satellite TV dishes. Each team has two playing fields at the
four-diamond complex. The crowd consists of scouts and players
sitting in a tower in the middle of the four fields.
</P>
<P>
   Under a blazing Caribbean sun, Santana starts strongly, working
two scoreless innings. At 6 feet 3, he now weighs 170 pounds, up
from 160 when he signed at 16. Thanks to better nutrition and
weight training, his fastball has improved 3 mph to the 87-88
range. ``Ten pounds and three miles an hour,'' Ladnier said. ``Put
on another 10 pounds, it might be 91-92.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Ladnier, ``None of these are guys who you're going
to say, 'Let's consider them for our top 10 prospects.' But some
have better tools than others. But none make you stand up and go,
'Wow!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Santana is pitching well until the third inning, when
he's knocked around, gives up six runs and departs with the bases
loaded. He then ices down his shoulder with some newly crushed ice;
trainer Jose Gil puts some ice cubes into a cut-off, taped-up
portion of a uniform pants leg, then pounds it with a sawed-off bat
barrel before pouring it into a plastic bag for Santana's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   After the three-hour, 10-3 loss, Santana is quiet on the bus
ride home. He eats lunch at the dorm and accompanies two visitors
in a taxi to Bernard's house. Then the cab cautiously snakes
through the dirt alleys of Santana's barrio, Juan Pablo Duarte.
Naked babies play in the dirt outside shacks. Stray dogs pick
through the garbage that is everywhere. The cabbie, Tulio Mercedes,
avoids huge potholes still filled with day-old rainwater.
</P>
<P>
   There, on the right side of Calle Elia Gonzalez, is Santana's
home, a tiny, two-room cinderblock hovel he's shared with his
mother and aunt for five years. Still wearing his game uniform, his
blue satin Braves warmup jacket buttoned to the neck, Santana gives
a quick tour. He lives behind the little kitchen, in a bedroom
built from pieces of wood. He can lie on his bed and watch baseball
on a little TV. On the wall hangs a color action photo of himself,
in full windup.
</P>
<P>
   In the backyard, Santana's aunt wields a butcher knife, sawing
the jawbone off a cow's head. That explains the mysterious contents
of the pot on the stove. Cow's brains.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, when asked to describe his pitching style, Santana had
grinned and said, ``Like Pedro Martinez.'' Now, he says goodbye.
While slowly navigating Calle Elia Gonzalez, Tulio Mercedes gazes
about him. ``San Pedro de Macoris,'' the taxi driver says. ``Mucha
pobreza.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Much poverty in San Pedro. But much baseball, too. Here,
where it's 335 feet down the lines, 385 to center and light-years
to Atlanta, hope floats on the cool tradewinds and every blessed
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Wilkinson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
