<HEADER>
A9301 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MINORS-TALENT-COX     08-18 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-TALENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINOR LEAGUE SERIES: It's a global game now
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world is indeed shrinking. At least when it comes to the
search for major-league baseball prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few places on the globe now where teams aren't
actively pursuing potential players,'' Atlanta Braves general
manager John Schuerholz said. ``Maybe Iceland or Antarctica, but
I'm not sure a scout hasn't been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta has players under contract from 15 countries, plus
Puerto Rico. The 40-man roster includes 11 players born outside the
continental United States, slightly more than the major-league
average. The minor-league system is more than 30 percent
foreign-born, with players from the Dominican Republic, Venezuela,
Nicaragua, Colombia, Panama, Mexico, Brazil, South Korea,
Netherlands Antilles, Australia, New Zealand, Aruba and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, we were in the Dominican and Mexico, but that
was about it,'' said Paul Snyder, the Braves' director of scouting
and player development. ``Our scouting efforts have probably
quadrupled in the '90s. Now we're all over South America and in the
Far East, even Europe. It has really exploded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has finally caught up with the times,'' said Bill
Clark, the Braves' director of international scouting. ``Talent is
talent, no matter where it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was in the forefront of international scouting, along
with the Dodgers and Yankees. ``It became a point of emphasis for
us,'' Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Every team is in on the talent search now. With only the United
States, Puerto Rico and Canada covered by the annual June draft,
the rest of the world is wide open to the most persistent or
highest-bankrolled scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Bonuses to foreign players were modest until 1993, when the
Braves gave $950,000 to Glenn Williams, a 16-year-old shortstop
from Australia. Now bidding wars are common.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no bargains out there anymore,'' said Snyder, who
has more than 25 foreign-based scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Curtright writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9302 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MINORS-DANVILLE-C     08-18 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-DANVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINOR LEAGUE SERIES: Danville players making it on their own
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Va. _ In time, Doug Dent's preparation might become a
model for the Appalachian League. What better training than a
two-year Mormon mission in a remote town on an island in the
Philippines?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably better than some of the living conditions
over there,'' Dent said.
</P>
<P>
   In the town of Naga, he slept on a foam mattress, boiled his
drinking water, washed clothes by hand.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Dent rents a two-bedroom, one-bathroom, $500-a-month
apartment with four other Danville Braves pitchers. Starters
Derrick Truitt and Justin Willoughby share one bedroom, relievers
Mike Gray and Pat Schmidt another. The living room couch? That's
where Dent dreams nightly of the big leagues and sleeps quite
comfortably for someone who's 6-feet-8.
</P>
<P>
   The cramped quarters, lack of privacy, lone toilet, monthly
cable TV and phone bills and sporadic attempts at home cooking are
minor inconveniences. Here, Appy-ness is a radar gun reading of 90
mph and roomies who can relate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all get along,'' Willoughby said about life in Apt. D-37.
``We root for each other. They're our brothers, our family away
from home.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Danville, home of the D-Braves, Atlanta's advanced
rookie-level team and the third stop up the organizational food
chain. Almost everything here is named the Dan something-or-other.
Even the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   The Dan _ Dan Daniels Memorial Park _ sits on the Dan River and
offers $1 hot dogs, $2.25 24-ounce beers, $6 box seats and 50-cent
scorecards that include Baseball Bingo cards. At every home game,
one lucky fan wins a free dry cleaning.Elliott's Cleaners. Making
your world cleaner one garment at a time.
</P>
<P>
   And for every day of the 2 1/2-month, 68-game Appy season, the
D-Braves have to improve themselves one game at a time while
learning to live on their own. At least they are allowed to bring
their cars, which is not the case in the Gulf Coast League.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first time away from home,'' said Truitt, 20, a
right-hander who pitched two years of junior-college ball in his
hometown of Columbia, Tenn., and signed with Atlanta after the
Braves picked him in the 24th round of the June draft. ``It's
different. You don't have mom and dad there to give you money. You
have to learn how to wash clothes for the first time. You have to
learn how to live with different types of people, too, from all
over the world. You may not live with 'em in the apartment, but on
the road you may have to room with a Latino. You have to learn to
cope.''
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, from the Mathews Motors Little League team through
Columbia Central High and then Columbia State, Truitt threw it to
one catcher, Todd Bell. Now he's coping with three new catchers,
four new roommates and 25 new teammates and pitching inside to
stronger, more disciplined hitters wielding wooden bats. He broke
up with his girlfriend, the 9 1/2-hour drive home proving too far
for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   Gray took the opposite approach. ``I got engaged a week before I
came here,'' said the 21-year-old, whose fiancee is back home in
California, where Gray pitched in junior college. ``So it's been
tough but not too tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly because Gray uses a major coping device of the modern-day
minor-leaguer: prepaid phone cards. For $10, you can talk for 95
minutes; for $20, 190.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a normal phone bill,'' he said, ``it would probably
be awful.''
</P>
<P>
   If not disconnected. But then, young minor-leaguers must learn
not only how to throw or hit a changeup but also how to budget.
Especially in reconciling a small paycheck and a big appetite. The
D-Braves' average salary is $900 a month; they're paid every two
weeks. Unlike the Braves' Gulf Coast Rookie team in Orlando, the
D-Braves must pay housing costs. Food is the next big budget item,
home and away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest adjustment is eating,'' said Gray, who likes being
able to sleep in for the nightly 7 o'clock games, ``not having
home-cooked meals.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that they haven't tried in D-37. ``I'm the cook,''
Willoughby said proudly. His specialities? ``I cooked spaghetti. I
cooked the Hamburger Helper.'' One night, he offered exotic fare,
meat from a hunting trip last winter near his hometown of
Princeton, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get Derrick to eat some deer steak,'' Willoughby
said. ``He put it in his mouth _ and headed to the trash can.''
</P>
<P>
   On overnight road trips, anywhere from two to five hours, the
D-Braves _ who travel in a modern, air-conditioned bus with three
TV screens _ get $15 a day meal money. For ``commutes,'' shorter
trips of 30 to 45 minutes when the team returns home after each
game, the per diem is $7.50. The longer the trip, the quicker the
per diem can disappear.
</P>
<P>
   The D-Braves stay at modest motels chosen for location as well
as for good rooms and rates. Because players can't afford cab fare,
they eat at restaurants within walking distance of the motel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever's closest,'' Gray said. ``Usually fast food. You eat
too many good meals, your money runs out.''
</P>
<P>
   Truitt tries to eat breakfast daily. ``It's important,
energy-wise,'' said Truitt, who eats again at 3:30 before going to
the ballpark. ``After the game is awful. Sometimes, games aren't
over 'til 10. We don't get back to the motel 'til 10:30, 10:45.
Everything closes at 10:30 or 11. One night we had to go to
Kroger's and eat a frozen ham sub.''
</P>
<P>
   In July, the D-Braves hit the road for nine days, their longest
road trip of the season. ``We had $135 to last us nine days,'' said
Truitt, who also brought along his paycheck of $230. By trip's end,
he'd spent all of his meal money and half his take-home pay.
</P>
<P>
   None of it bothers Dent, 21, who pitched at the University of
Utah, was drafted in the 13th round in 1997 and signed this summer
after returning from the Philippines. After not pitching for a
year-and-a-half, the right-handed starter reported to Orlando for
two weeks after signing, then came here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It actually feels like baseball for the first time,'' Dent
said. ``The crowd. The first time they played the national anthem
was nice. I'd forgotten that. They don't do that in the Gulf Coast
League.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest difference for most of these players is
every day,'' said D-Braves manager Franklin Stubbs, the ex-Dodger
in his first year as a minor-league manager. ``You've got to play
every every day. Most of 'em are used to playing three days a week,
maybe four. Their bodies aren't used to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen guys after 30 games hit that wall. You can see it.
Guys go, `Whoa!' You ask them how they're doing, they say, `Tired.'
I say, `Tired? You're 19!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, 19, and on the couch, on your own, often for the first
time. ``You definitely find out a lot about yourself in the first
few weeks,'' said Schmidt, 19, of Bellefontaine, Ohio. ``You find
out if you love baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
