<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9304 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MINORS-GULFCOAST-     08-18 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MINORS-GULFCOAST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MINOR LEAGUE SERIES: Surviving the Gulf Coast League can be
tricky
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO _ The team is based at Atlanta's spring-training home on
the edge of Disney World. But there is nothing big league or
magical about the Gulf Coast League, where most Braves hopefuls get
their first bittersweet taste of professional baseball under the
searing Florida sun.
</P>
<P>
   Games are played at noon in virtual privacy on a shadeless
practice field, not before screaming fans at the Braves' Wide World
of Sports Stadium nearby. And even if they had the time to make
regular visits, Disney World is out of the price range of most
players, who make just $850 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a player can survive this, the rest seems almost easy as he
moves up,'' manager Rick Albert said. ``This league is a real
grind. It's a rude awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   As Johnny McGinnis prepares to deliver his first pitch, the
temperature under the noonday sun is already nearly 100 degrees and
the sapping humidity makes it feel even worse. The non-crowd
numbers five, including a groundskeeper watching from on top of his
mower near the third-base dugout. There is no national anthem,
because there is no sound system or flag hanging in centerfield.
The only cheering during the game comes from a youth-league
tournament game on a nearby field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to get pumped up,'' said McGinnis, a lefthander who
was drafted in the fourth round in June after graduating from
Dacula High School in Gwinnett County. ``All your life, you are
used to having people cheer for or against you when you play. Now
you are in pro baseball, and there is no one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad teams in Little League have more people watching them than
we do,'' said Greg Dukeman, a relief pitcher from Long Beach,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   But the Gulf Coast League wasn't designed to draw crowds. The
goals always has been to develop young players in a
non-intimidating environment. Games are free and start as early as
possible to avoid Florida's regular late-afternoon thunderstorms.
Braves players get up shortly after dawn and board a bus for away
games on trips that last as long as five hours round trip. Games
are played Monday through Saturday, with Sundays off.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league stars Chipper Jones, Tom Glavine and Javy Lopez
each played his first minor-league season in the Gulf Coast League,
when the Atlanta team was based at Bradenton. The memories linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was terrible,'' Lopez remembers. ``No fans. Nothing to do
after the games. I got homesick after a couple of weeks. It wasn't
fun at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said, ``The only thing I can liken it to, from what my dad
tells me about being in the Army, is boot camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Players are picked up at the nearby Days Inn Suites at 7:45 a.m.
and are expected to be on the field for workouts before home games
no later than 8:30 a.m. There is a break at 11 a.m. for a sandwich,
and the game begins at noon. Extra base-running or fielding
practice occasionally is held after games. The players, who have
kitchens in their suites, are on their own for supper. Curfew is 11
p.m., expect for midnight on Saturday. The fine is $25 for missing
the curfew the first time and doubles with each additional
violation.
</P>
<P>
   But players say missed curfews aren't common. First-year players
can't bring their cars, so they basically are confined to the
hotel. And a 10-hour day in the Florida heat leaves little energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most nights I'm asleep by 11,'' said outfielder Ryan
Langerhans, a third-round draft pick from Round Rock, Texas, who
received near first-round bonus money ($775,000) to pass up a
scholarship to the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only play 60 games,'' Albert, the manager, said, ``but it's
still a long season.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't used to playing everyday,'' Albert said. ``Some
teams draft a lot of college players, but not the Braves. We take
mostly high-school kids and teach them to play our way. They
usually struggle a little at first, but potentially you get better
players in the long run. Sometimes, a feel like a first-grade
teacher. I just hope they remember me when they make it to the
majors.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert and his staff not only have to teach 18-year-olds how to
play the Braves way, but in many cases how to adjust to a different
country and a strange language.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' 30-man Gulf Coast League active roster this season
has included players from 10 countries _ the United States, the
Dominican Republic, Venezuela, Nicaragua, Colombia, Panama, Mexico,
Brazil, South Korea and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Albert doesn't speak Spanish, so he relies heavily on coaches
Edison Renteria _ a Columbian and brother of the Marlins' Edgar
Rentera _ and Eddie Watt. To help players adjust off the field,
English classes are held two nights a week. The instructor is Lana
Hausterman, a native of Colombia and the wife of team
administrative assistant Dave Hausterman.
</P>
<P>
   Langerhans and McGinnis _ the top two draft choices on the team
_ share a two-room suite with Jung Bong, an 18-year-old from Seoul,
South Korea. He was spotted by the Braves during an international
youth tournament in Canada and signed to a six-figure bonus after
his family was assured that he would be allowed to finish high
school.
</P>
<P>
   Bong lived with an aunt, Mi Sook Kim, in Norcross last school
year and attended Masters Christian in DeKalb County. He admits his
English still has a ways to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting better,'' he said. ``I can understand more now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bong, who dreams of becoming the next Chan Ho Park, and McGinnis
both rank in the top 10 in earned run average in the league.
However, wins are hard to come by in the GCL, where starters rarely
go the required five innings early in the season to get credit for
a victory. But they do pitch long enough to get a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've pitched OK, but my record doesn't look like it,'' said
McGinnis, who lost his first four decisions before getting his
first win last week.
</P>
<P>
   But statistics are virtually ignored in the league. Batting
averages can be as misleading as won-loss records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us are swinging wood bats for the first time and
facing better pitchers than we've ever seen,'' said outfielder
Damien Jones, a former Alabama high-school football star. ``It's
like starting with two strikes against you. It's really a learning
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The chance to teach raw players the game away from the usual
glare of pro baseball is what pitching coach Watt enjoys about the
league.
</P>
<P>
   ``A player needs a place to break in where he can fail without
having fans boo him or having to read about how bad he is in the
paper,'' the former major-league reliever said. ``This is where you
learn the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Most players escape the Gulf Coast League after one season.
Catcher Scott Frawley wasn't so lucky. This is his second year and
he is one of the older players at 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``You definitely don't want to be here two seasons,'' said
Frawley, who loses nearly 10 pounds every game he catches because
of the heat. ``This is really the bottom of the ladder. There is
nowhere to go but up. When I signed, I expected to be playing
before crowds and under the lights. I haven't done any of that yet.
Sometimes it is hard to believe this is pro ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Curtright writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
