<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING THE GAME IN PERSPECTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's all a matter of perspective.
</P>
<P>
   New York Giants coach Jim Fassel surveys the rubble of Friday's
24-10 exhibition defeat against the Jacksonville Jaguars and
declares, ``I'm not very happy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line all but escorted Jaguars pass rushers into
the backfield. Running backs carried the ball gingerly, as if the
only holes available to them were shallow graves. The season is
coming too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Grimly, Fassel vows to light a fire that will singe the players'
backsides.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'd feel a little better if he stepped back and took a
look at the other occupants of Giants Stadium. The New York Jets
suffered their worst exhibition defeat in 22 years Saturday. There
may have been the makings of a quarterback controversy before the
33-0 whipping by the Baltimore Ravens, but Glenn Foley and Vinny
Testaverde did everything in their power to quell that kind of
talk. For a true controversy to take hold, it helps if one
quarterback would make a difference over another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am concerned,'' Parcells says, ``about everything that
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'd feel a little better if he stepped back and took a
look at what's left of the Team of the '90s. The Dallas Cowboys
(6-10 last season) don't scare anybody anymore _ until they get off
the field. The latest escapade involves receiver Michael Irvin,
offensive lineman Everett McIver and a pair of barber's scissors.
</P>
<P>
   McIver was waiting for a teammate to give a free haircut and
ended up with his throat sliced. Maybe because the Cowboys have
applied a gag order on everybody involved, reports have circulated
that owner Jerry Jones arranged to pay off McIver so that charges
don't get filed against Irvin. Because if charges get filed, Irvin
runs the risk of getting thrown in jail for violating his
probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys,'' Irvin complains to reporters, ``are working harder
to put me in jail than the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Irvin would feel a little less persecuted if he put
himself in the place of the hero of Super Bowl XXVI. Quarterback
Mark Rypien isn't in training camp this year because he has more
important things to do than a job. Rypien's 3-year-old son, Andrew,
has a brain tumor. Doctors have warned that Andrew probably won't
make it through August. His wife, Annette, is recovering from
recent surgery for cervical cancer. So Rypien has chosen to stay at
home, to spend every possible moment with his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about making Andrew happy,'' Rypien says, adding,
``We're praying for a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it would do everybody good once in a while to take a
longer look around. Former New York Jets defensive end Paul Frase
wishes he could spend his days in Florida with his 3-year-old son,
Joshua, who has a rare and life-threatening muscle and nerve order.
Instead, Frase has been in camp with the Green Bay Packers,
fighting for a job he desperately needs. He can't afford to stay
home.
</P>
<P>
   Frase must pay bills and remain insured while his wife, Alison,
tends to Joshua. It is round-the-clock duty. Joshua is on a feeding
tube, and he often cannot clear his lungs on his own. If Frase
makes the team, he will send for his wife and son.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't make the team this year,'' Frase says, ``that does
give me more time to spend with the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo Bills linebacker Chris Spielman is taking a leave of
absence this season to be with his family. Spielman made the
decision in July when his wife, Stephanie, was diagnosed with
breast cancer. Explains Spielman: ``My wife has supported me for 10
years unconditionally, and the least I can do is go through this
with her unconditionally. I want to be the one to take her to the
treatments, I want to be the one to hold her hand, and I want to be
the one to be with my kids when she can't be.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all a matter of perspective. Shortly after wowing Giants
coaches in a minicamp, running back LeShon Johnson was diagnosed
with a lymphoma. He has to fight for his life before he gets around
to battling for a spot on the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
