<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON STARR &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ Ledeall on President Clinton's
testimony and speech, as well as the options of the independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr. By James Bennet and Don Van Natta Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VINEYARD (Edgartown, Mass.) _ The president makes phone
calls to rally support, then leaves for vacation on Martha's
Vineyard. What does he do on the Vineyard, and what is the reaction
to him there. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ Clinton and Starr are caught in a
deadly embrace on the issue of whether there can or will or needs
to be more testimony from the president. A news analysis by Jill
Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS (Washington) _ What is the initial political
impact of the testimony and speech; who is silent, who is vocal,
and what does it mean. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LEGAL (Washington) _ What are the legal realities of
Clinton's claim to have a right of privacy before the grand jury,
and of his defense against perjury. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Washington) _ Todd S. Purdum examines President
Clinton's speech in detail; how it was prepared, what was and was
not said, what techniques, successful in the past, were employed
again.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VOICES (Milwaukee, Wis.) _ Talking to people in
Milwaukee to gague their measured reaction to Clinton's speech. By
Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLLS (Undated) _ Reaction to the speech according to
the NYT-CBS poll and others.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, we are considering separate stories on the reaction
from the president's defenders and more on Hillary Clinton's role
and reaction.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MISS-KLAN-TRIAL (Hattiesburg, Miss.) _ Opening arguments in the
murder trial of a former Ku Klux Klan leader accused of
masterminding a firebomb attack that killed Mississippi civil
rights leader Vernon Dahmer 32 years ago. The trial is the fifth
for Sam Bowers, 73, whose four previous trials in the Jan. 10, 1966
attack on Dahmer's home ended with deadlocked juries. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AIDS-AFRICA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-MILK (Kakulu, Uganda) _ The basic rules of public
health are clear in Kakulu: only drink water from the well, not
from the polluted Nile; and breastfeeding is the best way to
nourish an infant. At least those were the rules until a few weeks
ago, when the United Nations _ struggling desperately to find a way
to cope with an AIDS epidemic that threatens the future of Africa _
took a giant step toward reversing them. After long deliberation,
U.N. AIDS officials announced that women infected with HIV should
consider feeding formula instead of breast milk to their babies. A
Special Report By Michael Specter. (2500 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Other international &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ Dollar-ruble rate firms a bit. Other
developments on the Russian economic front. By Celestine Bohlen..
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-DEBT (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Investors and analysts said
the moratorium was the most alarming of the decisions announced
today, because it marks the first time that Yeltsin has decided to
flout international financial commitments in order to bail out
Russian bankers and industrialists. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-FUNERAL (Augher, Northern Ireland) _ Several hundred
people, many weeping as they prayed, crowded around a small gray
stone church and graveyard near this rural village Tuesday to watch
the burial of Avril Monaghan, her 18-month-old daughter, Laura, and
the two infants in her womb, expected to be born next months. Ms.
Monaghan's Mother, Mary Grimes, is to be buried Wednesday. By James
F. Clarity.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. (United Nations) _ Under the oil-for-food exchange
program with Iraq, the U.N. announced Tuesday that Iraq would only
be able to exchange about $3 billion worth of oil because of its
weak oil pumping equipment and falling oil prices. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-U.S. (Washington) _ Developments in the East Africa
embassy bombing investigation. By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-ALBRIGHT (Nairobi) _ With the secretary of state in
Africa. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The Fed's policy-making committee
meets and is expected to leave interest rates unchanged. Two
economic reports are issued. One shows that consumer prices rose
0.2 percent last month and that the core rate, which strips out
volatile food and energy costs, increased by the same amount. The
other shows that the trade deficit in goods and services narrowed
during June for the first time this year, shrinking to $14.15
billion from a record $15.54 billion in May. Exports of goods and
services fell half a percent in June, while imports declined 2
percent. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments regarding the
timing or ground rules for the Gates deposition. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-VIDEO (Undated) _ The world's airlines have spent
millions on sophisticated systems that offer a video screen at
every airplane seat with a choice of as many as 20 different movies
plus computer games, shopping and even gambling. What used to be a
battle in the skies over who served the best steak and the finest
red wine has become a war over who offers the most films and
Nintendo games. The world's airlines are expected to spend $6
billion over the next five years to equip their planes with the
newest generation of the systems. By Laurence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-ECON (Caracas, Venezuela) _ The Russian devaluation and
moratorium are just the latest pieces of bad news for Latin
America's financial markets. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   See also RUSSIA-ECON and RUSSIA-DEBT, under International.
</P>
<P>
   KMPG (Undated) _ KPMG Peat Marwick plans to either sell as much
as 30 percent of its American consulting division to a private
investor or take the division public. By Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   KORN-IPO (Undated) _ Korn/Ferry files for an initial public
offering. By Dana Canedy.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Dell Computer reports earnings. By
Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   NETSCAPE-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Netscape reports earnings. By
Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   CANON (Undated) _ Canon rolls out new products. By Claudia H.
Deutsch.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The Business Travel column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stock market developments: The Dow Jones
Industrial Average was up 93 points at 2 p.m. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments: The long bond
was off 8/32 at midday. By Robert Hurtado.
</P>
