<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CHATTER SENDS THE INTERNET SPINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ President Clinton's historic on-air speech
Monday night was followed by a historic on-line tidal wave of
reaction.
</P>
<P>
   News and Web sites such as Yahoo logged a crushing number of
visits from Web Wide Web users, who unleashed an outpouring of
sound and fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest day ever,'' said Mary Kathleen Flynn, Internet
correspondent for MSNBC, recounting the day's on-line traffic in
various chat rooms and polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our busiest day ever,'' said Scott Woelfel, editor-in-chief of
CNN Interactive, the all-news cable channel's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Princess Diana, the bombing of U.S. embassies, the
demise of Buffalo Bob. You name it, and Clinton's admission of an
inappropriate relationship with a former White House intern dwarfed
them in the realm of the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of the outpourings, pulled from an MSNBC chat room,
ranged from the poignant to the, OK, see for yourselves:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad day in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is a turd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheese poofs.''
</P>
<P>
   On-line polls were jammed, logging hundreds of thousands of
electronic voters who weighed in with their picks.
</P>
<P>
   Though national polls showed support for Clinton _ about 60
percent to 40 percent were satisfied with the president's
explanation _ the Web-based polls consistently showed the polar
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   According to those running the sites, the on-line chatter is all
pretty much a computerized version of workplace gossiping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way for people to gather around and talk about what it
all means to them,'' Woelfel said. ``The benefit is hard to
describe at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people like having this virtual water cooler,'' Flynn
said. She said the most concrete benefit she had seen is people
asking each other how they were going to explain things like
presidential infidelity to their children.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, Woelfel said, the Web is empowering people to fight
back against that other tube, the television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a story that's gone on for seven months,'' he said.
``That's seven months of all these commentators talking about
nothing but this one story. The Web is a way for the common person
to be a pundit themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woelfel added that no one should assume that the on-line
chatter was representative of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it democracy,'' he said. ``It doesn't
represent who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Alexander, president of the California Voter Foundation said
the instant reaction may not be that healthy for an informed body
politic, as blather substitutes for the hard work of trying to
analyze issues. The California Voter Foundation publishes facts
about politicians over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Alexander couldn't resist a watery comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lets people blow off steam,'' she said. ``It's great that
people don't have to sit around and shout at the television set.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1434EDT &QL; 
