</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316.
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CAMPAIGN _ After his defiant nationally televised plea
to independent counsel Ken Starr to stop ``prying into personal
lives,'' President Clinton Tuesday began what is likely to be his
last campaign _ to save his embattled presidency by getting enough
credibility and traction with his party and the public in hopes of
being able to govern. Delaying his scheduled departure for a
Martha's Vineyard vacation, Clinton spent the morning on the
telephone in an attempt to shore up his Democratic Party base. It's
likely to be the first of many salvage operations. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIVACY _ WASHINGTON _ Aside from whether he can restore
his credibility, President Clinton's televised appeal to end the
``prying'' into his private life no doubt struck a chord with many
Americans who feel the government and private industry have gone
too far in delving into things that used to be purely personal
matters. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CENSURE _ Between the James Carvilles and Bob Barrs, a
growing number of people in Washington are looking for a middle
ground, a way of resolving this mess that is neither vindication
nor impeachment. Censure offers such a way and we look at those
calling for it and how it would work. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRIVATE _ Discussion of when the private becomes public.
Talking to those with experience: Barney Frank, Gary Hart, Bob
Packwood, Mike Bowers, Jim Bakker, Jimmy Swaggart. (Manuel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JACKSON _ In light of their midnight meeting after the
speech, is there more to do on the relationship between Jackson and
the Clintons? This might be where we can also deal more with
Chelsea and Hillary if there isn't enough to do a separate story.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LIBRARY _ LITTLE ROCK, Ark. _ How are the people raising
money for the Clinton Presidential Library in Little Rock reacting,
what sort of response are they getting today. (Rochell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDIA _ Following TV coverage, overnight ratings, what
else is planned, etc. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KIDS _ Special News For Kids piece explaining the
presidential crisis to kids. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PANEL _ Introducing our Atlanta-area panel and how
they're reacting to, talking about and feeling toward Clinton in
the cold light of day. (Visser, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ Advancer for Newt Gingrich's swing through the West,
campaigning for vulnerable Republicans. (Sherman, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS _ There's a new barometer for reading which races the
national parties are most worried about _ tax-exempt expenditures.
We take a look at which races are attracting the most independent
issue advertising and what that may say about the Democrats chances
of re-taking the House. (Sherman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-MIRABILIS _ JERUSALEM _ With recent software deals
pouring hundreds of millions of dollars into Israeli companies, the
new celebrities here are no longer army generals or politicians,
but high school dropouts. In June, America Online announced that it
bought Tel Aviv-based Mirabilis Ltd. for $287 million in cash and
up to another $120 million based on future growth. The two-year-old
company invented ICQ, an Internet chat service with more than 14
million users. Ninety percent of the money goes to its four
twenty-something founders _ two of whom never made it through 12th
grade _ and one of their parents. But, Mirabilis was topped _ in
dollars if not in cult fame _ last week when the more conventional
software company, Memco, was bought for $412 million in stock by
Illinois-based Platinum Technology. Memco makes software for
securing information stored on Internet servers. The two deals
highlight the growing Israeli software industry, where companies
are making their marks as acquisition targets or niche providers.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WARMING _ It may not prove the case for global warming, but the
weather in the United States has certainly taken some odd twists
and turns this year. A report by the Sierra Club maintains that the
recent extreme conditions are a sign that the output from mankind's
smokestacks and automobiles is increasing the temperature of the
earth which could lead to dire consequences in the future.
(Dempsey, Dayton Daily News). 25.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG _ Michael Favorov is a Russian doctor at the Centers for
Disease Control who helped discover a new strain of hepatitis.
Yiannis Ventikos is a Greek scientist at Georgia Tech whose
research helps to save fish endangered by hydroelectric power
plants. Lisa Cregan-O'Brien is a world-class Irish dancer who
teaches American children the traditional steps of her homeland.
All came to Atlanta on a special immigrant visa available only to
the world's best and brightest in science, arts, education,
business or athletics. Known as the national interest waiver, it is
given to immigrants who can prove their skills and talents are so
unique that America would substantially benefit if they were here.
(Kurylo, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
