<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDITORIAL-COX     08-18 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDITORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An editorial in The Atlanta Journal Tuesday, Aug. 18, 1998:
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In spite of it all, nation will survive
 &HT;    By The Atlanta Journal
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE SPECTER of a president of the United States who looked the
American people in the eye and lied to preserve his political
viability does permanent damage to the office of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Like Richard Nixon before him, Bill Clinton has frittered away a
national treasure: the respect a governed people have for a revered
institution. The president is wrong. This is not about sex. It is
not about a president's ``private'' life, as he asserted Monday
night. It's about trust. A president cannot look his people in the
eye and knowingly assert an untruth as fact, no matter how cleverly
drawn the lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that my public comments and my silence about this
matter gave a false impression,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   This is a president who lives in the legalistic margins, who
masters the law to fit a lifestyle among its nuances and in its
loopholes, a man who would stand at the gates of hell quibbling
legal semantics with the devil. Even in his speech Monday, the
quibbling semanticist reasserted himself. After professing to take
``complete responsibility'' for all of his actions, the president
proceeded to characterize his past testimony as ``legally
accurate'' and only improper in that he ``did not volunteer
information.'' This is a president still in denial.
</P>
<P>
   It's primarily a Kenneth Starr vendetta, the president and his
protectors in and out of the media would have us believe. ``The
independent counsel investigation moved on to my staff and friends,
then into my private life,'' Clinton said. Deep denial.
</P>
<P>
   The question now, though, is: Where does the nation go from
here?
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment?
</P>
<P>
   Resignation?
</P>
<P>
   Two more years of the ceremonial and fund-raising president
without the credibility and the moral authority to lead?
</P>
<P>
   We are not yet ready to recommend impeachment. We will say,
however, if grounds are established _ obstruction of justice,
perjury or suborning perjury _ the House decision on whether to
bring charges should not be influenced one iota by public opinion
polls. Public opinion will catch up with principled adherence to
constitutional duty.
</P>
<P>
   Resignation? We don't demand it. The damage to the presidency is
done. Resignation won't repair it. On one measure, the president's
defenders are right. The essence of the man was known to the
American people when they voted for him a second time. The pattern
of behavior exhibited in the White House is consistent with his
previous life.
</P>
<P>
   The nation is faced, then, with a credibility-bereft president
serving out the remainder of his term. The nation can limp through
that. In the event of national emergency, the nation rallies to
common purpose _ and we will, whether the president is strong or
weak.
</P>
<P>
   Among the lawyers, journalists and politicians who gather in
Washington watering holes to fashion the instant talk-show analysis
that characterizes political debate, the cleverness of the dodge _
it's ``inappropriate contact,'' not a ``sexual relationship''; the
matter is ``private,'' and Starr is the villain _ may be an
admirable, get-off-the-hook political strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The chattering class may express admiration for the cleverly
spun evasion. But at every Waffle House in America, nobody's
fooled. This is not contrition. It is combative denial and a heavy
dose of wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
