<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of WEDNESDAY, Aug.
19.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867. And be sure to look for other stories from our partners:
Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DINING &LR;  (``d'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EXOTIC-MARTINIS (Undated) _ First it was cool. Then it got hot.
Now it's bloated and out of control. The martini, sleekest and
suavest of cocktails, has entered the late-Elvis phase of its
once-splendid career, staggering under the weight of weird
garnishes, dazed and disoriented by years of experimenting with
chemicals like Jagermeister, Chambord and Kahlua. From sea to
shining sea, the bars of the United States are groaning under the
weight of horrible martinis. It's time to enter rehab. By William
Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   PEEKYTOE-CRAB (Deer Isle, Maine) _ The sun was just easing over
the horizon when Matthew Eaton hopped into his skiff and set off
into the glassy waters of Eggemogginn Reach. A short distance from
the shore, he reached his destination: a wooden platform where he
had suspended two traps the night before. Each held a small catch
of frisky, reddish crabs. It is the height of the lobster season,
when most Maine lobstermen let the little crabs go instead of
collecting them, as Eaton does. With so many lobsters, worth so
much more money, most lobstermen don't want to bother with crabs.
But Mr. Eaton is no fool; he knows his customer. Welcome to the
world of the peekytoe crab, where one man's trash is another man's
treasure. By Marian Burros.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   CRABBING (Undated) _ If the volatile stock market makes you
dizzy, just be glad you're not a crabber. Though America's
coastline and offshore waters boast more varieties of edible crabs
than any other part of the world, from year to year supplies
plummet, then soar, then plummet and soar again, for reasons known
only to nature. Yet there never seems to be enough crab to meet the
demand. By Florence Fabricant.
</P>
<P>
   ZUCCHINI-SOUP (Undated) _ Soup bases made from zucchini. By
Barbara Kafka.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   WHEAT-BEER (Undated) _ Summer is the season for wheat beers.
Their tartness distinguishes them: With their lemony tang, they
quench the thirst and rest light on the tongue. At their best, they
are fruity with just a hint of clove spiciness in the aroma. At
their less-than-best, they are so light that their flavor
disappears. We sampled 11 wheat beers, both American and European _
but only three stood out. By William Grimes and Elaine Louie.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ First column in a series from Charlie
Palmer: Whole roasted salmon.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Perpignan, France) _ The French call this western
Mediterranean corner of their country the last frontier. It is a
vast expanse of arid, inhospitable land bounded by this city,
Carcassonne and the Spanish border. In the back country leading up
into the Pyrenees and in some former fishing villages along the
coast, the old people still speak Catalan, which has been described
as the language of the Roman foot soldier. The language may be as
close as we will ever come to the Latin argot of the Roman Empire,
but it isn't the only remnant of those times: vines were almost
certainly planted here by the Phoenicians and later the Greeks. By
Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TASTINGS (Undated) _ Capsule review of a particular wine.
</P>
<P>
   BENTO-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Amanda Hesser reviews the book
``Simple Menus for the Bento Box''
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Indonesian chicken. By
Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   KITCHEN-WARES (Undated) _ The test kitchen column: immersion
blenders. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD-NOTES (Undated) _ News and notes on food and dining.
</P>
