<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9454 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIAN-ECONOMY-HNS &LR;      08-18 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIAN-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKER SEES CHINA AS SOURCE OF STABILITY AMID ASIAN WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The economies of many East Asian nations _ and
now Russia _ may be bleeding, but timely intervention can staunch
the hemorrhage and eventually restore the patients to health.
</P>
<P>
   That was the assessment of James A. Harmon, chairman of the
Export-Import Bank of the United States. Harmon, a longtime
investment banker who took over as head of the government agency in
July 1887, said the Export-Import Bank was ready to help U.S.
companies deal with the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-based agency offers guaranteed loans, insurance
and other services to American companies and foreign entities that
contract with U.S. corporations when the risk is too high for the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech to the Pan American Society of San Francisco, Harmon
recalled that U.S. loans to crisis-ridden Latin America in the
1980s were 90 percent repaid, with salutary results for the region
and U.S. business.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing will happen in Asia, Harmon said in an interview.
Harmon visited China, Thailand and Japan last month. China is the
second-biggest recipient of Export-Import Bank loans, at $5.2
billion, after Mexico's $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trip to China was a very productive trip. I was the first
senior U.S. government official to go there in the afterglow of
President Clinton's trip,'' Harmon said, referring to the
president's visit in early June.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon said he and high-ranking Beijing officials talked about
tighter environmental standards on Chinese infrastructure projects.
The Export-Import Bank and institutions such as the World Bank
refused to finance China's Three Gorges dam because of
environmental concerns and a lack of detailed information from
China.
</P>
<P>
   On his recent visit, Harmon said, Chinese officials expressed
interest in buying environmental equipment, hospital equipment and
other merchandise. ``U.S. manufacturers will make (these goods),
which will create jobs in the U.S.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon said the United States is pressing China ``to buy more of
our goods and services because our trade deficit with them is
growing.'' The deficit hit $20.4 billion through May 1998, up from
$16.9 billion at the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
   A chartered agency with 400 employees founded in 1934, the
Export-Import Bank operated last year with a budget of $635
million. It is comparatively small compared to the World Bank and
the International Monetary Fund, both international lending
agencies, but growing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has asked for $808 million for the bank in the coming
year, bank spokesman Ken Murphy said. Murphy said the House and
Senate are talking about a $750 million budget.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon spent most of his Asian trip in China because, he said,
the United States sees China as a huge and relatively stable player
in Asia. China has so far resisted devaluing its currency, the
yuan. Even more than the just-devalued Russian ruble, a devalued
yuan could set off another deflationary round, Harmon said.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon also pointed to the Export-Import Bank's support of South
Korea as an example of efforts to help calm the Asian jitters. The
agency increased loans and guarantees to Seoul to $2 billion this
year, from just $50 million a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We extended letters of credit to South Korea because they
couldn't get raw materials from us,'' Harmon explained, saying he
believes the South Koreans ``are very creditworthy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harmon acknowledged that problems in East Asia remain. As
examples, he cited ethnic strife in Indonesia and Japan's stalled
economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 percent of the entire East Asian economy, Japan is by
far the biggest player in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are hoping that they take bolder action,'' Harmon
said, ``chiefly by effectively managing nonperforming loans at
their banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Harmon allowed that some Asian countries may have to restructure
their loans, taking more time to repay. But rescheduling, he noted,
is not the same as default.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon predicted Asia, which takes a third of U.S. exports,
would be growing again ``in the not-too-distant future.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the fundamentals of the world economy, especially
in the United States, appear to be sound: ``This is the strongest
economy I've ever seen in my business life, including the '60s,
which I thought were quite good.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia and Russia, Harmon said, will slow the American economy but
won't stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There'll be a slowdown,'' he said. ``A soft landing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
