<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-EDITORIAL2-CO     08-18 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDITORIAL2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton tarnishes legacy
 &HT;    (An editorial published Aug. 18, 1998, by The Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By The Atlanta Constitution
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With nearly 29 months remaining in his second term, President
Clinton has come before the American people _ again _ to ask them
to forgive him for an extramarital affair and its accompanying
lies. The voters heard something similar from then-candidate
Clinton during the 1992 presidential campaign, when he and his wife
gave a remarkable interview to CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' during which he
admitted to causing ``pain'' in his marriage.
</P>
<P>
   These acts of contrition are less persuasive for their
frequency. If Clinton had been genuinely sorry in 1992, surely he
would have found the will to restrain himself from further
extramarital dalliances.
</P>
<P>
   He did not. Instead, he again embarrassed himself and humiliated
his wife and daughter. Because he is now the president, his latest
recklessness also demeaned the office he holds and distracted his
Cabinet from important business.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in sworn testimony before a grand jury, the president
reportedly admitted that for seven months, he flat-out lied to the
public. If he could justify those lies as necessary to spare
himself the embarrassment of his own conduct and his family further
humiliation, he cannot justify lying to members of his Cabinet and
other close associates, colleagues who must be able to depend on
the president's honesty. Instead, he sent them out to defend him
with what he knew were lies.
</P>
<P>
   Now Congress and the American public must ask themselves whether
Clinton's immoral behavior requires that he leave office, either
through resignation or impeachment. The case for resignation is
strong. If Clinton cared deeply about the nation and the fate of
his own programs, he would hand the keys over to vice-president Al
Gore, who might be able to push some of those proposals, such as
Social Security reform, through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little in Clinton's history that suggests he will
choose that course. In fact, Clinton was less sorrowful than he was
combative in his short address to the nation Monday night. Seconds
after he uttered the words, ``I must take complete responsibility
for all my actions,'' he sought to mitigate his role in this tawdry
mess by pointing to a ``politically inspired lawsuit'' _ a
reference to the Paula Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he stuck to the line that his testimony in a
deposition related to that case _ testimony that is at the heart of
any perjury allegations _ was ``legally accurate.'' That strains
credulity.
</P>
<P>
   So, the question becomes: Should Congress impeach him? That
raises a different set of considerations, and based on the
information that has been made public, the answer is no. There is a
difference between behavior that is immoral and unseemly and
behavior that is illegal. So far, it seems, independent counsel
Kenneth Starr's investigation has not revealed substantial evidence
of the kinds of high crimes and misdemeanors that would warrant a
forced removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   There does not appear to be credible evidence that Clinton tried
to persuade Monica Lewinsky to lie under oath, which would lay the
groundwork for a case of subornation of perjury. That was the most
serious charge connected with the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does it appear that Starr, whose office has been riddled
with leaks, has turned up evidence of wrongdoing in the
investigation of the Whitewater real estate deal. Indeed, if the
latest leaks are correct, his investigation, after four years and
$40 million, has turned up essentially nothing of substance on
topics ranging from the death of Vince Foster to ``travelgate.''
</P>
<P>
   Legally, then, what have we here? It appears that Starr has
caught the president in a lie about adultery. Because Lewinsky
never accused the president of sexual harassment, Clinton's
testimony about their relationship was immaterial to the Paula
Jones case, a civil suit alleging sexual harassment by Clinton
while he was governor of Arkansas. Moreover, Jones' suit was thrown
out of court.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the president's alleged perjury involves only
immaterial testimony in a dismissed civil case. That just does not
justify impeachment. If the president is not above the law, neither
is he below its protections. It is unlikely that any average
citizen would be prosecuted for perjury in these circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to Starr and Congress to wrap up this investigation
as quickly as possible. Starr should immediately present his
complete report to Congress, and its members should make that
report public. Though Clinton may never regain either the respect
or trust of the nation, a full public accounting of the Starr
investigation may help restore the voters' faith in the system set
in place to handle allegations of wrongdoing against a high-ranking
public official.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the president has ensured that his dream of
assuming a prominent place in American history will never be
realized. But there are still important issues to which he must
attend as long as he is in office: including Social Security,
health care, global warming, and Asian and Russian economies in
crisis, not to mention global terrorism. Sadly, with his
credibility permanently damaged, his leadership in those areas may
be limited.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
