<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-RAINBOW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CLANCY THRILLER FULL OF ACTION, LIGHT ON TECHNOJARGON 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: stands for BOOKS-REVIEW-MYSTERIES)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Clancy's ``Rainbow Six'' (G.P. Putnam's Sons, $27.95, 740
pages) starts with a hijacking on Page 4 and the pace rarely
slackens in this well-crafted, very readable thriller.
</P>
<P>
   John Clark has just been named to head Rainbow Six, a secret
international task force that fights terrorism from a base in
England. En route to the new assignment, three Spanish-speaking men
take over the aircraft and tell the pilot to fly them to the
Azores. But quickly Clark, his executive officer Alistair Stanley
and strike team leader Domingo (Ding) Chavez, Clark's son-in-law,
disarm the hijackers and instruct the pilot to reroute to Gander,
Newfoundland.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, 10 winos are being scooped up off the streets and
taken to an undisclosed medical facility where they are given clean
clothes, good food, lots of drugged booze and injections of a
plague virus known as Shiva. As the wino group begins dying, young
women get picked up at singles bars, drugged and taken to the
facility to be injected so the personnel can test Shiva on healthy
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   In England, Clark begins to put two strike teams together _ one
headed by Ding, the other by Briton Peter Covington. Within weeks,
Rainbow Six gets the first call for help. A bank robbery in Bern
has gone bad, a hostage has been killed and the robbers are
threatening to kill more. Ding leads the assault on the bank,
rescuing all the hostages and killing all four gunmen, former
members of the notorious German terrorist group Baader-Meinhof.
Watching the operation is former KGB agent Dimitry Popov, who
financed the terrorists at the direction of a tree-hugging
billionaire U.S. politician and scientist.
</P>
<P>
   Next a group of terrorists seize an Austrian castle and Rainbow
Six is called in. Soon after, Basque separatists take over an
amusement park in Spain and grab 33 French children and two
critically ill youngsters in wheelchairs. Of course, Rainbow Six
saves the day.
</P>
<P>
   These three seemingly unrelated incidents are too close together
to be a coincidence. But before Clark and crew can get some clues
on who is behind the incidents, IRA terrorists take over the
hospital where Clark's wife, a nurse, and his pregnant daughter, a
doctor, work. Popov is again watching, and when he learns prisoners
have been taken, he heads back to the United States and changes his
identify.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clark and crew begin a worldwide manhunt to find Popov, a
hunt that will bring them closer and closer to a band of
environmentalists set on killing most of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   As always, Clancy has created a band of very moral, but very
motivated characters who have no qualms when good people are in
peril. The pace never slows, even when Rainbow Six is doing routine
drills back at the base. Unlike most Clancy thrillers, ``Rainbow
Six'' is light on the technical jargon.
</P>
<P>
   There is some sloppy editing early on. And it is unbelievable
that such a top-notch strike force can't figure out that they need
helicopter support and cellular phones until after the second
mission. But that just proves that even Clancy isn't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rainbow Six'' is No. 1 on the best-seller list for good reason
_ this a terrific yarn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
