<HEADER>
A9512 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR &LR;      08-18 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-NEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTABLE BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ A survey of recently published books:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MANAGING MARTIANS &QL; 
 &UR; Donna Shirley (Broadway, $25)
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a sturdy little gal,'' says Donna Shirley about
Sojourner Truth, the 25-pound robot (it was the size of a microwave
oven) that sent remarkable images back to Earth from the planet
Mars last year. Shirley headed the team that had spent four years
designing and building Sojourner, which was a rip-roaring success,
broadcasting back to Earth 10 times longer than expected. It also
was a bargain at $25 million (the entire Mars misson cost less than
it took to make the movie ``Titanic''). This is Shirley's memoir.
Born in 1941 in Oklahoma, she grew up ``a smart, mouthy tomboy in a
2,500-person town where the ideal of womanhood carried with it a
lot of chiffon and mascara.'' At 10, she decided to become an
aeronautical engineer and build airplanes. At 16 she received her
pilot's license. A year later she started engineering school at the
University of Oklahoma, the only woman in her class. Her career in
space exploration began at the Jet Propulsion Laboratory in
California, where she became manager of the Mars Exploration
Program. The ``Martians'' of her title are the creative people on
her team, who helped her realize her lifelong dream of getting to
Mars despite limited budgets and other obstacles. This is the
engaging story of a strong, confident woman who knew through it all
that she could, as she says, ``endure and even triumph over
anything.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; PASS THE POLENTA &QL; 
 &UR; Teresa Lust (Steer Forth, $24)
</P>
<P>
   Frances Mayes, author of the delectable ``Under the Tuscan
Sun,'' notes on the cover of this book that Teresa Lust is
appropriately named because her passion for food is in every word
she writes. And it's true, your mouth will water from start to
finish. The pages she devotes to the simple but exotically named
leftover, polenta (known in the southern United States, she reminds
us, as cornmeal mush), are downright intoxicating. Other subjects
include roast chicken, sauerkraut, homemade bread, wine, pie
crusts, soup and strawberry shortcake, all presented with a minimum
of pretense and an abundance of sensual delight in good home
cooking. Lust set out to write a traditional cookbook but in the
end produced a volume of essays, with some recipes thrown in at the
end. She calls it ``two parts memoir, one part recipe collection,
one part natural history and a pinch each of culinary trivia and
personal meditation.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ALIEN INVASION &QL; 
 &UR; Robert Devine (National Geographic, $24)
</P>
<P>
   It is, writes Devine, the least-known of the world's major
environmental issues. ``Alien invasion'' is the infiltration of
non-native, exotic, or non-indigenous animals or plants into a new
environment, with potentially disastrous effects on the ecosystem.
This sounds like an important issue, but unless you are an educated
environmentalist you probably won't get far into this book before
you pack up and retreat to blessed oblivion. Devine describes
threats and hazards and things run amok, complex problems with
complex symptoms and solutions. It's not easy to slog through, even
though he's aiming for general readers. (Alien weeds, we notice,
seem to be a particular problem _ weeds that are ``reaching the
upswing in their exponential growth curves'' with dire
consequences.) Bruce Babbitt has contributed a short, readable
introduction, but otherwise the message gets lost in the delivery. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; INTO THE WILDERNESS &QL; 
 &UR; Sara Donati (Bantam, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   That's an endorsement from Diana Gabaldon at the top of the dust
cover, above Donati's name, above even the title, because there's
no one in the world Bantam would rather have associated with this
first novel. Gabaldon's audience is huge, and Donati's book is
practically a homage to the kind of story Gabaldon is known for:
It's long (700 pages) and set in the past (on the American frontier
in the late 1700s), has a strong heroine who finds love and great
sex with a virile and devoted man, is written well enough that it
doesn't insult a reader's intelligence (except in the sex scenes)
and has more adventure than any heroine should be able to survive.
And the coup de grace: The next installment is already in the
works. When Gabaldon says nice things about you, you can afford to
be bold. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; SMOKE SIGNALS: A SCREENPLAY &QL; 
 &UR; Sherman Alexie (Hyperion, $10.95)
</P>
<P>
   Alexie likes to say that the entire budget for his movie,
``Smoke Signals,'' was less than the cost of one chandelier on
``Titanic.'' And as for Alexie's movie tie-in _ well, there are no
towering photographs of sad-eyed lovers, no special effects and
hardly any water (much of this story is set in Phoenix), but you'll
get more for your buck and you'll learn about filmmaking that is
driven by heart and soul rather than cash and clout. Alexie
prefaces his script with a short essay that is full of his pleasure
over the fact that this movie _ the first feature film written,
directed and co-produced by Indians to receive major distribution _
was ever made. He says screenplays are more like poetry than
fiction. ``(They) rely on imagery to carry the narrative, rather
than the other way around. And screenplays have form. Like sonnets,
actually. Just as there are expectations of form, meter and rhyme
in a sonnet, there are the same kinds of expectations of
screenplays.'' We wonder if James Cameron ever thought of that. &QL; 
(Arizona Republic correspondent Anne Stephenson and be reached at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1534EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
