<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAXIMALIST CHICKEN SALAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Standard chicken salad _ poached chicken, mayonnaise and celery
_ is about as minimalist as it gets. But so is the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   I'd rather make a chicken salad that has only one thing _
chicken _ in common with the familiar variety. My favorite contains
grilled chicken and a super-flavorful dressing based on soy sauce,
peanut or sesame butter, spices and cucumber for crunch. If you
combine the chicken and sauce while the chicken is hot, the flavors
marry perfectly, and their clarity remains even after the chicken
has been chilled. I like to make extra dressing and serve the
chicken on top of a bed of salad greens.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If possible, use boneless chicken thighs rather than breasts;
their flavor and texture is superior, and they remain moist during
grilling and brown perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer only a slight hint of heat in the dressing, and
therefore limit the hot sauce to a few drops, but you can add as
much as you like. Garlic, vinegar and sesame oil can also be added
to taste. Unless you must omit it for health reasons, you should
really include the sugar, which even in this minuscule quantity
adds a certain roundness that is otherwise lacking.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The combination of chicken and cucumber is near-perfect, but
bell pepper, celery or zucchini are all good additions. The
simplest, most effective garnish is minced cilantro, but basil
(especially Thai basil), mint or a combination of these herbs is
also great, as are some minced scallions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIAN CHICKEN SALAD &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 30 minutes (or longer if you want to serve it cold) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds boneless, skinless chicken thighs or breasts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons peanut butter or tahini (ground sesame paste)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   A few drops of hot sauce, like Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon rice or other vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cucumber
</P>
<P>
   \ cup minced cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Start a charcoal or gas grill, or preheat the broiler. Cut
the chicken meat into {- to 1-inch chunks, and thread it onto
skewers. Put the skewers on a plate, and drizzle with 2 tablespoons
of the soy sauce.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a blender, combine the remaining soy sauce with the peanut
butter, sesame oil, garlic, hot sauce, salt, pepper, sugar and
vinegar. Turn the blender on, and add hot water, a teaspoon at a
time, until the mixture is smooth and creamy. (You will not need
more than 3 teaspoons of water.)
</P>
<P>
   3. Grill or broil the chicken, turning once or twice. Total
cooking time will be 6 to 8 minutes for breasts, 10 to 12 minutes
for thighs. Meanwhile, peel the cucumber (if it is waxed), slice it
in half the long way, and scoop out the seeds with a spoon. Cut it
into {-inch dice, and combine in a bowl with the sauce. When the
chicken is done, toss it with the sauce and cucumber. Taste, and
adjust seasoning if necessary; then, serve hot or cold, garnished
with the cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
