<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9552 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXOTIC-MARTINIS-NYT &LR;      08-18 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXOTIC-MARTINIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, FOR JUST PLAIN GIN AND DRY VERMOUTH  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   First it was cool. Then it got hot. Now it's bloated and out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   The martini, sleekest and suavest of cocktails, has entered the
late-Elvis phase of its once-splendid career, staggering under the
weight of weird garnishes, dazed and disoriented by years of
experimenting with chemicals like Jaegermeister, Chambord and
Kahlua. It's time to enter rehab.
</P>
<P>
   From sea to shining sea, the bars of the United States are
groaning under the weight of horrible martinis. A modern Dante, if
so inclined, could tour the many circles of this cocktail hell and
come up with a truly compelling mixed-drink Inferno.
</P>
<P>
   Moving west to east, the tour might start with the Sea Watch
martini at Lola's in Los Angeles, a beguiling blend of vodka
infused with lime leaves and garnished with edible flowers. It's
worth a quick trip north to Seattle, where Oliver's, the bar in the
Mayflower Park Hotel, offers the Fortunella martini, a blend of
gin, vodka, limoncello and kumquat nectar.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the pilgrim traveling this  &UR; via dolorosa &LR;  will find
the Martini Ranch, a Dallas establishment, whose manager says:
``The sky's the limit. If it's in a martini glass, it's a
martini.'' He ain't a-kiddin, either. One of the bar's standout
cocktails is the Mars Bar martini, a syrupy swirl of dark chocolate
liqueur, white chocolate liqueur, amaretto and Frangelico, served
in a glass whose rim has been dusted in chocolate flecks from
frozen Hershey bars that have been run through a blender.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, in Atlanta, the Martini Club offers each customer
a hellish document: a martini menu that runs to 50 items. These
include a Garden Martini with a garnish of pickled asparagus spear
and a spicy green bean. The bar plans to expand the list to 100
martinis this week.
</P>
<P>
   Following the martini trail north, what do we find? In New York,
capital of glamour and sophistication, it is now possible to raise
a martini glass, hold it to the light and find oneself gazing at an
oyster. ``As you start to drink, the oyster gradually releases its
brine,'' says Jeff Shaffer, the owner of Shaffer City Oyster Bar
and Grill, home of the oyster martini. ``It's like stepping farther
and farther out into the ocean. And in the end, you get to eat the
oyster.''
</P>
<P>
   In a court of law, this plea is known as ``guilty, with an
explanation.'' It's a rather appealing explanation, with a touch of
poetry to it. But in the end, the case comes down to one cold,
squishy fact _ that martini has an oyster in it.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurant trade magazine recently devoted an issue to jazzy
new variations on classic cocktails. The section on martinis
carried the headline ``Improving on Perfection.'' It's a damning
phrase.
</P>
<P>
   For more than century, the martini has held sway in the world of
cocktails by virtue of its purity and simplicity. It has but two
ingredients, gin and vermouth. It can tolerate only one of two
garnishes, an olive or a twist of lemon. The only major alteration
in this formula, the substitution of flavorless vodka for vermouth,
made the drink even simpler.
</P>
<P>
   It was too good to last. As the martini gained a new following
in the last decade, the name became a powerful signifier. The
martini was Frank, Sammy and Dean. It was unfiltered cigarettes,
Vegas and curvy babes. In a messy, confusing world, it stood for
clarity. In a time of collapsing values, it maintained strict
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, everyone wanted a piece of the action. Bars began
serving brightly colored drinks and calling them martinis. Liquor
companies, keen to promote their liqueurs, began inventing garish
recipes and calling them martinis. The self-infatuated lounge
culture worked overtime to develop attitudinal martinis _ drinks
that require extensive annotation to be understood.
</P>
<P>
   A prime specimen of the genre is the ultra-ironic Brazen
Martini, found in ``Atomic Cocktails: Mixed Drinks for Modern
Times'' (Chronicle Books, 1998). The drink, a vodka martini made
with Parfait Amour (a violet liqueur) and garnished with a long
spiral of orange peel, comes with its own user's manual: ``It's one
of those sex-goddess drinks, the kind of martini that calls for a
lipstick print on the glass, a pair of hot pink maribou slippers
and the sound of `Mondo Mambo' pulsing in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine, but once there was a time when real people
simply approached the bar and ordered a dry martini. There were no
set designers, no sound engineers and credits did not roll at the
end of the drink.
</P>
<P>
   The martini in its decadent phase has appalled its most fervent
devotees. Barnaby Conrad 2d, the author of ``The Martini,'' has
often been called on to judge martini contests. It's not always a
pretty sight. ``In one, I remember, a pickled shrimp found its way
into the glass,'' he said. ``It was sort of an Asian angle. Another
one had a candied violet.''
</P>
<P>
   It was cruel but necessary to inform Conrad that the
pickled-shrimp martini, by current standards, was chaste. Until it
changed ownership recently, Fred's Beauty, in Manhattan, sported a
hallucinogenic martini menu that included something called the
Snowman: Finlandia vodka, white chocolate liqueur and a garnish of
three miniature marshmallows. ``That's not just bending the
rules,'' Conrad said. ``That's destroying the whole game.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Donohoe, the self-elected president for life of the
American Standard Dry Martini Club, has calibrated the martini's
downward slide for a decade. ``Everybody's having fun with this
stuff, but real martini drinkers are suffering,'' he said, speaking
on the telephone from club headquarters in Athens, Ohio. ``When you
say you're a martini drinker, that's supposed to mean something,
but all this silliness has degraded the whole concept of the
drink.'' Donohoe has proposed a march on Washington, but serious
martini drinkers are notoriously difficult to organize.
</P>
<P>
   Donohoe and his allies have already lost the gin battle. Most
people drink vodka martinis. And even the most
strict-constructionist martini drinker has to concede that some of
the rococo martinis are rather clever, like the Pixie Stick
martini, a combination of pineapple vodka, sour cherry syrup, fresh
lime and lemon juice. The drink, created at Candy Bar in New York,
is not the kind of cocktail you find in a Raymond Chandler novel,
but it has a certain offbeat appeal. The Lolita, a new addition to
the menu at Grange Hall, calls for 12-year-old Scotch and
hazlenut-flavored sherry, a sly allusion to the real name of
Nabokov's heroine, Dolores Haze. The drink, topped with a mildly
salacious garnish, wins a point or two for inventiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Let no one think for a minute, however, that playing with the
rules does not have consequences. At Liquid Kitty, a bar in West
Hollywood, the signature drink is a vodka martini served with an
unfiltered Camel on the side. ``People put them in the drink by
mistake,'' said Dave Childs, an owner of the bar. ``One guy was
really angry. He returned the drink and said, `This martini is no
good.'''
</P>
<P>
   These days, how would he know?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
