<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MASSAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO SAYS NO NEW MASSAGE PARLORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COOSTANTINOU and GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ From the outside, it sure looks like a brothel _
at least Hollywood's version of one from the Wild West or, if the
awning is to be believed, Gay Paree.
</P>
<P>
   Venus de Milo and her girlfriend, a bathing beauty, are in a
window, a crimson curtain the backdrop for their white alabaster
figures. A gilt rococo lamp with a bosomy prancing belle is the
star attraction of the other window, also festooned with a red
curtain.
</P>
<P>
   Red is the color of the door and the awning and the outdoor
carpet. And in a reminder of the red-light district of yore, red
light bulbs line the perimeter of the windows, beckoning the
passerby.
</P>
<P>
   The sign at this establishment in San Francisco's Tenderloin
district announces that it is Les Nuits de Paris Massage and Sauna.
It is one of 22 massage parlors in the neighborhood. To some
residents, 22 is plenty.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the city's Board of Supervisors agreed, voting
unanimously to place a moratorium on any future parlors in the
Tenderloin district, and to restrict existing ones when there is a
change in ownership. The board will review the bill next week for
final passage.
</P>
<P>
   City planning officials, as well as members of the board's
Housing and Neighborhood Services Committee, say their next focus
will be on limiting parlors in the Mission District and
Bayview-Hunters Point, which they anticipate will get an influx of
new massage parlors once the Tenderloin ban takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   In this city of most anything goes, massage parlors have long
been viewed as magnets of sleaze. The foes contend that some
parlors are fronts for prostitution, drugs and other illegal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between the Civic Center area with its government and
cultural institutions, and the affluence of Nob Hill, Union Square
and the theater district, the Tenderloin neighborhood is struggling
to gain respectability and livability.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood is home to a large Asian population and a
growing number of Hispanics, most of them immigrants, about 5,000
of them children.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Leland Yee, who presented Monday's ordinance, said he
began work on it about a year ago after meeting with Tenderloin
neighbors who viewed the parlors as unsavory.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Amos Brown, a Baptist minister, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over-proliferation of massage parlors and too much massaging
will cause us to be socially and morally flabby,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Yee added that his ordinance was also aimed at bringing some
economic variety to the neighborhood, which has the highest
concentration of massage parlors in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want a diversity of businesses,'' Yee said. ``By putting a
cap on massage parlors, then other businesses can come in.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to banning new parlors, the ordinance would launch a
series of ``good-neighbor'' requirements that would kick in once a
parlor changes ownership, Those requirements include limiting hours
of operation to 7 a.m. to midnight, banning alcohol and prohibiting
sidewalk barkers from soliciting passersby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1615EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
