<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9577 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEEKYTOE-CRAB-ART-3RD     08-18 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEEKYTOE-CRAB-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 DEER ISLE: the rescue.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Oh that's a bay crab,'' he said, ``cancer irroratus. It's a
bycatch of fishing for lobster. I've always wondered about these
crabs because they have so many different names. I suspect sand
crab and rock crab are the same thing.'' And the Latin name for
rock crab is cancer irroratus.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what it is, you and I cannot go to a fish market and
buy a container of peekytoe crab under that name. You can buy Maine
crab, but it could be red or Jonah as easily as peekytoe, or a
combination of all three.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is a trip to a top restaurant, where you will
find it by name on the menu, or a trip to Maine. Along the coast,
look for signs that say ``crab meat'' posted on mailboxes. You may
have found the home of one of the many women who pick crabs for
America's fussiest chefs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The only way to buy peekytoe crab, outside of a restaurant, is
from one of the many crab pickers along the Maine coast,
particularly in the area of the Penobscot Bay and Deer Isle. Look
for signs offering ``crab meat'' posted in front of houses here and
there (these small home businesses do not want their addresses
published, and do not do mail order).
</P>
<P>
   Since there is more peekytoe crab available after August, there
might be more signs in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the crab meat is peekytoe or some other kind, only
the picker knows for sure. The differences are subtle. Peekytoe
crab is more delicate and sweeter than other Maine crab.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the claws, there is no lump meat such as what you
will find in a Jonah crab. The meat is white with tinges of pink _
pickers say peekytoe is pinker than Jonah, although it seems to
vary. Like any other variety, peekytoe should smell sweet and
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The following recipes will work well with other kinds of crab
meat _ Maine crab, stone crab or Dungeness crab in particular _ as
long as it is fresh and not pasteurized. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRAB SALAD WITH ZUCCHINI, TOMATO AND BASIL OIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Jo Jo Time: 40 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the basil vinaigrette: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   12 large basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the salad: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 medium zucchini
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 medium tomatoes, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   { bunch fresh thyme, tied together with kitchen string
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   { cup basil vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces fresh peekytoe or Maine crab meat
</P>
<P>
   rated zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Basil sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine vinaigrette ingredients in a blender. Blend one
minute. Set aside. (Note: after one day the vinaigrette loses it
green color.)
</P>
<P>
   2. Have a bowl of ice water ready. Scrub, trim and slice
zucchini into very thin coins and blanch them in boiling salted
water for one minute. Drain and plunge in ice water for 10 seconds
to stop the cooking.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat olive oil in a large pan over medium high heat and saute
onion and garlic until translucent, about 3 minutes. Add tomatoes
and thyme and cook for 15 minutes. Set mixture aside to cool.
Remove thyme and discard. Season tomato mixture with salt, pepper
and 3 tablespoons of the basil vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a small bowl, season zucchini with salt, pepper and two
tablespoons of the basil vinaigrette. In a medium bowl, season the
crab with salt, pepper, lemon zest and one-third cup of the basil
vinaigrette. On each of four plates, arrange zucchini in a circle,
overlapping slices to form a ring. Place crab in middle of ircle.
Spoon tomato mixture around the zucchini and garnish with basil
sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PEEKYTOE CRAB COCKTAIL WITH SEVRUGA CAVIAR, AVOCADO, &QL; 
GREEN ONION AND LEMON VERBENA VINAIGRETTE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Judson Grill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes, plus 3 hours resting time &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For verbena oil: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups grapeseed oil
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh lemon verbena, washed and dried (available at
farmers' markets)
</P>
<P>
   Zest of one lemon &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For lemon verbena vinaigrette:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons warm chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups verbena oil &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For basic vinaigrette: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the salad: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces baby greens
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces peekytoe or Maine crab meat
</P>
<P>
   2 green onions, thinly sliced white portion; bias cut some of
green portion for garish
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 avocado, peeled and quartered, each quarter sliced into fans.
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce sevruga caviar &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Place all of the verbena oil ingredients in a pot over medium
heat. Gently heat mixture until oil is very warm, about 3 minutes.
Turn off the heat and let rest for 3 hours. Strain and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make the lemon verbena vinaigrette: place yolk, stock, lemon
juice, salt and pepper into a blender. Blend on low speed and
slowly drizzle in the verbena oil. Adjust seasoning; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. Make basic vinaigrette: slowly drizzle olive oil into lemon
juice while whisking. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Dress greens with 2 tablespoons basic vinaigrette. Place in
four large martini glasses.
</P>
<P>
   5. Mix crab meat with white part of the green onions, parsley
and 6 tablespoons of lemon verbena vinaigrette. (There will be
leftover vinaigrette.) Mold crab meat into four ovals and place on
greens. Drizzle the avocado fans with some of the basic
vinaigrette. Place avocado fans into each glass, garnish with green
part of green onion; top with caviar.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
