<HEADER>
A9580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRABBING-NYT &LR;      08-18 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRABBING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICANS CAN'T SEEM TO GET ENOUGH CRAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the volatile stock market makes you dizzy, just be glad
you're not a crabber. Though America's coastline and offshore
waters boast more varieties of edible crabs than any other part of
the world, from year to year supplies plummet, then soar, then
plummet and soar again, for reasons known only to nature.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there never seems to be enough crab to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crab is THE American shellfish,'' said Clark Wolf, the
restaurant consultant. ``It has sweetness and richness. Chefs love
working with it because it's so versatile and easy.''
</P>
<P>
   And diners love crab meat so much that they are abandoning
regional loyalties and want crab cakes, soft-shell crabs and
Dungeness crabs wherever they go. Menu surveys by the National
Restaurant Association found shellfish on 91 percent of American
menus in 1997, with lobster, crab cakes and soft-shell crabs the
top three sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Partly to satisfy this seemingly insatiable hunger for crab in
any and all forms in a range of prices, fish markets and
restaurants are offering more varieties of crab than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike shrimp, crabs are not farmed, so the size of a catch
cannot be controlled or predicted. In this decade, the harvest of
blue crabs, which inhabit the entire Eastern Seaboard and account
for more than half the crabs and crabmeat eaten in this country,
has fluctuated by as much as 25 percent from one year to the next.
(Pfiesteria piscicida, the microbe that killed fish last year in
Cheasapeake Bay, does not seem to have any connection. ``It doesn't
affect crabs,'' said Noreen Eberly, the seafood marketing
specialist of the Maryland Department of Agriculture.)
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, after a long period of abundance, the
Dungeness harvest from the Pacific Northwest was down to about 40
million pounds in the 1996-97 season, compared with 72 million
pounds the year before. And in Alaskan waters, after years of
steady decline, snow crabs made a stunning comeback in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much snow crab all of a sudden that you'll find it
sold in poly bags in Winn-Dixie supermarkets in the Southeastern
states,'' said Laura Fleming, a spokeswoman for the Alaska Seafood
Marketing Institute, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. What are bags of frozen snow crab legs doing in
places like Florida, the state that's known for stone crabs?
Probably the same thing that a salad of Jonah crab, a specialty of
Maine, is doing on the menu at the Water Grill in Los Angeles, or
why Maryland soft-shell crabs are served at Charles Nob Hill in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Crabs, which nature has limited to regional markets for
centuries, have gone national. And with all this choice of flavor
and texture, chefs and consumers are playing favorites _ hence the
rage for peekytoe crabs in top restaurant kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, for example, there were Dungeness crabs for sale at
the Seafood Shop in Wainscott, N.Y., on Long Island's East End,
where local crabbers bring in blue crabs by the bushel. ``Some
people ask for them, so I get them,'' said John Haessler, the owner
of the shop.
</P>
<P>
   Sol Amon, the owner of the Pure Fish Market in Seattle, which
sells wholesale and retail, said that for the last two years, the
demand for Dungeness crabs has exceeded the supply. ``The East
Coast has found out about how great they are,'' he said. His
company ships them all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight shipping and more sophisticated freezing techniques
have helped spread crab varieties around.
</P>
<P>
   In Crisfield, Md., on Chesapeake Bay, John T. Handy Co., the
country's largest producer of soft-shell crabs, has seen the
appetite for those fragile molted crabs, once strictly a regional
specialty, turn ravenous. And instead of being limited to a season
in the Chesapeake area from May to August, soft-shell crabs from
Florida and Louisiana now get things going in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in this part of the country knew what soft shells
were, but now they're becoming popular everywhere,'' said Handy
president Carol Haltaman. ``One of our biggest markets is
California, and we also sell a lot in Chicago. It's like crab
cakes. I'm always amazed at where I'm seeing crab cakes in
restaurants lately.'' Though crab cakes are usually made from blue
crabs (which is why they were a Maryland specialty), Ms. Haltaman
said she had even seen them made from Dungeness crabs in Washington
state.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage to crab cakes is that they can satisfy the taste
for crab for a lot less money. The vast shifts in the numbers of
crabs scooped up from the deep or gathered inshore result in
constantly fluctuating prices. Right now, soft shells are
expensive, but snow crab is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``When lump crab meat gets to be $28 a pound, wholesale chefs
look for other crabs to serve,'' Wolf, the restaurant consultant,
said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, because of the demand (and the prices paid),
fishermen are no longer throwing back some kinds of crabs like
deep-water Jonahs, which had been merely byproducts of lobstering.
In lower Manhattan's Chinatown, live Jonah crabs stroll in tanks
that once held similar but more costly Dungeness crabs. So in
Cantonese restaurants, Jonah, not Dungeness, crabs now arrive at
the table chopped into big hunks, glistening and bright red.
Picking and sucking the sweet white meat of the claws, legs and
back fin glazed with the saline richness of black bean sauce, you
hardly know the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, about 15 years ago, when there was a drastic shortage
of the meatier Alaska king crabs, snow crabs gained a following.
Then, from 1994 to 1996 there were similar reverses for snow crabs,
which, for the moment, have rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Are there new crabs sidling onto the plate? In Maine, spider
crabs, which are very popular in Europe, have long been caught with
lobsters in winter. Rod Mitchell, the owner of Browne Trading, a
seafood dealer in Portland, Maine, has started selling them to
chefs. ``Some chefs know what to do with them and want them,'' he
said. ``They're small and spiny, but they have great flavor.
Everyone wants crab constantly, and these are something different.
And they're only $3 a pound.''
</P>
<P>
   A new flavorful cheap crab? There'll be plenty of takers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
