<SLUG> BC-WHEAT-BEER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEER THAT MADE WHEAT FAMOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ELAINE LOUIE and WILLIAM GRIMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer is the season for wheat beers. Their tartness
distinguishes them: With their lemony tang, they quench the thirst
and rest light on the tongue. At their best, they are fruity with
just a hint of clove spiciness in the aroma. At their
less-than-best, they are so light that their flavor disappears.
</P>
<P>
   We sampled 11 wheat beers, both American and European _ but only
three stood out.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the wheat beer ``is the entry-level
serious beer, the training wheel beer,'' said Bill Owens, publisher
of Beer, the Magazine, in Hayward, Calif. Not surprisingly, their
numbers have more than doubled in the last five years in this era
of microbreweries and brewpubs. Which doesn't mean they are all
successes.
</P>
<P>
   Labels can say wheat (or in German, Weizen) or white (in German,
weiss). By any name, it means a beer made with 40 percent to 60
percent barley, and a lesser percent wheat, Owens said. (Why wheat
beers are called white, however, is curious. One explanation is
that when it ferments, it produces a very pale foam, says the
beer-taster's bible, ``Michael Jackson's Beer Companion'' (Running
Press, 1993.)
</P>
<P>
   Celis White lives up to its label, which promises an authentic
Belgian-style wheat beer brewed with herbs and spices. Belgians
have been brewing wheat beer for 500 years, sometimes spicing it
with orange peel and coriander. In 1991, when brewer Pierre Celis
moved from Hoegaarden, Belgium, to Austin, Texas, he brought with
him a recipe from 1453. He opened Celis Brewery the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Celis White has a fruity and spicy aroma, a full body, and a
spicy lemony flavor. It is gently, but not overwhelmingly tart, and
a 12-ounce bottle sells for around $1.50.
</P>
<P>
   Paulaner Hefe-Weizen Dunkel from Germany, a light amber in
color, has a yeasty aroma, a round malty body, and just the
faintest lemony aftertaste. Paulaner, which was founded in Munich
by monks in 1634, makes both a Hefe-Weizen, a pale straw color
wheat beer, and the Dunkel, a darker version. And it was the latter
which possessed the most flavor. It sells for $2 for a 16.9-ounce
bottle.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Hacker-Pschorr Weisse, a Munich beer made since the
19th century, has a light, clean _ pristine _ wheat aroma, a
feather-light body, but a nice tart bite throughout. A 12-ounce
bottle is $1.75.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
