A9598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-18 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELIGHTING IN A REMOTE CORNER OF FRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERPIGNAN, France _ The French call this western Mediterranean
corner of their country the last frontier. It is a vast expanse of
arid, inhospitable land in southern France bounded by this city,
the city of Carcassonne and the Spanish border.
</P>
<P>
   In the back country leading up into the Pyrenees and in some
former fishing villages along the coast, the old people still speak
Catalan, which has been described as the language of the Roman foot
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   The language may be as close as we will ever come to the Latin
argot of the Roman Empire, but it isn't the only remnant of those
times: vines were almost certainly planted here by the Phoenicians
and later the Greeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the locals like to think that the first commercial wine
producers were the former Roman soldiers who settled here after the
Gallic wars, some 2,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The major wine areas here are Corbieres and Roussillon, but
where one begins and the other ends has always been something of a
mystery. With one exception, their modern wine history is not
particularly edifying.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this century, the region contributed
enthusiastically to the vast ocean of bad wine produced in southern
France, much of it eventually burned off as surplus. The exception
was natural sweet wine.
</P>
<P>
   The Roussillon region still produces some 90 percent of all the
inexpensive sweet wine made in France, and along the country roads
there are stands selling a local selection of Rivesaltes, muscat de
Rivesaltes or Banyuls, a sweet wine made from grenache grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Corbieres and Roussillon have gone through the same changes that
have affected better-known wine regions to the east, like Provence.
Serious winemakers and grape growers, attracted by cheaper land and
assured of some government support, have come south from Bordeaux
and Burgundy to instill new life into these ancient vineyards. The
results have often been spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Paris restaurateurs, seeking to replace the
unconscionably expensive Bordeaux and Burgundies, have turned to
other wines of the southwest. Some of these, from places like
Cahors, Gaillac, Madiran and Irouleguy, have become familiar names,
thanks in part to their reasonable prices and in part to
enthusiastic promoters like the restaurateurs Alain Senderens and
Alain Dutournier.
</P>
<P>
   I've never shared their enthusiasm. To me, the wines always
seemed hard and tannic and deficient in fruit. And at the risk of
henceforth being seated by the kitchen at some these restaurants,
I'll say that some of the wines from Corbieres- Roussillon are much
better.
</P>
<P>
   At their best, they display richness, fruit and roundness rarely
encountered in many of the wines of the Southwest, and none of the
defects usually associated with hot-climate wines _ too much
alcohol, oxydization, dryness.
</P>
<P>
   At the Terrasse de Soleil, an old Catalan farm house converted
into a country inn in the hills above the village of Ceret, I had a
cabernet sauvignon from the Mas Sauvy, a relatively new estate of
some 200 acres at Villeneuve de la Raho, just a few miles south of
Perpignan.
</P>
<P>
   While merely a vin de pays, this was a delightful cabernet that
had been aged 12 months in oak. It would be welcome anywhere in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The next day in Ceret _ where Picasso once lived and worked _ I
stopped at Les Feuillants, one of France's least-known restaurants
with two Michelin stars. Marie-Louise Banyols, the owner, presides
over a wine cellar like few others; her collection of the wines of
the Domaine de la Romanee Conti would make the owner of any
Burgundian three-star restaurant speechless with envy.
</P>
<P>
   She also has a fascinating collection of local wines. Her
assistant sommelier, Christine Cannac, chose a 1993 blend of
mourvedre and syrah from the Domaine du Mas Blanc that had the
richness and elegance of a Rhone wine by Jean-Luc Colombo or the
Perrin family at Chateau Beaucastel.
</P>
<P>
   Next day, at a dockside restaurant in Port Vendres, it was time
for a chilled bottle of a simple local white from the Chateau de
Jau at Cases de Pene, northwest of Perpignan. Probably made from
the macabeo grape, it had twice the character of the thin whites
sold at fish restaurants along the Cote d'Azur.
</P>
<P>
   The Chateau de Jau is one of the few wineries in this part of
France that sells regularly in the U.S. Its Jaja de Jau, a
delightful summer wine, is widely available.
</P>
<P>
   In the great rush to varietal names _ chardonnay, merlot,
cabernet _ the names of individual estates often are ignored. This
presents a particular problem for winemakers from an unfamiliar
region like Corbieres-Roussillon, who cannot get the wine-drinking
public's attention.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps quality does count in the end. If it does, we just
might see wines from this remote corner of France, like those from
Haut-Gleon, Clos des Paulilles or the Chateau la Boutignane, all of
them delicious and all of them relatively inexpensive, on our own
tables.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
