<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THIS KEYBOARD YOUR TYPE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the difference between a Dvorak keyboard and a
regular keyboard?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.E., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: A Dvorak keyboard has a different arrangement of keys that's
designed for easier typing.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional arrangement of keys is called the Qwerty
keyboard in reference to the order of the keys. It was designed by
Christopher Sholes to prevent machine jams by slowing down typists.
Sholes placed the most-used keys farther apart.
</P>
<P>
   In 1932, August Dvorak and William Dealey introduced a new key
layout that was the product of nearly two decades of research.
Although the Dvorak keyboard could be learned more quickly and
enabled faster typing, Qwerty has remained standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of trying to do something worthwhile for the human
race,'' an April 1997 Discover Magazine article quotes Dvorak as
saying. ``They simply don't want to change!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the actor who plays Olivia on ``Sunset Beach'' the same
person who played ``Sister Kate'' on the Odyssey Channel?
</P>
<P>
   _ U.C., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: They're different performers: Olivia Richards is portrayed by
Lesley-Anne Down, whose credits include ``Dallas,'' ``Rough Cut''
and three ``North &AMP; South'' miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   The title character of ``Sister Kate'' was portrayed by
Stephanie Beacham, who has appeared on ``Dynasty,'' ``The Colbys,''
``Beverly Hills, 90210'' and the ``Jackie Collins' Lucky/Chances''
miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   Both performers were born in England: Beacham on Feb. 28, 1947,
in Herefordshire and Down on March 17, 1954, in London.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that Harrison Ford was in ``E.T. The
Extra-Terrestrial''?
</P>
<P>
   _ N.T., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Ford plays a biology teacher in the film, which was written
by his wife, Melissa Mathison.
</P>
<P>
   However, most of his work didn't make the final cut of the 1982
movie. In his biggest remaining scene, Ford's back is visible as he
says, ``the frogs won't feel a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Another famous actor contributed to the film in a
less-than-obvious way. Debra Winger's voice was one of several that
were electronically combined to create E.T.'s speech.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
