<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-DAY ANXIETY A HAIRY SITUATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first day of school has come and gone without a hitch.
Hooray.
</P>
<P>
   My kids actually said it was ``OK.'' I can live with that. We
all know that the first day of most anything is an incredibly
anxious time. The first day on the new job, the first day at boot
camp, the first day as a parent _ all produce a certain degree of
heart pounding and stomach churning.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, all of that stress soon becomes a dim memory as we
adapt to the routine of our new environment. Before long, the
hidden nervousness becomes outright boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Those eight hours that seemed to fly by at first become a third
of your day that just never seems to end. That last half-hour of
your shift creeps by slower than rush hour traffic in Los Angeles _
during a blizzard. Sometimes it takes all of your willpower not to
tear at your clothing and run head-first into the nearest wall over
and over again. Then there's that jerk _ oh, sorry, I'm getting off
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   First days, yes, of course. I only remember one of my many new
beginnings at school. It was the fourth grade. New neighborhood.
New elementary school. Mom dropped me off because I insisted that I
did not need an escort. Subsequently, I could not find my homeroom.
When I finally located it, in a trailer house in the parking lot
behind the school, I was 10 minutes late. The teacher, a lovely
lady with seven chin hairs, had already called the roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who are you?'' she barked when I stumbled through the door
wide-eyed and panting. One glance at her and I wanted to say, ``I'm
from Schick and I brought the razor you ordered.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mom had warned me about being a smart aleck, so I said,
``I'm Mo-nee-ka.'' She glanced at her attendance sheet and told me,
``You must be in the wrong class. I don't have any students by that
name.''
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, I handed her the schedule that I had received in the
principal's office when I registered during the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh Monica,'' she said. ``I thought you said Monique.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's `Mo NEE ka,''' I responded, emphasizing the second
syllable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's spelled like Monica. My sister's kid is named
Monica, and she spells it just like this: M-O-N-I-C-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Give me a break lady, I thought. By then, everyone was staring
at me and I just wanted to crawl into a hole and die along with my
weird name.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, `Mo nee ka,' go sit over there by James.''
</P>
<P>
   `It's Jamal,'' responded my new neighbor. Jamal and I shared a
sympathetic glance. ``Call me Pete,'' he told me.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember much after that. I think we learned geography
and map reading that year, which might explain why I get lost all
the time. I do remember that my homeroom teacher mispronounced my
name the entire year. On several occasions she even called me
``James.'' I stopped correcting her after the first month and just
answered to whatever name she called me.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since the fourth grade, and I'm sure the
emotional scars left from that ordeal have all healed.
</P>
<P>
   However, the last time I saw that teacher, just a couple of
years ago, she had a thick beard and a moustache. Maybe it's a
coincidence, maybe not, but when she asked me about ``James,'' I
swear that thing grew an inch. Hhmmm.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. Call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in care of
the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington, TX
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
