<HEADLINE>
WHERE SANDWICHES AND DESSERTS ARE ALLOWED TO STAND OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At Mitchel London Foods, 542 Ninth Avenue (40th
Street), white walls, blond wood and marble tables provide a
properly neutral setting for the main attraction, the inviting
desserts, sandwiches and quiches.
</P>
<P>
   London, a caterer who also has a shop by the same name at 22A
East 65th Street and who prepares the food for the Parlour Cafe at
ABC Carpet and Home in the Flatiron district, moved his main
kitchen from 42nd Street to the new location and carved out enough
space for a retail shop and cafe.
</P>
<P>
   It is stocked with his rustic apple tarts ($2 each), big peach
and berry pies ($16), sumptuous cupcakes ($2) and fudge marble
brownie tarts ($3.50). On the savory side there are individual
quiches ($3.95) and delicious dilled egg salad sandwiches ($4.95).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the East 65th Street shop, the new operation has a
kitchen, in which London cooks and turns out an excellent hamburger
with fries ($4.95) or a half roast chicken ($8.95). Once things are
a bit more organized, there will be delivery in the neighborhood.
Information: (212) 563-5969. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Chase, an owner of Peaceful Palate, 247A Columbus Avenue
(71st Street), described his life as being ``surrounded by hot
dogs.'' His grandfather, Leonard Pines, founded Hebrew National.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Chase and his partner, Michael Leopold, are also in the hot
dog business, but their hot dogs are made from naturally lean
ranch-bred buffalo meat in a partnership with Frontier Buffalo, a
top purveyor of buffalo meat.
</P>
<P>
   Each hot dog, about 2 ounces, has 70 calories and 4 grams of fat
(compared with 120 to 190 calories and 10 to 17 grams of fat for
many major brands). The sodium content, 190 milligrams, is about
half the usual amount in a hot dog, but the protein, 10 grams, is
higher than the typical 6 to 7 grams.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's hot dogs are very tasty, with good snap when bitten. He
sells them at his minuscule storefront for $2.50 each, including a
roll and choice of toppings.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few weeks they will also be sold retail, for about $4
for a package of five, at the store and at Fairway, 2127 Broadway
(74th Street) and 2328 12th Avenue (132d Street); Balducci's, 424
Avenue of the Americas (Ninth Street); Dean &AMP; DeLuca, 560 Broadway
(Prince Street), and Stew Leonard's in Connecticut, at 100 Westport
Avenue in Norwalk and 99 Federal Road in Danbury.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected from someone whose family created Hebrew
National, Chase plans to introduce kosher Frontier Buffalo hot dogs
in about six weeks, and he is working on corned buffalo and
pastrami. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gourmet Garage, which has three locations _ in SoHo and on the
Upper East and West Sides _ will open a new store in Greenwich
Village, at 117 Seventh Avenue South (Christopher Street). The
space, which has 5,000 square feet and was formerly occupied by
Night Gallery, a restaurant, is expected to be ready in October. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, you do not have to book the Rainbow Room or Le Cirque 2000
for a birthday party for a 2-year-old. Wilton Industries, which
manufactures cake-decorating equipment and party accessories, has a
booklet that describes how to organize birthday parties for
children 1 to 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet, ``Birthdays Are a Piece of Cake,'' provides a
different party idea for each year, with a wealth of tips, games,
menu ideas and suggestions for inexpensive party favors. Its
available by writing to the Consumer Affairs Department, Wilton
Industries, 2240 West 75th Street, Woodridge, Ill. 60517. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
