<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP 100 LIST SPURS RENEWED SUPPORT FOR BOWEN, WEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sound and fury that followed the Modern Library board's
selection of the 100 best novels in English appear now to have
waned, and the list soon may be almost forgotten. But of necessity,
there will be postscripts, and here's one.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a few hundred others who watch the book scene and
work on its periphery, I got in my licks and supposed I was done
with the issue. But three readers _ two women, one man _ contacted
me by letters (the women) and by telephone (the man), all on the
matter of Rebecca West.
</P>
<P>
   My contention was that Dame Rebecca West belonged on the list
with one or another book, identifying two works of hers that I have
read _ ``The Fountain Overflows'' (1936) and ``The Thinking Reed''
(1956). Although distanced by 20 years, they are consecutive in her
scattershot experience as a novelist. (Her first novel appeared in
1912, her seventh and last one in 1966).
</P>
<P>
   In rooting for West, I posed her as superior to a contemporary,
the Anglo-Irish Elizabeth Bowen, who also published seven novels
and did make the list with her 1938 novel ``The Death of the
Heart.'' I've never read that one, but I read her well-praised
``The Heat of the Day'' (1949) and found it clear and antiseptic in
the best Henry James tradition, but lacking the crackling energy of
Rebecca West's prose.
</P>
<P>
   The three respondents endorsed my support of West, but with
rider clauses. One woman believed West definitely should be on the
list because ``The Fountain Overflows'' easily is one of the best
100 novels in its language, but she rated Bowen as the better
novelist overall. The other woman had not read (or heard of)
Elizabeth Bowen, but was adamant that ``The Strange Necessity,'' a
West title from the late 1920s, is a wrongly neglected masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   These two women may or may not be acquainted, but it's a
curiosity that neither wished to be identified in print. The male
caller may not have minded, but he didn't give his name. I became a
listener while he made a solid case for Rebecca West as a great
writer, but not so much a great novelist as a superstar journalist
and political philosopher whose nonfiction works cast a spell.
West's ``The Meaning of Treason'' (1949), published in the
aftermath of the Nuremberg war crimes trial, which she attended,
certainly fortifies that claim.
</P>
<P>
   She was an altogether remarkable woman, this woman who wasn't
Rebecca West at all, but was Cecily Isabel Fairchild, London-born
in 1892 with that well-known silver spoon in her mouth. She was a
precocious feminist, joining at age 16 the Women Writers Suffrage
League. At 19 she became a professional journalist (for ``The
Freewoman)'' and chose Rebecca West as her byline in homage to the
heroine of Ibsen's ``Rosmersholm.''
</P>
<P>
   She was 20 when her approving review of H.G. Wells' ``Marriage''
led to their meeting, which culminated in her 10-year love affair
with an undivorced man who was 26 years her senior. In 1914, she
bore a son, Anthony West, who eventually became a potboiling
novelist and his father's biographer. Some years after the liaison
with Wells, she had a long, childless and apparently placid legal
union with a London banker, but she continued to support Wells'
views against conventional marriage.
</P>
<P>
   For longevity, Rebecca West was the approximate literary
equivalent to Lillian Gish in the performing arts. Ever the
outspoken essayist, she contributed reviews past the 90th birthday
that was her last one. Since her death in 1983 (now I'm quoting
from the ``Oxford Companion to English Literature''), ``The
reputation of her `too intellectual' novels tends to have been
eclipsed somewhat by the aggressive panache of her reportage and
journalism, but feminist reassessments have admired her strong and
unconventional heroines, and her fine craftsmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the ``list tizzy,'' I feel a need to read more
West, and more Elizabeth Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7731. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
