<HEADLINE>
ROASTING SALMON WITH A TASTE OF THE WILD 
</HEADLINE>
   (This is the first of eight columns by Charlie Palmer, the chef and
owner of Aureole in Manhattan. His collaborator is Judith
Choate.)  
 (HLW)  
 By CHARLIE PALMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few years ago, needing some days of fishing to
clear my head, I took my wife, Lisa, and our eldest son, Court, to
the San Juan Islands off the coast of Washington. This part of
America has some of the world's most spectacular natural scenery,
with a series of pristine, forested islands dotting the tranquil
waters of Puget Sound. We stayed in a small cabin on Orcas Island,
where I'd heard that the salmon fishing would be stupendous. It
was.
</P>
<P>
   Early every morning, I went out on a small boat with some local
fishermen. Not a day went by that we didn't catch more than our
fair share of salmon. In fact, one day I caught nine silver salmon
weighing three to seven pounds each, which were perfect for cooking
whole. Good fishing always gets my creative juices flowing. Right
up from the dock I would head to the garden next door to the cabin.
It was overflowing with ripe vegetables, which made it easy to put
together a feast.
</P>
<P>
   Silver salmon is quite fatty, so it didn't seem suited to the
pungent dill and rich sauce that frequently accompany salmon. I
thought that the scent of an aromatic herb like rosemary with its
lemony, pine flavor and a simple roasting over some garden-fresh
vegetables would better highlight my catch.
</P>
<P>
   I wrapped it in very thin slices of lean, home-cured bacon,
which added a wonderful smoky flavor to the succulent fish.
Although this preparation was inspired by wild salmon, the approach
turned out to be fine for the ordinary farmed Atlantic salmon and,
in fact, imparted to it a taste of the wild.
</P>
<P>
   The next day on the island, the leftovers inspired me to create
a composed salad served with a simple sauce of freshly picked
watercress minced into some homemade mayonnaise and a touch of
lemon juice. Either way, served with bottles of the local riesling,
perfectly chilled, this was great American food at its best.
</P>
<P>
   WHOLE ROASTED SALMON WITH ROOT VEGETABLES
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds whole baby turnips, well-washed and trimmed
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds fingerling potatoes, well-washed
</P>
<P>
   1 6-pound whole salmon, cleaned, head and tail on
</P>
<P>
   3 5-inch branches fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 whole lemon, well washed, sliced crosswise
</P>
<P>
   Coarse salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   } pound very thinly sliced premium-quality bacon
</P>
<P>
   6 leeks, white part with a trace of green, split lengthwise and
well washed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon fresh rosemary needles
</P>
<P>
   Cracked black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches arugula, well washed and trimmed, optional
</P>
<P>
   6 fresh lemon slices, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place turnips in boiling salted water to cover. Simmer for 2
minutes, add the potatoes and simmer for 5 minutes longer. Drain
and pat dry. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Rinse salmon and pat it dry.
Place 3 long sprigs of rosemary into the cavity. Cover rosemary
with lemon slices. Season to taste with salt and pepper, noting
that the bacon will add saltiness. Carefully wrap the salmon in
bacon strips, completely covering the top side.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place leeks, along with reserved turnips and potatoes, in a
shallow roasting pan large enough to hold salmon. Sprinkle
vegetables with rosemary needles, and season to taste with salt and
pepper, again noting that the bacon will add saltiness. Lay the
bacon-wrapped salmon on top of the vegetables. Season top with
cracked black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place pan in oven, and roast for about 15 minutes per inch of
thickness of the fish, or until the fish is just opaque by the
backbone. (An instant-read thermometer will register 135 degrees
when inserted into center of fish.)
</P>
<P>
   5. Remove fish from oven, and allow to rest for about 30 minutes
or until the fish and vegetables have come to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   6. Place fish on a serving platter, and surround it with
vegetables. If desired, garnish platter with bunches of arugula or
any other bitter green and a few lemon slices. Serve at room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
