<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9652 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANTAFE-OPERA-960(3Ta     08-18 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTAFE-OPERA-960(3Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SANTA FE, EARTH, SKY AND MUSIC ACHIEVE A HARMONIC CONVERGENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. _ The theater set is simple and inspired. Red
blankets cover nine cots. Five blue cypress trees divide the stage
diagonally. The yellow floor rolls wavelike into the distant
backdrop, where a violet sky sets off a silhouette of black
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Credit designer Antony McDonald with the cots, trees and
flooring for the Santa Fe Opera's 1998 production of Berlioz's
``Beatrice and Benedict.'' Credit Mother Nature with the backdrop.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour before the house lights dimmed, opera lovers milled
about Stravinsky Terrace, watching the sun set behind the Jemez
Mountains, its last rays turning the underbellies of the clouds hot
pink. To the east, a full moon rose over the Sangre de Cristo
peaks, cast lilac in the dusk.
</P>
<P>
   Two shows for the price of one.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere do opera and creation mingle so harmonically as the New
Mexican high desert. Since 1957, the outdoor Santa Fe Opera has
been known as much for its sublime locale as its artistic merit and
adventuresome spirit. Cradled in a natural amphitheater 10 minutes
north of the city, the opera delights in its relationship with the
land and sky. Lightning punctuates arias. Chilly evening breezes
toy with the sopranos' skirts.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the summer's frequent rainstorms regularly
doused patrons. The theater's original architecture left almost all
seats open to the elements, making umbrellas as prevalent as opera
glasses. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen million dollars' worth of renovations this year bought
not only a new theater, minus the stage, but also a roof that
covers the entire audience. The revamped building _ partly inspired
by the nearby Puye Cliff Dwellings and suggesting Japanese design _
has generally received positive nods in the press. And most
opera-goers, when asked, expressed satisfaction with the changes.
But certain traditionalists are appalled by the new barrier between
the music and the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, as with every other part of Santa Fe, (the opera) has
been sold to the tourists,'' wrote Santa Fe critic and writer John
Pen La Farge on the opinions page of the daily Santa Fe New Mexican
last September. ``After all, it is not we who complain of rain; we,
as we always have, find such to be part of the experience, and
prepare for it with gusto and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   True or not, attending an opera in Santa Fe remains a special
event, for neophytes and connoisseurs, locals and tourists. Forget
the stereotypical images of haughty opera patrons in black tie. The
SFO takes its cues from Santa Fe itself: earthy, spiritual, a
little bit funky. Where else would you find opera patrons wrapped
in blankets to ward off the cold desert air, or bundled in parkas,
or wearing baseball caps?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just part of the Santa Fe experience _ a night like
this, this beautiful amphitheater out here, the views,'' says Paul
Roth, tailgating Santa Fe-style with wife Lucy before the
performance of ``Beatrice and Benedict.'' Seated on lawn chairs,
they dine on marinated chicken and spinach salad. The Roths, former
Dallas residents who retired to a home only minutes from the opera,
attend two or three of the five productions each summer.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every season includes two favorite operas, an opera by
Strauss, one premiere and one unusual or cutting-edge production.
In 1996, the SFO gave Thomas Picker's ``Emmeline'' its world
premiere. In 1970, the American premiere of Luciano Berio's
controversial ``Opera'' had patrons arguing its merits during the
performance. ``Opera's'' male nudity prompted one woman to threaten
to call the police.
</P>
<P>
   This night's performance puts a bit of a feminist twist on the
adaptation of Shakespeare's ``Much Ado About Nothing.'' In just a
couple of hours, native Texan Susan Graham will sweep onstage as
Beatrice in a red velvet riding coat and trousers, and launch into
melodius banter with Benedict, played and sung by Gordon Gietz. She
will tote a rifle and playfully swing a dead rabbit in a friend's
face _ not exactly ladylike.
</P>
<P>
   Even in English, opera can be difficult to dissect, but tonight
the words are less crucial than the music. The elegant curve of the
theater ceiling draws the principals' clear, rich voices up and
over the audience, and nearly lifts you from your seat. Song here
is a mortal rhapsody that complements the heavens.
</P>
<P>
   Opera may not be for everyone, but fans of the SFO say it's more
than just opera. Think of it as embracing the relationship between
earth, sky, art and humanity. Think about natural beauty vs. the
beauty we create.
</P>
<P>
   Or think about it this way: You can wear jeans.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   ONE MAN'S VISION: New Mexico was literally a cure for John
Crosby. During high school, chronic asthma prompted doctors to send
him west from Connecticut, and for the 1940-41 academic year,
Crosby attended school in Los Alamos, 15 miles west of Santa Fe. He
fell in love with the place.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby returned east, fought the war in Europe and attended Yale
and then Columbia University, where opera became his passion. In
1956, he conceived the idea for an outdoor summer opera festival in
Santa Fe. In addition to its beauty, he reasoned, Santa Fe had
fewer mosquitoes and less rain and air traffic than the outdoor
facilities back east.
</P>
<P>
   With a $200,000 loan from his father, Crosby bought the land and
built the opera in a natural amphitheater off the Tesuque Highway.
(Acoustician Jack Purcell determined the exact spot by firing a gun
at various points on the property and listening to the echo.)
</P>
<P>
   The original house seated 480 on wooden benches. Although the
repertory would extend from the traditional to the unorthodox, all
operas would be sung in English to make them more accessible, and
ticket prices would start at $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   In its first season, the opera gained a reputation for its
democratic setup (no one person maintained star status), its
penchant for physically appealing performers and its youth _ almost
everyone involved was under 35.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby, then 30, not only conducted, he also passed out
blankets, directed parking and fixed the plumbing. The first
night's performance of ``Madame Butterfly'' sold out, as did the
next five performances. Maestro Igor Stravinsky sat in during
rehearsals of his own work, ``The Rake's Progress,'' and developed
a close relationship with Crosby that lasted until Stravinsky's
death.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism in Santa Fe boomed, and the opera estimated that 70
percent of its audience that first season had never attended live
opera before.
</P>
<P>
   By 1958, the opera world still was not wholly convinced of Santa
Fe's legitimacy. ``There is no opera worth speaking of outside New
York City,'' the Metropolitan Opera's general manager, Rudolf Bing,
told the press. By the end of that same month, Bing had agreed to
serve on the SFO's Artistic Council.
</P>
<P>
   On July 27, 1967, the Santa Fe Opera burned to the ground. The
season continued in a school gymnasium, and eventually a new,
larger theater replaced the old, serving through the summer of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   In 42 seasons, the SFO has hosted eight world premieres and more
than two dozen American premieres. Its acclaimed apprentice program
for singers has graduated such opera luminaries as Sherrill Milnes,
Judith Blegen, Samuel Ramey, Ashley Putnam, Kurt Streit and James
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   The apprentice technician program accepts 60 young people a
season, and the opera's community-outreach programs serve tens of
thousands of children and adults every year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Santa Fe Opera is a major, major contributor to the
popularity of opera in the United States. It's a player on the
world stage,'' notes Fort Worth Opera general director Bill Walker.
``Santa Fe is a destination opera. You go there, and you know in
four or five days you're going to see three or four operas you want
to see. It's a thing that has become a tradition with people who
really enjoy opera and want to see what's on the cutting edge.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Walker, a principal baritone with the Metropolitan
Opera, performed in ``La Traviata'' at Santa Fe, with Crosby
conducting. The opera founder, Walker says, ``has been a visionary
from the very beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   In September 2000, the 72-year-old Crosby will pass the baton to
Richard Gaddes, currently the opera's associate general director.
Gaddes, a graduate of England's Trinity College of Music, was 26
when Crosby asked him to move to New Mexico from London and join
the Santa Fe Opera as artistic administrator. Despite the initial
culture shock, Gaddes stayed from 1969 to 1978. He moved to
Missouri in the late '70s after co-founding the Opera Theatre of
St. Louis in 1976, but in 1988 he returned to Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the SFO's identity comes from the esprit created among
the artists, Gaddes emphasizes. The artists often move to New
Mexico for the season, and they ``bring their families here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part holiday, part work,'' adds Gaddes. ``And why do the
artists come? Not for the money, because our fees don't compete
with the fees that are paid elsewhere. We're here for some reason
other than the big bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the opera's $10 million budget this year, ticket sales from
the 40 performances will generate about half. (Among opera
companies, that's considered quite good, Walker says; the Fort
Worth Opera takes in between 30 and 40 percent of its $1.4 million
budget through tickets, he says.) The remainder comes from
corporate, foundation and private donors, the vast majority coming
from outside New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   As do most of the patrons. While one-third of the opera's
audience lives in New Mexico, two-thirds come from the 49 other
states and 24 foreign countries. They range from a group of Swedes
traveling to see the American premiere of Ingvar Lidholm's ``A
Dream Play,'' based on the play by August Strindberg, to the 28
members of the Opera Lovers of Midland, here to see hometown girl
Susan Graham star as Beatrice.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   On average, patrons fill 90 percent of the opera's 2,126 seats
during any given performance.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Santa Fe's mission is to put up cutting-edge operas
other companies cannot or will not present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Fe's greatest image,'' Walker says, ``is that they have
no fear.'' And Gaddes acknowledges the opera's freedom in this
regard. ``We draw a sophisticated audience from elsewhere, and
frankly it's our niche. It's what we do, and it's what we've done
since 1957.''
</P>
<P>
   RANCH WITH A DIFFERENCE: Director John Copley is running late.
He rushes from the administrative office to the outdoor rehearsal
space called The Sombra, where two of his apprentices practice a
scene from ``The Barber of Seville.'' The demonstrative Copley
mouths along with the libretto and bounces on the balls of his feet
to the intermittent piano accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   The British director has spent his past 12 summers with Santa
Fe. This season he directs ``Madama Butterfly'' and the renowned
apprentice program. Today and on Aug. 23, the 40 apprentices will
perform a series of scenes before an audience that includes arts
administrators from around the country in search of new talent.
</P>
<P>
   The opera's ranch lies a short hike down the road behind the
theater. Here, the artists and apprentices have use of four
rehearsal halls, practice rooms, a cantina serving fresh-baked
scones for breakfast, even a swimming pool. (For instance, there's
the ``Magic Flute's'' Prince Tamino taking a dip.) During the
daytime, fluid singing voices wash over the grounds, emoting love,
rage and sorrow in various European languages.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe's ecological conscience extends to its opera as well.
The parking lot features non-sky-polluting lights. The huge sloped
roof catches thousands of gallons of rain each summer. And an
on-site wetlands cleanses the waste water, which irrigates the
shady flower-strewn grounds.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Thursday night, tailgaters begin filling the opera
parking lot two hours in advance of the performance. They include
opera virgins such as 20-year-old Ken Brodeur and 25-year-old Cindy
Zoldi, interns at the Los Alamos Laboratory this summer, eating
cheese and crackers in the back of a sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way opera needs to be for everyone,'' Brodeur
insists.
</P>
<P>
   And they include the staff of Jones Intercable from Albuquerque,
being wooed by a prospective client with a catered dinner under a
white tent featuring bouquets of red roses and glasses of fume
blanc.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the serious opera buffs attending the
weeklong seminar ``Opera: Drama, Music and Meaning,'' led by the
enthusiastic Mary Kime, a former music history professor at the
University of Denver. Kime's pupils attend four operas in a week
and critique each production the morning after.
</P>
<P>
   ``The drama of the setting is so spectacular that already you're
on another level when you come here,'' says Kime, who has been
leading groups here for 15 summers. ``You're looking at the
mountains, and as the night progresses you have the addition of all
the wonderful things that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalls a production of ``Don Giovanni'' when, at the moment
the title character is condemned to hell, a bolt of lightning shot
through the clouds. Walker was in the audience for that, too. ``It
was wonderful,'' he recollects.
</P>
<P>
   Of the new theater, Kime says ``It's spectacular. Now the
acoustics are the best they've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated nearby, eating dinner on a parking lot curb, Jon and
Julie Thomas of Lubbock, Texas, remember their first visit to the
Santa Fe Opera in 1975 as part of a graduate-level class. ``It was
cold and rainy, and we had standing-room-only tickets,'' Julie
Thomas says. ``It was an exciting experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you can see the lights in the mountains and you can
feel the breeze coming through the theater,'' adds her husband. ``I
like that. I like the outdoors.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before 9 p.m., the crowd begins filtering into the
amphitheater, packing the gift shop, mingling on the Plaza Cibola,
already wrapping themselves in quilts. ``Does it look like a flying
boat to you?'' one woman asks a friend, staring at the vast upward
sweep of the theater's pine ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about doing opera outdoors,'' muses
marketing director Tom Morris, wearing one of the night's rare
tuxedos. ``There's a barrier that is taken away.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunset over, the full moon escorts latecomers to their seats;
lights in Los Alamos and Pojoaque twinkle in the distance; and
Santa Fe settles in for another night at the opera.
</P>
<P>
   As Beatrice sings her final aria _ admitting to herself she
loves Benedict after all _ the Big Dipper peeks under a corner of
the theater roof. Maybe the stars miss their view of the audience
as much as some in the audience miss the stars.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they're just happy to listen.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
