<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STONE WALL CRUMBLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ So now the world knows for sure what most of us had
suspected all along _ the president of the United States, the most
politically powerful man on the globe, is a lying lecher.
</P>
<P>
   What can we do about it? Does it matter?
</P>
<P>
   Does it say something sad about us as a nation if we simply
ignore the immorality of our elected leader? Or is public
humiliation a sufficient penalty for private misdeeds that posed no
constitutional crisis?
</P>
<P>
   There are no easy answers to those questions.
</P>
<P>
   An overnight instant USA Today-CNN-Gallup Poll after President
Clinton's partial confession Monday night suggests that a majority
of the public does not want to kick the president out of the high
office to which he was twice elected. Subsequent television
interviews also indicate a strong public inclination to drop the
whole subject and let Hillary deal with him.
</P>
<P>
   The president's personal favorability ratings dropped to 40
percent from 60 percent, but 72 percent of those surveyed said it
would be in the national interest for Clinton to finish the
remainder of his term. Only about a quarter favored impeachment or
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   The president himself shows no sign of giving up. He may be
cornered but he is still a fighter. In the past, that fighting
spirit has helped him to rebound from potential political disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And there's a lot left to fight about. We are not rid of the
Monica Saga yet. The probe of the president's indiscretions
continues. We do not know what evidence of misbehavior Independent
Counsel Kenneth Starr has accumulated or how the president
testified Monday before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not answer all the questions from prosecutors,
leaving him vulnerable to yet another grand jury summons. And he
now has a vast credibility problem that may handicap his ability to
govern effectively, which in turn could undercut his high
job-performance approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, public opinion can be fickle. Those who live by the
polls can die by them.
</P>
<P>
   Voters may eventually turn against the president when they learn
more than he has yet told them about his 18-month dalliance with
former White House intern Monica Lewinsky. When they have had ample
time to ruminate on the enormity of his deceit, they may conclude
he's become an intolerable political liability.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Starr remains the least popular public figure
in the country. A majority of voters believe he is unfairly
hassling the president for partisan motives, which in the past has
helped immunize Clinton against public outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton struck a combative tone in his statement that indicates
he will go down fists flailing, if he goes down at all. He meant to
warn those who are already writing him off as a lame-duck president
that they are being vastly premature. His usually cuddly persona
was replaced by a chilly, even cold, veneer.
</P>
<P>
   In many of his remarks he angrily attacked the legitimacy of
Starr's four-year probe, which Clinton and his wife see as a
partisan vendetta. This approach had its downside. It so irritated
Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch that he called
Clinton a ``jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's statement was a signal that he will not meekly
capitulate if the House Judiciary Committee decides to hold
impeachment hearings based on Starr's final report, expected to be
issued soon. The committee can recommend impeachment, censure or a
mild reprimand _ or clear the president's name.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer weight of the scandal and the inability to reach
closure so long as Clinton is in office may ultimately force his
resignation to rescue his party and elevate Vice President Al Gore
before the 2000 presidential election. But the president is clearly
not contemplating that yet.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Clinton finally conceded that despite his
previous denials he indeed had indulged in an improper relationship
with Monica Lewinsky. But he bristled defensively rather than seek
sympathetic understanding. And he was conspicuously not forthcoming
about his actions.
</P>
<P>
   He made the technical argument that he had been ``legally
accurate'' in prior statements and never told anyone to lie, but he
skipped the details that might have convinced us he was really
sorry and would not betray our trust again.
</P>
<P>
   In all, it was an unsatisfactory performance.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next is anyone's guess. No matter how many people
say they are bored by this story, the appetite for it has not been
sated.
</P>
</TEXT>
