<HEADER>
A9783 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BENTO-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     08-18 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENTO-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIMPLE MENUS FOR THE BENTO BOX': TREASURE-CHEST DINING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Simple Menus for the Bento Box'' (William Morrow, $25),
Ellen Greaves and Wayne Nish have created their own kind of
cooking. That is, food colored with Asian, French and American
influences and designed to be served Japanese-style in a bento box.
</P>
<P>
   This book is not a treatise arguing that bento box meals are
healthier, spiritually sound or will improve your life. The authors
simply appreciate the esthetic qualities of the bento box meal and
have adapted their style to its spatial parameters.
</P>
<P>
   A bento box is a lacquered wooden box with four small
compartments and was derived from a farmer's seed box. Earlier this
century, Japanese cooks began using it to make a bento, or boxed
meal, with a different dish in each compartment, like steamed fish,
sticky rice or fried vegetables. In Ms. Greaves and Nish's bento
boxes, however, you may be alternating bites of grilled ham and
cheese and herb-steamed swordfish.
</P>
<P>
   Their real emphasis is visual. The pictures, taken by Nish, who
is the chef at March in Manhattan, beautifully represent the
authors' minimalist style, which, they write, incorporates ``an
interactivity of line, shape and color.'' There are clear
directions on how to arrange each dish, making it easy for home
cooks to replicate. Steamed sticky rice, for instance, is wrapped
in plastic wrap, molded into disks and the edges pressed with
chopsticks to make a flower shape.
</P>
<P>
   The attention to presentation provides a pleasant departure from
cooking, piling food on a plate and eating. It has a way of slowing
down the meal. Or as Ms. Greaves, the chef at Tea Box in Manhattan,
and Nish write, ``Through your artful effort, you can transform the
simple bento box into a treasure chest for every person at your
table.'' That is overly optimistic, perhaps, but when I cooked a
bento meal from the book, my guests did take time to remark on the
food before digging in.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes are arranged into four-dish menus. And the one I
tried _ chicken nuggets with spicy cucumber, curried acorn squash
with pecans, Japanese rice with salted peanuts and scallions, and
poached shrimp with navy beans, celery and saffron _ was a big hit.
</P>
<P>
   Separate, the dishes had blunt, candid flavors; but together,
the meal was well balanced with sweetness, acidity and spice. The
recipes were easy and worked well, but they made more than
indicated. The four bento dishes, meant to serve four people,
easily fed five.
</P>
<P>
   This is the kind of book you would use to add a twist to a
casual dinner with friends, much in the way you might use a fondue
pot or make fajitas. And it's not a bad excuse to go shopping for
the small, elegant dishes and a few bento boxes.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN NUGGETS WITH SPICY CUCUMBER
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Simple Menus for the Bento Box'' by Ellen Greaves
and Wayne Nish (William Morrow, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 seedless cucumber
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon Vietnamese chili paste or Tabasco, more to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons champagne vinegar or white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 quart peanut or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound skinless, boneless chicken breast or thigh
</P>
<P>
   Flour for dusting
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   1 cup panko or dried breadcrumbs, more if needed.
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut cucumber lengthwise into quarters. Cut quarters into
1/8-inch slices on an angle. In a medium bowl, combine cucumber,
chili paste and vinegar, and toss well. Season with salt, pepper
and chili paste. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a 2-quart saucepan, heat oil to 350 degrees. Cut chicken
into 1-inch cubes, and season with salt and pepper. Dredge chicken
cubes in flour, dip them in beaten egg and roll in the bread crumbs
to coat evenly. Add half the chicken to the oil, and fry until
crust is golden brown, about three minutes for breast meat, five
minutes for thigh. Using a slotted spoon, remove chicken from oil,
and drain on paper towels. Repeat with remaining chicken.
</P>
<P>
   3. In each of four small bowls, place a small tight mound of
cucumbers. Divide chicken nuggets among bowls, propping them
against cucumbers. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 small servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
