<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9808 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PATHETIC-SPEE     08-18 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PATHETIC-SPEECH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CLINTON, AMERICA NEEDS `A VALIUM OF SORTS' ... 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Eastern time zone or Canada, call BOB FARNELL
at 1-800-535-4425. Or send a fax to him at (717) 646-4850.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Central time zone, call CONNIE WHITE at
1-800-444-0267. Or fax her at (816) 822-1444.
 &HT;    _ If you're in the Pacific or Mountain time zones or in Latin
America, call OLIVIA VASQUEZ at (310) 996-0075. Or fax her at (310)
996-0089.
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1998 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   With the exception of Richard Nixon's televised resignation
announcement on another August night 24 years ago, Bill Clinton's
Monday night confession was the most unsettling and pathetic
presidential address I've witnessed in my lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   He is a liar.
</P>
<P>
   A cheat.
</P>
<P>
   A conniver.
</P>
<P>
   A manipulator.
</P>
<P>
   And we love him.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you're dancing the dance of vindicated Clinton-bashers
today or weeping tears of disappointment because your dreams of
Camelot II have been forever tarnished, it really won't affect the
business of the country. The reality is, we have a pathological
liar in the White House _ and yet the great majority of the
citizenry doesn't mind because he's leading the country through
some of the most peaceful and prosperous times in our nation's
history.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no impeachment proceedings, no criminal
indictments, no resignation. Bill Clinton will finish his second
term and he'll have a prosperous post-presidency: sitting on the
boards of various companies; writing books; giving speeches at
$100,000 a pop; advising other presidents; maybe even pitching in
to build a house or two with Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing _ nothing _ Clinton can do will erase the word
``philandering'' from the first paragraph of his obituary. And that
of course is no one's fault but his own.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Approximately three seconds after Clinton finished speaking
Monday night, I received a call from a female friend who's about
the same age as Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Clinton is so [goshdarn] sexy!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I think she was kidding.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Can you believe that sign-off from Clinton? He sounded exactly
like Johnny Carson!
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for watching, and good night,'' said the president.
</P>
<P>
   You almost expected to see him stand up and shake hands with the
producer as the band kicked in with some melancholy goodbye music.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether he's delivering a heartfelt tribute to the Americans who
were killed in the embassy bombings or confessing an extramarital
dalliance on live prime-time TV, Clinton is astonishingly assured
and polished _ rarely if ever stumbling on a line or committing any
sort of verbal misstep.
</P>
<P>
   There's something amiss in a world in which Academy
Award-winning actors can't give acceptance speeches without
screwing up every other line, while the president of the United
States is a one-take wonder.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best line I heard from the hours of pre-game talk spread across
the dial came from Bob Woodward of the Washington Post, who
interrupted the hyperkinetic James Carville on ``Larry King Live''
and said, ``Let me ask you a question that will serve as a Valium
of sorts ...''
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every so often I'm asked why I've never wanted to work in
Washington, considered by many journalists to be the ultimate
career destination.
</P>
<P>
   My reasons are myriad. But from now on when that question is
posed, I'm going to refer to the following verbatim transcript from
Monday morning's press conference with White House spokesman Mike
McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If the president makes a speech tonight, will the first lady
and Chelsea be with him?
</P>
<P>
   McCurry: As I've said earlier, I haven't heard any plans to that
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Will they be sitting there if he's talking about oral sex,
for instance? That would be embarrassing for them.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry: I think it's embarrassing to hear the question posed
here.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Well, it's embarrassing to have the accusation on the record.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry: Anything else?
</P>
<P>
   Q. Russia?
</P>
<P>
   McCurry: OK, let's do Russia . . .
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Presidents who, according to most historians, fooled around:
Jefferson, Franklin D. Roosevelt, Kennedy and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents, who, according to most historians, didn't fool
around: Hoover, Nixon, Ford and Carter.
</P>
<P>
   I guess job performance really is separate from other types of
performance.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You had to love all those live shots of the White House we saw
Monday during the wall-to-wall coverage on the 24-hour news
channels. There were so many lingering shots of the White House
that I half-expected it to blow up a la ``Independence Day.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more entertaining than the live shots of
buildings are those arrival-departure deals, covered with a
breathless anticipation that used to be reserved for Apollo
flights. Yep, there's nothing more thrilling than watching a
newsmaker entering or exiting a nondescript sedan and ignoring the
throngs of reporters who are shouting questions like ``What are you
going to say in court?'' and ``Who did your hair?''
</P>
<P>
   Just once I'd like to see someone pull up in a Humvee, or maybe
a Chevy Blazer equipped with a $25,000 stereo system blaring out
the latest from the Wu Tang Clan. For variety's sake.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We keep hearing about ``improper'' or ``inappropriate'' sexual
relations between Clinton and Lewinsky. Just wonder: What would
constitute ``proper'' or ``appropriate'' relationships between the
wo? Signed notes of consent from her mother and his wife?
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another example of actual developments far outstripping
anything imagined in recent political satires such as ``Primary
Colors,'' ``Wag the Dog'' and ``Bulworth,'' the Clintons' minister
was seen on TV this weekend, comparing our president to one of the
great Old Testament figures.
</P>
<P>
   From the Rev. J. Philip Wogaman: ``King David did something that
was much worse (arranging the death of his lover Bathsheba's
husband) than anything that President Clinton is alleged to have
done. And King David, if I read my Bible correctly, was not
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he didn't have an intern program, either.
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I don't know where Gennifer Flowers, Paula Jones, Kathleen
Willey, Lucianne Goldberg or Linda Tripp were Monday night, but
something tells me at least some of them must have had trouble
seeing the TV screen, what with all the champagne bottles that must
have been uncorked.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) can be heard on the
``Media Creatures'' show, which airs daily in Chicago from 10 a.m.
to 2 p.m. on WMVP-AM (1000) and appears Tuesday and Thursday at
7:55 a.m. on WFLD-TV's ``Fox Thing in the Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (A daily columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, Roeper has also
written for TV Guide, Spy, Playboy, Chicago magazine and many other
publications, and has appeared as a guest on ``Nightline'' and
``Oprah.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
