<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9820 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-KIDNAPPER-0819     08-18 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-KIDNAPPER-0819-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KING OF MEXICAN KIDNAPPERS, KNOWN AS THE 'EAR CUTTER,' IS
CAPTURED
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ He is Mexico's most notorious suspected criminal,
a former cop and car thief who graduated to kidnapping -- and made
millions by slicing off his victims' ears and mailing them to
families to let them know he meant business.
</P>
<P>
   But now Daniel Arizmendi, known as Mexico's infamous ``ear
cutter,'' is in custody, judicial authorities announced here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day of bad luck,'' Arizmendi told Mexico's Television
Azteca, as he was being transported to a maximum-security jail in
Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi's capture late Monday evening north of Mexico City is
the culmination of an intensive nine-month manhunt for a criminal
who came to symbolize cruelty, corruption and ineptitude on the
part of Mexican authorities.
</P>
<P>
   His capture represents ``a great effort in the fight against
impunity,'' said Samuel Gonzalez, federal director of Mexico's
organized crime unit.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez celebrated Arizmendi's downfall in a press conference
Tuesday in Mexico City with Jorge Madrazo, Mexico's Attorney
General.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo said the arrest was made possible with the help of
Mexico's Law Against Organized Crime, which offered guarantees of
witness protection and gave several judges the power to authorize
extensive wire-taps of private telephone conversations among
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnapping has become a virtual industry in Mexico in recent
years, second only to Colombia in magnitude. Arizmendi and his
network of family and friends -- including his wife, a former nurse
who may have supervised the severing of victims' ears -- were
considered among the most brutal and successful in their field.
</P>
<P>
   Police have linked Arizmendi's gang to as many as 200
kidnappings, some of which resulted in killings. In June, police
seized more than $5 million in pesos and U.S. dollars from the
family, as well as more than two dozen homes and radio equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Arizmendi, reportedly a former police officer in
Morelos state south of Mexico City, narrowly escaped capture during
a raid in May that netted his eldest son and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   On June 30, Daniel's brother, Aurelio, was wounded and captured
after police who were trailing him closed in and engaged him in a
shoot-out.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, a man reported to be Arizmendi's lawyer, Jose Angel
Vivanco -- a former Judicial Police commander -- was recently
arrested. Newspapers published a photo they obtained of Vivanco
posing with Arizmendi in a macho stance while holding automatic
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Mexicans are particularly outraged at reports of the widespread
police protection that Arizmendi enjoyed in various Mexican states.
Putting cops on his payroll gave Arizmendi critical support that
helped him elude justice while amassing as much as $40 million in
ransom money.
</P>
<P>
   The former chief of an anti-kidnapping unit in the state of
Morelos has also been arrested and is suspected of assisting
Arizmendi.
</P>
<P>
   When Arizmendi was captured Monday in Nacaulpan, a district in
the state of Mexico, police also detained 10 adults who are
suspected accomplices along with six minors.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo said authorities have learned that the son of a
well-known businessman, Raul Nieto del Rio, was killed Aug. 6
during an attempt by the Arizmendi gang to kidnap him on a highway.
</P>
<P>
   Although they had killed their victim, gang members were
pretending Nieto del Rio was still alive and they were attempting
to collect $15 million in ransom from the family, Madrazo said.
</P>
<P>
   A man who claimed to be Arizmendi recently called Reforma
newspaper in Mexico City and gave detailed accounts of his
kidnappings and the gruesome practice of severing victims' ears.
</P>
<P>
   In published reports, the man claiming to be the kidnapper said
he was addicted to the money he earned through his bloody
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he feared ``jail and poverty,'' but not death.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
