<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-PRIVACY     08-18 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-PRIVACY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON'S COMPLAINT ABOUT INVASION OF HIS PRIVACY STRIKES A
CHORD WITH MANY AMERICANS
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By calling for a halt to ``prying into personal
lives'' in his address to the nation, President Clinton may have
struck a carefully chosen chord with a populace increasingly fed up
with invasions of their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Americans are increasingly tired of intrusions of all
kinds _ everything from telemarketing calls during dinner to
unwanted e-mail. And they're fearful that computers and the
Internet have provided prying eyes an easy look at formerly private
aspects of their lives _ from medical and financial records to
their phone logs and purchasing preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are feeling there is no such thing as privacy in this
era of computers and credit card numbers,'' said Martin Pollner, a
former Treasury Department official who currently deals with
privacy issues as an attorney in New York City. ``I think the
president touched upon a raw nerve'' by demanding an end to
investigation of his private life.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the prying into Clinton's personal life stems from what
the president acknowledged Monday night in his nationally-televised
address as an ``inappropriate'' relationship with former White
House intern Monica Lewinsky. Independent counsel Kenneth Starr has
delved into such highly-sensitive areas as Clinton's sex life in an
attempt to determine whether the president committed perjury or
obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   After admitting to an improper relationship with Lewinsky,
Clinton said it was now a family matter and no longer a concern to
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is private and I intend to reclaim my family life for my
family. It's nobody's business but ours,'' Clinton said. ``Even
presidents have private lives. It is time to stop the pursuit of
personal destruction and the prying into personal lives and get on
with our national life.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, presidents are public figures and subject to a
different degree of scrutiny than private citizens. But some
experts say Clinton's plea to be left alone resonates with those
who face much less traumatic intrusions on a daily basis.
</P>
<P>
   Karlyn Bowman, who studies public opinion for the American
Enterprise Institute, said the ``stop the prying'' segment was one
of several parts of a speech that appeared crafted to conform with
polling data. Bringing up the cost of Starr's investigation and
emphasizing the need to ``move on'' were others, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the privacy issue, a June national poll of adults from 1,014
households, sponsored by Ohio University and Scripps Howard News
Service found that 81 percent of the respondents doubted the
security of their personal information including credit ratings,
medical histories and financial records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Polls show people don't want the media delving too deeply into
private lives of not just this president but other public
officials,'' said Bowman. ``Interestingly, most people say they
don't want to know this personal kind of information but they think
their neighbors do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Schwartz, policy analyst for the non-profit Center for
Democracy and Technology, a Washington-based advocacy group
concerned with Internet issues, said the Clinton administration
``has has been focusing on privacy already. They know it's a
popular issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore last month endorsed an Electronic Bill of
Rights and told the audience that ``You should have the right to
choose whether your personal information is disclosed.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveys show that concerns about privacy are the number one
reason that people stay off the Internet and also the number one
worry of people on the Internet, said Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's message on privacy ``probably had a receptive
audience,'' said Harold Krent, a professor at Kent College of Law
in Chicago and author of an article titled ``Diaries and
Databases'' that deals with privacy issues. ``People do recognize
that there should be a realm of self that is protected from prying
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Just giving Starr a drop of blood to test for DNA material in
the semen alleged to have been on Lewinsky's dress, said Krent,
would have enabled investigators to find out all sorts of unrelated
genetic information about him.
</P>
<P>
   However, others doubted the effectiveness of Clinton's plea on
prying.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Clinton is hoping to tap into some nationwide passion for
privacy, I don't think it's there,'' said Robert Ellis Smith, a
Rhode Island attorney who publishes the ``Privacy Journal''
newsletter and wrote the book ``Our Vanishing Privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are ambivalent about privacy,'' said Smith. ``The
polls show concern on a superficial level but if you scratch the
surface'' many people ``still think you have something to hide'' if
you raise privacy issues in a criminal case.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
