<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 19, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, midday temperatures hovered near 60 degrees across
upstate New York as a chilly air mass swept into the region behind
a cold front. Wednesday, this push of cool air will advance
southeast to coastal New England and the northern Middle Atlantic
states. Despite abundant sunshine, afternoon readings should hold
in the 70s from Philadelphia to Boston. It will be even cooler over
the interior Northeast where a patchwork of puffy cumulus clouds
shades the sun at times.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered thunderstorms will erupt over the Carolinas on
Wednesday as a wedge of cool air advancing southward lifts humid
air in place over the region. Meanwhile, partly to mostly sunny
skies will cover the remainder of the Southeast. Isolated
thunderstorms will form in the sultry air.
</P>
<P>
   A large cluster of showers and heavy thunderstorms, fueled by a
flow of humid air from the Gulf of Mexico, will affect portions of
the upper Middle West on Wednesday morning. The cluster will tend
to dissipate by late morning. Additional strong to severe storms
will ignite over the northern Plains and Mississippi Valley on
Wednesday afternoon as a disturbance passes along the U.S.-Canada
border.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and spotty thunderstorms will continue to temper the heat
across Texas and New Mexico. Farther north, however, afternoon
temperatures will soar past 100 degrees in parts of western Kansas
as a formidable high pressure system strengthens aloft.
</P>
<P>
   Dry and seasonable conditions will cover the Pacific Coast while
isolated thunderstorms occur in the mountains of the interior West.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The Real Season
</P>
<P>
   There is a hurricane season within the hurricane season. For the
Atlantic basin, the official hurricane season spans from June 1
through November 30. Statistically, however, most hurricanes occur
between August 20 and October 20, the time corresponding to the
climatological crest in tropical sea-surface temperatures
(hurricanes derive energy from warm tropical seas). In Florida, for
example, 36 out of the 40 hurricanes that have struck the state
made landfall during this period, including all 17 of the major
hurricanes. A major hurricane harbors sustained winds of 110 mph or
greater.
</P>
</TEXT>
