<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-KHRISTICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS WILL PAY KHRISTICH $1.95 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As expected, the Bruins have decided not to cut Dmitri
Khristich loose as a free agent and will pay him the $1.95 million
he was awarded last week in arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arbitration process is not an easy one for either the team
or the player,'' said Bruins president-general manager Harry
Sinden, who was part of the Delaware North strategy team that met
Tuesday to prepare the company's bid for the National Football
League's expansion franchise in Cleveland. ``When the decision came
down, it was only prudent on our part to evaluate whether to accept
the award. We feel that the arbitrator was fair and that we can
accept the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to having Dmitri back in uniform and
contributing this season.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains the Bruins' right, of course, to trade the
29-year-old Khristich any time before the March 1999 trading
deadline. But on a team with fragile scoring confidence,
Khristich's kind of offensive punch _ 29 goals and 66 points last
season _ can't easily be deleted from the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were hoping to pay Khristich about $1.4 million, and
he was looking for some $2.8 million. Arbitrator Claude Foisy
essentially split the difference, and Khristich now will stay put,
almost ensuring that he'll be back in arbitration again next year.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins had exercised their right to ``walk away'' from
Foisy's ruling _ they had until Thursday morning to decide _ he
immediately would have been declared a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant GM Mike O'Connell said Monday following netminder Rob
Tallas's arbitration award ($625,000) that the club will refocus on
signing Group 2 free agents Kyle McLaren and Jason Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Just before July 1, McLaren and Allison both were offered the
minimum 10 percent increase over their 1997-98 salaries, figures
that neither accepted. In the last seven weeks, Allison's agent,
Bob Gerow, has returned with a counterproposal for his client, one
that O'Connell said the club will respond to imminently. O'Connell
said he has not heard from McLaren's representatives, the Messier
family (the father, brother, and sister of Canucks center Mark
Messier).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
