<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-CLAIM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP CLAIMS RESPONSIBILITY FOR DEADLY OMAGH BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN   AND JOHN O'FARRELL  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ As people here began burying their
dead, a dissident republican group opposed to the peace process
claimed responsibility Tuesday for Saturday's car bomb that killed
28 people and injured some 200 others.
</P>
<P>
   The self-styled Real IRA admitted responsibility for the worst
atrocity in three decades of violence in Northern Ireland. It
apologized for killing civilians, but insisted it had given ample
warnings.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone call to the Dublin office of the Irish News, a
Belfast newspaper, a male caller using a recognized code word tried
to shift the blame onto police who unwittingly moved crowds of
shoppers near the bomb after being told the bomb was somewhere near
the town's courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite media reports, it was not our intention at any time to
kill any civilians,'' the caller said. ``It was a commercial
target, part of the ongoing war against the Brits. We offer
apologies to the civilians. There were three warnings put in. There
were 40-minute warnings on each of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The caller said the warnings had made clear each time that the
bomb was located 300 to 400 yards from the courthouse on the main
street, and never claimed the bomb was near the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at Ulster Television, which received two of the
three calls, said the caller did not give a location for the bomb
in either warning.
</P>
<P>
   British Secretary of State Mo Mowlam called the attempt by the
bombers to blame others for the carnage ``contemptible and an
insult to the people of Omagh.''
</P>
<P>
   The Monaghan and Grimes families suffered staggering losses in
the Saturday bombings, and their funerals Tuesday began a week of
more funerals and public grieving, that will culminate with a
national moment of silence on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Avril Monaghan, 30, was holding her daughter Maura and standing
next to her 65-year-old mother, Mary Grimes, when the bomb
exploded, killing three generations of women from the same family.
Monaghan was eight months pregnant with twin girls.
</P>
<P>
   The family asked politicians not to attend the service at St.
MacCartan's Church in the picturesque village of Clogher, just
outside Omagh. In a statement after the funeral, Kevin Murnaghan, a
lawyer and family friend, said they wanted no one to use the
tragedy for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The silence of hundreds of mourners outside the small,
19th-century church and around the Celtic high crosses of the
adjacent graveyard was eerie. The funeral Mass was relayed by
speaker to the overflow crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. James Grimes, Avril Monaghan's uncle, who performed her
wedding ceremony, officiated at her funeral. He asked mourners to
forgive the bombers. He also prayed that the Omagh bombing would be
``the last of the terrible agonies our people have suffered over
the past 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two coffins were carried from the church, many people
broke into restrained sobs. There was a jarring juxtaposition of
colors: five altar boys with flowing red cassocks led a procession
of three priests in white, Bishop Joseph Duffy in purple vestments,
followed by the brown oak coffin of Avril Monaghan and, most
poignant, the tiny white coffin of Maura carried by two of her
uncles.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately behind, Avril Monaghan's husband, Michael, carried
his sleeping 3-year-old son, Patrick, on his shoulder, while two
other daughters, Aoibheann, 6, and Eilise, 4, walked behind. His
other shoulder was grasped by Mick Grimes, his father-in-law, who
will bury his own wife today in the same churchyard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
