<P>
   AIDS-AFRICA-MILK (Kakulu, Uganda) _ The basic rules of public
health are clear in Kakulu: only drink water from the well, not
from the polluted Nile; and breastfeeding is the best way to
nourish an infant. At least those were the rules until a few weeks
ago, when the United Nations _ struggling desperately to find a way
to cope with an AIDS epidemic that threatens the future of Africa _
took a giant step toward reversing them. After long deliberation,
U.N. AIDS officials announced that women infected with HIV should
consider feeding formula instead of breast milk to their babies. A
Special Report By Michael Specter. (2,500 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Washington) _ The Fed's policy-making committee
meets and is expected to leave interest rates unchanged. Two
economic reports are issued. One shows that consumer prices rose
0.2 percent last month and that the core rate, which strips out
volatile food and energy costs, increased by the same amount. The
other shows that the trade deficit in goods and services narrowed
during June for the first time this year, shrinking to $14.15
billion from a record $15.54 billion in May. Exports of goods and
services fell half a percent in June, while imports declined 2
percent. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-ASSESS (Kinshasa, Congo) _ The leaders of the rebellion
are trying to present an ethnically diverse face to the country to
avoid the hostility a Tutsi-led regime would attract, but few
Congolese say they would accept any government that they believe is
installed by Rwanda. Instead, the outcome of this conflict, the
latest of many in a country whose history has been full of
uprisings, is likely to be decided by more powerful neighbors.
These countries have sharply divergent interests, but one trait in
common: during the rebellion that brought Kabila to power, they
grew used to playing kingmaker in Africa's third largest country.
By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   HOPPER-LIGHTHOUSE (Cape Elizabeth, Maine) _ Dispute erupts as
the new owners plan partial a demolition of the Maine lighthouse
often painted by Edward Hopper. By Judith H. Dobrzynski.
</P>
</TEXT>
