<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-MUSIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: 'PRESIDENT'S OWN' MUSIC TELLS HISTORY OF OFFICE
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Put aside the legalities of did-he or did-he-not
commit perjury, the endless off-color jokes on late-night TV, and
the burst of Internet ads that use Oval Office sex for their sales
pitches. How's one to measure the stature of the presidency in the
era of Bill Clinton?
</P>
<P>
   Try the music test.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, this is a president known for his love of music
and who only a few weeks back presided over a celebration of 200
years of stirring marches and anthems performed by the U.S. Marine
Band, so closely identified with the chief executive that it was
nicknamed ``the President's Own'' by Thomas Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton told the picnic celebration on
the South Lawn of the White House that her husband has on some
occasions played with them and secretly harbored a desire to be one
of the saxophonists. And she wrote in her weekly column, ``In the
White House, no occasion goes unmarked without the help of the
Marine Band.''
</P>
<P>
   So amid Clinton's admission of improper behavior with a White
House intern, a compact disk of Marine Band recordings given out
that July day becomes a measuring stick for the dignity and
endurance of the nation's highest office.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A performance of ``The President's March,'' written at the
time when George Washington, recalls the man who, more than any
other, set the tone for the office. Washington the war hero might
have been king, but he chose emphatically to be ``Mr. President.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hail to the Chief,'' that arresting tune that alerts crowds
to the arrival of presidents, came into use under John Quincy
Adams, a president who failed to win popular support and was
defeated after a single term. Yet Adams was not too proud to take a
seat in the House of Representatives, where he served the rest of
his life.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A mournful march written at the time of Abraham Lincoln's
assassination offers a reminder of the nation's resiliency in
extremity. Not only did the nation lose the leader who had
struggled to bind the divided nation, but Lincoln's successor
Andrew Johnson was impeached and came within a single vote of being
thrown out of office.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A performance of a march written for Franklin D. Roosevelt
marked the only president to be elected four times. But unknown to
most voters during that last election, he was too weak to leave the
White House for his inaugural, and he died within months, with the
nation still fighting World War II. His little-known successor,
Harry S. Truman, had not even been told about the secret
development of the atomic bomb, but he led the nation to victory
and has since become an icon for politicians who admire his ``The
buck stops here'' motto.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Liberty Bell,'' a composition by the famed Marine Band
director John Philip Sousa, became a favorite piece for the
nation's Bicentennial in 1976. Just two years earlier, the
unthinkable had happened at the White House when Richard Nixon
became the first president to resign. Earlier, Nixon's first vice
president, Sprio Agnew, had been forced to resign and replaced by
the appointment of Gerald Ford. Yet with a minimum disruption, Ford
was sworn into the presidency, and he led the country in
celebrating both its birthday and the strength of its constitution.
</P>
<P>
   If the Marine Band's music history provides insights into the
past, toward the end of the recording is a rendition of ``America
the Beautiful'' that seems to offer an intriguing message for the
current White House crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn from the poem by Katherine Bates, the opening verse that
begins ``Oh beautiful for spacious skies,'' is familiar to almost
every American. But Marine soloist Michael Ryan concludes with a
verse much less remembered:
</P>
<P>
   ``America! America!
</P>
<P>
   God mend thine every flaw
</P>
<P>
   Confirm thy soul in self-control
</P>
<P>
   Thy liberty in law.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
