</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARNHART-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No summer break for aspiring athletes
 &HT;    By Bill Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Summertime is a time for being lazy. Summer
is a time for trips to the beach, for lying in a hammock, running
through a sprinkler. Summertime is for fresh, fat, juicy peaches.
And not having to worry about school.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is a time to ... bust that behind.
</P>
<P>
   Say what?
</P>
<P>
   In these days of athletics as big business, there is no time for
a summer, or anything resembling time off from sports.
</P>
<P>
   Summer is the time for hosting and going to camps. Summer is the
time for hitting a hot, sweaty weight room. It's the time for
recruiting, restocking and rebuilding. Summer is the time for
refinishing the gymnasium floor or cultivating new grass on the
football or soccer fields.
</P>
<P>
   Because, as of this week and rapidly approaching weeks, it will
be too late.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few months, I've been putting together stories
that check out what area players and coaches do during the
offseason. The primary thing I discovered was that the word
``offseason'' doesn't really apply if one plays sports at the upper
echelon of high schools or any level of college.
</P>
<P>
   That was the tack I took with my story last week on North
Carolina Wesleyan's John Thompson, my final piece in the informal
series. After going to Thompson's basketball camp in Greensboro, we
hopped in the car and steamrolled to Charlotte for the Prep Stars
recruiting camp. It was a great opportunity to see what coaches and
players go through, a one-day snapshot of big-time college
recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   I was dumbfounded. All the players were wearing jerseys with
numbers, so I went to a camp organizer to request a list of player
names so I could see if there were any kids from our area attending
the camp. The guy looked at me and said ``40 bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty bills for a list of names? And that was the cheap list,
with just names and numbers. The expensive list included stats,
player bios and other info. An absolute necessity for college
recruiters, who had to shell out $125 for the good list. There was
a lot of paper running through that camp, and most of it was going
into the wallet of the guy who ran the show. Not only did the
coaches pay big money, but the players had to cough it up as well.
</P>
<P>
   We went to basketball camp at Northern Nash. N.C. State standout
Chasity Melvin was there to speak to the youngsters. Coaches can
sometimes talk until they are blue in the face and not command the
attention that a college or pro hero will grab.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes camps will substitute star power for learning
power, which was obvious at another camp I attended. At that
particular camp, kids got autographs from folks like Jerry
Stackhouse and Vince Carter, but they didn't learn anything.
Another camp was the exact opposite. Former Harlem Globetrotter
Meadowlark Lemon concentrated on spreading love and the good word.
There too, the basketball lessons were secondary: But it was in a
good way.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the recruiting jaunt, my favorite trips for the summer
were to a summer hoops league at the YMCA and a football passing
league at Fike. Maybe it's because I miss those sports the most
during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   All the schools, coaches and players made one thing readily
apparent: One thing that doesn't happen during the summer is a
three-month vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Barnhart writes for the Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky Mount,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
