</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCLEESE-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collecting mementos and valuables not the same anymore
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Until the Sports Collectibles show last weekend
at Palmer Auditorium, I hadn't pulled out my collection of baseball
autographs for a decade or two. But I've always slept better
knowing it was there. When I was 9 and 10 years old _ even 11 _ I
would send double postcards, purchased at the post office, to as
many players as my allowance permitted. On one card, addressed to
the player's home ballpark, I would pledge my fandom and explain
how much an autograph would mean to me. The attached card would be
blank, prepaid and self-addressed.
</P>
<P>
   And so they responded, future Hall of Famers such as Warren
Spahn, Yogi Berra and Stan Musial (who stamped rather than signed
his). But my favorites were the rookies and second stringers of my
beloved Chicago Cubs, the guys who weren't deluged with autograph
requests, and thus took the time to deliver more of a personal
touch:
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear Don, Thanks for the card. Your Pal, Lou Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To Don, Best Always, Al Heist, Chicago Cubs.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure such mementos are worth much on today's burgeoning
collectors' market, but I'd guess that whatever is driving the
prices up _ into the hundreds and thousands of dollars for
particularly prized autographs _ is something different from the
boyhood devotion that made my collection priceless to me. As the
rows upon rows of autographed bats, balls, jerseys and baseball
cards in the bowels of Palmer made plain, yesterday's treasure is
today's commodity, tomorrow's investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's so remarkable about this business or hobby is that it
goes from 8 to 80 (years old),'' said show promoter Larry Dluhy,
whose Sports Collectibles store was the first of its type in
Houston 20 years ago. ``And they're not just sports nuts. You could
spend a couple of bucks or thousands and thousands of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, the mass-produced trading cards that once dominated
are giving way to limited editions at higher prices, while the
proliferation of counterfeit autographs has put even more of a
premium on authenticity. At the booth run by the Austin Sports
Connection stores, a plastic-encased Dan Marino card with a
certified autograph was priced at two grand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with the kids, the high-end stuff is what they really
want,'' said store manager Bobby Lo. ``Austin used to have more
than 20 baseball card shops, and now there's only four left.
(Actually, the phone book lists a half-dozen more.) Right now, the
biggest thing is those Beanie Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   Such variables and fluctuations mean little to Jim Murphy, who
drove directly from Dallas to Austin at midnight Friday after
learning that Lou Brock would be Saturday's featured attraction.
With a bat and two balls for Brock to sign, Murphy was paying
almost a hundred bucks for the privilege of receiving the Hall of
Famer's signatures. Unlike so many signees at such shows, Brock
took the time to chat and pose for pictures rather than rushing
through the hundreds in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born in St. Louis, and my grandfather brought me to see
Lou Brock in 1968,'' explained the 38-year-old Murphy. ``Here's the
chance to meet the guy and shake his hand. I'm hanging this bat on
the wall, and I'll save it for my son. It's something that I'll
remember forever. And it's how I'll remember my grandpa.''
</P>
<P>
   Don McLeese writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. He can be reached at dmcleese(AT)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
