<SLUG> BC-PHYMATRIX19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO plans new name, focus, for PhyMatrix Corp.
 &HT;    By Phil Galewitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ PhyMatrix Corp. has decided to get out of the
physician management business, which has been the core of the
company's operations since its founding in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company headed by Palm Beach businessman Abe Gosman
will concentrate on its clinical trials business, which manages
sites that drug makers use to test their products.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Gosman said he also plans to change the
name of the West Palm Beach company, since the PhyMatrix moniker no
longer applies. And PhyMatrix's headquarters will move from
Phillips Point office center in West Palm Beach to PhyMatrix's
Medical Mall in Palm Beach Gardens, Gosman said.
</P>
<P>
   PhyMatrix also will expand its medical real estate development
company, Dasco, into non-medical areas as well. For example, Dasco
developed the Medical Mall as an outpatient health center but now
plans to add to other office towers mainly to house non-medical
offices.
</P>
<P>
   PhyMatrix is still considering whether it will keep Dasco or
spin it off into a separate publicly traded company. A company
source said a spin-off early next year is likely. Gosman, who is
chairman and CEO of PhyMatrix, has become CEO of Dasco, replacing
Bruce Rendina, who resigned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in diversification,'' Gosman said, in explaining
Dasco's move into non-health care real estate development.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted to the changes with a shrug. PhyMatrix
(Nasdaq: PHMX) closed at $5.13, down 59 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
