A9903 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROUND-ROCK19-COX     08-18 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROUND-ROCK19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fastball legend's nickname will go to his team
 &HT;    By Christian Davenport
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUND ROCK, Texas _ After more than a month of voting in the
contest to rename the minor-league baseball team Nolan Ryan wants
to bring to Round Rock, his son Reid announced the new name Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Drum roll please.)
</P>
<P>
   And the winner is . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Round Rock Express.
</P>
<P>
   The moniker comes from Nolan Ryan himself, the right-handed
Texas hero who was nicknamed the ``Ryan Express'' for his
locomotive-like fastball. The name is, as the future hall of
famer's oldest son pointed out, another in a long line of tributes
to the man _ the legend _ who is revered for his rectitude as well
as his celebrated career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't surprise me,'' Reid Ryan said at Damon's restaurant
in Round Rock, which was packed for the announcement with parents,
baseball fans, and children in baseball caps. ``When they had a
chance, the people of this area chose to honor Nolan Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   As more than a hundred people looked on, with their stomachs
full of free food and drink, Reid Ryan with the help of a couple of
young fans unrolled the banner that stated the Express would be
``rolling into town the spring of 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet some at the restaurant said they were pulling for one of the
other three options on the ballots that have been circulating for
more than a month: the Fire Ants, the Round Rock Rattlers, and the
Texas Outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 2,862 votes, the Express garnered 628. In second place
was the Texas Outlaws with 487; third was Reid Ryan's favorite, the
Texas Fire Ants, with 417; and last was the Round Rock Rattlers
with 400 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Estevan Uriegas, 8, said he liked the Rattlers the best. His
11-year-old brother, Marcelo, said was rooting for the Outlaws.
Their father, Rudy, seemed to shy away from one name rather than
embrace the others: ``Fire Ants _ that one I might have had a
problem with.''
</P>
<P>
   There were also 930 write-in candidates for the team, a
minor-league affiliate of the Houston Astros. The Round Rock
Pioneers topped the write-in list with 55 votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since Nolan Ryan started it, it should be named for him,''
said Doris Harvey, who with her husband Dan, makes several trips a
year to Houston to see the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the tie with the team's famous owner, the Express
is a fitting name because trains following the Union Pacific tracks
rumble along U.S. 79, where the stadium is expected to be built. If
voters in November approve a measure that would allow the city to
finance its portion of the stadium with hotel-motel tax revenue,
the team, currently the Jackson (Miss.) Generals, will play its
first game in Round Rock in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Before the team name was announced, 7-year-old Casey Strong said
he liked the Rattlers the best. After the announcement he said he
had changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Express now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
