<P>
   DELTAWEB _ Delta offering a 50 percent discount on future
round-trip ticket to passengers who book a flight online before
Sept. 1. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-CHRYSLER _ The Chrysler Corp. will appeal an $800,000
federal fine for failing to recall more than 90,000 cars that had
faulty rear seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   The fine was imposed Monday because Chrysler failed to recall
Cirrus and Stratus cars after the government told the company those
vehicle seat belt systems were unsafe. The fine is the largest
penalty ever imposed on an automaker for violating safety rules.
(Wagner, Dayton Daily News ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   INTRANET _ATLANTA _A look at the evolution of the intranet: how
they've grown, like the Web, from fairly static sources of
information to interactive, in-house tools. Focusing on local
companies developing intranet software and looking at how and why
local companies are using them, in general. (Clothier, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-DISCOUNT _ Delta is offering a 50 percent discount on
future round-trip ticket to passengers who book a flight online
before Sept. 1. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K _ ATLANTA _ For many of metro Atlanta's largest companies,
the price tag of fixing the millenium bug is starting to firm up.
In second quarter filings that hit the Securities and Exchange
Commission last week, 11 of metro Atlanta's 20 largest companies
disclosed what they expect to spend, and a few revealed what
they've spent already. The total isn't cheap: $554.6 million to
$708.6 million for the 11 expecting a material impact. (Two
companies didn't mention the Year 2000 issue at all.) (Mitchell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   w/Y2KSIDE _ ATLANTA _ Today is the first day of the rest of your
Y2K countdown. Actually, it's the 500th day before the millennium
monster begins byting vulnerable computer systems on January 1,
2000. (Chambers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   CINNABON _ ATLANTA _AFC Enterprises, which last week called off
its acquisition of the small West Coast chain Paradise Cafe, is
buying the Cinnabon chain, with 358 locations, mostly in malls. The
deal closes in September, and is expected to work well with AFC's
Chesapeake Bagels, Bakery &AMP; Cafe and Seattle Coffee brands.
(Gramig, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA 8 p.m. ET.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCSTAR _ AUSTIN, Texas _ A Colorado limited partnership hopes
to gain approval from an Austin City Council committee today to
become only the second holder of a cable television franchise in
the city. LyncStar Integrated Communications of Denver would market
its service to apartment complexes. (Hight, Austin
American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   PHYMATRIX _ WEST PALM BEACH _ PhyMatrix Corp. has decided to get
out of the physician management business, which has been the core
of the company's operations since its founding in 1994. Instead,
the company headed by Palm Beach businessman Abe Gosman will
concentrate on its clinical trials business, which manages sites
that drug makers use to test their products. (Galewitz, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
