<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIENDS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKERS WHO CAN'T COMMUNICATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
Our rating: 3{ Stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Neil LaBute, the writer-director of the
earth-scorching, enjoyably evil ``In the Company of Men,'' lets
some ladies in on the fun with ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors,'' his
hilarious, merciless new study of how awful people can be.
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't just ``Company'' with mirrors, where bad boys
meet their female matches. Only one of the six principals in this
roundelay of rotten relationships and worse sex seems intentionally
cruel. And even Jason Patric's Cary probably doesn't think of
himself as all that mean; he's just the kind of calculating egotist
who plots an act of revenge for every perceived slight, then
justifies his sadism with the thought that ``common decency
dictated the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest, they're just young adults in the big city
searching for satisfaction. And devastating anyone they think they
love in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Eckhart, who played the wicked deceiver in ``Company,'' is
cuddlier here as a chubby hubby named Barry who is very sweet to
his adorable wife Mary (Amy Brenneman) but sexually dysfunctional
nonetheless. Mary, naturally, finds this frustrating, so when good
friend Jerry (Ben Stiller) proposes an affair, she's intrigued.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry may be acting out of his own frustration. His live-in
girlfriend Terri (Catherine Keener) has a razor-sharp tongue and,
maybe as a result of that, a driving need for silence during
lovemaking. Being a drama teacher and, so, prone to dramatics,
Jerry tends to be vocal during intimacy. Things between these two
are rather strained.
</P>
<P>
   Circling the periphery of the couples like preying hawks are the
misogynistic Cary (he recites raunchy pillow talk into a cassette
recorder while exercising) and Cheri (Nastassja Kinski), a gay art
gallery employee whom just about everyone else in the movie
approaches at different times with almost the exact same pickup
lines _ Terri most successfully.
</P>
<P>
   As this synopsis indicates, the emphasis here is on words and
their power to excite, seduce, delude and, especially, to cut like
a Ginzu. There's also an odd formalism to the repetitive
conversational ploys, recombining couplings and unpleasant
character traits that don't change under different circumstances
with new partners. Filmed in appropriately inappropriate widescreen
_ every scene is just people talking _ it's like LaBute feels we're
all trapped in individual romantic rat mazes. It's a libidinized
``No Exit.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but within the constricting structures, what a bracing
variety of behavior. Patric and Keener have the showiest, most
overtly nasty roles, so of course things liven up whenever they
appear (and their one encounter, an atypically fluid Steadicam shot
in a bookstore, is the film's most relentlessly acrid).
</P>
<P>
   But Terri and Cary's monstrous selfishness is only the flash.
``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors' '' depth lies in the creepy way it
keeps manipulating our feelings for the supposedly more likable
characters. Is Stiller's Jerry a heartless cad or a sympathetic
failure at the moving communication that's so important to him? Do
men let Brenneman's Mary down, or is she too impatient and
unforgivng to enable them not to?
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, ``Your Friends &AMP; Neighbors'' can indeed be
enjoyed as a co-ed ``Company of Men,'' a particularly vicious
comedy about the war between the sexes. But there's a richer, if
camouflaged tenderness in the new film. The sad choke you hear
accompanying the clever, well-crafted jibes is the sound of people
who desperately want to connect and couldn't be angrier that words
don't get the job done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
