<HEADLINE>
MILLENNIUM MEANS MOOLAH FOR BLOOMIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; It's further away than Christmas _ this year or
next _ but the countdown to the millennium has officially begun.
</P>
<P>
   Today, marking the 500th day until the year 2000, Bloomingdale's
is opening its Mark of the Millennium shops inside all 23
Bloomingdale's stores across the country.
</P>
<P>
   According to Valli Zale, manager of the Bloomingdale's store at
Fashion Square in Sherman Oaks, the shop-within-a-shop will receive
new merchandise each month to keep the excitement level high as the
M-date draws near.
</P>
<P>
   In a special retail partnership with Ken Walker, president of
01-01-00 Products, Bloomingdale's Millennium shops will feature
merchandise in a black-and-white color combination with the
01-01-00 logo by more than 45 designers, including Adrienne
Vittadini knitwear, Nicole Miller and Ferragamo ties, Crunch
athletic styles and Josie Natori sportswear.
</P>
<P>
   On display today will be T-shirts, caps, mugs and countdown
clocks. In October, shoppers will find backpacks, duffel bags,
wallets and pet dishes, said Zale, who added that Christmas gift
ideas with the countdown logo will be accented with touches of red
and silver.
</P>
<P>
   After making their debut at Bloomingdale's, 01-01-00 products
will be offered at J.C. Penney, Sears and Macy's, but each store
will have its own version of 01-01-00 merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Macy's spokeswoman Merle Goldstone said Macy's will have a
millennium shop with the 01-01-00 logo on boxer shorts, jackets and
digital watches, as well as other novelties by the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   Items are priced from $6 to $250.
</P>
</TEXT>
