<SLUG> BC-TALKIN-RADIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C.C. SMITH BRINGS `PLANET GROOVE' TO KCSN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Northridge public-radio station KCSN-FM (88.5) has
added an international music program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Planet Groove'' can be heard at 8 p.m. Saturdays. The host is
C.C. Smith, editor of the Beat magazine and a former KCRW-FM (89.9)
world-music disc jockey.
</P>
<P>
   Smith describes the program's fusion of world dance music as
``reggae, soca, samba, soukous, ska, makossa and more,'' adding
that she focuses on special dance-party mixes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very different show than people are used to on KCSN,''
Smith said. ``In fact, all the weekend programming is different,
too, with country and American roots-music shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says she tries to keep the music going nonstop with little
interruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very wide range of music out there,'' she said.
``The part I tend to focus on is special dance mixes, plus a lot of
crossover fusion between genres. I'm trying to mix different
cultures and sounds.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BROTHER COPELAND: Longtime music-business veterans Miles,
Ian and Stewart Copeland are hosting an hourlong talk-radio show
during the month of August.
</P>
<P>
   The call-in program, `Sibling Rivalry,'' aims to dispel myths
about the three brothers. Among the regular features will be music
news and gossip, new records, unsigned bands and tips from the
pros.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there has ever been a time when my brothers
and I have ever been at a loss for words or had nothing to say,''
said Miles Copeland, who manages Sting and is chairman of the Ark
21 Records label.
</P>
<P>
   Copeland brother Stewart was drummer for the Police and now
creates film soundtracks. Ian Copeland has been a booking agent for
such artists as the Verve and Snoop Dogg and recently opened a new
bar in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sibling Rivalry'' is broadcast at 5:30 p.m. Fridays on
adult-contemporary KPLS-AM (830).
</P>
<P>
   CORBETT ON Y-107: Kat Corbett has joined the modern-rock Y-107
morning show, ``The Untitled Hardwick Cox Project,'' as news
anchor. Corbett most recently filled in for afternoon-drive host
Sheri Donovan while she was on maternity leave.!end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
