A9931 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-CRIMES-1STLD-WRI     08-18 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-CRIMES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW EXPERT SAYS HATE CRIMES LAWS ARE POINTLESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: SUBS the word attacks for crimes in third line of lede, fixes
2d graf)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By NICOLE TSONG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A leading expert on hate crimes said Tuesday that
felons should not be subjected to longer sentences because their
attacks stem from prejudice based on race, religion, gender, sexual
orientation, ethnicity or disability.
</P>
<P>
   James B. Jacobs, a New York University criminal law professor
and co-author of ``Hate Crimes: Criminal Law and Identity
Politics,'' said that it is ``really bizarre that two people are
beaten up and one crime is worse'' because it grew out of hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, speaking at a policy forum sponsored by the Cato
Institute, a conservative think tank here, also said laws against
hate crimes are unnecessary because states and the federal
government already have statutes covering the offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no law enforcement crisis calling out for these
laws,'' he said. ``All of these offenses ... are already a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-nine states have laws that make it a crime to attack a
person based on race, religion, ethnic background, disability,
gender or sexual orientation. Most of these laws increase the
defendants' sentence if their attack was based on hate.
</P>
<P>
   Last month hate-crime victims and dozens of civic, church and
civil rights groups urged Congress to pass a bill making it a
federal crime to attack someone based on bias against gays, women,
or people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs argued that the definition of prejudice varies with
the statutes and that they can be ``counterproductive'' because
none of them covers all forms of hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some states, for example, that have (laws against)
racial and religious prejudice, but not homophobic prejudices,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's largest gay
rights political group, 29 states do not have anti-gay-bashing
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said the movement for creating various categories of hate
crimes can pit interest groups against one another as each seeks
protection for itself.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he noted, people can commit crimes not because they hate
certain defined groups but because they hate individuals or such
categories of people as the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   David Friedman, director of the Washington bureau of the
Anti-Defamation League, a New York-based civil rights group
fighting prejudice and discrimination, disagreed with Jacobs'
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said there is no sign that the anti-hate-crime laws
have caused conflict among groups. The statutes, he said, actually
bring communities together.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that in Billings, Mont., someone in 1993 threw a brick
through a window that had a Menorah displayed in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people did not say this: `Oh, this is just a broken
window,''' Friedman said, adding that they ``cut out of their local
newspaper ... an image of a Hanukkah Menorah (and) put that image
in their windows.''
</P>
<P>
   Their action made a statement that such attacks will not be
tolerated, Friedman said.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that anti-hate-crime laws are needed because the
attacks they cover cause pain to a larger group of people than the
victims themselves. He cited a synagogue that was vandalized in a
Washington, D.C., suburb. The pain to Jewish people in the entire
area ``was palpable,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
