A9938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CSIBLEY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Would anyone read a book about 1930's ballgowns?
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A writer friend of mine says when you're working on a book, some
of the best ideas you'll ever have come to you in the middle of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that what I've been having, good ideas?'' I asked her. ``I
thought they were bad dreams.'' She said to keep a pencil and paper
handy, and when you awaken in the middle of the night, make haste
to jot down your dreams.
</P>
<P>
   My middle of the night dreams are less imaginative, less
creative than some writer's, I've decided. I dreamed I fell off the
ladder while washing the bedroom windows. That's good for a book? I
don't think so. I dreamed I was hungry, and awakened with my feet
on the floor, a start toward the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no sizzling plots, no beguiling characterizations, have
come to me in dreams. When the glimmer of an idea hits me, I have
to go to the library or seek out an expert among my acquaintances.
Since I have been unnaturally interested in ballgowns for Mardi
Gras in Mobile(Ala.) in 1930, I have haunted the desk and
bookshelves of our fashion writer Marylin Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The other day I asked Marylyn if French seamstresses are
superior to those in rural Alabama. I know their designers are
highly thought of, but when I was growing up, all women could sew,
some more skillfully than others, but anybody knew how to ply a
needle if the need arose. Our neighbor ``Miss Lily'' Myers would
have made a fortune if she had lived close to the market. She could
copy any garment she saw pictured in the Sears-Roebuck catalog or
the Mobile Register. And she never had a lesson. On my first trip
to New York _ $100 excursion with three other Mobile girls on the
Greyhound bus _ I was splendidly arrayed in costumes made for me by
Miss Lily. Could French seamstresses do as well _ or better?
</P>
<P>
   I asked Marylin, and she handed me one of her big books on the
subject. It's fascinating the amount of time, thought and prose
some people have put into clothes. The section on French clothes
was big and authoritative, and I didn't see anything I recognized
but the French seam, which in my day all girls were taught to make
when they were learning to sew. Plain, hidden and not chic by any
means. Certainly nothing to stand out on a Mobile Mardi Gras
ballgown.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that I caught on to clothes late. I am somewhat
like my grandson, who is starting Georgia State University this
fall. ``Do you have enough clothes?'' I asked. He shrugged. He had
clearly given it no thought. He as going to register wearing blue
jeans out at the knees. Well, I know ragged blue jeans are
considered ``cool'' by the young, so why should I worry about them?
If you can wear holey blue jeans to college, my character's
preoccupation with a ballgown seems excessive. Except that was 1930
_ and I believe the young took clothes more seriously in those
days.
</P>
<P>
   World War II must have interrupted preoccupation with dress.
According to Marylin's book, the government started regulating how
long dresses could be, how full trousers, to save material.
Besides, there was nothing that surpassed a uniform for style and
glamour. I recall no hardship was involved in the government's
restrictions, except the loss of nylons. Even Hollywood stars who
came to town on bond-selling expeditions painted their legs and,
like the rest of us, saw the paint melt and run down in their shoes
on a hot day.
</P>
<P>
   But now ballgowns ... maybe I should take a nap and see if it's
true about dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
