<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SMOKYMTNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wingdings in Waynesville, N.C.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- Haywood happenings: Three big end-of-summer events are on the
horizon in mountainous Haywood County(N.C.), which boasts 20 of the
Blue Ridge's highest peaks. First up is the Atlanta Ballet's
residency at Haywood Community College in Waynesville, followed by
the Autumn Showcase of arts, crafts and music at the Balsam
Mountain Inn (just over the Jackson County line), and the 27th
Smoky Mountain Folk Festival at Lake Junaluska.
</P>
<P>
   -- Folk ways: Traditional Appalachian music and dance will fill
the stage Sept. 4 and 5 at the 2,000-seat Stuart Auditorium at Lake
Junaluska. ``We have four or five dance teams each evening and
about 20 other acts _ lots of variety,'' says festival director Joe
Sam Queen. ``It's a family-friendly occasion.'' Also, there will be
a children's tent and jam sessions under the big oaks. There will
be free watermelon, and the kids ``can chase the ducks down to the
water if they get bored,'' says Queen. Jamming and kids' events
begin at 5 p.m.; the big shows start at 7 p.m. Tickets $7.50 at the
door. Call 828-452-0593. Lodging and dining available by
reservation at Lake Junaluska, a year-round conference center of
the United Methodist Church; call 828-452-2881.
</P>
<P>
   -- Art at the inn: Autumn Showcase at Balsam Mountain Inn Sept.
1-Oct. 31 features works of 45 Haywood County artists, who will
attend a reception 2-5 p.m. Sept. 13. Work is restocked twice a
week. Hours 10 a.m.-9 p.m. daily. Free concerts Thursdays at 8:30
p.m. feature Anne Lough, Sept. 10 and Oct. 22; the Reel Band, Sept.
17 and Oct. 15; Sentimental Duo, Sept. 24; Mountain Aire String
Band, Oct. 1 and 29; and the Dowden Sisters, Oct. 8. Call
828-456-9498 for lodging or dinner reservations at the inn, a 1908
lodge on 26 acres.
</P>
<P>
   -- Ballet in the mountains: The Atlanta Ballet's seventh annual
Mountain Homecoming includes school visits, master classes and
parties culminating with two performances 7:30 p.m. Aug. 29 and 2
p.m. Aug. 30 at Haywood Community College Auditorium. Among the
works is a premiere of ``Earth,'' choreographed by North Carolina
resident Laura Dean, and a new work by Val Caniparoli. Tickets $15
to $25, children and senior citizens half-price on Sunday.
Information, 1-800-491-6803.
</P>
<P>
   -- Theatrical bonus: The Haywood Arts Repertory Theatre (HART)
presents William Inge's ``Picnic'' at the barnlike Performing Arts
Center at the Shelton House, 250 Pigeon St. (U.S. 276 south), in
downtown Waynesville. The play runs Aug. 28-Sept. 6. Adults $10,
seniors $8, students $6. Reservations, 828-456-6322.
</P>
<P>
   -- Staying over: In addition to Lake Junaluska and the Balsam
Mountain Inn, the area offers a variety of country inns and
bed-and-breakfasts. The Haywood County Chamber of Commerce
(828-456-3021) or Maggie Valley Chamber of Commerce (828-926-1686)
can help with accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
