<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TEXASFAIR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sights galore at huge Texas fair
 &HT;    By Alan Patureau
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colloquially called ``The Big One'' by residents of ``Big D,''
the State Fair of Texas will hold forth in Dallas from Sept. 25 to
Oct. 18, a mammoth event that fits the image of the biggest and
bragging-est state of the Lower 48.
</P>
<P>
   This fair boasts the tallest Ferris wheel (212 feet), the most
animals (10,000), the biggest IMAX screen (70 feet), the largest
crowd (3.5 million) and the tallest greeter, a 52-foot statue of
``Big Tex'' booming ``howdy, folks!''
</P>
<P>
   A highlight of this year's ``Puttin' on the Glitz'' theme will
be daily afternoon Coliseum shows by the Royal Lipizzaner
Stallions, 14 white horses performing spectacular leaps and
maneuvers in the style of the Spanish Riding School of Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   ``FutureVisions'' will be the main exhibit, a vast hall filled
with high-tech wonders such as a futuristic hospital operating room
and a display of high-definition TV sets. Other buildings will
feature shiny new cars and experimental vehicles, livestock shows,
IMAX films, exhibits of dinosaurs, doll houses, video games and
butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a nightly Starlight Parade through the park, with
lighted floats, marching bands and equestrian units. The midway
boasts 75 rides, including a new bumper car attraction called Carat
2000, with made-in-Paris cars and a kaleidoscope of colorful
lights. The Cotton Bowl, a focal point of the fairgrounds, will
offer college football games every Saturday, capped by the annual
``Red River Showdown'' Oct. 10 between the Universities of Texas
and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Two Texas-born stars will offer free 8 p.m. concerts, Clint
Black on Oct. 10 and LeAnn Rimes on Oct. 17, while the national
touring company of the recent Broadway version of ``Showboat''
plays nightly at 8 in the Music Hall; tickets are $30 to $70. A
popular free-flight bird show, ``Kings of the Wind,'' will be back
for a 10th year, with a new bird encounter area and a lorikeet
feeding aviary added.
</P>
<P>
   Tailor-made for families with children are attractions such as
``Alien Ballet,'' a gymnastics show set to music; ``Kid Fish,'' a
well-stocked fishing pond with child-sized poles; ``The Jamitors,''
a trash-drum band; and a birthing parlor addition to the Petting
Farm, where expectant nanny goats can be seen bringing their young
into the world.
</P>
<P>
   The fair is open daily from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m.; adults $9,
senior citizens and children under 4 feet tall $5, age 2 and under
free. Call 214-565-9931 or go to http://www.texfair.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- Fair enough: Dating to 1886, Fair Park is a 277-acre art deco
complex two miles east of downtown Dallas off I-30. It draws crowds
year round to the big Steam Railroad Museum; the Hall of State,
with murals, statuary and historical exhibits; the Dallas Museum of
Natural History; the Dallas Aquarium; the Science Place, filled
with hands-on exhibits for children and adults; the Dallas Civic
Garden; and the Music Hall, home of the Dallas Opera and concerts.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sightseeing: Dallas has finally acknowledged that its biggest
tourist attraction is the former Texas School Book Depository in
Dealey Plaza, where Lee Harvey Oswald allegedly fired the shots
that killed President John F. Kennedy. Called simply the Sixth
Floor, it's a multimedia museum with audio guide. Adults $8, senior
citizens and children $7. Call 214-747-6660 or go to
http://www.jfk.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
