<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HESAID-SHESAID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He should be at Hillary's knees
 &HT;    By Maureen Downey
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Post crowned a photo of a downcast Hillary Rodham
Clinton on Tuesday with the damning headline ``HUMILIATED.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such widespread catcalls, the first lady shouldn't be
embarrassed. She should be enraged. And not at Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   History will judge whether Bill Clinton proves a good president.
But the jury's already in on whether he's a good husband.
</P>
<P>
   The galoot cheated on his wife under their own roof with a young
woman not much older than daughter Chelsea, sputtered at the
allegations and then encouraged Hillary to hoist a megaphone in his
defense.
</P>
<P>
   It's plain Hillary loves the lout, despite his chronic failure
to keep his executive privilege under wraps. While he was buying
``Leaves of Grass'' for Monica Lewinsky, Hillary should have
thumbed through ``Smart Women, Foolish Choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The beltway bench warmers maintain that Hillary Clinton is too
sharp to have bought her husband's innocence. I disagree. If she
doubted him, she's far too bright to have voiced such a strong and
public stand on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Women are willing to accept that Hillary intends to stand by her
man again. It's just that they don't believe Bill should be
standing tall next to her.
</P>
<P>
   He should be on his knees _ begging for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   He was her choice _ ours, too
</P>
<P>
   By Bo Emerson
</P>
<P>
   c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   I don't buy the idea that Hillary Clinton was fooled about her
husband's peccadilloes. Hillary knew what she was getting when she
picked Bill Clinton. And so did we.
</P>
<P>
   We'd already had a faithful, Sunday school-teaching president
whose affairs were only in his heart. But pure-as-the-driven-snow
Jimmy Carter didn't keep us from humiliation overseas and a 17
percent prime interest rate.
</P>
<P>
   As if to underscore the point that private conduct does not
predict the ability to govern, we elected the allegedly
philandering Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a booming economy and a balanced budget.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night he told us just what we wanted to hear, which
was as little as possible. Like an aggrieved spouse, we didn't want
the details. We just wanted him to say he was sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Now the pundits are descending like a cloud of magpies, claiming
that Hillary's bargain with Bill is a deal with the devil, that she
coolly looks the other way to continue to enjoy the perks of the
office.
</P>
<P>
   Hogwash. Though it was a craven move on Clinton's part to invoke
the sanctity of the family when he clearly doesn't respect the
institution himself, the irrefutable fact remains: We can't judge
their relationship. We don't have the facts and we never will.
</P>
<P>
   If Hillary chooses to forgive, that's up to her. And before we
disrespect her for her decision, we should look at ourselves.
Because we chose him too.
</P>
<P>
   Write married staffers Maureen Downey and Bo Emerson at The
Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail them at mdowney(at)ajc.com or bemerson(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
