<P>
   ``It's a landmark study because it's the first really scientific
study of women randomly assigned to take hormones,'' said Wenger,
who conducted a portion of the study at Emory. ``Many physicians
were recommending hormone replacement therapy for cardiac
protection based on the previous observational studies.''
</P>
<P>
   Those observational studies, which looked at large groups of
women who chose to take hormones, concluded that estrogen decreased
the risk of heart disease 35 percent to 50 percent in
post-menopausal women, compared to women who did not take hormones.
But it remained unclear whether hormones were protecting women
against certain diseases or whether the women were healthier
because they exercised more, did not smoke and ate less fat than
women who did not take hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers cautioned against applying findings from the study,
published in today's Journal of the American Medical Association,
to healthy women who may be taking hormones. Many women take
estrogen to ease symptoms of menopause, including hot flashes and
night sweats, but the choice is a difficult one because long-term
effects are unproved.
</P>
<P>
   Observational studies also have suggested that healthy women who
take estrogen may lower their risks of developing heart disease and
osteoporosis, the bone-thinning disease. Estrogen also may have
some benefits for preventing Alzheimer's disease, but research
suggests hormones could raise risks of endometrial and breast
cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Definitive answers for healthy women won't come until 2005, with
completion of the Women's Health Initiative, the largest study ever
undertaken on American women's health. Emory also is participating
in that study.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, women need to continue discussing with their doctors
the risks and benefits of taking hormone replacement therapy,
researchers emphasized. ``This study doesn't say anything about any
other hormone regimen or anything about how healthy women are
affected,'' Wenger said. ``It's confusing, we realize that. This
provides us with an answer, but it also raises more questions that
still have to be answered.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the HERS findings, researchers recommend that women
with heart disease not begin hormone replacement therapy solely to
protect themselves from further coronary disease. However, they
also emphasized that women already taking hormones should not stop
such treatment because the benefits may kick in over time.
</P>
<P>
   The study also verified negative effects of taking hormones
suggested by observational studies: gallbladder disease and an
increased risk of blood clots in the legs or lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
