<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-SIDE-COX     08-18 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hormonal replacement therapy for heart disease may not be the
best course of action
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eleonore Winecoff waited four years for a prescription that
turned out too good to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Hormones, she found out Tuesday, won't be added to her heart
smart remedies.
</P>
<P>
   That's because of the unexpected findings of a national study
looking at hormone replacement therapy on postmenopausal women with
heart disease. Officially released today, the clinical trial found
estrogen and progestin did not have the protective benefit on their
cardiovascular system that had long been assumed. ``I had expected
to find out that hormonal replacement therapy would help you
against further heart disease,'' said Winecoff, 75, and one of 112
Atlanta-area women who participated in the Heart and
Estrogen/progestin Replacement Study, or HERS, study. ``I might
have started it. My doctor and I had discussed that, and we were
waiting for these results. But I'm not going to do that now. I
don't think it will do much good.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the study, researchers now are advising doctors not to
prescribe hormones to women such as Winecoff, who suffered a major
heart attack six years ago and had never taken any artificial
hormones following menopause at age 48.
</P>
<P>
   However, women already taking such therapy with the hope that
it's helping their heart should not discontinue estrogen because
it's known to have other benefits, such as staving off
osteoporosis, and it appears to have long-term positive cardiac
effects, states an editorial in today's Journal of the American
Medical Association. Those women should discuss hormone therapy
with their doctors, but that discussion isn't urgent, the editorial
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The HERS results are important for women to consider in making
decisions about hormone replacement. Physicians need to review
carefully the HERS findings, but no woman, including those with
coronary disease, should abruptly cease use,'' writes Dr. Diana B.
Petitti of Kaiser Permanente Southern California research
department. ``Discussions of the HERS findings between women and
their physicians do not need to occur today, this week, or even
this month. HERS identifies no new risks, and there is no
emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   Winecoff, of Buckhead, was among the group of women taking an
inactive pill, or placebo, whose health was compared to those in a
comparable group of women taking Prempo, one of the most widely
prescribed estrogen-progestin oral medications. She was followed by
doctors and staff at Emory University and Grady Memorial Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The study involved 2,763 women in 20 sites. The Atlanta-area
participants are to be treated to a luncheon today on the Emory
campus to thank them for their contributions to science and women's
health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these women are heroines,'' said Dr. Nanette Wenger,
Emory professor of medicine and chief of cardiology at Grady
hospital. ``They were sick but they volunteered to participate, to
take medicine without knowing what it was, for the benefit of
future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither researchers nor the women knew who received the hormone
pills in the randomized trial. However, participant Lee Caronia
said that, for her, it wasn't hard to figure out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew within three weeks (of beginning the unknown pills)
that I was taking hormones, ''said Caronia, 70, who suffered a
major heart attack 15 years ago. ``If you haven't had a period in
10 years years and suddenly you do, then you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Caronia didn't like going back to using sanitary pads, so she
asked to discontinue the hormonal therapy. To her surprise, the
Snellville resident said she wasn't dropped from the study but kept
on because researchers seemed interested in how she was handling
her post-heart attack health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very interested in my condition and the HERS staff
seemed very interested, too,'' she said. ``I had always thought
women were second-class citizens when it came to heart conditions.
Doctors didn't seem to take our heart disease as seriously as
men.''
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the results delivered to her door Tuesday morning,
Caronia said she's glad she stopped taking the hormones. But she
added: ``I really think its a very personal decision for each
woman. Every one has to come up with their own conclusion about the
risks and benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings: Those taking the hormones experienced a
nearly 50 percent increase of heart attack during the study's first
year. But by the fourth year of treatment, women taking the drug
had a 40 percent reduction in heart attack risk.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the initial heart trouble are unclear. The gradual
improvement could be because it takes about one or two years for
estrogen to reduce cholesterol levels, which can trigger heart
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The $40 million HERS study was funded by Wyeth-Ayerst Research,
the makers of Prempo. An observational follow-up study on the women
is planned to see if the beneficial trend seen during the trial's
last two years continues.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
