<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9950 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TGRAHAMBROWN-COX     08-18 1364
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TGRAHAMBROWN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Singer, now a surrvivor, is making a name for himself
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nashville --This sunny Tennessee afternoon, singer T. Graham
Brown is standing in the kitchen of his home high in the hills
above Nashville, making a tomato and mayonnaise sandwich. At 43,
his face is still boyish, framing a devilish smile and the piercing
blue eyes that could charm a meter maid out of a ticket. He still
wears a let's-party Hawaiian shirt, though the shaggy hair has
turned gray. One other thing is different for this former
chart-topping country music star and Athens, Georgia frat band
legend: When he pours his drink into a plastic tumbler, he's not
putting vodka in it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is a man poised for a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got real bad,'' he says. ``It was one big ol' rolling
party. It was great. I was young and strong and I could do it back
then. But it got to the point that I was getting up and pouring me
a drink first thing in the morning. I just got sucked in. I knew
what I was doing, but I said hey, I don't have a problem. Then God
got my attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 25 years he's been belting out his soulful sound _ first
in the Sam and Dave-inspired Athens party duo Dirk &AMP; Tony, then as
a bad-assed Southern rocker and, ultimately, as a hit-making
country music star _ Brown has been a survivor. Now, after a career
that stalled and crashed in a sea of partying, alcohol and changing
musical tastes, he's releasing his first album in seven years,
appropriately titled ``Wine Into Water.'' The title song, a
gut-wrenching anthem Brown wrote ``to get it all out of my
system,'' was released to radio Monday.
</P>
<P>
   At the high point of his career in the '80s, the Athens native
had a string of top Nashville hits such as ``Hell and High Water,''
``Don't Go To Strangers'' and ``Don't Go Out,'' a duet with Tanya
Tucker, who today calls Brown ``one of the best voices in country
music.'' In the 1970s, long before R.E.M. or the B-52s, Brown was
perhaps the most popular musical act in Athens, throwing back shots
of whiskey as UGA students partied hard to songs like ``Double Shot
of My Baby's Love.'' Athens producer John Keane (R.E.M., 10,000
Maniacs), who played guitar in Brown's country/rock band Reo
Diamond in 1980, recalls that Brown ``was the top draw in town'' at
that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony was pretty wild,'' Keane says. ``One of his claims to
fame is he would open a bottle of Wild Turkey at the beginning of
the set and strum it like a guitar. By the end of the night, the
bottle was empty.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's real fame came in a most unlikely role: as a pitch man.
In the late '80s, the fast food chain Taco Bell tapped him to sing
and star in the company's new ad campaign. The widely aired
television commercials _ raucous, technicolor spots in which Brown
drove across the nations screen in a convertible growling ``run for
the border'' _ made him a household face at the end of the Reagan
era.
</P>
<P>
   But by 1991, Brown's career stalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget it,'' he says with a laugh. ``I was on
Capitol, and they had just brought in (legendary producer) Jimmy
Bowen. He had me over to the mansion for lunch, and told me `you
are the flagship of this label. We're gonna make beautiful music
together'.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came Garth.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the pep talk from Bowen, Capitol's newest artist,
Garth Brooks, won his first Country Music Association award. At the
party following the ceremonies, Brown remembers watching Brooks
walk in ``with his big white hat and long tails.'' Although he says
Bowen quipped that Brooks was ``just a flash in the pan,'' Brown
didn't realize that a revolution was taking place that would put
his career on the shelf. Soon, every label in town was looking for
a hat act, leaving little room for artists like Brown who were
churning out country blues.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, nothing was happening,'' he recalls. ``They
put $80,000 into a new video, but they weren't working the
record.''
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated at the lack of support, Brown left his $900,000 deal
with Capitol and signed with Warner Bros. In his first meeting with
label execs, they had one request: Wear a cowboy hat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `you got to be kidding. I don't wear a hat. That's not
who I am'.''
</P>
<P>
   It went downhill from there. Brown describes those years this
way: ``I was mad and I was drunk.'' As his record sales dropped,
Brown turned up the burner on his partying lifestyle. One of his
closest drinking buddies was country singer Keith Whitley, who
later died of acute alcohol poisoning. It was the start of a
wake-up call for Brown, who checked himself into the Cumberland
Heights recovery center in Nashville for one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a real strong will, and I thought I could just quit,''
he says. ``Then I joined a group of alcoholics and drug addicts
that met every Monday right on Music Row, and I knew every one of
'em. But we were all still drinking, and it was expensive, so I
dropped out and kept right on.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's parents, Royce and Jackie, who live in Commerce, had no
idea what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept it hid pretty much,'' Jackie says. ``We never had any
inkling. We've always been a tight-knit family, but sometimes they
can wander away from that. Life on the road is very hard, we
understand that. I'm just thankful he realized in time that life's
too short not to enjoy each day.''
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came in 1994, when son Acme, now 9, was rushed
to the hospital for emergency surgery. Brown's wife, Sheila, a
University of Georgia student who married the singer in 1980, asked
him not to come to the hospital. She sat down and wrote her husband
an eight-page letter, pouring out her heart in concern over what he
had become, and how he was missing the opportunity to reach his
potential and watch his child grow up.
</P>
<P>
   Hung over, Brown read the letter and was shaken to his soul. He
hasn't had a drink since. ``All of a sudden, I felt a lot of
passion. I was able to sing all kind of ways, and it made me happy
inside. My soul was happy,'' he says of the months following the
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Brown continued to tour, and made the decision with Sheila to
stick it out in Nashville in spite of the fickle musical climate.
The couple dipped into their savings in order for Brown to record
demos in his home studio. ``I believe in him,'' Sheila says.
``Everyone says he has one of the best voices in Nashville, but
he's not a cookie-cutter hat act. He doesn't sound like everybody
else.''
</P>
<P>
   One demo Brown cut two years ago is the song ``Wine Into
Water.'' It's a deeply personal tune, with lyrics that cut to the
heart of the matter:
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I'm as low as any man can go/I'm down and I can't fall
much farther/Once upon a time you turned the water into wine/But
now on my knees I'm turning to your Father/Could you help me turn
the wine back into water.''
</P>
<P>
   The song caught the attention of executivesat the new Nashville
label, Intersound, who signed Brown to a deal.
</P>
<P>
   How likely is a comeback?
</P>
<P>
   Neil McGinley, operations manager for Atlanta's two country
radio stations, Kicks 101.5 and Y-106.7, says, ``I think anybody
can come back. Randy Travis and John Anderson are perfect examples.
Obviously, T. has talent. I think the new stuff is great. What you
have with these guys is that they all sound somewhat unique, their
singing styles and their voices. So many of the acts now all sound
and look alike; you can't tell one from the other. Sometimes the
pendulum does swing 180 degrees in the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and his family seem deeply committed to the new project,
but exude an even more profound determination for a sober and
spiritual lifestyle. In the evenings, as the sun sets over the
rolling Tennessee hills, they often sit in a wooden swing
overlooking the lush bottom land of the Harpeth River.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it our prayer swing,'' Sheila says. ``I guess you can
figure out what we do in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown talks like a man at peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``People our age are coming to a crossroads. Either you're gonna
keep living like that, or you're gonna get healthy. Really, that's
the only choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1853EDT &QL; 
