<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9951 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SURFER19-COX     08-18 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER19-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Comedy Central's new show goes to the edge
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Longinoc. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Comedy Central's got the groove.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight it begins a new season of the outrageous ``South Park''
(10 p.m. EDT) and then launches the even more bizarre ``Upright
Citizens Brigade'' (10:30 p.m. EDT).
</P>
<P>
   ``UCB'' (as we're sure the requisite fan T-shirts will be
labeled in the days to come) is an outlandish long-form sketch
comedy show that's the kind of demented, well-executed programming
you want to see on Public Access Television but never do.
</P>
<P>
   It's decidedly original and certifiably sick. Wickedly funny,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCB'' comes from a Chicago-bred comedy troupe. Their show
motto: ``Our enemy is the status quo; our only friend is chaos.''
Tonight's first 30-minute sketch introduces a small band of
space-flying geeks who do everything in their power to wreak havoc
on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine ``Mystery Science Theater 3000'' on speed.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's a pesky Bucket of Truth _ actually a white
plastic mop pail. The only thing known about the darned bucket is
this: ``whoever shall look into the bucket shall know unmitigated,
unadulterated, immutable truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the quick route to madness, no?
</P>
<P>
   ``UCB's'' victims act wacko from the get-go. There's Capt.
Lunatic, the stressed-out cop, who curses God through clenched
teeth while hunting the world's notorious Bong Boy, a pot-smoking
dude who strangely shows up wherever tragedy strikes.
</P>
<P>
   There's Lunatic's 29-year-old ``high-on-life'' son Leonard,
whose ruminations spill from his fried brain. ``Daddy,'' he wonders
in spazspeak, ``how come at night when you put the barrel of your
gun in your mouth it makes you cry?''
</P>
<P>
   And there's Cassie, the girl scout, who while out selling
cookies winds up playing campout in the living room of the
Unabomber. ``Once I made a handpuppet out of an old sock and
macaroni,'' Cassie says. Her laughing playmate's reply: ``I once
blew off a man's hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Their adventures are fiendishly twisted and delivered in
non-stop, triple-shot-espresso comedy riffs.
</P>
<P>
   Many might call this edgy. Their half right.
</P>
<P>
   ``UCB'' does head straight for the edge. Then gleefully jumps
right off.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1853EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
