<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9952 &Cx1f; paxxx
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-CONG-PA     08-18 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-CONG-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        RESIGN OR BE IMPEACHED, LEHIGH VALLEY LAWMAKER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Paul Kane  
 &HT;    c. 1998 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Aug. 18 -- A House member from the Lehigh Valley has
become one of the first congressmen -- Republican or Democrat -- to
publicly call for President Clinton to resign from office or face
the harrowing prospect of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As most Democrats tried to rally around the White House and
Republicans urged caution amid waiting for an impeachment report,
Rep. Paul McHale, D-Bethlehem, announced Tuesday he could no longer
support Clinton remaining in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   McHale, who served about five years in the Marine Corps and is
still a reserve officer, said he believed the president perjured
himself and ``almost certainly'' attempted to obstruct justice by
buying Monica Lewinsky's silence with job offers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perjury is not excused by an apology compelled by overwhelming
evidence and delivered under pressure,'' he said, adding: ``We
could spare the country a great deal of pain by abandoning the rule
of law. That's too high a price. With great sadness, I have
concluded that President Clinton should resign or face
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   McHale's pronouncement does not carry a whole lot of political
weight on Capitol Hill -- he is a six-year House veteran who is
retiring at the end of the year -- but it was a bombshell just
because he's the first Democrat to publicly denounce Clinton.
McHale is not a member of the House Judiciary Committee, which
would take up any impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats, however, fell in line with Clinton's call to
``turn away from the spectacle of the past seven months.'' Said
House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.: ``It is my most
fervent hope that this investigation can be brought to its long
overdue conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Rep. Chaka Fattah, D-Phila., who had said all along that he
believed Clinton's original denials of a sexual relationship with
Clinton, does not think Clinton should suffer from an impeachment
proceeding based on perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's at the basis of all this, I think it's an
embarrassment to (Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr) and the
Republican Party,'' Fattah said.
</P>
<P>
   Since he is retiring from Congress, McHale is much more free to
speak his mind without any fear of retribution from the party
leadership. McHale could not be reached to further explain to his
decision, but speculation focused on his background with the
Marines -- the most rigid of all the services in its ``code of
honor'', including a tough anti-adultery and anti-lying policy.
</P>
<P>
   McHale served active duty from 1972 to 1974 and again in 1990
and 1991, when he resigned his seat from the state legislature to
reenlist for duty in the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   He was at one time considered in the running to be secretary of
the Navy, but has apparently been ruled out by the Clinton
administration. Tuesday's comments will do little to endear him to
the White House, which said nothing would distract Clinton. ``He
said it's time to get back to the country's business, and that's
what he intends to do,'' said Kara Gerhardt, spokeswoman for
Clinton, who left Tuesday for two weeks vacation in Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., however, noted that McHale's call for
Clinton to resign was noteworthy because it came from a fellow
moderate Democrat, and could not be discredited as a partisan
attack.
</P>
<P>
   And Specter said Clinton's extraordinary address to the nation
Monday night ``had all the earmarks of deception.'' Because Clinton
will not answer questions about specific sexual acts he had with
Lewinsky, Specter said, it becomes difficult to determine if
committed perjury when he testified that he never had ``sexual
relations'' with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to analyze what he says very, very closely,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
