</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-SLAYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA TEACHER SENTENCED TO LIFE IN PRISON IN HOUSTON SLAYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Monroe, La.) 
 
By STEVE BREWER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A Louisiana schoolteacher who closely followed the
O.J. Simpson case was sentenced to life in prison late Monday for
killing a Houston man that his estranged wife was dating.
</P>
<P>
   The sentencing of Roy Neal Shelling, 30, in the Nov. 30, 1997,
slaying of Carlos L. McMahon, 23, means that Shelling will not be
eligible for parole for at least 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The body of McMahon, who worked at a local optical business, was
found by Shelling's estranged wife and a friend at his southeast
Houston apartment one day after his murder.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon's throat had been cut and he had been shot five times
and stabbed numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stranger aspects to the case, said prosecutor Vic
Wisner, was Shelling's intense curiosity about the criminal trial
of Simpson, the ex-football star and actor who was acquitted of
criminal charges in 1996 in the slayings of his former wife, Nicole
Simpson, and her friend Ronald Goldman.
</P>
<P>
   Shelling would videotape the televised Simpson trial during the
day and then watch the court proceedings late into the night,
according to testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some eerie similarities to the O.J. case,'' Wisner
said. ``Part of our theory was that he was very possessive of his
estranged wife and had threatened to harm anybody he ever caught
her with. We don't know if he modeled the crime after the O.J. case
consciously or unconsciously, or at all. But there are some
similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   Jealous confrontations, the fact that McMahon's throat was cut
and his numerous stab wounds were factors that mirrored the Simpson
case, Wisner said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelling also tried to have an alibi in place and left town
immediately after the murder, Wisner said. Shelling, who taught
elementary school, was later arrested in Louisiana. He also
disposed of the knife and gun used in the murder, and authorities
found no clothing that might have been stained with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Wisner said Shelling and his wife, a local school teacher, once
lived in Houston together. But when they split, the defendant moved
to Monroe, La., where other members of his family also work as
educators.
</P>
<P>
   The woman started dating McMahon, and Shelling promised he would
kill anyone he caught her with, according to testimony. Before the
murder, Shelling had already confronted a man he thought had left a
phone message for his wife. The message had actually been left by
McMahon, and Shelling intercepted it and went to the school where
his wife worked and confronted her with it.
</P>
<P>
   During the Thanksgiving 1997 holiday, Shelling and his wife went
to Chicago together and he asked her to reconcile with him, Wisner
said. But she told him it wasn't going to work.
</P>
<P>
   After they returned from the trip, Shelling told his wife he was
going back to Louisiana. But instead he went to McMahon's
apartment, according to testimony. After McMahon's attack, the wife
saw her husband driving away from the complex. She left and called
police.
</P>
<P>
   Officers knocked on the door that night and left after getting
no answer or spotting anything suspicious, Wisner said. The next
day police returned after Shelling's wife found McMahon's body.
</P>
<P>
   Wisner said forensic evidence indicated that McMahon was already
dying of the gunshot wounds when his throat was cut.
</P>
<P>
   A fingerprint from Shelling's pinky finger was found on a
compact disc case that was sitting on a kitchen ledge above the
body, Wisner said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
