<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWS-ADS-NYT &LR;      08-18 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWS-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATIONS SEEKING RESPECT VIA ADS ON NEWS TALK SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few fans of the upscale Sunday morning news programs and of
public television's weeknight ``Newshour'' can have more than a
vague notion of what Archer Daniels Midland Co. is up to off
camera. Its omnipresent soft-focused high-minded commercials croon
that Archer Daniels is a charitable institution, dedicated to
saving the universe even as it brings edifying television to a
select audience. Other companies have been inspired to mimic its
advertising strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Not so widely advertised is the giant grain processor's success
in seeding politicians of both parties with contributions and
lobbying to insure that its interests are attended to in
Washington; its television commercials fit snugly into that
high-power campaign. Such exertions are meant in part to repair the
image of big-scale price-fixing, for which Archer Daniels was fined
$100 million in 1996, an embarrassment that was recalled this month
by the Chicago trial of three former Archer Daniels executives.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution played a videotape that it says showed the
executives and their confreres from a major competitor, Ajinimoto
Co. of Japan, haggling over controlling the world market of a feed
additive called lysine. The executives having pleaded not guilty,
one must withhold judgment as to their culpability, but readers of
Kurt Eichenwald's report in The New York Times may have been struck
by a comment (caught on tape) to the Japanese executives by James
Randall, at the time the president of Archer Daniels: ``Our
competitors are our friends and our customers are our enemies.'' A
zippy line, worthy of the people who came up with ``supermarket to
the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Such blips are not noted in the commercials that extol Archer
Daniels as a global savior. Advertising professionals, after all,
are not in the business of biting the hand that feeds the world.
Archer Daniels is engaged in chronic image enhancement, identifying
itself with such respected institutions as ABC's ``This Week,''
NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and of course PBS's ``Newshour.'' It's a
form of lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   The contaminating influence of Archer Daniels is not confined to
price-fixing. Many admirers of David Brinkley were distressed early
this year to learn that he was capping his career in journalism by
signing on with Archer Daniels, even though his words were crafted
as infomercials with no direct plug for the company. He was being
used in much the way his former program, ``This Week,'' is used, as
a reach for reputation by association. The resultant criticism
caused ABC to drop the Brinkley psuedo-commercials for a while, but
they can now be seen, ``on behalf of ADM,'' on at least three
Sunday network programs, including ``This Week.'' All is forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated audience that depends on the Sunday morning
interviews to explore Monica Lewinsky and other ethical issues
understands that the programs, whatever their other qualities, also
do what they have to do to stay in business. If the revered
Brinkley, too, chooses to turn himself into a commercial enterprise
by selling his reputation to Archer Daniels, that's a reward of
stardom.
</P>
<P>
   When we come to public broadcasting, however, the apologia is
uncomfortable. The tendency in recent years has been for public
broadcasters to carry ever more expansive commercials, which go
smack against the rationale for what in more wishful times was
known as noncommercial television.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, public broadcasting, perpetually underfinanced and
scraping for cash with begfests and potboilers (even now on show),
needs the money. Alas, like everything else in the market, that
does not come free. As originally conceived, the hope of public
broadcasting was not just that it would supply programs that could
not make it in the marketplace, but that it would also respect its
audience by eliminating the hokum of advertising. PBS would be a
commercial-free, hypocrisy-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   But the tendency has been to make nonprofit broadcasting sound
ever more like for-profit broadcasting. Since the commercial has
become an accepted element on PBS, admirers of Jim Lehrer &AMP; Co.
must resign themselves to hearing senseless slogans as the price of
admission. Even when they do not achieve the rhapsodic appeal of
Archer Daniels, financial institutions in particular use vapid
pomposities as a sure route to the pockets of the moneyed classes.
Every night during ``Newshour,'' for example, Salomon Smith Barney
announces, ``Success is earned.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely if there is an implicit contract between viewers and
public broadcasters it must contain a provision against treating
the audience like saps. As the PBS promotions, which are themselves
increasingly adding to the on-screen clutter, put the case, ``If
PBS doesn't do it, who will?'' But no surge of resistance to hype
is observable. The underwriters' slogans go down easily in a nation
dosed on ``supermarket to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, PBS programs are not interrupted by such ``messages'';
with adroit use of the mute button, you can spare yourself bushwa
to the effect that ``At the CIT Group, we believe that growth
begins with money well lent.'' And Jim Lehrer is not about to sign
on with Archer Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the direction is dire. (``The Nightly Business Report'' is
already a supermarket of plugs.) The commercialization is a bow to
reality: the nation doesn't want the purer form of television
enough to pay for it, and the merger of PBS ideals and business
interests is swallowed as readily as the Archer Daniels-Brinkley
merger.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether PBS programmers can remain uninfluenced
by corporate largess in their choice of subjects to play up and
those to avoid and the spirit in which business news in particular
is treated.
</P>
<P>
   Can seepage into programming be resisted? On that account, an
analysis on ``Newshour'' of the motives, techniques and impact of
the advertising increasingly being directed at viewers like us
would be enlightening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
