<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERMELON-SALAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SOUL OF SUMMER IN A BURST OF SERENDIPITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ How rare it is to come across a restaurant dish that
leaves you feeling refreshed as well as satisfied. Sensations are
deeply layered in Patroon's tomato watermelon salad: it is sweet
and wet, cool and filling all at once.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Zackarian, the chef at the restaurant, at 160 East 46th
Street, said that one day recently the kitchen was loaded down with
tomatoes and watermelon. So, in the free spirit of summer, he
decided to combine the two.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting salad looks like a plate of glistening jewels,
with heirloom tomatoes (green, purple pear, jelly bean, yellow
pepper, yellow currant and red currant), yellow watermelon, basil,
currants, lamb's-quarters and mango.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bit of a hodgepodge, perhaps, but one that definitely
works _ and, it turns out, is easy to prepare. The acidity in the
tomatoes and the sugar in the watermelon keep each other in check,
the lamb's-quarters help the dish maintain the feeling of a salad,
rather than a fruit cup, and Lebanese extra virgin olive oil
smooths out any rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   It is an exquisite final burst of summer, and if you're staying
for a full meal at Patroon, your only chance at spa food before one
of Patroon's monstrous steaks arrives at the table. The salad,
which costs $10, will be on the menu until tomatoes run out,
sometime in September. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO WATERMELON SALAD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Geoffrey Zackarian, Patroon &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3 cups mixed heirloom tomatoes (green, purple pear, jelly bean,
yellow pepper, yellow currant and red currant), cut into wedges,
thin slices, { inch cubes or in half, depending on the size
</P>
<P>
   2 cups yellow or red seedless watermelon, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons champagne grapes or currants
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons mango cut into \ inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon white wine vinegar, more to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2{ tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon crushed coriander seed, more &QL; 
to taste
</P>
<P>
   Coarsely ground white pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 large basil leaves, torn into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 handful lamb's-quarters leaves
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt, to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large stainless steel bowl, combine tomatoes,
watermelon, grapes, mango, vinegar, brown sugar, olive oil and
coriander. Toss gently to mix. Season to taste with pepper and more
coriander, if desired. Divide basil and lamb's-quarters among four
shallow bowls. Arrange salad on top of leaves. Season with salt,
and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
