<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLAN-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSE LAWYER IN KLAN TRIAL CHARGES POLITICAL PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ Minutes after Sam Bowers's lawyer began his
defense Tuesday by denouncing the aging Ku Klux Klan leader's
murder trial as a ``media-orchestrated and politically driven
prosecution _ a persecution,'' state prosecutors began laying out a
tapestry of testimony designed to link Bowers to the fatal
firebombing in 1966 of a local civil rights leader.
</P>
<P>
   In his opening argument, Travis Buckley, a quintessential
country lawyer who represents Bowers and has his own background as
a defendant in Klan cases, accused the state of ``appealing to
emotions'' and knuckling under to pressures to pursue the
32-year-old case involving the death of Vernon Dahmer, president of
the local NAACP chapter.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley, 63, was once indicted himself in the Dahmer case and
later convicted of kidnapping in another trial that grew out of an
attempt to intimidate a fellow Klansman in Bowers's unit. According
to a previous account by Billy Roy Pitts, a former Klansman
expected to testify against Bowers this week, the lawyer brandished
a hunting knife while Pitts administered a beating and Bowers
watched in an incident that took place in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley's conviction was overturned by the Mississippi Supreme
Court and he has been able to continue to practice law.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley is a long-time associate of Bowers in Laurel, a tough,
working-class city in Jones County, 35 miles north of Hattiesburg.
After Dahmer's murder, the attorney told a local radio station in
1966 that FBI agents knew who was responsible but would not move on
the killers because it would be damaging to President Lyndon B.
Johnson and ``the racial-radical civil rights organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Buckley had new theories in the case that has attracted
widespread attention in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Though Buckley did not mention Mississippi Attorney General Mike
Moore by name in his courtroom remarks, his reference to political
motivation was implicit because Moore has expressed interest in
seeking the Democratic nomination for governor in 1999. Moore's
decision a year ago to throw the weight of his office behind the
investigation was instrumental in bringing Bowers back to trial
three decades after he escaped conviction in three separate
mistrials.
</P>
<P>
   Since Mississippi is a state where a third of voters are black,
Buckley seemed to be suggesting that Moore was making an overt
appeal for black votes. Moore was not in the courtroom, but one of
his assistants is helping the county prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers's attorney also singled out Jerry Mitchell, a reporter
for The Clarion Ledger newspaper in Jackson, for stoking interest
in the case. Mitchell has written a number of articles about the
Dahmer case since his reporting helped create a climate for the
1994 retrial of Byron de la Beckwith, another white supremacist,
that resulted in Beckwith's conviction for the assassination of
another NAACP leader, Medgar Evers, 30 years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith was sentenced to life imprisonment, and there are
echoes of his case in the prosecution of Bowers. Although Bowers is
charged with murder, the state is not seeking the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   After the selection of a racially mixed jury _ six whites, five
blacks, and one Asian-American _ was completed, the prosecution
began its case by setting the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two a.m. A cold January morning,'' said assistant district
attorney Robert Helfrich, speaking in a quiet, laconic manner.
``Two cars with heavily armed Klansmen, Unit 4, Jones County White
Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, attacked the Dahmer property. They
came armed with pistols, shotguns, and 12 gallons of gasoline.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer died hours after his rural home near here was firebombed,
his lungs seared by flames.
</P>
<P>
   Helfrich promised that witnesses would relate details of the
raid, and declared that the testimony would show ``the attack was
ordered by this defendant, the imperial wizard of the White Knights
of the Ku Klux Klan.'' Across the courtroom, the 73-year-old Bowers
stared impassively.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckley countered that some of the state witnesses,
including the former Klansman Pitts, who have agreed to cooperate
with the prosecution, were ``like fish with a hook caught in their
mouth _ they'll go anywhere they're told to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The first three witnesses were members of Dahmer's family: his
widow, a son, and a daughter. They testified how Dahmer had fired
shots to defend the house and helped them through windows of the
burning building.
</P>
<P>
   Bettie Dahmer, who was 10 years old at the time of the
firebombing, tearfully recalled how her father sat on a bale of hay
in the relative safety of a barn behind the house after the
nightriders fled. ``I saw my house burning,'' she said. ``I saw
skin hanging off my daddy's arm.''
</P>
<P>
   When Buckley cross-examined the witness, he created the first
sparks of the trial. Although he expressed regret over Dahmer's
death, he and Dahmer's daughter clashed over whether the case
should be pursued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to see my daddy done justice, just like everybody
else in America,'' she said. When Buckley remarked that nothing
could bring Dahmer back from the dead, she wiped away tears and
replied, ``That's right. Once he was dead, he was dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
