<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9981 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-GOLF-TE     08-18 1615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-GOLF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS GOLF THE LAST BASTION OF GOOD SPORTSMANSHIP?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The long history of professional golf has been so pure, so
apparently free of unsportsmanlike incidents on the course, that
what went down on an August day in 1995 in Akron, Ohio, had
everybody in shock.
</P>
<P>
   One touring pro accused another of cheating.
</P>
<P>
   To the novice, unfamiliar with the game's code of honor, it
might have seemed like a small thing. Greg Norman accused fellow
PGA Tour veteran Mark McCumber of touching his own putting line on
a seven-foot par putt during a round of the World Series of Golf.
</P>
<P>
   What it amounted to was this: Norman believed that McCumber
touched a piece of grass in the line of his putt, a violation of
golf rules. McCumber said Norman was mistaken; he had merely
squashed a bug.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the vile conduct exhibited in other sports _
taunting, spitting, brawling _ it was almost hopelessly quaint. But
in golf, it caused an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Norman refused to sign McCumber's scorecard. He even considered
withdrawing from the event because he was so upset. McCumber was
forced to defend his honor in public.
</P>
<P>
   While their positions on the incident differed, Norman and
McCumber agreed on the importance of the issue. And that spoke
volumes about how golf is different from other sports when it comes
to sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do what is the right thing, the game might get
away from us,'' said Norman, speaking of the need to protect the
integrity of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is played as a game of honor, and you have to rely on
the other players to go that way,'' said McCumber, adding, ``My
life speaks for itself. I have nothing to defend, nothing at all.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine Dennis Rodman taking a head-butting act so
to heart. But that is basketball, and this is golf, perhaps the
last bastion of sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   The norm in golf is to abide by both the letter and spirit of
the law, golfers maintain. Even if no one else in the world would
know you're breaking the rules. Even if it would help you make a
lot of money, or win a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Gay Brewer, the 1967 Masters Tournament champion and now a
member of the Senior PGA Tour, recalled being paired with Bruce
Crampton for the final round of the 1998 Southwestern Bell Dominion
tournament in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   At the ninth hole, Crampton's tee shot caromed off a tree into a
hazard. While Crampton headed to his ball, Brewer set out down the
other side of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Brewer turned and spotted Crampton chipping out
of the hazard. Brewer saw Crampton reach the green on the par-5
hole with his third shot, then watched him sink a long putt for
what he figured was a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned to him and said, `Man, that was some birdie,'''
Brewer recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `That was a six.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Puzzled, Brewer asked what had happened. Crampton told him that
his caddie had removed a branch from the hazard while he was
preparing to hit his second shot, a two-stroke penalty under the
rules of golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called it on himself, and nobody even saw it,'' Brewer
said. ``The ball never moved. But if you pick something up in the
hazard, it's a two-shot penalty. The (caddie) was young and didn't
know what he was doing. It didn't affect his shot at all, but
that's the rule, so he called it on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way these guys are. If you don't call it, you've
got to sleep with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We pride ourselves a lot on that,'' PGA Tour commissioner Tom
Finchem said of sportsmanship's role in golf.
</P>
<P>
   Finchem attributes the level of honor in the game to ``the
caliber of people who play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're blessed compared to other sports,'' Finchem said. ``Our
players are mature, educated. They've finished college, by and
large. To play the game at their level, you have a certain
evenness, a certain amount of restraint and control of your
emotions. If you don't, you can't play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think golf is such a game of discipline that it disciplines
everybody,'' said Gary Player, one of only four players to win each
of golf's four major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Finchem said there is a practical, economic reason for golf to
maintain its tradition of sportsmanlike behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the image of the players, as it contrasts to other
sports, gives us a significant leg up in the marketplace,'' Finchem
said. ``There is no hesitation by governments or by corporate
America to be involved in our sport because of that image.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf has had its share of hot-tempered individuals through the
years. ``Terrible'' Tommy Bolt and his club-tossing comes to mind.
Tom Weiskopf also flashed his emotions at times. There is even the
story of a skirmish between J.C. Snead and Dave Hill at a 1991
Senior PGA Tour event in Napa, Calif. There, an errant drive struck
on the practice range by Snead is reported to have incensed Hill
and led to what, for golf, amounted to a donnybrook as the two
tussled to the ground with spectators watching in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   Golf has also witnessed occasional acts of gamesmanship,
intentional or not. The best recent example came at last year's
Ryder Cup matches when Scotland's Colin Montgomerie appeared, in
interviews, to question the ability of certain Americans to perform
under pressure in the U.S.-European international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did American players react negatively to Monty's
assessments, galleries at PGA Tour events picked up on his
observations and began to ride Montgomery verbally on the course.
</P>
<P>
   At the U.S. Open this year, one gallery member even told
Montgomery to ``go home.'' When a shocked Montgomery asked the fan
why he should, the fan replied: ``Because of the Ryder Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the tiff between golf fans and players was about as
unusual as Montgomery's frank assessment of the American team. In
no other sport are spectators and athletes as close to one another
as in golf, yet there have been few incidents of disrespect _ other
than an occasional murmur in the crowd during a shot, or a clicking
camera.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the now-standard shouts of ``You da man!'' still come
after a swing is completed, although there is growing concern that
inappropriate behavior might be on the rise, particularly among
alcohol-consuming spectators.
</P>
<P>
   In the main, though, golf is worlds apart from the on-field and
on-court antics of other major sports. Even in another country-club
sport, tennis, sportsmanship has declined.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, players have thrown their rackets at officials,
cursed linesmen, baited opponents and tanked matches. Bad boys such
as Ilie Nastase, John McEnroe and Jimmy Connors all were
celebrated, not just for their winning performances, but for their
breath-of-fresh-air attitudes toward what some regarded as a far
too stuffy sport.
</P>
<P>
   Women's tennis, which has lagged the men's game in
unsportsmanlike behavior, appears to be following suit. Venus
Williams' temper tantrum at this summer's Wimbledon tournament was
the latest in a growing list of examples of poor behavior on the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times have changed,'' tennis great Billie Jean King says.
``Women's tennis is becoming more like the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf has seen no such decline.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if sportsmanship in golf is unique among sports, LPGA
player Laura Davies said, ``I think so, definitely. There are no
referees in golf, for one thing, so it's up to each player to play
by the rules. There's not another sport like it.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU graduate and 1971 Masters winner Charles Coody explained,
``It's just that golf is an ethical sport and players do their best
to keep it that way. Maybe a guy might bend a rule here or there,''
Coody said, ``whether it was intentional or unintentional. But if
he does, another golfer will go up and say something to him on the
side. That's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Golfers don't just observe good sportsmanship by adhering to the
rules.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1969 Ryder Cup, an international competition that then
pitted a squad of top U.S. golfers against the best of Great
Britain, Jack Nicklaus and England's Tony Jacklin came down to the
final hole in the final match all square, with the Cup at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus knocked down a four-foot putt for par, seemingly
placing extraordinary pressure on Jacklin, who needed a two-footer
to give the British a tie.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicklaus, in an extraordinary display of sportsmanship,
conceded the putt, allowing the draw.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, in golf's most prestigious championship, the U.S.
Open, Tom Lehman and Steve Jones battled each other as playing
partners throughout the final round. Neither had won a major title
at the time, but Jones might have been more eager because he had
been out of the spotlight and winners' circle for a longer period.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jones was his foe on the course, Lehman went out of his
way to calm his friend down on the back nine holes, giving him
comfort and encouragement that likely helped Jones to the biggest
victory of his career. Lehman still hasn't won the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Grace in the most dire of circumstances continues to be on
display on the PGA Tour. This year, for example, area fans got to
watch Plano's Fred Couples cope publicly with a disappointing loss
at the Masters and, just a month later, another wrenching loss at
the GTE Byron Nelson Classic in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, Couples faced the media with class, though he may
have wanted to toss his bag in a lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf's been a gentleman's game ever since it started,'' Brewer
said. ``It still is. I think it always will be.''
</P>
<P>
   (Staff writer Jimmy Burch contributed to this report.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
