<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ARREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S MOST-WANTED CAPTURED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Daniel Arizmendi Lopez, Mexico's most notorious
fugitive and the alleged leader of a kidnapping ring known for
cutting off victims' ears to get families to pay ransoms, has been
captured, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old suspect, who has been accused of masterminding
dozens of kidnappings in recent years, was caught Monday night in
the northwestern Mexico City suburb of Naucalpan, the federal
attorney general, Jorge Madrazo, said Tuesday at a press
conference. Another 16 people, including Arizmendi's girlfriend and
six minors who are believed to be connected to the kidnapping ring,
were also detained that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that with the work we have done so far,'' said
Samuel Gonzalez, chief of the federal organized crime unit, the
suspects ``will receive thousands of years in jail, and this is a
great effort to bring down this kind of impunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has seized about $5.7 million in cash, more than
100 one-ounce gold coins, and 25 houses.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Arizmendi's younger brother and alleged chief accomplice,
Aurelio, has said that the gang had cut off the ears of eight
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi's arrest ended an intense nationwide manhunt that had
grown increasingly dramatic over the last three months as
investigators from various federal and state police agencies closed
in on their suspect. But as details of the arrest were released
Tuesday, it appeared that the country's most wanted criminal was
caught not with a bang but in a quiet and high-tech manner.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview broadcast Tuesday afternoon by the network Radio
Red, Jorge Reyes Satayna, attorney general for the state of Mexico,
said police had tracked Arizmendi via a cellular telephone call
that he made late Monday to his accomplices, whom police had
arrested without his knowledge. When Arizmendi arrived at the
hideout later, about a dozen officers were waiting for him. He was
arrested without incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operation was so efficient that there was no violence,''
Satayna said. ``Arizmendi arrived in a disguise and didn't put up
any resistance. He was arrested easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi, wearing a beard and shoulder-length hair, arrived in
Mexico City Tuesday in shackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess today was a day of bad luck for me,'' he said in a
brief interview with TV Azteca.
</P>
<P>
   In May, law enforcement officials raided a half-dozen of
Arizmendi's hideouts and captured his wife and children, but failed
to catch Arizmendi, who slipped away in a stolen car. In late June,
police arrested Aurelio after an afternoon sidewalk shootout. And
last month, officials arrested Arizmendi's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi, a former Morelos state police officer, had become a
symbol of the crime epidemic that has swept through country since
the economic crisis of 1994. In a newspaper interview this summer,
he said he ``would rather be killed than go to jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities also have voiced hope that the arrests would help
change the image of corrupt police. Arizmendi allegedly paid
several rank-and-file and top officers to either carry out
kidnappings or to provide him with tips on the investigations to
help him avoid being caught.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo said that almost 40 members of the Arizmendi ring had
been arrested, and that 80 people have come forward claiming to be
victims and seeking their share of the recovered ransom.
</P>
<P>
   This month, Madrazo added, the gang kidnapped the son of a
wealthy gasoline executive and demanded a $15 million ransom from
the family despite having killed the victim the day of the
kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the news of Arizmendi's arrest, Mexico City is still
vexed with law enforcement problems. Dozens of brief kidnappings
and robberies committed in stolen taxis are reported daily, and a
record 120 bank robberies have been committed this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Arizmendi's arrest on Monday, the federal
government and the Mexico City mayor's office announced plans to
invest more than $28 million to bolster anti-crime programs in
Mexico City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
