<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9988 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT &LR;      08-18 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMBATIVE CLINTON RANCOR AGAINST STARR SUGGESTS CONTINUING
TENSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES
with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS, NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(JT) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Far from signaling the beginning of the end of the
Monica Lewinsky investigation, Monday's testimony and speech by
President Clinton, may only have ratcheted up the tensions between
him and the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The combative tone of the president's speech, in which he
continued to attack Starr as overzealous and partisan, was one sign
of continuing rancor. Another was the readiness of the special
prosecutor to press on with his investigation, calling Richard
Morris, former Clinton political adviser, before the grand jury on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm reminded of two heavyweights who are determined to go
fifteen rounds,'' said Stanley Brand, a Democratic lawyer who
served as general counsel to the House of Representatives.
``Whoever wins, they are both going to be terribly bruised at the
end of the fight. And the two institutions will never be the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, several lawyers said, the battle between the
president and the special prosecutor could become even uglier, a
prospect no one relishes. One key reason would be the questions the
president did not answer, though it is not clear just what they
were.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel might decide that the president's
answers during his unprecedented grand jury testimony on Monday
were insufficient and Starr could move to reissue the subpoena that
he withdrew after the president agreed to testify.
</P>
<P>
   The White House could claim that such a subpoena is
unconstitutional and force another legal confrontation with Starr
lasting many more weeks. At the same time, it could spread the
story that all Starr wanted was more prurient details, a charge he
would find hard to rebut, even if false, because Judge Norma
Holloway Johnson is angry over leaks from his office.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Starr decides to wind down his investigation and file a
report with the House of Representatives, Clinton will surely paint
any impeachment referral to the House as a further intrusion into
his private life. Fighting in a political arena, he may enjoy the
upper hand. Starr, in turn, is likely to add weight to suspicions
that the president lied and covered up a relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky, framing his report around
perjury and obstruction of justice, not sex.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the immediate outcome, lawyers interviewed about the
long term effects of Starr's seven-month-long sex and perjury
investigation said that both institutions at the center of the
legal storm, the presidency and the office of the independent
counsel, had been grievously harmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both have been seriously hurt,'' said C. Boyden Gray, who
served as White House counsel to President Bush. Gray said he
doubted the independent counsel statue would be reauthorized when
it is set to be renewed in two years. He also said that the White
House's losing court battles to assert attorney-client privilege,
executive privilege and a protective privilege for the Secret
Service had all diminished the office of the presidency itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House made a big mistake in litigating all these
things because it has weakened the presidency,'' Gray said.
``There's been a cutback in the leverage and bargaining power.
These things have been lost forever for every future president.
It's now clearly law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Cutler, a Democratic lawyer who served as Clinton's second
White House counsel, agreed that the court fights over these
privileges had hurt the office of the presidency in both the near
and long term, though he said the White House was not wrong to
litigate them. He emphasized a lack of prosecutorial discretion on
Starr's part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has ever pushed the envelope so far,'' Cutler said.
``No president has ever been subpoenaed before to testify about his
own alleged criminal conduct. I don't question the independent
counsel's right to do so. But there is such a thing as
prosecutorial discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   In resisting the independent counsel's attempts to question his
closest advisers and the agents who protect him, Clinton has
portrayed himself as fighting for political survival, against what
he and his wife have characterized as an unfairly intrusive,
partisan witch-hunt.
</P>
<P>
   The suspicions of bad faith on both sides have meant that the
White House and the independent counsel have both been determined
to fight every issue to the hilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of them wants to give an inch,'' said E. Lawrence
Barcella Jr., a former federal prosecutor, who likened the struggle
to a cafeteria food fight. ``The independent counsel isn't going to
develop perspective and restraint he never had and the president
isn't suddenly going to decide to give in to this four-year
obsession.''
</P>
<P>
   While few would predict a victor in the battle, there was wide
agreement that when the independent counsel statute comes up for
re-authorization next year, it will face dim prospects for renewal
in its current form. Even Lawrence Walsh, the independent counsel
who spent six years and $40 million investigating the Iran-contra
affair, said he felt the statute should only apply to offenses
committed sitting presidents relating to their official duties. He
also said he worried that a long-term consequence of the Lewinsky
investigation was ``the burlesquing of law enforcement in this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the inner workings of the White House have already
been affected by years of investigative scrutiny. For example,
White House lawyers are now careful not to take notes, Cutler said.
``When the attorney-client privilege with a government lawyer is
virtually destroyed, that means you don't dare take notes,'' he
explained. ``You are going to be cautious about what you say and
the president will be cautious about what he tells you. That's a
serious blow to the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   However the battle between Clinton and Starr is decided, its
levels of harsh rhetoric and polarizing effects have further
coarsened the tone of political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This episode, however it turns out, will be listed along with
Watergate and the Vietnam War as another benchmark of our cynicism
toward our institutions,'' lamented Sen. Fred Thompson, the
Republican chairman of the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee, a
former prosecutor who is thought to be considering a run for the
White House. ``It's another one of those public, traumatic events,
whatever or whoever's side you are on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
