<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-MAIN-0819     08-18 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-MAIN-0819 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    CLINTON STRIVES TO SURVIVE SCANDAL
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON In the aftermath of his secret grand jury testimony
and his admission of having lied to the public about his affair
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, President Clinton
urgently sought on Tuesday to rally his political supporters and
salvage what remains of his beleaguered presidency.
</P>
<P>
   While in his Monday night remarks Clinton had forcefully called
for independent counsel Kenneth Starr to end his investigation and
for the nation to ``turn away from the spectacle of the past seven
months,'' there were signs that his call would not be heeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over,'' one senior Democrat, Rep. Lee Hamilton of
Indiana, cautioned in undermining Clinton's bid to declare a
unilateral end to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Another Democrat, retiring Rep. Paul McHale of Pennsylvania,
said ``perjury is not excused by an apology compelled by
overwhelming evidence and delivered under pressure.'' Clinton, he
added, ``should resign or face impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Alone among congressional Republican leaders, House Republican
Whip Tom DeLay of Texas called on Clinton to resign. ``Clearly, the
president has done irreparable damage to the office of the
presidency. More troubling, the president has lied to his family,
his friends, his Cabinet, the Congress and the American people,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But House Speaker Newt Gingrich cautioned fellow Republicans to
reserve final judgment on the president until they receive Starr's
investigative report, expected within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that everyone would be best served if they waited for
Judge Starr's report and found out what all the facts were,''
Gingrich told reporters in his native Georgia. ``We'd all like to
get that done as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Tuesday, First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, through
her spokeswoman Marsha Berry, said she ``believes in this
marriage'' despite her husband's most recent infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her love for him is compassionate and steadfast,'' Berry said,
adding that Mrs. Clinton has forgiven her husband. ``She clearly is
uncomfortable with her personal life being made so public.''
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's mid-afternoon departure for a 12-day vacation on
Martha's Vineyard, accompanied hand-in-hand by his wife and
daughter Chelsea, the focus returned to Starr and the legal options
open to the independent counsel in pursuing a perjury and
obstruction of justice case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Starr promptly summoned Lewinsky, the 25-year-old woman behind
the scandal, to testify again on Thursday before the grand jury
under a broad grant of immunity. She had already told the grand
jury that she had a affair with Clinton, which the president
characterized on Monday as a liaison that was ``not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   After Lewinsky testifies anew, Starr must decide whether to seek
a subpoena that would force the president to answer specific
questions about the sexual nature of his 18-month relationship with
her. Clinton's personal lawyers would almost certainly challenge
any such subpoena, which could drag out the case further while
raising fresh constitutional issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private attorney David Kendall acknowledged that the
president did not answer in detail ``a very few highly intrusive
</P>
<P>
   questions'' put to him in his session with Starr's prosecutorial
team in the Map Room of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Both Clinton and Lewinsky had denied the affair under oath in
January in statements in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit.
But Lewinsky told the grand jurors on Aug. 6 that the two did in
fact have a sexual relationship and that they had discussed ways of
covering it up.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the grand jury continued to meet on Tuesday, hearing,
for more than four hours, former Clinton adviser Dick Morris
describe his conversations with the president shortly after the
scandal broke in January. Morris, a former Clinton political
strategist, resigned from the re-election campaign in 1996 over his
own sexual scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not Starr succeeds in eliciting further testimony
from Clinton, he is well along in writing a report to Congress,
which should reach the lawmakers by mid-September. They must then
decide whether to deal with it quickly or to hold it in abeyance
beyond November's mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
   On that score, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who chairs the House
Judiciary Committee, said on Tuesday that it would be foolish to
speculate now on how Congress will proceed until Starr actually
submits his report.
</P>
<P>
   ``If and when the independent counsel sends such a report, it is
reasonable to expect answers to many as yet unanswered questions,''
Hyde said. ``It is our constitutional duty to provide a fair, full
and independent review of these facts in their proper context.'' he
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The law under which Starr was named requires that such a report
be based on ``substantial and credible evidence'' that the
president committed an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clinton is able to duck a full-scale impeachment
hearing, he must still show that he is an effective leader in light
of the damage cause by the Lewinsky affair and the subsequent
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, that process began on Tuesday with calls to more
than a dozen key Democratic members of Congress who have been his
most stalwart supporters.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Mike McCurry said Clinton was ``very
encouraged by these exchanges'' in which the president again voiced
his regret over what he had done and accepted responsibility for
his actions.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also apologized individually to several senior members
of his staff who had been most vocal in their public backing of his
denials over the seven months since the scandal broke, McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
   The president has placed a ``top priority'' on making amends to
Hillary, his wife of 20 years, and 18-year-old Chelsea, who will
begin her sophomore year at Stanford in September.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, the first lady's press secretary, said that Mrs. Clinton
still loved her husband deeply and was committed to him. ``This has
certainly not been the best day of her life,'' Berry said, but
added that she had a strong religious faith upon which she relied.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
