u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-VOICES-ART-64     08-18 1288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VOICES-ART-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY AFTER, CLINTON DEFENDERS FEEL BETRAYED, FOOLISH, CONFUSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-RDP, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-PUNDITS,
NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ For her loyalty to the president, Mary Allen had
endured the snickers and condescending smirks from friends, a
sister, her husband.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Democrat, she spent seven months believing and
defending Bill Clinton's denials of a sexual relationship with a
former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I feel pretty foolish,'' said Ms. Allen.
</P>
<P>
   As the 41-year-old woman watched President Clinton acknowledge
on television Monday that he ``misled people'' about his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, she simply shook her head with
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Like the majority of Americans, Ms. Allen does not believe the
president should lose his job, or that the investigation
spearheaded by Ken Starr has been worth the time and money spent.
In fact, she still believes Clinton has done a good job as a world
leader and steward of the nation's economy.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she will never trust him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked us right in the eye and lied to us,'' said Ms.
Allen, recalling the president's impassioned, finger-wagging, ``now
listen to me'' insistence that he had never had sexual relations
with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In this old Middle American city of smokestacks and church
spires, a hard-working place famous for making Harley Davidson
motorcycles and Miller beer, people seemed intrigued with the
steamy details of the president's predicament, even as they
professed a weariness about the long-running national soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   To most people, it amounts to a sorry mess that has no heroes
and plenty of villains: a flawed president, an overzealous
prosecutor, back stabbing co-workers, arrogant lawyers, spin
artists and intrusive journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from more than two dozen interviews in this metropolis
of about 1.4 million people _ at outdoor cafes on the trendy East
Side, on the broom-swept sidewalks of immigrant neighborhoods, at
the campus of Marquette University, inside the gleaming shopping
malls on suburban Bluemound Road _ many voters found Clinton's
televised talk to be rather disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   Most also expressed alarm at the president's apparent
recklessness and said they were disappointed in his actions, his
foot-dragging and what they saw as his half-hearted apology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't help himself with this speech,'' said Terry Welch,
45, whose family owns a business that makes leather finishes in
Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Characterizing the president's talk as more legalistic than
candid, Welch said Clinton is becoming something of a parody.
``When you have to listen to his tenses of speech _ subjunctive?
conditional? _ you've got some problems with credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The host of a radio call-in show on WISN, Jerry Bott, noted that
Clinton's speech were conspicuously missing two words: ``I'm
sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   A caller named Patrice said she was angry about the president's
tone. ``He was defiant,'' she said, ``like he dared us to even
question him.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of voters say the president's private life is nobody's
business but his family's. Clinton's defenders, and even a few of
his political foes, expressed concern about a 90s brand of
McCarthyism _ inquisitors searching under every bed, not for
Communists, but for paramours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a right to know who he's sleeping with,'' said
Jeff England, a 35-year-old stock trader. ``It makes government so
frivolous.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Van Hoof, a 45-year-old architect who lives in the leafy
Shorewood community along Lake Michigan, said there is a simple
explanation for Clinton's actions. ``Guys cheat on their wives,
that's just the way the world works,'' said Hoof, a married man,
who excepted himself from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But others accepted no such excuses. George Ziedonis, a
41-year-old warehouse worker who clutched a thermos as he waited
for the 7 a.m. bus, said Clinton's performance on Monday night was
characteristically riddled with wiggle words.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was true to form,'' said Ziedonis. ``He never tells the
whole truth. He lives in a fantasy world where he thinks he can go
by his own rules.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   To most people who voiced anger about Clinton, it was the lying
more than any sexual misdeed that caused the most harm.
</P>
<P>
   A city with strong Democratic leanings and a tavern on almost
every corner, Milwaukee is nonetheless known as a well-behaved,
follow-the-rules kind of town, a place where immigrants from
Germany and Eastern Europe brought their children up to respect the
flag, the police and the church. Milwaukeeans do not generally
tolerate the sorts of political shenanigans that are commonplace in
cities like Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of Clinton's address to the nation, the Milwaukee
Journal-Sentinel, a newspaper that has generally been friendly to
the president, published a searing editorial under the headline, ``
President, we've had enough.'' The next day, the newspaper's
editorial was titled, ``Clinton's speech falls woefully short.''
</P>
<P>
   If conservatives and liberals agree about anything on this case,
it is a shared lamentation that children can no longer read
newspapers or watch the television news without being confronted
with the sort of sexual talk that used to make people blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine Walter Cronkite talking about oral sex and
semen stains?'' said Welch, the business owner.
</P>
<P>
   But on the campus of Marquette University, a Roman Catholic
institution run by the same Jesuit order of priests that educated
Clinton at Georgetown, young people say the Lewinsky case simply
reflects a looser culture, but did not shape it.
</P>
<P>
   Robyn Coleman, a 22-year-old physical therapy major at
Marquette, noted that most young people grew up watching such
risque shows as ``Melrose Place'' and ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' She
said Jerry Springer's show, a wild, profane tabloid talk show that
almost always focuses on sex, is the hottest show on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex is just part of life,'' said Ms. Coleman. ``People aren't
embarrassed to talk with each other about it. Unless maybe it's
with your parents, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sordid case, the deepest sympathies among voters,
Democrats and Republicans, lie with the president's daughter,
Chelsea, a student at Stanford University. Most people voice
support for Mrs. Clinton. But there is even some measure of
disappointment with her.
</P>
<P>
   To Ms. Allen, the suburban homemaker, Mrs. Clinton has
disappointed those who cheered her as a symbol of strong womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's lost credibility on women's rights,'' said Ms. Allen,
the mother of two young children. ``How can you have any respect
for a woman who puts up with a marriage like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Ralph Gross, a man who is in the business of hearing
confessions, voiced concern over the sense of righteousness and
angry judgment that seems to prevail among many Americans today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm troubled by this hunger for details,'' said the
54-year-old Catholic priest, adding that Clinton's acknowledgment
of having done wrong should suffice, without a specific accounting
of sexual misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must be very careful about making judgments. People
struggle with different parts of their lives. For some people, it's
lust. For others, its racism or sexism. Let's be forgiving and
leave the judging to God.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
