<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CABINET-NYT     08-18 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CABINET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABINET MEMBERS STAND BY CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES
with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS, CLINTON-CABINET, NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A day after President Clinton's speech to the nation on his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, members of his Cabinet who
expressed strong support for him after learning of the allegations
in January had this to say Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   William M. Daley, Secretary of Commerce:
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a very difficult thing for the president, to address
the people and apologize for his actions. It's a difficult thing
for him, for his family, for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed the president in January, as did the vast majority
of the American people, according to the polls. He has now come
forward and stated the facts. His apology and his statement are
enough for me. The facts turned out to be different from what we
were told and believed. But there is no reason for us to dwell on
something that was said seven months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish the situation was what he said in January. But it
isn't. So let's move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction is one of sorrow. The president has apologized. He
wants to move on and do what the American people elected him to do
_ govern.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew M. Cuomo, Secretary of Housing and Urban Development:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's statement to the American people took real
courage. I respect and applaud him for taking responsibility for
his actions. My heart goes out to the president and his family at
this difficult time. The president has now spoken to the American
people. We should get on with the work of this nation, build on the
president's many achievements in office, and work to address the
serious issues that affect the lives of our people.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard W. Riley, Secretary of Education:
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made a a strong statement last night. He took
complete responsibility for what he called a `personal failure' on
his part. I am pleased that he came forward and took full
responsibility for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am relieved. We can now put this behind us so we can
continue to do our work on behalf of the American people. The
president's charge to the Cabinet all along has been to maintain
our focus on our work, and that's what I've been doing. Education
is a terribly important issue to the American people, and that's
where we need to keep our energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Madeleine K. Albright, Secretary of State, in Tanzania:
</P>
<P>
   ``This might not be the time or place to have this kind of
discussion. I have come to Africa on a mission of help and healing,
but I would like to state that I have complete confidence in the
president, and he is doing a terrific job for the United States,
both domestically and in terms of our foreign policy, and he has
urged all of us to put this behind us, and for all of us to do our
jobs, and that is what I think I am doing here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
