<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0303 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9996 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEART-BETA-BOS &LR;      08-18 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART-BETA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS CITE BENEFITS OF BETA BLOCKERS IN CORONARIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Americans die each year because doctors
fail to prescribe beta blocker drugs that can substantially improve
survival after a first heart attack, according to two reports that
are expected to reshape the way doctors treat heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   One of the studies, in the New England Journal of Medicine
published Wednesday, says the pills work so well that virtually
every heart attack patient should take them, even if they suffer
lung problems, diabetes or other severe conditions. Doctors
currently shy away from giving such patients beta blockers for fear
they will aggravate those conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The second report, in the Journal of the American Medical
Association, published Wednesday, also found strong evidence that
beta blockers are drastically underutilized. But it stopped short
of recommending use by heart attack survivors who have other severe
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Taken together, the two studies ``are going to wake up people,''
predicts Dr. Valentin Fuster, president of the American Heart
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened before is that many times we didn't give beta
blockers even to patients who didn't have risk factors. Now doctors
are going to be giving them,'' Fuster adds. ``If we do this right
we'll save tens of thousands of lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The JAMA study analyzed the nationwide pattern of use of beta
blockers, a class of drugs that lower blood pressure, reduce the
heart's demand for oxygen and otherwise spare it stress that can
produce additional attacks. The authors reviewed hospital discharge
records in 1994 and 1995 of 45,308 Medicaid patients who had
survived a heart attack and were considered ``ideal'' candidates
for beta blockers because they did not suffer severe asthma, very
low blood pressure or other conditions the drugs could aggravate.
</P>
<P>
   The most disturbing finding was that half of those elderly heart
attack survivors were not prescribed beta blockers when they
checked out of the hospital. The price they paid was clear: A year
after discharge, those who hadn't been given the drug were 14
percent less likely to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Use of the drugs varied by region: doctors in New England
prescribed them to 72.6 percent of their patients, compared to just
30.3 percent in Mississippi and 33.5 percent in Arkansas and
Oklahoma. Patients admitted by cardiologists and internists,
meanwhile, were much more likely to be prescribed beta blockers
than those admitted by general practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seems to be a huge opportunity to do better'' in getting
the drugs to patients who could benefit, concludes Dr. Harlan M.
Krumholz, lead author of the JAMA study and associate professor at
Yale University School of Medicine. ``We wouldn't accept this level
of problem with the airline industry. We're trying to develop
systems in medicine that enhance this decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   The New England Journal study examined 201,752 Medicaid records
of patients discharged after a heart attack, which included
patients who suffered other severe conditions that doctors fear
could make beta blockers dangerous. It zeroed in on a different
question: In the real world, do patients with such conditions
benefit from beta blockers despite the presumed risk?
</P>
<P>
   The answer was surprising and controversial. Patients with
pulmonary disease, diabetes and other ailments thought to preclude
them from taking beta blockers all had lower death rates taking the
drug than their counterparts who didn't. The reductions were as
high as 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Does that mean every heart attack survivor should be taking beta
blockers, regardless of their other medical problems?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is yes, since ``almost everybody'' will benefit,
argues Dr. Stephen S. Gottlieb, lead author of the New England
Journal study, which was released a day early to coincide with the
JAMA report. ``There are occasionally people who get side effects,
and if you're worried about somebody, watch them carefully. If
somebody does have side effects, you stop using the drug on that
particular person.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuster, the Heart Association president who runs the
Cardiovascular Institute at Mt. Sinai Medical Center in New York,
takes a similar view: ``You have to think about using beta blockers
on everybody, but using your clinical judgement. If a patient has
very severe cardiac failure or pulmonary disease, you might have to
be cautious.''
</P>
<P>
   Krumholz, who coauthored an editorial in the New England
Journal, is more reserved, echoing the recommendations of the Heart
Association and other groups. Gottlieb's study, Krumholz says,
fails to distinguish people with minor side effects from those with
severe ones. With the latter, he adds, ``it would be a mistake to
challenge them with beta blockers.''
</P>
<P>
   While they disagree about ``high-risk'' patients, those and
other heart specialists agree that far too few heart attack
survivors are taking beta blockers, in part because the pills are
available in generic form, which makes them so cheap that drug
companies feel it is unprofitable to promote them.
</P>
<P>
   A study released earlier this summer that doubted the
effectiveness of beta blockers also may have created confusion. But
that report dealt only with people who have high blood pressure but
not underlying heart troubles. ``There's no question in my mind
that beta blockers are a cornerstone for treatment'' in patients
who already have had a heart attack, says Dr. Franz Messerli,
author of that earlier study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
