<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-ECON-575&AMP;ADD-N     08-18 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN INVESTORS' WORRIES SLOW RUSSIA ON RESTRUCTURING PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE, RUSSIA-DEBT) 
(mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The Russian government Tuesday night put off the
announcement of its plan to restructure ruble-denominated
government debt, after alarm spread in the world's financial
community that Russia was prepared to discriminate against foreign
creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Boris Fyodorov, now in charge of Russian
economic policy, said he would first review the plan with
representatives of J.P. Morgan and Deutsche Bank. Details of the
expected swap of treasury bills for longer-term securities, a key
element in Russia's anti-crisis program, were to be released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors that the government was proposing a plan that would have
penalized foreign creditors in favor of Russia's own troubled banks
had swept through Moscow's foreign investment community Tuesday,
prompting warnings that such a plan would kill off any future
foreign investment in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   `'Everyone was becoming more and more nervous, and bitter,''
said one Western investment banker, who spoke on condition that he
not be identified. ``Had they gone ahead with the plan we were
hearing, it would have created enormous concerns in the investment
community. Now we feel that fairness and market practices will come
into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors said the government was considering proposals that
would have differentiated between foreign and Russian creditors, as
a way of shoring up its local banking system. The proposals, which
reportedly included a two-tier redemption schedule, were the
subject of heated debate Tuesday inside the government, one analyst
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trading in Russia's outstanding treasury bills was suspended on
Monday when the government announced a crisis program which imposed
a 90-day moratorium on privately held foreign debt, and set the
ruble free to float to as little as 9.5 rubles to the dollar, from
about 6.4 rubles recently.
</P>
<P>
   Russian banks and their foreign creditors are to discuss the
debt moratorium on some $4 billion in outstanding loans next
Monday. The government has stated that it will continue making
payments on its publicly-held foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
   As the value of the ruble skittered downwards at banks and
currency exchange booths across the country, shoppers and bankers,
Russians and foreigners were waiting to see who would be left
holding the bag.
</P>
<P>
   According to a countrywide survey aired on Russian television
news programs, not that many people rushed Tuesday to exchange
their rubles for dollars, preferring to wait and see where their
currency will eventually land.
</P>
<P>
   At Moscow's currency market, the value was fixed Tuesday at 6.8
rubles to the dollar _ roughly the same rate as on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, after a day of heavy trading in ruble futures.
The ruble rate in Moscow on Monday was 6.4 and in Chicago, 6.5.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Bank of Russia Tuesday said it would move against
currency traders who posted more than a 15 percent spread between
their buying and selling prices for currencies. It already had
restricted the sending of capital out of the country, and
lengthened to three days the time required to withdraw large dollar
sums from corporate bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts interpreted ruble rates of 9, 10 or even 15 to the
dollar posted at some banks and traders as the equivalent of
hanging an `out of order' sign on the teller window. `'Those are
`we don't want to trade' levels,'' said one analyst. `'Essentially,
people are waiting to see if things are going to calm down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But for average Russians, lurking behind the devalued ruble is
the fear of inflation, similar to the kind that emptied their
pocketbooks in the early 1990s when Russia let go of Soviet-era
price controls.
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey published in Russia's leading financial
newspaper Kommersant, most food wholesalers are prepared to hold
their prices at current levels, unless the ruble ends up trading at
levels above 8 to the dollar. In interviews, traders noted that
their prices will ultimately be dictated by the market _ namely
what the average Russian can pay.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Harman, the American finance director of the
Russian-owned Cherkisovsky meat-processing company, which is
heavily dependent on imported raw meat, said the situation Tuesday
looked better than it did on Monday. `'It seems that they may have
deliberately set expectations low,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in scattered cases, the ruble's drop was already showing up
on shelves, despite threats by the Russian tax police that they
will ride herd on those who raise prices in order to take advantage
of the confusion caused by the slide in the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   At a small grocery in central Moscow, Olga Larina, the store's
administrator, said she raised prices on imported goods 10 per cent
after suppliers announced that they would be increasing prices.
</P>
<P>
   `'We realized that this was the pattern when three of our
suppliers told us the same thing,'' she said. `'So we had to raise
our prices accordingly.'' Prices on domestically produced food,
such as milk and cheese, will stay the same at least until
September, she said.
</P>
<P>
   `'Everyone is worried,'' she said. `'You can imagine how it is
for pensions and families with many children. Imagine how worried
they are. Imagine how worried people who work in banks are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
