<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0003 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-CLINTON-CENSURE     08-18 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-CLINTON-CENSURE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESSIONAL CENSURE OFFERS LAWMAKERS A MIDDLE GROUND ON
CLINTON
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only if and when independent counsel Kenneth Starr
sends a report to Congress on the results of his investigation of
President Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky will
lawmakers have the means to determine the president's proper
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two most talked-about options _ the momentous step
of impeachment and doing nothing _ lies a novel political middle
ground.
</P>
<P>
   A resolution of censure, a well-established form of
congressional punishment of a lawmaker less severe than expulsion,
would be one way for Congress to express its distaste for Clinton's
actions. It would have no legal consequences, but would serve as a
``tangible sign of the dimunition of the president's political and
moral authority,'' said John Bolton, a former assistant Attorney
General in the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
<P>
   The idea also drew support from Leon Panetta, Clinton's former
chief of staff, who told USA Today that a censure vote ``would be
to everyone's advantage'' because it would allow Clinton to remain
in office, Congress to express itself and healing to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The House has used the penalty to discipline members who have
been involved in inappropriate sexual relationships. In 1983, the
House censured Rep. Daniel Crane, R-Ill., for his affair with a
17-year-old female page and Rep. Gerry Studds, D-Mass., for his
sexual relationship with a 17-year-old male page.
</P>
<P>
   Crane lost his next bid for re-election. Studds served in the
House until 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Newt Gingrich, who as a junior Republican unsuccessfully
urged his two colleagues' expulsion in 1983, had his speakership
threatened by a potential vote of censure following his admission
in late 1996 that he violated House ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
   Republican rules bar members who have been censured from serving
as committee chairmen and by inference, in leadership positions. In
the end, the House voted to reprimand Gingrich, a lesser penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with censuring the president, according to
congressional expert Thomas Mann and Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., is that
it is an empty gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Barr complained that some House members might opt for censure
because they ``don't have the backbone for impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of a fig leaf for those who don't want to do
anything,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Mann, a scholar at the Brookings Institution in Washington,
called censure a ``cop out'' that sounds like a middle ground, but
in fact would be an irresponsible exercise that, lacking any
evidence to impeach Clinton, would further weaken him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you care about the well-being of the country you either
want to force the man out of office,'' Mann said, ``or allow him to
conduct the remaining years of his presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution sets out impeachment as Congress's way to deal
with a wayward president. It says nothing about any other form of
discipline.
</P>
<P>
   One has to look back 164 years for any guidance. In 1834, the
Senate censured Andrew Jackson in a dispute over the Bank of the
United States. The House refused to go along with the Senate and
Jackson ignored the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   When Jackson's party recaptured the Senate in 1837, Jackson's
censure was expunged from Senate records.
</P>
<P>
   There also is scant historical background to advise Congress how
to proceed if it chooses censure.
</P>
<P>
   Bolton said it seemed most likely that a vote for censure might
follow from hearings by the House Judiciary Committee into Starr's
report.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the punishment would reflect the committee's
belief that the evidence did not warrant impeachment, but demanded
some response from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But Bolton said a resolution of censure would not have to come
from the Judiciary Committee or even originate in the House, as
would, for instance, articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House and Senate can pass resolutions on anything,
including whether the moon is made of bleu cheese,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
