<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0015 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-NYT &LR;      08-18 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BETTER OR WORSE, THE SPEECH WAS PURE BILL CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES
with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS, NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(JT) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was just over four minutes long, barely 500
words, the shortest big speech of Bill Clinton's presidency. It had
to satisfy the president's lawyers, his public and his wife, and it
came together only after a grueling day of testimony to a federal
grand jury and frantic final tinkering.
</P>
<P>
   But in its tone and content, in its blend of unapologetic
umbrage and tightly conditioned admission, the president's mea
culpa was minima, and deeply personal. Begun in his own
backward-slanting handwriting, annealed with the iron-willed anger
of his wife, the speech was pure Bill Clinton, for better and
worse.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, senior aides said, the president was
determined to vent his frustration at what he sees as Kenneth
Starr's unjustified investigation, an approach strongly seconded by
the first lady, Hillary Rodham Clinton, but by virtually none of
the White House staff.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton confidants said Tuesday that a subsequent draft,
prepared early Monday by the longtime adviser Paul Begala, struck a
softer, elegiac tone of regret for the trouble Clinton had caused
to an office he had dreamed of since he was a boy.
</P>
<P>
   But after the president spent more than four tense hours with
Starr and his investigators, and returned grim-faced to the
solarium in the family quarters, his lawyer, David Kendall, and
Mrs. Clinton pressed for a steelier tone. The first lady finally
sealed the question by telling her husband that it was his speech
and he should say what he wanted. It was precisely the advice she
had given him as he struggled to finish the longest speech of his
tenure, the 1995 State of the Union, which lasted 81 minutes, a
speech that journalists labeled a failure but one the public
ultimately embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff didn't want to say anything about Starr,'' one aide
said. ``But this is uniquely his, much more than any policy
address, uniquely his. I don't think he was desperately interested
in the entreaties of his advisers.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, aides said, it was Clinton's profound distrust of Starr
that had helped drive the president's seven-month strategy of
delay, denial and attack, because he worried that Starr would not
accept whatever he might say. In the end, Clinton was determined
that any concession get in his licks, too.
</P>
<P>
   From its emphasis on accepting responsibility to its closing
call to ``repair the fabric of our national discourse,'' the
speech's language and images echoed the notions of Clinton's 1992
and 1996 campaigns and his second inaugural address last year. The
attack on an investigation that has ``gone on too long, cost too
much, and hurt too many people,'' played to the public's
poll-tested distaste for Kenneth Starr and its desire for an end to
the drama.
</P>
<P>
   The president's rhetorical arguments _ in which he tried to
square ``legally accurate'' answers with confessions of a ``false
impression'' _ were also entirely consistent with Clinton's past
lawyerly responses to the crises of credibility that have
periodically bedeviled him: it was an apology for sex, lies and
audiotape that never used any of those words.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family feels that whatever the faults of the father and
the husband, the fact that the mother and the daughter have had to
endure this excruciating public venting of this issue _ Ken Starr's
responsible for that,'' one aide said, insisting on anonymity.
``The president probably said something that his wife wanted
said.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To paraphrase Queen Victoria, she was not amused,'' said James
Carville, one of the original architects of Clinton's 1992 victory,
who went to the White House to offer moral support in the hours
before the speech was delivered.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Mrs. Clinton complained that a ``vast, right-wing
conspiracy,'' was bent on her husband's downfall, and Clinton's
denunciation of the ``politically inspired lawsuit'' brought by
Paula Corbin Jones and his demand that ``it is time to stop the
pursuit of personal destruction and the prying into private lives''
amplified his wife's accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton confidants said that Sidney Blumenthal, the White House
communications aide who has often fostered conspiracy notions, had
sent suggestions from his vacation in Italy. The Clintons' old
friends, the Hollywood producers Harry and Linda Bloodworth
Thomason, were on hand to provide informal advice, and sat in the
Map Room during the televised speech.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has been sampling public opinion throughout this
crisis and public polls suggest those arguments may carry weight
with one important part of Clinton's intended audience _ television
viewers and voters at home.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News Poll last week found that two-thirds of the public
see ``this whole situation more as a private matter having to do
with Bill Clinton's personal life'' as compared to a public matter
relating to his job as president, although 7 in 10 Americans at
least leaned to the belief that Clinton had an affair with Monica
Lewinsky and nearly half said they thought that he encouraged her
to lie under oath.
</P>
<P>
   The same poll found that 6 in 10 Americans see Starr's
investigation as a partisan attempt to damage the president, and
two-thirds said that regardless of what the president might have
done, the country would have been better off if the Lewinsky
investigation had never begun.
</P>
<P>
   But most aides, who worried about the president's other audience
_ congressional Republicans _ regretted that he chose to lambaste
Starr's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there were many people who thought he should
have complicated what was a heartfelt act of contrition'' by
talking about the independent counsel, one senior aide said. ``But
he was going to be honest in talking about how he felt. He's the
president and we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
