<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLLEGIATE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURSE TAKES TOLL IN OPENING ROUND OF COLLEGIATE PLAYERS
TOURNAMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EULESS, Texas _ Rather than focusing on the competition in
yesterday's opening round of the Collegiate Players Tour National
Championship, most players found the Texas Star Golf Course to be
the real challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And in most cases, the course _ at least for this day _ walked
away victorious.
</P>
<P>
   Only two players in either the men's or women's fields shot
below par yesterday, the lowest of those scores being a 2-under-par
69 posted by C.W. Mallon of Trophy Club. Of the 84 players in the
field, 77 shot above par 71 in the first of three rounds of the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Considering how tough Texas Star played, Mallon, a junior at
Rice, had to be more than pleased with his round. The 20-year-old
left-hander recorded birdies on the par-3 No. 3, the par-5 No. 7
and the par-4 No. 9 on the way to a 33 on the front. He recorded
two more birdies on the back to finish round one with a one-stroke
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is playing pretty hard, but I was hitting it pretty
well and I made some putts,'' Mallon said. ``I've just got to try
and keep the same mentality the last two days. You've just got to
keep it in play and make some putts.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon leads Joe Liley of the University of Colorado, who shot
35 on both sides for a 1-under 70. Five players are tied at
even-par 71, including Michael Pruitt, an incoming freshman at
North Texas, and Dallas' Patrick Hawkins, who attends the
University of San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Duke's Anne Cardea grabbed a one-stroke lead in the women's
division with an even-par 71. The 20-year-old from Midlothian, Va.,
had two front-nine birdies to balance out two bogeys on the back
nine. She needed just 30 putts to finish the round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hit a bad shot until my 17th hole,'' Cardea said. ``I
hit it in the bunker there, but I still got it within 15 feet and
made par. I got up and down a lot today.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardea holds a one-stroke lead over Mansfield's Carrie Cole, who
leaves for the University of Tennessee after the championship, and
TCU golfer senior Shannon Fisher. Cole shot a 2-under 33 on the
front nine, but bogeyed three holes on the back _ including the two
par-5s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just got to putt a little better,'' Cole said. ``I made
some good putts, but I also had a few three-putts. I've got to get
rid of those. I feel pretty good about how I'm hitting the ball. I
just need to be more consistent with my putter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
