<HEADER>
A0045 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STUPID-KIDS-THEATER-A     08-18 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUPID-KIDS-THEATER-ART-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S A REBEL, AND IT LOOKS LIKE HE'LL BE VERY GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Texas)  (For release Sunday, Aug. 23)  
 (ART ADV: Photos of Keith Nobbs and James Carpinello are is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If being cool translates as feigning indifference,
then Keith Nobbs _ a 19-year-old actor in ``Stupid Kids'' _ is
decidedly uncool. This live wire (``I have the metabolism of a
shrew,'' he volunteers cheerfully) is suddenly hot, in a satire
that examines the vagaries of coolness in the conformist atmosphere
of a suburban high school in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Written by John C. Russell, who died of AIDS in 1994 at the age
of 31, ``Stupid Kids'' opened off-Broadway in June to a shaky start
at the WPA Theater, where it received several mixed reviews, with
some critics complaining of a thin story. Still, the 80-minute
play, directed by Michael Mayer, seemed to be finding its legs just
as it closed in July. Now it has been given another chance.
</P>
<P>
   It begins a commercial run Tuesday at the Century Theater on
East 15th Street with a gilt-edged pack of producers behind it.
Shubert Organization chairman Gerald Schoenfeld is a fan, as are
the other producers: Scott Rudin, Roger Berlind, Robert Fox and ABC
Television. ``I saw it and found it very appealing,'' Schoenfeld
said. ``It's fresh, it's young. It's just the type of thing to
bring young people back to the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Between bites of a cheeseburger at an East Village diner
recently, Nobbs talked about the reasons he thinks ``Stupid Kids''
has appeal. ``It's basically `Rebel Without a Cause' meets an '80s
teen movie, with the outcast as hero,'' he said. ``And I get to
wear lime-green Converse sneakers, which is excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid Kids,'' with its cast of four, tells the story of two
boys and two girls at a fictional high school on Long Island.
Nobbs' gay character, Neechee (as in Nietzsche: a knowing nod to
the outsider Plato in ``Rebel Without a Cause''), harbors an
intense crush on Jim, the big-man-on-campus (played by James
Carpinello). Neechee's counterpart, Kimberly (Mandy Siegfried), is
equally obsessed with Jim's girlfriend, Judy (Shannon Burkett).
Does this foursome manage to unscramble its collective libido?
Hardly.
</P>
<P>
   The performance by Nobbs has been singled out for praise.
Michael Feingold in The Village Voice said the actor worked ``with
a conviction and clarity that normally come only with decades of
experience,'' and Fintan O'Toole in The New York Daily News said
Nobbs was ``particularly good as the dreamy, awkward Neechee,
capturing perfectly the hurt and bluster of a fragile
personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention of Nobbs' reviews elicits a teasing, ``Aw, you make me
blush like a schoolgirl,'' a camp comment in keeping with the tone
of ``Stupid Kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobbs grew up in Kingwood, Texas, a suburb north of Houston, the
youngest of four children, and went to a school that prepared him
well for the outcast character he plays on stage. ``The kids were
like robots _ same hair, same jeans,'' he said. ``Ten minority
students out of 4,000. Nazi-land.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was 15, his family moved to Kew Gardens, Queens, and he
went to the High School of Performing Arts, from which he
graduated, winning the American Theater Wing's Isabelle Stevenson
Award. ``It's a totally different world,'' the actor said.
``There's so much mutual respect because everyone is working on his
art. I went from guys in Texas threatening to go gay-bashing to two
guys getting engaged at my senior prom.''
</P>
<P>
   Head constantly bobbing, hands thrashing the air in karate
chops, Nobbs peppers his speech with affirmations like ``groovy''
and ``bonus.'' But he has an introspective side. From his
first-year classes at the School of General Studies at Columbia
University, he said, he distilled an esthetic philosophy that he is
applying to his acting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like art with no fingerprints,'' he said. ``Like
Michelangelo, who let David emerge from the stone, whereas
Bernini's David is imposed with all sorts of the artist's ego.
Imposing ego is bad acting _ the neurosis of, `How am I being
perceived?'''
</P>
<P>
   On the strength of his performance in ``Stupid Kids,'' he has
been sought out for auditions. But because he is such a new kid on
the block, Nobbs said, producers often ``don't know what I'm right
for, so they put me in a room and have me tell stories'' _ as
director Joe Mantello did recently when auditioning actors for
Terrence McNally's controversial new play ``Corpus Christi.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer, who is also directing the current ``A View From the
Bridge'' and ``Side Man,'' has already cast Nobbs in the Roundabout
Theater Company's revival of ``The Lion in Winter,'' which will
begin performances in February with Laurence Fishburne in the lead
role. Mayer said of Nobbs that the author of ``The Lion in
Winter,'' James Goldman, ``his wife, the Roundabout's casting
director and I all thought, `He's the one,' independent of one
another _ and that never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The East Village lunch was wedged between shooting an episode of
HBO's new hourlong drama ``The Sopranos'' and a callback for a
film. Is this an actor worried about running out of gas? ``Nah,''
he said, ``I just eat my breakfast of champions _ a bottle of Coke
and Reese's Peanut Butter Cups.'' Cool.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0047 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-CRITICS-$ADV23     08-18 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CRITICS-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN PHRASES THAT FLATTER ARE MISUSED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23.) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hope there's some distinction to looking like the biggest fool
in the world of film. Because I had that honor in a recent
advertisement for the videotape of ``John Grisham's `The
Rainmaker,''' one that quoted me as describing ``The Rainmaker'' as
Francis Ford Coppola's ``best and sharpest film.''
</P>
<P>
   Now you, I, Coppola, Paramount Pictures and the man in the moon
all know this is untrue (a certain multipart masterpiece comes to
mind), but I had accidentally made the studio's advertising
department an offer it couldn't refuse. What I had written months
before in my review of the movie was, `` `John Grisham's ``The
Rainmaker''' is Coppola's best and sharpest film  &UR; in years &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Fair game. It's cricket today, with print-media movie ads at
their most ruthless and breathless, to find phrases yanked from
reviews out of context, words picked out of separate paragraphs and
strung together, exclamation points sprinkled like confetti. There
are even gasps of admiration specially solicited to suit
advertising needs.
</P>
<P>
   As The Wall Street Journal pointed out recently in a scarifying
piece on the marketing of ``Armageddon,'' Disney so fancied the
image of an asteroid hurtling through a vowel that it simply
searched for a critic willing to say ``Wow!'' A friend of mine
points out that ``Lousy!'' would have done the job _ and a little
more accurately, too.
</P>
<P>
   We all learn the hard way that a flattering phrase tossed off
casually can become an advertisement nightmare somewhere down the
line. ``Can we watch this?'' my little sons asked a while ago,
waving an evil-looking video in my direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nope,'' I said, without even looking closer. ``Are you
 &UR; suuuurrre &LR;  you don't like it?'' they asked gleefully, and then
they turned over the box. There on the back was my name, attached
to the words ``It's fun!''
</P>
<P>
   Hasty research on this no-account horror film established that
what I had actually written in my review was a wee bit different.
</P>
<P>
   For better and worse, critics find themselves integral to the
process of promoting movies, and there are times when we gratefully
seize that opportunity. Consider ``Western,'' a beguiling, offbeat
French film that I adore.
</P>
<P>
   Currently hanging on semi-desperately at a single Manhattan
theater, this little treat has no easy selling points of its own.
The director, Manuel Poirier, is a Peruvian raised in France. And
like the film's two funny, sheepish stars, he is quite unknown here
in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The title (``Western'' is set in western France) is useless to
the point of being a deterrent: cowboy fans may not be in the
market for a tender French road movie with an ending that prompts
tears of happiness, and moviegoers who gravitate toward foreign
films are perhaps scared away by the thought of cattle drives. So
in a case like this, an extra chance to be heard is all too
welcome. It's a privilege to help a struggling favorite by being
quoted with some version of ``Go!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Western,'' Hal Hartley's ``Henry Fool'' and the reissue of
Fellini's ``Nights of Cabiria'' offered the most transcendent
non-battlefield filmgoing experiences I've had this summer. (``The
Opposite of Sex'' and ``There's Something About Mary'' delivered
the dizziest laughs.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet those first three films, collectively, have grossed not even
$2 million in the United States (as compared with about $70 million
each for ``Six Days, Seven Nights'' and ``Lost in Space''). For all
practical purposes, at a time when audiences surely long for films
worth caring about, those three films have barely been seen.
</P>
<P>
   What better opportunity could there be to be involved in a
little drumbeating for a good reason? Trouble is, critics can't
save their credibility for the movies that matter.
</P>
<P>
   With the mania for rhapsodic quotes in ads at such a feverish
pitch, crying wolf is a serious occupational hazard, one to make us
wince at appearing to endorse films we think are negligible. Look
closely and you'll sometimes see the equivalent of ``The lights
went down! I watched it!'' being trumpeted to the skies.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing readers are the savviest participants in the
quote-ad sweepstakes. Surely you know the rules of this game. If
you can't make out the source of the quote without a magnifying
glass, chances are that it isn't your eyesight that's the problem.
And you know better than to trust ... any statement ... full of
holes ... like this. Beware of any form of quote-ad rapture that
originates too far before the film has opened, perhaps even before
it has been made.
</P>
<P>
   And know that certain buzzwords are a dead giveaway to so-so
sentiment. ``Compelling,'' ``worthy'' or ``engrossing'' are not the
language of a writer in love.
</P>
<P>
   If the laudatory words have come to sound awfully familiar,
that's because the quote-ad vocabulary is notoriously tiny and
tired. Even when a film does make the pulse quicken, must it really
be as brilliant, heart-stopping, bold and audacious a thrill ride
as all that?
</P>
<P>
   Phrases get flogged, borrowed and recycled until even the
simplest and mightiest of accolades (``Great!'') is reduced to
hype. I promise never to call anything ``wickedly funny'' again.
Even if it is.
</P>
<P>
   But there are certain forms of critical shorthand that
encapsulate an opinion quickly, even if they do it in
all-too-quotable form. ``Just saw `The Horse Whisperer' and found
it to be `voluptuously soapy,' '' my best friend from high school
wrote in a letter last month. ``You are definitely the master of
the adverb and adjective combo.''
</P>
<P>
   She was an English major, and she naturally takes a wry (another
word suffering critical injuries) view of this process. She also
knows this: Quotations should come from the sages who wrote ``The
quality of mercy is not strained'' or ``Do not go gentle into that
good night.'' Not from the writer who cried ``Wow!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
