<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-VINEYARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELL-WISHERS WELCOME CLINTONS TO CAPE COD ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ One day after President Clinton confessed to
the nation, he found forgiveness on Martha's Vineyard, where he was
greeted by a few hundred well-wishers who turned out to greet the
First Family.
</P>
<P>
   It was, by all accounts, business as usual. And in some ways,
that was the biggest surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Washington insider and summer resident of Martha's Vineyard
Vernon E. Jordan Jr., who has been caught up in the controversy
over Monica S. Lewinsky, has been noticeably absent from Clinton's
side in recent months. But Tuesday, as he has in three summers
past, Jordan wore a golfing cap and was the first to greet the
Clintons as they got off the plane.
</P>
<P>
   While controversy continued swirling back in Washington, with
talk of impeachment, and polls across the country showing a drop in
Clinton's credibility ratings, the airport welcome was a clear
signal that many people here are hoping he can enjoy a pleasant
stay on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The plane touched down just after 5 p.m., and the Clintons and
daughter Chelsea emerged waving and smiling, though the president
was wearing a business suit. In years past, the president has
arrived in casual clothing, looking far more relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   As he does every time he arrives on this island, Clinton
lingered with the crowd assembled at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Casselli and his wife Dawn of Stratford, Conn., have
vacationed the last four years with the Clintons in Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Caselli was one of the first Americans to have the opportunity
to give the president a piece of his mind Tuesday, as he shook
hands and spoke with Clinton for several minutes at the Martha's
Vineyard Regional Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that what he said last night was a great apology,''
said Caselli, 64. ``I said, let's forget about all that stuff,''
Caselli went on as Clinton stood and listened. Caselli was
overheard telling the president that the economy was good, and that
just about everyone he knew could afford a new home.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds had been growing smaller each summer as the First
Family's presence has become more of a routine. Tuesday's crowd,
which began lining up two hours in advance for the president's
arrival was about the same in size as last year's of about 200,
many of them making the trip for the fourth time.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those dressed in red white and blue and carrying banners
said that it was more important than ever to greet Clinton Tuesday,
at a time when his presidency is vulnerable, and his family is
gathered after a legendary week of intense public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really relieved to see the crowds. I came here and sweated
in line, to make sure that he knew he still had friends on the
island.'' said Barbara Courtney, whose husband Geno owns several
island shops and is renowned for his tacky T-shirts, designed for
the annual presidential vacation.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, though, has weightier issues on her mind. She said
that she brought along her daughter Lauren and this year the two
had to talk about extramarital affairs and sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, she said to me with all the wisdom of a 12
year-old, `I think that that's between the president and Mrs.
Clinton, isn't it?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea Clinton greeted fans first, and as usual, teenagers were
thrilled to see her and gushed over her stylish clothing. She was
met by a couple of boys her age, who White House aides say are also
vacationing here.
</P>
<P>
   In summers past, the Clintons have made several public outings
during their vacations, with the president scheduling early golf
games and Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea enjoying afternoon shopping
trips. Tuesday, White House aides issued what the press corps
called ``the vacation Bible,'' a daily schedule of events. On each
page it was printed ``there are no public events on the schedule of
the president.'' indicating that, so far, the Clintons plan to keep
to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   However, several sources familiar with the presidential vacation
calendar say he is likely to schedule short departures from the
island during his stay. There will be a morning press briefing at
the Edgartown Elementary School, which will again serve as the
island press center.
</P>
<P>
   Richard L. Friedman, a Cambridge, Mass. businessman and real
estate developer, is once again the presidential host, and the
first family will stay in the main house on his Oyster Pond estate.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, his wife, Nancy Klemm Friedman, and his son Alex were
also among those who greeted Clinton as he stepped from the plane.
Singer-songwriter Carly Simon, though recently diagnosed with
breast cancer, stood beside them and offered the Clintons hearty
hugs.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the smaller guest house on the property has been
filled with exercise equipment for the Clintons, according to those
who have visited the property recently. The Freidmans will stay in
another home on the prperty, and the antique farmhouse, already
filled with gifts from island residents, is where the Clintons will
stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most challenging issue for (Clinton) is going to be
Jenny,'' said Friedman, jokingly referring to the Norwegian
elkhound dog whose feisty personality is known to Oyster Pond
residents. The family brought along their own dog, Buddy a
chocolate Labrador.
</P>
<P>
   Islanders sent baskets of sunflowers and a painting of the
Oyster Pond property, which has become the summer White House.
</P>
<P>
   Though many residents and summer visitors relax on this island,
few experience the solitude that the Clintons can on the property
that sits at the end of a long and winding sandy road that
stretches uphill to Friedman's farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they will be able to relax'' Friedman said. ``That's
all that matters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
