<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0050 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAKE'S-PROGRESS-OPERA     08-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAKE'S-PROGRESS-OPERA-$ADV23-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETHINKING A MOSTLY MOZARTEAN STRAVINSKY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stravinsky was a slow worker. He produced, on average, one major
composition, or an equivalent number of smaller ones, per year. Of
course, he lived many years, from 1882 to 1971, and produced many
works, about 100, though only a handful run longer than a
half-hour. The longest by far is his only full-length opera, ``The
Rake's Progress.'' Each of its three acts took a year to compose.
</P>
<P>
   So by the time of the opera's premiere, in 1951 in Venice, with
a luminous cast including Elisabeth Schwarzkopf, Robert Rounsville
and Jennie Tourel, the musical world was immensely curious. The
most important living composer had essentially been silent for some
time. What had he been up to?
</P>
<P>
   Many cutting-edge modernists who attended, or heard reports,
were baffled. For 20 years, Stravinsky had been immersed in
Neo-Classicism, his breathtakingly brilliant effort to reanimate
classical genres and forms through reinvented tonal procedures and
complex shifting meters.
</P>
<P>
   To the modernists, ``The Rake's Progress'' seemed not just
Neo-Classical but a virtual pastiche of Mozartean opera. Stravinsky
admitted to having studied Mozart's operas closely as models and
declared himself ``Mozart's continuer.'' But the hostile reactions
of many composers and critics rattled him, and may have helped
provoke him to give up Neo-Classicism and investigate 12-tone
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   The true significance of ``The Rake's Progress'' has since
become clearer. The opera has had numerous prominent productions,
and last season, the Metropolitan Opera unveiled a new one,
directed by Jonathan Miller and conducted by James Levine. ``The
Rake's Progress'' now seems a work of incomparable genius, and the
release of two new recordings reinforces this assessment.
</P>
<P>
   On one, Seiji Ozawa conducts the Saito Kinen Festival Orchestra
and Chorus from Japan (Philips 454 431-2; two CD's); on the other,
Kent Nagano leads the Lyons Opera of France (Erato 0630-12715-2;
two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   What's more, these recordings affirm the opera's place within
the international repertory of the 20th century. This outcome is
all the more striking, since the piece is pervaded by a British
quality. Stravinsky was inspired to compose it when, in 1947, at an
exhibit in Chicago, he saw Hogarth's ``Rake's Progress,'' a series
of eight engravings depicting the ruination of a young English
gentleman.
</P>
<P>
   Here, at a stroke, the composer got the idea for an opera, a
title and the gist of a story: a loutish gentleman comes into an
inheritance, wastes his money on gambling, foolish luxury and
prostitutes, and winds up in a madhouse, where he is faithfully
visited by the forgiving woman to whom he was once betrothed.
</P>
<P>
   The libretto, by W.H. Auden and Chester Kallman, evokes with
fondness but also satire the ornate poetic style of Pope and
Congreve. So Stravinsky felt that he was writing a thoroughly
English opera, and he hoped for a premiere production in a small
New York theater, like that of Gian Carlo Menotti's ``Consul'' in
1950. But it failed to materialize.
</P>
<P>
   Important recordings of the past, including the two conducted by
Stravinsky, have used mostly English and American singers,
orchestras and choruses. And even the new recordings use native
English-speaking singers in the leading roles.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky's first recording, for Columbia, used the cast that
gave the work's Met premiere in 1953 and has long been out of
print. Stravinsky's 1964 recording, made in London for Columbia,
offered Alexander Young as Tom Rakewell, Judith Raskin as Anne
Trulove and John Reardon as Nick Shadow, with the Royal
Philharmonic Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Still available on Sony Classical, it remains indispensable. The
performance is not flawless. Details in the orchestra are sometimes
unclear; Stravinsky sometimes fails to highlight arresting inner
lines and harmonies. Yet the conception has an organic quality, the
tempos work perfectly, and the cast sounds inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Other recordings also drew primarily on English or American
forces. Riccardo Chailly conducted the London Sinfonietta with the
English tenor Philip Langridge in the title role in a Decca/London
release from 1983, not now available in the United States. And
Robert Craft, whose professional association with the composer
began on March 31, 1948, the very day the libretto of ``The Rake's
Progress'' was delivered into Stravinsky's hands, and lasted until
his death, conducted the Orchestra of St. Luke's in an insightful
Musicmasters recording from 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky might have been delighted to hear the Japanese and
French choristers in the new recordings working so diligently to
enunciate the English text. But the primary considerations in any
performance are musical, and here the opera, a marvelous creative
balancing act, presents a formidable challenge.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, ``The Rake's Progress'' is a sincere homage to the
18th-century ``number opera,'' in which the music unfolds in a
numbered series of arias, ensembles and choruses, connected with
recitatives; yet at the same time, Stravinsky pokes fun at the
number opera.
</P>
<P>
   The libretto is archly British and filled with florid poetic
language; yet Stravinsky sets the words with clipped rhythms and
fractured phrase lengths. Some cite this feature as an example of
his flawed skills at prosody, but it seems deliberate to me, and it
cajoles the poetry to sound surprising and modern.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The main characters in the tale are little more than emblematic:
Tom, a lazy Englishman of no means and less discipline; his
betrothed, Anne, the guileless, good-hearted daughter of a widower
from the country; and the Devil, in the guise of Nick Shadow, who
tempts Tom with wealth into a life of debauchery and ruin. They
might be stock players in a morality play.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Stravinsky's precise, lucid, emotionally restrained music
endows them with complexity and humanity. And the harmonic
language, while essentially rooted in diatonic keys, amounts to a
textbook in how to discombobulate and burst the tonal system.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa has had a variable relationship with the Boston Symphony,
which he has directed for a quarter-century. But in the Philips
recording, the Saito Kinen players, from the festival named for
Ozawa's beloved teacher, are clearly enthralled. You can hear the
respect of these immensely talented younger musicians for Ozawa in
the involvement and precision of their playing.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Ozawa is scrupulously attentive to Stravinsky's
metronome markings and displays a keen ear for textures and inner
voices. He captures the dancelike quality of the accompanimental
figurations and negotiates the music's shifting meters and
asymmetrical phrases with ease. And the cool restraint he brings to
the score allows the music to seem at once beguilingly
Neo-Classical and startlingly modern.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of Ozawa's finest recordings, and it suggests that
he should be doing more Stravinsky and contemporary music in
general instead of overblown performances of Mahler and Brahms.
</P>
<P>
   His cast is headed by Anthony Rolfe Johnson, a distinguished
English tenor. Though captured here past his vocal prime, Rolfe
Johnson provides a quality of oratorical elegance, complete with
proper ornamentation, and projects the fragility in Tom's
character.
</P>
<P>
   The soprano Sylvia McNair, as Anne, sings with honeyed tone and
exquisite delicacy. The shamefully underappreciated bass Paul
Plishka brings his husky voice and vivid dramatic flair to the role
of Shadow. Jane Bunnell, as Mother Goose, and Jane Henschel, as
Baba the Turk, are solid. And the English tenor Ian Bostridge
transforms the small role of Sellem, the auctioneer, into an
intriguing portrait of a seductively slippery operator.
</P>
<P>
   Nagano, conducting the Lyons Opera Orchestra in the Erato
recording, delivers a clear-textured, tellingly paced performance.
He does not elicit as much detail and rhythmic precision from his
players as Ozawa does from his, but this is a fine account of a
difficult score.
</P>
<P>
   The singers in the three main roles will be familiar to those
who attended the recent Met performances. Dawn Upshaw is a deeply
affecting Anne, singing with her customary creamy soprano tone,
supple phrasing, unmannered diction and poignant vulnerability. The
bass Samuel Ramey is a superlative Shadow, bringing even greater
depth and vocal presence to the role than he did in the Chailly
recording.
</P>
<P>
   The performance that may divide listeners is Jerry Hadley's, as
Tom. Hadley, a gifted American tenor, has said that he feels closer
to this role than to almost any other he sings, and you feel that
engagement in his ardent performance. He has thought about every
phrase, every word, and he sings with bright sound, vital rhythm
and crisp diction.
</P>
<P>
   But his involvement may be too deep, for in bursts of sound that
occasionally blare, you sense him trying too hard. The renowned
mezzo-soprano Grace Bumbry, recorded here at 58, makes an earthy
Baba, and Anne Collins is a winning Mother Goose.
</P>
<P>
   Ozawa's Japanese chorus, on Philips, does surprisingly well by
the English text. If anything, its enunciation is slightly clearer
than that of its French counterparts, on Erato. But even the
English and American choristers on the earlier recordings had
trouble with lines like ``Many a duchess divested of gems/Has
crossed the dread Styx by way of the Thames.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rake's Progress'' has clearly arrived as a masterpiece of
the international repertory, and collectors have two fine new
recordings to chose from. Yet if I could have only one of all the
available versions, it would still be Stravinsky's excellent
account from 1964, informed by a sense of history in the making.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
