</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-WEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOROTHY WEST, AT 91; ONE OF LAST HARLEM RENAISSANCE AUTHORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dorothy West of Oak Bluffs, Mass., an author who was one of the
last living figures of the Harlem Renaissance movement, died Sunday
in New England Medical Center in Boston. She was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Miss West was born in Boston in 1907. She was the daughter of an
emancipated slave.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel, ``The Living Is Easy,'' about the black middle
class in Boston, was published in 1948. Her second novel, ``The
Wedding,'' about the black aristocracy on Martha's Vineyard, was
published in 1995. ``The Wedding'' was adapted by Oprah Winfrey
into a TV miniseries broadcast earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Among her many fans was Hillary Rodham Clinton, who called her
``a national treasure'' at her 90th birthday party on Martha's
Vineyard last year, and Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, who encouraged
her to write ``The Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1926, shortly after she graduated from Girls Latin School,
Miss West's short story ``The Typewriter'' tied for second prize in
a short story contest with Zora Neale Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   Hurston befriended Miss West and brought her to New York, where
she was befriended by the more established writers of the Harlem
Renaissance, including Richard Wright and Langston Hughes. Miss
West, the youngest of the group, was called ``The Kid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know it was the Harlem Renaissance, because we were
all young and all poor,'' Miss West told the Associated Press in
1995. ``We had no jobs to speak of, and we had rent parties'' to
raise rent money.
</P>
<P>
   She remained in New York for more than a decade, selling stories
to the New York Daily News and working as a welfare investigator,
then a relief worker during the Depression. She founded and edited
two black literary journals, ``Challenge'' and ``New Challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1930s, after the Depression had decimated Harlem's
economy and arts scene, she returned to Boston and settled down in
her family's summer cottage in Oak Bluffs on Martha's Vineyard.
Though she put a sign out in front of the little gray cottage that
read ``Please, no unannounced visitors,'' her house became a mecca
for fans.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 30 years, she wrote a weekly column for the
Vineyard Gazette. In the 1980s, her work caught the eye of
Doubleday editor and summer island resident Onassis, who became a
regular visitor to the cottage and eventually convinced her to
finish ``The Wedding,'' which she had begun to write in the 1960s
but dropped because she thought it would be misunderstood during
the heyday of the Black Panthers and other militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I liked about her is that she listened,'' Miss West said
of Onassis in a story published in the Globe on Oct. 11, 1995.
``I'd talk on about this or that, and she'd say, `Oh, you must
write that,' or `You must write this.' She was a listener. She was
a learner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wedding'' was published by Doubleday and dedicated to
Onassis. Shortly after, Miss West's short-story collection, ``The
Richer, The Poorer,'' was published.
</P>
<P>
   Some said Miss West's books were about race, but she said they
were about class. ``Color never mattered to me,'' she said in the
Globe article. ``Class is always more important than color.''
</P>
<P>
   A memorial service was planned for Saturday in Union Chapel in
Oak Bluffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
