<HEADER>
A0055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGO-ASSESS-700&AMP;ADD-     08-18 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGO-ASSESS-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL NEIGHBORS WILL LIKELY DETERMINE VICTOR IN CONGO'S CIVIL
WAR  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ By day's end here, when the sun's red disk
sinks below the horizon and this electricity-deprived city that is
now on the razor's edge fades to black, the only people who remain
in the street are the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of uniformed men patrol on foot, clinging tightly to
their rifles, uncertain of their future as rebel forces threaten
the capital and President Laurence Kabila's hold on power. And
thousands of fresh recruits, still dressed in rags, mill about on
streets whose names still date from the last fallen dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to fight to save our nation from the Rwandans,'' said
Pierre Kunga, an 18-year-old who is one of the hordes of recent
recruits who haunt the streets at night but who have not been given
arms. ``This is no time to debate the flaws of our leaders. Our
country is about to be swallowed up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kabila has turned out thousands of volunteers in recent days for
what he says will be a ``long and popular war'' against a
Rwandan-backed rebellion. But these new ``fighters,'' many of them
teen-agers who have been trained with nothing more than rusty auto
mufflers to use as mock guns, are unlikely to be play a decisive
role.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of the rebellion are trying to present an ethnically
diverse face to the country to avoid the hostility a Tutsi-led
regime would attract, but few Congolese say they would accept any
government that they believe is installed by Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the outcome of this conflict, the latest of many in a
country whose history has been full of uprisings, is likely to be
decided by more powerful neighbors. These countries have sharply
divergent interests, but one trait in common: during the rebellion
that brought Kabila to power, they grew used to playing kingmaker
in Africa's third largest country.
</P>
<P>
   When Kabila himself was swept to power at the head of an
alliance principally armed and manned by Rwanda, Uganda and Angola,
the United States seemed to applaud after a brief moment of
hesitation over the military overthrow of a longtime ally, Mobutu
Sese Seko. These were ``African solutions to African problems,''
according to a phrase that became fashionable in policy circles.
</P>
<P>
   As Kabila's star wanes, however, following a 15-month-long
presidency marked by erratic behavior, diplomatic blunders and
sinking popularity, it is those very same allies whose interests
are beginning to clash dangerously as the Rwandan-led effort to
overthrow Kabila gains pace.
</P>
<P>
   In launching the second rebellion in Congo in as many years on
Aug. 2, Rwanda quickly secured the allegiance of Kabila's biggest
army unit, the 10th Brigade, in the eastern city of Goma. Two days
later, rebel troops were being flown boldly to the opposite end of
the country, where they opened a front near Kinshasa in the west.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' gushed a Western diplomat, before the
evacuation last weekend of the U.S. Embassy here. ``They have
nearly achieved as much in seven days as the Kabila rebellion did
in seven months.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rather than give up without a fight, as Mobutu did, what Kabila
has done in the last few days is to throw his energies into
rallying Angola and a number of other African countries behind the
idea that what Rwanda is doing is threatening stability on a grand
scale.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Kabila's personal diplomacy comes too late
or will produce too little concrete support to save his own
government. Local businessmen and others with knowledge of military
supplies here say that Angola has been using its airplanes to ferry
troops for Kabila's army and has provided the government with a
battalion of so-called Katangese Gendarmes, longtime Congolese
exiles who have fought in Angola's army.
</P>
<P>
   What is becoming clear, however, is that there is a growing rift
within the continent separating countries like Rwanda and Uganda _
two of the United States' closest African friends _ from a series
of other countries, particularly in southern and central Africa,
like Angola and Zimbabwe, that resent their far-flung
interventionism.
</P>
<P>
   For now, say experts in African political affairs, Congo is the
theater of this tension, whose immediate effects are still mostly
unpredictable. What is to be feared, however, they say, is that the
rivalries and instability these tensions create will eventually be
played out on a far larger stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening now could lead to the breakup of the
Congo,'' said one senior Central African diplomat who spoke on
condition of anonymity. ``It could lead to a new explosion of the
civil war in Angola. It could backfire on Rwanda, exacting a
terrible price from a country that is ruled by a small minority.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the first scenario the diplomat cited, if Kabila's forces
are unable to hold the capital, they may simply decide to retreat
to Lubumbashi, the president's ethnic fief in southern Congo. That
would effectively turn Lubumbashi, a mining center and the
country's second largest city, into a de facto rival capital of
Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   What is worse, these analysts say, however well masked by
hastily cobbled together coalitions, the imposition of a new
government in Kinshasa by a foreign power like Rwanda, which is
deeply despised by the population of much of this country, is
unlikely to produce stability.
</P>
<P>
   Although Angola, which has the region's largest army, has yet to
show its hand completely in the current crisis, African diplomats
say that country's primary interest here is in having a stable
government, and hopefully one that can secure the long common
border.
</P>
<P>
   This interest has begun to drive Angolan diplomacy in a separate
direction from Rwanda's.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, the bitter Angolan opposition movement known as
Unita, which was allied with Mobutu, would like to see a weak
regime in Congo, or at least one too disorganized to prevent
Unita's soldiers and diamond traffickers from using Congolese
territory for rear bases.
</P>
<P>
   The new rebel coalition that is fighting Kabila has had close
contacts with people who were dignitaries in Mobutu's regime,
making many suspect that their friends in Unita stand ready to
assist the rebellion against Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is tiny, but powerful, Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the rebellion succeeds in toppling Kabila or not, many
here say that over the long term, Rwanda's interventions in Congo
politics are likely to come back and haunt it.
</P>
<P>
   Already, in Kabila's desperate efforts to save himself, his
government has openly made common cause with anti-Tutsi guerrilla
groups that have been attacking both Rwanda and Burundi for years
from Congolese soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rwanda has decided to make life difficult for us, and we have
understood that the only way for Congo to have peace is to make
trouble for Rwanda,'' said Jean-Baptiste Sondji, one of Kabila's
health minister, in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the enemies of your enemy become your friends, well
we are going to work with the Hutu to end minority power in Rwanda
once and for all. We cannot let the massacres start up again, but
Congo must come to dominate Rwanda and not vice versa.''
</P>
<P>
   His bitter vow may not come true anytime soon, but for anyone
who has experienced the shrill hatred of Rwanda in this country
since the latest rebellion, it is not hard to imagine that a grudge
against that country will be held for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This war is a repeat of an already failed attempt to settle
the future of Congo by force,'' said one senior African diplomat.
``Instead, it has set people and whole regions against each other.
What we have now are nations and whole communities that are
learning to hate each other. The only hope for putting an end to
that is through talking.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
