<SLUG> BC-MA-OBRIEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'BRIENS SEEK DISBARMENT OF DA WHO LED PROSECUTION OF SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The parents of Edward S. O'Brien Tuesday asked the
Board of Bar Overseers to begin the process of disbarring Middlesex
District Attorney Thomas F. Reilly for the way he oversaw the
murder conviction of their son for the killing of his Somerville
neighbor, Janet Downing.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly dismissed the move as a desperate attack by two
emotionally overwrought parents.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's parents, Edward and Patricia O'Brien, Tuesday filed a
three-page complaint with the bar overseers, the board that
disciplines attorneys in Massachusetts. Should the board determine
that the O'Briens' complaint has merit, it would be passed on to
the Supreme Judicial Court.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Briens claim that Reilly violated numerous ethical
guidelines for prosecutors between July 23, 1995, when Downing's
body was found in her home on Boston Street, until Oct. 1, 1997,
when a Middlesex Superior Court jury convicted the teenager of
first-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we'd love to see him disbarred,'' the elder O'Brien
said of Reilly, in a telephone interview Tuesday. ``He's abused too
many people in his career -- all for political gain.''
</P>
<P>
   The O'Briens assert that Reilly violated ethical guidelines
calling for him to share evidence with the defense and avoid
pre-trial publicity.
</P>
<P>
   They also claim he violated ethical rules in his closing
argument, and, when a Somerville Juvenile Court judge ruled that
O'Brien should be tried as a juvenile, Reilly ``went shopping'' for
a tougher judge.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly is currently a candidate for the Democratic nomination
for attorney general. The elder O'Brien said he was not involved in
the political campaign, and was acting solely because he believed
it was in his son's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our son is serving life without parole,'' he said. ``I will do
anything, and I mean anything, to clear his name and get him home.
Both me and my wife will go to any extent to right this wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly said in written statement Tuesday that the allegations by
the O'Briens are ``reckless and they are false.'' He added that
``we all know that the O'Briens are very emotional when it comes to
their son's case. And it's not unexpected that they would continue
to lash out at our office and me personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly also said, ``It must be very painful for them, but Janet
Downing was brutally murdered by their son and her family has
suffered a great deal. ... Edward O'Brien received a fair trial and
was convicted on the evidence. Our job was to hold him responsible
for murdering Janet Downing and that is what we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld, bar counsel to the BBO, said Tuesday that his
office would not investigate the O'Briens' complaint about Reilly
until appeals courts rule on the case.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, the courts find that prosecutorial misconduct
occurred, then the BBO would likely become involved, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
