<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0060 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRIVATE-COX     08-18 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRIVATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Past headline-makers keep quiet on Clinton controversy
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When the details of a public figure's private life
become water cooler conversation, the topic of discussion often
ducks for cover _ for the moment and sometimes forever.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's admission Monday night of a relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky that ``was not
appropriate'' sent many reporters Tuesday in search of other public
figures who have been touched by private scandal.
</P>
<P>
   But even years after sordid private details circulated about
them, many of those once accustomed to the media circus now prefer
silence.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Republican Bob Packwood resigned from the U.S. Senate
amid accusations of sexual and ethical misconduct by women on his
staff. At the time, the Oregon legislator said, ``Am I sorry? Of
course _ if I did the things that they said I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at his Washington office Tuesday, Packwood kept quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not whine about the past,'' Packwood said. ``You're
generous to ask, but I'd rather not talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the most salacious campaign scandals of the 1980s,
presidential hopeful Gary Hart dared journalists to follow him to
determine if he was involved in an extra-marital affair. He was
caught with mistress Donna Rice, who has since added the married
name Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not talking about any of that or the current situation
because it doesn't help with what I'm doing,'' said Hughes, now a
crusader against pornography on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Hart also refuses comparison of his situation with Clinton's,
despite nearly 30 media requests, his Denver law secretary said
Tuesday. In 1988, publicity about his affair capsized his
presidential campaign. He later called it a ``damn fool mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   On television in 1969, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy (D-Mass.) didn't
acknowledge driving his car into the Chappaquiddick River in an
accident that killed passenger Mary Jo Kopechne. ``The car that I
was driving went off a narrow bridge,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Just two months ago, Kennedy said, ``And I've indicated before,
you know, that I've accepted responsibility for it.''
</P>
<P>
   For many politicians, a straightforward apology, especially for
private lapses, is hard to deliver. Often, there's ``regret.'' But
to ``apologize'' is an art in politics. Some seized on that during
Clinton's address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised that he just didn't say, `I apologize,' or `I'm
sorry' to the American people,'' said Chris Cabbot, a student at
Pennsylvania's La Salle University. Some at the White House shared
his sentiment while others were content with his contrition.
</P>
<P>
   On TV, Clinton admitted a ``critical lapse in judgment and a
personal failure on my part for which I am solely and completely
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That certainly sounded like an apology to me,'' said Ann
Lewis, White House communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
