<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMMIGRATION-COX     08-18 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Talent in the national interest
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Kurylo
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Michael Favorov is a Russian doctor at the Centers for
Disease Control who helped discover a new strain of hepatitis.
</P>
<P>
   Yiannis Ventikos is a Greek scientist at Georgia Tech whose
research helps to save fish endangered by hydroelectric power
plants.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Cregan-O'Brien is a world-class Irish dancer who teaches
American children the traditional steps of her homeland.
</P>
<P>
   All came to Atlanta on a special immigrant visa available only
to the world's best and brightest in science, arts, education,
business or athletics. Known as the national interest waiver, it is
given to immigrants who can prove their skills and talents are so
unique that America would substantially benefit if they were here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked for me and I would say this is a great thing for the
United States, too,'' said Ventikos, 33, who has a doctorate in
fluid mechanics. His national interest waiver application was
approved last year and he became a U.S. permanent resident this
year.
</P>
<P>
   There are several paths to U.S. permanent residency, which can
lead to citizenship. The majority of immigrants are allowed to
enter because a family member is a U.S. citizen. Others are
sponsored by employers who have to prove the immigrants are not
taking jobs from Americans. That process, coordinated by the U.S.
Labor Department, is called labor certification.
</P>
<P>
   But skilled professionals who can prove their work is in the
national interest of the United States can get on the fast track
and bypass labor certification, which can take 18 months or more.
By contrast, national interest waivers can be approved in several
months.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not taking jobs from American workers,'' said Carolyn
Soloway, an Atlanta immigration lawyer whose firm has helped
hundreds of immigrants get national interest waivers. ``They are
granted the visa because they have something so unique and so
unusual to contribute that you can't just stick an ad in the
newspaper and find someone that can do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who get national interest waivers are doctors,
scientists and researchers who work at the Centers for Disease
Control and research universities such as Georgia Tech, Emory and
the University of Georgia. The national interest waiver is also
open to artists and others who make cultural contributions.
Cregan-O'Brien, 24, qualified because she was able to prove that
she could make cultural and educational contributions through Irish
many lines step dancing. A competitive dancer for 20 years, she
also is qualified to teach. She arrived in Atlanta in July and has
started teaching students through the non-profit Irish Dancers of
Atlanta. Before she arrived, the school had been flying in Irish
dance teachers from Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't qualified teachers coming out of the woodwork,''
said Jack O'Neill, president of Irish Dancers of Atlanta. The
group, founded last year, includes about 60 families with 80
children. Most are of Irish extraction and their goal is to learn
Irish dancing and celebrate their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill advertised for an Irish dance teacher in the United
States but found no one who was willing to move to Atlanta. ``To
get the quality of teacher we wanted, we needed to go to Ireland,''
he said, adding that children who want to compete have to be taught
by certified instructors.
</P>
<P>
   Cregan-O'Brien's attorney, Benjamin Landey, was able to prove
that her talent would benefit America culturally and educationally.
She applied for a national interest waiver last November and was
approved in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an art form that's taken very seriously throughout the
world,'' said Landey. ``Among people of Irish descent, it strongly
assists them in maintaining their cultural roots. There aren't that
many qualified teachers around who can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Landey discovered that an eclectic array of immigrants had
gotten national interest waivers because of their cultural
contributions, including a Russian ballroom dancer, a folk dancer
from Mexico, a Filipino painter, a classical musician from India
and a Chinese composer. So he agreed to help Cregan-O'Brien get
one, too.
</P>
<P>
   Applicants must document their unique talents, educational
background and extraordinary contributions to their field. They
must also provide up to a dozen letters from experts who can
explain how their work will benefit the United States.
Cregan-O'Brien had letters from Irish dance experts in Ireland and
the United States, and officials from the Georgia Council for the
Arts, Callanwolde Fine Arts Center and the Fulton County Arts
Council. She also was endorsed by Georgia Sen. Max Cleland and Rep.
Joseph P. Kennedy II of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Soloway said her clients submit letters from international
institutes and organizations in the private and the public sector
that have the expertise to determine whether a person's
contribution would be in the national interest. Scientists and
doctors, for instance, might ask officials from the World Health
Organization or UNICEF to vouch for their work, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to show the person has a very wide and international
reputation by getting letters from experts in the field from as
many different countries as we can,'' Soloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the effort, Landey said, ``Not too many people qualify
for this. It is hard to prove.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no clear rules on who is eligible for a national
interest waiver, immigration officials in Washington said. Neither
Congress, which wrote the law in 1990, nor the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, which has to write rules to apply it, have
defined national interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't really any firm guidelines out there,'' said
Edward Skerrett, chief of the INS administrative appeals unit in
Washington, D.C., which reviews applications that have been denied.
``When we wrote the regulations, we said it was up to the
petitioner to demonstrate that a waiver of the job labor
certification would be in the national interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirements are vague and subjective. Decisions are made by
officers at INS centers across the country. Denials can be appealed
to INS officers in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've consistently looked for some substantial benefit to the
United States,'' said John Grissom, an INS official in Washington.
``It is a bit difficult to quantify.'' Although the INS could
provide no exact figures, Grissom said ``very few'' national
interest waivers get approved on appeal. ``They approve a lot of
them in the field. They get all the petitions and we only get the
bad ones. That's why we don't approve many.'' He recalled a
petition by a man who claimed to be ``the world's greatest
whistler'' whose application still was not approved on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, Congress wrote the law to include artists and
others who make cultural and educational contributions, which is
why dancers and scientists have an equal shot at getting a national
interest waiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for a guy who's got some kind of track record, who can
submit evidence that his future work would be in the national
interest,'' he said. ``We look for evidence that indicates they are
a cut above the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
