<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0062 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT &LR;      08-18 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-REPORT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GOOD NEWS ABOUT TODAY'S ECONOMIC REPORT? ... THERE WAS NO BAD
NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MARKET-NYT, CREDIT-NYT) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By SYLVIA NASAR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tuesday's good news about the U.S. economy was the
refreshing absence of bad news: The Federal Reserve did not raise
interest rates at this morning's monetary policy meeting. Inflation
did not rise much in July. And the trade deficit did not widen
further in June, as economists had expected.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lowest unemployment rate in a generation, consumer
prices edged up just 0.2 percent in July, the Commerce Department
reported. Prices are up just 1.7 percent from a year ago, an
extraordinary &QL; 
performance for the seventh year of an economic expansion. And
despite the robust dollar and deepening depression in Asia, the
U.S. trade deficit fell by more than $1 billion in June to $14.2
billion. In dollars, that's still close to a record high, but as a
share of the economy _ a more meaningful yardstick _ the trade
deficit is still just two thirds of its 1980s peak. Exports fell
but at a far slower rate than in recent months. Imports fell as
well, as businesses purchased less equipment from abroad and oil
prices dropped another notch.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the Federal Reserve announced that it was
leaving its target for the overnight lending rate known as the
federal funds rate _ a benchmark for all interest rates _ at 5.5
percent and the discount rate, the rate the Fed charges banks for
emergency loans, at 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the central bank offered no explanation of its
decision, but hardly any economists were predicting a change in
policy. With inflation tame, the economy slowing but not in
immediate danger of slipping into recession, and turmoil in Russia
and elsewhere, the Fed's best action was inaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fed has been very successful ... and blessed,'' said
Robert di Clemente, co-head of U.S. economic research at Salomon
Brothers Smith Barney. ``Most of us feel that they would have been
compelled to tighten if it had not been for the shock from Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose sharply for the second day. Bute whatever the market
was celebrating, it probably wasn't economic news, which came as no
surprise to Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Inflation may well be leveling out after declining for much of
this expansion. Right now, however, the strong dollar and the
growing share of imports are helping to hold down prices. Consumer
prices for goods are up just 0.4 percent from a year ago. It's not
just that imports, like gasoline, clothing and consumer
electronics, are cheaper. It's also that inexpensive imports are
helping restrain domestic prices by intensifying competition.
</P>
<P>
   The most encouraging news in Tuesday's consumer price report is
that inflation in the service sector _ which accounts for
two-thirds of spending and more than four-fifths of employment _ is
a remarkably tame 3 percent. That's half the rate of inflation in
services at the end of the 1980s boom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Services inflation is very benign,'' said Maury Harris, chief
economist at PaineWebber. ``It's higher than goods inflation, but
it hasn't accelerated.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's true across a wide range of services. From a year ago,
for example, housing is up 3.3 percent, car repair 2.4 percent,
haircuts and other personal services 2.2 percent and airline and
other transportation 1.2 percent. Even the prices of medical
services, a category in which economists expect heftier increases
now that the shift to managed care has pretty much been completed,
is up just 3.2 percent, faster than a year ago but moderate by past
standards.
</P>
<P>
   With labor markets tighter than they've been in decades,
employment in services in growing by more than 230,000 workers a
month, and wages are rising handily. So the absence of inflation in
services is a puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Like Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, Harris said he suspects that
the productivity of workers in services may be rising faster than
the official measures are capturing. Competition in services is
also fierce, so businesses are having a tough time raising prices.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, cheaper imports are having an indirect effect on
wage-setting in the service industry by holding down the cost of
living.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit will almost certainly keep getting bigger as
the troubles in Asia deepen. Exports to Asia have already fallen 21
percent from a year ago, and exports to the rest of the world are
growing slowly. Imports are apt to bounce back. Imports from Asia
are beginning to head higher. Indeed, the trade deficit is apt to
remain the biggest drag on economic growth, as it was during the
year's first half. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected improvement in the trade deficit is a temporary
respite. June's smaller trade deficit implies that growth in the
second &QL; 
quarter, which slowed to 1.4 percent from 5.4 percent in the
winter, might have been a bit stronger than first estimated. But
one detail of Tuesday's trade report _ a sharp decline in imports
of capital goods _ implies that business spending on new equipment
may have been weakening at the end of last quarter. If that's so,
the effects would cancel each other out.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the widening trade deficit has knocked 2.5
percentage points off economic growth. The negative effect is
likely to diminish over time but economists expect it to persist
well into next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's bad news for American manufacturers, but good news for
inflation,''said Pierre Ellis, senior economist at Primark Decision
Economics, an economic forecasting firm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
