<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-AUBURN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    QB Leard prepared for first start
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN, Ala. _ In an ideal world, Ben Leard's first start as a
college quarterback would be a low-key, low-pressure afternoon. One
of those directional Louisiana schools would be the opponent, and
the game would be over at halftime _ no TV and very little hype.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Leard's debut as Auburn's quarterback on Sept. 3 will
take place in the most visable of circumstances: against a highly
ranked team _ No. 16 Virginia _ on national televison (ESPN), on a
Thursday night when it's the only game in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``A writer asked me if I was going to be nervous, knowing there
would be millions of people watching if I screwed up,'' Leard said.
``I hadn't really thought about it that way. I like to think of
millions of people watching when we play well and win.''
</P>
<P>
   What others might view as a nerve-wracking moment on a national
stage, the sophomore from Hartwell sees as a golden opportunity
that has been two years in the making. He has served his
apprenticeship under Dameyune Craig, Auburn's No. 3 all-time
passer. Craig, said Leard, taught him patience, leadership and the
benefits of hard work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backing him up for two years was one of the most beneficial
things that has ever happened to me in football,'' Leard said.
``Dameyune has a brilliant football mind. He prepared me for
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Craig left, he did something even more important for
Leard. After tutoring the young quarterback for two years, Craig
sent this message to the rest of the returning Auburn football
team: ``This guy can play. Treat him as you would me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dameyune paid a lot of attention to me, and that got me some
respect, even though I hadn't played,'' said Leard, who attempted
only two passes in four games last season. ``Dameyune accepted me,
so they accepted me. It gave me the confidence to tell a 320-pound
offensive lineman to get his butt in gear.''
</P>
<P>
   Leard's steep learning and leadership curve is one reason that
coach Terry Bowden feels confident as he reshapes the Auburn
offense in 1998. Last season under Craig, 78.7 percent of Auburn's
offense was passing and the Tigers were an uncustomary 11th in the
SEC (73.83 ypg) in rushing offense.
</P>
<P>
   This Auburn offense will be more conventional and balanced. The
Tigers have a veteran offensive line and, they hope, an emerging
star at tailback in sophomore Demontray Carter. Leard's job,
particularly early in the year, will be to keep things simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job, especially at first, is not to lose the football game
for us,'' Leard said. ``I can't make stupid mistakes. I have to
make good decisions. I have to get the ball to the right people and
see the right things. If I can do that early, then later on I'll
get the opportunity to have the pressure on me to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bowden wants to make one thing clear about his new
quarterback. Leard is young, but he's not some guy to just hand the
ball off and get out of the way. Bowden says that when it comes to
describing Leard, he'll defer to Dameyune Craig: This guy can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``People forget that Ben was an outstanding recruit. A lot of
people wanted him,'' said Bowden, who is beginning his sixth season
at Auburn. ``He hasn't played much in two years, so maybe some
people forgot about him. When it comes time to play, I expect him
to have a lot of polish.''
</P>
<P>
   As a high school senior in 1995, Leard was one of four Southern
quarterbacks who had the recruiters burning the midnight oil. The
others were Tim Couch of Hyden, Ky., Quincy Carter of Atlanta and
Tee Martin of Mobile, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the group of quarterbacks that everybody was
recruiting. We all traded information about where we were going.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the four quarterbacks, only Couch ended up where most
expected, when he signed with Kentucky after a flirtation with
Tennessee. Carter signed with Georgia Tech, played two years of
professional baseball and then enrolled at Georgia. Martin verbally
committed to Auburn and then signed with Tennessee. Leard, who grew
up dreaming of playing for Georgia, signed with Auburn. All four
could be starting for their respect schools this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Two major events on Nov. 18, 1995, converged to steer Leard away
from Georgia and into the arms of Auburn. Early on that Saturday, a
press conference was held in Athens, Ga. to announce that Ray Goff
had been dismissed after seven seasons as Georgia's head coach.
</P>
<P>
   That night, at the invitation of Auburn assistant coach Rodney
Garner, Leard attended his first Auburn-Alabama game. Auburn won
the game 31-27 at Jordan-Hare Stadium, and Leard was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been to all the big rivalries _ Florida-Florida State,
Georgia-Georgia Tech _ but I had never seen anything like that,''
said Leard, who visited Auburn again in January and decided to sign
with the Tigers despite a late push from the new staff at Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   More irony: Garner, the man who persuaded Leard to say goodbye
to Georgia and sign with Auburn, is now on the Bulldog coaching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough decision at the time, but now I can't imagine
being anywhere else,'' Leard said. ``Some things just feel right.
And Auburn feels right for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leard's decision to leave home begins to pay its first real
dividends on Sept. 3. That when the nation _ and any family members
who couldn't get tickets _ will be watching as Leard fulfills his
dream of being a starting college quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting a tremendous opportunity here, a better
opportunity than I could ever have imagined,'' Leard said. ``Now
it's up to me to take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming Thursday: Georgia Southern
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
