<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-FEATURE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some complaints follow the close of the PGA Championship
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Was obscure Sahalee Country Club a success last week
as the venue for the 80th PGA Championship? For the most part, yes,
particularly with reports of an $80 million impact to the Seattle
area. But don't confuse it with a Winged Foot or Riviera for total
contentment.
</P>
<P>
   Many players don't like a course where cramped conditions take
the driver out of their bags. There's something missing when
everyone tees off at the first hole of a major championship with a
long iron in their hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unique with the trees, but I'm anxious to start hitting
drivers again,'' Mark Calcavecchia said Sunday afternoon before
flying to Castle Pines, Colo., for the Sprint International. ''I'm
looking forward to the International and lashing some 350-yard
drives off that first tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything else? Yes. Par-5's converted to par-4's were too severe
and didn't fit the topography. Especially the 475-yard 18th, which
required a good drive to reach the top of the slope, but offered
players a tiny landing area and beckoning rough. Plus, a long iron
to a green built for a shorter iron.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a really nice golf course,'' said Joey Sindelar, ''but
I personally wish they would leave the par-5's as par-5's. The 18th
would have been a cool par-5.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Sahalee's 18th became a par-4 more mostly for fan
access. With the 17th green directly behind the tee used for the
18th as a par-5, tournament officials did not feel fans could view
each without disturbing the other.
</P>
<P>
   One thing's certain: Sahalee was a smash compared to the PGA of
America's own Valhalla Golf Club in 1996. That the PGA has chosen
Valhalla to be its showcase venue for 2000 _ when Augusta National,
Pebble Beach and St. Andrews will house the other three majors _ is
a situation already gaining unpopularity.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just can't believe it,'' said Atlanta's Billy Andrade. ''I
thought Valhalla was awful compared to this.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They had some good holes there (at Valhalla),'' said
Calcavecchia, ''but I'd rather play here (Sahalee).''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA clearly gambles when it moves to the Crooked Sticks and
Valhalla's of the golf world. Being the last major of the year, the
PGA needs substance to maintain big-time interest, and places like
Riviera, Winged Foot or Medinah ('99) always make for better
championships. As the Atlanta Athletic Club, which has hosted a few
majors, is likely to do in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the last five years: Nick Price goes wire-to-wire
at Southern Hills in 1994. (Grade: A). Steve Elkington beats Colin
Montgomerie in a playoff at Riviera in 1995, birdieing the storied
18th (A+). Mark Brooks beats Kenny Perry in a playoff at Valhalla
in 1996 (C+). Davis Love III outduels Justin Leonard at Winged Foot
in 1997 (cue the rainbow, roll teary footage; A+); Vijay Singh
bests Steve Stricker at Sahalee in 1998 (B-).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
