<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-NOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Norman cleared to hit balls
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greg Norman? Remember him? Out since April following surgery on
his right shoulder, Norman was given the OK to start hitting
pitching wedges with a full swing this week in Hobe Sound, Fla. He
plans to work up to longer clubs over the next two months and will
make the Shark Shootout Nov. 13-15 his return event, followed by
the Australian Open and the Presidents Cup at Royal Melbourne.
Caddie Tony Navarro, who's working for Jeff Sluman while his boss
mends, predicts he's ''really going to be ready.'' He wasn't
talking about Norman's physical condition, either. . . Marietta's
Larry Nelson will see Columbus orthopedic specialist Tom Boers
today for another opinion on the herniated cervical disk that took
him off the Senior Tour July 24. Working with light weights this
week to strengthen his shoulder, Nelson has felt the return of some
pain and therefore backed off earlier plans to start hitting
wedges. Frustrated with his progress, Nelson said, ''Each day or
each week I delay hitting balls pushes me a week further into the
year. Right now I don't see playing before Indianapolis (Sept.
11-13).'' Although Nelson and Orlando orthopedic specialist Norton
Baker feel surgery can be avoided, the two-time PGA and U.S. Open
champion said, ''Sometimes you think, 'Will you ever play the same
way again? Will I ever gain back the strength and distance I once
had?'
</P>
<P>
   It kind of worries you sometimes. I don't want to compete if I
can't compete at the level I was at before.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh speaks through his game
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, the new PGA champion, would labor to gather votes
for golf's congeniality award. He is often grumpy with reporters
and is prone to refusing invitations to the media center. Beyond
that, Singh seems to blame reporters if they mention the accusation
of cheating on his scorecard during the 1985 Indonesian Open that
led to a suspension from the Asian Tour. Say this for Singh,
though. Sunday's pressure at Sahalee wasn't the most intense of his
life. As the story goes, back when Singh was making a couple of
hundred bucks a month as a club pro in Borneo, he supplemented his
income by gambling with well-to-do members. During one,
palm-sweating occasion he played the 18th hole of a match, as
Sports Illustrated's John Garrity chronicled, ''with $10 in his
pocket and $700 on the line.'' When Singh hit his first drive out
of bounds, he remembered thinking, ''How would I pay if I lost?
Would I lose my job? Would I tell my wife?'' Singh averted the
emergency by reloading, making ''eagle'' with his second ball for a
par and winning the match when his opponent hit into the water and
double-bogeyed. Said Singh. ''Now, whenever I'm in contention in a
tournament, I think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
