u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT &LR;      08-18 0402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE: FIRM LOYALIST WHO STANDS A STEP (AND A VACATION) AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES
with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS, NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(JT) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KONA, Hawaii _ While many Americans spent a good part of Tuesday
mulling over President Clinton's speech, when he acknowledged his
relationship with a White House intern, Vice President Al Gore did
his best to continue avoiding the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who is on a two-week vacation with his family here on the
island of Hawaii, made a brief public appearance across the state
at the airport in Lihue on Kauai island.
</P>
<P>
   But he said little that was different from his remarks following
the president's speech Monday night, in which Gore expressed
support for Clinton and the hope that the nation would get beyond
the matter. He took no questions.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the likely Democratic presidential nominee in 2000,
the controversial developments swirling about the president are a
political minefield. Throughout the investigation into the
president's relationship with a former intern, Monica Lewinsky,
Gore has been a Clinton loyalist but has seemed to position himself
far enough to avoid being tainted by any fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Even his vacation plans, scheduled long ago, give at least the
appearance of separation. Hawaii is about as far from the White
House as Gore could have gone and still be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But his trip here is serving another purpose. Unlike most other
places, the state economy in Hawaii is sagging, a condition that
has undermined support for Gov. Ben Cayetano in the governor's
race. Statewide polls show that Cayetano is trailing his Republican
challenger, Linda Lingle, the mayor of Maui.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving for the mainland next week, Gore is scheduled to
make several appearances with Cayetano, including one at a
fund-raiser. Gore is also scheduled to speak at the annual
convention of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees and at a school to drum up support for smaller
class sizes, a favorite issue of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading back to Washington on Aug. 27, Gore is planning
to make several appearances in the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
</TEXT>
