<HEADLINE>
HUFFMAN ATTEMPTING TO CAST A NEW LOOK TO TCU FOOTBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ At the end of another long, hot practice
session, TCU running back LaDainian Tomlinson leans against a
cyclone fence in the shade, waiting for a ride back to the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   The serenity of the moment, however, is jolted by the sound of a
familiar voice: ``Hey L.T., you're gonna dye your hair pretty soon,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   Momentarily startled, Tomlinson smiles and says, ``Yeah, man,
I'm gonna dye it ... pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, the disease spreads. The bleached blond malady that has
struck the TCU receivers will evidently soon infest the running
backs. And there are those higher in the organization who might be
in grave danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches have promised that if we go to a bowl or do
anything like that, they'll bleach theirs, too,'' said the
perpetrator, Royce Huffman, grinning widely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Royce already hit me with that one on a TV show,'' coach
Dennis Franchione said, laughing, ``and, well, I guess I said yes.
He challenged us to do it, and if it helps us, I'll do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will take more than blond hair to transform the
1-10 Frogs into princes, but Huffman is a key milepost on TCU's
road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   He returns for his third season as the team punter and second as
punt return specialist. He is also running No. 1 at a slot receiver
position, and Franchione is disappointed that he was unable to try
out for the quarterback job during spring drills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really would have liked to have him trying for that job,''
Franchione said. ``He was a good high school quarterback, and I
think he might have been a fit for our offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has good skills and he's extremely competitive. But the
biggest thing is that he just understands the game so well, and
he's a valuable person to have out there on the field. He picks up
things very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, however, Huffman was busy gaining second-team
All-America status as TCU's sturdy third baseman _ hitting .420
with 17 home runs, 77 runs batted in and a .783 slugging
percentage.
</P>
<P>
   He candidly admits he was disappointed at not being drafted, but
the game ain't over yet.
</P>
<P>
   A junior in football eligibility, he will be a baseball senior
in the spring and _ barring injury _ is a virtual cinch to become
the school career leader in hits, doubles, home runs, total bases
and walks. He already holds the record for RBI. He also figures at
no worse than second in runs, batting average and slugging
percentage. Among the season's highlights were a 20-game hitting
streak and 27 multihit games, including 16 where he had three or
more hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be kind of stupid of me to say I wasn't disappointed
in the draft,'' he said, ``but I'm not going to dwell on it. It's
football season now, and this team is coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, Huffman will doubtless be a major reason. After averaging
42.6 yards per punt in 1996, he averaged 41.6 on 81 punts last
season and ran down under five of them to make the tackle on a
startled return man. He averaged 5.6 yards on 31 punt returns,
earning second-team All-Western Athletic Conference honors. He
completed a pass and caught one.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the nickname, ``Slash,'' after the Pittsburgh Steelers'
multi-talented quarterback Kordell Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Franchione admits to some misgivings about watching his star
punter run pass routes in a game but figures the return on the
investment could be beneficial for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Royce and I have sat down and discussed it a couple of times,
and he seems comfortable with it,'' Franchione said. ``Also,
(freshman) Joey Biasatti is coming along well and could probably
take over the punting if he had to.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my standpoint, we're in a situation where we need to put
our best people out on the field, and right now, Royce is running
No. 1 at three positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is also his value to the team in other ways. There is a
leadership council on this team, and in the spring his teammates
voted Royce onto the council, even though he's a junior and was off
playing baseball at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, armed with Huffman's leadership and grooming skills, the
Frogs are ready for a brave new world. So is Huffman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, the only real problem I have right now is that I'm so
excited I can't sleep,'' Huffman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
