<SLUG> BC-CINNABON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC poised to go public after announcing buyout of Cinnabon
Int'l
 &HT;    By Mickey H. Gramig
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AFC Enterprises is buying Cinnabon International for
$65 million, giving the Atlanta-based restaurant company the
country's largest cinnamon roll retailer and setting the wheels in
motion to take AFC public.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle-based Cinnabon, which posted $140 million in sales for
the 12 months ending March 31, has 358 retail cinnamon roll
bakeries in 39 states, Canada and Mexico. The 13-year-old company
specializes in high-traffic locations at malls, airports and
supermarkets; it owns and operates 214 of its stores and franchises
the remaining 144.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, set to close in late September, will give AFC six
brands with $2 billion in annual sales and roughly 3,200
restaurants, bakeries and cafes in 25 countries. It also will give
AFC the momentum it wants to achieve before an initial public
offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd probably be targeting sometime in second quarter or later
of next year, depending on market conditions,'' said Chief
Executive Frank Belatti.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly feel that we've accomplished the task of getting
ourselves ready for new growth,'' he added. ``This is kind of a
pivotal year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Belatti helped form AFC, then known as America's Favorite
Chicken, in 1992. That year, the company's Popeyes Chicken &AMP;
Biscuits and Churchs Chicken chains posted a $32 million loss on
$1.1 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   AFC celebrated its five-year turnaround with 1997 net income of
$8.8 million, or 25 cents per share, on $1.6 billion in sales. AFC
also stepped up its growth strategy last year, by selling $175
million in 10-year notes to fund acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, AFC spent $11.8 million to acquire the Chesapeake
Bagel Bakery chain, which it overhauled and now calls Chesapeake
Bagels, Bakery &AMP; Cafe. Less than a year later, it completed its
purchase of Seattle Coffee, and its Seattle's Best and Torrefazione
Italia brand cafes, for an estimated $50 million to $75 million.
</P>
<P>
   This past spring, AFC announced a deal to buy the
California-based Paradise Bakery &AMP; Cafe chain. That acquisition,
which included 49 West Coast restaurants, was called off last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been pursuing the Paradise transaction as well as
(Cinnabon) and one other opportunity,'' Belatti said. ``You never
really know which one will materialize.''
</P>
<P>
   Belatti said the Paradise deal was called off because the more
expensive Cinnabon deal came through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, we just don't have the people to devote to doing two
integrations and all the work that needs to be done,'' he said.
``We have to target and focus our energies.''
</P>
<P>
   That will involve determining how AFC wants to leverage Cinnabon
in connection with the company's other brands. For example, it must
decide whether to replace Cinnabon's current coffee with Seattle's
Best or add the chain's cinnamon rolls and other offerings to AFC's
Chesapeake locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea will be to take the brands we have and build brand
awareness for all of them...and make sure we're not cannibalizing
on the existing business,'' Belatti said.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabon will continue to have offices in Seattle, as is the
case with Seattle Coffee, but some key executives likely will be
relocated to Atlanta. About 50 new Cinnabon locations will be added
each year for the next several years, and most will be franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
