<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTRANET-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intranets changing the way some conduct business
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It is euphemistically called busy work, but it can
drain a day in a bad way.
</P>
<P>
   A marketing rep needs an ad display for a trade show. But half a
dozen people are in charge of knowing what's available. Hours can
burn securing the right one.
</P>
<P>
   Nokia hopes to tighten that process, and others, with its
Intranet. An in-house network, Nokia's Intranet will give the
company's 3,500 employees in the Americas desktop-access to
companywide information such as human resources department forms
and company news and site-specific services such as reservation
lists for conference rooms and trade show displays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty easy sell,'' said Stephen McClintick, who will
head the eight people developing and maintaining Nokia's Intranet,
the password-protected part of the telecommunication company's
World Wide Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that a lot of companies are doing and I
think everybody here saw the need for it,'' McClintick said.
``Improving employee communications was the main selling point.
It's fairly easy to point out to somebody that if you could reserve
a conference room on the Intranet by looking at a map, clicking on
a room and pulling up a schedule, it saves time and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Intranets are evolving, like their big brother the Internet, at
Pentium-like speed. Companies posted first versions in 1995. Early
sites were more or less electronic bulletin boards, static
documents electronically tacked for employees to read.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Intranets, like Ketchum Public Relations Worldwide's,
which went online in February, are becoming workday fixtures,
although the term Intranet is still not a common term outside the
online world. Ketchum PR's Intranet is called the Ketchum Global
Network, or KGN _ avoiding the use of the word Intranet altogether
to dilute the technospeak and confusion that comes from the
similarly named Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Ketchum network has an electronic listing of names and
addresses, forms, e-mail addresses, media lists, company news
updated daily, management memos, and an in-house search engine,
which acts as a kind of corporate yellow pages, a way of preserving
institutional knowledge. If a public relations representative is
working on an airline account, he or she can search for others in
the company who have worked on similar accounts as well as read the
text of old presentations to airline accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Intranet is an electronic equivalent of everything we do
at our desk on a daily basis,'' said Paul McKeon, president of
Ketchum PR's Crescent Communications in Atlanta. Ketchum PR has
developed a new media group that will coordinate and develop
Internet and Intranet marketing efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Creating an Intranet site can be expensive and time consuming.
The typical Intranet has a three-month gestation period and costs
about $100,00 for the consulting. And that does not include
hardware costs. Ketchum PR is consulting with Nokia on the
development of its Intranet, which will consolidate 30 networks
used by the Finnish company's American business groups.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Ketchum PR's full-time employees _ one in New York City,
one in Washington, D.C. _ update the global Web site daily. Any of
Ketchum's 1,000 employees can e-mail information for posting. The
two staffers also listen in on conference calls and write reports
for the company news section of the in-house network.
</P>
<P>
   Norcross-based Etech develops software to make Intranets more
user-friendly. Karla Mock, Etech director of business development,
said most companies use Intranets to improve efficiency in their
human resources, sales and marketing, manufacturing and accounting
departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``More tools and technology are available. It's not just
browsing and looking at information,'' she said. ``It allows more
intricate searches, functions like mortgage calculators and links
to related articles and company archives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Benelli of Kinetic Design, a Web-design firm in Midtown
Atlanta, said she hops on her Intranet up to 20 times a day,
looking for client and prospect information and pulling up employee
schedules to track down a telecommuting worker with a call holding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intranets got a little bit of a slow start, but they've really
taken off,'' said Andy Roach, director of Ketchum PR's new media
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``They represent a kind of a sea change in the way people do
business. It gives them access to things they didn't have.
Companies are saying more and more that our greatest champions of
who we are as a company are our employees and they need to know
what we're doing from a strategic level and a marketing level,''
Roach said.
</P>
<P>
   For developers, an Intranet is a chance to work with a captive
audience. Intranets have fewer users and more of a built-in sense
of community than the Internet. And developers know the equipment
capabilities of their users.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Web, you have to go with the lowest common
denominator,'' Roach said. ``Intranets are actually kind of fun for
developers because we can go to town on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
