<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2KSIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    500 days and countingBy Rob Chambers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today is the 500th day before the millennium monster
begins biting vulnerable computer systems on Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Today's milestone is a serious reminder of the approaching
deadline. And it's more of a ceremonial date than a real one, since
Year 2000 problems have and will crop up before then. But it's a
good time to take stock. If your company is running behind, there
are some user groups in the area that can help you get started or
get the process completed.
</P>
<P>
   If your company is big or can benefit from the experience of
large organizations like Ford Motor Company, then the Information
Management Forum may be for you (http://www.infomgmtforum.com).
It's an Atlanta headquartered association of U.S. and Canadian
information technology professionals at Fortune 1000-sized
companies. In the metro area, Coca-Cola Enterprises, Equifax,
Georgia-Pacific, Life of Georgia, Southern Company, and SunTrust
Banks are members.
</P>
<P>
   This organization's Year 2000 group meets each quarter for two
days to share information. Written reports of the proceedings are
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, Day 500 indicates there's not a whole lot of time
left ... While there's 500 days until Jan. 1, 2000, before that
many systems will be affected by what we call millennium events,''
said James A. Jones, a director of the Information Management Forum
and head of its Year 2000 group.
</P>
<P>
   Before Jan. 1, 2000 many computer systems ``will have to
encounter or process a date in the year 2000 or beyond. So, for
example, business and inventory planning systems that go out 12
months or beyond could have trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones went on to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a very large company and you haven't done anything
yet, you're in trouble. You have systems that are date impacted and
the time you have left isn't enough to make systems compliant.
There is still time, however, to get core systems compliant and to
develop contingency plans for those systems you will not have time
to make compliant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Small companies that use stand-alone PCs or small network
systems in their business still have plenty of time, but they have
to get going. And the issue for them could become the shortage of
people available to do the work and potentially a shortage of
parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in Atlanta at this time the companies in my group are not
experiencing a skill shortage at this time,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   A broader forum is offered by the Atlanta Year 2000 Users Group
(http://www.bytewise.com/atlyear2000/). It was organized by larger
companies, but it's open to all, said Paul Arne, a partner at the
Morris, Manning &AMP; Martin law firm and a board member of the Atlanta
Users Group.
</P>
<P>
   So where do most companies stand? On Day 500 the news is not
exactly good. Consulting giant Cap Gemini America unveiled a survey
last week showing that half of the interviewed companies plan to do
no Y2K testing. That's disturbing because virtually all the experts
in the field say that testing is the most essential part of the
cleanup process.
</P>
<P>
   Also last week the Gartner Group released the results of its
worldwide survey of 15,000 companies and government organizations
in 83 countries _ 23 percent of those who responded haven't done
anything about Y2K yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about those companies who are not fully aware of the
problem and who are not working hard,'' said Arne.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
