A0076 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AHEAD-BOS &LR;      08-18 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AHEAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS TRYING TO DECIDE HOW TO DEAL WITH CLINTON REVELATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The combination of President Clinton's defiant
attack on independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr and his failure to
explain why his sworn denial of an affair with a former White House
intern was ``legally accurate'' has infuriated key Republicans and
heightened the possibility that impeachment hearings will be held.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress, meanwhile, were studying alternatives
to impeachment, including the possibility that hearings could lead
to a vote to reprimand or censure the president. That would be
comparable to what happened in 1983, when former Representative
Gerry Studds, a Massachusetts Democrat, was censured for having
sexual relations with a teenage male page.
</P>
<P>
   This reaction to Clinton's nationally televised admission Monday
night that he had an inappropriate relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky is the opposite of what Clinton and his aides had desired.
Indeed, some Clinton allies Tuesday continued to express
astonishment at Clinton's decision to use more than half of his
brief address to attack Starr, whom many Republicans now believe is
a vindicated prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a showdown coming. ... Tuesday was not it,'' said
Representative Martin Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who sits on
the House Judiciary Committee that would consider whether to launch
impeachment proceedings. Meehan said Clinton did not provide
``enough detail'' for the issue to be resolved, yet Meehan stressed
that he does not see grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   But Representative Bill McCollum, a Florida Republican who also
sits on the Judiciary Committee, said he would be compelled to vote
to impeach the president if it is proven that Clinton lied last
January when he swore in a deposition that he did not have sexual
relations with Lewinsky. While Clinton said Monday that his initial
denial was ``legally accurate,'' he did not explain what he meant,
possibly opening the door for Congress to examine details of the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the president has clearly at the end of the day been guilty
of having committed perjury and lied under oath, then I would have
to vote for impeachment,'' McCollum said in an interview. McCollum
also said Congress has the authority to censure or reprimand,
noting that ``we condemn things every day.'' But McCollum stressed
that perjury should lead to impeachment, not just a censure.
</P>
<P>
   While Republicans were expected to be critical of the president,
the Democratic response to Clinton's admission clearly was not as
positive as the White House had hoped. House minority leader
Richard Gephardt said he was ``gratified'' the president testified
before the grand jury. ``I cannot condone the relationship the
president has acknowledged and am very disappointed in his personal
conduct,'' Gephardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate minority leader Thomas Daschle said he was
``disappointed'' that Clinton had not given a full explanation
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Dianne Feinstein of California, who was assured by
Clinton in January that he did not have an affair with Lewinsky,
announced she no longer has the same degree of trust in the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trust in his credibility has been badly shattered,''
Feinstein said &UR;  &LR; Tuesday. And Representative Paul McHale, a
Pennsylvania Democrat, said Clinton should ``resign or face
impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders such as House Speaker Newt Gingrich took
pains to stay above the fray: ``Everyone would be best served if
they waited for Judge Starr's report and found out what all the
facts were.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Orrin Hatch, a Utah Republican who chairs the Senate
Judiciary Committee, said Starr has been vindicated by Clinton's
admission. And as he left a television studio in Utah Monday night,
Hatch said Clinton's attack on Starr was a huge mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the day-after reaction in Congress to Clinton's speech
focused on the president's assertion that his initial denial of an
affair with Lewinsky was ``legally accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition for the Paula Jones lawsuit, Clinton was given
a definition of sexual relations that some Clinton defenders
maintain did not include acts such as oral sex. However, the
definition was broad enough to include ``contact with genitalia.''
But Clinton reportedly told the grand jury on Monday he didn't
think it was necessary to describe what kind of contact he had with
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal analysts and a number of Democrats believe that no
matter what Clinton said in the deposition, it does not constitute
perjury because the Jones lawsuit was thrown out and the
president's statements about Lewinsky were not ``material'' to the
case. Meehan, a former prosecutor, is among those who hold this
view. In legal terms, he said, ``there is a difference between
lying and perjury.'' While Clinton admitted he lied to the public,
Meehan said, that does not mean the president committed perjury in
the legal sense. As a result, Clinton should not be impeached for
perjury, Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the evidence out there, it is highly unlikely that
even Republicans would vote for impeachment,'' Meehan said. He
added that Republicans might try to invoke a lesser penalty such as
censure of the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
