<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0084 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-380&AMP;ADD     08-18 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGAL-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUBPOENA WOULD UNDERMINE CLINTON'S RESISTANCE, EXPERTS AGREE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES with photo,
CLINTON-PUNDITS, NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton refused to answer several
questions before a grand jury on Monday on the ground that they
invaded his privacy, but legal experts generally agree that if he
were to appear before the grand jury under subpoena he would have
no recognized legal grounds to continue resisting.
</P>
<P>
   When ordinary citizens appear before a grand jury, usually under
subpoena, they are required to answer every question put to them
unless they invoke the Fifth Amendment right against compelled
self-incrimination or some other recognized privilege, like the one
that protects spouses from being required to testify against each
other. Subpoenaed witnesses may be compelled to testify against
their friends, siblings and children, and to disclose the most
embarrassing of personal details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grand juries may ask just about anything,'' said Yale Kamisar,
a law professor at the University of Michigan. ``There's simply no
protection against embarrassing yourself or humiliating yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   In nearly five hours before the grand jury, President Clinton
acknowledged an inappropriate relationship with Monica Lewinsky but
pointedly refused to answer several of the prosecutors' questions
about the details of that relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was not under subpoena, however _ Whitewater independent
counsel Kenneth Starr had withdrawn it once the president agreed to
testify _ and so was not required to answer all questions. Yet he
did not resist on that ground. Instead, he made a broader claim
that the details of any sexual relationship were an unnecessary
intrusion by the prosecutor of his privacy rights.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts said that if Clinton is forced to appear
before the grand jury under subpoena, that would quickly alter the
ground rules and oblige Clinton to provide the answers he declined
to give Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In effect, you've got to tell them everything,'' Kamisar said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers may challenge any subpoena, arguing that under
the concept of separation of powers, the president, unlike any
other citizen, is immune to subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Kamisar said that he is unaware of any instances in which a
court allowed a witness to avoid answering questions on privacy
grounds. He said it would be a novel, ``even far-out strategy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nathan Lewin, a Washington lawyer who first publicly suggested
in an op-ed article in The New York Times that Clinton could resist
questions about the details of sexual events, said he still
believes there is a zone of privacy that may be used to block
prosecutors' questions. But even Lewin said he no longer believes
that would be appropriate for Clinton to do, because he has made
the details themselves an issue.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Monday night, Clinton said that his answers during
a Jan. 17 deposition taken in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct
suit were ``legally accurate'' although they may have been
misleading. Clinton denied then that he had engaged in ``sexual
relations'' with Ms. Lewinsky, apparently relying on a definition
of sexual relations used that day that could be interpreted to
exclude their specific sex acts.
</P>
<P>
   Lewin, who said he had not discussed the issue with Clinton's
lawyers, argued that by relying on such specific wording issues as
to what constitutes sexual relations, ``it would be perfectly
reasonable for the prosecutors to ask Clinton about the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's careful explanation both before the grand jury and the
public of his denial of ``sexual relations'' was apparently
designed to avoid a perjury charge. There are many court cases
which establish the notion that one may mislead without committing
perjury.
</P>
<P>
   A 1973 Supreme Court case that has been cited many times by
lower courts established the premise that the burden is on the
questioner to pin down the details of a response and that a vague
or evasive answer is not necessarily perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem that comes from Clinton's acknowledgment of a
sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky is how he squares that with
another statement he made on Jan. 17. In that statement he said
that he does not remember ever being alone with her except for
brief moments when she might have delivered documents in her role
as a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   How can he acknowledge sexual contact with her but not remember
whether he was alone with her? Courts have increasingly held that
saying ``I can't remember'' does not necessarily end the inquiry
into whether perjury occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
