<HEADLINE>
TREASURY PRICES FALL ON FEAR THAT INFLATION COULD PICK UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to correct day in lede to Tuesday)  (bl) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prices of Treasury securities fell Tuesday after a
smaller-than-expected trade deficit in June suggested that economic
growth was quickening. The news raised concern among some investors
that inflation could accelerate in the near term.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, market participants were focusing on the dollar, a
Treasury bill auction of new one-year bills and a separate report
on consumer prices.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year bond rose 6/32, to 99 7/32.
The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the
price, slipped to 5.55 percent from 5.54 percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Federal Reserve policy-makers left interest rates
unchanged at the end of their meeting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Federal Reserve adhered to an unchanged monetary policy in
light of the perceived counterbalance between a slackening economic
advance, benign inflation environment, budget surplus and continued
fragility in overseas financial markets on one hand,'' said Donald
Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management, ``and robust
consumer spending and torrid housing activity on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   The dollar fell against the yen as Japanese officials said they
were ready to take action to bolster the currency. A weak dollar
makes dollar-denominated investments like Treasury securities less
attractive to foreign investors. Stocks in the United States also
gained for the second consecutive day, and that also eased some of
the flight to quality into the debt market.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the Treasury market, traders said the sale of a new
one-year bill Tuesday went off without a hitch, with the average
rate at 5 percent, the lowest since 4.965 percent on Jan. 29.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
