<SLUG> BC-MA-LOTTERY-DISPUTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDOW TO KEEP $20M OF CONTESTED JACKPOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM F. DOHERTY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It's official: Variety store owner Nick Havan may not
have hit the $21 million Mass Millions lottery jackpot last
February, but he got a $1 million payoff just for his persistence.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Paraskeve Kantges, the 72-year-old Watertown widow who
picked the winning numbers, was formally declared the winner of the
jackpot after Havan, the owner of a store where she bought the
winning ticket, withdrew his claim to the prize.
</P>
<P>
   But it also was announced that Kantges has agreed to share part
of the jackpot with Havan, who insisted he bought the winning
ticket after Kantges changed her mind and canceled the bet.
</P>
<P>
   Havan's lawyer, Laurence Johnson, said Kantges and Havan have
agreed to ``apportion'' the winnings and keep the details secret.
</P>
<P>
   But a source familiar with the settlement said Havan will get $1
million before taxes, less than 5 percent of Kantges's total
jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relatively small amount to make him just go away,'' the
source said. ``She is elderly and she wants to enjoy her winnings
while she can. She did the prudent thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The settlement brings to an end a six-month controversy over who
was entitled to the winnings, a dispute which could have dragged on
for years in the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Treasurer Joseph Malone said Kantges will get her first check in
a matter of days. ``Any side agreement she may have (with Havan) is
up to her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The payment, about $704,000, will be the the first of 20 checks
issued to Kantges each year.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said he was ``delighted'' that Kanges was declared the
winner. ``Her story held together from day one, backed up by the
facts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Havan also appeared delighted Tuesday at his store, Coolidge
Provisions. He offered to buy a round of sodas for reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone want a drink?'' he asked gesturing toward the shelves.
``I can buy plenty of drinks now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Havan declined to say how much money he will get or what he
intends to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no comment,'' he said. ``I want to want to live like a
normal store owner and go on with my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Kantges, who will be 73 in October, could not be reached
Tuesday. Her lawyer, James Merberg, declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers in the case are expected to ask a Superior Court judge
to dissolve an injunction Kantges obtained in February, barring the
lottery from paying the winnings until the dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, reached Aug. 7, became public Tuesday after
retired Superior Court Judge Robert Steadman, who presided at the
Lottery Commission hearing last month, filed his recommendations
</P>
<P>
   Steadman told the commission it should reject the claim of a
third person, Sonya Bardakjian of Watertown, and award Kantges the
jackpot. The commission adopted his recommendations at a meeting
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges claimed she phoned in the winning Mass Millions bet to
Havan on Feb. 5, along with 95 other bets. But when she went to
pick up her tickets at Coolidge Provisions the next day, the
winning ticket was not among the pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like the legs had been cut out from under me,'' Kantges
testified at the July hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Havan claimed that Kantges had called back the night before the
drawing and canceled that bet, so he kept the ticket for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Kantges has records showing that she has played the winning
combination, 4-6-10-16-19-25, for years. She said the number
signifies her birth, at 4 a.m. on the sixth day of the week Oct.
16, 1925. She maintains she never canceled the winning bet.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime lottery player, Kantges has admitted she ran up a
$3,000 tab for lottery tickets at another Watertown store and quit
making payments after reducing her debt to $2,000. Watertown
officials also say she owes $10,000 in unpaid property taxes on her
condo.
</P>
<P>
   Bardakjian, the third claimant, gave the same story as Kantges.
She said she phoned in a bet on the winning number to Coolidge
Provisions along with 36 other bets Feb. 5, and that the next day
Havan gave her all the tickets except the winning one.
</P>
<P>
   But Steadman said a review of all Bardakjian's bets that day
established that she never played the winning number. She had
presented the lottery commission with 25 tickets and the corner of
a 26th ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Havan's license to sell lottery tickets was suspended when the
dispute erupted. Malone said that action might be reviewed ``down
the road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
