<HEADLINE>
U.S. PRESSING AFGHANISTAN TO EXPEL BOMBING SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AFRICA-BOMBING) 
(JT) 
 By PHILIP SHENON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya _ The United States is urging the Taliban militia
in Afghanistan to expel a Saudi-born multimillionaire from the
country in hopes that he can be captured as a suspect in the
bombing of American embassies in East Africa, senior Clinton
administration officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright came close to making the
request public when she described the views of the man, Osama bin
Laden, as ``inimical to those of the civilized world'' and called
on Afghanistan to ``stop harboring those considered terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has called bin Laden ``one of the most
significant financial sponsors of Islamic extremist activities in
the world.'' American officials say he has sponsored terrorist acts
and militant groups around the world, from Algeria to the
Philippines. And a suspect in the twin embassy bombings, on Aug. 7,
has reportedly identified him as the mastermind of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   He has threatened to strike American sites in and around the
Middle East and has applauded the bombings of American military
posts in Saudi Arabia in 1995 and 1996, which killed a total of 24
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Albright's comments came at the end of a whirlwind two-day trip
to Africa to tour the shattered embassies here and in Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania. The Kenyan police and FBI were continuing their
interrogation of the suspect who has reportedly linked bin Laden to
the embassy bombings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a war _ that's what it looks like,'' Albright said as she
wandered the charred rubble of the embassy complex in Nairobi,
drawing a comparison to her childhood during the Nazi blitz of
London, where her family had fled from Czechoslovakia. ``As
somebody who actually saw the bombs in London during the war,'' she
said, ``this is what it looks like.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing at a news conference here to say directly that
bin Laden was a suspect in the bombing investigation, Albright had
no hesitation in offering a blunt public condemnation of the
shadowy Saudi millionaire, who has bragged of offering financial
support to terrorists who target Americans abroad.
</P>
<P>
   And she seemed eager to suggest that the Taliban, the
fundamentalist Muslim militia that controls most of Afghanistan and
is eager for American diplomatic recognition as its rightful
government, has no hope for formal ties to the United States unless
it expels bin Laden, who is reported to live in the war-ruined
Afghan city of Kandahar.
</P>
<P>
   `` Bin Laden's activities are inimical to those of civilized
people in the world and in the United States,'' she said. ``And
whatever the connection to this, I have said previously that his
funding of terrorism is something that the world is quite aware
of.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that if the Taliban wanted diplomatic relations with
the United States and other nations, ``it should not be in the
position of harboring any of those who are considered terrorists.''
Asked at the news conference specifically whether she wanted to see
bin Laden expelled from Afghanistan, Albright replied, ``I'm not
going to go into further details.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials have said that during a meeting
in Afghanistan with senior Taliban leaders last April, Bill
Richardson, the U.S. delegate to the United Nations, suggested that
the United States would not consider diplomatic relations of any
sort with the Taliban unless bin Laden were forced out of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get bin Laden out of Afghanistan, our hopes of
bringing him to justice increase exponentially,'' a senior
administration official said Tuesday in Washington. Officials said
the United States would also require a dramatic improvement in the
human rights record of the Taliban, especially in its treatment of
women, if it wants diplomatic ties.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   American law enforcement officials have said that the suspect
who is now being held in Kenya, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, appears to
have been an important figure in the Nairobi bomb plot and has
knowledge of most of the details of the attack, which killed more
than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani officials have said that he acknowledged participation
in the bombing when he was arrested shortly after landing in
Karachi on a flight from Kenya only hours after the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials in the United States have not disputed
reports from Pakistan that Odeh voluntarily confessed there and
that he had called bin Laden his spiritual guide in an Islamic holy
war against the United States. A prominent Pakistani newspaper, The
News, has reported that Odeh is a 34-year-old Palestinian engineer
who is married to a Kenyan and who described bin Laden as his
``supreme commander.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright would not comment on the arrest of Odeh. But after
meeting with senior FBI officials who are overseeing the criminal
inquiry here, she said that ``the investigation is proceeding
fairly well'' and that American, Kenyan and Tanzanian law
enforcement officials were cooperating closely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together we pledge to bring to justice the murderers of our
loved ones, colleagues and friends,'' she said before laying a
wreath before the blackened hulk of the American Embassy in
Nairobi, a place she described Tuesday as ``a sorrowful and now
sacred location.''
</P>
<P>
   In her public appearances Tuesday, Albright struggled to end the
perception among many Kenyans and Tanzanians that American
officials were indifferent to the plight of all but the American
citizens who were injured in the bombings. The perception was
reinforced by news reports in Kenya that rescuers who had tried to
save people from the shattered embassy here minutes after the blast
were chased away by machine-gun-wielding marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's anger about what happened in the aftermath of
the bombing,'' Albright said. ``And I cannot say we acted
perfectly. But I believe the allegations of callousness are
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that the ``U.S. Marines limited access to the embassy
not out of indifference but because they were afraid that the
weakened building would collapse and trap new victims.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
