<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0106 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE-AR     08-18 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-MARKETPLACE-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: PORTFOLIO MANAGERS IN QUANDARY OVER RUSSIA CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also RUSSIA-ECON) 
(ART ADV: Graphic on Russia bond funds is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the second time in a year, mutual funds that
invest in emerging markets have been snared in a foreign financial
crisis. And once again, their managers are trying to value
securities for which there is little, or in some cases no, real
market.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Russian securities are at issue. So far, the Russian
government has provided almost no information to help portfolio
managers gauge how much their investments are worth.
</P>
<P>
   That has left some mutual fund managers to place widely
different values on their Russian securities, possibly skewing the
real impact of Russia's decision on Monday to allow its currency to
fall in value and to call a debt moratorium. The full report may be
yet to come for investors, who have been pulling money out of
emerging-market debt and equity funds in recent weeks, according to
AMG Data Services, which tracks mutual fund cash flows.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time in five years that investors in
emerging-market funds have been stunned by upheaval in what had
been a rapidly growing economy. In addition to a decline brought on
by a devaluation of certain currencies in Southeast Asia last year,
emerging-market funds plunged in late 1994 after Mexico devalued
the peso, leading to a tumble in most Latin American stock and bond
funds.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty is greatest now in portfolios that hold
short-term Russian government notes, known as GKOs. After the
Russian government decided on Monday to restructure the notes and
to allow the ruble to fall by as much as 34 percent in value, the
T. Rowe Price Emerging Markets Bond fund cut about 15 percent from
the market value of its Russian Treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
   That was only half the decline recorded by the Lexington Troika
Dialog Russia fund, which reduced the value of its GKO investments
by about one-third.
</P>
<P>
   Each fund could only estimate the value of these holdings at the
end of each day because the securities are not trading while the
Russian government irons out the details of a debt-restructuring
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty is not likely to clear up soon. On Tuesday,
Russia said it would delay a debt announcement, originally planned
for Wednesday, until Monday. It is expected to convert the
short-term holdings, which were due to be redeemed by the end of
next year, into long-term bonds that are redeemed over the next
four or five years, fund managers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with the restructuring is that we don't know what
we are going to get,'' said Michael Conelius, manager of the T.
Rowe Price fund. ``If we get ruble-denominated debt, that would be
negative,'' because fund managers would then be selling rubles to
hedge their currency risk, perhaps leading to a collapse in the
currency's value.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, the three-month GKOs are exchanged for five-year,
dollar-denominated Treasury bonds, Conelius said, ``the question
becomes how comfortable are we holding the longer-term bonds.''
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Bank AG, J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. have
been approached by the Russian government to provide advice as it
restructures its debt.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging markets traders and bankers said Tuesday that there had
been speculation that the Russian government would pay foreign
investors about eleven cents on the dollar for their GKOs, while
domestic investors would receive about 32 cents on the dollar. If
foreign investors wind up swallowing larger losses on the
securities than domestic investors, they will undoubtedly be
reluctant to reinvest in Russia anytime soon.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many emerging-market debt funds that have invested in Russia
hold long-term government bonds, which are denominated in dollars
rather than rubles. Unlike the GKOs, these bonds have continued to
trade over the last two days, and have fallen sharply in value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonds that were priced at 30 cents on the dollar on Friday
fell to 25 cents on Monday and about 21 cents today,'' Craig Monro,
manager of the AIM Global High Income fund, said Tuesday. In April,
when Russian investments accounted for about 18 percent of the AIM
fund's $354 million in assets, the bonds were valued at 64 cents on
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bonds have been trading, but certainly the liquidity is
nothing like it was a few weeks ago,'' Monro said. ``A lot of fund
managers are apparently being told to exit the market. This is a
classic end-of-a-meltdown phase we are going through.'' At least
for now, the AIM fund is holding onto its Russian bonds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging market funds that buy debt have suffered far more in
the Russian economic upheaval than funds that buy equities. Last
October, the Asian turmoil mainly dealt blows to investors in
emerging-market stock funds.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the biggest emerging-market debt funds declined in
value by 5.5 percent to 8 percent, according to Lipper Analytical
Services. Emerging-market equity funds declined by 0.5 percent to
3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The big exception was the Lexington Troika Dialog Russia fund,
primarily a stock fund, which reported a decline of a whopping 13.5
percent that day. The fund, which already had fallen 72 percent
from the beginning of the year through Friday, plunged because
about 10 percent of its $30 million in assets are in short-term
Russian government notes.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Kantor, a spokesman for Lexington Asset Management,
said Lexington devalued the notes by about one-third on Monday to
conform to the lower end of the new trading range for the ruble.
</P>
<P>
   The T. Rowe Price fund took a different approach. Conelius said
the fund priced its GKO securities on Monday to yield about 220
percent, up from 150 percent on Friday. That resulted, he said, in
a 15 percent decline in the market value of the notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was consistent with the market for dollar-paying external
debt,'' he said, where ``everything went down Tuesday by 10 to 20
percent. Fifteen percent seemed prudent and seemed right.''
</P>
<P>
   Fund managers should be better able to determine the long-term
value of their investments after details of the restructuring are
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement will also help banks gauge the value of their
portfolios. Even a complete writeoff would not be overly damaging
to the big U.S. commercial banks because they have limited Russian
exposure. BankAmerica Corp., for example, had about $668 million in
loans or investments in Russia at the end of June, an undisclosed
portion in GKOs. Chase Manhattan Corp. has less than $1 billion in
exposure to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, investors will remain skittish. According to
AMG Data Services, they withdrew an average of $4 million a week
over the past month from emerging-market debt funds. That was
before those funds lost an average of 8 percent of their value in
the week ended last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawals have been greater from emerging-market stock funds,
whose declines have been all the more striking as the U.S. stock
market has surged ahead. Over the past month, investors have taken
$90 million a week out of the stock funds, AMG said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
