<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLINTON-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SENATORIAL CANDIDATES SPAR ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES
with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS, NY-CLINTON-SENATE) 
(JT) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Rep. Charles Schumer turned up at a center for
the elderly in central Harlem Tuesday, he discovered more
television cameras crammed in one small room than he had seen
before during his entire campaign for Senate. The Brooklyn Democrat
read a brief statement attacking Republican policies on Medicare,
and then gestured to his audience of reporters and elderly New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, does anybody have any questions, any senior or any
of the press, on this subject?'' Schumer inquired. There was
silence. ``You didn't come here to hear my talk about Newt?''
</P>
<P>
   They did not. For the next two minutes, before the normally
camera-friendly lawmaker hustled his way out the door and to his
car, Schumer fielded questions not about Republicans and Medicare
but about about President Clinton and Monica Lewinsky and how that
issue might affect the Democratic race to unseat Sen. Alfonse M.
D'Amato, the New York Republican seeking a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president did was irresponsible and wrong,'' Schumer
said, in one variation of what he promised would be his ``one
statement'' on the matter. ``He apologized for it. He said he wants
to move on, and I agree with that, and start talking about issues
that are of great concern.''
</P>
<P>
   With obvious nervousness and uncertainty, the same Democratic
candidates for governor and the Senate from New York who had voiced
strong support for Clinton just two weeks ago moved to distance
themselves from the White House Tuesday. Faced with a politically
volatile situation in Washington just as their campaigns were
getting engaged in New York, the candidates expressed varying
degrees of disappointment with Clinton's behavior, and expressed
hopes that voters could move beyond the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed by his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,''
said Geraldine Ferraro, one of Schumer's rivals for the Democratic
nomination. ``And I was also disappointed by the fact that he
misled the public. But since he apologized, I think we should all
move on. Enough, already.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Green, the third contender for the Senate, described
Clinton, whom he has repeatedly called ``a friend,'' as an ``almost
always disciplined leader who made an obviously foolish personal
mistake, for which he and, in a sense, the country is now paying a
price.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
