A0108 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-AFTERMATH-BOS     08-18 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AFTERMATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIGNATION VOICED AS CLINTON CONFESSION ASSESSED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Clinton-Marriage; 1200 words)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats and Republicans alike rained shame on
President Clinton Tuesday for his belated confession of sexual
misconduct and his defiant tone, as senior White House officials
tried to regroup in the face of what some privately said was a
betrayal by the president they had blindly defended.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr's
investigation steamed ahead, despite Clinton's pointed pleas for
closure. Former White House intern Monica W. Lewinsky has been
summoned back before the grand jury Thursday, according to an
associate familiar with the process. And former Clinton consultant
Dick Morris appeared before the panel Tuesday to discuss telephone
conversations with the president dating back to January.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, after spending all of Monday in his residence, arrived
in the Oval Office Tuesday morning for a lengthy briefing with his
senior policy advisers on issues ranging from Northern Ireland to
the Russian economy to East Africa. He met privately with some
political aides in an attempt to soothe feelings, and made about a
dozen calls to key senators and House members who were spread
across the country and the world on their summer holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the afternoon, Clinton, accompanied by his wife Hillary
and daughter Chelsea, boarded Marine One on their way to their
belated Martha's Vineyard vacation. Twice _ at the doorway of the
helicopter and again on the steps of Air Force One _ Clinton's hand
grazed his wife's back, but the two seemed barely to acknowledge
one another.
</P>
<P>
   In the White House, on Capitol Hill and around the nation,
opinions were mixed and slow to form on the ultimate impact of
Clinton's extraordinary five-minute address from the Map Room
Monday night, during which he admitted an inappropriate
relationship with Lewinsky, struck back at Starr and pleaded for
his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   In one public opinion poll, sponsored by CNN and USA Today,
Clinton's favorability rating plummeted 20 percentage points after
the speech, to 40 percent. In an ABC News poll, 52 percent of the
respondents said they did not believe Clinton when he said he did
not obstruct justice in the Paula Jones sexual harassment suit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the ABC poll, 59 percent of those interviewed said
Clinton had said enough about the situation, and another 53 percent
in the CNN/USA Today poll said they were satisfied with Clinton's
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a reaction, it will be a slow burn,'' said Richard
Neustadt, a presidential scholar at Harvard University. ``We're not
going to know tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In one focus group conducted by Democratic pollster Peter Hart
during the speech, respondents registered strong approval when
Clinton accepted responsibility for his actions and sounded a note
of contrition. But when Clinton talked about Starr, the focus group
members registered disapproval.
</P>
<P>
   ``They already have an opinion of Ken Starr,'' Hart said
Tuesday. ``Those things that didn't relate to the president
himself, his family and his relationship with the public, they
thought that was outside the bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior advisers inside and outside the White House, as well as
Democratic allies, expressed frustration with Clinton's tone in the
speech. Several said they had tried to mute his defiance, but were
overruled by Clinton and his wife in a climactic meeting Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the speech, Clinton railed against the length and scope of
the investigation, saying, ``This has gone on too long, cost too
much and hurt too many innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was he right about the independent counsel? I think so,'' said
Mark Mellman, a Democratic consultant with ties to the White House.
``I don't know if anyone thinks the country was better off with
what Starr does. Tactically, was it smart? I'm not sure, but it was
heartfelt.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Representative Barney Frank, a Massachusetts Democrat:
``The criticism of Starr was intellectually legitimate, though not
tactically wise.''
</P>
<P>
   A few Republicans, led by former Vice President Dan Quayle;
Senator John Ashcroft of Missouri, a presidential aspirant; and
Senator Bob Smith of New Hampshire, called on Clinton to resign
Tuesday. Representative Tom DeLay of Texas, the House majority
whip, became the most senior lawmaker to call for the president's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, House Speaker Newt Gingrich staked out a more
moderate position. ``It's premature for anyone to make any
judgment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Democratic opinion that White House officials likely
found the most disturbing. Throughout the seven-month probe, House
Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Illinois and Senate
Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch said Congress could not
seek impeachment without Democratic support, and some of that
support seemed to waver Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was present in the Roosevelt Room in January when the
president denied any sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky,''
Democratic Senator Dianne Feinstein of California said in a written
statement. ``I believed him. His remarks last evening leave me with
a deep sense of sadness in that my trust in his crediblity has been
badly shattered. My heart and thoughts go out to the First Lady and
Chelsea.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt said he was ``very
disappointed in his personal conduct.'' And Democratic
Representative Paul McHale of Pennsylvania said Clinton ``should
resign or face impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   In the White House, some advisers were still taking stock of the
situation. Asked if he had come to terms with Clinton's reversal,
press secretary Michael McCurry replied: ``No. I'll think about it
over the next couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   White House communications director Ann Lewis, one of Clinton's
most vocal defenders since January, abruptly said, ``I'm not
getting into it,'' when asked whether she felt betrayed by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Others, though, were more conciliatory. Deputy chief of staff
John Podesta said he privately told Clinton that he would continue
his admiration and respect for the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough deal,'' said Podesta. ``I felt badly for him. He
had a tough job to do and he did it. He talked to the American
people and we'll move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
