</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-VINEYARD-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEPARTS FOR VACATION ON MARTHA'S VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY, CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL,
CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS,
CLINTON-CABINET, NY-CLINTON-SENATE, CLINTON-GORE) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Seeking solitude and a respite from the most
wrenching experience of his political life, President Clinton
departed Washington on Tuesday for a twelve-day vacation on the
resort island of Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who Monday evening made a combative admission of an
illicit relationship with a former White House intern, Monica
Lewinsky, strode from the White House in mid-afternoon clutching
the hand of his 18-year-old daughter, Chelsea. Chelsea, in turn,
was holding hands with her mother, First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton. Their Labrador, Buddy, bounded up the stairs of the
presidential helicopter before them.
</P>
<P>
   The televised tableau of family togetherness was designed to
convey a sense of an embattled family rallying together in one of
the most difficult hours of a political career and a marriage that
have survived repeated crises brought on by Clinton's infidelity
and his parsimony with the truth. But never before Monday's painful
confessional has the president's behavior been laid so bare before
his family _ and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a family that has some healing to do,'' said Mike
McCurry, the White House press secretary who accompanied the
Clintons on Air Force One to Martha's Vineyard. He said the
president's first priority on his vacation is to find the privacy
he needs ``so he can do some repair work within the family.'' After
that, McCurry said, the president will begin a series of public
appearances designed to regain some momentum for his stalled agenda
and to try to rebuild the trust of the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, a spokeswoman for Mrs. Clinton, said that the
first lady is ``committed to her marriage and she loves her husband
and daughter very much.'' Ms. Berry said Mrs. Clinton's love for
her husband is ``compassionate and steadfast'' but that she is
uncomfortable with the public airing of the family's soiled linen.
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not release any details of the first
family's plans during their stay on Martha's Vineyard. Aides are
preparing a small, private celebration of Clinton's 52nd birthday
on Friday. They indicated that it would not be a lavish,
celebrity-drenched affair like those marking earlier presidential
birthdays, but they would not reveal more.
</P>
<P>
   Among those greeting Clinton at the Edgartown airport was Vernon
Jordan, the Washington lawyer and presidential confidant, who
enveloped Mrs. Clinton in an enormous bear hug when she stepped off
Air Force One. Clinton waited silently and alone a few paces away
as Mrs. Clinton and Jordan spoke, apparently unwilling to wade into
the crowd without his wife by his side.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was one of the first witnesses called before a federal
grand jury investigating the relationship between Clinton and Ms.
Lewinsky. Jordan helped secure a job for Ms. Lewinsky at Revlon,
where he is a director, at a time when she was under subpoena to
testify in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit against the
president. Jordan has said that his efforts on Ms. Lewinsky's
behalf were a personal favor and not an attempt to influence her
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Carly Simon also appeared to greet the Clintons. Hundreds
of other supporters turned out to welcome the first family at the
Edgartown airport in a small-scale demonstration of support that
the Clintons obviously relished.
</P>
<P>
   The three Clintons _ with Chelsea in the lead _ shook hands with
members of the crowd for about 35 minutes before getting into their
car and heading to the borrowed home where they are staying here,
an Oyster Pond waterfront compound owned by Richard Friedman, a
Boston property developer. Their visit here was their fourth since
Clinton assumed the presidency in 1993. The president and Mrs.
Clinton worked the crowd together without speaking to one another
or touching.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent part of the day before leaving Washington taking
calls from Democratic members of Congress, who urged the president
to try to put the Lewinsky matter behind him, aides said. The tone
of the talks, according to a White House official, was similar to
that of the president's Monday address _ regretful but determined
to continue to challenge the legitimacy of the investigation of the
Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the President also spoke privately with several
members of the White House staff who have ardently defended him
against the charges of public and private wrongdoing that have
seized the presidency since January. Those aides were subdued on
Tuesday, stunned by the president's admission but hardly surprised
that what many in Washington suspected turned out to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's some sense of relief'' that the waiting for Clinton to
speak on the affair had ended, McCurry said. ``People just want to
get on with why they came here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   McCurry has already announced his departure from the White House
in October. Joe Lockhart, the deputy press secretary and McCurry's
designated successor, parroted the official line. ``People are
generally relieved that we got through the day yesterday and
they're glad it's over,'' Lockhart said. ``People are satisfied
with the speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Rahm Emanuel, one of the president's most aggressive defenders,
said that opinion varied among White House staff members about the
president's statement, but said that he is content with the
explanation of his actions that Clinton gave.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling about the person is the same as the feeling was
before,'' Emanuel said, his tone lacking the usual combative edge.
``I was raised that you don't walk on a man when he's down. He
acknowledged that he misled his wife. I don't need more than that.
Do you? He doesn't have to say he's sorry for misleading me.''
Emanuel also is planning to leave the White House this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how political Washington and the American public
receive Clinton's grudging confession of personal sin, those who
turned out to welcome them to their island escape were supportive
and sympathetic. Ann Sherman, a Martha's Vineyard resident and
retired pediatric nurse, said she had never gone to the airport to
welcome Clinton but came this time to show her support.
</P>
<P>
   ''People feel a little sorry for him and his family and they
want to let him have a vacation here,'' she said. ``He looked very
terrible last night. He's been wrung through the ringer.'' Ms.
Sherman added, ``He has to set an example but we are human. He made
a very very bad mistake, but he's got to get back to running this
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Feingold, a summer resident and a managed health-care
consultant from Boston, said she was ``embarrassed'' for the
president but wanted to show solidarity. ''One wants to show a
sense of respect for Hillary and Chelsea and take one's cue from
them,'' Ms. Feingold said. ``I can't expect it's going to be a
celebratory time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
