<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Special News for Kids Report: President Clinton and the Monica
mess
 &HT;    By Julie Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ All year long, you've seen headlines wondering whether
President Clinton had done something bad.
</P>
<P>
   What's all the fuss?
</P>
<P>
   In short, Clinton got himself in a mess of trouble. Personal
trouble. And for many months, he said, he misled everyone,
including his best friends and, it seems, his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble: Clinton had a relationship with a young woman who
worked in the White House. They weren't just friends. They had the
sort of relationship that husbands and wives have. It was a
romantic relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The woman is named Monica Lewinsky. She's been on the covers of
magazines because of her friendship with the president. Lewinsky is
25 now, but was 21 and fresh out of college when she became
romantic with Clinton, who is now 52.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, when Clinton had to testify in a court case, he
reportedly said under oath that he did not have that sort of
relationship with Lewinsky. Ten days later, after his friendship
with Lewinsky became known, Clinton told some reporters: ``I did
not have ... relations with that woman, Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday night, seven months after he denied the
relationship with Lewinsky, Clinton changed his story.
</P>
<P>
   Looking very serious from his seat in the White House, he
addressed the nation. In a speech just more than four minutes long,
the president said: ``Indeed, I did have a relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky that was not appropriate. In fact, it was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that he ``misled people'' to protect himself from
embarrassment and also to protect his family.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, the president waited until last weekend to
tell his wife, Hillary, and daughter, Chelsea, the truth. Now the
family is on vacation on Martha's Vineyard, Mass., an island.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the story go from here? That's a question on many
minds right now.
</P>
<P>
   Some people think a president should be a model citizen _ the
best our country has to offer and a hero young people can look up
to. Before Lewinsky came along, some people think Clinton lied
about a romantic involvement with another woman. Some think that
Clinton should not be president.
</P>
<P>
   Others think that if he has lied about his personal life, that
isn't important. They say our nation should focus on more important
things, such as dealing with terrorist bombings in Africa and
nuclear weapons in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons will take their vacation, and reporters will
continue to cover this story. Still to be determined: Will the
nation forgive Clinton? Did he tell a lie in the court case in
January?
</P>
<P>
   Telling the truth
</P>
<P>
   Many parents and teachers have had a hard time trying to explain
this ``Monica mess'' to kids. It's because the whole story involves
adult situations. Think of it this way: If this story were a movie,
it would be rated ``R.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is one lesson in the Clinton-Lewinsky episode that
does seem to be coming through loud and clear: the importance of
telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Have you ever lied about something you did or didn't do at home
or at school? Have your parents or teachers urged you to tell the
truth? Have you ever found out that you get in less trouble when
you tell the truth right away instead of waiting until you are
caught telling a lie?
</P>
<P>
   After watching President Clinton's speech Monday night, Eric
Dobbs, 34, of DeKalb County talked about the matter with his
9-year-old son, Eric II. He wanted his son to see that it was
Clinton's decision to mislead people that landed him in so much
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him the thing we can learn from this is: Honesty is
always the best policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Glossary
</P>
<P>
   Here are some names and terms you might have heard in stories
about the president and Monica Lewinsky:
</P>
<P>
   _ Kenneth Starr: the man who is investigating President
Clinton's relationship with Lewinsky and other matters. He is
sometimes called a ``special prosecutor'' or an ``independent
counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Perjury: a crime. When someone who has sworn to tell the truth
tells a lie. Some people think President Clinton committed perjury
in describing his friendship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   _ Impeachment: part of a process of removing someone from
office. Some people say Clinton should be impeached if he committed
perjury. For a president to be removed, he must be impeached by the
U.S. House of Representatives and convicted by the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _ Grand jury: a group of people who decide whether a person
should be tried for a crime. Before his speech to the nation on
Monday, President Clinton answered questions in front of a grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
