<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' No. 4 QB faces long odds
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John Dutton finds himself on the fringe these days,
which is not the best place to be if you're a football player.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons rookie quarterback already has been cut once, and
the Falcons picked him up so late in training camp it would be an
upset if he made the team.
</P>
<P>
   But Dutton, 22, is used to this.
</P>
<P>
   He was a highly touted recruit at Texas in 1993, but ended up
redshirting and then transferring to Nevada-Reno after not playing
in '94.
</P>
<P>
   He put up big numbers in two years there, completing 444 of 701
passes (63.3 percent) for 6,276 yards, 42 touchdowns and just 12
interceptions. But that was in the Big West conference, and scouts
weren't convinced that the 6-foot-4, 222-pounder was as good as his
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   So he lasted until the sixth round, where the Dolphins took him.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's battling uphill on a team that already has starter
Chris Chandler and backups Tony Graziani and Steve DeBerg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need time to develop, and I know that,'' said Dutton,
who was waived last Tuesday by Miami, and claimed Wednesday by
Atlanta. ``I just need to stick somewhere and learn.''
</P>
<P>
   It figures to be tough for him to stick in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He's only thrown in very basic drills, won't play Saturday at
Pittsburgh, and probably won't play next week against Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   It might be hard to get him on the practice squad because he
first must become a free agent, and other teams could outbid
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Reeves is big on his quarterbacks being familiar with
every detail of his offense. That won't happen fast. The prospect
of keeping four quarterbacks is limited because it would leave
another position short.
</P>
<P>
   Dutton knows the odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just going out every day, and ... trying to show that I
can make the throws at this level,'' he said. ``I've got a lot to
prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, next week I can get in there and throw with the
offense, and go from there. This is totally different from Miami.
(The offense is) much more complex, and the terminology is
different. If I do get waived, there will be 28 other teams, and
the World League.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
