<SLUG> BC-GYM-GYMNASTICS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Zmeskal returns to gymnastics forefront at Championships
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The squeak has left her voice, but the creak
hasn't set into her bones as Kim Zmeskal returns to the city of her
greatest triumph for another whirl at gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   At age 22, once considered geriatric for a woman in her sport,
she'll compete in the U.S. Gymnastics Championships alongside girls
who once dreamed of becoming the next Kim Zmeskal. The event, which
ends Saturday, will be held at Market Square Arena, near the
Hoosier Dome where in 1991 the Houston teen became the first
American to win a World Championships all-around title.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1998, Zmeskal's last amateur competition was the
Barcelona Olympics. She had been favored to win individual medals,
but made errors that stunned her as much as it did her fans, and
came home only with a team bronze.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is just that I really enjoy doing it still,''
said Zmeskal, who last year was on the pro tour and coaching
athletes she'll be up against here. ''There's just been a piece of
me that's been missing since I stepped away from competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Without prompting, Zmeskal addressed the obvious question: ''A
lot of people ask me if the reason I'm doing this is because I
didn't do what I had wanted to do in Barcelona... It really doesn't
have anything to do with that. I've been really fortunate that God
has blessed me with a body that's still intact and still able to
take the pounding that gymnastics requires, so I'm going to go for
it while I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Her coach, Mary Lee Tracy at Cincinnati Gymnastics, believes
that Zmeskal, who took third at a qualifying competition, ''has an
opportunity, if she hits (her routines) both days, to finish in the
Top 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Zmeskal's at a disadvantage because the start values of her
routines are not as high as those of her limber new rivals, and
said Tracy, an Olympic coach, ''the margin for error gets
reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of a new code of points in gymnastics, ''If I was doing
the same routines as Barcelona, they would be worth nearly
nothing,'' Zmeskal said.
</P>
<P>
   The athlete whom Bela Karolyi called the toughest competitor he
ever coached had to sharpen her skills with a new body.
</P>
<P>
   Zmeskal grew only from 4-foot-7 1/4 to 4-9 1/2, but her body
gained a woman's curves.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not the little pixie 16-year-old that I was, but I feel
very in shape now,'' said Zmeskal, who, despite precautions on the
hard mat to protect her body, still sprained an ankle and tore a
miniscus recently. ''I've always been a strong, quick athlete, and
through the years I haven't really lost that.''
</P>
<P>
   Zmeskal tried a comeback in 1994, but soon tore the anterior
cruciate ligament in her right knee on a vault. She was an athletes
representative at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics, staying with the
gold-medal winning U.S. team at their Emory house.
</P>
<P>
   ''As much as you get excited for everybody to do well, there's a
part that tears at you, 'Gosh, I wish I could have been out
there,''' Zmeskal said.
</P>
<P>
   Olympians Shannon Miller, who shot to glory in Barcelona when
Zmeskal faltered, and Amanda Borden are among Zmeskal's closest
friends. In fact, she was so sad about leaving the pro tour, where
Borden had helped make gymnastics fun again, that her boyfriend
suggested she join Borden in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've never been as happy doing gymnastics as I am now,''
Zmeskal said. ''I was anxious, worried about how the reception
would be now that I'm older than the girls. It seems everybody is
cheering me on.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is I don't want people to only see me as the
athlete that I was when I was younger.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Gymnastics Championships
</P>
<P>
   When: Today through Saturday
</P>
<P>
   Where: Indianapolis
</P>
<P>
   Who: 140 athletes, including Dominique Moceanu, Dominique Dawes,
Kim Zmeskal, Vanessa Atler, Blaine Wilson and Jay Thornton of
Augusta competing for spots on national teams.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
