<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEDEPOT-EARNINGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2nd quarter earnings up at Home Depot 30%
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot reported better-than-expected earnings with
a 30 percent increase in profit for the second quarter, braced by
strong home sales and demand for kitchen, bath and flooring
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street responded by boosting the stock $2 to $44.81 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Home Depot, the world's largest do-it-yourself
home improvement retailer, said second-quarter net income was $467
million, or 31 cents a share, up from $358 million, or 24 cents, a
year ago. The results beat analysts' estimates by a penny.
</P>
<P>
   Sales increased 24 percent to $8.14 billion, up from $6.55
billion one year ago, and sales at stores open at least one year
increased 7 percent. Home Depot's pretax margin was 9.45 percent,
the company's highest second-quarter pretax margin in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   For the first half of the fiscal year, Home Depot earned $804
million, or 53 cents a share, against $617 million, or 41 cents a
share. Sales totaled $15.26 billion in the first six months against
$12.21 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse, No. 2 in the home improvement
retailing business, also reported second-quarter earnings that
exceeded estimates. Lowe's announced Monday its earnings rose 31
percent to 47 cents a share, a penny over estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The housing supply retailers are cashing in on low interest
rates and vigorous home sales that are feeding demand from a
variety of customers, including do-it-yourselfers, contractors and
interior decorators.
</P>
<P>
   While its core supply products still propel earnings, Home Depot
is broadening its business with services.
</P>
<P>
   As a natural offshoot of its core supply business, Home Depot is
beefing up installation services, including a test dubbed ``At Home
Services,'' in which the company contracts with vendors that
specialize in roofing, vinyl siding and windows. Roofing is
currently offered through 125 Home Depots, including all metro
Atlanta stores. Home Depot is pushing the message by having
employees answer phone calls at some metro stores with a greeting
that says, ``We install.''
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl siding installations are being tested in 70 stores in the
Carolinas and Boston. Lowe's is also ramping up plans for
installation services.
</P>
<P>
   Installation, though, is a risky market that presents challenges
in customer satisfaction, something that Home Depot has built its
reputation on. ``It's not an easy business by any means,'' said
analyst Wayne Hood of Prudential Securities. ``Your installation
business is driven by how strong your installers are. It can create
all kinds of customer service problems, and there's potential to
lose money on call-backs,'' Hood said. Plus, it's difficult to
achieve consistency on a national basis in a highly fragmented
business dominated by independent contractors, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Other project-oriented work is being fueled through Home Depot's
Expo Design Centers, a long-term growth plan that picked up steam
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced sites Tuesday for six new Expos, including
one in Marietta, that are scheduled to open next year. The street
location of the planned Marietta store was not disclosed. The city
of Alpharetta recently denied a zoning permit for an
87,900-square-foot Expo behind a 107,500-square-foot Home Depot.
Company spokesman Jerry Shields said the Marietta store does not
replace plans for Alpharetta.
</P>
<P>
   Other newly announced openings for next year include Houston,
Smithtown, N.Y., and Fairfax, Va., as well as two Los Angeles area
stores in Monrovia and Huntington Beach. The two California Expos
will be reformatted Home Depot stores. Expos will open in Boynton
Beach, Fla. and Plano, Texas, this year.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot has 16 percent of the $140 billion do-it-yourself
market in the United States. Experts expect it to ultimately have
half of the market as it continues to grab market share.
Head-to-head combat with Lowe's is proving to be good for both
companies so far, as well as consumers who are benefiting from
competitive pricing.
</P>
<P>
   PaineWebber analyst Aram Rubinson counts cars in the parking lot
each month at spots in metro Atlanta where a Lowe's has moved in on
Home Depot turf. Instead of putting a crimp on business, customers
flock to both retailers because it creates a destination, he said.
In some cases, his research shows Home Depot is busier than before
Lowe's came.
</P>
<P>
   ``It proves that these two can peacefully coexist across the
street from each other, but they end up beating up the little
guys,'' Rubinson said.
</P>
<P>
   In metro Atlanta, Lowe's has recently set up shop near Home
Depots in Lilburn and Woodstock and has plans to open a store next
spring near the Austell Home Depot by Cobb Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot will open its first store outside North America next
week in Santiago, Chile, with a second store opening in November.
Next month the first Home Depot in Puerto Rico will open in San
Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
