u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS &LR;      08-18 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT TOO EARLY TO TALK PEDRO AND CY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At the request of Pedro Martinez, there will be only a
quiet mention of him becoming a 20-game winner. Why jinx him when
he probably has seven or eight starts left this season?
</P>
<P>
   But there is still nothing wrong with an old-fashioned campaign
on his behalf for the Cy Young Award. In Tuesday's matinee,
Martinez picked up his 16th victory, 4-1, and looked as sharp as he
has all year. Sure, he's still two wins behind David Cone, who
leads the majors with 18. But Cone and the Yankees will be coasting
to the American League East title in September while Martinez and
the Red Sox battle to retain their wild-card lead.
</P>
<P>
   Why am I backing Martinez? Well, chiefly because Martinez is
ahead of Cone in every one of those computer-generated numbers that
keep fantasy hackers awake at night: walk/strikeout ratio, hits per
inning, runners per nine innings, strikeouts per nine innings,
batting average vs. righthanders and lefthanders, and hits allowed
with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Trust me. You won't see them on ESPN or the 11 o'clock news, but
these are numbers that count.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe them, then believe what the eyes of 33,201
at Fenway Park saw Tuesday. Martinez, improving to 16-4, worked 8
2/3 innings, giving up five hits, one run, and one walk. He struck
out 10 Rangers _ the seventh time this season he has reached double
figures. Martinez leads the AL with a 2.82 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, Martinez won last year's National League Cy Young
Award with a 17-8 record for a Montreal club that went nowhere.
This year he appears to be on his way to the playoffs for the first
time. Each victory down the stretch is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people have faith in you,'' said Martinez, ``and that's
where the challenge comes from. This is the closest you get to a
playoff game. That's what it is all about. I wasn't afraid of
anything today.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who champion Cone correctly mention his determination and
his return to excellence against all odds. But right now I like
Pedro.
</P>
<P>
   And here's why.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve days ago, Martinez suffered a 4-3 loss to Texas, a game
in which he struck out 13 but was taken out by manager Jimy
Williams after 6 2/3 innings. He left in a huff but he got over it.
Six days later, he wilted in a game in which the Sox gave him six
runs and was removed again. Boston eventually won, 8-7, but all
Martinez got was a no-decision. He got over that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro hadn't come out to work on the sidelines in a long while
before those two starts,'' said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``But
he saw things in his tape and said he wanted to come out and make
adjustments. I'm very glad that he did. That's why he's good. He
had the best curveball he's had all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers must have thought they got the wrong scouting
report. Martinez got six of his 10 strikeouts with curves. If you
have to watch out for his curveball, you're in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in control of his delivery,'' said Williams. ``He
wasn't rushed and he was really consistent with most pitches. If he
happened to rush once in a while and his tempo slowed down the next
pitch, he made that correction on his own. It was a tribute to him
and his understanding going out there.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did Williams remove him with two on and two out in the
ninth, after 127 pitches, and bring in Tom Gordon?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he'd done his job and we had a guy out there who has
been extremely effective all year long,'' said Williams. ``We like
to give Gordon a lot more breathing room than what we gave him. But
I also wanted to give Pedro a shot to finish the game, and once
they got two men on, it kind of made up your mind for you. It was a
shame because he pitched a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez feels no remorse about leaving games. Maybe he never
did. He understands that he's going to have to do it again in five
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was off on my mechanics,'' he said, ``and Joe and I went
back on the side for a couple of days. We corrected everything.
Dick Pole helped me a little bit. So did Bret Saberhagan. It all
came back all right. I was flying out and getting a little bit too
spread with my front leg. I had better command and more strength.
</P>
<P>
   That's how you win a Cy Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't mention it too loud,'' said Martinez. ``You're going to
jinx me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
