<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0126 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-525&AMP;AD     08-18 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-BOMBING-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 NEW SUSPECTS ARRESTED IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also AFRICA-ALBRIGHT) 
(mk) 
 By RAYMOND BONNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistani authorities have arrested two
additional suspects in the bombings of the American Embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania, senior Pakistani officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The men were arrested Monday as they were trying to cross into
Afghanistan at Torkham, in the Khyber Pass, said the officials, who
insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   One suspect was a pivotal participant, an official said, adding
that the description was based on a statement by the previous
suspect arrested in the case, Mohammed Saddiq Odeh. Odeh, who was
seized Aug. 7 as he tried to enter Pakistan from Kenya with a fake
passport, named the two as accomplices when he was interrogated
last week, the official added.
</P>
<P>
   Odeh is a devotee of the Islamic fundamentalist Osama bin Laden,
a leading suspect in the embassy bombings who has vowed a holy war
against the United States. On Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright's trip to Africa to tour the shattered embassies in Kenya
and Tanzania, senior officials said Tuesday that the United States
was urging the fundamentalist government of Afghanistan to expel
bin Laden, so that the United States could try to capture him.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at the American Embassy said that the Pakistani
government had not notified the embassy of the latest arrests.
Pakistani authorities declined to say whether they would make the
suspects available to the Americans. The government sent Odeh to
Kenya without making him available for questioning by the
Americans. But the Kenyans let the FBI interview him.
</P>
<P>
   A Pakistani official said Tuesday that Odeh had acquired a valid
visa from the Pakistani Embassy in Kenya. Pakistani officials are
investigating how Odeh, who had a fake Yemeni passport, obtained
the visa, an official said.
</P>
<P>
   When he first came to the Americans' attention, Odeh was said to
have had a slightly different rendering of his name, Mohammed Sadik
Howaida.
</P>
<P>
   The two other suspects also had fake Yemeni passports, Pakistani
authorities said Tuesday, but they had slipped past immigration
police in Karachi.
</P>
<P>
   One is a Saudi and the other a Sudanese, authorities said.
Officials would not release the suspects' names. But one official
described them as 25 to 35 and generally fitting the same profile
as Odeh, a devotee of bin Laden. American officials say they
believe that bin Laden has extensive wealth and an international
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The men are being interrogated by Pakistani intelligence, a
Pakistani official said. One aspect they want to know is what role,
if any, bin Laden had in the blasts.
</P>
<P>
   In a week of interrogation, Odeh reportedly told Pakistani
police that he had taken part in the operation and that bin Laden
had directed it. But since being sent back to Kenya on Friday, Odeh
has not made similar confessions to FBI interrogators.
</P>
<P>
   The new suspects entered the country on Aug. 7, the day of the
simultaneous bombings, which killed more than 250 people and
wounded 5,000. They were on the same flight from Kenya with Odeh,
an official said. Odeh was arrested when the immigration
authorities noted that the photograph in his Yemeni passport was
not of him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the investigation intensified, fears of further retaliation
against American officials resulted in more than 200 Americans'
leaving Pakistan Tuesday. The State Department ordered them on
Sunday to leave. Families waited at the airport for six hours
before the plane took off, carrying them and a score of their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a day that, of course, is sad for us,'' the American
ambassador, Thomas Simons Jr., said at the airport Tuesday morning.
``There will be a disruption of family life.''
</P>
<P>
   Simons is remaining, along with a scaled-down staff.
</P>
<P>
   But for other reasons the departures are not sad, said Simons, a
career foreign service officer whose father was a diplomat in
Karachi about 50 years ago. ``For those of us who are leaving,'' he
said, ``we are coming back, because the Americans always come back,
and we like Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   Interior Minister Shujat Hussain said he did not understand why
the Americans were leaving. ``We asked them,'' he said, ```Why are
you so panicky?'''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Americans are going home. In addition to ordering
diplomatic dependents to leave, the State Department strongly urged
all Americans to do so. But only a handful were on the official
plane Tuesday. The embassy said 6,700 Americans were in Pakistan.
</P>
</TEXT>
