<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0127 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZ     08-18 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, BABY! TIME REALLY DOES FLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Time changed on me again recently.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not time itself. Presumably, a second still lasts
only a second, a minute a minute and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   It just doesn't seem like it anymore.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, this happens to everyone. It depends on the
circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   An hour spent making yourself run in the middle of a scorching
Arizona day, for instance, certainly seems to last longer than the
hour it takes to watch ``E.R.'' even if a stopwatch tells you they
both last 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That's not what I mean. I'm talking about long-term, seemingly
permanent changes in time.
</P>
<P>
   Supposedly if you listen to old folks talk about it, time passes
much more quickly as you age. And there is probably some truth to
that.
</P>
<P>
   Think about how you consider an hour. When you were squirming in
your desk in the third grade listening to your teacher drone on
about long division, and you looked up and saw that you still had
an hour to go until the bell rang, it seemed like forever. You
cannot convince me that the second hand on the clock didn't move
backward part of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to your adult life. You have one hour to complete
the report your boss just assigned you. Every time you glance at
your watch, another 15 minutes has passed. No one can convince you
that the digital second counter isn't speeding up on you. &QL; 
 &QL; 
On the run &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But nothing has thrown my internal clock out of whack like the
birth of my daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Now time really flies.
</P>
<P>
   Like everything else about fatherhood, people can try to tell
you about it all they want, but until you're actually in the
full-time diaper-changing business, you're not going to believe
them.
</P>
<P>
   (Speaking of things you won't believe until they happen, about
those diapers . . . nah. That's another column. Or not.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the things that struck me about the many books I read
while my wife was pregnant was the way the authors considered time:
Don't worry about the horrible, crusty, flaking rash that has
spread across your child's forehead, they say _ it'll pass in four
to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever I read this, my reaction was: four to six weeks? weeks?
How do these people tell time? With a sundial?
</P>
<P>
   I'd calm down, figure things couldn't be as bad as they seemed,
and continue.
</P>
<P>
   And the authors would write blithely on, assuring the
prospective parent that a third eye growing out of the back of the
head usually closes of its own volition after the first year or
some such. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Race with clock &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other parents treated time the same way. They talked about weeks
as if they were days, days as if they were minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I remember little Barney liked to strike matches and
throw them at the cat, but that only lasted a couple of months. We
were never worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they were right. Suddenly, a week is a laughably
short amount of time. A day? Over before it starts.
</P>
<P>
   And I think I know why. Turns out _ and this is another one of
those things experienced parents warn amateurs about _ a baby keeps
you so busy all the time that you don't even notice the passage of
an hour or two. The hours turn into days, the days into weeks, and
there you have it.
</P>
<P>
   As eternal vigilance is the price of freedom, constant attention
is the cost of parenthood. Even when you're not coaxing a burp or
warming a bottle, even when you're trying to doze off for the
night, you're thinking of your baby, listening for telltale sighs
and coos and what they might mean. At work, you're busy wondering
if she's OK, and you can't wait to see her again.
</P>
<P>
   And it's well worth it. It's ironic _ the time that's passing so
fast is the best time you've ever had.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after my daughter was born, a friend in North Carolina
e-mailed me, asking if she could do any new tricks. Sure, I told
him, she can hold her head up a little and she's more alert.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing you know, he said, she'll have her driver's
license and want to borrow the car and be moving out.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure he's right. But I won't try to guess how long it will
seem till then. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
