<HEADER>
A0130 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-FUNERAL-810&AMP;     08-18 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-FUNERAL-810&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FIRST VICTIMS ARE BURIED, IRA SPLINTER GROUP ADMITS BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Spelling of Lliam in second-to-last graf cq.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGHER, Northern Ireland _ A pregnant mother and her baby
daughter, victims of the terrorist bombing on Saturday, were buried
Tuesday. Just hours later, a Catholic splinter group took
responsibility for the bomb, which killed 28 people and wounded 220
in the town of Omagh.
</P>
<P>
   The group, calling itself the Real IRA, said it had not intended
to kill people, but only to destroy property in the shopping
district of the town, 60 miles west of Belfast. The bombing was the
worst in 29 years of sectarian violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA, made up of about 100 nationalists, including some
skilled in bomb-making, split away from the Irish Republican Army
this year. The official view of both the British and Irish
governments is that the IRA and the Real IRA are separate groups,
based on intelligence reports and on information from Sinn Fein,
the political wing of the IRA
</P>
<P>
   The police said the warning they received on Saturday stipulated
the courthouse area as the target, leading them to move hundreds of
shoppers closer to the bomb, rather than away from it.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA, in a telephone call to a newspaper office in
Dublin, denied assertions by the authorities that it had
deliberately misled the police.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA spokesman, using a recognized IRA code word to
identify himself, said that in three telephone calls on Saturday,
two to Ulster Television in Belfast, it was made clear that the
bomb would be 300 to 400 yards from the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Tuesday afternoon a Real IRA spokesman said that
``at no time was it said it was near the court house.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement continued: ``It was a commercial target. Despite
media reports it was not our intention at any time to kill any
civilians. It was a commercial target, part of an ongoing war
against the Brits. We offer apologies to the civilians.''
</P>
<P>
   The police and officials greeted the statement with scorn.
Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said: ``I think it is a
pathetic excuse for mass murder. Responsibility for this atrocity
rests entirely with the bombers. The Irish and British governments
will do all they can to hunt them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts said it was possible that inexperienced terrorists made
ghastly mistakes in their operation, making unclear statements, or
placing the car bomb in the wrong place, fouling their own plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish Republican Army, which has been observing a cease-fire
for 13 months, often hit economic targets in the middle of business
districts in mainly Protestant towns, but only after giving the
police accurate information on the time and place. Some IRA
operations killed civilian passers-by. But none has approached the
Saturday attack in which the Real IRA, a Catholic group, hit the
center of a town that is 70 percent Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   Seven hours before the group's statement, several hundred
mourners, many weeping as they prayed, crowded around a small, gray
Catholic church and graveyard near this rural village to watch the
burial of Avril Monaghan, 30, her 18-month-old daughter, Maura, and
the twin girls in her womb, due to be born next month.
</P>
<P>
   The Monaghans were the first victims to be buried after the
attack. Mrs. Monaghan's mother, Mary Grimes, also was killed in the
bombing; she will be buried on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   No one could recall when a single attack had killed members of
three generations of the same family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for forgiveness for those who caused that most awful
act of murder,'' said the Rev. James Grimes, Avril Monaghan's
uncle. ``We hope that this may be the last of the terrible agonies
that people have suffered during the past 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of mourners, with a view of several fields of grazing
cattle, gathered on the hillside outside the 200-year-old Church of
St. Macartan to listen to the Mass through loudspeakers. Some stood
guiltily on graves and leaned on headstones, straining for a look
at the burial.
</P>
<P>
   Many people broke down in tears as two coffins, a large wooden
one and a small white one, were carried out of the church to the
graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Monaghan, the husband and father, who has three
surviving children, two girls and a boy, lowered his head and was
guided by friends who held his arms.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. O'Connor, 45, a cousin of Monaghan who also works with him,
said he and others had sat up Monday night with the bereaved
father. ``He was taking it fairly well,'' O'Connor said. ``With
people around you, you're all right. We talked about other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The police Tuesday were still questioning five men arrested in
the area on Monday in connection with the attack. The Irish and
British governments were preparing new security measures to curb
terrorism, but indicated that they would not now propose the
restoration of preventive detention or internment of terrorism
suspects without trials.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A neighbor, Lliam McConnell, who runs a pub here, said he had
just agreed to hire Mrs. Monaghan as a bookkeeper. He brought his
old mandolin to St. Macartan's Tuesday and played a traditional
Gaelic song of mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, Prince Charles visited Belfast and Omagh to
offer the British Royal Family's sympathy. He recalled that his
uncle, Lord Mountbatten, had been killed by the IRA in 1979, ``so I
do have some understanding of the awful horrors that people have to
put up with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
