</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves Notebook: Once again, Braves well-represented in Cy Young
hopefuls
 &HT;    By I. J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Cy Young Award ballots went out this week to 28
sportswriters around the country and what looked like a Greg Maddux
landslide a couple of weeks ago is suddenly become a pretty good
race.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to teammate Tom Glavine.
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, who gets the start tonight against the Giants, is
pitching his best baseball ever this late in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   In his last six starts, he is 4-0, allowing five runs on just 25
hits covering 47 innings. He has thrown 23 straight scoreless
innings, and in a season where his team has the division wrapped
up, the Cy Young is on his mind. Also, San Diego's Andy Ashby
(16-6) and Kevin Brown (15-4) have to be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to win another one,'' he said. ``Doggy (Maddux)
is the favorite, but we have six weeks left.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday's game, the numbers between Maddux and
Glavine were very close. Maddux had 15 wins, Glavine 16, Maddux has
a 1.67 ERA while Glavine is at 2.35. Opponents are hitting .206
against Maddux and .235 against Glavine. But Maddux does have five
shutouts to Glavine's two and 157 strikeouts to Glavine's 125. But
Glavine has been super in the clutch. He's 8-1 after a Braves loss
while Maddux is 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tommy is pitching as good as I have ever seen him,'' pitching
coach Leo Mazzone said. ``Of course, I have been saying that about
him for years.''
</P>
<P>
   A new Byrd
</P>
<P>
   Proving that Atlanta's discards can fit in elsewhere, Paul Byrd
and the Phillies shut out Randy Johnson and the Astros Monday
night. Was Braves general manager John Schuerholz surprised. ``He
pitched a good game against Florida for us (last year),''
Schuerholz said. ``I'm glad for Paul. But I probably talked to 21
clubs about deals and there was no interest in him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves decided to place Byrd on waivers to make room on
their 40-man roster for veteran reliever Norm Charlton. Byrd was
claimed by several teams, the Phillies getting him because they had
the worst record.
</P>
<P>
   Said Byrd, who pitched a four-hitter against the Astros, ``I was
almost in tears when they gave me a standing ovation at the end of
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   This and That
</P>
<P>
   Former Brave Francisco Cabrera, who more than a month ago signed
with the Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs of the Northwest League,
finally made to the club after a month of visa problems. Cabrera,
now 31, was expected to be in the lineup Tuesday night and feels
the independent league is his first step back to the majors. ``I
feel I can keep playing for maybe six, seven more years,'' he said.
... Shortstop Ozzie Smith used a bat made the company Hoosier.
Under his name on the bat are the words THE DREAM. ... Utility
infielder Rafael Belliard, who has been out since April 9 with torn
quadriceps, will leave today for a rehab assignment, possibly Class
A Macon. ... Reliever Russ Springer (bone spur in elbow), who is
eligible to come off the disabled list on Friday, threw again in
the bullpen Tuesday and had no problems. ...Since August 1993, the
Braves are 34-12 against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
