<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PLACE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE POWER OF PLACE (NOT NECESSARILY ONE'S OWN)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, AUG. 23.) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If home is where the heart is, then the repertory in which a
musician feels most at home may have more to do with aptitude and
sympathy than with where that musician was born or lives.
</P>
<P>
   Yet sometimes a relationship between geography and music holds
true, and two new piano recordings, by Stephen Hough and Leif Ove
Andsnes, make a persuasive case for the power of place.
</P>
<P>
   Hough's ``New York Variations'' explores music connected with
the city in which the pianist, who is English, spends half of each
year. Andsnes' ``Long, Long Winter Night'' is devoted to music by
five composers who were born in Norway, that pianist's homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Both CDs present unhackneyed fare. Indeed, two of the four works
Hough plays (John Corigliano's ``Etude Fantasy'' and George
Tsontakis' ``Ghost Variations'') are new to records. And though the
material Andsnes presents may be familiar to Scandinavians, most
Americans will not find it so.
</P>
<P>
   Hough's Manhattan paean (Hyperion CDA 67005) opens with
Corigliano's five-movement ``Etude Fantasy,'' from 1976, a work
that benefits from the pianist's focus and natural reticence.
</P>
<P>
   In the first etude, ``For the Left Hand Alone,'' a spare
six-note row yields to increasing intensity. Culmination comes when
the right hand enters to start the second etude, ``Legato.'' Here,
Hough imparts immense concentration, drawing the listener into
quiet music that in lesser hands might seem cerebral and
uninvolving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifths to Thirds'' is a playful romp, and Hough reveals
virtuosity without ostentation. In ``Ornaments,'' he embellishes
the music with a painterly touch, shifting subtly to project
colors.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Melody,'' the final etude, Hough brings a brooding quality
to Corigliano's stark, melancholy strains. And as the music slows,
the piece ends before the listener even realizes it, as if carried
off by a gentle breeze.
</P>
<P>
   In Copland's lapidary Piano Variations of 1930, the best-known
work on the disk, Hough performs with his customary good taste. The
variations offer playful athleticism as well as more earnest
musical strivings, and he plays them soberly yet with an admirable
twinkle. In the coda, he lends keen edge to an ending fraught with
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Weber's 12-tone Fantasy of 1946, also a series of
variations, is a richer-sounding piece, and Hough graces it with a
kind of tempered bravura. Weber (born William Jennings Bryan),
though practically self-taught in composition, was an accomplished
stylist, and this lush work, a pastiche of influences, proves a
fine canvas for Hough's flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   The album aptly concludes with its biggest offering (at more
than 30 minutes), George Tsontakis' excellent three-movement
``Ghost Variations,'' from 1991, an expansive tonal work of fluid
contrasts and striking musical episodes.
</P>
<P>
   To this ambitious work, Hough applies his formidable technique
and fine interpretive sense to nearly overpowering effect.
</P>
<P>
   The first section is divided into five parts, ending with
variations on a snippet from the finale of Mozart's Piano Concerto
No. 22, a familiar, childlike theme that appears as if from
nowhere. The theme reappears in the two scherzos that follow, now
more ghostly than before and more fully woven into the structure of
Tsontakis' thickly textured, dynamic music.
</P>
<P>
   Hough renders these movements sonic collages, contrasting bold
colors with subtle hues worthy of the French Impressionists.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the often brash, dissonant, even acerbic world
Hough conjures in ``New York Variations,'' Andsnes' ``Long, Long
Winter Night'' (EMI Classics CDC-56541), brings to mind placid
environs of cool beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Andsnes, a young Norwegian pianist, begins this collection of
miniatures conventionally, with nine gems from Grieg. But instead
of excerpts from the famous ``Lyric Pieces,'' he offers selections
from the Norwegian Folk Songs (Op. 66) and the ``Peasant Dances''
(Op. 72). Essentially scenes of pastoral life, these little pieces
delight the ear.
</P>
<P>
   The jaunty ``Tomorrow You'll Marry Her'' (Op. 66, No. 10), for
instance, is full of charm, as is ``Halling From the Fairy Hill''
(Op. 72, No. 4). ``Lullaby'' (Op. 66, No. 17) sounds almost too
engaging to be soothing.
</P>
<P>
   Geirr Tveitt's 50 Folk Tunes From Hardanger, published more than
50 years after Grieg's efforts, spring from the same sylvan well.
Andsnes plays seven of these mini-sagas. By turns refined
(``Welcome With Honor''), jocular (``Tears and Laughter for a
Boat'') and rustically attractive (``The Long, Long Winter
Night''), these works stealthily embed themselves in the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Andsnes puts his characteristically deft touch to ideal use in
David Monrad Johansen's ``Pictures From Nordland,'' a suite from
1919. Especially in ``The Little Stone God,'' the pianist uses his
solid technique to expose nuance and accentuate drama. And in
``Reindeer,'' you can practically see the beasts scampering about.
</P>
<P>
   The most substantial work on the disk is Fartein Valen's 12-tone
Variations for Piano of 1936. As in so many other items on this CD,
the music starts out sedately, but tensions soon build.
</P>
<P>
   At less than eight minutes, the piece remains modest, even as
Andsnes' accomplishment transcends such limitations. In his
crystalline tone, every note matters.
</P>
<P>
   The disk concludes with music by Harold Saeverud, who died in
1993 and is the best-known composer here after Grieg. In selections
from Saeverud's ``Tunes and Dances From Siljustol,'' mostly
composed during World War II, ``Ballad of Revolt'' sounds like a
combination of ``When Johnny Comes Marching Home'' and
Rachmaninoff's Rhapsody on a Theme of Paganini, and is pretty much
what its title suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cotton Grass Plays on a Moonbeam,'' ``Thor and His
Hammer'' and ``Tone's Cradle Song'' revert to a more detached, less
martial esthetic.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the short ``Hymn Against the Boyg,'' from Saeverud's
1947 incidental music to Ibsen's ``Peer Gynt,'' that commands real
attention. With this score, a gloomy meditation that begins deep in
the bass and rises, Saeverud intended to forge a path for Ibsen's
themes that differed from Grieg's much-loved approach.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from this excerpt, he accomplished his goal, and
Andsnes plays the crisp music with a savvy sense of foreboding.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these albums makes a strong case for the place of
geography in music. They are stronger, more compelling statements
thanks to thematic threads that reveal something extra about the
performers. That the music is close to the players' hearts must be
obvious, but it is through repeated hearings that one realizes the
scope of that significance.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Hough's and Andsnes' personal connection to these
scores, listeners may appreciate music they might otherwise never
have bothered with. That in itself is an achievement worth noting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
