<HEADER>
A0151 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-SOLVE-T     08-18 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSMANSHIP-SOLVE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAIR, CLEAN PLAY NEEDS TO HAVE ITS ROOTS IN YOUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By DAVID A. MARKIEWICZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do a Mark Gastineau-style sack dance over a fallen quarterback
and an NFL referee flags you 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Start a bench-clearing brawl by playing the batter a little too
much chin music and a major-league baseball umpire will eject you
from the game. The commissioner's office will likely follow with
fines and suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   Turn a blind eye when one of your college athletes accepts perks
from an overzealous athletic booster and you risk serious sanctions
from the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Even the NHL will lock your skates in the cooler for five
minutes if you mix it up too vigorously on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Sports, from the professional level down to youth leagues, has
volumes of on-field and off-field penalties for illegal play and
poor conduct. Yet, by most accounts, the wave of unsportsmanlike
behavior is on the rise. All those rules just don't seem to be
working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have too many rules,'' argues William Shelton, former
chairman of the NCAA Committee on Sportsmanship and Ethical
Conduct. It has gotten to the point, Shelton says, where athletes
and coaches believe that if there is no rule specifically
prohibiting an act, it must be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the penalties for misconduct are clear, however,
athletes, coaches, fans and administrators sometimes flaunt the
rules. They deem the consequences of their actions worth the risk,
or they simply ignore possible penalties in the heat of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   If more and tighter rules aren't the answer to better
sportsmanship, what then?
</P>
<P>
   Many sports figures concerned with the issue suggest the
solution lies at the roots _ with young athletes, who must be
taught right from wrong.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to sportsmanship, Hall of Fame basketball player
Kareem Abdul-Jabbar says, ``They have to have it explained to them
as children.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar states that much of the unsportsmanlike behavior
seen today is ``human nature,'' with players simply acting in the
moment. But, he adds, it is critical that athletes, particularly
when they are young, are taught ``to channel that fury into
competing, rather than acting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers manager Johnny Oates says: ``It's about respect, and
when you have a lack of respect, that leads to a lack of
sportsmanship. Two words that mean a lot to me are respect and
integrity, and that's what we need to be teaching our children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go at it directly at the youth level,'' agrees
Craig Clifford, who teaches philosophy at Tarleton State University
and is co-author of the book ``Coaching for Character (Reclaiming
the Principles of Sportsmanship)''.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other place you target,'' Clifford adds, ``is the colleges
because they're turning out all the high school coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   John Mackovic, former University of Texas football coach and
chairman of the American Football Coaches Association Ethics
Committee, agrees that coaching is critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people watch everything we do and listen for everything
we say,'' Mackovic says. ``We are developing leaders through
athletics, and the lessons we teach are real. We need leadership
from coaches at all levels to take our profession to higher
standards of sportsmanship and ethical conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The young athlete's parents also have an important role,
athletes say. For it is the parents, they say, who must show
children the way to behave in life and on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   Says tennis great Chris Evert, ``It's called parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that by teaching sportsmanship at the youth level, a
code of behavior will develop and spread through the high school
and college ranks and even into the pros as those children mature
and carry their values with them into adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   Just as unsportsmanlike behavior subtlety infiltrated ballparks
and field houses over the years, so, too, can good sportsmanship.
But, experts say, it must start at the youth level.
</P>
<P>
   Darrell J. Burnett, a clinical and sports psychologist who works
with troubled youth, calls youth sports, ``the last vestige of
sportsmanship,'' adding, ``We're living in an age where the
preservation of traditional values can no longer be taken for
granted. It's no different in the world of sports. The traditional
value of sportsmanship is being challenged from all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   It is necessary, Burnett says, ``to guide our youth, reminding
them what sportsmanship is all about, rewarding them for showing
good sportsmanship and showing, by our example, that sportsmanship
is still alive and valued in youth sports today.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett suggests a 10-item checklist for youths trying to
practice good sportsmanship:
</P>
<P>
   1. Abide by the rules of the game.
</P>
<P>
   2. Avoid arguments.
</P>
<P>
   3. Share in the responsibilities of the team.
</P>
<P>
   4. Give everyone a chance to play according to the rules.
</P>
<P>
   5. Always play fair.
</P>
<P>
   6. Follow the directions of the coach.
</P>
<P>
   7. Respect the other team's effort.
</P>
<P>
   8. Offer encouragement to teammates.
</P>
<P>
   9. Accept the judgment calls of game officials.
</P>
<P>
   10. End the game smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Burnett defines sportsmanship as winning without gloating,
losing without complaining, and treating opponents with respect.
</P>
<P>
   Young athletes, he says, must be taught to not make excuses or
pout when they commit a mistake in a game, or lose the game. They
also should be taught to encourage teammates who fail, rather than
criticize them, and to avoid embarrassing a defeated opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The National Alliance for Youth Sports, a Florida-based
nonprofit organization that trains and certifies volunteer youth
coaches, has issued separate sportsmanship challenges to coaches
and to parents of young athletes.
</P>
<P>
   One is a list of the top 10 warning signs of a bad volunteer
youth coach. According to the Alliance, the bad volunteer coach:
Stresses winning at all costs; doesn't let every child play equal
time; yells at officials and argues with opposing coaches;
encourages cheating to win the game; physically punishes players
for losing; and doesn't shake the hand of the opposing coach after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The pushy parent is one who: pushes a child to sports success in
order to win an athletic scholarship; gets into game-related
arguments with other parents; compares the child's performance to
that of other children; and forces the child to practice at home.
</P>
<P>
   While a ``winning is the most important thing'' philosophy might
be acceptable at the professional level, it is not at the youth
level, says John R. Gerdy, a New York educational consultant and a
former sports ethics fellow of the Institute for International
Sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Challenging the belief that the final score is all that
matters is not about tearing down an ideal,'' Gerdy has written.
``It is not about de-emphasizing or trivializing sport. It is not
about settling for mediocrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is, however, about regaining perspective. It is about
refocusing on the primary reason for participation in athletics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
