A0155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LIBRARY-1STLE     08-18 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LIBRARY-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little Rock banking on public's fascination
 &HT;    (EDS: CORRECTS dateline.)
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Even if the Monica Lewinsky scandal proves to be
President Clinton's undoing, officials in his home state of
Arkansas said Tuesday they will carry on with plans for his
presidential library.
</P>
<P>
   Little Rock, which beat out 40 other Arkansas cities and towns
vying to be the library site, is busy buying land along the
Arkansas River and preparing the way for construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been a voice of opposition out there to the
project,'' said City Manager Cy Carney. ``But the City Council has
been unanimous in its support, and they are not making moves to do
anything but continue moving forward on the project. Our view is
this is eight years of American history that we can have here in
Little Rock.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Brantley, editor of the weekly Arkansas Times, said no one
has given any serious thought to the idea of not having a
presidential library in Little Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Presidential libraries have become a staple of the 20th
century,'' he said. ``And no president has been more fascinating
than Bill Clinton, except maybe Kennedy _ I didn't say `good' but
`fascinating' _ so it's hard to see why a Bill Clinton presidential
library wouldn't hold interest.''
</P>
<P>
   An impeachment or resignation could delay the project, however,
Brantley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if he is driven from the presidency, it certainly, in
the short run, will put a damper on the project, and will make the
fund-raisers' task more difficult. Clinton would have to go into
seclusion for a while before he hit the banquet circuit.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the 26 acres needed for the library have been purchased and
cleared, private donations will cover the $100 million needed for
construction and the establishment of an endowment. Fund-raising
efforts are under way, both in and out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents expressed opposition to the City Council's
initial announcement that it would issue more than $16 million in
bonds for the project, but a financing plan passed in March. A
lawsuit has been filed by a group that opposes taxes, but Carney
called it a ``nuisance suit'' that he expects to be thrown out of
court any day now.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Little Rock is banking heavily on the library to
attract visitors and give a boost to the local economy, so killing
the project could prove disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important economic development project,''
Carney said. ``We project 300,000 visitors a year into the library,
so it's a key part of our redevelopment effort downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   For a presidential library to come into being, the municipality
chosen by the president must buy and clear the land for
construction. Private donations then pay for construction. Finally,
the National Archives has to approve the library and agree to staff
and run it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reportedly is shopping for a high-profiled architect to
design the library, banking on his Hollywood connections to land
one.
</P>
<P>
   There are 11 presidential libraries in the United States, all
opened in this century. The first federally designated library was
Franklin Delano Roosevelt's in Hyde Park, N.Y. The most recent
opened in 1997 in Texas for George Bush. Only Richard Nixon's
library is not supported by the National Archives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
