<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUSSIA SET TO REVIEW DEBT PLAN WITH BANKERS
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government delayed announcing its plan to change the
repayment terms on its debt, after alarm spread amoung foreign
bankers and investors that Russia was prepared to discriminate
against foreign creditors. Deputy Prime Minister Boris Fyodorov
said he would first review the plan with representatives of
Goldman, Sachs, J.P. Morgan and Deutsche Bank. Details of the
expected swap of treasury bills for longer-term securities, a key
element in Russia's program, may be released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   DELL SURPASSES EARNINGS ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Dell Computer fell $1 Tuesday before the computer
maker reported that its second-quarter earnings exceeded analysts'
estimates. After the markets closed, Dell said profits jumped 62
percent attributing the increase to the strength of its direct
sales model, in which the company bypasses distributors and dealers
and builds each computer to order. The stock rose sharply in
after-hours trading.
</P>
<P>
   PROFITS STRONG AT MOST RETAILERS
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's biggest retailers reported
better-than-expected second-quarter earnings, but J.C. Penney had a
steep decline in the quarter in part because of weak department
store and catalog sales.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG TO EXPLORE SELLING A STAKE
</P>
<P>
   The accounting firm KPMG Peat Marwick plans to hire an
investment banker to consider selling between 20 percent and 30
percent of its consulting business to either an outside investor or
to the public through a stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   KORN FERRY PLANS PUBLIC OFFERING
</P>
<P>
   The executive search firm Korn Ferry International has filed for
an initial public offering, which it expects will raise $230
million.
</P>
<P>
   LATIN AMERICA'S DIMINISHED ALLURE
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after Brazil's triumphant sale of the Telebras phone
giant to investors for almost $19 billion, shares in Latin
America's largest privatization have fallen sharply. The decline
reflects a broad retreat in all Latin stock markets, worsened by
the selloffs in Russia and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   PARTY BOSS SAYS NO BANk CLOSINGS
</P>
<P>
   Taku Yamasaki, a power broker in the Liberal Democratic Party,
was quoted as saying the Japanese government has decided to prevent
the failure of any major Japanese bank. If his assertion is true,
it would mark the kind of ambivalence that has plagued Japanese
policy makers over the debt-laden banking system. Many analysts
have suggested an orderly closure of one of Japan's big, troubled
banks would send a strong message that the government is serious
about finding a solution to the problems of its ailing banking
system. Toyota Motor and Nissan Motor said they had made payments
to a company that has figured in two recent arrests involving
accusations of extortion against Japan Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   FEDERAL-MOGUL BUYING PARTS UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Federal-Mogul has agreed to acquire the auto-parts businesses of
Cooper Industries, which includes Champion spark plugs and Anco
windshield wipers, for $1.9 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   TREASURY BOND YIELDS RISE SLIGHTLY
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond increased to 5.55 percent
from 5.54 percent on Monday. The jump came as Federal Reserve
policy makers, as expected, left interest rates unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
