<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-CAR-THEFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR THEFTS LEAD ISRAEL TO WALL OFF WEST BANK 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A record number of car thefts has persuaded Israel's
right-wing government to abandon its longtime opposition to
erecting any new barriers between Israel and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's government had resisted the
idea fiercely out of concern that such a line could be interpreted
as a demarcation of Israel's future border. But it has shifted
course in the face of public outcry over the disappearing cars,
some 46,000 of which were stolen in Israel last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli police have said that nearly all of those cars end
up in Palestinian-controlled areas of the West Bank, but they have
been unable to recover more than a small handful of them, and had
called for new barriers as the only sure way to sever favorite
escape routes.
</P>
<P>
   That idea had seemed to echo calls by left-wing legislators for
a permanent dividing line between Israel and the Arab land it
captured in the 1967 war, and police officials said that
Netanyahu's government _ which opposes the idea of a Palestinian
state _ had rejected the calls as recently as two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But last weekend, Netanyahu's government finally approved a
partial version of the plan, authorizing some 50 miles of walls,
ditches and fences along stretches of the 194-mile Green Line,
which divided Israel and the West Bank before the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Because the new barriers will not be continuous, aides to
Netanyahu have said they should not be perceived as representing a
de facto border. Israeli newspapers have also reported that the
barriers will be erected ``a few kilometers'' to the east of the
old Green Line, to signal the current government's insistence on
maintaining a security buffer across the old border even under a
permanent peace accord with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the move has inspired taunts from Israeli leftists,
including Yossi Sarid, head of the Meretz Party, who described the
decision to build the new barriers as the ``last nail in the coffin
of the illusion called the Greater Land of Israel.'' That is a term
used by the most extreme among Israeli conservatives to claim
Israeli sovereignty over the West Bank and Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of separation has long found strong backing among the
Israeli public, with as many as 85 percent of people polled saying
that they favor the idea of a complete separation between Israel
and Palestinian-ruled territory.
</P>
<P>
   The idea has gained in support as the number of reported car
thefts in Israel soared to a record last year. The Israeli police
have said that as many as 80 percent of the stolen vehicles end up
in the West Bank after either passing across open fields or through
Israeli checkpoints, where soldiers usually scrutinize only
vehicles heading into Israel.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of this year, according to police officials,
the Israeli police and their Palestinian counterparts launched 56
different anti-theft operations and arrested nearly 200 suspected
car thieves. But they have been able to recover only about 450
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   As part of new crime-fighting efforts, the Israeli police have
already assigned special squads of border police to try to
intercept suspected car thieves before they pass into
Palestinian-controlled areas. But the police have said that task
will become much easier if the traffic can be funneled into a
manageable number of choke points, with the remote crossing points
sealed with the construction of the new barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials have said that the cost of the plan could
amount to more than $25 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The approval of the initiative comes at a time of little
apparent progress in Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations, which
have been stalled for months over the extent of Israel's further
withdrawal of troops from the West Bank. The last high-level talks
between the two sides took place more than three weeks ago. In that
lull, both Netanyahu and Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
have once again asked Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
intervene in an attempt to break the deadlock, but American
officials have said that the two sides must first make more
progress toward mending their divide.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Palestinian officials have criticized the idea of
building barriers between Israeli and Palestinian land, saying that
the only certain effect would be to make it easier for the Israeli
authorities to bar Palestinians from reaching jobs in Israeli
territory.
</P>
<P>
   In the current atmosphere, however, Jibril Rajoub, the
Palestinian chief of the Preventive Security Service in the West
Bank, has issued a clear endorsement of Netanyahu's decision.
Rajoub was quoted by Reuters as saying: ``I am for the separation
between them and us so that we can have our land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0398 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0174 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CLINTON-RICH-COLUMN     08-18 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CLINTON-RICH-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STAIN OF THE NATION  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add CLINTON to slug)   By FRANK RICH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was probably too much to hope that the first line of
President Clinton's address to the nation would be: ``Thank you for
tuning in to my presidential dialogue on race.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead we got a speech, at once mortifying and legalistically
hairsplitting, that proved one thing: People do not change their
character. The same can be said for the media, which spent two days
prior to Clinton's four-minute speech busily manufacturing
entertainment in the guise of ``news.''
</P>
<P>
   And so there was no catharsis on Monday, no big Shakespearean
emotions that follow a tragic fall. If Watergate gave us ``a
cancer'' on the presidency as its metaphor, Clintongate has given
us ``wiggle room.'' We don't feel like crying, and we don't feel
like laughing (the summer's best semen-stained farce, by popular
acclamation, remains ``There's Something About Mary''). We mainly
feel like taking a bath.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're trapped in Groundhog Day. We know the story is over:
the public told pollsters its denouement (yes he's a liar, no to
impeachment) weeks ago. But the sordid melody will repeat itself
with variations for two more years. Kenneth Starr's report will be
finessed by both Clinton and Congress. There will be no dialogue on
race, or Social Security, or anything else _ just a lame duck
running out a second-term clock. And you know what? The Republic,
if not the immediate political prospects of the Democratic Party,
will survive.
</P>
<P>
   The only real suspense is whether Starr has anything to show for
the non-erotic investigations he spent $30 million or so pursuing
for three-plus years (Castle Grande, anyone?) before being turned
on to sex by Linda Tripp in January, and whether Al Gore, who chose
to spend this week checking out global warming in Hawaii firsthand,
will return to face the campaign finance music on the mainland. In
Gore's absence, the de facto vice president has been Jesse Jackson,
whose bulletins to the press of his prayerful sessions with the
Clintons would be touching if they weren't so reminiscent of the
absolution bestowed on the disgraced Richard Nixon by the late,
great Rabbi Baruch Korff.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the rest of the marathon pre-speech countdown on
television, at least Jackson's lamentations had some news content.
CNN posted a digital clock on screen ticking off the ``time
elapsed'' of the president's testimony _ a gesture to blood-sport
fans that not only was pointless but inaccurate, since the
testimony was interrupted by breaks. On MSNBC, a Newsweek
journalist did a wrap-up of politicians' bimbos past. On Fox, the
figure who is most emblematic of this whole story, Clintonian
toe-sucker turned thumb-sucking pundit Dick Morris, retailed
innuendo about Orrin Hatch. It was also on Fox that another
Newsweek writer's ruminations were framed by rapid-fire graphics on
the ``alleged'' scandals of every president, not excepting Taylor
(nepotism) and Pierce, Andrew Johnson and Grant (a trifecta of
alcoholism).
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The Los Angeles Times on Sunday, William Schneider
noted that in a new Gallup Poll the news media's 74 percent
disapproval rating had surpassed Starr's 58 percent to approach Ms.
Lewinsky's. ``In the public's view, the press is no different from
Monica,'' he wrote. ``They're all tramps!''
</P>
<P>
   It's days like Monday that have led to this pass. If the biggest
lie of 1998 has been ``I did not have sexual relations with that
woman,'' the second-biggest lie is a pious talking head on TV
saying some version of ``Oh how we hate covering this story about
the president's sexual relations with that woman.'' The tone of the
coverage has been orgiastic from the moment the pope was dumped in
Cuba; for every factual development there have been days of
prurient speculation and open longing for what in the porno biz is
called ``the money shot'' (the still-elusive dress). On Monday,
even when there was no information to be had about what was going
on in the White House Map Room, TV anchors interviewed each other
or replayed a recondite piece about cyber-optic cable rather than
devote appreciable air time to, say, the ongoing story in Northern
Ireland or even the non-erogenous Clinton scandals.
</P>
<P>
   This saga has soiled everyone who has touched it _ and I
certainly don't exclude myself. Only the bipartisan majority of the
American people, who have been crying ``Enough!'' for months now
and whose number easily dwarfs the Nielsen ratings of the All
Monica show, are clean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
