<SLUG> BC-ORE.-SUICIDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 SUICIDES UNDER OREGON'S DEATH WITH DIGNITY ACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Oregon officials announced Tuesday that eight people
in the state had died after taking lethal medications prescribed
under the law allowing doctor-assisted suicide for terminally ill
people, which took effect last November.
</P>
<P>
   Two other people who were certified as terminally ill and who
had received state authorization to take the drugs died before
doing so, according to a report released by the Oregon Health
Division.
</P>
<P>
   The state law, officially known as the Death with Dignity Act,
is the only one in the nation allowing doctor-assisted suicide.
While advocates for the practice view the law as a potential
bellwether for other states that have considered similar measures,
opponents have fiercely criticized the Oregon law and fought _ so
far successfully _ against its adoption elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report, the first to detail deaths under the law, was
described as a ``tragic development'' by a spokesman for the
state's Catholic Conference, but supporters said the relatively
small number of deaths disproved predictions by church leaders and
other opponents that the law would be abused or that sick people
would flock to their doctors to end their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon law applies to an adult of sound mind who has, in the
opinion of two doctors, less than six months to live. Doctors may
prescribe but not administer the lethal dose. Those wishing to die
fill out and sign a single-page form, titled, ``Request for
medication to end my life in a humane and dignified manner.''
</P>
<P>
   While no names of the 10 deceased people were included in
Tuesday's report, the report included a number of statistics that
offered a stark glimpse into legally assisted suicide, including
these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Five were men and five were women.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cancer was the underlying illness in nine of the 10 cases,
while the 10th person suffered from heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   _ The average age at death was 71.
</P>
<P>
   _ All received a medical evaluation by at least two doctors to
confirm their terminal condition, and their doctors judged each to
be capable of making and communicating health-care decisions, as
required by the law. All complied with the 15-day waiting period
between the first and second requests for the lethal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Eight of the 10 had more than a high-school education.
</P>
<P>
   _ Of the eight who actually took lethal medication, the wait
between acquiring the prescription and death ranged from less than
a day to 16 days. The average wait was two days.
</P>
<P>
   _ The eight who who took the drugs died within seven hours of
doing so; the average time before death was 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon Health Division said Tuesday that it was conducting
in-depth interviews with the doctors involved in assisting or
attending the suicides, and that a more extensive report covering
all cases under the Death with Dignity Act would be made public
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are releasing this preliminary summary to inform the public
and those concerned about ethical, legal and medical aspects of the
act,'' said Dr. Katrina Hedberg, medical epidemiologist for the
division. But the law had confidentiality provisions that
explicitly prohibited the state from releasing many other details
of the suicides, she added. ``Release of more specific information
at this time would jeopardize this guarantee of protection,''
Hedberg said.
</P>
<P>
   The Oregon law was originally approved in a 1994 vote on a
narrow 51-49 percentage by state residents, but was promptly put on
hold by a series of court battles. The fight seemed to have been
settled last year, when Oregon voters, this time by a 60 percent to
40 percent majority, turned back a measure to repeal the law.
</P>
<P>
   A new wrinkle quickly developed when federal drug-enforcement
officials threatened to impose severe sanctions on any doctor who
prescribed suicide drugs, the Oregon law notwithstanding. But
Attorney General Janet Reno removed that obstacle in June,
effectively overruling the drug officials by declaring that no such
prosecutions would take place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
