A0182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN19-COX     08-18 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN19-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Commentary: Clinton's scripted lies
</P>
<P>
   By Rowland Nethaway
</P>
<P>
   c: 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ President Clinton's five-minute televised address
to the nation was an admission that he lied about having sex with a
White House intern, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   He apologized, nearly.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted responsibility, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   To say that Bill Clinton lies is like saying the Houdini
performed tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Both characterizations are woefully inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton lies. It's in his nature. Scorpions sting.
Clinton lies.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton lies with practiced style. When it comes to lying,
Clinton is one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way a smooth bunko artist is respected by the
police, Clinton's ability to lie has earned the respect of his
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   One-time Democratic presidential candidate U.S. Sen. Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska once remarked in awestruck admiration, ``Clinton's an
unusually good liar. Unusually good. Do you realize that?''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently few Americans realized or cared.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later another war hero and Clinton opponent again
tried to warn Americans. ``Wake up, America,'' said Republican
presidential candidate U.S. Sen. Bob Dole. Clinton, he said,
``tells you one thing and does precisely the other, time after time
after time.''
</P>
<P>
   Political opponent Ross Perot doesn't sound quite so goofy now
that Hillary has blamed her husband's troubles on a vast
right-wing, anti-Arkansas conspiracy. Perot warned that a Clinton
second term would become ``a second Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody believes he slept with this tootsie and lied about
it,'' said former New York mayor Ed Koch six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Koch evidently has seen his share of slick confidence men
because everybody did not believe that the president of the United
States could really go on national television, look the American
public straight in the eye and lie through his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not . . . have . . . sexual relations with that woman,
Miss Lewinsky,'' Clinton said on Jan. 26, looking stern and sincere
and waving an index finger for added effect.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Koch, many loyal Democrats and credulous Americans took
Clinton at his word.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reinforced his televised denial with private eye-to-eye
conversations with his cabinet members, staff and closest
supporters. He said the accusations against him were lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four days ago,'' one frustrated Clinton friend told the New
York Times, ``the president told me he never had sex with Monica.''
That was shortly before Clinton went on television to admit that he
had sex with Monica, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton never really said they had sex. He said they had
``inappropriate'' conduct. The word ``inappropriate'' was chosen
because Clinton emphatically told reporters in January that he did
not have an ``improper'' relationship with Lewinsky _ a lubricated
lie.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's habit of manipulating and misleading people for his
benefit now is aided and abetted by professional manipulators of
make believe.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Jan. 26 finger-wagging denial speech was produced with
the expert help of Harry Thomason, Clinton's wealthy Hollywood
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Thomason polished Clinton's script and delivery so the president
could fool as many Americans from the White House as Thomason can
fool from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Americans now know that the Jan. 26 denial speech was an acting
job and an Oscar-quality lie.
</P>
<P>
   In his Monday night televised White House contrition speech,
Clinton again asks the American people to believe him. Standing off
camera was Thomason and another Hollywood make-believe executive
watching their performer deliver another polished acting job.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has turned the White House into an X-rated movie set.
The nation deserves a better leading man.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: RNeth(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
