<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0183 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RDP-ART-2TAKE     08-18 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RDP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR CALLS LEWINSKY BACK TO TESTIFY BEFORE GRAND JURY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also: CLINTON-RDP with photo, EXCLUSIVE-CLINTON-LEWINSKY,
CLINTON-VINEYARD, CLINTON-ASSESS, CLINTON-HILLARY,
CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-LEGAL, CLINTON-SPEECH, CLINTON-VOICES
with photo, CLINTON-PUNDITS, CLINTON-CABINET, NY-CLINTON-SENATE,
CLINTON-GORE) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES BENNET and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prosecutors opened a new line of inquiry into
President Clinton's actions on Tuesday, summoning Monica Lewinsky
to testify again to the federal grand jury here on Thursday. It was
one of several signs that President Clinton did not end his legal
or political troubles by acknowledging an intimate relationship
with her.
</P>
<P>
   The move to bring Ms. Lewinsky back to the grand jury reflected
a decision by the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, to
play off her testimony against the president's to see if there are
inconsistencies, according to people familiar with his strategy.
</P>
<P>
   That approach, a classic prosecutorial tactic, indicated that
Starr was trying to determine whether Clinton might have perjured
himself before the grand jury, a new approach in an investigation
that has already lasted seven months.
</P>
<P>
   New details emerged on Tuesday about what was described as a
warlike exchange during the president's testimony on Monday, which
was transmitted to the grand jury here. Although Clinton politely
shook hands with prosecutors before and after they squared off, the
questioning turned confrontational, with Starr threatening at
points to subpoena the president for further testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined to answer some of the prosecutors' questions
about the details of his sexual contact with Ms. Lewinsky. His
private lawyers signaled an end to the four-hour session before
Starr and his team had finished.
</P>
<P>
   While he acknowledged an intimate relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, Clinton denied under oath, as he did later in his address
to the nation, that he had obstructed justice, lawyers said.
Specifically, they said, he testified that he had not asked his
personal secretary, Betty Currie, to retrieve from Ms. Lewinsky
some gifts that he had given her.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's private attorney, David Kendall, said on Tuesday that
the president did not decline to answer any questions about
possible obstruction of justice. ``As to a very few highly
intrusive questions with respect to the specifics of his relation
to Ms. Lewinsky, he gave candid but not detailed answers,'' Kendall
said. ``This was to preserve personal privacy and institutional
dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Clinton family, the White House staff, and the country
began on Tuesday to absorb Monday's extraordinary events, friends
of Ms. Lewinsky, like many Republican and Democratic officeholders
here, expressed disappointment with the president's speech. They
said that the president should have apologized directly to Ms.
Lewinsky and her family for his role in shoving them into a
maelstrom of legal and media scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's four-minute address left even some Democrats
complaining on Tuesday that he fell short of an apology and spoke
more in anger than in sorrow. Some said that they would have to
await a report by Starr to Congress before deciding whether the
matter should be set aside without impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Hand in hand in hand, Clinton, his wife, Hillary, and their
daughter, Chelsea, strolled to a helicopter on the South Lawn on
Tuesday afternoon and departed for a twelve-day vacation on
Martha's Vineyard. Aides to the president said that he would
probably interrupt his trip for at least two public events, putting
into practice his argument Monday night that it was time to turn
from the investigation to ``important work.''
</P>
<P>
   Before departing on Tuesday, Clinton spent more than an hour
with his foreign policy advisers, and also worked the telephone.
His advisers said that he was mostly fielding supportive calls from
friends on Capitol Hill and elsewhere.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
