u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      08-18 1297
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISS-KLAN-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-KLANSMAN AGAIN ON TRIAL FOR ORDERING 1966 MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATTIESBURG, Miss. _ In the first day of testimony in the murder
trial of the aging former Ku Klux Klan leader accused of ordering
the firebombing that killed her husband, Ellie Dahmer described
that chilly night in 1966 when she woke up to the blaring of a car
horn at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   There had been threats before against her husband, Vernon
Dahmer, a storekeeper who angered the Klan when he offered his shop
as a place that blacks could pay their poll tax and register to
vote. But this time, as the masked Klansmen outside in the dark
rushed into their yard carrying gallon jugs of gasoline, she sensed
that her worst fear had come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I yelled for Vernon to get up,'' said Mrs. Dahmer, looking
down from the witness chair on the defendant, Sam Bowers, once a
feared leader of Klan activity in Mississippi, now 73, who
prosecutors believe ordered the burning of the Dahmers' home in the
Kelly Settlement community outside Hattiesburg in Forrest County.
She testified that she told her waking husband that, ``I believe
they got us this time.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the fifth time Bowers has been tried in connection with
Dahmer's death; the others ended in hung juries. Mrs. Dahmer,
fighting to keep her composure, told the jury Tuesday that she saw
her husband fire a shotgun over and over out a window as he shouted
for her to leave him, to take their two children out the back door.
She told the jurors how he kept firing as the flames from that
burning house burned into his arms.
</P>
<P>
   But what she could not say was that she saw Bowers there, among
the two carloads of Klansmen who rumbled up to their home armed
with shotguns and the 12 gallons of gasoline on Jan. 10, 1966.
``No,'' she said, when asked by defense lawyer Travis Buckley if
she saw Bowers take part in the crime. ``I didn't see him.''
</P>
<P>
   And that _ linking a man who was nowhere near the crime scene _
is the challenge that prosecutors face here in this historic old
courthouse, in an antiquated courtroom where the jury sits in the
middle of the room on the elevated jury stand, to decide Bowers'
fate.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers was not even in the Hattiesburg area that day, though law
enforcement officers who have tracked the case off and on for three
decades have said he was the driving force behind it. He helped
plan it in detail, and gave the word to go ahead when all was
ready, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This cowardly attack was ordered by Sam Bowers,'' said Bob
Helfrich, an assistant district attorney who is prosecuting the
case, in his opening statements.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bowers' lawyer, Buckley, dismissed the new trial as
``media-orchestrated prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to link him, directly, to the murder and arson failed
in the past, as all-white juries could not reach verdicts. But
racism, more than any lack of lack of evidence, decided those
trials, Dahmers' family believes.
</P>
<P>
   All day Tuesday, people with gray in their hair _ both Dahmer
family members and now aged investigators who were at the crime
scene as it smoldered the morning after _ filed into the witness
stand, to talk about things they saw as children or very young men.
</P>
<P>
   It is fitting, spectators and lawyers agreed, that this case
from the past be decided in this setting, which looks more like a
scene from ``To Kill a Mockingbird.'' But while the courtroom is
something out of the past, much has changed outside that courtroom
that leaves prosecutors hopeful that this time, the outcome will be
different.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Bowers faces a jury of six blacks, five whites and
one Asian. The very thing Dahmer died for _ working to register
blacks to vote _ would one day lead to this diverse jury. Only
registered voters are summoned to jury pools, and at the time of
his murder, all-male, all-white juries often decided the fates of
blacks in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors on Wednesday are expected to produce witnesses,
including at least one ex-Klansman who will testify, prosecutors
say, that Bowers was the mastermind of the crime. One of them is
former Klansman Billy Roy Pitts, who pleaded guilty to murder and
arson charges in connection with the killing. Three other men were
convicted in the killing.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, what the courtroom did most was relive the past.
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer was not a nationally known civil rights figure like
Medgar Evers, whose killer, Byron de la Beckwith, was finally
convicted in Jackson in 1994, three decades after the 1963 murder.
(It was the success of that case, along with some new evidence,
that helped prompt prosecutors here to re-open the Dahmer
investigation.)
</P>
<P>
   Dahmer was a family man, storekeeper and local official with the
NAACP, who thought that allowing blacks to pay their $2 poll tax _
in itself a device intended by segregationists to hold down black
voters _ at his store would encourage them. They trusted him.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers was a businessman in Laurel, a small town near
Hattiesburg, and in 1964 had founded and become Imperial Wizard of
the White Knights of the Ku Klux Klan, an organization linked to 10
murders, church burnings, assaults, and jury tamperings _ Klansmen
were believed to have contacted jurors in at least one of Bowers'
pervious trials in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said he became angry when Dahmer began encouraging
blacks to register, and ordered his death. His murderers even went
through ``dry runs'' in which they rehearsed the killing, case
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   It was never intended to just frighten the Dahmer family, but to
remove a local civil rights leader who had become troublesome,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   As the jugs of gasoline crashed through the windows, Dahmer
reached for the 12-gauge shotgun and revolver that he always kept
loaded, for a night such as this.
</P>
<P>
   He told his wife to get the children outside, ``while I hold
them off.''
</P>
<P>
   But the house was already engulfed. Their two sons tumbled out a
back window to safety, but a 10-year-old daughter, Bettie, had
already been burned on her arms and forehead by the time they all
made it outside. Mrs. Dahmer said she looked up to see her husband
there with her. He handed her their daughter, then went back to the
front of the house.
</P>
<P>
   As the flames engulfed him, he continued to fire the shotgun, as
masked men flashed through the yard.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Bettie Dahmer, then 10, recalled seeing him later,
sitting outside, ``with his skin hanging from his arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He never complained,'' she said from the witness stand. ``He
just wanted to know if we were all right.''
</P>
<P>
   The flames had seared his lungs. He died 12 hours later in a
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved my chair around so that I could look at his face,''
said his widow, Mrs. Dahmer, of her husband's last moments. ``The
next thing I know he yells my name, he yells my name and fell back
into my arms,'' and died.
</P>
<P>
   Their home, car and the adjoining store were in ashes. An
elderly aunt, who had been in the store, barely escaped.
</P>
<P>
   Bowers did do prison time for his role in that violent era. He
served six years in prison for his behind-the-scenes role in the
much more highly publicized 1966 murders of three civil rights
workers, Michael Scheerner, James Chaney and Andrew Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   But he has not done time in connection with Dahmer's case. Until
his arrest last May on murder and arson charges, he had lived
modestly in a predominantly black section of Laurel, owner of a
video business.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his neighbors, apparently, did not even know he had
links to the Klan.
</P>
<P>
   But over the years, his family never stopped pushing for a
re-trial. Bettie Dahmer said she just wants his father ``to have
justice,'' no matter how long the wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
