<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-UN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN SAYS IRAQ WILL HAVE MORE TO SPEND ON FOOD AND MEDICINE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As Iraqi President Saddam Hussein continues to
defy arms inspectors and demand an end to the eight-year trade
embargo against his nation, the United Nations said Tuesday that
Iraq would have more money to spend on imported food and
humanitarian supplies this year than at any time since sanctions
began.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's recent conduct makes it unlikely that the Security
Council will want to lift that embargo anytime soon, and the money
will be less than he had sought. But U.N. members also recognize
that public support for continued sanctions would rapidly evaporate
unless the harshest effects on ordinary Iraqis are mitigated by
allowing Iraq to sell some of its oil for food and other
necessities.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council introduced the ``oil for food'' program in
April 1995, allowing Iraq to sell a designated quantity of oil
under U.N. supervision every six months. Part of the oil money is
used to compensate victims of Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, and to pay
the arms inspectors' costs.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of May, Iraq was authorized by the Security Council
to sell $5.2 billion worth of oil during the subsequent six months,
but it has only managed to sell $1.06 billion worth of oil because
of weak world demand and the damaged state of its oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, oil experts have warned the United Nations that the
country is unlikely to be able to raise more than $2.5 billion to
$3 billion during the current six month period.
</P>
<P>
   This means that if the United Nations is to succeed in its
objective of raising the nutritional value of the food ration each
Iraqi receives from the government from 2,030 calories a day in
1997 _ regarded as about the minimum for healthy living _ to 2,268
calories this year, it will need to allocate more money to food and
less to other humanitarian needs like medicine and health care.
</P>
<P>
   While two thirds of the money raised from oil sales is available
for buying food and other humanitarian goods, another 30 percent
goes into the Kuwait compensation fund and the remainder is spent
on the arms inspectors and administrative expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Because of weak oil world prices, Iraq is currently getting an
average price of only $9 to $10 a barrel for its oil compared with
$19 to $20 when it first started selling oil under the program in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But another important factor, officials say, is the time it is
taking for Iraq to order, receive and install the $300 million
worth of spare parts that the Security Council allowed it to buy
last June to repair damage done to its oil industry by the Persian
Gulf war and the trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Officials point out, though, that raising between $2.5 billion
and $3 billion by the end of November will still give it
substantially more than the $2 billion it has been allowed to earn
during each of the three previous six month periods since May 1996.
That was when Iraq finally accepted the Security Council's oil for
food offer, 13 months after it was made.
</P>
<P>
   When it more than doubled the size of the program in May, the
Security Council acknowledged that its previous $2 billion limit
every half year was insufficient to provide Iraq with the level of
humanitarian imports needed to halt the catastrophic decline in
living standards Iraqis were suffering under the trade embargo.
</P>
<P>
   According to U.N. figures released Tuesday, Iraq has imported
6.5 million tons of food and $330 million worth of medical goods
since the first shipments under the program in March 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
