<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0189 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRLINE-WAROFWORDS-CO     08-18 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-WAROFWORDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American takes off after Southwest's customers
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ American Airlines is still two weeks away from
taking off with new service between Austin and Dallas and Houston,
but already it's waging a war of words with rival Southwest
Airlines, the biggest carrier at Robert Mueller Municipal Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Aug. 31, American will offer 14 daily flights between
Austin and Love Field in Dallas, where Southwest is based. On Sept.
9, the airline will start three daily flights between Austin and
Houston Hobby.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, American mailed tens of thousands of postcards to
American frequent flier members in Austin, Dallas and Houston,
offering them 2,500 extra miles for every five segments they fly
between Austin and either Dallas Love Field or Houston Hobby
between Aug. 31 and Dec. 15. The airline's top-tier frequent fliers
are being offered additional inducements to fly the routes.
</P>
<P>
   The airline also has launched a newspaper advertising campaign
in the three cities, using the theme ``To Austin with Love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there are competitors in the marketplace, but we fully
expect to capture our share,'' said American spokes man Tim Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the airline's sales staff also is meeting with travel
agencies to let them know abut the new service, touting the
differences between American and Southwest _ reserved and
first-class seating and the broader scope of its frequent flier
program.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth-based airline currently offers jet service only
to Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport and Houston's George
Bush Intercontinental Airport, rather than the two urban-area
airports.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly 20 years, the Wright Amendment has restricted service
at Love Field, just north of downtown Dallas, to flights to and
from other Texas cities and four adjoining states _ Arkansas,
Louisiana, Oklahoma and New Mexico. The law was designed to
decrease competition for D/FW and to increase air safety between
the two airports. But last year, Congress added three more states
that can be served from Love Field: Alabama, Kansas and
Mississippi, prompting airlines like American to take notice.
</P>
<P>
   Some airline analysts said they think American will become a
major player in the market between Austin and Dallas and Houston _
a market long dominated by Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Airlines can do pretty much anything it wants to
do,'' said Edward Starkman, a director of Warburg Dillon Read, an
investment banking firm. ``It would be understating it to say they
have a strong frequent-flier base in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin has been a good market for American. With the new
service, it will have 42 daily flights out of Austin, including
nonstops to Chicago, San Jose, Calif., Miami and Los Angeles. It
also is adding daily one-stop service to New York's LaGuardia
Airport beginning Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   American's market share has steadily grown, rising 4 percent
over the past year to 27.6 percent, according to the City of Austin
Department of Aviation, and currently it is Mueller's
second-biggest carrier behind Southwest. Through July, Southwest
had 33.9 percent of the Austin market, about the same as it did a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   American officials said they must offer service to Love Field to
fend off competition. But they said expansion to a second Dallas
airport threatens the viability of 18,000-acre D/FW.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we're philosophically opposed to that, we do need to
compete,'' Smith said. ``Austin is a logical first choice.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Southwest Airlines officials say they are ready
to handle additional competition from American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southwest isn't new to competition from American or another
airline,'' said Melanie Jones, spokeswoman for Southwest. ``We
compete with other airlines in every market we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   R. Michelle Breyer writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
