A0212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION     08-18 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-INVESTIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS URGE CLINTON TO RESIGN AS STARR CONTINUES INVESTIGATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
and GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after President Clinton's belated confession
of an improper relationship with a White House intern, independent
counsel Kenneth Starr pushed ahead with his sex-and-perjury
investigation Tuesday and a handful of conservative lawmakers
called for the president to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Polls taken after the president's admission indicated most
Americans want Starr to end his inquiry. But the prosecutor
summoned former presidential paramour Monica Lewinsky to appear
again Thursday before the grand jury examining whether Clinton
tried to cover-up their relationship.
</P>
<P>
   While congressional leaders cautioned the nation against
premature speculation about the possibility of Starr notifying
Congress of impeachable offenses, House Majority Whip Tom DeLay
joined four other Republicans and a Democrat in demanding Clinton's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is bad enough that our president is guilty of having an
extramarital sexual relationship with one of his young interns,''
said DeLay, R-Texas, ``but it is much more damaging that this
president looked the American people in the eye and knowingly lied
to us.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the good of the country, and to put this scandal behind
us, the president should resign,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar calls were issued by Republican Sens. Bob Smith of New
Hampshire, Dan Coats of Indiana and John Ashcroft of Missouri. Also
urging the president to resign was former Vice President Dan
Quayle. Both Ashcroft and Quayle are considering Republican
presidential bids in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Paul McHale of Pennsylvania joined the chorus,
signaling the severity of Clinton's troubles. ``Perjury is not
excused by an apology compelled by overwhelming evidence and
delivered under pressure,'' said McHale.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``lied under oath and he almost certainly used
government resources and employment opportunities to encourage
Monica Lewinsky's silence,'' said McHale, who is not seeking
re-election this year. ``With great sadness, I have concluded that
President Clinton should resign or face impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   The calls for Clinton to quit the White House came as he and his
family left scandal-obsessed Washington for a two-week vacation at
Martha's Vineyard, an island off the Massachusetts coast.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Washington, the president sought to reassure
members of the White House staff by ``reaching out particularly to
those people who had been particularly public in their defense of
him,'' said press secretary Mike McCurry.
</P>
<P>
   The president also spent several hours on the telephone urging
congressional Democrats and party leaders to stick with him in the
wake of Monday's grand jury testimony and national television
address in which he admitted engaging in a seven-month lie about
his relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on Capitol Hill made it clear the president was
damaged goods as they struggled to find words of support. And they
worried publicly that the worst may be yet to come in Starr's
investigation of whether Clinton or his associates tried to
illegally block the grand jury inquiry or the sexual harassment
lawsuit Paula Jones filed against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``My faith in the president's credibility has been shattered,''
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., ``I'm
disappointed in not being told the truth. What he did was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., said most Democrats will continue
supporting Clinton, but ``it's not over.'' His fate depends on
``the quality of evidence'' being amassed by Starr and his team of
prosecutors, Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us are disappointed in the president's personal
behavior in the past few months. None of us approve of what he
did,'' Hamilton said. ``But I don't think that, at this point, that
the Democrats are going to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said he ``cannot
condone the relationship the president has acknowledged'' and is
``very disappointed in his personal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, the Illinois
Republican whose panel would handle an initial impeachment inquiry,
said many questions remain unanswered. Until Starr submits a report
``we simply should not speculate about how the House would
proceed,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Among those called early Tuesday by Clinton was Vice President
Al Gore, who was vacationing in Lihue, Hawaii. Gore said the
president ``showed courage in acknowledging his mistakes ... and
accepting responsibility for his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, disgraced former presidential adviser Dick Morris
spent more than four hours before Starr's grand jury recalling five
telephone conversations he had with Clinton shortly after initial
news reports of the Lewinsky sex scandal in January.
</P>
<P>
   In a Jan. 21 talk, Morris recalled in a Fox News interview, the
president said he ``just slipped up with that girl.'' In the same
conversation, according to Morris, Clinton denied lying in the
Jones lawsuit saying, ``I didn't do what they said I did, but I did
do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris, who was forced to resign from Clinton's staff in 1996 in
the middle of his own sex scandal, said he was told by Clinton that
``there would likely be gifts and messages on her answering
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinion surveys in the wake of Clinton's televised address found
about two-thirds of Americans polled calling for Starr's
investigation to end now that the president has admitted his
involvement with Lewinsky. And a clear majority do not want him to
resign or face impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News poll showed that 69 percent want the inquiry to end,
while 29 percent think it should continue. A Gallup Poll found 65
percent ready for Starr to quit the sex-and-perjury investigation
that grew out of his examination of Clinton's Arkansas business
dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The Gallup Poll found the number of people with a favorable
opinion of the president dropping by 20 points _ from 60 percent
favorability a week ago to 40 percent after his speech. But his job
approval rating remained above 60 percent. One-third of those
surveyed by Gallup said they lost confidence in Clinton as
president after his comments.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC News poll found 70 percent of Americans saying they do
not want him to resign or be impeached. A similar ABC News poll
over the weekend found 60 percent against resignation or
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
