<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0217 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-MALAYSIA-NYT &LR;      08-18 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-MALAYSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. CASE HIGHLIGHTS REPRESSION IN MALAYSIA
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A dispute between Malaysia and the United
Nations is casting light on how the Malaysian legal system is used
to stifle criticism, in this case by business interests.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general says that a U.N. human rights monitor, who
is a Malaysian, should be able to do his job free of legal
repercussions, but that Malaysia has failed to assert his immunity
before Malaysian courts, where he is facing lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia, which is expected to win a seat on the Security
Council this fall, says it wants to cooperate in ending the
impasse. The government has not objected to a recent decision by
the U.N. Economic and Social Council to refer the case to the
International Court of Justice in the Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Hasmy Agam, Malaysia's representative at the United Nations,
told the Economic and Social Council in July that his delegation
had ``deep regrets'' over the confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia has had an uneasy relationship with human rights
bodies, whether national or international. The government has been
a proponent of writing a declaration of responsibilities to match
the Universal Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the case is Param Cumaraswamy, a well-known
Malaysian lawyer appointed in 1994 as the U.N. Human Rights
Commission's Special Rapporteur _ or monitor _ on the independence
of judges and lawyers internationally.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1995, Cumaraswamy said in an interview with a London
publication, International Commercial Litigation, he had received
complaints that powerful corporations were influencing judicial
decisions in Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Cumaraswamy was quoted in the article, which also encompassed
interviews with numerous experts on Malaysian law and business
practice, as saying that a particular case under review looked like
``a very obvious, perhaps even glaring example of judge-choosing.''
But he added that he had not finished his investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Four defamation suits were subsequently filed against him by
Malaysian companies in Malaysian courts, seeking a total of about
$80 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Although action on the cases has been stayed until September,
Cumaraswamy was told on Aug. 1 that he would be billed more than
$200,000 in court costs, according to a message on Aug. 3 from Kofi
Annan, the secretary-general, to the Economic and Social Council.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups say Cumaraswamy has been forced under the
pressure of litigation to resign from a law firm he founded in
Kuala Lumpur. His predicament is not unlike that of other lawyers
in Malaysia and Singapore whose practices have been destroyed after
they took controversial positions at home and abroad. In Malaysia,
there are close links between the governing party, the United
Malays National Organization, and businesses, some of which are
owned or partly owned by the party.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of 1997, Annan and the U.N. legal counsel,
Undersecretary-General Hans Corell of Sweden, have told Malaysia
that Cumaraswamy had a ``global mandate'' to examine charges such
as those made against the Malaysian legal system and was protected
from lawsuits by international conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Malaysia was asked to inform its courts that Cumaraswamy is
immune from national suits.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Annan appointed a Canadian expert, Yves
Fortier, as a special envoy to handle the Cumaraswamy case, for
which the United Nations may be financially liable.
</P>
<P>
   Two trips to Kuala Lumpur convinced Fortier ``that the
government of Malaysia was not going to participate either in
settling this matter or in preparing a submission to the current
session of the Economic and Social Council,'' a report from the
Secretary General said on July 28.
</P>
<P>
   The Economic and Social Council, a usually quiet counterpart to
the Security Council, voted last week to ask the World Court for an
opinion. This is where the matter now rests.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights in New York, Stefanie
Grant, director of programs and policy, said the Cumaraswamy case
was important to all U.N. activities in human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``As U.N. human rights work becomes more field-based, so the
vulnerability of U.N. experts, officials, criminal investigators,
becomes much greater,'' Ms. Grant said on Tuesday. ``If you're
going to have effective discharge of human rights tasks, people
must be able to be confident that they're not going to be put in
jail or charged with some offense, either at the time or much later
down the line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
