u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASER-EDUC-NYT &LR;      08-18 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASER-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD IS EXPECTED TO BAN USE OF LASER POINTERS  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Brown has been dotted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shook out of my mind,'' said Brown, 20, of Harlem. ``I
was walking on Broadway and I looked at my pants, and I saw a red
dot. I was terrified. I was paranoid, looking around, but it was
just my friend putting one of those lasers on me.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last year, the little red dots _ emitted by hand-held
laser pointers that have migrated from the board room to the
classroom to the streets _ have been popping up on people's
clothing, on movie screens and even a few blackboards across the
country. It is called dotting, and it even made an appearance in a
``Seinfeld'' episode when George Costanza was frustrated by a dot
that kept showing up on his face.
</P>
<P>
   The people wielding the lasers say it is all in good fun, but
others see a more menacing side. Doctors say a laser trained
directly on the eye for several seconds could damage the retina.
Some people, most notably police officers, say the dots resemble
those produced by laser gun sights, making them think the red dot
is about to be followed by a bullet. Others just find being dotted
by strangers an intrusion and an annoyance.
</P>
<P>
   And while reports of injuries from the increasingly inexpensive
lasers are few, school districts across the country have banned or
say they plan to ban the pointers from classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Board of Education is expected to vote
Wednesday to join several others that already prohibit students
from using the devices, a compact, high-tech replacement for the
wooden and metal pointers common in corporate offices.
</P>
<P>
   A board spokesman said that there had been no injuries reported
yet but that officials did not want to wait for someone to get
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Jeffrey Dinowitz of the Bronx has also introduced
legislation that would prohibit merchants from selling the pointers
to minors. A similar law was passed in June in suburban Westchester
County, which is believed to be the first municipality in the
country to restrict the sale of the devices. (Officials in Ocean
City, Md., enacted a law this month prohibiting the pointing of the
laser beam at people.)
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Police Department says its officers have been
increasingly harassed by people dotting them for sport, a
potentially lethal practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because some weapons are equipped with laser-type aiming
devices, officers are instructed and trained to treat each one of
these incidents as potentially life-threatening incidents,'' said
Inspector Michael Collins, a department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the department has logged 96 incidents of officers
being dotted, with 61 people arrested for menacing, a misdemeanor
punishable by up to a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   But from the classrooms of suburban Los Angeles to the hippest
Manhattan clubs, the laser craze shows little sign of abating.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Monahan, a 20-year-old Brooklyn construction worker,
recently had some fun with a pointer with his friends at the
expense of a man sitting in a bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were driving by Barnes &AMP; Noble and we flashed the dot on
his chest,'' Monahan recalled Tuesday. ``He was looking all around,
he looked real scared and then he just ducked under the table. He
had no idea what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Damion Miles, 15, who lives in Harlem and goes to school in
White Plains, N.Y., said restrictions on the devices would not faze
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like playing with it,'' said Damion, who owns two
lipstick-size pointers. ``I like to see people's reactions. They
start looking at their clothes and they wonder where it's coming
from. Sometimes they're in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Technological advances have caused prices of the battery-powered
pointers, which are sold in office supply and electronics stores as
well as over the Internet and through mail-order catalogs, to drop
in the last year to less than $15 from more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   The devices come in various shapes, the most popular models
including pens, pointers and square ones with loop for keys. A
street vendor on Canal Street was recently seen selling them for
$8.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Williams, a Wisconsin distributor whose Internet
advertisement for the pens bills them as both fun and practical,
said he sold 400 to 500 a month, at $27 each, mostly to
adolescents. His pointers, he said, all carry warnings about aiming
in the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were obviously initially designed as an aid to teach and
for professionals who needed to point out things on a wall or a
screen and who would rather not use a long stick,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And, of course, what people discovered is that kids and older
kids _ like myself included _ like to shoot it through puffs of
smoke because you can actually see the beam. Kids play a form of
laser tag with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
