<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0222 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      08-18 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY `COMMITTED TO HER MARRIAGE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ Her eyes hidden behind dark glasses as the
first family arrived here Tuesday, Hillary Rodham Clinton for the
first time allowed White House officials to describe her feelings
about the president's disclosure of an inappropriate relationship
with a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is committed to her marriage and she loves her husband and
daughter very much,'' said Marsha Berry, the first lady's
spokeswoman, adding that Hillary Clinton is relying on her
religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``She believes in the president. Her love for him is committed
and steadfast. She is certainly uncomfortable with how her personal
life has been made public,'' Berry said. ``This is not one of the
best days of her life.''
</P>
<P>
   Berry said the first lady was misled by her husband and did not
learn what the president's testimony to independent counsel Kenneth
Starr's grand jury would be until this past weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to make some of the first lady's thoughts public
came as the president and his wife tried to put the sordid affair
behind them _ a task that may not be easy. Joined by daughter
Chelsea, the Clintons began a 12-day vacation on Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is clearly a family that has a lot of healing to do,''
said White House spokesman Mike McCurry after the C-9 Air Force jet
ferrying the entourage landed.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday is Clinton's 52nd birthday.
</P>
<P>
   The president, drained from the previous day, slept late
Tuesday, worked out and spent time with his family before coming to
the Oval Office around 11 a.m. He delayed his vacation departure
for several hours while tidying up ``odds and ends'' and calling
more than a dozen senators to discuss his situation.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said Clinton also met individually with some members of
the White House staff. ``He was reaching out particularly to those
who have been particularly public in their defense of him,''
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the president is gratified with the response to his
remarks last night. He did not expect public opinion to change
immediately but he's gratified by some indications that the
American public accepted what he had to say last night,'' McCurry
said.
</P>
<P>
   Independent public opinion surveys showed the president's
personal approval rating dropping sharply, but his job approval
ratings at more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president feels the most important thing he can
do now is spend time with his wife and daughter ``so that he can do
some repair work within his family'' and begin thinking about ``how
he reinvigorates the agenda he laid before the country in the State
of the Union address this year.''
</P>
<P>
   A suggestion that Clinton travel this week for a campaign-style
event never made it on the itinerary. However, the president may
briefly interrupt his vacation next week to make a pitch for his
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   On arrival here, aides hurriedly moved clothes, golf clubs and
tennis rackets into waiting cars. The president descended the
stairs first, pulled along by his dog Buddy. Father, mother and
daughter plunged into a friendly crowd with Chelsea, 18, leading
the way. The president appeared to wait for the first lady before
moving toward the onlookers.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry made a plea for photographers to give the Clintons their
privacy. On recent vacations, photos have been taken of the
president and first lady on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   But every where around them were reminders of the Monica
Lewinsky mess. The Clintons were greeted at the airport by Vernon
Jordan, the powerful Washington, D.C., lobbyist. Jordan has been a
target of Starr's investigation because he helped Lewinsky find a
job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of people gathered at the airport to welcome the
Clintons, including some wearing The Black Dog T-shirts from the
famous bakery and restaurant here. It was at The Black Dog gift
shop last year that Clinton, with his unsuspecting daughter in tow,
purchased gifts for Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said that on the flight from Washington to Martha's
Vineyard, the president found a bittersweet message in the New York
Times crossword puzzle. The questioning clue on number 46 down
stopped him cold: ``Meal for the humble?'' Clinton turned to staff
members and said, ``Here's one that's appropriate for today.''
</P>
<P>
   The four-letter answer: Crow.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
