<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHREBET THE MISSING JET IN PRESEASON  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Coach Bill Parcells berated his sputtering
passing unit during a demanding Jets practice Tuesday, directing
most of his attention at Wayne Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet has only caught two preseason passes, none during the
Jets' embarrassing 33-0 loss to the Baltimore Ravens on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Chrebet has caught 208 passes in three seasons,
Parcells wonders how he will do as a full-time starter teamed with
Keyshawn Johnson in a two-receiver set.
</P>
<P>
   During training camp, Parcells has repeatedly said that there
would be more pressure on Chrebet as a starter. Chrebet is split
wide much of the time, while much of his early success came when he
lined up in the slot and became a spectacular underneath receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to give him the opportunity and we will see,'' said
Parcells, who is concerned that the Jets' receivers had trouble
getting free against the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   More important, Parcells knows that if opposing defenses sense
that the passing game is weak, they will gang up on Curtis Martin,
the premier running back who was the showpiece of the off-season
restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other teams are going to try to gang up on Curtis and see
if we can go outside,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells halted Tuesday's practice when his offense was not
working well. He punished the players by sending them to the next
field, 100 yards away and over a slight hill, at a gallop. Then
they trotted back.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before one pass play, Parcells shouted at Chrebet. Players
lined up. Chrebet dashed for the right sideline 35 yards downfield
and dived for a Glenn Foley pass. Cedric Donaldson grabbed Chrebet
by the ankles, but the receiver managed to hold on to the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Panting, Chrebet ran back near the huddle, expecting to sit out
the next play. Suddenly, Parcells bulled his way into the huddle
and chased away wide receiver Alex Van Dyke. He told Chrebet to get
back in.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the play called for Chrebet to charge down the right
sideline. This time, diving again, he caught a sideline pass.
</P>
<P>
   Before practice, Chrebet said he was not concerned about not
getting the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read anything into it,'' he said. ``It's just a matter
of getting the timing down.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year in the off season, Chrebet spent considerable time
working out with Neil O'Donnell at a high school field and at the
quarterback's home in Madison, N.J. This year with Foley as the
quarterback, there may not be as much familiarity between passer
and receiver. Also, Foley enjoys going deep and seems to seek out
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet, whose contract is up after this season, contended that
he is not concerned about ongoing talks between his agent and the
Jets. He also said that the offense didn't ``pull a lot out of the
arsenal'' against the Ravens. Thus, there weren't too many chances
for the receivers, although three passes were thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   Strange as it may sound, Parcells has real concerns about the
running game. There is a new quarterback, a new receiving tandem,
new fullbacks and a tight end corps he is not in love with. He has
tried to put in place sure-hands people, but if the offense can't
get together on a passing attack, the running game will suffer
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   So Parcells kept the receivers after practice this morning
working on their routes. Despite the addition of Martin, the most
significant acquisition of a rising star in recent Jets history,
the ground game could be groundless if the Jets do not have a
receiving threat to counterbalance the defense.
</P>
<P>
   Chrebet has been such a popular player that his No. 80 jersey
outsells San Francisco's Jerry Rice and Johnson's. Indeed, in the
first six months this year, helped by the change to the original
Jets logo, Chrebet jerseys outsold everyone else's in the National
Football League except Green Bay's Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
