<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0224 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-RDP-ART-2NDTA     08-18 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RDP-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: and elsewhere.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Assorted characters who had faded from Clinton's long-running
political drama abruptly reappeared on the stage. Dick Morris, once
Clinton's most valued political adviser, testified for nearly five
ours at the federal courthouse here.
</P>
<P>
   Morris resigned during the Democratic National Convention in
August 1996, after it was disclosed that he had conducted an affair
with a prostitute. Starr's decision to call him to the federal
courthouse on Tuesday provided a sharp counterpoint to Clinton's
plea Monday night to turn away from seamier aspects of political
life.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Jones, whose sexual misconduct lawsuit against Clinton led
to the Lewinsky investigation, issued a rare public statement on
Tuesday. ``It is very important that Mr. Clinton and other men like
him learn that what Mr. Clinton did to me was wrong and that there
are consequences to taking advantage of other people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Jones claimed in her lawsuit that in 1991, when he was
governor of Arkansas, Clinton lewdly propositioned her in a Little
Rock hotel room. Clinton denied the accusation, but during his
deposition in the suit in January he was asked whether he had a
sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   He denied such a relationship under oath, unaware that Starr had
already begun investigating whether he had tried to obstruct
justice by covering up his ties to Ms. Lewinsky. Starr added the
possibility that Clinton committed perjury to his list of possible
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' lawsuit was dismissed by a federal Judge in Little
Rock on April 1, but she is appealing the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Mr. Clinton's lack of remorse for his
wrongdoing shows why it is so important that the trial court's
decision in my case be reversed,'' Mrs. Jones said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While he admitted in his testimony on Mondayto ``inappropriate,
intimate physical contact'' with Ms. Lewinsky, Clinton argued that
he had not committed perjury in the Jones deposition, lawyers
familiar with his sealed testimony said. The president said that
the type of contact he had with Ms. Lewinsky did not fit the
definition of sex used by the Jones attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``While my answers were legally accurate, I did not volunteer
information,'' the president explained in his speech on Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   About mid-way through the questioning, Clinton lost his
notoriously volcanic temper at a question posed by one of Starr's
prosecutors. Shortly afterward, there was a break in the testimony
for nearly one hour while Clinton huddled with his lawyers in the
doctor's office on the ground floor of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   While they talked, an electronic system maintained by the Secret
Service that tracks the president's movements showed that he had
gone to the doctor's office, raising concerns among White House
staff members that he had fallen ill.
</P>
<P>
   Morris testified on Tuesday for nearly five hours about five
conversations he had with the president in January, after the
Lewinsky accusations were disclosed. Although Clinton publicly
distanced himself from Morris after Morris' relationship with a
prostitute was disclosed, the White House has acknowledged that
they have talked from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Morris appeared Tuesday night on Fox News, where he said that on
the morning of Jan. 21, the day the Lewinsky matter became public,
the president had acknowledged that `'something'' had occurred
between him and Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Morris said the president told him, ``I just slipped up with
that girl.'' But Morris said the president denied that he had urged
Ms. Lewinsky to lie under oath. ``I didn't do what they said I
did,'' Morris quoted the president as saying. ``But I did do
something.''
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Morris said that he conducted a poll, and found
that people were inclined to forgive the president if he had
committed adultery, but that they were concerned if he had lied
under oath. ``Then they wanted his scalp,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:30 p.m. that night, Morris said he called the president,
and told him, ``Mr. President, if they feel that you lied under
oath, and they feel that you suborned perjury in any way, you're
cooked. They want you out.'' He said he added, ``Forgiveness won't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded, ``Well, the charges aren't true,'' Morris
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said,'' Morris continued, ``well, I think that a full
explanation of what you did with Lewinsky just won't work. I just
don't think this is going to fly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation the following day, Morris said that he
believed the president was genuinely ``remorseful'' on Jan. 21.
``He felt very badly, he felt shame, contrition, none of the things
I heard on Monday night. But he really felt that stuff. And I think
he probably wanted to go before the American people and tell the
truth, and I think that he felt that he couldn't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
