<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANELL KNOWS JETS GAME HOLDS SPECIAL MEANING  
 (JT) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Danny Kanell has read the newspaper stories
chronicling the untidy Jets quarterback situation this summer.
Kanell, whose Giants play the Jets on Thursday night at Giants
Stadium, has formed an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read the stories, and it made me feel very fortunate that
I'm in the situation I'm in,'' Kanell said Tuesday at Giants
training camp. And, Kanell credited Coach Jim Fassel with keeping a
quarterback controversy out of the mix of the Giants' camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played the position,'' Kanell said of Fassel, who was a
college and pro quarterback. ``He knows how emotional it can be to
go through something like that, and he knows the distraction it can
cause. He knows how important it is to avoid all that, and he's
done a good job making things go smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell was asked if he had wondered what it would be like to
play under Bill Parcells, the Jets' coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would probably be totally the opposite _ different
styles,'' Kanell said with a wide grin. ``But they've both won.
Coach Fassel can be demanding, too. He looks quiet, but he knows
when to turn it on. He talks to you. He doesn't have to yell at
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year, he has tried to make things calm for me in the
off season and in training camp. And I'm very thankful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell is one of the few Giants to acknowledge that Thursday's
game carries a special meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I think we do care who wins _ as much as
the fans do,'' he said. ``You'll probably see a few more scuffles
on the field than you'd see in a regular preseason game. People
talk about bragging rights, and for the players there's something
to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know their players pretty well. We'll see them at
appearances and see them around the city. You don't want to have
them talking about their win in this game all year.''
</P>
<P>
   One other Giant, safety Sam Garnes, has openly embraced the
game's significance. Garnes grew up in the Bronx as a Jets fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a midseason game to me,'' he said. ``I'll bet it is
for them, too. We both looked bad in our last preseason game, and I
expect both sides will come out swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   A sore shoulder has kept Garnes out of the first two preseason
games. He is expected back for the Jets game. ``I can't wait to hit
somebody, and hitting someone in a Jets game is even better,'' he
said. ``It's that kind of game around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, meanwhile, has done little to hype the match. ``It's
good for New York football,'' he said. ``And I know it's not just
like any other preseason game because we're playing the other team
in New York. I would venture to say that both teams will play with
more intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I walk around New York, the teams people bring up to
me are Dallas, Washington, the Eagles. No one brings up the Jets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
