<SLUG> BC-TEN-PILOT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS NEXT FOR TEEN-AGER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ When Lleyton Hewitt failed to draw Pete
Sampras in the opening round of the Australian Open last year, he
conceded that he was disappointed. Maybe his eagerness was a matter
of impetuous youth, since Hewitt was 15 years old at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, this past January, Hewitt was ecstatic when he was
matched against Andre Agassi in the semifinals of the Australian
Hardcourts Championships in his hometown of Adelaide, where he was
a wild card. Ecstatic but not overwhelmed, Hewitt upset Agassi _
whose picture he has hanging on a wall at home _ and then his
compatriot Jason Stoltenberg in the final.
</P>
<P>
   That not only sent Hewitt's hometown fans into a frenzy but also
made him _ at 16 years 10 months _ the third-youngest player after
Aaron Krickstein and Michael Chang to win an ATP tournament and, at
No. 550, the lowest-ranked one ever to do so.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Hewitt, now 17 and ranked 151st, will get his
chance to play Sampras, in the second round of the Pilot Pen
International here at the Connecticut Tennis Center. Hewitt, the
youngest player on the ATP Tour, earned the opportunity to play the
top-seeded Sampras when he beat Sargis Sargsian by 6-3, 6-4 on
Tuesday. Sargsian, who was born in Armenia, was the 1995 National
Collegiate Athletic Association singles champion as an all-American
at Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Hewitt to refocus on Sampras. ``It
should be a good experience,'' said Hewitt, who has an 8-7 record
on the ATP circuit. ``I'll just try to play my best, stay relaxed
and try to stay aggressive. There's no pressure on me because I
have nothing to lose, and he's got everything to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
