<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NY     08-18 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PROCTER &AMP; GAMBLE CALLS INTERNET MARKETING SUMMIT
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ohio)   (af)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An advertising behemoth is gathering hundreds of
executives for a one-of-a-kind conference with an ambitious goal:
improving the Internet as a marketing medium by hastening the
discovery of solutions to the panoply of problems that now vex
cyberpeddlers.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which begins Thursday, stems from the increasing
frustration of its sponsor, Procter &AMP; Gamble Co., at what is widely
perceived as the poky pace of efforts to eliminate the difficulties
confronted by marketers using online media to pitch products.
</P>
<P>
   P&AMP;G spends $3 billion a year on advertising but has been
recently spending only $3 million a quarter on interactive ads.
</P>
<P>
   The conference is significant because P&AMP;G _ the packaged-goods
powerhouse that sells such omnipresent brands as Tide detergent,
Crest toothpaste and Bounty towels _ is considered a leader among
mainstream marketers in such realms as building brands, developing
products and cultivating longterm relationships with agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that if you get a call from a Procter &AMP;
Gamble, you're going to pay attention,'' said Wenda Harris Millard,
executive vice president for marketing and sales at Doubleclick in
New York, a Web advertising network.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buzz among Internet companies is `Are you going?''' said
Ms. Millard, who was invited to attend. ``Nobody even says `To
what?'''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she would indeed go, Ms. Millard replied, laughing,
``Have you ever heard me so excited about going to Cincinnati in
August?''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is significant for another reason: P&AMP;G's well-known
reputation for media innovation. Indeed, the company's early
enthusiasm for radio was so ardent that soap operas still bear that
name in tribute to their initial sponsor's brands of soap and soap
flakes like Ivory, Oxydol, Duz and Dreft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very savvy move on P&AMP;G's part because it puts a company
that carries an immense amount of weight at the forefront of an
evolving medium,'' said Evan Neufeld, practice director for online
advertising at Jupiter Communications, the Internet consulting
company in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Neufeld, who is scheduled to address the meeting, said: ``P&AMP;G is
telling us `We know this is important, but if you want our money
you have to be part of the solution and not part of the problem.'
Three years from now, we might look back and say that it all began
to make sense after the FAST forum.''
</P>
<P>
   His reference was to P&AMP;G's formal name for the meeting, the
Future of Advertising Stakeholders. Plans for the meeting were
announced in May at Adtech, a digital marketing conference in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If packaged-goods companies like P&AMP;G start moving ad dollars
into the Net, it could change the dynamics of all media,'' said
Chuck Martin, who was the chairman of the Adtech conference and has
written books about interactive marketing including the forthcoming
``Net Future: The Seven Cyber Trends that Will Drive Your Business,
Create New Wealth and Define Your Future'' (McGraw-Hill, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   The meeting is set to discuss the impediments to such
investments of ad dollars. They range from inconsistent standards
of measurement to incomplete data on effectiveness to infighting
among the advertisers, agencies and media.
</P>
<P>
   Some who will attend the meeting say they hope the agenda will
be expanded beyond those concerns. They note that 50 years after
Milton Berle first put on a dress, the ratings system that measures
television audiences remains fiercely disputed _ but that has not
kept TV from becoming the biggest ad medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are trying to get the Holy Grail of all media
measurement from the Web,'' said Chan Suh, chief executive of
Agency.com, an interactive agency in New York, who is to
participate in a panel on Friday. ``But it's so 1996 to fixate on
that. I hope we can get out of the meeting not only a `state of the
nation,' but also where we go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Topics to be considered at the meeting are to include
measurement standards, advertising formats like banners, consumer
acceptance of online advertising (including privacy issues) and
making online media easier to buy.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the executives mentioned above, P&AMP;G invited to
the meeting about 400 representatives of such companies and
agencies as AT&AMP;T Corp., Clorox Co., Coca-Cola Co., Kraft Foods unit
of Philip Morris Cos., Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., McDonald's Corp., Modem
Media.Poppe Tyson unit of True North Communications, Ogilvy One
Worldwide unit of WPP Group PLC and Unilever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Industry conferences are always for the usual suspects,'' said
Rich LeFurgy, chairman of Internet Advertising Bureau in New York,
which represents more than 300 cyberplayers. ``This will be the
unusual suspects, and that in and of itself is very important.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The news here is that this is the first time within the
Internet industry that traditional advertisers, online media
companies, interactive agencies and service infrastructure
companies are coming together,'' said LeFurgy, who plans to attend
the meeting. ``It's an opportunity for us all to check our agendas
at the door and speak to the higher good of advertising on line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
