<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0239 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-1STL     08-18 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: the world.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said Clinton's political standing
has been so badly weakened that he lacks the credibility to press
for legislation like an overhaul of the campaign finance system.
``Moral authority is needed to pass legislation like that,''
Thompson said. ``You need a president to be able to put some fear
of the Lord in your constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks of most top Republican leaders in Congress were
unusually tame. Aides to some of those lawmakers said that
Clinton's actions spoke for themselves, and they were taking care
not to appear overly partisan, given the possibility of impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Starr's pending report to Congress, House Speaker
Newt Gingrich said, ``My deepest belief is that all of this is part
of a much bigger story, and we have to wait until the report is in
before we make judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott admonished Clinton for ``the
pain he has caused his family, his friends, his supporters and the
American people since January.'' But he cautioned that he would
wait until Congress reviewed Starr's report and then decide ``if
further action is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, which would handle any initial impeachment inquiry, said
many questions remain unanswered and until Starr has submitted a
report, ``we simply should not speculate about how the House would
proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   But other prominent Republicans were particularly harsh in
denouncing Clinton. House Majority Leader Dick Armey said Clinton
``has brought shame to the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   And House Majority Whip Tom DeLay was one of a handful of
Republicans who urged Clinton to resign, declaring, ``This
president looked the American people in the eye and knowingly lied
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Gov. John Engler, a Republican, said Clinton ``is going
to be a very weak and forlorn figure _ I don't think he's in a
position to be laying down terms with the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   While some Democratic challengers were reluctant to criticize
Clinton, Tim McCown, who is running for a House seat in Maryland,
was not bashful. He called for the president's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not the sex thing,'' McCown said. ``That's between Bill
ad Hillary. It's the honesty thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, said he hoped that Clinton could put
the scandal behind him but he was worried that Republicans ``will
not be happy unless they put the president in stocks or have some
kind of public flogging for his sins.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the worries of disillusioned Democrats, a dozen or so
state party chairmen insisted Tuesday that they would still welcome
Clinton in their states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton is welcome to come to this state anytime he wants
to,'' said Ohio Democratic Party chairman David Leland. ``He'll be
a grand boost for our candidates. People will remember this man for
the good times, not his personal problems for which he
apologized.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arkansas Gov. Mike Huckabee, a Republican who is a former
Baptist preacher and is seeking re-election this year, said he was
thrilled that Clinton campaigned in his state recently. ``I can say
I'm glad he was campaigning for my opponent and not for me,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those aren't pictures I would put in my campaign literature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
