</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL'S EARNINGS SURGE; PC MAKER SAYS IT TRAILS ONLY COMPAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y., Calif.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Defying the inventory glut and macroeconomic woes
that have waylaid its competitors, Dell Computer Corp. reported a
62 percent gain in earnings for its second fiscal quarter Tuesday,
exceeding Wall Street analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The computer maker, based in Round Rock, Texas, also announced
another stock split.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dell cited market research showing that it had
moved into the No. 1 position in the United States in desktop
computer sales, and the No. 2 place over all, behind Compaq
Computer but ahead of IBM and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
   But while those companies' PC operations have struggled to
maintain profitability in a tough retail environment, Dell gained
market share during the quarter while also improving its profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of Dell's strength, its revenue in the troubled
Asia-Pacific region grew 34 percent, compared with the similar
quarter a year earlier, even as most companies were reporting
double-digit declines.
</P>
<P>
   Dell officials attributed the earnings to the strength of their
direct-sales system, in which the company bypasses distributors and
dealers and builds each computer to order. Because Dell holds very
little inventory, it takes advantage of lower component costs and
is always selling a fresher product, which can command a higher
profit margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Dell market _ the right time, right place, right
customer,'' said Seymour Merrin, president of Merrin Information
Services, a PC industry consulting firm in Mountain View, Calif.
``Everybody else is not really coming to the table with the right
pricing and the right stuff. Virtually all of the more
sophisticated buyers today are buying from Dell.''
</P>
<P>
   The company announced its results after the market closed. Dell
ended regular NASDAQ trading at $109.5625, down $1, but in
after-hours trading it moved as high as $114.25. Dell announced a
2-for-1 stock split, its sixth in six years.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Aug. 2, Dell reported earnings of $346
million, or 50 cents a share, fully diluted, up sharply from $214
million, or 29 cents a share, in the similar period a year earlier.
The per-share figures reflected a decrease in the number of shares
outstanding. Revenue rose 54 percent, to $4.33 billion, from $2.81
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call had expected Dell to earn 46
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the core, we were able to use the structural advantage of
the Dell direct model along with our great velocity to gain market
share,'' Tom Meredith, Dell's chief financial officer, said. ``We
believe we are now significantly larger than the No. 3 and 4,
I.B.M. and HP. It wasn't just a matter of gaining market share; it
was a matter of gaining market-share profitably.''
</P>
</TEXT>
