<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 8/18/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or (212) 556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) MIDLAND, Mich. -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- TEN-DRUGS, 8-18 --
Samantha Reeves says her failed drug test was the result of an
``all-natural'' diet aid. The dietary product, it turned out, had
contained Nor-Andro 19, a variation on the classic steroid
nandrolone and one of the substances banned by the sport. ``I have
never knowingly done anything that would be harmful to my tennis
career,'' Reeves, 19, says in a statement released after her test
result was made public this summer. (Sally Washburn/Midland Daily
News Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MILWAUKEE -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- CLINTON-VOICES-3, 8-18 --
There are those who are more than willing to offer an explanation
for Bill Clinton's relationship with former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky. ``Guys cheat on their wives,'' says Tom Van Hoof,
a 45-year-old architect. ``That's just the way the world works.''
(Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) MILWAUKEE -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- CLINTON-VOICES-2, 8-18 --
Like a majority of Americans, Mary Allen does not believe the
president should lose his job because he admitted Monday that he
had a relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky
that was ``not appropriate.'' But she will never trust him again.
``He looked us right in the eye and lied to us,'' says Mrs. Allen,
shown with her husband, Jay, and children, Lee and Rex. (Todd
Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MILWAUKEE -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- CLINTON-VOICES-1, 8-18 --
In the aftermath of Bill Clinton's disclosure Monday that he had a
relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky that
was ``not appropriate,'' many Americans are disappointed in his
actions, but still feel he has done a good job as president. ``Sex
is just part of life,'' says Robin Coleman, a student at Marquette
University. ``People aren't embarrassed to talk with each other
about it.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) KAKULU, Uganda -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- AIDS-AFRICA-MILK,
8-18 -- Margaret Birungi Nannyongoi nursing her three-day-old
child, Dorothy Nalule, in the village of Kakulu. U.N. AIDS say that
women infected with HIV should consider feeding formula instead of
breast milk to their babies. ``I would never be able to feed my
baby with formula,'' says Mrs. Nannyongoi, who, like at least 95
percent of Uganda's village women, has no idea whether she is
infected with HIV. (Michael Specter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- CLINTON-LEWINSKY, 8-18 --
President Clinton adjusting a microphone for Jim Brady during a
handgun control event in the Rose Garden on August 6. The tie
Clinton is wearing was given to him by former White House intern
Monica Lewinsky, with whom Clinton admitted having a relationship
that was ``not appropriate.'' (Stephen Crowley/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- CLINTON-VINEYARD, 8-18 --
The Clintons - and their Labrador Buddy - strolling hand-in-hand on
the South Lawn on Tuesday. Seeking solitude and a respite from the
most wrenching experience of his political life, President Clinton
and his family departed Washington for a twelve-day vacation on the
resort island of Martha's Vineyard. ``This is a family that has
some healing to do,'' says White House Press Secretary Mike
McCurry. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PURCELLVILLE, Va. -- Aug. 18, 1998 --
CHAVEZ-HISPANICS-EDUC, 8-18 -- The conservative Hispanic leader
Linda Chavez at her new home in Loudon County, where her critics
say she is far removed from the experiences of Hispanic Americans
trying to carve out a life in a new land. ``I don't speak for
anyone but Linda Chavez,'' says Ms. Chavez, 51. ``I've been in the
civil rights business since 1972. I am articulate, and people are
going to come to me.'' (Michael Geissinger/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   P93QM *OME -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- ITALY-U.S.-TV, 8-18 -- CBS News,
outbidding its rivals, has contracted for the use of the Hotel
Atlante Star's terrace in the event of the Pope's death. Francesca
Mecucci, left, and her sister Roberta enjoy the prized view of St.
Peter's Basilica in Rome. (James Hill/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) STERLING, Mass. -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- LAMB-DEBATE-BOS,
8-18 -- A statue commemorating the poem ``Mary had a Little Lamb''
resides in Sterling. A century and three-quarters after the poem
was published, residents of Sterling and Newport, N.H., are still
arguing over ownership of the famous little ditty about a faithful
lamb and unwelcoming schoolteacher. (Thomas Hurst/Boston Globe
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BOSTON -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- PROFILE-HARRIS-BOS, 8-18 --
Bishop Barbara Clementine Harris, 68, at St. Paul's Episcopal
Cathedral in Boston. ``You don't set out in life to be a bishop,''
says Ms. Harris, who, before becoming a priest at age 50, spent
nearly three decades as a corporate executive. ``At least I
didn't.'' (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- MA-CELLUCCI-BOS, 8-18 --
Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci in his Boston office. A man who has
served in the State House for nearly his entire adult life,
Cellucci, 50, is renowned for his ability to dive into issues,
forge consensus, and reach resolution. ``I'm just intent on doing
my job,'' he says. ``I'm just continuing to fight for the things
that I think are important to the working families of
Massachusetts.'' (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- WHEAT-BEER-B&AMP;W, 8-18 -- From
left, Celis White has a fruity and spicy aroma, a full body, and a
spicy lemony flavor. It is gently, but not overwhelmingly tart;
Paulaner Hefe-Weizen Dunkel from Germany, a light amber in color,
has a yeasty aroma, a round malty body, and just the faintest
lemony aftertaste; Hacker-Pschorr Weisse, a Munich beer made since
the 19th century, has a light, clean, wheat aroma, a feather-light
body, and a nice tart bite throughout. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) ATLANTA -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- LOGGING-COX, 8-16 -- ``We
need to move out of the era where the primary focus was timber
harvesting and other things were secondary,'' says U.S. Forest
Service Chief Mike Dombeck during a recent interview. ``We need to
realize the land will produce water, it will provide recreation and
it will produce fiber, but timber should no longer dominate.''
(W.A. Bridges Jr./Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CAPE ELIZABETH, Maine -- Aug. 18, 1998 --
HOPPER-LIGHTHOUSE, 8-18 -- The Two Lights Lighthouse and keeper's
cottage, immortalized by Edward Hopper. Scenic but somehow forlorn,
frozen in a long-ago time, the lighthouse evokes the sense of
isolation inherent in so many of the master's classic paintings.
(David McLain/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- PETS-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-2,
8-17 -- Alternative veterinary treatment is not limited to dogs;
Spike, receives acupuncture for kidney problems. How much of this
is pure quackery? Less than one might think. Dr. Richard Swanson,
president of the American Veterinary Medical Association, says that
the legitimacy of acupuncture, at least on mammals with skeletal
structures similar to people's, was beyond doubt. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- PETS-ALTERNATIVE-MEDICINE-1,
8-17 -- Al, a greyhound with a bad back, works out with Jodi
Richard, owner of Bonnie's K 9 Swim Therapy in Manhattan. Such
alternative medical treatments are becoming increasingly popular
for pets. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) CASES-DE-PENE, France -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- WINE-TALK, 8-18
-- Chateau de Jau in Cases-de-Pene produces a light summer wine, Le
Jaja de Jau. Probably made from the macabeo grape, it has twice the
character of the thin whites sold at fish restaurants along the
Cote d'Azur. The Chateau de Jau is one of the few wineries in this
part of France that sells regularly in the U.S. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) UNDATED -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- KITCHEN-WARES, 8-18 -- No
wonder immersion blenders have been a hit with home cooks over the
last 10 years - once it became known that pumpkin soup could be
thinned to a silky puree right in the pot there was no going back.
From left, Cuisinart's Quick Prep Hand Blender, $45.99; the
Cuisinart Smartstick, $90 (also sold cordless, $82); and the
Multiquick Handblender with Chopper and Whisk by Braun, $34.99.
(David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NY2) DEER ISLE, Maine -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- PEEKYTOE-CRAB-2, 8-18
-- Maine crab pickers like Tina Gray are valued by chefs for their
skill in keeping crab meat pure. Every picker has a slightly
different routine for processing the crabs; Ms. Gray's are kept in
the water until minutes before cooking. (Herb Swanson/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) DEER ISLE, Maine -- Aug. 18, 1998 -- PEEKYTOE-CRAB-1,
8-18 -- Peekytoe crab, once a throwaway known as a mud crab, rock
crab or sand crab, is now revered by top chefs. It is caught by
fishermen like Matthew Eaton, in the waters off Deer Island. (Herb
Swanson/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
