<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0246 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-MILITARY-400&AMP;A     08-18 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-MILITARY-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH DUEL OVER ISLAM SEEMS TO FADE
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Three Turkish generals who led the military's
campaign against what it sees as the rising influence of Islamic
fundamentalism have retired or been transferred to provincial
posts, where they will presumably have little to do with politics.
</P>
<P>
   The transfers, part of a normal military rotation, have
nonetheless led some Turks to wonder whether the military will take
a lower profile in its battle against religious fundamentalism.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a four-day meeting earlier this month, military
spokesmen announced the retirement of the army's Chief of Staff,
Gen. Ismail Hakki Karadayi, who had served the prescribed four
years but whose friends had sought to prolong his active service;
the transfer of Gen. Cevik Bir, the second-ranking commander, to a
field command near Istanbul; and the appointment of Gen. Erol
Ozkasnak, secretary to the general staff, as chief of a cavalry
school.
</P>
<P>
   All three were major figures in the military-led campaign that
forced the resignation of Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan in June
1997. They accused him of plotting to undermine Turkish secularism.
</P>
<P>
   The generals then approved the new prime minister, Mesut Yilmaz,
and have continued to denounce what they describe as growing
fundamentalist influence in Turkish society.
</P>
<P>
   The military's own political influence has risen sharply in
recent years. Rivalries among civilian political factions have
weakened successive Turkish governments, and partly as a result the
military has taken on a larger role in key policy decisions. It is
principally responsible for policy toward Israel, Greece and nearby
countries. It also directs the war against Kurdish insurgents and
helps set the limits to political dissent.
</P>
<P>
   Because criticism of the military can be judged criminal, debate
over the legacy of the outgoing generals cannot be conducted freely
in public. Some Turks, however, believe they did what was necessary
to preserve secularism. Others feel they brought the military too
fully into politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd make your judgment according to what side of the
cleavage in Turkish society you're on,'' said Ilter Turan, a
professor of political science at Koc University in Istanbul.
``Secularists will tend to evaluate this as a great service to the
nation and enhancement of democracy. The more religious camp sees
it as an unsolicited intervention on the part of state elites.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Turkey's new military commander, Gen. Huseyin Kivrikoglu, and
his new deputy, Gen. Hilmi Ozkok, have served in NATO positions,
speak English and have many contacts in Western armies. The new
secretary of the general staff, Gen. Atila Isik, is less well
known.
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders have publicly rejected press reports
speculating that the incoming team might take a softer line toward
political Islam. The outgoing commander, Karadayi, asserted that
such reports ``encourage reactionary circles and lay the groundwork
for fundamentalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Western governments, joined by some Turks, have expressed
concern about the role that the Turkish military plays in civilian
politics. Perhaps in response, there have been tentative signs that
the military may be lowering its profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``The period is over,'' said Haldun Gulalp, a professor of
sociology at Bosporus University in Istanbul. ``Some people may
have said: `Take it easy. There's a limit to what we can do.'
Pressure on the civilian government has been reduced in the last
few months.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulalp said that as a sign of this loosening, a case filed
against a Muslim business federation accused of fomenting
fundamentalism might be dropped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
