<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PANEL-COX     08-18 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PANEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Opinions about Clinton-Lewinsky subject as varied as ever
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton wants his extramarital relationship
to be a debate about privacy, and while many Atlantans agree with
him, some think its a question of whether there was perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that if in fact he lied under oath, then he should be
impeached,'' said businessman Charlie Loudermilk, who voted for
Clinton's opponent in both presidential elections. ``Probably our
most most sacred tenant of justice is that you don't lie under
oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Loudermilk, who said he has never trusted Clinton's character,
chuckled and said: ``I think that dress (that Lewinsky claimed was
stained during a visit with Clinton) might go into the Smithonian
as the dress that took down the presidency of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Atlantans as equally disgusted with Clinton as Loudermilk
think impeachment would be too time-consuming. ``I think he should
resign now,'' said Mike Nance, a high school teacher. ``He could
have come a long way to retrieving (with his speech), and I'm not a
big fan, if he had been forthright and he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   `` I have to teach a course in government a week from today. I
don't know how I'm going to do it with a straight face. Can you
imagine the things kids are going to say to me?''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed. ``He needs to go,'' said Amy Covington, a
helicopter pilot. `` He could have told the truth in January, but
he went on national television and he denied it. He made a bad
situation worse by lying about it because it makes people think
what else have you lied about. As a president, you have to have
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is perfect, but I expect the president of the United
States to exceed my standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Atlantans contacted in an informal telephone survey
weren't calling for Clinton's head and seemed to agree with the
national polls that showed that while Americans distrusted the
president's credibility, the majority thought he should stay in
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I truly believe he wants to do the right thing, and I believe
he has demonstrated a fair amount of sincerity, which is what the
country is looking for,'' said businessman Roger Key. ``The country
wanted him to say exactly what he said. The country wanted him to
admit to doing some wrong, and he did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton supporters sounded a little disgusted by the whole
Monica Lewinsky affair, not wanting to know the seamy details of
the relationship and willing to write it off as a private matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in time, I don't care what he is doing in his
bedroom and let's just let it be over,'' said Jenny Morrell, a
school teacher. ``I was satisfied with what he had to say. He
didn't seem overly distraught by the whole thing but he seemed
sincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were as equally troubled by Special Prosecutor Kenneth
Starr's investigation as they were with the president's ``improper
relationship'' with a young White House intern. At the same time,
they found Clinton's admissions a low point for the country and
blamed the president for not having the courage earlier to be
candid with the country _ or at least not mislead it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he had told us earlier,'' said Tom Budlong, a librarian
and Clinton supporter. ``I still think Ken Starr should have stayed
out of his personal life. If he had done things like Iran-Contra,
where they had done things that actually hurt the country, it would
be better grounds for an investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Bills, an Arkansas native before moving to Atlanta, agreed
that Clinton shouldn't have tried running from the truth. `` I
think it would have basically been easier if he had just come out
and told the truth in the beginning,'' Bills said. ``He was being
pushed into the corner where the truth had come out sooner or
later.''
</P>
<P>
   But Budlong believed that as far as the president's evasions
went, if he had only mislead the country and the Paula Jones
lawyers about sexual improprieties, then there aren't grounds for
impeachment. He had always doubted Clinton on the Lewinsky matter
anyhow, Budlong said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always an element of doubt given his track record
with other women,'' he said. ``On the other hand, I think if you're
going to have an affair in the first place, you're not going to
tell the truth about it. Not that it justifies it, but I think that
it's typical human behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something troubling about taking advantage of the age
and power difference between him and a young intern, who is
flattered by his attentions. It was just stupid. It was a very
stupid thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bills said that Clinton deserved a second chance for a
misleading the country about an embarrassing episode in his private
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt he was sorry for it and he did regret lying and felt
bad about what he had done,'' he said. ``I can't say it was because
he got caught or that guilt was eating him up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all make mistakes.''``Even my self, if I had done something
like that, my first reaction would be to deny it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
