<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE RESULTS BEAT FORECASTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Netscape Communications Corp., the leading maker
of Internet browser software, reported third-quarter earnings
Tuesday that exceeded Wall Street estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape now gives away its browser but competes in the market
for corporate communications software and derives substantial
revenue from its Web site, Netcenter, which offers directory
services and sells advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the revenue side, they did a little bit better than Street
expectations,'' said David Readerman, an analyst with Nationsbanc
Montgomery Securities. ``They are both selling license software and
services and on the Netcenter side generating sponsorship and
advertising revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, based in Mountain View, Calif., reported its results
after the market closed. In NASDAQ trading, shares of Netscape rose
$1.8125, to $32.125.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended July 31, Netscape earned $88,000, or
break-even on a per-share basis, compared with a loss of $44.7
million, or 53 cents a share, in the quarter ended June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 10 percent, to $150.2 million. Analysts had
expected Netscape to report a loss of 2 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The results were not a direct comparison because Netscape
changed to a fiscal year from Nov. 1 to Oct. 31 from a calendar
year to better align itself with the buying patterns of corporate
customers.
</P>
</TEXT>
