<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-BANKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIXED SIGNALS FROM JAPAN ON BANK-SYSTEM OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi's government, less than a
month old, already seems to be getting mired in foot-dragging,
waffling and confusion over how to cure the sickly banking system,
a predicament it had sought to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The latest suggestion of trouble came Tuesday evening when Taku
Yamasaki, a power broker in Obuchi's dominant Liberal Democratic
Party, seized attention by telling reporters that the government
had decided to prevent the failure of any major Japanese bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``This morning, I contacted very important persons in the
Japanese government, and they said they had decided not to let
ailing major banks go bankrupt to avoid negatively influencing the
economic situation in the world, especially in Asia,'' the Kyodo
news agency quoted Yamasaki as having said through a spokesman on a
trip to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Kyodo later reported that Yamasaki's spokesman subsequently
clarified the remark, saying that measures to prevent such failures
were under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of clarification reflects the ambivalence that has
plagued Japanese policy-makers over how to repair the debt-laden
banking system, widely regarded as the heart of the nation's
economic ills. Many analysts have suggested that an orderly closing
of one of Japan's big, troubled banks would show that the
government is serious about a solution.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, foreign investors have pushed Japanese
banking stocks down to their lowest levels in a decade, an
expression of doubt on the government's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Akitaka Saiki, a spokesman for Obuchi, said Yamasaki did not
represent the government. Still, the party leader's quoted remarks
were likely to inflame debate in Parliament over six bills that, if
passed, would lead to creation of a ``bridge bank'' system to
dispose of bad loans, while strengthening failing financial
institutions to protect depositors and borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition parties, which control the upper house of Parliament,
are calling for much tougher measures, including the nationalizing
of insolvent banks and the closing of institutions with intractable
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In legislative debate on Monday, Naoto Kan, the popular leader
of the opposition Democratic Party, forced Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa and Masaru Hayami, governor of Japan's central bank, to
concede that the proposed bridge banking system was probably not
the best solution for big banks with substantial international
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshito Sengoku, chairman of the Democratic Party's planning
committee, said that it and other opposition parties were willing
to let banks fail. But he also said that some bank failures must be
prevented to preserve order in the financial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't let all banks be liquidated because that would
be chaos,'' Sengoku said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are currently pursuing an alliance with smaller
opposition parties to block the banking bills in the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   The governing Liberal Democrats hold a 12-seat majority in the
lower house of Parliament and are reportedly trying to woo members
of the Communist Party in the upper house, which would give them a
majority there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have not specified whether they intend to
allow insolvent banks to fail. But the financial markets keep
pushing for some token of seriousness. Shares of Long-Term Credit
Bank, one of the most troubled, are now trading below par value,
and many investors seem to regard the bank as a sort of sacrificial
offering the government must make to prove its commitment to
revamping the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means it has been ordered by the market to close,''
Sengoku of the Democratic Party said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also said he foresaw a system-wide panic if the bank were
to go under and suggested that instead, the best solution would be
the nationalization proposed by his party.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi has repeatedly said he is willing to adopt opposition
policies that make sense, but he has so far bided his time. The
governing party is betting that the opposition will be forced to
accept most of its proposals or risk a voter backlash.
</P>
<P>
   But Sengoku predicted Tuesday that voters would instead
appreciate that the opposition was trying to repair the financial
system while the Liberal Democrats were just trying to carry out
``the same old bad policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
