<SLUG> BC-FBC-UNT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTH TEXAS LINEBACKER OVERCOMES SETBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ Darron Hester had been an outstanding football
player out of Dallas Hillcrest High School in 1995, and once was
headed to play for Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   After a few setbacks, he signed with North Texas four weeks ago,
and for this, Hester said, he's a better man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot happen to me on my way here,'' Hester said, ``and
I'm better for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hester experienced bitter disappointments and learned valuable
lessons on his way to UNT, where less than a week into practice, he
has crept onto depth charts as a possible starter at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. 1,'' Hester said of his lessons, ``always take care of
business first.''
</P>
<P>
   It was this lack of attention to detail that almost buried him
back in Dallas three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His trek to Ohio State ended abruptly when he failed to earn the
necessary test scores. He turned, instead, to Trinity Valley
Community College, and helped them win a junior-college national
championship in 1997, despite playing with a partially torn
anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Hester played through the pain in hopes of securing a Division
I-A scholarship, and it appeared his wishes had been answered when
the University of Houston expressed interest in signing him. He had
decided on Houston only to learn Houston had decided against him _
his knee was too risky.
</P>
<P>
   Hester said he once again felt like a child peering into a toy
store from the sidewalk. ``I thought that my last chance had come
and gone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, he returned to Dallas with his transferable credits, and
went about settling into a job. It was there he stayed until UNT
secondary coach Gary DeLoach tracked him down in July.
</P>
<P>
   DeLoach had been his defensive coordinator at Trinity Valley
last season, and realized Hester's potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like he could help us out,'' DeLoach said. ``Now, he
has a long way to go. He's very much out of shape, and he's just a
newcomer.''
</P>
<P>
   He was like a Christmas present for UNT coaches, who had spent
all spring poring over linebacking depth charts that lacked depth.
Only sophomore Fred Pertile returns with any starting experience,
leaving two open linebacking spots, a half-dozen inexperienced
returners and Hester.
</P>
<P>
   Hester, a junior, said he can be an impact player at this level.
</P>
<P>
   He realizes he has gained a few pounds that need to be lost, and
that he lost a bit of an edge that needs to be regained.
</P>
<P>
   But the desire is there, maybe more so than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably knows that for college, this is his last
opportunity,'' UNT coach Darrell Dickey said. ``I think a lot of
times you go in and don't realize what you have until you don't
have it anymore and then to get another chance. He wants to do
something here at this stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
