<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0442 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAVEZ-HISPANICS-EDUC     08-18 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-HISPANICS-EDUC-ART-800&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC AND CONSERVATIVE, LINDA CHAVEZ CARVES A NICHE FOR
HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (JT)  
 By MACARENA HERNANDEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCELLVILLE, Va. _ Linda Chavez was one of the most powerful
Hispanic officials in the Reagan administration, with an
influential voice in Hispanic affairs. She even had an office in
the West Wing of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Most conservatives respected her.
</P>
<P>
   Most Hispanic advocates resented her.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Reagan era ended, many thought her power had ended.
</P>
<P>
   But more than a decade after falling from the political
spotlight, Linda Chavez has returned as a conservative leader,
urging assimilation and the use of English among Hispanic
immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, Chavez has been an adviser to Ron Unz, the
Silicon Valley millionaire who financially backed Proposition 227,
the successful California ballot measure that will put an end to
three decades of bilingual education in the state this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's public-policy organization, the Center for Equal
Opportunity, which she founded in 1995, is providing legal support
against challenges to the proposition, and is helping New Mexico
parents who oppose bilingual education in that state. She also
promotes her views in a weekly syndicated column, which is
published in 50 newspapers nationwide, including the Philadelphia
Inquirer the Chicago Tribune and the Orange County Register.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez, 51, brushes off any suggestion that she speaks on
behalf of a larger Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't speak for anyone but Linda Chavez,'' she said in an
interview at her home in Purcellville, where she lives with her
husband, Chris Gersten, who heads the Institute for Religious
Values, a public policy organization he recently founded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the civil rights business since 1972,'' she
added, trying to explain her appeal. ``I am articulate, and people
are going to come to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of her appeal, her detractors say, is the combination of
her Hispanic heritage and conservative politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``A neoconservative with a Hispanic surname makes her big
news,'' said Raul Yzaguirre, president of the National Council of
La Raza, a Hispanic civil rights organization. ``It is sort of a
man-bites-dog story. This minuscule minority of thought drowns out
the major voices in our community, and in fact we become the silent
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   In her 1991 book, ``Out of the Barrio: Toward a New Politics of
Hispanic Assimilation,'' Chavez writes of a younger Hispanic
population more likely than their parents to assimilate and to
become part of the middle class and are less likely to view
themselves as ``helpless victims of societal pressures.''
</P>
<P>
   Her critics challenge such conclusions as the flawed views of
someone who is neither bilingual nor bicultural. Indeed, one of the
most frequent and persistent criticisms of Chavez as a Hispanic
leader is her lack of fluency in Spanish. They argue that her
message of assimilation, delivered from the comfort of the Virginia
suburbs, has little meaning for millions of Hispanic Americans
carving out a life in a new land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her assimilation is apple pie and hot dogs,'' said Antonia
Hernandez, president of the Mexican-American Legal Defense and
Education Fund, which is trying to block implementation of
Proposition 227. ``Well, I am an American, and I like chili, and,
instead of apple pie, I like flan, and that doesn't make me less of
an American.''
</P>
<P>
   Abigail Thernstrom, the conservative co-author of ``America in
Black and White: One Nation, Indivisible'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 1997)
and a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute, has known Chavez
for almost two decades and counters that Chavez is ``deeply
committed to racial and ethnic equality and therefore to civil
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't take simply as a given,'' Ms. Thernstrom said.
``that because some Hispanic activists are speaking in voices
different from hers they represent Hispanic public opinion and she
doesn't.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's experiences are far removed from those of most other
Hispanic Americans. Her father's ancestors came from Spain, and her
mother is of English and Irish descent. Neither spoke Spanish. And
although she is Roman Catholic, she has reared her three sons in
the Jewish faith of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez says her politics were shaped by her years in the White
House; in academia, where her Hispanic surname prompted
administrators to assign her to teach Chicano literature; and
growing up in Albuquerque, N.M.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Rudolph Chavez, never graduated from high school and
worked in the family real estate company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linda adored him,'' said her mother, Velma McKenna Chavez, who
lives in Albuquerque. ``Anything he thought, she thought the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the family not speaking English, Mrs. Chavez explained,
``They had been here so long.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's ancestors emigrated to what is now New Mexico from
Spain in the 17th century, and have been primarily English speakers
since the 1870's, her mother said. In fact, after Chavez became
active in politics, she served as president of U.S. English, a
national lobbying group that has led campaigns to make English the
official language of various states.
</P>
<P>
   Her ancestors are like characters in a historical novel: a
great-uncle who fought, under age, in the Union Army in the Civil
War; a bootlegger during Prohibition; and a casino owner in Mexico
who was killed by his partners.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Gen. Manuel Armijo, Governor of the Mexican state
of Nueva Mexico in the early years of the Mexican War. When the
general failed to show up to fight the United States Army near
Santa Fe in 1846, it was not clear whether he had been bribed or
simply felt that the region could not be defended.
</P>
<P>
   ``He turned over the land to the United States,'' Chavez said
with a wry smile.
</P>
<P>
   When Chavez was in the fourth grade, her family moved to Denver,
closer to her mother's relatives. As an 18-year-old freshman at the
University of Colorado, Chavez met Chris Gersten. They married a
year later.
</P>
<P>
   Before entering college, Chavez had been oblivious to racial
differences, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thought to ask anybody what they were,'' Mrs. Chavez
said. ``There was no such thing as Hispanic. That was not a word.
Linda started noticing that when she went away to school. Race
became important, and I think that is when the `Hispanic' word was
coined.''
</P>
<P>
   With the raising of racial consciousness in the late 1960's,
Mexican-American students felt empowered. Cesar E. Chavez, the
civil rights leader _ no relation to Chavez _ was organizing farm
workers. Students were protesting the Vietnam War and demanding
ethnic studies programs.
</P>
<P>
   As a college senior, Chavez joined Mexican-American and black
students in demanding affirmative action programs and teaching
remedial courses for minority students. But she said the classes
became what she now calls ``political indoctrination'' camps where
minority students segregated themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Disillusioned by the experience, Chavez some 10 years later
would become an outspoken opponent of racial preferences as the
staff director of the federal Commission on Civil Rights in the
Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that I was a conservative,'' she said. ``I was a
liberal Democrat. I think it had to do with my sense of how you
succeed in life, and thinking of yourself as a victim and hating
those that have oppressed you doesn't get you anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the University of Colorado, Chavez pursued
a Ph.D. in English literature at UCLA and was assigned to teach
Chicano literature. But she found the canon limited, so she
included not only Mexican-American writers in her syllabus, but
also non-Chicano authors who wrote about the Chicano experience.
The first week, 15 students walked out on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I was more conservative than I knew,'' Chavez said,
``because I found this appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the semester, her class of 60 students had
dwindled to 15. After she failed a dozen students, she said, they
began ``terrorizing'' her, vandalizing her car and cutting off her
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Chavez, son of Cesar Chavez, took an English class with
Chavez. She tried to teach, he said, but students did not take her
seriously and threw her graded papers on the classroom floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of students who were hard on her because they
didn't feel she was, quote, `Chicana enough,''' said Chavez, who is
now a lawyer in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After three semesters at UCLA, before finishing her degree, she
packed her bags for Washington, where her husband had taken a job
with the AFL-CIO.She went to work for Yzaguirre, the civil rights
advocate, who was operating a Hispanic research and consulting
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was somewhat aloof _ it's the kindest word I can think of
_ about her own ethnicity,'' Yzaguirre said. ``Her Hispanic
ethnicity is at most genetic and not cultural.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, Chavez was hired by the American Federation of Teachers
as editor of the union's publications. Albert Shanker, the union's
president, became her mentor and influenced her views on
affirmative action and bilingual education. She began to
re-evaluate her political views while editing work by
neoconservatives like Jeane Kirkpatrick, former chief U.S. delegate
to the United Nations; Judge Robert Bork, whose 1987 nomination to
the Supreme Court raised an acrimonious national debate, and
William Bennett, the former secretary of education.
</P>
<P>
   It was Bennett who recommended her for the job on the Civil
Rights Commission. Then, in 1986, she ran unsuccessfully in
Maryland for the United States Senate. She went to work for U.S.
English, lectured, wrote and discussed political issues on a
variety of television panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always had a good sense that in Washington, people are
interested in you only because of the position you have,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She resumed a more active role in politics when conservatives in
California sought her support for Proposition 209, the 1996
initiative that barred state and local governments from using
racial and sexual preferences in hiring, contracting and college
admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez began to be compared with Ward Connerly, the black regent
of the University of California who emerged as a public figure
after strongly endorsing Proposition 209.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to view him as the black Linda Chavez,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When Unz began to draft Proposition 227, the ballot measure that
sought to end bilingual education in California, he turned to
Chavez, who spoke on campuses and wrote columns advocating its
passage. In his campaign, Unz often cited data from ``The Failure
of Bilingual Education,'' a book published in 1966 by Chavez's
center.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is one of a handful of people who really followed this
issue all these years,'' Unz said. ``The fact that she's personally
from the Latino background means that she directly or indirectly
would be able to talk to some of the parents of these children who
are being forced into the programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is pleased with the role she played in Proposition 227.
</P>
<P>
   Her next project, will be a book on feminist ideology. The
working title is ``What Went Wrong on the Road to Liberation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
