<SLUG> BC-KPMG-PEAT-MARWICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y., N.H.)  
 PEAT MARWICK TO HIRE INVESTMENT BANKER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By REED ABELSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ KPMG Peat Marwick, one of the nation's largest
accounting firms, announced Tuesday that it planned to hire an
investment banker to help it consider the sale of a minority stake
in its consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting, which brought in $1.5 billion in revenue in the
company's fiscal year that ended in June, accounts for about 40
percent of KPMG's sales.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG, which is based in New York, is contemplating selling
between 20 percent and 30 percent of the consulting business either
to an outside investor or to the public through a stock offering,
George J. Ledwith, a KPMG spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Consulting firms, in need of capital to expand, have been in a
rush to go public. Among those that have recently completed initial
public offerings are International Integration Inc. and Answerthink
Consulting Group, which is made up some former KPMG consultants.
</P>
<P>
   As public companies, these businesses can raise capital to buy
other companies and to finance the expensive computer systems that
they need to serve clients. They are also able to issue stock
options as a way to attract top talent.
</P>
<P>
   If KPMG decides to sell a minority stake, the company said, it
should be able to raise several hundred million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This initiative will permit our consulting business to fully
unlock its potential to make acquisitions to grow the business, to
make more alliances with industry leaders like Cisco Systems and
Microsoft, and to implement our strategic initiatives,'' Stephen G.
Butler, KPMG's chairman and chief executive, said in a statement.
The plan was reported Tuesday by The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG's move also seems to be an attempt to jump-start a
consulting business that some observers see as an also-ran, despite
KPMG's contention that its growth rivals that of any competitor of
similar size and scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``They desperately need to differentiate themselves in the
marketplace,'' said Tim Bourgeois, the director of research for
Consultants News in Fitzwilliam, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   If KMPG decides to take its consulting business public, it would
be the first of the Big Five accounting firms to do so. Other firms
have chosen to merge in order to pool their capital for expansion,
but KPMG's combination with Ernst &AMP; Young fell apart earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could lead to a real wave among the other four,'' said
William K. Smith, a portfolio manager for the Renaissance IPO Fund,
noting the fierce competition among the large firms. ``This is a
race. They are all looking over their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   But most of the other accounting firms say that they have no
plans to follow KPMG's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen Consulting, which has a much larger business and a
stronger brand name, insisted that it would not sell stock in its
business.
</P>
<P>
   PricewaterhouseCoopers said that it also had no plans for such
action and that it had fulfilled its capital needs through the
recent merger that created it. Ernst &AMP; Young said it considered
itself ``well-capitalized.'' Deloitte &AMP; Touche declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2241EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-METHADONE-NYT &LR;      08-18 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-METHADONE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI'S METHADONE PROPOSAL IS BACKED BY LITTLE EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It took Diana, a 34-year-old recovering heroin addict
from the Bronx, exactly 95 days to wean herself from methadone at a
residential clinic on Manhattan's Lower East Side last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I counted every day,'' she says. ``On Dec. 8, they announced I
was drug- free. It was the greatest feeling in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana's success in getting off methadone in a little more than
three months would seem to support Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's call to
move 2,000 heroin addicts off methadone at city hospitals _ an
initiative grounded in a belief that most addicts would need only
about 90 days to achieve total abstinence.
</P>
<P>
   But Diana, who spoke on the condition that her last name be
withheld, is hardly typical of methadone users. She is a college
graduate with a long work history and a supportive family. And her
heroin use had lasted only six months, compared with a decade or
more for most recovering addicts taking methadone. Even so, it has
taken her more than a year of intensive counseling, training and
therapy to feel ready to return to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   Experience at the few methadone-to-abstinence programs in New
York shows that they produce lasting results in only a small number
of methadone users and that success comes much more slowly than
city officials might like to believe. Critics say that without any
research to back it, the administration's plan amounts to a risky
experiment in drug treatment on a vulnerable population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not for everybody,'' said Ruben Medina, chief executive
of Promesa, a Bronx multiservice agency that offers
methadone-to-abstinence treatment along with open-ended methadone
programs. ``Some clients are very strong and prepared to move off
methadone quickly,'' he said. ``With others, who are marginalized
in virtually every definition of the word, you have to, in effect,
rebuild a whole human being.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's policy shift, which could take effect in as little as
two months, has drawn vehement criticism from drug treatment
experts in government and medicine who say it defies decades of
scientific research showing that methadone maintenance offers the
best hope for the vast majority of recovering heroin addicts. Of
those who stop using methadone, they say, more than four out of
five relapse within months, often with deleterious physical,
psychological and social effects.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has characterized open-ended methadone treatment as an
exchange of one chemical dependency for another, and he has said
that the city would be doing addicts a disservice if it did not
urge them to free themselves of both heroin and methadone.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration's plan is based on the city's
experience with a methadone-to-abstinence program at Kings County
Hospital in Brooklyn that treats about 50 patients a year, Dr. Luis
Marcos, president of the Health and Hospitals Corp., said.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which lasts 6 to 12 months, is offered alongside a
larger methadone maintenance program that treats 700 people a year
at the same hospital and would be closed under the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   Under the city's plan, said Marcos, those weaned from methadone
in an average of 90 days would receive counseling afterward,
including referrals to so-called drug-free communities and other
rehabilitation programs.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Marcos was unable to provide data on the rate
of relapse among patients. ``We haven't done any scientific
studies, with controlled experiments and so forth,'' the
spokeswoman, Jane Zimmerman, said. ``We're a public hospital
system. We don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Stephen Zukin, director of clinical and services
research at the National Institute on Drug Abuse, part of the
National Institutes of Health, said he knew of no rigorous studies
of such methadone-to-abstinence programs. He cautioned that such
research ought be done in small numbers, not ``by mayoral decree''
affecting hundreds or thousands of patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Vincent Dole, a retired professor at Rockefeller University
who in the early 1960s first promulgated methadone maintenance as a
treatment for heroin addiction, called the Giuliani
administration's plan ``a radical experiment with no research or
background and certainly not with the informed consent of any of
the subjects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
