<SLUG> BC-CANON-PRINTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANON OFFERS 5 NEW HIGH-SPEED PRINTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Welcome another entrant to the free-for-all that
marketing copiers and printers has become.
</P>
<P>
   First Hewlett-Packard Co. weighed in with printers aimed at the
Xerox Corp.'s market for high-speed corporate applications. Then
Xerox aimed at Hewlett in the household printer market.
</P>
<P>
   Now Canon USA has roared in with five high-speed printers and
copiers that it says will grab $1 billion in sales, or 20 percent
of the high-speed corporate market, by the end of the year 2000.
Lest anyone doubt whose market that is, Canon's publicity slogan is
``X will no longer mark the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken Xerox on as we never have before,'' Robert Bryson,
an executive vice president of Canon, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Canon's high-speed products are destined for central
reproduction departments, print-on-demand applications and pay for
print customers like Kinko's.
</P>
<P>
   They include color printers, a printer/copier/scanner hybrid
that can hook into computer networks, and a black-and-white copier
that Canon says will serve as an introduction to customers who will
later trade up to color copiers.
</P>
<P>
   Canon developed the higher speed products specifically for North
American customers, who typically copy five times as many pages as
their Japanese counterparts. Analysts applaud the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These new products are exactly what Canon needs to make it in
the exploding color printing and copying market,'' said Theodor J.
Kundtz, an analyst with Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, which will introduce a new black-and-white copier
Wednesday, is not worried. ``These are me-too, follow-the-leader
products,'' said Jeffrey J. Simek, a Xerox spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders see it that way too. ``Canon is trying to make up for
lost time,'' said Frank Cannata, editor of The Cannata Report, an
information technology newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   That is a bittersweet role for Canon. Canon was one of the first
to offer color copiers, and to connect them to computer networks.
And, it was one of the Japanese companies that pushed Xerox out of
the low-priced copier market in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But this decade, while Xerox developed corporate accounts, Canon
focused on lower-speed machines, and on making printer engines for
other manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Canon's new products do fill vacant niches. Its $50,000
24 page-per-minute copier fills the gap between Xerox's $38,000
nine page-per-minute product and Canon's $74,000 31 page-per-minute
product.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inventing a new, mid-to-high end market,'' said Mason
Olds, a Canon assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching that market will not be easy, in that Canon's sales
force does not have the same long-time relationships with corporate
customers that Xerox has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canon will have to pay a lot more attention to independent
distributors,'' Cannata said. ``Don't underestimate Canon's
commitment, but Xerox doesn't have much to worry about for now.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
