<SLUG> BC-KORN-IPO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEEKING TO EXPAND, KORN FERRY FILES FOR INITIAL PUBLIC OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Korn Ferry International, the giant executive search
firm, has filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission for an
initial public offering, the proceeds of which it plans to use to
expand its business.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is based in Los Angeles, expects to raise
about $230 million from the offering to repay debt, redeem
preferred stock, expand to the Internet and make acquisitions,
according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO would be the latest recent public offering or planned
stock sale by a professional services firm, including one by
another large executive recruiter, LAI Ward Howell, which went
public last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do, in general, tend to see companies from one industry
file close together,'' said Ken Fleming, a research analyst with
the Renaissance Capital Corp. ``One company sees that the
environment may be favorable and the same factors are going to be
affecting other companies in that area.''
</P>
<P>
   In the filing, Korn Ferry said its objective is ``to expand its
leadership position as a preferred global executive search firm by
offering a broad range of solutions to address its clients'
management recruitment needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has more than 380 consultants in 71 offices in 41
countries. It had revenue last year of $315 million, a 16 percent
increase from the year earlier, but net income declined 41 percent
to $5.2 million, according to the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the executive search business is booming because of a
strong economy and corporations' emphasis on casting a wide net to
fill top posts instead of simply filling them from within.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, revenues for the top 10 firms grew by 23 percent last
year, according to Hunt-Scanlon Advisers, publisher of Executive
Search Review newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the industry has become more competitive as clients
demand more for their money. That has forced firms to look for ways
to expand, which, of course, requires cash. And in an industry with
a high turnover rate, firms that can offer stock and options may
have an advantage to lure the best talent.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Korn Ferry has ventured into the
equity markets. The company first went public in 1972, but it was a
much smaller business with thinly traded and volatile shares.
</P>
<P>
   Its founders, Lester Korn and Richard Ferry, found the swing in
the stock price distracting and later repurchased the shares and
took the firm private.
</P>
<P>
   Korn Ferry now wants to be traded as KFY on the New York Stock
exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0452 </DOCNO>
