<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No. 200 doubly fun for Maddux
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On paper it was a typical Greg Maddux performance.
Nothing fancy, just another efficient win.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this one was special.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitcher in baseball won his 200th game Tuesday night as
the Braves beat the San Francisco Giants 8-4 in their return to
Turner Field after a West Coast road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux won his 16th of the season and lowered his ERA to 1.65 as
the Braves continued to beat up on the Giants this season, winning
for the seventh time in eight meetings.
</P>
<P>
   All nine of the Braves' hits were doubles, the most two-base
hits in a game by Atlanta since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants gave Maddux some trouble early, but it was the result
of some sloppy play in the field and an uncharacteristic wild pitch
by the Braves starter that let in a run. Maddux went seven innings
and gave up five hits and two runs, one earned, while walking three
and striking out six.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Maddux, the show belonged to outfielder Gerald Williams,
who again made a case for more playing time. Williams doubled twice
in his first two at-bats, scoring both times.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Giants center fielder Ellis Burks made one
of the best catches of the season. With Williams at third, Andres
Galarraga drove a ball to deep center that Burks tracked, then
leaped for right before the fence, his glove at the top of the
wall. Burks made the catch, crashing his head into the wall and
falling to the ground. He later had to leave the game because of
dizziness.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves scored two in the first off Giants left-hander Kirk
Rueter. Walt Weiss led off the inning with a double and scored on
the two-base hit by Williams, who would come home on Galarraga's
sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants closed within one in the third when Marvin Benard
made it to second on a double error by Braves second baseman Tony
Graffanino. Benard went to third on a groundout and scored on a
wild pitch by Maddux, who got to the plate to retrieve the throw
from catch Eddie Perez but applied the tag too late.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pushed ahead by two again in the third when Chipper
Jones brought in Williams on a double. The Giants scored their
second run in the fifth when, with two out, Jeff Kent lined a ball
into left and Rueter was waved around third. The throw from Danny
Bautista was strong but it short-hopped Perez and Rueter was safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves then put it away in the next two innings, on a
two-run double by Bautista in the sixth, then a bases-loaded double
by Perez in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
