<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-SIDEBAR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charlton's past not an issue with Braves
 &HT;    By Michael Lee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Recently acquired reliever Norm Charlton arrived in
Atlanta this week for the first time since being called up last
Tuesday from Class AAA Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting settled in, Charlton is living in a hotel. His
locker, though loaded with shoes and home uniforms, doesn't even
have a name above it yet.
</P>
<P>
   All that could change soon. Especially if he could return to the
form that made him one of the ``Nasty Boys'' as a member of the
world champion Cincinnati Reds in 1990 and an All-Star in 1992. But
not, however, if he remains the pitcher whose career has taken a
dip since helping the Seattle Mariners to their first playoff
appearance in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we brought him here is because he does have a lot
of experience, he's been through the wars. If we can get him back
on top of his game, he can be an asset to us,'' general manager
John Schuerholz said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlton has seen little action since Atlanta signed him Aug. 5,
eight days after he was released by Baltimore, where he went 2-1
with no saves and a 6.94 ERA. In 35 innings, he gave up 36 hits and
27 runs, while striking out 41.
</P>
<P>
   Last season with the Mariners, Charlton made a career-high 71
appearances but was 3-8 with a 7.37 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   He's thrown just three innings in his time in Richmond and
Atlanta combined. In his Braves debut last Wednesday against San
Diego, Charlton pitched one inning, allowing one run on two hits
and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't as prosperous as I wanted,'' Charlton said, ``but
I'm looking forward to the second (outing).''
</P>
<P>
   And an opportunity to contribute to the Braves' stretch run. The
last time Charlton was released in the middle of the season was
1995, when the Phillies gave up on him. He went on to record 14 of
15 save opportunities for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to be released by Baltimore, (but) I'm
actually kind of happy to get out of there,'' Charlton said. ``This
is the place I wanted to be. Obviously, it's good to be on a team
that has a chance to go to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Leo Mazzone downplayed Charlton's past, good and
bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doesn't matter if you're a veteran or a young'n. It matters
how you throw the baseball,'' Mazzone. ``Hopefully we can get him
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
