<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS ADD SOME POWER TO SHATTER ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (story will update later)  
 (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Mets' lineup this season can hardly be
labeled a murderers' row. Going into the first game of Tuesday's
doubleheader at Shea Stadium, the Mets had hit just 91 home runs,
third fewest in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   But they flashed a good deal of muscle Tuesday as Edgardo
Alfonzo, Todd Hundley, John Olerud and Brian McRae hit home runs
off Pedro Astacio. And with Al Leiter (12-4) breaking nearly a
dozen Colorado bats with his pitching, the Mets defeated the
Rockies, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   The first-game victory pushed the Mets (67-55) a season-best
dozen games over .500 for the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the defense kept us in the game, the homers put us
in front and Al battled all the way against a very good-hitting
team,'' manager Bobby Valentine said between games.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Lopez and John Olerud provided the best defensive gems
behind Leiter, who surrendered 10 hits but allowed just 2 runs in 8
innings before Turk Wendell pitched a scoreless ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't particularly sharp,'' said Leiter, who labored
through 135 pitches in his first start in eight days. ``And I
didn't feel like I was as complete today. But any time you allow
two runs in eight innings against a Colorado team, I'll certainly
take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the game, Leiter decided to abandon his changeup and
curve and, in his words, ``resort back to what you know best,
which, for me, is hard in.''
</P>
<P>
   That resulted in a lot of cruelty to some Colorado bats _
especially the ones swung by Mike Lansing, Dante Bichette and Larry
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm right and the ball's moving a lot, I break a few
bats,'' Leiter said. ``I got three of Lansing's and Bichette a
couple of times. And Walker might've been the most mad. He might
have had a lucky bat or something. I know for him tonight it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Not nearly as lucky as the Mets' bats were for Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's second homer of the season was his first at Shea since
he hit his 30th (and last) home run on Sept. 8 last year, before
reconstructive elbow surgery. Tuesday, Hundley belted a 2-1 pitch
from Astacio into the bullpen in right to lead off the fourth and
give Leiter a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had earned it. In the top of the fourth, the left-hander
had left the bases loaded after his defense failed him. Alfonzo
began the fourth by throwing high to first on a grounder to third
by Bichette and pulling Olerud off the bag at first. The miscue was
Alfonzo's first since June 28, snapping a streak of 42 games
without an error.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Castilla followed with a double over third and just out of
Alfonzo's reach, putting two Rockies in scoring position in a 2-0
game.
</P>
<P>
   But Leiter bore back to strike out Todd Helton and retire
Lansing on a pop-up to short. After an intentional walk to Kirt
Manwaring, Leiter struck out Astacio to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the whole game,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter said: ``Three years ago, if I had runners on second and
third with nobody out, they're both scoring. Just through lack of
confidence. And that's just the difference between having a good
year and a bad year.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Rockies went 0 for 6 in the first four innings with
runners in scoring position. The Mets, meanwhile, scored in the
first on a single by Mike Piazza that scored Tony Phillips from
third. Phillips had led off the inning with a single to center,
taken second when Alfonzo was hit by a pitch, and then taken third
on a force-play grounder.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' next two runs came on solo homers by Alfonzo (his
ninth, to left, leading off the third) and Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's homer took on added significance in the fifth, when
Colorado finally broke through for a pair of runs. Darryl Hamilton
led off with a double over first, was sacrificed to second by Neifi
Perez, then scored on a double by Walker that Hundley turned into
an adventure in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, the catcher turned outfielder, had dropped a liner by
Walker for a two-base error in the first. This time Hundley chased
the high fly to the warning track before watching it plop off the
fence. Walker _ who, like Bichette, is chasing Olerud in the race
for the National League batting title _ then took third on a
groundout, before Vinny Castilla drove him home with a single. All
of a sudden, it was a 3-2 Mets lead.
</P>
<P>
   Helton followed Castilla's single with a single that advanced
the potential tying run to second base. But Alfonzo made a nice
play on a grounder by Lansing, forced Helton at second and ended
the threat. And then, in the Mets' fifth, Olerud blasted a two-run
homer (his 17th) some 419 feet to straightaway center field two
batters before McRae looped his 19th home run, a solo shot, to the
opposite field in left.
</P>
<P>
   It gave Leiter a 6-2 cushion, more than enough, it turned out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
