<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NAZI-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      08-18 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NAZI-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDANT DENIES WAR CRIMES AT NAZI CAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over 47 years, Jack Reimer, the retired businessman
who is accused of participating in Nazi atrocities, has told many
stories of his wartime experiences to many investigators _ so many,
he has maintained during four days of testimony in U.S. District
Court, that he was no longer sure of what he knew, when he knew it
and what he really meant to say.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle to pin Reimer down on his often contradictory
statements reached a peak Tuesday in his civil trial before Judge
Lawrence McKenna. Justice Department lawyers, who are seeking to
have Reimer's U.S. citizenship revoked, began a laborious
cross-examination that focused on inconsistencies in his various
accounts of what he did at the Polish concentration camp Trawniki.
</P>
<P>
   According to the government, Reimer, now a 79-year-old retired
restaurant manager, was a much-decorated officer and willing killer
who participated in the mass murder of Jews, the brutal crushing of
the Warsaw ghetto uprising and the training of guards who
terrorized Jewish inmates at notorious camps like Treblinka and
Sobibor.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer steadfastly denied that he had any knowledge at the time
of Nazi atrocities. He frequently testified about some event or
date during the war, only to say under questioning that he had no
recollection. What he knows, he often said, came from wartime
documents and witness statements gathered by the government over
the course of its long investigation.
</P>
<P>
   That Reimer worked for the SS officers who ran Trawniki from
mid-1941 to 1944 is not in dispute _ although Reimer has admitted
he does not remember if he mentioned it when he first applied for a
U.S. visa in 1951.
</P>
<P>
   Reports by U.S. military investigators at the time indicate that
Reimer did not tell them about Trawniki until a second round of
interviews in 1952. Reimer said he did not know why his initial
application listed his wartime whereabouts at two other Polish
cities that he could not remember ever visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't recall what I knew then,'' he told Edward Stutman, the
Justice Department lawyer who questioned him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are not my words,'' he added when shown the application
he now repudiates. ``Those are not my statements. They only got in
there by suggestion, by I don't know who.''
</P>
<P>
   Reimer has steadfastly maintained that he was merely a prisoner
of the Germans throughout his time at Trawniki and that except for
a brief period when he trained a group of fellow prisoners to serve
as guards for the Nazis, he spent the war as the Trawniki paymaster
and rarely left the isolated confines of the camp's administrative
office.
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey Clark, his lawyer, said the documents provided by the
Justice Department did not prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department contends that if it can be proved that
Reimer persecuted even one person during the war on the basis of
race, religion or national origin, he would be ineligible for U.S.
citizenship. Government lawyers said that whether the act was
voluntary or not, it would still disqualify him.
</P>
<P>
   At various times over the last six years, Reimer has made
contradictory statements on whether he took part in any atrocities.
One of the strongest pieces of evidence against him was his
statement during a 1992 interrogation by three Justice Department
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   He said then that he was at the site of a killing of 50 to 60
Jews at a pit outside Trawniki. But he said he overslept, arrived
late and saw only one Jew who seemed to be alive. Reimer said he
shot him.
</P>
<P>
   The story, including its most potentially damaging detail, has
evolved and shifted since then. In interviews with the news media
and in depositions, Reimer said at different times that all the
victims were dead when he arrived, that he fired over the heads of
the people in the pit to avoid killing them, and that the victims
were not Jews but Polish railroad workers.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned by Stutman on Tuesday, he said he remembered
stumbling on the way out of his barracks to the pit and was knocked
unconscious. He said he was brought out to the pit and forced by an
SS commander to shoot at the bodies inside, but that he was not
sure if he hit anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Reimer said his statement in 1992 _ that he knew he killed one
of the people in the pit _ was not true. ``It grew in me over 50
years,'' he said. ``Thinking about it, listening about it _ don't
you see how I exaggerate over the years?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
