<HEADLINE>
NETSCAPE
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - NETSCAPE  
 see  NETSCAPE: Page B8 Col. 4 
 
 j,14p10    frm  From Page B1 
  
  
 h,14p10,42   
 Netscape 
Ekes Out 
A Profit 
 eck,14p10 sw,17.3   
 Quarterly results beat 
analysts' expectations 
 ,14p10  By David Einstein 
   Chronicle Staff Writer 
   Showing signs of rebounding from a disastrous war with
Microsoft, Internet pioneer Netscape Communications beat Wall
Street expectations yesterday by reporting a token profit for the
third quarter.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mountain View-based Netscape said it eked out a net profit of
$88,000 (0 cents per share) on revenues of $150.2 million, although
it had an operating loss of $2.1 million. The net earnings exceeded
analysts' forecasts of a small loss.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Netscape lost $44.7 million (53 cents) on revenues of
$135.9 million in its quarter that ended in June. The company has
since moved its fiscal year ahead by one month.
</P>
<P>
   The results were released after the market closed. Netscape
shares gained $1.81 to $32.13 in yesterday's trading.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, which sells Internet software to corporations and
operates a popular Web site, posted solid growth in both those
businesses. Revenues from software and associated services such as
consulting grew 16 percent from the previous quarter to $111.6
million, while the Netcenter generated $38.7 million, a 24 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR; ``Overall, we are pleased with the results,'' said chief
executive Jim Barksdale. ``We're seeing strong momentum in both the
enterprise software and Netcenter businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, which pioneered the Web browser, was badly bruised in
a battle over browser market share with Microsoft. In fiscal 1997,
Netscape lost $115.5 million as the Redmond, Wash., software giant
ate into its business.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, Netscape decided to give its browser away _
matching Microsoft's successful strategy _ and to concentrate on
selling more-expensive software used by companies to manage their
intranets.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR; Netscape also embarked on a campaign to reinvent its Web
site as an Internet portal offering news, shopping, free e-mail and
financial services. The company believed its site, which is among
the most popular on the Web, could generate significant revenue
even while competing against other top portals such as Yahoo,
America Online and Excite.
</P>
<P>
   During the just-completed quarter, Netscape beefed up Netcenter
with a new look and signed several high-profile deals to obtain
content for the site. It enlisted Citibank to provide financial
services and arranged to get local content from AOL's Digital City.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings results, which were released after the market
closed, cheered analysts who had considered the third quarter
crucial to Netscape's stability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a good quarter,'' said Andrea Williams of Volpe
Brown Whelan. ``They exceeded both top and bottom line estimates.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; x  &LR; Williams said it is too early to say whether Netscape is out
of the woods, ``but there are positive indications that they're
getting traction on both sides of their business.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; uncx  &LR; ``It was what they needed to do to maintain credibility
and instill confidence in their strategy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape also announced that Adobe Systems chief executive John
Warnock has resigned from the board of directors, to be replaced by
William Campbell, chairman of Intuit.
</P>
