<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW IS TIME FOR RANGERS TO STEP IT UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American League schedule has not been kind to those
prisoners of room service, the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox haven't been so kind to them lately, either.
</P>
<P>
   Matched against a division foe who roosts two time zones and one
Disneyland away, the Rangers were scheduled to return home today
after eight days in crowded, hostile places.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was mugged. Nobody fumbled a punt in Spanish. But the
Rangers left Boston yesterday knowing their road trip could
have/should have been a lot more memorable than 2-and-6.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it does matter that the Rangers played the Cleveland
Indians, mighty New York Yankees and Red Sox to quasi-standstills.
Style points count when you're being surveyed for possible
postseason body language.
</P>
<P>
   But losses are losses. And teams with high aspirations need to
be making the defensive plays, delivering the clutch hits and
hurling the game-turning innings that make a team a champion.
</P>
<P>
   On the road trip, the Rangers were erratic on all three counts.
</P>
<P>
   And thus, here they make their pillow today, trailing the
Disney-owned Anaheim Angels and unable to salt away a division that
could have/should have been seized three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   For the next five nights, the opponents will be the Indians and
Yankees again. The home team needs to win at least three of the
five.
</P>
<P>
   Says who?
</P>
<P>
   Says Sigmund Freud, says Zonk, says anyone else who has tried to
study this team as it has treaded water this season.
</P>
<P>
   The loyal home fans _ and they have been more than loyal and
forbearing _ need to see some sign that their five-month vigil
isn't going to be in vain. They want to see this Rangers team, once
and for all, mark its own turf.
</P>
<P>
   The rumblings from the West Coast precincts are encouraging for
the Rangers. The Mariners' ship is starting to look like the Edmund
Fitzgerald. The Angels have plates spinning left and right.
</P>
<P>
   For all of their wishful talk in Seattle about mounting a
late-summer comeback, the fact is that the Mariners are still
palpably closer to having the worst record in the American League
than they are to contending for a wild-card spot. The talk in
Seattle these days isn't about playoffs, but rather when general
manager Woody Woodward is going to be lashed to the mast of the
Bremerton ferry and whether eager Mariners fans will get to see it.
</P>
<P>
   And now, it's really gotten cheeky. Assistant general manager
Lee Pelekoudas weighed in in ``The Seattle Times'' on his views
about Randy Johnson's ``resurgence'' in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to see that someone's performance can turn around
so abruptly,'' Pelekoudas told ``The Times''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Randy pitched the way he's pitching now, this team would
be in a different position.''
</P>
<P>
   This unseemly remark came in the wake of the Mariners returning
from a 5-4 road trip, a trip in which they won the first four.
</P>
<P>
   But what nerve. The reason the Mariners are double digits under
.500 is because of Randy Johnson?
</P>
<P>
   Pelekoudas even chided the big thank-you ad that Johnson took
out in the Seattle newspapers after the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thanks he could have given the fans in Seattle,''
Pelekoudas said, ``was to go out strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. Isn't this the same Seattle front office that
somehow botched deals over the last year that could have brought
them Bartolo Colon, Mariano Rivera, Andy Pettitte or Ismael Valdes?
</P>
<P>
   In Anaheim, there apparently are no botched deals. Just the
plates spinning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels responded to the Rangers' bold moves of acquiring
Esteban Loaiza, Todd Stottlemyre, Royce Clayton and Todd Zeile by
adding . . . Mike Fetters and Jeff Juden?
</P>
<P>
   With the AL West there for the taking, manager Terry Collins has
turned over the holes in the team's offense to Troy Glaus, Justin
Baughman and Todd Greene.
</P>
<P>
   But look who's in first place.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, who launch their eight-game homestand tonight,
it might be time for that speech again _ that Johnny Oates speech
about not sitting on their posteriors, waiting for new owner Tom
Hicks' money to bail this thing out.
</P>
<P>
   Another deal might yet be coming. But the Rangers are amply
equipped for the weeks ahead with the bodies and arms they have
now.
</P>
<P>
   They simply need to rise to the occasion. They need their No. 1
pitcher, whether it's Stottlemyre, Loaiza or Rick Helling, to
perform the way the Indians', Yankees' and Red Sox' No. 1s have
just performed. They need their first baseman to deliver in the
clutch the way that Mo Vaughn did last night.
</P>
<P>
   They need to come home tonight and mark their turf.
</P>
<P>
   Style points and playing the Yankees ``close'' are fine. Seizing
first place, once and for all, would be so much better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
