</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREETSMARTS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STREET SMARTS/MARK VEVERKA  
 AFTER VINEGARY IPO, GOLDEN STATE SHARES POISED TO POP A CORK 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - STREET SMARTS  Golden State Vintners has turned sour since going public last
month, but the company's first earnings report tomorrow and the
initiation of analyst coverage should give the wine concern some
legs.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock has been crushed by a moribund initial offering market
and by dour national press about the wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   But for those investors who are compelled to pick some grapes
for their portfolio (and judging by the response to an earlier
column, there are a lot of readers intoxicated with wine stocks)
Golden State certainly is in the bargain bin these days.
</P>
<P>
   After going public at $17 a share on July 22, Golden State went
sideways for three days before starting its precipitous descent.
(It had a brief pop above $18 on its first day of trading.)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Golden State shares hit the bottom of the barrel on
August 5 at $10.88, before creeping back to the current price of
$12. That's still roughly a 30 percent discount to the IPO price,
which may entice stock pickers who were interested in the company's
prospects at $17.
</P>
<P>
   The stock is poised for a modest, short-term bounce. Earnings
for the Greenbrae company's fourth quarter ended June 30 are
expected to be in line with what management told institutional
investors during IPO road shows.
</P>
<P>
   And as long as that is better than last year's numbers, the
market should be content with the news. (Of course, analysts have
yet to publish their first research reports with financial
projections on the company.)
</P>
<P>
   Golden State's slowest quarters are during the second half of
the year. The company racked up only $10 million in sales during
the fiscal fourth quarter last year, nearly one-tenth of its total
annual sales of $95.8 million. Net profit for the fiscal year was
$6.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason why Golden State shares conceivably could get a
lift is because of bullish analyst reports. Brokerage researchers,
who are required to honor a 25-day quiet period after a company
goes public, are expected to initiate coverage after the company
releases its year-end results.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, if the underwriters' corporate finance departments
thought the stock was worth $17, their sell-side analysts
(researchers who recommend stocks for brokers to peddle) are likely
to fawn over the stock at $12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  But what caused Golden State's shares to crash in the first
place?
</P>
<P>
   They fell victim to a double punch. First, timing was atrocious.
Non-Internet IPOs have struggled in recent weeks, and Golden State
was not immune to the downdraft despite lead underwriter Goldman
Sachs' support for the shares in the early go-ing.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Barron's ran a bearish cover story August 3 predicting
that a wine glut was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   The Barron's piece, which smacked the entire wine sector,
fixated on a 24 percent rise in the amount of new acres devoted to
growing wine grapes since 1991, predicting that oversupply would
lead to lower wine prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the bulls argue that Barron's failed to address the demand
side of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The article was decidedly negative in tone and unfortunately
short on facts,'' according to a research note by analyst David
Goldman of NationsBanc Montgomery Securities, which was not a
Golden State underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, ``we are in the midst of a very serious
shortage of grapes. Sure, grape supplies could increase by 9
percent or so per year over the next three years, but demand for
California (premium) wines surged at an average of nearly 11
percent'' per year during the past decade, Goldman states.
</P>
<P>
   Those issues aside, Golden State faces a perception problem. It
isn't a name brand, such as other publicly held wineries like
Robert Mondavi or Beringer. What's more, the company is a bulk
producer, which means that it crushes grapes and ages wine but
doesn't usually bottle the stuff.
</P>
<P>
   But ``bulk wine'' shouldn't be confused with ``jug wine.'' In
fact, even though Golden State doesn't possess the brand sizzle of
Mondavi or Beringer, it is a huge supplier to premium winemakers.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, it theoretically is a wine play of less risk. Golden
State is a supplier and vendor to several big wineries, some of
them publicly held. If one has a bad year, Golden State's stock
doesn't necessarily head south because it isn't totally dependent
on that customer's performance. Its risk is spread over a range of
wineries.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat Emptor: Wine stocks are not necessarily the best
investments, because they are subject to the same unpredictable
whims as agricultural stocks, meaning that Mother Nature's future
performance is difficult to forecast. In addition, vino stocks
might be best suited for people who like wine and want to learn
more about the industry by being a shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
On the Rebound
</P>
<P>
   Monday's column on the prospects of a new basketball league that
would pay players to attend college sparked enormous response. It
will be nearly impossible to answer all of readers' queries about
the Collegiate Professional Basketball League, but I wanted to
address a couple of recurring themes in some of your missives.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, as an investment, the league is a high-risk
venture for a select group of sophisticated investors. To be sure,
the financial track records for new professional leagues are
dubious at best.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, this entrepreneurial league would not supplant
college basketball. At best, it might spur positive change in the
National Collegiate Athletic Association and give kids on the
margin more opportunity to play.
</P>
<P>
   That already may be happening. In yesterday's Wall Street
Journal, an NCAA official said the organization was reviewing its
policies about letting athletes earn money while in college.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, however, the purpose of the column was to
trigger debate about changing the economics of professional and
college sports. The idea was to provoke thought and reaction. And I
believe, judging by the passionate calls and messages, that it was
a layup.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, to the anonymous caller who suggested that I
``become a comedy writer'' because he thought the column's premise
was so hilarious: I think you're pretty funny, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka &LR; sfgate.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
