<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LAD     08-18 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA COULD BUILD NATIONAL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A huge decision should be forthcoming this week from Hawaii,
where U.S. Soccer's Annual General Meeting is taking place. Oh, and
a new president, someone to step in for Alan Rothenberg if such a
thing is possible will be selected, too.
</P>
<P>
   The most visible determination concerns the new national team
coach, either former U.S. boss Bora Milutinovic or D.C. United
coach Bruce Arena, if what appears to be so is so. Milutinovic
apparently was the frontrunner until Rothenberg met with Arena at
Major League Soccer's All-Star weekend, and now sources close to
discussions report Arena appears likeliest to get the post.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news. Arena is a winner who has proven adept at
developing talent and building teams with superior talent and
chemistry, skills that would serve him well at the international
level and in whatever role he might play with regards
</P>
<P>
   to Project 2010, U.S. Soccer's plan to become World Cup
contenders in the next 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Arena, whose brusque manner has made him some enemies within the
federation, has some international experience he guided the 1996
U.S. Olympic team in a worthy showing against far stronger
competition but, most important, has won everywhere he's been. He
captured five NCAA titles at Virginia and won the first two MLS
crowns with D.C. United. And D.C. on Sunday won the CONCACAF
Champions Cup, the greatest accomplishment by an American club.
</P>
<P>
   Giving Arena the reins makes sense. He knows U.S. talent and can
begin to rebuild the squad in advance of the 2002 World Cup, using
a planned exhibition against Australia this fall and next year's
Confederations Cup in Mexico where World Cup finalists France and
Brazil are likely U.S. opponents to test his schemes and the player
pool. If, after two years, Arena hasn't done the job, it's not too
late to bring in Milutinovic, or perhaps Carlos Queiroz, to make
things right before heading to the Far East.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is primarily Rothenberg's, though Saturday when
either Dr. Bob Contiguglia or Larry Monaco is elected to a
four-year term as president he will no longer be in charge, at
least not officially.
</P>
<P>
   Contiguglia, 56, a Denver kidney specialist who chaired the U.S.
Youth Soccer Association in 1990-96, is the favorite in Saturday's
election, although Monaco, 60, a retired Washington-area lawyer and
a U.S. Soccer executive vice president, has plenty of support.
Ultimately, it may not matter who wins.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-year reign, during which American soccer has
grown from a small, struggling organization into a rich and
powerful player in world sport, Rothenberg will continue to exert
heavy influence on the game. That, no matter what criticism of his
reign may be valid, is very good news, indeed.
</P>
<P>
   A `Super' millennium?
</P>
<P>
   What sounds like a European Super League, with all the best
teams on the continent, is two years from reality regardless of
whether anybody thinks it's a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for a 32-team venture, featuring Juventus, Manchester
United and Real Madrid of Europe, are more or less finalized, with
Bayern Munich manager Uli Hoeness whose squad would take part
confirming Italian and English reports that it's a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of the European league is developed to the last
comma,'' he told weekly magazine Focus. ``Even if the German
(federation) or UEFA refuse to support it, the league will start''
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   If so, club soccer in the new millennium won't be much like it
is now, and that's not necessarily good news. The best of the best
will leave their national leagues to compete in a super Super
League, which would leave the sport's major leagues Italy's Serie
A, England's Premier League, Germany's Bundesliga and Spain's
Primera Liga decidedly minor. It could kill off some of the smaller
clubs, which would lose attention from media and fans and gate
receipts from its matches against the biggest clubs.
</P>
<P>
   There is probably too much money at stake for it not to happen.
How are these for numbers: revenues of $1.95 billion ... $57.3
million for the champion ... $22.7 million minimum to each
participant (more than Real Madrid got for winning the Champions
Cup last May) ... $1.1 billion TV package?
</P>
<P>
   UEFA, European soccer's governing body, is against the idea it
apparently plans to broaden its Champions League and combine the
Cup Winners Cup and UEFA Cup in response but Hoeness insists it
will happen whether UEFA, and by extension FIFA, approves. That
could lead to a schism in world soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The details: Sixteen teams would be permanent participants with
the remainder of the field filled in qualifying, and the competing
squads would cease playing in their national leagues. Two other
tournaments the ProCup and an unnamed event would replace the Cup
Winners Cup and the UEFA Cup. Among the names of those involved:
former Italian premier Silvio Berlusconi (owner of AC Milan),
Dodgers' owner Rupert Murdoch and German magnate Leo Kirch.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 ``permanent'' teams, according to Italian magazine
Tuttosport (which is owned by the same people who own Juventus):
Juventus, Inter Milan and AC Milan (Italy); Arsenal, Liverpool and
Manchester United (England); Barcelona and Real Madrid (Spain);
Bayern Munich and Borussia Dortmund (Germany); Paris-St. Germain
and Olympique Marseille (France); Ajax Amsterdam (Netherlands);
Benfica (Portugal); RSC Anderlecht (Belgium); and Panathinaikos
(Greece).
</P>
<P>
   Notes: America's England-based goalkeepers looked good in
Premier League openers over the weekend. Leicester City's Kasey
Keller
</P>
<P>
   shut out host Manchester United for 61 minutes Saturday before
leaving the game with a bruised knee; his teammates squandered a
2-0 loss, surrendering two goals in the final 12 minutes of a 2-2
draw. Liverpool's Brad Friedel
</P>
<P>
   also was victorious, helping the Reds to a 2-1 comeback
victorywin
</P>
<P>
   at Southampton.
</P>
<P>
   The Orange County Zodiac is playoff-bound for the first time
after improving to 15-9 with ALeague wins last weekend over San
Francisco Bay and New Orleans. Coach Mike Gartlan
</P>
<P>
   isn't satisfied. ``It's cool,'' he said after Friday's clinching
victory. ``What do you want me to say? We don't want to just get
in. We want to win it.'' Most likely ALeague champion is MLS
wannabe Rochester, which is 19-3 and has outscored opponentsfoes,
53-11.
</P>
<P>
   Marcelo Bielsa, coach of Spain's Espanyol, confirmed Monday that
he's been offered the Argentina job abandoned by Daniel Passarella.
Bielsa called the offer a ``dream,'' and Espanyol officials hinted
they'd let him out of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Not a whole lot of competition awaits the U.S. women's team in
U.S. Women's Cup '98, which will be played at four East Coast
venues Sept.12-20. Only South American champion Brazil figures to
give the Americans much of a challenge Russia and Mexico are the
patsies. Four of the six matches will be televised: U.S.-Mexico
(Sept. 13 at noon, ESPN2), Brazil-Russia (Sept. 15 at noon, ESPN),
U.S.-Russia (Sept. 18 at 5 p.m., ESPN) and U.S.-Brazil (Sept. 20 at
noon, ESPN2 and Telemundo).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
