<SLUG> BC-ALBERTSON-FOUNDATION-565&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION PLEDGES $110 MILLION FOR PUBLIC SCHOOLS IN IDAHO
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEPHEN STEUBNER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ The Albertson Foundation, a $1 billion family-run
charitable trust, has announced a three-year pledge to award $110
million in grants to public schools in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   While not the largest gift to public education, it would be the
largest commitment on a per-school basis, at $176,000 a school, if
spread over the 626 public schools in Idaho. In that respect, the
grants even top the Annenberg Foundation pledge of $500 million,
made in 1993; a typical grant to a school from that pledge is about
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Grants for four new programs in Idaho are beginning to filter
into public schools this summer, including about $80 million for
computer and software investments promised over the next three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Albertson Foundation, based in Boise, emerged on the scene
unexpectedly last year, when Kathryn Albertson, the widow of the
grocery entrepreneur Joe Albertson, donated $660 million in company
stock to her husband's foundation. The gift made it one of the
Northwest's wealthiest foundations and among the nation's top 35.
Albertson, who built a grocery chain with stores in 21 states,
opened his first Albertson's store here in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Loren Renz, vice president of research at the New York-based
Foundation Center, a policy and research organization, said it is
unusual for a foundation to put its resources in one state and in
K-12 public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not many of them that large spend all of their money in one
state,'' Ms. Renz said. ``But it's a great benefit to the state
because you really know your grantees.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 42 percent of private foundations focus on higher
education, compared to 27 percent for K-12 education, Ms. Renz
said. But since national attention in recent years has been focused
on the shortcomings of public schools, the number of gifts to
primary and secondary education is increasing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Idaho's public schoolchildren fall roughly in the middle of all
students in terms of test scores, although the state is among the
bottom 10 in per-pupil spending, at $4,500 per student, and in
student-teacher ratios, with 18.8 students per teacher. In
addition, crumbling primary and secondary schools face a $700
million backlog in maintenance and repairs.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mel Richardson, a Republican from Idaho Falls who is
on the budget committee that allocates funds for school computers,
said the Albertson gift provides a geometric leap in financing.
Until now, the Idaho Legislature has spent only about $10 million a
year on computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-eight million is going to be spent immediately on
computer hardware and software,'' Richardson said. ``That means
we'll have a computer for every teacher in the state, and more
computers and software for students.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not want the foundation money to replace state
financing. ``The big battle is going to be to keep the funding
coming from the Legislature,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Split among 112 districts, the money for computers amounts to
$250,000 a district. To qualify, districts must have a technology
plan, which already is required by the Idaho Board of Education in
order to qualify for state money.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the best of our knowledge, this is the largest grant that's
been given for technology in one state for education,'' said Rich
Mincer, bureau chief of technology services for the Idaho
Department of Education.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Three other new programs being financed by the foundation are:
education of preschoolers ($3.8 million), reading in the lower
grades ($24.5 million) and professional development for teachers
($2 million).
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is making it possible for 140 teachers to take a
rigorous training program offered through the National Board of
Professional Teaching Standards. Nationwide, only 914 teachers have
been certified under the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course made us look very critically at how we were
teaching, and whether we were getting through to our students,''
said Shanon Blosch, a third-grade teacher in Arco, Idaho. ``I never
could have taken the course without the Albertson's money. Now I'm
really excited for next year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
