<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SEXTON-PROFILE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM ART SOCIETY TO TIMES SQUARE, ELBOWS BARE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was probably inevitable that the man who invented
those lurid chartreuse stickers cemented to certain car windows
around town _ ``This vehicle violates NYC parking regulations!'' _
would not last forever as president of the Municipal Art Society.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Brendan Sexton has no sense of esthetic decorum;
in fact, most preservationists agree that he has helped improve the
city's physical landscape in the three years that he has led the
art society. But ultimately, Sexton is an operations man, as they
say at City Hall, the kind of guy who likes to get his fingernails
dirty planning sanitation routes and figuring out traffic patterns
and engaging in the delivery of city services in a way not usually
practiced in the more rarefied world of the urban-design
association.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why many of his friends believe his next job as
president of the Times Square Business Improvement District will be
such a snug fit. Running one of these districts means supplying
basic services the city has neither the money nor the will to
provide, along with cheerleading and long-term planning. As Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani has recently come to realize, it's a bit like
being mayor of one of the city's best-known, most prosperous
neighborhoods, with $6 million in tax money to play with and no
daily news conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect match for Brendan,'' said Stanley Brezenoff,
who as a deputy mayor in the administration of Mayor Ed Koch was
Sexton's boss. ``When he was running the city's Office of
Operations, he reveled in figuring out how to make the agencies
work better, coming up with milestones and benchmarks for
sanitation and public safety and the general quality of life. He
likes digging into problems up to his elbows.''
</P>
<P>
   At just under five-and-a-half feet tall, Sexton, 53, is a feisty
and talkative man whose elbows are usually exposed by rolled-up
sleeves. He is careful not to denigrate the job he is leaving,
pointing out that the society played a major role in the design of
the structure that is to replace the Coliseum at Columbus Circle,
as well as the new Hudson River Park. But his role at the arts
society was primarily that of a negotiator and lobbyist, testifying
at hearings, writing beseeching letters to public officials, and
speaking with newspaper reporters. When he talks about his next
job, one can almost hear his heart pounding.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen in Times Square in the last several years is
what I think New York's next century will be very largely based
on,'' he said, sitting in the society's crisp midtown offices in
the Villard Houses, on Madison Avenue near East 50th Street.
``Times Square is the place where New York is both encouraging and
experimenting with the density of the future, the combination of
residents and visitors that makes this the global capital of world.
You get paid to be excited, to foster excitement, to make
excitement friendly and safe. The fact that I got this chance is
sort of amazing to me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sexton said he wasn't looking for a new job but had expressed
interest after a search firm called him, looking for a replacement
for Gretchen Dykstra, who is leaving after six years to move to San
Francisco. During Ms. Dykstra's tenure, the neighborhood scraped
off its grime and ousted its shabby restaurants and movie theaters
to become the city's new real estate playground, an overheated
greenhouse for developers, publishers and entertainment companies
thriving in the city's end-of-century exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   But both Sexton and Ms. Dykstra insist that the hard work is far
from over. The district's problems now involve managing its
success: finding sidewalk space for boisterous crowds that often
spill over the curb, planning for the day when economic growth
begins pressuring Eighth Avenue and Hell's Kitchen, getting ready
for the unimaginably large celebration of the new millennium that
will occur exactly 500 days from Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton says he wants the district to grow without losing the
``little things that make you happy to be there,'' like the Colony
Record store or the musical instrument dealers on 48th Street.
</P>
<P>
   He will also have to accommodate the looming presence of
Giuliani, who recently shut down another improvement district after
its director was insufficiently deferential. But that should not be
an enormous problem for Sexton, who long ago learned to deal with a
mayor-sized ego when he worked in several posts for Koch.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the substantial salary that comes with the job, Sexton's
getting worried about convincing his children (there are seven,
including three from his wife's previous marriage) that he still
works for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the person in this job is more of a ringmaster
or a maitre d' at a really super party,'' he said. ``It's hard to
justify yourself to your kids when you tell them your job is to
make New York as much fun as possible.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
