<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: HOWARD STERN, SAVIOR;   RATHER LOBBIES FOR JOB; BEST WEEK
FOR CABLE;   'TOONS FROM ABROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Declaring ``I am the savior of the Tiffany network'' and ``I'm
Ed Sullivan on acid,'' Howard Stern used about an hour of his
morning radio talk show Tuesday to promote his new late-night
television show, which starts on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Stern, who has made his reputation by taking vulgarity to new
levels on the radio and on the E! Entertainment cable network, also
said, ``It's very brave of CBS to put me on,'' and ``it could be
suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   But, despite his repeated references, the CBS network is not
putting Stern on the air. His show is syndicated _ meaning sold by
a production company to individual stations around the country _
and in most cities where it will appear, the show will not be on a
CBS-affiliated station.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 14 stations that CBS owns, one in Salt Lake City, the
other in Green Bay, Wis., refused to broadcast the show, which is
being syndicated by Eyemark Entertainment, a CBS-owned company; the
other 12, including Channel 2 in New York City, will carry it.
Eyemark has sold it to stations covering more than 70 percent of
the country, including stations affiliated with Fox, WB, UPN and
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``The Howard Stern Radio Show,'' the television show will
combine recycled segments from his daily radio show, which is
already videotaped for use on his six-nights-a-week half-hour
E!-channel show, and new segments, including some animation.
``We're going to take some radio bits we've done in the past and
animate them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What he will not do, Stern said emphatically, is sketch comedy _
a staple of NBC's ``Saturday Night Live,'' against which Stern's
show will compete in most cities, appearing at 11:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do sketches about lesbians _ we haul in real
lesbians,'' Stern said. ```Saturday Night Live' sketches go on too
long and they're never funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern also called David Letterman, CBS' weeknight late-night
star, ``a crybaby,'' and Walter Cronkite, its retired news anchor,
``boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter Cronkite is calling Dr. Kevorkian and making an
appointment right now,'' Stern crowed. ``He hates me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the most valuable jewel in the Tiffany network.''
</P>
<P>
   Turn Back the Clock?
</P>
<P>
   Dan Rather, who was a ``60 Minutes'' correspondent from 1976 to
1981, wants to reprise that role for the second edition of the
venerable CBS news magazine, due early next year and informally
known inside CBS News as ``60 II.''
</P>
<P>
   Although such a move would make sense _ the executive producer
for ``60 Minutes II,'' Jeff Fager, was most recently executive
producer of ``CBS Evening News,'' anchored by Rather, and the new
program could benefit from the addition of such a well-known news
name _ it would also present daunting difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces reported for ``60 Minutes'' take considerable time, and
Rather's schedule is already overbooked. In addition to the
``Evening News,'' he also anchors ``48 Hours,'' the network's other
news magazine program, and he writes a syndicated newspaper column
and does commentary for CBS radio.
</P>
<P>
   And ``48 Hours,'' after struggling in the Nielsen ratings for
some years, made a strong comeback this past season _ a season in
which Rather devoted more time to it.
</P>
<P>
   Executives who work in the news division said that Rather would
like to have a prominent role on ``60 II,'' and that Fager and Don
Hewitt, the executive producer of ``60 Minutes'' who will supervise
``60 II,'' would like to have him. That makes the odds pretty good,
the executives said, that something will be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Hot Wired
</P>
<P>
   Cable-network competition got pretty heated Sunday night, with
the Discovery Channel showing a live telecast of explorers roaming
the ruins of the Titanic deep under the North Atlantic ocean, TBS
opportunistically showing the romantic comedy ``The American
President,'' the all-news channels carrying programs about
President Clinton's scheduled grand jury testimony and the new Fox
Family Channel in the midst of its much-publicized weekend debut.
</P>
<P>
   All helped give basic cable its best week ever in the Nielsen
ratings, with an average prime-time share of 47, meaning of all
American households using television last week, an average of 47
percent were tuned to a basic cable channel in prime time. The six
broadcast networks combined had a 44 share in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Titanic Live,'' a two-hour special, gave the Discovery Channel
its second-highest Nielsen rating ever, a 4.1, which means slightly
more than 3 million households. Fascination with the doomed Titanic
seems perennial; the only Discovery show to score a higher rating
was ``Anatomy of a Disaster,'' also about the Titanic, which got a
4.5 rating in April of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On TBS, ``The American President'' had 4.96 million households
tuned in, for a 6.6 rating that was the highest ever for a
theatrical movie on basic cable. (And it drew another 3 million
homes for a second showing at 10:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   On the new Fox Family Channel, formerly just the Family Channel,
a concert by the Spice Girls got a 1.8 rating, which, considering
the competition, pleased the network's president, Rich Cronin. He
was happier, though, about Saturday night, when Fox Family showed
the movie ``Mrs. Doubtfire'' and drew 2.4 million homes, tied for
13th on the list of most-watched shows in cable last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled,'' Cronin said Tuesday. ``We didn't know what
to expect. We knew our competitors would put good stuff up against
us, but we didn't see the whole thing with President Clinton coming
up.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the network had doubled its rating on Saturday
among 18-to-49-year-olds and had tripled its audience of children
under 12, in relation to its third-quarter average so far, and to
the same date last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while to build an audience but this was a great
start,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nose Knows
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder if the people who make cartoons are as crazy in
other parts of the world as they seem to be here? Nickelodeon, the
cable network for children, has some stake in finding out. And on
Saturday, Nickelodeon viewers can get some idea, too, when the
network shows a half-hour special featuring 10 animated shorts,
eight from Nickelodeon channels outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The special, ``Toons From Planet Orange'' (Saturday, 12 noon
Eastern time), includes four cartoons from Australia, two from
Latin America, one from Britain and one from Germany.
</P>
<P>
   As for themes, two of the cartoons feature maniacal plants (a
cactus and a zucchini), one stars three Martians, seven have animal
or insect stars (ranging from ants to toads) and two feature nasal
excretions. One Australian cartoon features a superhero piece of
nasal material who lives in the Sphinx's nose in Egypt; the German
entry, ``Helmut and the Killer Nose,'' has a main character that
annihilates whole cities with its excretions.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what Nickelodeon fans will fancy?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
