<HEADLINE>
MINORITY STUDENTS SCORING HIGHER ON ACT TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More minority students took the ACT college entrance examination
this year, and improved their scores slightly in the process,
according to data released Tuesday by ACT. Incorporated, one of the
two major nonprofit organizations that offer college entrance
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Hayden, a spokesman for the organization, said the that
number of students who placed themselves in a racial or ethnic
minority grew this year by 18,188m, or 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The national average score, a composite of tests in English,
mathematics, reading and science reasoning, remained constant at 21
out of a possible 36 points this year.
</P>
<P>
   But while most minority groups remain below that average, scores
continue to improve slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minority students are increasingly thinking of themselves as
college material and are taking more college preparation courses in
high school,'' Hayden said.
</P>
<P>
   Over a five-year period, the average scores of American Indians
has risen to 19 from 18.5. African-American scores went up to 17.1
from 17. The scores of Asian-Americans rose to 21.8 from 21.7.
</P>
<P>
   The scores of Hispanic students could not be compared to past
years, Hayden said, because the categories defining ethnic
backgrounds changed this year.
</P>
<P>
   In another trend suggested by this year's tests, said Richard L.
Ferguson, the president of ACT, many students' career aspirations
seemed out of step with the job market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Large numbers are interested in entering crowded fields where
the available openings may decrease in the coming years,'' Ferguson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Students are asked to check off on accompanying questionaires
the careers they hope to pursue. A comparison to Labor Department
projections indicate that the top three occupations expected to
grow most rapidly between now and 2006 are all computer-related.
Yet relatively few students (3 percent) checked off computing and
information science.
</P>
<P>
   Students' first choice of career was health sciences (20
percent), followed by business and management (11.3 percent) and
education (9.6 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The test was taken by 60 percent of all high school seniors, or
just under a million, about 100,000 fewer than those who took the
SAT. The ACT test is more popular in central United States while
the SAT is the dominant test on both coasts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
