<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MOSBY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALINE MOSBY, UPI CORRESPONDENT FOR MORE THAN HALF CENTURY, DIES AT
76 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aline Mosby, a former correspondent for United Press
International who reported from Hollywood, Paris, Beijing and
points between for more than 50 years, died on Aug. 7 at Palomar
Medical Center in Escondido, Calif. She was 76 and had moved from
Europe to the Silvergate retirement community in San Marcos,
Calif., this year.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a cerebral hemorrhage, The Associated Press
reported from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mosby, a native of Missoula, Mont., and a graduate of the
University of Montana, joined United Press, which later became UPI,
in Seattle in 1943. She retired from the agency in 1984, but her
freelance articles continued to appear in various publications,
including the Travel section of The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   She was one of the first women assigned to cover the Kremlin
and, later, Beijing. While stationed in Moscow in 1959 she
interviewed a self-exiled Lee Harvey Oswald, who described his
upbringing and his embrace of Marx's socialism. She also
interviewed Gary Powers, the downed U-2 pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in her career she reported Hollywood gossip, among other
things. Her Hollywood column was credited with helping to propel
Marilyn Monroe to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Mosby is survived by a sister, Mary Jane Bader of Escondido.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
