<HEADER>
A0467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOREA-NUKES-NYT &LR;      08-18 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOREA-NUKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NORTH KOREA'S NUCLEAR AMBITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 19:
</P>
<P>
   North Korea seems to have been caught preparing to betray its
1994 commitment to trade in its nuclear weapons ambitions for $6
billion in international assistance. U.S. intelligence agencies
have detected construction of an elaborate underground nuclear
complex. If completed, the nuclear reactor and plutonium
reprocessing plant expected to be built there could allow the North
to produce as many as half a dozen nuclear bombs two to five years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   Washington must insist that work on this project be halted
immediately. If North Korea wants economic cooperation from the
United States it must honor its promise to renounce all nuclear
weapons activity.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has not yet violated the letter of its 1994 nuclear
agreement with the United States. Reprocessing of spent nuclear
fuel from the North's existing, above-ground reactors into bomb
plutonium remains suspended. Construction work has not yet begun on
either the new reactor or new reprocessing plant. That means the
nuclear cooperation deal can be preserved, provided North Korea
stops work on the new site.
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 deal provided for North Korea to freeze all work on
suspect nuclear programs. In exchange a group of countries, led by
the United States and South Korea, agreed to provide fuel oil and
to build two replacement power reactors whose spent fuel cannot
easily be converted into bombs. Washington has fallen badly behind
on fuel oil deliveries, with less than half the annual amount due
by October so far delivered.
</P>
<P>
   The North has complained about this shortfall, and it is
conceivable that its recent construction work is intended to
pressure America into speedier oil deliveries. If so, it is a badly
misconceived tactic sure to stiffen Congressional resistance to
paying for more fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, Washington's special envoy for Korean nuclear
issues, Charles Kartman, will meet North Korean officials in New
York. Halting the newly discovered construction work will rightly
be high on his agenda. Beyond that, the Clinton administration
needs to proceed firmly but carefully, closely coordinating its
diplomacy with South Korea, whose new government remains committed
to expanding economic cooperation with the North.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is a dangerous, unpredictable country. A breakdown
of the nuclear cooperation agreement would heighten tensions on the
peninsula, where 37,000 U.S. troops still stand guard. Washington
should make every reasonable effort to keep the nuclear deal alive.
But the agreement clearly cannot survive if North Korea still
imagines itself becoming a nuclear power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
