<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-REDSOX-BO     08-18 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ HELPS RED SOX SWEEP RANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez restored pace, passion, and purpose to the Red
Sox' pursuit of a wild card Tuesday afternoon. Mo Vaughn added some
late-night percussion, leading to a doubleheader sweep of the Texas
Rangers at Fenway Park that brought the Red Sox closer to those
playoff dates written in red on Jimy Williams's wall calendar.
</P>
<P>
   After Martinez won his 16th game, beating the Rangers, 4-1, in a
matinee played with a swiftness and sureness missing throughout
this languid homestand, Vaughn won the nightcap, 5-4, with a
tie-breaking home run that split sheets of rain and a stiff breeze
before settling into the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro started it off early for us today, got us in the flow,''
said Vaughn, ``and these were big games, no doubt about it. We're
shooting for something and right in the thick of things, and it was
important to get these two. We knew going head to head against
these guys, we had to play well.''
</P>
<P>
   With 13 pitches, Tom Gordon saved both ends of the sweep, which
gave the Red Sox a 5-3 record for the homestand as they head to
Kansas City and Minnesota for a quick five-game swing.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn hit a 422-foot home run off reliever Danny Patterson to
lead off the seventh after the Red Sox fought back from a 4-2
deficit the inning before. It was Vaughn's 33d of the season, his
seventh against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams have a Mo,'' said Rangers manager Johnny Oates,
whose team dropped eight games behind the Sox in the wild-card race
while the Orioles, 7-1 winners over the Twins, are seven back.
``But Mo is Mo, and he's put mo' hurtin' on us than most people,
especially with the long ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Bret Saberhagen was unable to duplicate Martinez's mastery in
the nightcap _ done in by back-to-back home runs in the fifth _ but
the Red Sox continued to play with an urgency that made the
evening's persistent showers tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro set up the second game for us,'' said Saberhagen, who
gave up consecutive blasts to Luis Alicea and Roberto Kelly that
left him annoyed about not throwing his fastball more. ``He did
what he does best. He gets the ball into the late part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had to use Flash (Gordon) for one out in the ninth
inning of the first game, which gave Jimy the chance to use a
variety of guys in the second game, especially after the day off
(Monday).''
</P>
<P>
   And use them Williams did: four relievers in the eighth inning
alone, when Derek Lowe, Greg Swindell, Dennis Eckersley, and Jim
Corsi all faced a batter apiece. The win went to Lowe, who also
pitched the sixth and seventh and allowed just one hit in 2 1/3
innings, while Gordon's saves now number 36, the last 33 in
succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can honestly tell you, against the Twins, we may have been
dragging a bit,'' said John Valentin, whose opposite-field double
was a vital piece of the jigsaw puzzle of a four-run rally with
which the Red Sox won the first game. ``We weren't sharp. We
weren't crisp. Today we knew we'd lost two, the team coming in was
very good, and we couldn't be flat. Basically, I told these guys,
`We've got to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's a message carried out with much greater facility when
Martinez is on the mound. In the second inning, the Red Sox ace
gave up a 414-foot home run to Rangers strongman Gonzalez that
bounced off the camera well underneath the center-field flagpole.
But he did not allow another runner past first until there were two
out in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   After allowing singles to Mark McLemore and Will Clark in the
ninth, Martinez yielded to Gordon as a sellout crowd of 33,201
registered their protest of Williams's decision.
</P>
<P>
   But those boos died along with Ivan Rodriguez's game-ending fly
ball to Troy O'Leary, whose single had broken a 1-1 tie in the
sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in a situation where we'd gotten into a little bad
streak,'' said Martinez, who gave up just five hits and walked one
to improve his record to 16-4 while lowering his ERA to an American
League-leading 2.82.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also struck out 10, the seventh time this season he has
punched out 10 or more and the 34th time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That long road trip had caught up with us,'' he said. ``The
bad weather, the time we spent traveling, the long games were
catching up with us. On the team, it showed. Everybody on the team
was a little tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the night off yesterday helped a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits of Monday's rainout did not show immediately as the
Red Sox were held to one hit _ Nomar Garciaparra's ground-rule
double _ by starter John Burkett through the first five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I figured my team was going to get him,'' said Martinez,
who allowed only four balls to be hit to the outfield, not
including Gonzalez's 34th home run on a changeup that reversed
direction at warp speed. ``And I knew I had to have a long outing
to save our relievers for the second game.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was right on both counts. Mike Benjamin's topped roller
down the third base line for an infield hit touched off the winning
rally in the sixth, one that was executed with optimum efficiency.
Darren Lewis bunted Benjamin to second, and Valentin, who has had a
miserable time of late _ batting just .190 in his previous 19 games
_ drove a 1-and-2 sinker into the right-field corner to score
Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   Singles by Vaughn and O'Leary followed, and after Mike Stanley
was hit by a pitch, pinch hitter Damon Buford came up big with a
two-run double off lefty reliever Eric Gunderson.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had spent much of the night coming up empty. He struck
out four times, twice in each game, and bounced into a double play
in the nightcap before hitting his game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a professional hitter separates himself from that,''
Vaughn said. ``He takes it at-bat by at-bat. They made a lot of
good pitches to me with men on base, but I got one mistake, and
that's the name of the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-18-98 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0478 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-WILLIAMS-WALKER-H     08-18 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WILLIAMS-WALKER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
UT's Williams strikes remarkable friendship with Doak Walker
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Every day when Ricky Williams reports to Texas' new football locker
room, he will see Doak Walker. But he won't see the old man whose
life has been taken over by paralysis. He won't even see the young
man whose 1940s magazine-cover-perfect photograph Williams ordered
to have pinned to the middle of his new locker.
</P>
<P>
   He sees a friend. He sees a mentor and inspiration, a role model
from a half century earlier whom Williams has chosen for his own.
</P>
<P>
   And every few weeks, sometimes more often and sometimes less,
when Walker's wife, Skeeter, reads her husband the letters and
faxes he has received in bulk since his horrible skiing accident
seven months ago, they find another note from Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened, I try to get something in the mail to him
just so he knows he's in my thoughts and in my prayers,'' said
Williams, who struck a friendship with Walker just days before the
accident. ``With what he accomplished and what he was, and the way
he was _ so selfless _ he is who I want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as Williams was concerned a year ago, Doak Walker was
just the name of an award. But before Williams would accept the
honor last season as the nation's top running back, he decided to
learn about the player for whom the trophy was named. He read first
about the former SMU and Detroit Lions star's place in football
history as the first post-World War II sports hero, perhaps the
last before television made players legends.
</P>
<P>
   But when reading about Walker's personal style and values,
Williams recognized that what mattered most to him, he and Walker
shared. And when they met, first in Orlando, Fla., for one awards
ceremony and then in Dallas for the Walker Award, they clicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just became very good friends,'' Skeeter Walker said, as
if the mix of Walker, 72, and Williams, 21, were just that simple.
``They're very, very good friends. That's why Ricky's letters mean
so much to Doak.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked how Walker reacts to the letters, Skeeter would
rather not say. But the only interview Walker has agreed to since
the accident was for a cable-television piece about Williams. And
when he was asked about the letters, a man who makes hospital
visitors laugh to relax them was moved to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent me the tape,'' Williams said. ``I had to brush a
tear from my eye, too. I didn't know they had so much of an effect
on Doak.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what has bonded them, what they share. The player who 50
years ago was every mother's choice for her son's role model saw
through another generation's dreadlocks, tattoos and pierced body
parts to find much in common.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Williams has written Walker now, Walker wrote notes to
fans he had somehow touched or magazine editors he believed treated
him kindly.
</P>
<P>
   Both are dramatically shy, uncomfortable with the praise their
talents draw. Both even earn unrelenting grief from teammates about
their inexplicably high-pitched voices. Each seemed to appreciate
the other's ability to look beyond appearances to the basic
kindness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky writes his thoughts and thoughts between the two of
them,'' Skeeter Walker said. ``I think it's unbelievable. I'm very,
very fond of Ricky. I understand why they hit it off. They're both
very humble _ genuine and humble.''
</P>
<P>
   To Williams, there can be no greater compliment than to be
compared to Walker, particularly by the person closest to Walker.
And it has nothing to do with yardage, records or awards but rather
the reminder Williams plans for each time he opens his locker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is,'' Williams said, ``the way I want to be every day of my
life, on and off the field.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
