<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980818.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-18 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0479 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS &LR;      08-18 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   Murray wrote book &QL; 
on sports columns
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
What does the artist say on the day when there is no genius hand to
pick up Picasso's brush and bring the canvas to life? Or the
musician when there is no Bernstein to stand before the orchestra?
Or the soldier without Patton to lead him on the next march?
</P>
<P>
   Jim Murray died Sunday night at the age of 78. He was a sports
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   No, he was the sports columnist.
</P>
<P>
   Murray was Babe Ruth always reaching the fences. He was Jim
Brown always running into the end zone. He was Secretariat at the
Belmont _ so strong, so graceful, so very far ahead of the rest of
the field while making it look so easy.
</P>
<P>
   He was a regular fixture in the Los Angeles Times since 1961 and
a regular god among his peers, and sitting next to him at the World
Series or the Super Bowl was, for any of us columnist wannabes,
like sharing a work space with Zeus on Mount Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   What can anyone write about Jim Murray that Jim Murray wouldn't
have written better himself? That he was a friendly, gentle soul
who used sports not as a way to keep track of life's wins and
losses but as a vehicle to entertain. With wry, insightful _ and
inciteful _ columns that for nearly four decades in LA, and via
syndication in newspapers across the country, made the morning
coffee taste a little better, even if the words were sometimes hard
to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   A keen observer
</P>
<P>
   Murray on the Indy 500: ``Gentlemen, start your coffins.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray on the sizable Merlin Olsen: ``He went swimming in Loch
Ness, and the monster got out.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray on Woody Hayes: ``Consistent. Graceless in victory and
graceless in defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray on Iowa fans at the Rose Bowl: ``Thousands of people in
calico and John Deere caps in Winnebagos with pacemakers and potato
salad, looking for Bob Hope.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, the governor of Iowa was still taking shots at
him. But like so many before and after, the Guv just didn't get it.
To be tweaked by Murray in a column was like being touched on the
shoulder with a sword by the queen. It was an honor. No city in
sports was ever truly on the map until Murray zinged it.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati: ``Closed for repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Birmingham, Ala.: ``Gateway to the Ku Klux Klan, where evening
dress means bring a bedsheet with eyeholes.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit: ``Should be left on the doorstep of the Salvation Army,
but I don't think they can save it.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire state of West Virginia: ``An area of such permanent
arrested economic development that the only way out is to wage war
on the United States and try to lose. Even the Confederacy didn't
want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray did it his way, strictly for amusement. He was a man who
found his way into his readers' consciousness through the world of
sports, where he took few things less seriously than himself.
</P>
<P>
   Admiration society huge
</P>
<P>
   While working as a Hollywood reporter for Time magazine in 1953,
he was having dinner with a young actress named Marilyn Monroe.
Late in the meal, Monroe asked, ``Would you mind if I went home
with someone else?'' ``Not as long as you introduce me,'' he
replied. So she waved, and a man approached the table. ``Jim,'' she
said, ``this is Joe DiMaggio.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn went home with the Yankee Clipper. Murray went home to
write his story and, eventually, a legacy that would earn him a
Pulitzer Prize. He played poker with John Wayne, had drinks with
Bogey. He received fan mail from Groucho Marx and Charlton Heston.
And all the while, he wrote with the style of Fred Astaire and the
humor of Jack Benny, also friends.
</P>
<P>
   He was the writer who other writers read, the columnist that I,
like so many other columnists, always wanted to be. The first time
I came across a Jim Murray column, as a teen-ager, it was like
finding the Rosetta Stone, discovering the key to a new language.
He was funny and fair. Like the late author John D. McDonald, he
could take the ordinary and make it extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   He lost a son at age 29 to drugs. He lost a wife to brain
cancer. But never the sense of humor or the touch. He lost all of
his sight in one eye and most of it in the other. But he still saw
things better than the rest.
</P>
<P>
   It is a small, strange fraternity of disparate personalities
that fills the sports columns in America's dailies, sharing the
experiences, the deadlines, the responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   This from Murray's autobiography: ``A column is more than a
demanding mistress. It is a raging master. It consumes you. It is
insatiable. It becomes more than you. You are not a person, you are
a publicly owned facility. Available on demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now. The king is dead. My profession lost a beacon in Jim
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   I lost an idol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
